<HEAD>

<TITLE>Environmental Information: Find it on the Internet</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, August 21, 1996  9:35 AM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.ercweb.com/SPECKLE.GIF">
<A NAME="Top"></A>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.ercweb.com/BCLOGO.GIF" HEIGHT=61 WIDTH=480 ALT="Beyond Compliance - September 1996"></CENTER>

<HR>
<CENTER><H1>Environmental Information: Find it on the Internet!</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H5><A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/EMPL.HTM#Brian">Brian Karnofsky<BR>President</A></H5></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="INTERNET.GIF" HEIGHT=149 WIDTH=100 ALT="The Internet offers many opportunities to get free environmental information"ALIGN=LEFT>

If you have a computer and a modem, you have access to a vast array of virtually free environmental information on the Internet. The data available is so comprehensive that soon you'll forget about getting information from books, magazines, and newspapers (except, of course, <I>Beyond Compliance </I>).

<P>

First, you'll need a personal computer that can run either Windows, DOS, or the Mac operating system. Second, you'll need an Internet account and a browser (software that searches the Internet). One of the easiest ways to get an account and a browser at the same time is to sign up with one of the major on-line companies, such as America Online (AOL; 800-827-6364) or CompuServe (800-487-0453). Both companies send you free, easy to load and use software. The service costs about $10 a month and includes about five hours of connect time per month-additional time is about $4 per hour. Another option is to hook up with a direct Internet Service Provider (ISP), such as Netcom or GNN (800-819-6112). They also provide free software, and for about $20 per month, you get unlimited access time.

<P>

If your ISP doesn't provide it free, you'll need browser software. The most popular browser is from Netscape, but others such as Microsoft Explorer or Netcom Netcruiser work fine for most of us.

<P>

Today, the easiest method of searching the Internet is via the WorldWide Web (WWW), and Internet browsers make searching the Web easy.

<P>
 
Some information is only available via File Transfer Protocol (FTP) which is a fast way to download data files and software, but you have to know where the information is, and exactly what you are looking for, to find it. A "gopher" search tool, which is built into AOL and some Web browsers, can help you find your way through FTP files.

<P>
 
To find information from a world wide web home page, type the address (if you know it) into your browser. Most addresses look something like ours, <A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com">http://www.ercweb.com</A>. For environmental information, our home page is the best place to start because you'll find information that we have developed to keep you up-to-date with environmental regulations. Another good place to look is EPA's home page at <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov">http://www.epa.gov</A>.

If you don't know the address, you can search one of the Internet directories on-line. To do this, use the address - <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</A>. If Yahoo can't find what you are looking for, in place of yahoo, type "altavista" or "webcrawler" or "infoseek."

<P>

If you ever get lost, just click the "back" button on your browser and you'll go back to the previous page; or click on home, and you'll get back to where you started.

<P>
 
Our home page contains "links" to most of the other home pages that you'll want to search. A link is a connection to another page of information that could be at the same organization or across the planet. Links are usually highlighted in blue, and when clicked on, they jump you to the new location. Our home page has links to EPA, OSHA, DOT, all 50 states, and other useful sources of information.

<P>
 
If you have an e-mail address that is connected to the Internet, you can join a "listserver" and let the information come to you. Listservers will send you continuous e-mails of all kinds of environmental information. Just send an e-mail to a listserver and then wait for the flood of information.

<P>
 
Here are a few listservers to get you started:

<P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER>
<TR><TH>Name</TH><TH>Description</TH></TR>
<TR><TD>EPA-PRESS</TH><TD>EPA press releases.  If you want to know <BR>where Carol Browner is speaking next week,<BR>this is for you.  You'll also get releases on <BR>new regulations</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>EPA-TRI</TD><TD>SARA Title II Federal Registers</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>EPA-WASTE</TD><TD>RCRA Federal Registers</TD><TR>

<TR><TD>HOTLINE_OSWER</TD><TD>RCRA Hotline Questions and Answers</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>EPA-AIR</TD><TD>Clean Air Act Federal Registers<BR>This one is thje most active.<BR>You'll get several e-mails per day.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>EPA CONTENTS</TD><TD>The table of contents to the Federal Register.<BR>If you do not want to get dozens of <BR>e-mails per day or if you do not have much<BR>space on your dive to store all the regs,<BR>this is the place to start</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>EPA-TOX</TD><TD>TSCA Federal Registers</TD></TR>


</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>

To subscribe to any of these listservers, follow these instructions closely. One typo and it won't work.
<OL>
<LI>Send an e-mail to: <A HREF="mailto:listserver@unixmail.rtpnc.epa.gov">listserver@unixmail.rtpnc.epa.gov</A>
</LI>
<LI>Leave the subject field of your e-mail message blank (very important)
</LI>
<LI>Your e-mail message should read (for example): subscribe EPA-PRESS Jane Doe
</LI>
<LI>Use your real name in place of "Jane Doe."
</LI>
<LI>In place of "EPA-PRESS," enter the name of any one of the other listservers that you want to subscribe to.
</LI>
</OL>

<P>

If you subscribe to all of the listservers described earlier, you could receive several dozen e-mails per day. If that's too much for you, or if you prefer your information in English (rather than regulatoreese) you can subscribe to our Environmental Tip of the Week, which includes selected information from the listservers and other sources. To subscribe, send an e-mail to <A HREF="mailto:tnielsen@ercweb.com">tnielsen@ercweb.com</A> and include your name, mailing address, and the word subscribe in the message.

<P>

In future issues of Beyond Compliance we will include more information about useful Internet sites and listservers. If you have a favorite site, newsgroup, or listserver that our readers would be interested in, send it in an e-mail to <A HREF="mailto:bkarnofsky@ercweb.com">bkarnofsky@ercweb.com</A>.

<P>

