<HEAD>

<TITLE>ISO 14000 Publication Date Changed</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, August 21, 1996  10:37 AM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.ercweb.com/SPECKLE.GIF">
<A NAME="Top"></A>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.ercweb.com/BCLOGO.GIF" HEIGHT=61 WIDTH=480 ALT="Beyond Compliance - September 1996"></CENTER>

<HR>
<CENTER><H1>ISO 14000 Publication Date Changed</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H5><A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/EMPL.HTM#John">John Maroney<BR>Environmental Consultant</A></H5></CENTER>

<P>

The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) was scheduled to publish the first of its final standards in the 14000 (environmental management) series by mid-1996. So far, they have only published the Committee Drafts (CDs) or Draft International Standards (DISs) of the foundation documents of the series. Informed sources now believe that the final 14001 and 14004 environmental management system standards will be published by mid-October, about the same time as the 14010, 14011, and 14012 environmental auditing standards.

<P>

The ISO 14000 series is the first set of generic standards developed by ISO to provide business management with a structure for managing the environmental impacts of their activities. The standards cover a wide range of environmental disciplines, including Environmental Management Systems (EMSs), Auditing, Environmental Performance Evaluations (EPE), Labeling, Life-Cycle Assessment (LCA), and Environmental Aspects in Product Standards (EAPS).

<P>

As of mid-1996, ISO intends the initial 14000 series standards to be organized as shown below:

<P>

<TABLE BORDER>
<TR><TH>ISO Number</TH><TH>Title</TH><TH>Subcommittee/<BR>Working Group</TH><TH>Current Status*</TH></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>1400-</TD><TD>Environmental Management Systems</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>SC1 (United Kingdom)</TH><TD ALIGN=CENTER>DIS</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>14001</TD><TD>-Specification with guidance for use</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>/WG1</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>DIS</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>14004</TD><TD>-General Guideline on principles,<BR>systems and supporting techniques</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>/WG2</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>DIS</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>1401-</TD><TD>Guideline for Environmental Auditing</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>SC2 (Netherlands)</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>DIS</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>14010</TD><TD>-General principles of environmental auditing</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>/WG1</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>DIS</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>14011</TD><TD>-Audit Procedures-Part 1:<BR>Auditing of environmental management systems</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>/WG2</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>DIS</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>14012</TD><TD>-Qualification criteria for environmental auditors</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>/WG3</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>DIS</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>14015</TD><TD>-Guidelines for environmental site assessment</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>/WG4</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Preliminary</TD></TR>

</TABLE></CENTER>
<CENTER><H6>*Status of Standards: Preliminary WD = Working Draft CD = Committee Draft <BR> DIS = Draft International Standard ISO = ISO Standard</H6></CENTER>

<P>

The best way to plan for conformance with the new standards is to begin the ISO five-step process described in Environmental Resource Center's new <I>ISO 14000 Handbook: Preparing for Certification or Registration under ISO 14001</I>. The steps are Commitment and Policy, Planning, Implementation, Measurement and Evaluation, and Review and Improvement.

<P>

Environmental Resource Center's environmental management team is ready to help you in every step of the process.  For details, call <A HREF="mailto:ewalsh@ercweb.com">Ed Walsh</A> or <A HREF="mailto:jmaroney@ercweb.com">John Maroney</A> at (919) 469-1585.

<P>

