<HEAD>

<TITLE>Risk Management Plans Required Soon</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, August 21, 1996  10:40 AM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.ercweb.com/SPECKLE.GIF">
<A NAME="Top"></A>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.ercweb.com/BCLOGO.GIF" HEIGHT=61 WIDTH=480 ALT="Beyond Compliance - September 1996"></CENTER>

<HR>
<CENTER><H1>Risk Management Plans Required Soon</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H5><A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/EMPL.HTM#Mike">Mike Randall<BR>Vice President, Consulting and Training</A></H5></CENTER>

<P>

Under a final rule signed May 24, 1996, facilities that manufacture, process, use, store, or otherwise handle any of 139 regulated substances that exceed threshold quantities are required to develop and implement a risk management program. Owners and operators of sources subject to the Risk Management Program have until June 20, 1999, to achieve compliance with the final rule.

<P>

Under the final rule, your facility will be required to do three things: (1) register with EPA, (2) develop and implement your risk management program, and (3) develop and submit to the Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board, EPA, the State Emergency Response Commission, and the Local Emergency Planning Committee a risk management plan (RMP) that outlines the results of your risk management program.

<P>

Your risk management program will be required to have three major elements: (1) a hazard assessment, (2) a prevention program, and (3) an emergency response program.

<P>

<H3>Hazard Assessment</H3>
The first element, the hazard assessment, must be completed for each regulated substance present at the site in quantities greater than the associated thresholds (see sidebar.) You should evaluate many scenarios to determine a range of releases that may occur within the facility. It is important that the worst-case scenario is also identified and included. Usually, the worst-case scenario is considered the instantaneous loss of all of the regulated substance in a process, with failure of all mitigation systems. The range of releases should only include those "significant" events that could lead to off-site deaths, injury, or serious adverse effects to human health or the environment.

<P>

After identifying "significant" release scenarios at your facility, analyze the potential off-site consequences associated with each of the scenarios. You should estimate the possible rate of release of regulated substances and the quantity that may be released, identify potential human and environmental pathways of exposure, estimate the duration of releases, and identify any other consequences.

<P>

As part of your hazard assessment, you are also required to submit a five-year accidental release history that outlines any "significant" releases. You should include information on the substance released, the quantity released, the concentration of the substance when released, time and date of release, duration of the release, off-site consequences, and any other pertinent information.

<P>

<H3>Prevention Program</H3>
The second element, the prevention program, adopts and builds on OSHA's process safety management standard (57 FR 6356). The nine procedural areas outlined by EPA as areas that should be addressed in your prevention program include:
<UL>
<LI>Process Hazard Analysis
</LI>
<LI>Safety Information
</LI>
<LI>Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs)
</LI>
<LI>Training
</LI>
<LI>Maintenance
</LI>
<LI>Pre-startup Review
</LI>
<LI>Management of Change
</LI>
<LI>Safety Audits, and
</LI> 
<LI>Accident Investigation
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

<H3>Emergency Response</H3>
The third element is emergency response planning which includes development of evacuation plans, emergency response plans, community relation plans, and informing the appropriate authorities of what responses will be taken in the event of an accidental release. The emergency response program should also include written sections covering emergency response equipment, first aid and emergency medical treatment, training, and drills and exercises.

<P>

<H3>Getting Started</H3>
To find out if your facility must develop a Risk Management Plan, you can <A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/INBC.HTM">download a copy of the proposed rule and final chemical list</A>.

<CENTER><IMG SRC="LITTLEE.GIF" ALT="End."></CENTER>

<P>

