<HEAD>

<TITLE>New Hazardous Materials Regulations</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, August 21, 1996  10:43 AM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.ercweb.com/SPECKLE.GIF">
<A NAME="Top"></A>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.ercweb.com/BCLOGO.GIF" HEIGHT=61 WIDTH=480 ALT="Beyond Compliance - September 1996"></CENTER>

<HR>
<CENTER><H1>New Hazardous Materials Regulations</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H5><A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/EMPL.HTM#Ednuti">C. Edward Nuti<BR>Transportation Consultant</A></H5></CENTER>

<P>


Since President Clinton's Regulatory Review Initiative, which directed all Federal agenices to eliminate, simplify, or revise those regulations in need of reform, the Department of Transportation has issued and finalized several hazardous materials proposals, summarized in the table below.

<P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER>
<TR><TD ALIGN=TOP>HM-200</TD><TD>Defines "Materials of Trade" in 49 CFR 171.8, and provides exceptions in new section 173.6 for these materials via motor carrier.  Only certain hazard classes are eligible and only in certain quantities.  Maximum gross weight on a motor vehicle is 150 kg.  Designed primarily for private carriage of materials used in the conduct of business.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=TOP>HM-214</TD><TD>Establishes a requirement for comprehensive response plans for oil shipments in bulk packagings in quantities greater than 42,000 gallons.  Less detailed plans are required for petroleum oil shipments in bulk packages of 3,500 gallons or more.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=TOP>HM-216</TD><TD>Miscellaneous amendments to the hazardous materials regulations for transportation by rail.  Section 172.205(f) is amended for consistency with the EPA hazardous waste manifest requirements for transportation by rail contained in 40 CFR 263.20(f).</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=TOP>HM-222A</TD><TD>Format changes to the Hazardous Materials Table in 49 CFR 172.101 are made.  Label column 6 changed to specify "label codes" instead of the associated hazard class name.  Codes are defined in a new Label Substitution Table.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=TOP>HM-222B</TD><TD>Eliminates 49 CFR 172.203(e)(3) to preface non-bulk packages of hazardous substances with "RESIDUE: Last Contained."<BR>Adds a new section 173.13 incorporating the provisions of DOT exemptions E-7891 and E-9168 (poison pack exemptions).<BR>Changes to marking requirements for hazardous substances on non-bulk packages.  Must identify and mark the two substances (if more than one) with the lowest RQs.  Changes are in 49 CFR 172.324.<BR>Consumer Commodities will no longer require emergency response information or emergency telephone number on shipping papers.<BR>Recurrent Training requirements for "hazmat employees" decreased to "at least once every three years."</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=TOP>HM-224</TD><TD>Oxygen generators prohibited from passenger aircraft, except when for medical or personal use of a passenger.</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>

Some changes were significant and others were not.  All of them, however, change the regulations in some way. The "materials of trade" exceptions, for instance, are particularly helpful if your business requires you to carry certain quantities of hazardous materials in a truck free of regulations. This provision excepts from regulation certain small quantities of hazardous materials transported and used by carriers (particularly private carriers).

<P>

Another change is somewhat controversial. In light of the recent Valujet tragedy, and the importance of a re-commitment to safety training in general, there have been indications of a movement underway to repeal the change that decreases the recurrent training provisions for "hazmat employees" from once every two years to once every three years. This ruling does not affect the current requirements of IATA/ICAO which continues to mandate recurrent training every 24 months. Stay tuned to <I>Beyond Compliance</I> to keep up-to-date. Contact Ed Nuti at (919) 469-1585 or e-mail him at <A HREF="mailto:enuti@ercweb.com">enuti@ercweb.com</A> if you would like to arrange on-site DOT or IATA training.

<P>

Attend Environmental Resource Center's Hazardous Material Handling Certification for DOT HM-181, HM-126F, and HM-215A or The Advanced Hazardous Materials DOT and IATA Workshop to stay current with DOT regulations.  If you can't attend the course, buy the book!

<CENTER><IMG SRC="LITTLEE.GIF" ALT="End."></CENTER>

<P>

