<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Lights at the End of the Tunnel?</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, August 21, 1996  11:04 AM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.ercweb.com/SPECKLE.GIF">
<A NAME="Top"></A>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.ercweb.com/BCLOGO.GIF" HEIGHT=61 WIDTH=480 ALT="Beyond Compliance - September 1996"></CENTER>

<HR>
<CENTER><H1>Lights at the End of the Tunnel?</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H5><A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/EMPL.HTM#Scott">Scott Birchfield<BR>Senior Environmental Consultant</A></H5></CENTER>

<P>

<IMG SRC="LIGHTS.GIF" BORDER=2 ALIGN=RIGHT ALT="Fluorescent Bulbs">
If you are confused about how to handle mercury-containing lamps, you are certainly not alone. On July 27, 1994, EPA proposed a regulatory program that would give mercury-containing lamps an exclusion from classification as a RCRA regulated hazardous waste if the lamps were recycled or managed at an appropriate land disposal facility. EPA does not have a projected time table for establishing a final rule regarding mercury-containing lamps, and sources at EPA have indicated that with the publication of the universal waste rules, the mercury lamp proposal is not a high priority.

<P>

The Universal Waste Rule, published May 11, 1995, deals with certain hazardous wastes generated by a wide cross-section of the regulated community, whichpose relatively low levels of hazard. The universal waste program includes three types of wastes: hazardous waste batteries, hazardous waste pesticides, and mercury-containing thermostats. EPA designed the universal waste system to allow authorized states to add other low hazard wastes, such as fluorescent lamps, to their state universal waste programs.

<P>

Fluorescent lamps contain elemental mercury as an essential component for operation. A typical 4-foot lamp contains between 30 and 40 milligrams (mg) of mercury. When these lamps are evaluated using the EPA toxicity characteristic leaching procedure (TCLP), they exceed the maximum regulatory level of mercury (0.2 mg/l) that qualifies a material as a hazardous waste.

<P>
 
In addition to federal regulatory standards, many states have published compliance documents dealing with the management and disposal of spent mercury-containing lamps.  Following are some of the strategies that state regulatory agencies have taken:

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Some states have made the determination that if fluorescent lamps are accumulated, maintained intact, and managed in a recycling program they are classified as characteristic by-product and are not subject to the hazardous waste regulations.
</LI>
<LI>States who have received universal waste authorization may add fluorescent lamps to the universal waste program.  This would require a generator to comply with the standards at 40 CFR 273 or their state universal waste codes.
</LI>
<LI>Crushing fluorescent lamps is considered treatment under the hazardous waste regulations in some states and will require a permit or license.  In other states, it is not considered treatment and is permissible provided that there is a vapor recovery system installed to capture the mercury vapor that is released when the lamps are crushed.  If the lamps are crushed, the crushed material must be evaluated to determine if it is a hazardous waste by performing a toxicity characteristic leaching procedure for mercury.
</LI>
<LI>Other states have linked the regulatory status of mercury-containing lamps to the quantity of lamps that a particular site generates in a month.  Under this system, any site that generates greater than 1000 kg of lamps per month will be required to manage their lamps as hazardous waste, or as universal waste if the lamps are recycled.  Sites that generate less than 1000 kg, but more than 100 kg, may recycle their fluorescent lamps as non-hazardous waste, or send them to an authorized disposal facility as a universal waste.  Sites that generate less than 100 kg of fluorescent lamps may send their lamps to a landfill or recycle their lamps as non-hazardous waste, provided they do not discharge the mercury to the environment or send their lamps to a landfill that is not authorized for mercury-containing lamps.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

Given the ever-changing state of regulations that could be applicable to fluorescent lamps, you must be very careful to establish the proper handling and management procedures for your facility. 

<P>
<CENTER><H3>State Regulatory Status on Flourescent Lamps</H3></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER>
<TR><TH>States</TH><TH>Regulatory Status</TH></TR>

<TR><TD>AL, AK, AZ, AR, CO, CT, DE, GA, HI, ID, IL, IN, IA, KS, KY, LA, ME, MD, MI, MS, MT, NE, ND, NJ, NM, NY, OK, OR, PA, RI, SD, TN, TX, UT, VA, WA, WY, DC</TD><TD>Lamps that fail TCLP for mercury must be managed as a hazardous waste.  Lamps that do not fail TCLP are non-hazardous solid wastes.  Comply with state solid waste disposal requirements.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>OH, NH, VT</TD><TD>Lamps that fail TCLP and are recycled are not regulated as hazardous waste.  Lamps that fail TCLP and are disposed must be managed as hazardous waste.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>NC, WI</TD><TD>Lamps that fail TCLP and are recycled are subject to reduced waste management standards (universal waste regulations).  Lamps that fail TCLP and are disposed must be managed as hazardous waste.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>CA,FL</TD><TD>Disposal above a specified quantity requires management as a hazardous waste.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>MA</TD><TD>May be shipped to a receiver without a manifest.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>MN</TD><TD>Mercury containing lamps must be recycled and meet MN pollution control guidelines.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>MO</TD><TD>Recommended managment as potentially hazardous waste</TD></TR>

</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>






The table above summarizes the regulatory status of mercury-containing lamps in various states as reported in EPA's Green Lights Program, Lighting Update Manual, March 1995.

<P>

For assistance in establishing the regulatory status of these types of wastes at your facility, contact your state environmental agency or find your state regs on our website at <A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/LINKS.HTM">http://www.ercweb.com/LINKS.HTM</A>.
<CENTER><IMG SRC="LITTLEE.GIF" ALT="End."></CENTER>

