<HEAD>

<TITLE>EPA Prefers Integrated Contingency Plans</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, August 21, 1996  11:05 AM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.ercweb.com/SPECKLE.GIF">
<A NAME="Top"></A>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.ercweb.com/BCLOGO.GIF" HEIGHT=61 WIDTH=480 ALT="Beyond Compliance - September 1996"></CENTER>

<HR>
<CENTER><H1>EPA Prefers Integrated Contingency Plans</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H5><A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/EMPL.HTM#Amy">Amy Knight<BR>Environmental Consultant</A></H5></CENTER>

<P>


Preparing and implementing multiple emergency response plans can be complex, confusing, and costly. Finally, the agencies that require you to develop emergency response plans have gotten together and will allow you to develop a single plan. The interagency "one-plan guidance" document that you can use to prepare emergency response plans, The National Response Team's Integrated Contingency Plan Guidance (One Plan), was published in the June 5, 1996, Federal Register.

<P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="CONTPLAN.GIF"><H5>Preparing emergency response plans just got easier.  The agencies that require you to develop emergency response plans have gotten together and will allow you to develop a single plan.</H5></CENTER>


<P>

A Presidential Review concluded that facilities faced a burden when preparing emergency response plans due to multiple and overlapping federal requirements. A National Response Team was created to provide a mechanism for consolidating multiple plans that facilities may have prepared to comply with various regulations into one functional emergency response plan or integrated contingency plan (ICP). The National Response Team (NRT) is composed of several agencies including Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), U.S. Coast Guard (USCG), Minerals Management Service (MMS), Research and Special Programs Administration (RSPA), and Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA).

<P>
 
The NRT believes that the preparation and use of the ICP has several advantages, such as the use of a single emergency response plan which will eliminate confusion for first responders who often must decide which of their plans is applicable to a particular emergency; it will minimize duplication in the preparation and use of emergency response plans at the same facility; facility expenditures for the preparation, maintenance, submission, and update of a single plan should be much lower than for multiple plans; and the use of a single integrated plan should also improve coordination between facility response personnel and local, state, and federal emergency response personnel.

<P>
 
For some instances, the NRT believes that the adoption of a single, common, ICP outline such as the one proposed in the guidance, would facilitate a move toward integration of facility plans with local, state, and federal plans, which will more efficiently and effectively protect public health, worker safety, the environment, and property. 
The ICP does not relieve facilities from their current obligations, although the NRT designed it specifically to help meet those obligations by providing a format for organizing and presenting material currently required by the regulations. You are free to continue maintaining multiple plans to demonstrate federal regulatory compliance; however, the NRT believes that an integrated plan prepared in accordance with the guidance is a preferable alternative.

<P>

The ICP format is organized into three main sections:  an introductory section, a core plan, and a series of supporting annexes. The elements contained in each of these sections are not new concepts or new planning requirements, but rather accepted emergency response activities addressed in existing contingency planning regulations in various different forms. 
The introductory section includes a statement of purpose and scope, a table of contents, the current revision date, and general facility information. It is designed to provide basic information about the plan so users may assess the relevancy of the plan to a particular type of emergency.

<P>
 
The core plan is intended to reflect the essential steps necessary to initiate, conduct, and terminate an emergency response action. In the guidance, the core plan is based on the structure of the National Interagency Incident Management System (NIIMS) Incident Command System (ICS). It is intended to contain essential response guidance and procedures.

<P>
 
The annexes are to contain more detailed supporting information on specific response management functions as well as document compliance with regulatory requirements not addressed elsewhere in the ICP. The annexes should also address issues such as incident history, training and exercises, prevention strategies, written follow-up reports, and plan critique.
You may <A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/INBC.HTM">download a copy of the "one-plan guidance"</A> from our Web site. If you have questions about the preparation of emergency response plans or the National Response Team's integrated contingency plan, let the experts at Environmental Resource Center help prepare your ICP. Environmental Resource Center can prepare individual emergency response plans to meet specific regulatory requirements or Integrated Contingency Plans. Our expert staff is also available for on-site emergency response plan development and training. For written cost proposals contact Amy Knight via e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:aknight@ercweb.com">aknight@ercweb.com</A>, phone (919) 469-1585 x 224 or fax your request to (919) 469-4137.

<CENTER><IMG SRC="LITTLEE.GIF" ALT="End."></CENTER>

<P>

<CENTER><A HREF="#Top">Top of Article</A> <BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/BCSep96.HTM#Top">Beyond Compliance Table of Contents</A> | <A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com">Environmental Resource Center</A></CENTER>

