<HEAD>

<TITLE>Excellence and Leadership: The Perfect Partners</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, August 21, 1996  11:12 AM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.ercweb.com/SPECKLE.GIF">
<A NAME="Top"></A>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.ercweb.com/BCLOGO.GIF" HEIGHT=61 WIDTH=480 ALT="Beyond Compliance - September 1996"></CENTER>

<HR>
<CENTER><H1>Excellence and Leadership: The Perfect Partners</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H5><A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/EMPL.HTM#Jack">Jack Martindale<BR>Environmental Consultant</A></H5></CENTER>

<P>


EPA recently announced the first Project XL plan (Excellence and Leadership) with Jack M. Berry, Inc., a citrus juice manufacturer. This is the first of as many as 50 planned pilot projects designed to streamline environmental compliance while creating better environmental results.

<P>

"EPA has found that allowing facilities and other entities to explore non-traditional pollution control solutions can result in the regulated community achieving environmental protection results beyond those anticipated by traditional means. We have also found that better environmental decisions result from a collaborative process with people working together.  We are fortunate to have formed such a partnership with Berry and the Florida DEP and South Florida WMD," said John H. Hankinson, Jr., Administrator, EPA Region 4.

<P>
 
Under Project XL, regulated entities test creative strategies that will achieve cleaner, cheaper, smarter results than conventional regulatory approaches. Last year, EPA announced that both private and federal facilities can participate in the program, and that several were testing the design elements of Project XL. Criteria for a full-scale program in which additional companies can apply should be developed by January of 1997.

<P>

Organizations that participate in the leadership program could receive public recognition, fewer inspections, and expedited permitting. Facilities that discover deficiencies may also have a limited time in which to correct any violations as long as none are criminal in nature or could pose an imminent threat to public health or the environment.

<P>

Each participating facility develops and tests one or more of the following compliance projects:   

<P>

<OL>
<LI>advancing the design of Environmental Management Systems (EMS) which both prevents and assures continuous environmental improvement;
</LI> 
<LI>incorporating multi-media compliance assurance into daily management practices;
</LI> 
<LI>using independent verification of compliance;
</LI> 
<LI>developing and conducting self-certification protocols;
</LI> 
<LI>enhancing public accountability by measuring a facility's compliance record and making goals for improvement;
</LI>
<LI>initiating facility involvement; and for large companies,
</LI> 
<LI>becoming a mentor to smaller businesses by assisting them with model training programs.
</LI>
</OL>
<P>

The full-scale leadership program will be available in those states that buy into the project. To join, the facility will submit an application to EPA, then EPA will work with the state and region to establish how each company qualifies as an environmental leader. Later this year EPA will receive comments, hold meetings, and publish their preliminary findings in the Federal Register to establish how to review a facility's leadership program for approval.

<P>

If you would like to learn more about EPA's Project XL, attend our course <I><A HREF="http://www.ercweb.com/COURSES.HTM#EHSMAN">How to be an Effective Environmental, Health, and Safety Manager</A></I>.

<CENTER><IMG SRC="LITTLEE.GIF" ALT="End."></CENTER>

<P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER>

<TR><TD>The Berry company project is expected to result in cost savings that will be reinvested by the company in new environment enhancement efforts and environmentally beneficial operating procedures.  Following are the benefits of the Berry project.

<P>

<B>Environmental Benefits:</B> Berry is committed to achieving superior environmental performance in water consumption reduction, the utilization of process wastewaters for irrigation, the use of non-hazardous pest controls, reserving of acreage for habitat conservation and overall pollution prevention practices.

<P>

<B>Consistency in environmental protection during non-monitoring periods</B> as a result, assuring the predictability of the environmental protection process.

<P>

<B>Cost reductions for the facility and for the regulatory agency:</B> A comprehensive operating permit will be prepared by EPA and the company and will allow for public comment.  This new type of singular permit will be multi-media, assuring the requirements of several previous permits, and will translate to greater flexibility and cost savings.  It will not expire automatically and will allow expedited development of a new permit with reduced paperwork and reduced expenses for the company and the agency.  This permit will be for the entire facility, call for maintaining all environmental standards, and consolidate federal, state and local facility permits.

<P>

<B>Increased compliance with environmental regulations:</B> Since employees will be involved in writing the comprehensive operating permit, they should be able to understand its language better.</TD</TR>


</TABLE></CENTER>


<CENTER><IMG SRC="LITTLEE.GIF"></CENTER>

<P>

