<HEAD>

<TITLE>Beyond Compliance-News in Brief</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Thursday, May 23, 1996  8:40 AM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.ercweb.com/SPECKLE.GIF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.ercweb.com/BCLOGO.GIF" HEIGHT=61 WIDTH=480 ALT="Beyond Compliance-September 1996"></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER><H2>SEPTEMBER 1996</H2><BR></CENTER>

<P>

<IMG SRC="http://www.ercweb.com/BRIEF.GIF" ALT="Briefly"></CENTER>

<H2>Safe Packing Assistance</H2>

<P>

To promote safe packaging reduction, the Institute of Packaging Professionals (IoPP) has prepared Guidelines for Responsible Chemical Packaging Management and Guidelines for Disposition of Used Packaging. This guide helps companies determine the best strategy for managing containers that have been used to store hazardous materials. The guide includes sections on residue minimization, recycling, reconditioning, returnable packaging, and consumable chemical packaging. Each section contains an introduction, a description of the strategy, its pros and cons, and specific examples. The guide is available from IoPP for $25. To order, contact IoPP at 703-318-8970.

<HR>


<H2>Silver BMW not Carol Browners's</H2>

<P>

It turns out that a silver BMW that carries the tags "EPA 1" and has a Clinton-Gore bumper sticker on it, doesn't belong to EPA administrator, Carol Browner. (She drives a Volvo wagon with a "Treasure the Chesapeake" sticker with Maryland tags.) The car belongs to David Petrou, president of the marketing firm Eisner, Petrou & Associates (EPA), who reports he constantly gets notes from citizens tucked under his windshield.

<HR>

<H2>New Audit Policy Gets Good Start</H2>

<P>

According to Eric Schaeffer, of EPA's Office of Enforcement and Compliance Assurance, 76 companies have participated in EPA's new limited-immunity audit policy which began January 22, 1996. The companies discovered a variety of environmental violations and agreed to correct them. Most of the companies will not be fined by EPA, and the Agency will release detailed information about the companies and their violations. EPA expects increased participation in the program in the future.

<HR>

<H2>10 State Air Permitting Programs Taken Over by EPA</H2>

<P>

As published in the Federal Register August 1, 1996, EPA will establish a Clean Air Act Title V federal operating permit program for 10 states, three territories, and one local operating permit program. Most of the 10 states will be subject to the federal program for only a short time until they submit applications for permit programs.

<P>
 
States affected are Alaska, Arizona, Connecticut, Idaho, Maine, Michigan, New Hampshire, New York, Vermont, and Virginia. Virginia will likely be subject to the federal program for a longer period due to contention between EPA and the commonwealth. The agency will also issue permits for the South Coast Air Quality Management District in California.

<HR>


