<HEAD>

<TITLE>Beyond Compliance-News in Brief</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Thursday, May 23, 1996  8:40 AM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="SPECKLE.GIF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="BCLOGO.GIF" HEIGHT=61 WIDTH=480 ALT="Beyond Compliance"></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER><H2>JUNE 1996</H2><BR></CENTER>

<P>

<IMG SRC="BRIEF.GIF" ALT="Briefly"></CENTER>

<H2>Introducing Amy Knight</H2>
Environmental Resource Center is proud to introduce <A HREF="mailto:aknight@ercweb.com">Amy Knight</A>, our newest environmental consultant. Ms. Knight has extensive environmental, public health, and safety experience, with an emphasis on regulation compliance, environmental health program management, technical assistance, and public affairs. She has worked with both government and private industry to maintain compliance with state and federal environmental regulations. She has served on a Local Emergency Planning Committee and an environmental response team responding to hazardous materials spills and providing guidance on environmental protections.

<HR>

<H2>EPA Issues Volatile Organic Compound Proposal</H2>
EPA has issued a proposal to control volatile organic compound (VOC) emissions from a variety of consumer products, including engine degreasers, insecticides, and oven cleaners. VOCs are a prime ingredient of urban ozone, or smog, which has serious health effects. The proposed rule is based on reformulation of products, instead of add-on control devices, to reduce the amount of VOCs in the product. Several states have already set reformulation standards for these products as part of their smog-control programs. EPA's proposal will establish one national standard with which manufacturers will have to comply rather than numerous state standards. EPA expects its proposal to reduce VOC emissions nationally by 90,000 tons annually. The proposed rule is computer accessible immediately through EPA's Technology Transfer Network at (919) 541-5742 under "Recently Signed Rules."

<HR>

<H2>RCRA Fax Back</H2>
Now you can get immediate access to EPA's Office of Solid Waste guidance documents regarding hazardous waste regulations via EPA's new Fax-Back service. The Fax-Back system enables you to receive selected materials by calling their fax machine. Instructions for the Fax-Back system can be obtained through the RCRA/Superfund Hotline at (800) 424-9346 or (703) 412-9810.

<HR>

<H2>20 Toxic Substances Targeted for New Workplace Exposure Limits</H2>
OSHA wishes to establish new Permissible Exposure Limits (PELs) for 20 substances. The targeted substances are: carbon disulfide; carbon monoxide, chloroform, dimethyl sulfate, epichlorohydrin (used in some epoxy mixtures), ethylene dichloride, glutaraldehyde, n-hexane, 2-hexanone, hydrazine, hydrogen sulfide, manganese, and manganese compounds, mercury and mercury compounds, nitrogen dioxide, perchloroethylene, sulfur anhydride, toluene, toluene diisocyanate, trimellitic anydride and vinyl chloride. While this list is not large there are several widely used chemicals covered by the proposed new regulations. Many painting operations use toluene as a paint solvent or thinner. Almost all welding rods contain manganese or will generated manganese or manganese compound fumes. Perchloroethylene is widely used in cleaning and degreasing operations. You should review your lists of chemicals used in your processes to determine if you will be impacted by the forthcoming regulations.

<HR>

<H2>Perchloroethylene Not A VOC</H2>
Perchloroethylene is no longer classified as a Volatile Organic Compound (VOC) for purposes of the ozone depletion regulations. In a rule issued February 5, 1996, perchloroethylene was listed as "negligibly reactive" when released to the atmosphere. This compound is still considered a "hazardous air pollutant" and continues to be regulated under the HAP regulations and the hazardous waste regulations of RCRA.

<HR>

<H2>New EPCRA 313 Reporting Deadline for 1996</H2>
The government shutdowns in December and January have resulted in an extension to August 1, 1996 for submission of required "Form R" reporting under section 313 of EPCRA. The agency said it does not expect to mail out the required forms until mid to late April.

<HR>

<H2>Used Oil Mixture Rule Revisited Again</H2>
EPA's administrative stay (40 CFR 279.10(b)(2)) which said that generators would no longer be able to mix their used oil with hazardous waste has been overturned.

<P>

The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit overturned the decision to claim a stay action on the used oil ruling.  An administrative stay can delay proceedings of a proposed regulation, however a stay cannot suspend rules that have already been adopted until there is time for public notice and comment.

<P>

According to the used oil regulations (40 CFR 279.10 (b)(2)(iii)), mixtures of used oil and hazardous waste which solely exhibit the characteristic of ignitability are regulated as used oil as long as the resulting mixture does not meet the definition of ignitability.  However, if the resulting mixture is EPA ignitable, then the resulting mixture would be classified as hazardous waste.

<P>

The final news is that EPA will allow more time for comment on this issue before taking action on existing used oil regulations, and used oil mixed with hazardous waste (solely ignitable) won't be subject to stringent RCRA requirements unless it is ignitable.

<HR>

<H2>Data Collection and Form 200 Changes</H2>
EPA's administrative stay (40 CFR 279.10(b)(2)) which said that generators would no longer be able to mix their used oil with hazardous waste has been overturned.

<P>
The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit overturned the decision to claim a stay action on the used oil ruling.  An administrative stay can delay proceedings of a proposed regulation, however a stay cannot suspend rules that have already been adopted until there is time for public notice and comment.

<P>

According to the used oil regulations (40 CFR 279.10 (b)(2)(iii)), mixtures of used oil and hazardous waste which solely exhibit the characteristic of ignitability are regulated as used oil as long as the resulting mixture does not meet the definition of ignitability.  However, if the resulting mixture is EPA ignitable, then the resulting mixture would be classified as hazardous waste.


<P>

The final news is that EPA will allow more time for comment on this issue before taking action on existing used oil regulations, and used oil mixed with hazardous waste (solely ignitable) won't be subject to stringent RCRA requirements unless it is ignitable.

<HR>

<H2>Metalworking Fluids Targeted for New Regulations</H2>
EPA's administrative stay (40 CFR 279.10(b)(2)) which said that generators would no longer be able to mix their used oil with hazardous waste has been overturned.

<P>

The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit overturned the decision to claim a stay action on the used oil ruling.  An administrative stay can delay proceedings of a proposed regulation, however a stay cannot suspend rules that have already been adopted until there is time for public notice and comment.

<P>

According to the used oil regulations (40 CFR 279.10 (b)(2)(iii)), mixtures of used oil and hazardous waste which solely exhibit the characteristic of ignitability are regulated as used oil as long as the resulting mixture does not meet the definition of ignitability.  However, if the resulting mixture is EPA ignitable, then the resulting mixture would be classified as hazardous waste.

<P>

The final news is that EPA will allow more time for comment on this issue before taking action on existing used oil regulations, and used oil mixed with hazardous waste (solely ignitable) won't be subject to stringent RCRA requirements unless it is ignitable.

<HR>

<H2>EPA Announces New, Flexible Ways to Meet Clean Air Act Standards</H2>
On March 25, 1996, EPA announced a draft final regulation that will ensure that all types of industrial categories as yet unregulated by the agency must protect the public from toxic air pollutants until an applicable federal standard for the industry is issued. The action could result in a substantial reduction in paperwork, while still protecting public health. It also allows states a transition period to prevent project delays for sources where construction is about to start.

<P>

The proposal limits requirements to the facilities where air toxic emissions are likely to be highest-, such as the construction of new facilities, and the reconstruction of large existing facilities. The proposed regulation removes the complex requirements for modifications at existing facilities. An existing source would only be affected if it adds or rebuilds a large production line or process that emits air toxics above the "major" source threshold in the Clean Air Act (above 10 tons annually for any single pollutant or above 25 tons annually for a combination of pollutants). 

<P>

Under the 1990 Amendments to the Act, EPA is required to regulate by category major industrial facilities that emit one or more of 189 congressionally-listed air toxics. EPA has already issued air toxic standards for 47 different industrial categories and expects to regulate most remaining industries by the year 2000.

<P>

The proposal is computer-accessible immediately through EPA's Technology Transfer Network (TTN) at (919) 541-5742 under "Recently Signed Rules" on the TTN's Clean Air Act Amendments bulletin board.

<HR>

<H2>ISO 14000 Update</H2>
The final voting on the proposed ISO 1400x series of standards related to environmental management systems (EMSs) is scheduled to be complete by April 1996. No substantial changes from the proposed standards or requirements are expected. Insurance companies in the United Kingdom, Japan, and Switzerland are prepared to promise rate reductions for companies which promote "best environmental practices" including installing an ISO 14001 EMS. The US DOE has stated that certification under the ISO standards will be required of certain contractors beyond 1997. Several state agencies are meeting to determine what regulatory relief will be available to companies or organizations certified under the ISO standards.

<P>

In a related note, an Arthur D. Little survey reported that 60 percent of managers of large corporations surveyed see certification as a competitive advantage in the market place. The same survey reported that 90 percent stated that their EMS should be at least equivalent to the minimum ISO 14001 requirements.

<P>

Now is the time to get informed about these important standards and to begin the first steps in meeting the requirements that will most probably lead to reduced waste or compliance costs.

<HR>
