<A NAME="EPCRA"><HR></A>

<CENTER><H1>Upcoming Changes for EPCRA Reporters</H1></CENTER>

<P>

<CENTER><H5><A HREF="EMPL.HTM#Esther">Esther Christian<BR>Environmental Consultant</A></H5></CENTER>

<P>

TRI reporting requirements are expanding! Spring of this year is expected to bring changes in the TRI reporting requirements. EPA plans to announce several changes which will affect facilities required to file Toxic Release Inventory reports, commonly referred to as the TRI or Form R reports.
<P> 
The TRI program was formed under Section 313 of the Emergency Planning and Community Right-To-Know Act, (EPCRA) or SARA Title III, in order to establish a publicly available database of toxic chemical information. Under the Act, facilities are required to report their environmental releases of any of the more than 600 listed toxic chemicals which are made, produced, or used by the facility in quantities equal to or in excess of specified amounts. Reporting facilities must submit their TRI reports to EPA and state agencies annually by July 1 of each year.
<P>
For some time, according to EPA, there has been interest in expanding the TRI to include additional facilities and requiring a more comprehensive data set be reported. The last significant phase of TRI expansion was a 1994 chemical expansion rule that added 286 new chemicals and chemical categories to the TRI list of toxic chemicals. The upcoming second expansion phase adds to the types of industries covered by the TRI requirements. EPA states that the third expansion phase could fill in what the agency says are "remaining data collection gaps" by providing information on chemicals moving through communities and workplaces in products.
<P>
Currently, only facilities that fall within Standard Industrial Classification Codes (SIC) 20-39 and federal facilities have the potential to be subject to regulation under the Section 313 requirements. Industries that EPA is considering for addition to the reporting requirement include electric utilities, waste management facilities, mining, and oil and gas production facilities. Materials recovery and recycling activities as well as certain warehousing activities may also be included.
<P>
According to an EPA issues paper released in the fall of 1995, another change in the TRI reporting program is expected to be announced in March of this year. This modification is an expansion of the type of chemical end use and chemical exposure data that EPA obtains through the TRI reports. The issues paper was in response to an August 8, 1995 memorandum, issued in conjunction with Executive Order No. 12969, from President Clinton to EPA Administrator Carol Browner. In the memorandum, EPA was directed to develop and implement a plan to expand the TRI reporting requirements by adding information on mass balance, materials accounting, or other chemical use data to the reporting form.
<P>
According to the issues paper, EPA may include materials accounting data and worker exposure information in future versions of the TRI report format. Materials accounting (MA) involves determining the amount of a chemical at key points in its progression through the processes at a facility. MA differs from engineering mass balance in that mass balance is a more technical procedure and requires the measurement of process streams. In the past, the National Research Council has concluded that a materials accounting approach would satisfy the public right-to-know intent of TRI and would also create less of a reporting burden to industries subject to these requirements.
<P>
The issues paper stated that EPA is considering adding the following data elements to the TRI:
<P>
<UL>  
<LI>	Starting amount of raw material inventory;
<LI>	Amount of toxic chemicals brought on-site;
<LI>	Amount of toxic chemicals produced or manufactured on-site;
<LI>	Amount of toxic chemicals processed on-site;
<LI>	Amount of toxic chemicals otherwise used;
<LI>	Total input amount of toxic chemicals;
<LI>	Amount of toxic chemicals shipped off-site;
<LI>	Ending raw material amount;
<LI>	Amount of toxic chemicals stored on-site in product;
<LI>	Amount of toxic chemicals shipped off-site in product;
<LI>	Total number of workers on-site;
<LI>	Number of workers potentially exposed to the reported toxic chemicals; and
<LI>	Whether exposure monitoring has been performed at the site.
</UL>
<P>
Six data gaps in the current TRI, which EPA may choose to address in future actions, were identified in the issues paper. These data gaps include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>	Lack of information on the flow and use of toxic chemicals at a facility;
<LI>	Need to track toxic chemicals in products;
<LI>	Need for a scorecard to promote and track pollution prevention/source reduction efforts;
<LI>	Lack of a ledger check on TRI estimates;
<LI>	Need to enhance the TRI for regulatory integration efforts; and 
<LI>	Need to identify and research issues such as multiple chemical exposures.
</UL>
<P>
Contact EPA at (202) 554-1404 to obtain a copy of the issues paper and stay updated on changes by attending any of Environmental Resource Center's nationwide SARA Title III seminars. Call 800-537-2372 to register today!
<CENTER><IMG SRC="Littlee.GIF" ALT="End"></CENTER>
