<A NAME="Records"><HR></A>

<CENTER><H1>Maintaining Training Records</H1></CENTER>

<P>

<CENTER><H5><A HREF="EMPL.HTM#Scott">Scott Birchfield<BR>Senior Environmental Consultant</A></H5></CENTER>

<P>

<IMG SRC="Computer.GIF" WIDTH="126" HEIGHT="144" ALT="Computer" ALIGN="LEFT">

A clear understanding of an employee's work functions and an understanding of the training programs required by each regulatory agency is essential to maintaining compliance with the multiple laws governing training for employees who work with potentially dangerous chemicals. Each employee's duties and the chemicals they work with should be evaluated and documented to establish the applicability of environmental, safety, and health training requirements.
<P>
Take Jeff, for example, a degreaser technician, who operates a parts washing machine that uses methylene chloride. On a weekly schedule, Jeff drains the used degreasing solvent from the machine and places it in 55 gallon drums. The used solvents are transported to a solvent recovery facility to be recycled every 90 days.
Jeff's duties and the chemicals he works with require OSHA hazard communication training, RCRA hazardous waste training, and DOT hazmat training.
<P>
The topics that must be covered under these three programs overlap significantly. Each training program is regulated by a different agency and during an inspection you need to show clear documentation that all employees have met each particular agency's training requirements.
<P>
Due to the complexity of the information that must be presented, the differences in the frequency of training, and the independent certification requirements, employee training documentation must be managed very carefully. In industrial settings where there are many employees who must receive training, a computer database such as <A HREF="TRNTRK.HTM">Training Management Software (TMS)</A> is useful to manage and document training compliance. In <A HREF="TRNTRK.HTM">Training Management Software (TMS)</A>, each employee has an independent file which identifies their work function, the training topics required for that employee, the required frequency of training, and the latest training date for each topic.
<P>
At any time a training record can be generated that shows any or all of the training that Jeff has received. This information can be arranged to document compliance with each regulatory program. Also, the database will warn the user of any employee who has a training deficiency. This allows a manager to track, document, and schedule training modules to ensure compliance.
<P>
When evaluating training compliance, the three regulatory agencies will request to see different types of documentation. The databases allow you to generate pre-selected reports that are specific to the requirements of a regulatory inspection.
<A HREF="TRNTRK.HTM">Training Management Software (TMS)</A>;  is essential to keeping your facility in compliance. See for yourself by calling 1-800-537-2372 for a free demo disk or <A HREF="DEMOS.HTM">download a copy here</A>.
<CENTER><IMG SRC="Littlee.GIF" ALT="End"></CENTER>
<P><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
