<A NAME="WasteMin"><HR></A>

<CENTER><H1>Waste Minimization Pays Off: Employee Involvement</H1></CENTER>

<P>

<CENTER><H5><A HREF="EMPL.HTM#Mike">Mike Randall<BR>Vice President</A></H5></CENTER>

<P>

<IMG SRC="WasteMin.GIF" ALT="Waste Minimization" ALIGN="LEFT">

Waste minimization strategies that go <I>Beyond Compliance</I>   are a long term solution to rising waste management costs and disposal liabilities. Preventing or eliminating waste at its source not only makes sense for long term environmental health, it can result in substantial benefits.
<P>
It takes informed employees to achieve waste minimization. Since employees are ultimately the people that will implement waste prevention ideas, make them a part of waste minimization strategies. Teach them the company and employee benefits of waste minimization strategies.
<P>
<H3>Economic Benefits</H3>

Regulations governing the handling, storage, treatment, and disposal of waste have caused a significant increase in waste management costs. Reduction efforts offer a way to reduce disposal, permitting, and insurance costs. Also, production costs are reduced through better management and reuse of spent materials, thus reducing the risk of employee layoffs.
<P> 
You may decide to reward employees for their efforts toward waste minimization. These rewards may be either financial or in the form of personal recognition, or both. You could: 
<OL>
<LI>return some of the savings to the budget of the department that generated the savings; 
<LI>establish a special bonus for teams that achieve their waste minimization goals;
<LI>use some of the savings to buy successful team members "waste buster" jackets or coffee mugs; 
<LI>use the savings for high priority budget items that were not funded; or 
<LI>send your entire team to an Environmental Resource Center workshop in Orlando!
</OL>
<P>
<H3>Decreased Employee Exposure</H3>

Waste minimization strategies that reduce the volume or toxicity of waste also decrease employee exposure to toxic constituents making jobs easier and safer.
<P>
<H3>Environmental Benefits & Minimization of Liability</H3>

Myth No. 1: When waste leaves the plant, it is gone for good. Improper waste management may someday pollute your workers' neighborhoods and potentially harm their families. How we manage (or mismanage) hazardous waste is a crucial environmental issue with vast implications for public health and the ecological systems on which we depend.
<P>
<H3>Improvement of Corporate Image</H3>

Because of several incidents in the past involving industrial wastes, the general public is extremely sensitive to industrial releases and mismanagement of wastes. In addition, the public is becoming increasingly more informed. Consumers are looking at your company's policies, and a positive image associated with reducing waste could improve public perception about your company.
<P>
<H3>Government Mandate</H3>

Section 3002(b) of RCRA requires hazardous waste generators who ship hazardous waste off-site to certify on the manifest that an economically practicable waste minimization program is in place at their facilities, and the generator has selected the practicable method of treatment, storage, or disposal currently available. Section 3005(h) requires owners/operators of permitted on-site treatment, storage, and disposal facilities to make the same certification at least annually. Small quantity generators certify on the manifest that they have made a good faith effort to minimize the generation of hazardous waste and have selected the best, affordable waste management method available.
<P>
This column, "Waste Minimization Pays Off" explores what companies have done to minimize or prevent waste. Sharing successful waste minimization programs will serve to benefit everyone. If your company has had success in waste minimization and you would like to share your experience, please <A HREF="mailto:mrandall@ercweb.com">e-mail</A> or mail your story to 

<P>

<CENTER><I>Beyond Compliance</I><BR>
 Environmental Resource Center<BR>
101 Center Pointe Drive<BR>
Cary, North Carolina 27513-5706.</CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="Littlee.GIF" ALT="End"></CENTER>
<P><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
