<A NAME="WasteMin"><HR></A>



<CENTER><H1>Waste Minimization Pays Off</H1></CENTER>

<CENTER><H5>Mike Randall<BR>
Vice President, Consulting</H5></CENTER>

<IMG  SRC="WORLDIN.GIF"  ALT="World In Hands" ALIGN=Left Height = 70 Width = 63>

Confronted with escalating costs for waste disposal and concerns for increased liabilities, companies and government agencies and installations that generate waste have responded with waste minimization strategies. Many of these minimization strategies go <I>Beyond Compliance</I> .
Frequently, good materials are disposed of as waste before they are spent. Employees are usually the first to recognize waste, and with encouragement, can minimize waste. Here are just four ways employees can save money:<BR>
 
<OL>
<LI>Many preventative maintenance programs set specific times to change filter media; instead, encourage employees to change filters only when they are spent. An increase in pressure drop, indicated by a differential pressure gage, across the filter bag is a good indicator that it is time to change a dirty filter. Also available are filters on rolls that automatically advance when the pressure across the filter media builds up.
<LI>Many materials that are removed from filter housing, pipes or hoses, and containers may still be usable. Frequently, these materials can be used directly in the process or transferred to a new container.
<LI>Material losses from spills, leaks, and evaporation are difficult to measure and are often underestimated. Consequently, these losses are often a low priority. One leak, extrapolated over a year, and multiplied by the number of such leaks can be significant. Although it seems obvious, we often fail to recognize that material leaking is being paid for three times. First, as raw materials; second, for disposal; and third, to replace it. The best leak detection system available today may be employees.
<LI>Create an in-plant waste exchange. If one department or shop area has unused or partially used materials that they want to dispose of, check to see if another department needs it before they dispose of it. Anything from unused bench stock or partially filled aerosol containers is a candidate. If you can't use it on-site, maybe someone else can use it off-site. Make sure, however, that wastes use it for a beneficial purpose and be sure that they are not speculatively accumulated.
</OL>
<CENTER><IMG  SRC="Littlee.GIF" ALT="End"></CENTER><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
