<A NAME="ISO14001"><HR></A>


<CENTER><H1>Getting Started on the ISO 14001 Certification Process</H1></CENTER>

<CENTER><h5>Dr. Ed Walsh<br>
Senior Environmental Consultant</h5></CENTER>




<IMG  SRC="ISOGlobe.GIF"  ALT="ISO 14001" ALIGN=LEFT>

The International Standards Organization (ISO) has established standards for environmental compliance that go well beyond simply meeting legal requirements.  These standards make up the ISO 14001 program. The five elements of the program include:
<BR>

<OL>
<LI>Commitment and Policy
<LI>Planning
<LI>Implementation
<LI>Measurement and Evaluation
<LI>Review and Improvement
</OL>

<BR>
If your organization has been involved with the ISO 9000 standards related to quality certification, you will note a definite similarity.  The intent of the ISO 14001 standards is to define structured systems that recognize organizations with a systematic approach to continual improvement of environmental management. Although the final requirements of the ISO certification process have not yet been confirmed by all of the ISO committees, there is currently enough information available to allow you to begin preparations.
Start the process by establishing your organization's policy and commitment statements and conducting a survey of your existing systems to determine actions or changes which will be required to meet the standards.
During the survey of your existing systems, you should:

<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Identify the legislative and regulatory requirements which impact your facility
<LI>Identify the environmental aspects of all activities, products, and services produced or conducted at your facility to determine which may produce significant environmental impact or liabilities
<LI>Evaluate your performance compared to relevant internal criteria, external standards, regulations, codes of practice, and benchmarks
<LI>Determine your existing environmental management practices and procedures
<LI>Identify existing policies and procedures related to procurement and contracting
<LI>Examine feedback and reports from the investigations of previous incidents or non-compliance situations
<LI>Examine opportunities for competitive advantage in your industry due to your management of environmental issues
<LI>Determine the views of all parties that will be incorporated into the program from existing programs
<LI>Determine existing functions or activities that may enable or impede environmental performance
</UL><BR>


Concurrent with the review process, your organization should establish a formal policy which clearly defines your organization's commitment and goals related to the environment, continual review, and improvement.  It is not necessary for this statement to stand alone; it may be part of a larger organizational policy statement, but certain elements must be present in order to establish it as an ISO 14001 policy statement.
The following questions can serve as a guide to the construction of your policy statement:

<BR>
<OL>
<LI>Does your organization currently have an environmental policy that is relevant to all of your activities, as well as any products or services produced?
<LI>Does the policy reflect your organization's values and guiding principles?
<LI>Has the environmental policy been approved by top management and has someone been identified and given the authority to oversee and implement the policy?
<LI>Does the policy guide the setting of environmental objectives and targets?
<LI>Does the policy guide your organization towards monitoring appropriate technology and management practices?
<LI>What commitments are embodied in the environmental policy (e.g. support for continual improvement, support for pollution prevention, meeting and monitoring legal requirements, worker training, considering the expectations of other interested parties, etc.)?
</OL>
<BR>

The policy should be a comprehensive document designed to guide the progress of the company in environmental compliance throughout many years to come. While the policy may be used to set short term goals and objectives, specific items should not be included in the policy.  The inclusion of specific items in a guiding policy will make it necessary to revise the policy frequently and undermine its credibility as a long-term document.
Once your organization has completed the review process and developed a policy statement, you will be well on your way to compliance with ISO 14001 standards when they are finalized. This early preparation will pay off in dividends of lowered compliance costs, higher quality goods and services, and goodwill towards your neighbors for years to come.<BR>
<BR>

 
<i>Edward Walsh, Ph.D. has over 18 years experience in environmental management. He is an expert on environmental health and safety regulations, has performed over 200 environmental, health, and safety audits, and is the author of more than 25 articles and papers on a wide variety of environmental topics. He may be reached at Environmental Resource Center at (919) 469-1585.</i><BR>
<BR>
<CENTER><IMG  SRC="Littlee.GIF" ALT="End"></CENTER><BR>
