<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>USAF RDLL</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H2>The United States Air Force Research and Development Liaison Office - London  <BR>
(USAF RDLL)</H2>

<H3>Background</H3>

USAF RDLL was created in the mid 1980s to place specific representation in-country for USAF international cooperative R&D, acquisition (including acquisition logistics) (ICRDA) with the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland (UK).  USAF RDLL works closely with other organizations in the UK that participate in the broad ICRDA mission spectrum. Three are collocated with USAF RDLL in the Edison House in London:  the USAF European Office of Aerospace Research and Development (EOARD), the Office of Naval Research-Europe (ONREUR), and the US Army Research, Development, and Standardization Group (USARDSG).  Another is the DOD Office of Defense Cooperation (ODC) in the US embassy. <P> 

The focus then and now is to integrate the broad range of activities touching on but beyond the "science" mission of the EOARD and touching on but not overlapping with the "Foreign Military Sales" mission of the ODC-London.  Also, in contrast to EOARDs pan-European coverage, RDLL concentrates on the UK.  In contrast to ODC-Londons DOD interests, USAF RDLL concentrates on USAF interests.  <P>

USAF RDLL reports to the Deputy Under Secretary of the Air Force (International Affairs) Armaments Cooperation Division (SAF/IAQ).  When communicating with USAF RDLL consider it "SAF/IAQ(UK)".  The term USAF RDLL derives from the fact that the much older, original, sister office in Bonn GE has always used the simple abbreviation "RDLO", stemming most likely from an old HQ USAF organizational symbol, AF/RDLO, reporting to AF/RD-I.  What was once AF/RD-I became SAF/AQXI in the late 1980s.  In 1994, SAF/IAQ was created out of the former SAF/AQXI.<P>

<H3>Mission</H3><P>

As we were quoted in a recent (3 Sep 94) Janes Defence Weekly article, "USAF RDLL is to maximize the benefits of and demonstrate USAF commitment to US-UK cooperation in order to strengthen USAF capabilities through acquisition of the best technologies available and interoperability".  In simpler terms, the mission of USAF RDLL is to seek out, promote, and support ICRDA for the mutual benefit of the USAF and the UK.  USAF RDLL works closely with the British Ministry of Defence (MOD) and its RDT&E support establishments, including the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency (DERA) as of 1 Apr 95, and industry.  The Janes article expands in detail on USAF RDLL.  There are seven areas of mission responsibility:  

<OL>
<LI>Identify key UK technologies and requirements.  This is accomplished through close observation and interaction with the MOD Operational Requirements and Scientific Staffs, DERAs Defence Research Agency (DRA) and the other establishments, and through meetings and visits with UK defense equipment suppliers.  The last are often referred to USAF RDLL by the Defence Export Services Organization (DESO).  USAF RDLL does not indiscriminantly send UK industry knocking on USAF lab and program office doors.  We screen and advise industry if they have something of potential interest to the USAF, what points are of main interest, and how to communicate with American customers, then attempt to coordinate with the right people to review the technological information before ever passing industry along.  This area is among the toughest to work due to our limited resources and the nature of the area.
<P>
<LI>Advise US/UK senior leadership of their counterparts government/industry policies, procedures, organization, and situation.  This is accomplished mainly in two ways:  1) by obtaining information and briefing various audiences, 2) by collecting news items from sources not readily available in the US and forwarding to selected audiences and/or publishing summaries in London Calling!, the USAF RDLL newsletter.  This area has taken increasing proportions of USAF RDLL resources as the Post Cold War Era brings on massive reorganizations and physical moves on both sides.
<P>
<LI>Prompt, arrange, and facilitate meetings and visits among appropriate officials.  USAF RDLL also accompanies visitors who need help in-country.  USAF RDLL enjoys special rates at a convenient hotel nearby for visitors.  For the convenience of its visitors, USAF RDLL maintains a visitor support office in its suite for visitors to work.  Visits to the UK are not "controlled" by USAF RDLL, but visitors are encouraged to inform USAF RDLL via their country clearance message if their upcoming visit is of a USAF "R&D" nature.  Informing us of your business here helps us be prepared to support you.  Refer to DOD 4500.54-G.  Please note, visitors in the context of extensive support means government personnel and government support contractors on official business.   
<P>
<LI>Lead or assist in the negotiation/tracking of agreements.  This is accomplished as required to ensure the viability and value of the numerous information (data) exchange and development memoranda of understanding.  Often our knowledge of an existing agreement itself is enough to solve a problem in cooperation.  The art of creating an international partnership is in place here through previous experience and training at the Defense Systems Management College and UK institutions.  Fortunately, as this area also grows due to the Post Cold War Era prompting a renaissance in cooperation, the support tools and community of experienced "internationalists" are also growing.  For US government visitors, we have the International Agreements Generator on hand.
<P>
<LI>Establish new relations to expand cooperation.  This area is both an adventure and a challenge.  There are several MOD organizations for which there is little direct interaction with the USAF.  At the same time, some of these organizations are being subsumed under DERA, while others are being deactivated.  The RAF itself, in the acquisition logistics area, is an example of cooperation USAF RDLL is seeking to expand.
<P>
<LI>Provide critical communications/terminology support.  USAF RDLL provides visitors voice, fax, and secure voice commercial and DSN dedicated lines.  Additionally, it is procuring a portable secure telephone unit and upgrading its secure telephone function to identify in finer detail the type of call based on the participants on this end.  USAF RDLL enjoys the latest technology in internet access and e-mail sevices, and word processing, spreadsheet, and graphics applications, thanks to the host of experts in the Edison House.  Terminology support seems rarely needed, but is in fact integral to international cooperation, even between the US and the UK.  For example, to "table" an issue in the UK means essentially the opposite of the US meaning.  Here it means to bring something to immediate discussion.  If you tell someone to "call first", here it will not necessarily mean to "phone first".  Speaking of phoning, USAF RDLL has broadcast the country-wide telephone area code change of 1995, and stands ready as always to locate anyone in the ICRDA business in the UK as change continues.
<P>
<LI>Administer assigned activities in-country.  USAF RDLL supports the Air Senior National Representatives meetings in-country, processes proposed Nunn-funded project and other agreements, and will act for EOARD as required in the placement and oversight of USAF participants in the UK under the Engineer and Scientist Exchange Program.
</OL>
<P>
<HR>
