<HEAD>
<TITLE>Created With HTML Assistant Pro - 12/16/96</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Naval International Cooperative Opportunities
in Science and Technology Program (NICOP)</H2>

<H3>PROGRAM GUIDANCE<BR>
November 1996</H3>

The Office of Naval Research (ONR) Naval International Cooperative Opportunities in Science and Technology Program (NICOP) fosters international cooperative S&T through:<P>

(a)  Development of strategies and supporting regional and country plans for DON international cooperation in S&T;<BR>
(b)  Construction of a distributed data base of international S&T contacts and capabilities; and
  Cost-sharing with other S&T Sponsors to encourage and support high quality collaborative international S&T projects that respond to DON priorities.<P>

NICOP is one of the major programmatic mechanisms by which the ONR International Field Offices support DON objectives by identifying opportunities for S&T collaboration and encouraging US sponsors to participate in them.  The program is administered by ONR Europe on behalf of the International Field Offices. <BR>
This memorandum provides information on the cost-sharing portion of the program, and more specifically on the submission of requests for the next semi-annual deadline, 15 January 1997.<P>

NICOP Cost-Sharing Program:<P>

The objective of this portion of NICOP is to encourage and support long-term collaboration between US and international researchers on projects of major importance to DON.  Ideally, NICOP projects result from co-planning of S&T programs between US and partner sponsors and researchers, and lead to co-development of naval concepts and systems.  Dedicated planning workshops are encouraged to develop NICOP proposals.  The international Field Office Conference Support Programs are appropriate vehicles for supporting such planning workshops.<P>

The next selection will pay particular attention to larger projects, in this context viewed to be greater than $100K, which have significant potential to impact DON requirements.  Smaller projects which address country-specific interests of the DON/ONR; provide NICOP program balance between basic and applied research; or foster new collaborations, will also be considered.  All projects, regardless of size, will be judged on technical merit; potential impact on Naval needs and ONR objectives; and potential for long-term collaboration.<P>
  
To be eligible for NICOP cost sharing, a project must provide for face-to-face exchange of technical expertise and perspective among participating US and international scientists and engineers.  International participants may be from any nation other than the US, and substantial portions of the research must be accomplished outside of the US.<P>

The format for requests is  Attachment 1.  Approximately 50% of the NICOP funding allocated for any fiscal year will be competitively awarded after each deadline.  Thus of the $1M allocated for FY97, approximately $500K will be available for the next competitive award, which will be determined from those requests received prior to the 15 January 1997 deadline.<P>

All requests must be submitted by, or with the endorsement and financial commitment of, the sponsor who will share costs with NICOP.  In addition, all requests submitted from sponsors other than ONR Program Officers (POs) must contain a comment from the cognizant ONR PO; this is intended to keep NICOP projects consistent with core ONR programs.<P>

NICOP awards will be made by funds transfer to the sponsor who requests the cost-share; that sponsor will be responsible for all grants & contracts, and for management of the projects.  NICOP will assist as requested and periodically will request follow-up information on progress.<P>

NICOP generally will provide no more than 50% of the US contribution to the costs of the non-US researchers.  NICOP funds generally will not be used to support the US partners costs.  However, it is understood that foreign investigators ability to participate financially vary widely. <BR>
In some instances, more than 50% of the award may be required to be invested abroad, or alternatively, some funds may be required to be invested domestically to insure a collaboration with a well-supported foreign partner moves forward.  Requests for exception to either of these guidelines must be explained in detail.  <P>

Procedures<P>

1. Forward requests for NICOP cost-sharing support, in the format of  Attachment 1, to ONR Europe.  Requests should be less than three pages long (Courier 12 pitch).<BR>
2. ONREUR will acknowledge all requests, discuss their completeness (but not quality) with the requester,  and maintain a data base of their status.<BR>
3. ONREUR will consider all requests before a selection board and recommend approval of awards, with justification, to DCNR prior to 1 Feb 97.<BR>
4. For successful requests, the sponsor who requested NICOP cost sharing will be notified of the amount and duration of the NICOP award. If that sponsor decides to proceed as proposed with the amount of support to be provided by NICOP, ONREUR will provide ONR Headquarters the necessary information on funds transfer.  If that sponsor decides that the NICOP award is inadequate to permit the program to proceed as planned, the funds will be either be awarded to another request, or held until the next call.<P>

Comments and Suggestions<P>

Based upon questions asked during the first round (15 Sep 96) of NICOP awards, the following hints may prove useful:<P>

There are no geographic or institutional restrictions on NICOP participants, except that each project must involve collaboration between US and non-US investigators.<P>

Collaborations should be mutually beneficial, and match strength to strength.<P>

If the project is military-to-military, information exchange must be covered by a DEA or similar agreement.<P>

The intent of NICOP cost-sharing is to fund projects where the US should appropriately bear some or all of the costs of the international participant.<P>

Requests that come directly from investigators, without the commitment of another US sponsor to share costs with NICOP, will not be considered.  It is the responsibility of investigators to identify such sponsors,   although ONR Europe and ONR Asia will help international investigators locate potential sources of support.  The reason for this requirement is that NICOP is not a stand-alone program. Rather it seeks to support and encourage US sponsors to take advantage of international opportunities.   It does this by assistance from the ONR International Field Offices with planning and coordination (via, e.g., liaison visits, conference and visit support), and by providing some financial support for the international portion of the work. <P>

Intellectual property rights are a significant issue for all projects that do not result solely in new knowledge that is published in the open literature.  The International Field Office in Europe has an Intellectual Property Rights lawyer on site who can assist with advice, although in all cases final negotiations and decisions will be made by the contracting office that supports the requesting sponsor.<P>

Not all cost sharing must come from an ONR source.  Other government agencies, universities, industry and philanthropic organizations can participate in sharing. However, NICOP is an ONR program, and the projects it supports must be important to the command.  Therefore all requests must have a comment from an appropriate ONR Program Officer, discussing how the project will enhance the ONR core program.<P>

NICOP has two annual deadlines for submission of requests for cost sharing: 15 June and 15 January.  Deadlines dates are hard.<P>

Please use e-mail for submitting requests and communicating. The best address for the 15 Jan 97 call is -<A HREF="mailto:nicop@onreur.navy.mil">nicop@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>

There are no set rules regarding the amount of support that NICOP will provide to any project, or to the number of years supported (subject to appropriated funds).  However, the bias is toward focused collaborative programs that can substantially impact major DON initiatives.  NICOP will seek to have maximum impact for money available.<P>

Full proposals need not accompany requests.  If they are available, fine.  However, many international collaborative projects are best finalized in formal proposals after the available funding has been determined, i.e. after it is known whether or not a NICOP award has been won.  The simple request, per the Attachment 1 format, is adequate.  The request must however contain adequate technical and managerial information that a decision can be made based on the criteria mentioned above.  Research objectives, procedures, and participants must be clearly identified.  Funding amounts and sources required for the total project must also be described, so that the scope of the effort can be understood; and in particular, the use of the share requested from NICOP, its destination, and the nature of the share from the other US sponsor, must be clearly identified.  Requests for exception to the above guidelines must be clear and compelling.<P>

The cost sharing rules caused considerable confusion during the first round, so they need some discussion. NICOP is a relatively small program, and its objective is to involve the best international scientists in important US S&T thrusts in which they ordinarily would not participate.  Because the US is actively seeking and promoting the collaboration, it is appropriate that the US fund some or all of the costs of the international participant.  Some contribution by the international partner is of course encouraged, since the project must be one that they will benefit from.  In projects which are independently supported both here and abroad, NICOP could be used to provide the "glue" (e.g., travel, shared international graduate students or post-docs, etc.) that ties together efforts in the US and abroad.<P>

NICOP is designed to encourage S&T sponsors to think more broadly about international opportunities.  Therefore it requires them to initiate the request for cost sharing and leaves program management completely in their hands.<P>

As with all ONR projects, the likelihood of support is considerably enhanced by prior consultation with the sponsor.  For NICOP, that means with an International Field Office staff member; with the ONR Program Officer; and most importantly, with the sponsor who is officially making the request for cost sharing.<P>

Our overall objective is to encourage collaborations that result from co-planning of S&T projects and that ultimately lead to co-development of naval concepts and systems.<P>

<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/onreur.htm">Return to previous page</A>

