<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Progress in Electromagnetics Research Symposium 1996</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<CENTER><H3>Progress in Electromagnetics Research Symposium 1996 (PIERS'96)</H3>
<I>Report to the<BR>
Office of Naval Research European Office<BR>
and the U. S. Army Research and Standardization Group</I></CENTER><P>
by H. Rott<BR>
General Chairman, PIERS'96<P>

The Symposium took place in the Congress Center, Innsbruck, Austria, from 8 July to 12 July 1996. 560 scientists from 41 countries participated.<P>

On 8 July, morning, a plenary session was held with opening addresses and review papers on Computational Electromagnetics and on Remote Sensing Use of Multisatellite Constellations.  Between Monday noon and Friday noon 72 session with oral presentations of papers on a wide range of topics in electromagnetic theory and its applications was held.  The session were organised in thematic streams with the main topics:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Electromagnetic theory and computational electromagnetics
<LI>Wave propagation in the atmosphere and atmospheric remote sensing (with emphasis on microwaves, radar, and communication)
<LI>Scattering theory and inverse scattering for surfaces and media
<LI>Radar and optical remote sensing of the earth surface (with emphasis on quantitative methods for vegetation, cryosphere, and hydrosphere)
<LI>Radar signal processing, interferometry and polarimetry
<LI>Antenna theory and applications 
<LI>Wave propagation in planar structures and in complex media 
<LI>Guided waves
</UL>

Detailed information on the sessions and presented papers is contained in the Final Program and in the PIERS'96 Proceedings which have been sent to ONR Europe by separate mail.  A high percentage of the papers at the conference contained significant and new contributions.  This high standard was reflected in scientifically stimulating discussions throughout the 5 days of the conference, both during the sessions as well as during breaks and unofficial meetings.<P>

Below is a summary on the contributions of the supported invitees.  Though representing only a small part of the whole symposium, these contributions reflect well the diversity and actuality of the papers presented at PIERS'96.<P>

<B>Contributions of the supported scientists</B><P>

The attendance of 11 scientists from Russia and Ukraine was supported by the grant of ONR Europe.  The papers presented by these scientists gave clear evidence that the level of theoretical research in electromagnetics, and in some fields also of experimental research, is very high in these countries.  The symposium provided the opportunity to discuss potential collaborations and to exchange information on ongoing and planned research activities.<P>

All the papers presented by the supported scientists were of good quality.  The papers covered topics in the field of radiowave propagation, radar polarimetry, atmospheric remote sensing, wave propagation in media.<P>

The papers were presented in the Following sessions:<P>

<I>Session on Transhorizon Tropospheric UHF/VHF Radiowave Propagation</I>.  This session was organised and chaired by Prof <I>G. V. Sharygin</I>. 10 papers on original results of experimental investigations and on theory of UHF/VHF tropospheric propagation beyond the horizon were presented.  In spite of financial difficulties the investigations m this field are going on in Russia, because they are very important for telecommunication.<BR>
<I>G.S. Sharygin</I>: Review on recent experimental research Russia regarding tropospheric VHF wave propagation.<BR>
<I>Yu. P. Akulinichev</I>: (i) on theory of trans-horizon propagation and experimental verifications at 100 to 3000 MHz over the Sea of Okhotsk and the Caspian Sea; (ii) on experimental studies of temporal and spatial correlation lengths in the atmosphere related to radiowave propagation.<BR>
<I>T.I. Arsenyan</I>: on studies of turbulence with laser beams to describe the atmospheric conditions for transhorizon radiowave propagation.<BR>
<I>VN. Troitsky</I>: on experimental studies of transhorizon propagation at 1 and 6 GHz in mountain areas of the Kamchatka Peninsula.<P>

<I>Session on Scattering Phenomena at Transition between Periodic and Disordered Structures.  SA. Bulgakov</I>: (i) on modelling of electromagnetic field distribution in 1-D random photonic lattices; (ii) on electromagnetic wave propagation through photonic superlattices with different structural topologies.<P>

<I>Session on Transport and Localisation of electromagnetic Waves in Media with Volume and Surface Disorder
A. V Ilyenkov</I>: on (i) theoretical and (ii) experimental studies on evolution and annihilation of phase singularities in laser beams passing through photorefractive crystals.<P>

<I>Session on Electromagnetic Modelisation of Microwave Planar Components 
I Vendik</I>: on modelling the propagation characteristics of high-Tc (HTS) superconductor devices. <P>

<I>Session on the Use of high Tc Superconductors in Active and Passive Circuits 
I Vendik</I>: on modelling of high-Tc (HTS) superconductor resonators and filters for design purposes.<P>

<I>Session on Polarimetric Radar Sensing, Imaging and lnterferometric Topography
V.N.  Tatarinov</I>: (i) on the calculation of bistatic cross-sections including polarimetric characteristics for radar detection of small, complex targets; (ii) on experimental studies of radar cross-sections and polarization characteristics of artificial targets and distributed background.<BR>
<I>E.A. Loutin</I>: on polarimetric algorithms for the detection of natural and artificial targets.<P>

<I>Session on Polarimetric and Doppler Methods of Atmospheric Remote Sensing
V. V Sterlyadkin</I>: on laboratory measurements and theory of optical properties of nonspherical and oscillating water drops; the results are of interest for inversion of radar measurements.<BR>
<I>F.R Yanovsky</I>: on experimental and theoretical studies of radar reflection and polarimetric properties of clouds and precipitation.<P>

<I>Session on Remote Sensing of the Atmosphere
V V. Sterlyadkin</I>: on theoretical studies and numerical simulations of the Doppler-correlation method for determining the atmospheric wind field.

<P><HR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A>
</BODY></HTML>
