<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Trip Report #7-96</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>15 April 1996<BR>
ONR, NRL and Warfare Center Trip Reports<BR>
Smadar Karni, Temple University and Courant Institute<P>

Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
Trip Report #7-96<BR>
Conference on Hyperbolic Systems of Conservation Laws</H3>

Travel Period: 28 Apr- 4 May 96 1996<P>

<I>Keywords: Applied Mathematics; hyperbolic systems; multi-dimensional problems</I><P>
<PRE><B>
Contents:</B>
1.  Summary
2.  Conference Description
3.  Narrative
4.  Feedback
</PRE>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
The Conference on Hyperbolic Systems of Conservation Laws was held at the Oberwolfach Mathematics Research Institute, Germant, 28 April - 3 May 1996. The Conference covered recent theoretical and computational advances in solving hyperbolic systems of conservation laws, and the application of the new ideas to solving problems in fluid mechanics, solid mechanics, phase transitions, and two phase fluid flows.  The author describes the meeting and discusses 3 issues: the gap between theoretical and computational communities, lack of a criterion for comparing computed solutions in the (usual) absence of an exact solution, and pros and cons of different numerical schemes. See Trip Report #6 for additional views on this conference.<P>

<B>2.  Conference Description</B><BR>
The Mathematics Institute at Oberwolfach is located in the picturesque Black Forest, and runs meetings all year round in the format of one-week workshops devoted to a particular topic.  This is a highly prestigious institute and participation is by invitation only. The forum is usually quite small and the atmosphere is very informal.  Working conditions are ideal, the stay at the institute is very comfortable (and free of charge).  The institute has an impressive mathematics library, convenient  computer access to all and Xerox facilities.  The organization and hospitality are impeccable, and permit participants to concentrate solely on the meeting and make the most out of it. <BR>
The meeting was organized by Constantine Dafermos of Brown University, Dietmar Kroner of University of Freiburg and Randy LeVeque of University of Washington, Seattle.  Participants could choose their preferable format of presentation, ranging from long talks (40 mins.) through medium (20 mins) and short (10 mins.) talks, to leading a discussion session. The program was flexible. It was organized from one day to the next and tried to answer to the interests and requests of the participants. Substantial amount of time was left for discussions, both organized and informal.<BR>
A central aim for the meeting was to bring together  researchers from both the PDE community and the numerical and computational communities and to provide a forum within which to present and discuss the state of research in the field of hyperbolic systems of conservation laws, and get some feel for where the field is going. Indeed, the program provided a nice balance between theory and applications.<P>

<B>3.  Narrative</B><BR>
Among the topics of interest were multidimensional conservation laws, both the theoretical understanding (e.g. self similar solutions) as well as the design and implementation of numerical methods for multidimensional flows; high order numerical schemes for fluid flows, which have less dissipation hence may be more suitable for problems involving long time integration or small amplitudes (e.g. aeroacoustics); low Mach number (near incompressible) flows, where one has to deal with stiffness in the governing equations; reactive flows, two phase flows, and nonequilibrium flows; kinetic models and their gas dynamical limits including numerical schemes with relaxation. <BR>
The program included several informal discussion sessions led by one (or more) participants of the meeting. Several important issues came up. <BR>
(*) The need to bridge the gap between the theoretical and numerical communities and the expectations that these communities have from each other for more fruitful collaborations in the future.  Certain mutual frustration has been voiced.  On the one hand, there are expectation of the theoretical community from the computational/ experimental communities to provide a lead as to what problems are of interest and importance to study, yet realistic problems of interest turn out to be much too hard for theory. On the other hand, the numerical community wants more problems with closed form solutions that have enough 'meat' in them, which could be used to validate schemes, and such closed form solutions are extremely difficult to obtain. <BR>
(*) A criticism has been raised toward the numerical/ computational communities, as to the lack of some tools to assess the accuracy of numerical solutions in situations where exact solutions are not available (as is usually the case).  Is it possible to design a criterion which will enable to compare two computed solutions and decide which one solves the problem better?  I totally agree with this 'complaint', and have already started preliminary work toward establishing such a criterion.<BR>
(*) A useful discussion was held on the dis/advantages<BR>
of genuinely multidimensional schemes versus more 'simple minded' schemes such as  dimensional splitting and 'one and a half' dimensional schemes that are less grid independent. The former contain genuinely multidimensional physics and are 'grid-blind', but are difficult to extend to high order of accuracy, the latter are usually quite straight forward to implement in any number of space dimensions and to extend to higher orders, but suffer some grid dependence.  Here, again, there is no clear winner and one can always find a counter example to any general statement. <BR>
All in all, this was a very good meeting. I presented my work on computations of slowly moving shocks, which are notorious for generating post-shock oscillations.  These oscillations are very undesirable, for example they inhibit convergence of transient solutions to steady states. They occur only in nonlinear systems of conservation laws which makes rigorous analysis difficult. My talk was very well received and raised interest from both the theoreticians and practitioners. <P>

<B>4.  Feedback</B><BR>
For further information on this report, please contact:<P>

	Dr. Smadar Karni<BR>
	Temple University and Courant Institute<BR>
	karni@YALI.CIMS.NYU.EDU<BR>
<I>or</I><BR>
	Dr. Andre M. Van Tilborg<BR>
	ONR 311 Rm 607<BR>
	BCT 1<BR>
	800 North Quincy Street<BR>
	Arlington, VA 232217-5660<BR>
	703-696-4312<BR>
	vantila@onrhq.onr.navy.mil<P><HR><P>
The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A></BODY></HTML>

