<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>S&amp;T Summaries #18</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
Science and Technology Summary #18<BR>
23 January 1997</H3><HR><P>

This is one of a series of reports that summarize the assessments produced by the scientific liaison officers at ONR Europe, by Navy visitors to Europe, Africa, and the Middle East, or by organizers of conferences supported by ONR Europe.  The full reports are available under their by-line on this homepage, or by e-mail to the author.<P>
<B>
Topics:<P>
<OL>
<LI>General European S&T Topics:  
<DD>a.  R&D in Turkey: Overview & Focus on METU and Oceanography
<DD>b.  Computer Science and Education in Europe
<DD>c.  Joint EC-US Workshop on Environmental Biotechnology
<LI>Division of Hydraulics & Environmental Engineering Aristotle University of Thessaloniki
<LI>Marine Technology Directorate Merger
<LI>Conference Reports
<DD>a.  Light Scattering and Photon Correlation Spectroscopy
<DD>b.  Alternate Camera Technology
</OL></B>

<B>1. General European S&T Topics:</B>  
<B>a.  R&D in Turkey: Overview & Focus on METU and 
Oceanography, Craig Dorman</B> (<A HREF="mailto:cdorman@onreur.navy.mil">cdorman@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
Turkey is a staunch ally, a strong NATO partner, and a "Big Emerging Market" with a rapidly growing but volatile economy.  The Turkish Defense Forces remain a highly respected and powerful force for Turkeys secular western orientation.  The Turkish General Staff recognizes the multiple security threats in the region, and plans continued modernization accompanied by expansion of indigenous defense industries through co-production and technology transfer.  Turkey historically has invested very little in R&D, but both defense and commercial trends indicate a significant upswing in the near future; and the Universities, exemplified by the Middle East Technical University (METU), are ready and eager to respond.  One area where Turkey does have a significant world-class scientific capability is oceanography.  Turkish ocean scientists play a leading role in physical and biogeochemical studies of the Eastern Mediterranean and the Black Sea.  The Black Sea is of interest intrinsically, geopolitically, and as a model for both environmental processes and approaches to the remediation of a badly damaged ecosystem.  This newsletter briefly treats this set of issues: defense cooperation and modernization, the Turkish S&T Research Council, METU and its structure for innovation, and METUs Institute of Marine Sciences and the status and plans for Black Sea studies.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/cdnews10.htm">CO/TD Report #10</A><BR>
<B>b.  Computer Science and Education in Europe, Bruce Barnes</B> 
(<A HREF="mailto:bbarnes@nsf.gov">bbarnes@nsf.gov</A>)<BR>
Computer Science and Engineering education in Europe is extremely active and of very high quality.  The programs are vigorous, well structured and taught by highly educated and dedicated faculty.  They tend to be professionally oriented with most of the instruction in Computer Science, Computer Engineering, and Software Engineering; liberal arts and science do not play a very significant role.  Since the programs are professionally oriented, accreditation is a well-established part of the educational infrastructure. The content of European programs is comparable to that of the US.  English language is widely used in European education in computing and many institutions teach some classes in English.  The Masters programs are considered to be part of the undergraduate programs.  The Ph.D. programs are focused almost entirely on research and the thesis, with very little course work or other requirements.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/bbnews29.htm">Newsletter #29</A><BR>
<B>c.  Joint EC-US Workshop on Environmental Biotechnology 
(EB), Igor Vodyanoy</B> (<A HREF="mailto:ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil">ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
The EC-US Task Force on Biotechnology Research encouraged the EU Working Group on EB to support this EC-US workshop, Nov96, Granada, Spain. Objectives were to examine the biochemical and genetic bases of biodegradation in different environments and for the rational design and use of microbes in polluted sites; to foster EC-US cooperation; and to provide research managers with insights, based on case studies, into new directions in EB. 19 research leaders and 20 advanced students and post-docs took part in oral and poster sessions and extensive discussions that generated a number of interesting new research venues. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/ivnews27.htm">Newsletter 27</A> summarizes the discussions and directions, lists presented papers, and describes the EC-US Task Force and the current EC EB program.<P>

<B>2.  Division of Hydraulics & Environmental Engineering, 
Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Michael Bruno</B> (<A HREF="mailto:m1bruno@stevens-tech.edu">m1bruno@stevens-tech.edu</A>)<BR>
The Division is an active participant in EU and locally-sponsored research covering a wide range of ocean engineering issues.  Primary interests are Aegean Sea circulation and water quality dynamics; nearshore processes; fundamental fluid dynamics; and water resources management.  The Division's focus is heavily weighted towards numerical modeling, an area in which the staff excels.  It possesses an impressive suite of numerical models, including codes developed by the staff as well as codes originating in the U.S. and Europe.  The Division is less well equiped for lab and field work.  However, via participation in EC MAST and the EU-sponsored facilities-sharing programs, it is becoming more active in acquisition and analysis of field and lab data.  This has greatly enhanced staff capabilities, and should contribute to the continued expansion of the Division's ocean engineering research.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/bruno12.htm">OAS&T #12</A> is based on the Dr. Brunos experiences during a 4-month Fulbright appointment. He acknowledges the generous assistance of the staff and students of the Division during his stay in Thessaloniki.<P>

<B>3. Marine Technology Directorate Merger, Peter Majumdar</B> (<A HREF="mailto:pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/pmnews2.htm">Newsletter 96-002</A> reported on Marine Technology Directorate (MTD), a UK consortium for research in ship and offshore technologies, of which ONR had just become the first non-UK-based member.  Very recently a merger has occurred between MTD and the Edinburgh-based Petroleum Science and Technology Institute (PSTI) which has been an organization for basic and applied research in sciences related to petroleum and extraction.  The name for the amalgamated organization is Centre for Marine and Petroleum Technology (CMPT); its management and operations will follow that of MTD, but oil company sponsorship is expected to promote additional emphasis on marine petroleum topics. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/pmnews8.htm">Newsletter 97-001</A>.<P>

<B>4.  Conference Reports<BR>
   a. Light Scattering and Photon Correlation Spectroscopy, Aug 27-30 96, Krakow, Poland.
Directors: Prof E.R Pike, FRS, Dept Physics, King's College, London </B> (<A HREF="mailto:erp@maxwell.ph.kcl.ac.uk">erp@maxwell.ph.kcl.ac.uk</A>); <B>Dr Igor Yudin, Oil and Gas Research Institute, RAS, Moscow</B> (<A HREF="mailto:yudin@fluid.msk">yudin@fluid.msk</A>)<BR>
Since their inception over 25 years ago, photon correlation techniques for temporal or spectral analysis of fluctuating light fields have found ever-widening applications.  These methods are non-invasive, intrinsically digital in nature, and in many experimental situations offer a unique degree of accuracy and sensitivity, particularly in using a laser probe to study light scattering from pure fluids and macromolecular suspensions, but also to study the flow and turbulence of fluids. Following the earliest developments in laser scattering by dilute macromolecular suspensions, in which particle sizing was the main aim, significant advances have been made in recent years in many other areas; those presented included experimental techniques, statistics and data reduction, colloids and aggregation, polymers gels, liquid crystals and mixtures, protein solutions, and critical phenomena and dense media. Other notable recent developments have been in basic physics experiments on phase transitions in the microgravity environment provided by the space-shuttle missions, in quantum cryptography and in the application of the technique at x-ray wavelengths.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/confsum5.htm">Conference Report #5</A> contains abstracts of the 40 talks from 17 nations, and presenters email addresses.<BR>
  <B>b.  Alternate Camera Technology (ALCATECH) Jens Arnspang, Computer Science Department, University of Copenhagen.</B>
(<A HREF="mailto:arnspang@diku.dk">arnspang@diku.dk</A>) <BR>
Jul 20-27 96, hosted by Ruzena Bajcsy and Sherman Frankel at their farm at Sjaellands Odde. Denmark. The Workshop gathered 23 experts within vision research to discuss alternatives of image capturing electronic and optic devices, and how specific tasks within applied informatics might benefit from such devices in terms of augmented or enhanced 3D scene analysis capabilities, or in terms of lower cost or less computational power requiring equipment. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/confsum6.htm">Conference Report #6</A> summarizes workshop motivation, scientific background, objectives, and conclusions, and gives email addresses of participants. See also Bruce Barnes <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/bbnews24.htm">Report #24</A><P><HR><P>

The opinions and assessments in these reports are solely those of the authors and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.
<P><HR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR newsletters</A><P>
