<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>S&amp;T Summaries #17</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
Science and Technology Summary #17<BR>
19 December 1996</H3><HR><P>

This is one of a series of reports that summarize the assessments produced by the scientific liaison officers at ONR Europe, by Navy visitors to Europe, Africa, and the Middle East, or by organizers of conferences supported by ONR Europe.  The full reports are available under their by-line on this homepage, or by e-mail to the author.<P>
<B>
Topics:<P>

<OL>
<LI>General European S&T Topics:  
<DD>	a. Tri-Service Workshop; Private R&D in the FSU </DD>
<DD>	b. European and Middle East Technology in Support of Littoral Warfare: a Survey and</DD><BR> <DD>Assessment</DD>
<LI>More on UKs Defense Evaluation & Research Agency
<DD>	a. DRAs Structural Materials Center, Farnborough</DD>
<DD>	b. DRA Lab at Winfrith, Dorset</DD>
<LI>DANTEC Measurement Technology
<LI>Ocean, Atmosphere & Space S&T
<DD>	a. 10th International Ship Operators Meeting - Lots of Ship Resources Available</DD>
<DD>	b. International Symposium on "New Challenges for North Sea Research" - Lots of Interaction</DD>
<DD>	c. Post Cold War Collaborative Research at NRL: Lab Oceanographers Participate in Joint</DD><BR><DD> Research with Russians and Norwegians in Norwegian Sea</DD>
<DD>	d. Workshop on Theoretical and Observational Studies of Polar Lows</DD>
<DD>	e. Workshop on International Collaboration in Nearshore Coastal Research</B></DD>
</OL>

<B>1. General European S&T Topics:  </B><BR>
  <B>a. Tri-Service Workshop; Private R&D in the FSU, Igor Vodyanoy</B> (<A HREF="mailto:ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil">ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
The three Service organizations here at Edison House (Air Force EOARD, Army EOR and Navy ONREur) jointly sponsored a review of research being conducted by small private FSU R&D companies, held near Moscow in Sep 96. As the first meeting of its kind, it attracted the attention of the Russian Department of Commerce and large Russian R&D institutions, as well as US industrial reps in Moscow. About 40 formal papers were given as discussion posters. Most were on materials, physics of materials, and surface physics. There were also papers on laser physics and laser technologies. A private design bureau based at the Bauman Technical University (Moscow) offered a number of materials and robotics technologies based on their space vehicle research. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/ivnews26.htm">Newsletter #26</A> lists all reviewed papers and describes a few general interest items such as thermal insulating materials, coatings, and lasers. The unedited proceedings can be made available upon request to Dr. Vodyanoy.<BR>
  <B>b. European and Middle East Technology in Support of Littoral Warfare: a Survey and Assessment, R. Kenneth Lobb</B> (<A HREF="mailto:rkl4@psu.edu">rkl4@psu.edu</A>)<BR>
Report 96-1-R summarizes the author's assessments while at ONREUR from Dec 95-May 96.  It surveys European technology needs and developments with emphasis on regional and littoral conflicts.  The principal warfighting and technical areas covered in the study are: AAW - Ship Self Defense; ASW; C4I; Mine Countermeasures; and Naval Surface Fire Support.  It contains information that is for "official use only", and distribution is limited to DoD components (copies available from Dr Lobb).  A few summary comments:<BR>
<I>AAW  (Ship Self Defense)</I> -  A number of our allies are working hard to overcome the critical problems associated with the advanced sea-skimming missile threat (High speed, maneuvering, low signature, and saturation attacks).  The combination of a new APAR radar plus ESSM will give some of these nations a greatly improved capability.  More power in the radar would be desirable but even so the active elements in APAR are at the leading edge of technology.  Some of our allies are just starting to think about an anti-tactical ballistic missile capability.  The Rolling Airframe Missile is still a winner.<BR>
<I>ASW</I> -  Our European allies see a continued threat from the large number of exported modern, quiet, diesel, air-independent, bottom-sitting, low target strength submarines.  Over 40 new export orders are under contract.  4th gen SSN and SSBNs also will appear early next century.  Many countries seem to believe that the submarine is destined to become the Capital Ship of most navies in the future.  There is great concern for ASW in the difficult littoral environments and there is an increased interest in air ASW and non-acoustic ASW.<BR>
<I>C4I</I> - In the past, many of our allies focused primarily on European conflicts and only those communication links required to support their ground forces on the continent .  Landlines were the key element.  Now there is increased interest in over the horizon communication links to support their naval forces at sea, but even so there are considerable deficiencies with respect to providing timely imagery data, interoperability with GCCS, T1 data rate SHF modems, and replacement satellites - to mention a few.  (It is interesting to note that there is increasing support for high-altitude aerostats or balloons that could be used as relay platforms for over the horizon communications.)  And finally, there seems to be little interest in organic, theater, and strategic targeting systems (such as JSTARS, ASARS-2, GUARDRAIL Common Sensor, etc) that could support naval and amphibious forces operating in the littorals.<BR>
<I>Mine Countermeasures</I> - MCM has always been an important aspect of Naval warfare for our European allies, but now they are thinking about operations beyond their own territorial waters (NATO and coalition ops).  There is great concern about the appearance of "modern" mines and as a result considerable emphasis on remote mine hunting and sweeping. There is also some excellent work on expendable mine neutralization vehicles e.g. the Norwegian minesniper.<BR>
<I>Naval Surface Fire Support (NSFS)</I> -  Based on this assessment study, it appears that there is little European interest in NSFS.  There is, however, an increasing support for amphibious operations (particularly in the UK, the Netherlands, and France), so an increased interest in NSFS should follow.  Practically all the work in Europe and the Middle East seems to be in support of Army needs.  There is some good electrothermal chemical gun work that is showing excellent reproducibility and a roughly 20% increase in velocity.  Israel and Sweden have pushed some advanced technology for base bleed projectiles that confirms the author's theoretical and experimental results that were obtained at the old Naval Ordnance Laboratory in the 1950s.<P>

<B>2. More on UKs Defense Evaluation & Research Agency</B> (see <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/cdnews9.htm">CO/TD Report #9</A> for an overview of DERA and its components)
  <B>a. DRAs Structural Materials Center, Farnborough, Ben Wilcox</B> (<A HREF="mailto:bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil">bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
DRAs Structural Materials Centre (SMC) was established in 1994 to bring together the staff working in structural materials from 8 MOD labs.  SMC now has some 500 materials scientists and engineers conducting research in three general areas:  Advanced Metallic Alloys and Ceramics, Advanced Non-Metallics, and Multi-Functional Materials.  Their mission includes providing technical advice and research to assist all three services, both directly and through the other DRA Sectors.  Approximately 20% of SMCs effort is directed toward dual-use research aimed at benefiting both the military and the civilian sector.  The extremely capable technical staff soon will occupy an outstanding new 28,000 square meter lab. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/bwnews5.htm">MS&E#96-005</A><BR>
  <B>b. DRA Lab at Winfrith, Dorset, Bob Dolan</B> (<A HREF="mailto:rdolan@onreur.navy.mil">rdolan@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
This lab is part of DRAs Sea Systems Sector. Its 50 DERA scientists, augmented by about 30 researchers under contract, focus on military applications in oceanography.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/bdnews3.htm">Report #3</A> describes conversations with Graham Jackson who heads the program, John Scott who manages the satellite remote sensing group, and Tony Heathershaw, head of the applied coastal research program.<P>

<B>3. DANTEC Measurement Technology, Peter Majumdar</B> (<A HREF="mailto:pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A>) <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/pmnews7.htm">Newsletter 96-007</A> <BR>
Long recognized as a world leader in technology for measurement of complex fluid flow, Dantecs corporate headquarters are in Skovlunde, Denmark.  In addition to its recent advanced techniques in Laser-Doppler Anemometry (LDA) with real-time data processing, Dantec has maintained a consistent focus on developments toward understanding fluid flow phenomena which are not easily assessed by point-measurement techniques such as LDA or hot-wire anemometry.  It thus has invested substantially in development of a very comprehensive measurement method based on Particle Image Velocimetry (PIV), together with capabilities for on-line, real-time processing of data.  Dantec has also utilized its laser expertise in the development of precision measurement techniques for manufacturing.<P>

<B>4. Ocean, Atmosphere & Space S&T</B><BR>
  <B>a. 10th International Ship Operators Meeting - Lots of Ship Resources Available, Alan Weinstein</B> (<A HREF="mailto:aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil">aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil</A>), <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/awnews7.htm">Newsletter #7</A><BR>
The purpose of this annual meeting is to compare notes and share experiences.  25 operators and sponsors from 11 countries attended.  Following regular reports by each ship operator on activities for the year, discussions centered on insurance, autosubs, performance indicators, databasess and planning, Marine Technicians Workshop, ISM code, manning and budgets, vessel and personnel clearances, scientific diving, and deep CTD deployments.  Highlights:<BR>
a)  Although the U.S. has the largest number of oceanographic research vessels, many other countries have excellent facilities, and there are a lot of them available.<BR>
b)  There is an increasing use of other countries vessels as part of a "bartering" system,<BR>
c)  All countries share common concerns over budgets, manning and excess capacity.<BR>
  <B>b. International Symposium on "New Challenges for North 
Sea Research" - Lots of Interaction, Alan Weinstein</B> (<A HREF="mailto:aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil">aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil</A>), <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/awnews8.htm">Newsletter #8</A><BR>
21-23 Oct 96, Hamburg, Germany; the symposium was both a retrospective look at twenty years of North Sea research since the Fladenground Experiment (FLEX 76), and a prospective view.  @ 150 scientists, most from countries around the North Sea, remained right up to the very last session, a testimony to the importance that northern Europe attaches to the North Sea. The retrospective look showed that we understand quite a lot about the boundary forcing (from air, land via river runoff, and surrounding water from the Atlantic Ocean and Baltic Sea) and the resulting circulation, and are beginning to gain insight into the resulting biogeochemical structure.  The prospective view called for research on interactions among space and time scales (e.g. coastal response to global warming) and disciplinary processes (e.g. bio-physical, air-sea), and a series of specific process studies as opposed to one major experiments. Highlights:<BR>
a)  Industrialized countries bordering the North Sea (e.g. UK and Germany) have considerably reduced the nutrient (nitrogen and phosphate) content of their river runoff;<BR>
b)  Atmospheric particle deposition contributes 4x the nutrient loading of river input;<BR>
c)  Most of the water entering the North Sea gets circulated around the coasts and exits through the Norwegian Current, leaving only very small (and hard to detect) changes in the large interior bulk;<BR>
d)  Individual species play critical roles in North Sea ecological dynamics;<BR>
e)  The Skagarrak (Channel connecting Baltic and North seas) and the Norwegian Trench are the final resting places for most of the sediments entering the North Sea; and
North Sea morphodynamics are 3-dimensional.<BR>
  <B>c. Post Cold War Collaborative Research at NRL: Lab Oceanographers Participate in Joint Research with Russians and Norwegians in Norwegian Sea, Dr David K van Keuren, NRL Historian</B> (<A HREF="mailto:dvk@ccf.nrl.navy.mil">dvk@ccf.nrl.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
An NRL led international scientific team of U.S., Russian, and Norwegian scientists spent 24 Jul-23 Aug 96 aboard the Russian R/V <I>Professor Logachev</I> carrying out geological and geophysical research in the Greenland-Norwegian Sea.  One major objective of the cruise was to return to a Norwegian Sea mud volcano site to conduct extensive surveys and analyses as a follow-up to an Aug 95 NRL/Norwegian cruise.  Unique temperature anomalies recorded there by Professor Kathy Crane were a scientific first according to Dr Peter Vogt, the lead American scientist.  Additional data from the Knipovich Ridge Valley indicates signs of hydrothermal mineralization and recent volcanism.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/jjnews9.htm">Newsletter #9</A><BR>
  <B>d. Workshop on Theoretical and Observational Studies of Polar Lows, Dr Gunther Heinemann and LCDR John Joseph</B> (<A HREF="mailto:jjoseph@onreur.navy.mil">jjoseph@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
The European Geophysical Society Polar Lows Working Group (EPLWG) held its 6th meeting at the State Scientific Center of the Russian Federation Arctic and Antarctic Research Institute (AARI) in St Petersburg, 23-26 Sep 96, with 25 participants from Denmark, Germany, Iceland, Norway, Russia, UK, & US, plus papers from absent Canadian and French members. Papers covered climatological and satellite studies and numerical models. Two polar low cases were discussed in more detail in working groups, as were programs in order to coordinate international research on polar mesocyclones. Reports <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/jjnews10.htm">#10</A> and <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/jjnews11.htm">#11</A>.<BR>
  <B>e. Workshop on International Collaboration in Nearshore Coastal Research, Bob Dolan, Tom Kinder and Linwood Vincent</B> (<A HREF="mailto:rdolan@onreur.navy.mil">rdolan@onreur.navy.mil</A>, <A HREF="mailto:kindert@onrhq.onr.navy.mil">kindert@onrhq.onr.navy.mil</A>, <A HREF="mailto:vincenl@onrhq.onr.navy.mil">vincenl@onrhq.onr.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
ONREUR hosted this workshop in London, 17-18 Oct 96, to explore potential international collaboration in research on nearshore coastal processes. The motivation was the desire of both US and European managers to promote long term international research, and to discuss the opportunity for its support under ONRs new NICOP program.  The specific objective was to develop a framework for long term initiatives based on expansion of research underway within programs of noted excellence.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/rdnews4.htm">Report #4</A> lists participants and provides the results of deliberation in several focus areas.  The workshop will result in international proposals for NICOPs 15 Jan 97 deadline.  This was the first ONREUR workshop deliberately designed to promote international co-planning of collaborative research, and was deemed a major success by participants.<P><HR><P>

The opinions and assessments in these reports are solely those of the authors and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.
<P><HR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR newsletters</A><P>
