<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>S&amp;T Summaries #16</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
Science and Technology Summary #16<BR>
25 November 1996</H3><HR><P>

This is one of a series of reports that summarize the assessments produced by the scientific liaison officers at ONR Europe, by Navy visitors to Europe, Africa, and the Middle East, or by organizers of conferences supported by ONR Europe.  The full reports are available under their by-line on this homepage, or by e-mail to the author.<P>
<B>
Topics:<P>

<OL>
<LI>General European Science Topics:  Restructuring UK Public Sector Research Establishments
<LI>Ship Science and Shipbuilding
<DIR>   a. Workshop on Electronic Communications for the Shipbuilding Industry and its Vendor Base</DIR>
<DIR>   b. University of Southampton Departments of Ship Science and Electronics</DIR>
<DIR>   c. Eighth International Conference on Laser Techniques in Fluid Mechanics</DIR>
<LI>Computer and Software S&T
<DIR>   a. University of Leeds Keyworth Institute of Manufacturing and Information Systems Engineering </DIR>
<DIR>   b. University of Leeds Computer Model for Simultaneous Engineering</DIR>
<DIR>   c. Computer Science at the University of Copenhagen</DIR>
<DIR>   d.  First International Workshop on Image Databases and Multimedia Search</DIR>
</OL></B>

<B>1. Restructuring UK Public Sector Research Establishments (PSREs), Craig Dorman</B> (<A HREF="mailto:cdorman@onreur.navy.mil">cdorman@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
DoD has been tasked by both Congress and the President to rationalize the Military Departments RDT&E infrastructure.  A well accepted process in responding to such challenges is benchmarking.  The UK, for over 16 years, has been implementing a policy of public devolvement and rationalization.  In the expectation that we have something to learn from their experience, a DoD "Vision 21" delegation spent a week visiting with those involved.  The delegation focused on the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency (DERA) of the Ministry of Defense, but also looked at civil PSREs because in both countries security relies on the total national intellectual infrastructure.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/cdnews9.htm">CO/TD #9</A> tries to depict what the group learned: not just the rationalization process and its results, but the national policy environment that both inspired and enabled the very remarkable changes that have been accomplished.  This lengthy report should be worth reading for those involved with the DoD process, if only as background for further assessment of US options.<P>

<B>2. Ship Science and Shipbuilding<BR>
   a. Workshop on Electronic Communications for the Shipbuilding Industry and its Vendor Base, Howard Bunch</B> (<A HREF="mailto:hbunch@onreur.navy.mil">hbunch@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
An emplaced electronic communications network is widely seen as one of the mechanisms needed to significantly improve competitiveness of the shipbuilding enterprise.  Rapid information transfer supports shortened production time, flexible manufacturing systems, and mass customization of  products.  In recognition of these benefit, shipyards and their vendors around the world are actively developing electronic communication systems.  National efforts are supported in the US, Europe, and the Pacific Rim.  Individual shipyards are aggressively evaluating concepts, and some are actively into the implementation phase.  Some vendor associations are supporting the implementation initiatives of their members, and most of the classification societies are evaluating networks linking them to the shipyards and to the vendor base.  ONREur hosted a 2-day workshop in October to examine the benefits of international cooperation among these efforts, to assess the degree of interest in cooperation, and start to address some of the technical issues. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/hbnews6.htm">Newsletter #6</A> describes US, European and Japanese initiatives, and summarizes the breakout sessions that all concurred on the need for coordination among interest groups.  Coordination should be directed through the MARIS G-7 organization, in particular the MARVEL activity (see <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/cdnews7.htm">CO/TD Rpt #7</A>)<BR>
   <B>b. U. Southampton, Depts of Ship Science and Electronics, Peter Majumdar</B> (<A HREF="mailto:pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
Prominent research areas in the Dept of Ship Science are ship dynamics, propulsor hydrodynamics with emphasis on computational fluid dynamics (CFD), and ship structures with emphasis on light-weight composites.  Its undergraduate program has a unique requisite, involving all of the real-world features: project definition; preparation of technical and cost proposals; presentations; obtaining approval and budget; project planning; hardware purchase; project management and execution; and, possible budget cuts!  The Dept Head, Prof W.G. Price, long regarded as one of world's foremost authorities on ship dynamics, joined University eight years ago and has brought the quality and diversity of ship related research in this Department to match today's specialized demand.<BR>
Established in 1946, Southampton's Dept of Electronics and Computer Science is the oldest such department among the UK universities.  It is engaged in very high quality research, including some which combines computer science with neuroscience, and fuzzy logic for application to real-time active control systems design.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/pmnews5.htm">Newsletter #5</A>.<BR>
   <B>c. Eighth International Conference on Laser Techniques in Fluid Mechanics, Peter Majumdar</B> (<A HREF="mailto:pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
8-11 Jul 96. This conference, held every two years at U. Lisbon, updates the community on developments in non-intrusive measurement techniques for unsteady turbulent fluid flow and related energy transfer. It closely followed the 21st ONR Symposium on Naval Hydrodynamics in Trondheim, which featured Navy emphasis on numerical simulation and prediction of ship dynamical and propulsive performance for realistic ship hull geometry and ocean environments.  In many cases such numerical "model tests" are aimed at replacing the traditional, expensive practice of physical model tests.  Detailed and accurate lab measurements are however essential to develop sufficient confidence in these numerical models: for validation of their physics-based modeling of fluid-flow and associated energy-transfer mechanisms, and for certification of a physical parameter-based envelope within which such validation holds.  Because this validation must be established for each computational step representing a re-distribution of energy within the fluid, the corresponding lab tests must provide a very accurate, high-resolution description of the kinematic and dynamic properties of the fluid.  Recent advances in non-intrusive measurement techniques and related data-processing software (especially in Denmark, UK and US) discussed at this conference are of great significance for numerical model validation and certification.  ONREur will hold an international workshop in a few months, towards establishing specific needs, related plans, and international collaboration possibilities in both sponsorship and execution of the research plans. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/pmnews4.htm">Newsletter #4</A><P>

<B>3. Computer and Software S&T</B><BR>
  <B> a. U. Leeds, Keyworth Institute of Manufacturing and Information Systems Engineering, Bruce Barnes</B> (<A HREF="mailto:bbarnes@nsf.gov">bbarnes@nsf.gov</A>)<BR>
The Keyworth Institute was endowed in 1993 to enhance the organizational competitiveness of UK manufacturing and service industries by increasing their responsiveness and flexibility.  Its principle activities involve R&D, tech transfer and education.  U. Leeds has a long and distinguished history of education and research in Computer Science and related topics.  The school of Computer Studies is among the largest in Britain and has an international reputation. It offers a very rich and diverse set of degree programs. The Faculty of Engineering, especially the Dept of Mechanical Engineering, has been a leader in the development of computer aided design (see below).  Combining these strengths within the Keyworth Institute should provide a suitable instrument for effecting change within British industry.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/bbnews26.htm">Newsletter #26</A><BR>
   <B>b. U. Leeds Computer Model for Simultaneous Engineering, Peter Majumdar</B> (<A HREF="mailto:pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">pmajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
In the UK, both MOD and the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC) (as well as industry) support research on streamlining process engineering and manufacture as well as in-service configuration control and logistics support.  The model currently under development at the ME Dept at Leeds is an example of such efforts. In conformity with ISO standards the model architecture comprises modules for requirements, resources, their interpretation and test for compatibility; the development of product model of a generic description for manufacture; and life-cycle configuration control. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/pmnews6.htm">Newsletter #6</A>.<BR>
   <B>c. Computer Science at U. Copenhagen, Bruce Barnes</B> (<A HREF="mailto:bbarnes@nsf.gov">bbarnes@nsf.gov</A>)<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/bbnews28.htm">Newsletter #28</A> reports a visit with faculty from the Computer Vision, Programming Languages, Numerical Analysis, and Optimization research groups of the Computer Science Dept at the U. Copenhagen, officially the Datalogisk Institut, Kobenhavns Universitet (DIKU).  The department grew out of Mathematics and this is reflected in the research and educational programs which have a very solid mathematical orientation.  Visual exploration, particularly 3D reconstruction from 2D images, is one of the specialties of the Computer Vision research group.  They are particularly active in various alternative camera technologies.  The department is very strong in areas associated with operations research, especially various types of optimization problems.  They are employing parallel computers in many of their applications and are beginning to incorporate computational geometry in some of their algorithms.  The English language plays a central role in their educational programs and non Danish students who are reasonably fluent in English can obtain the Ph.D. degree at the University of Copenhagen.<BR>
   <B>d.  First International Workshop on Image Databases and Multimedia Search, Stan Sclaroff</B> (<A HREF="mailto:sclaroff@cs.bu.edu">sclaroff@cs.bu.edu</A>)<BR>
U. Amsterdam, Aug 22-23 96.  The workshop was sponsored in part by the International Association for Pattern Recognition (IAPR); approximately 100 attendees and 30 papers, mainly focused on image database indexing based on color, shape, and motion properties.  Notably absent were papers that described results using texture, or methods that employed combinations of image properties. The author
presented recent results of research in shape representation, in particular nonrigid shape representation. The report gives technical highlights from the workshop, with emphasis on the shape indexing papers, though some other papers in color and video are described, plus critical analysis and assessment of scientific benefit to the ONR supported research program as appropriate. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/sclaroff.htm">Stan Sclaroff's report</A><P><HR><P>
The opinions and assessments in these reports are solely those of the authors and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.
<P><HR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR newsletters</A><P>
