<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>S&amp;T Summaries #15</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
Science and Technology Summary #15<BR>
4 November 1996</H3><HR><P>

This is one of a series of reports that summarize the assessments produced by the scientific liaison officers at ONR Europe, by Navy visitors to Europe, Africa, and the Middle East, or by organizers of conferences supported by ONR Europe.  The full reports are available under their by-line on this homepage, or by e-mail to the author.<P>

Topics:<P><B>

<OL>
<LI>1. General European Science Topics
<DIR>   a. EU & US Participation in the G7 Project MARIS</DIR>
<DIR>   b. S&T in Ireland, Part 1</DIR>
<DIR>   c. NATO Science Programmes</DIR>
<LI>2. Materials
<DIR>   a. Technology Assessment: Materials S&T (Mecholsky Final Report)</DIR>
<DIR>   b. The Inaugural Hirsch Lecture: Surprises in Materials Science by Sir Alan Cottrell FRS</DIR>
<DIR>   c. Ceramic and Metal Matrix Composites: CMMC 96</DIR>sumnew15.htm

<LI>3. International Center for Genetic Engineering and Biotechnology
</OL></B>

<B>1. General European Science Topics, Craig Dorman</B> (<A HREF="mailto:cdorman@onreur.navy.mil">cdorman@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<P>

<B>a.  EU & US Participation in the G7 Project MARIS</B><BR>
MARIS-the "Maritime Information Society"-is one of 11 pilot projects adopted by the G7 in June 95, to address the revolution in information technology.  The title comes from the European approach to IT: an emphasis on people and social/industrial adjustment.  The Dublin meeting (24Sep) was one of several around Europe to further develop the concept, identify opportunities for joint projects, and expose local IT and Marine industries to the opportunities.  The EC is actively soliciting and supporting research and industrial participation in MARIS.  Canada (Joint project leader with the EU) has no single source of MARIS funding, but reported a few marine safety related projects.  Japan established a national forum to develop a consensus on what theyre willing to share and how to approach the issue.  The US reported that we essentially have done nothing identifiable as MARIS; we agreed to the concept at the Presidential level, but that has not been translated into programmatics or even coordination.  The differences between the US and EU (and Japanese) approaches are palpable. We view the basic IT issue from fundamentally different viewpoints; the EC has leaped on this opportunity to advance European maritime potential and tie this initiative in with their Framework programmes via bottoms-up participation, and Japan developed a consensus national approach, while the US - for whatever reason - has virtually ignored it.  Equally interesting, no one seemed surprised at the US attitude.  Europeans are looking after their interests and pushing opportunities to improve safety and competitiveness of their industry, especially for SMEs, and if we dont want to, well thats just fine.  American maritime industry can just fend for itself, by itself. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/cdnews7.htm">Newsletter #7</A>.<P>

<B>b.  S&T in Ireland, Part 1</B><BR>
Universities are the center of Irish S&T.  The nation, and the Universities themselves, are avidly directing research efforts toward innovation and linkages to the booming enterprise sector.  The EU has been a major source for S&T support, and leading researchers have close collaborations throughout the continent as well as with Irish companies.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/cdnews8.htm">Newsletter #8</A> describes in some detail the various EC, federal, and local mechanisms employed to successfully couple S&T to innovation in Ireland, and gives examples in materials, optoelectronics, biotech, and environmental sciences at Trinity College Dublin and U. College Gallway.<P>

<B>c.  NATO Science Programmes</B><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/cdnews10.htm">Newsletter #10</A> is a reminder about a NATO research program that much of our DoD audience may have heard about but not thought much about, since it is on the civilian vice military side of the NATO house, with little connection to DRGs/AGARD (except cross-briefings).  The NATO Science Programme has a nearly 40 year history of broad based support of inter-Alliance collaborative research.  Its major mechanisms are senior teaching seminars (ASIs) and visits between collaborators.  More recently, it has established priority areas (and several new funding mechanisms) for research collaboration with Cooperation Partners (CPs; essentially FWP/FSU nations).  All projects are open to application from any Alliance researcher (including those in federal labs-thus this note); the intra-Alliance programs are hotly competitive, but there are ample opportunities for support of high quality projects with CPs, especially in "S&T Policy".  The program soon will receive scrutiny for NATO relevance, and would benefit from new projects of high alliance impact.  US DoD and DoD-affiliated applicants should keep the US Mission to NATO aware of their interests.<P>

<B>2. Materials</B><P>

<B>a. Technology Assessment: Materials S&T (Mecholsky Final Report), Jack Mecholsky</B> (<A HREF="mailto:jmech@silica.mse.ufl.edu">jmech@silica.mse.ufl.edu</A>)<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/jmnews12.htm">ONREur Report 96-2-R</A> is an in-depth summary of Jacks assessments while assigned to this staff from Aug95-Aug96.  The 3 major sections cover biomedical applications of materials, advanced ceramics and composites, and fractal fracture.  The report describes the technical and procedural strengths of the European community as a whole, and national capabilities, in each of these technology areas.  The author notes several areas in which European work equals or exceeds ours, as well as European interactions worthy of emulation.<P>

<B>b. The Inaugural Hirsch Lecture: Surprises in Materials Science by Sir Alan Cottrell FRS, Ben Wilcox</B> (<A HREF="mailto:bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil">bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
Presented Oct 4 96 at the University Museum, Oxford, it honored Sir Peter Hirsch, formerly Chair of the Materials Department on the occasion of his 70th birthday.  Sir Alan's lecture was a tour de force for both its clarity and its content of exciting "surprises". Included in his list were: the observation by Hirsch and his group in the 1950's using transmission electron microscopy that dislocations in Al moved due to stresses generated by beam heating; unexpected catastrophic failure of Liberty ships during World War II because the ductile-to-brittle transition temperature of the ship steel was not sufficiently low to withstand brittle fracture in icy waters; the surprising behavior in Ni3Al where the strength increases with increasing temperature; the observation that brittle solids (glass and ceramics) can be made to fail non-catastrophically by reinforcing with fibers; the discovery of quasicrystals ,or solids which exhibit five-fold crystallographic symmetry; fullerines or , C60, sometimes referred to as "bucky balls"; and most importantly high temperature ceramic superconductors based on the cuprate family. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/bwnews3.htm">MSE#96-003</A><P>

<B>c. Ceramic and Metal Matrix Composites: CMMC 96, Ben Wilcox</B> (<A HREF="mailto:bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil">bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
This conference on CMC's and MMC's, held in San Sebastian, Spain, Sep 9-12 96, was very well attended by representatives from 25 countries.  There were 20 half day oral sessions, and 60 posters.  Five papers were on ceramic fibers, and the remaining talks and posters about equally divided between CMC's and MMC's. The presentations showed considerable recent progress in developing the microstructures (especially the interface between matrix and reinforcement) required to achieve desired performance goals.  The only composite system which appears to be gaining substantial use at present is particulate SiC reinforced Al.  Others, i.e. CMC's and SiC fiber reinforced Ti alloys, show promise in jet engine applications.  However costs must be reduced through improved innovative processing before the composites will see widespread applications. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/bwnews4.htm">MSE #96-004</A><P>

<B>3. International Center for Genetic Engineering and Biotechnology, Igor Vodyanoy</B> (<A HREF="mailto:ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil">ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil</A>)<BR>
The UN Industrial Development Organization (UNIDO) recognized at a very early stage the potential of genetic engineering and biotechnology to alleviate disease and starvation and to promote the economic progress of the developing world. It began the initiative that has led to the foundation of ICGEB, located in Trieste and New Delhi. The research, training schemes and services of ICGEB represent an innovative and comprehensive approach to promote biotechnology internationally. The Center helps developing nations help themselves by strengthening their research capabilities, and holds out the prospect for advancing knowledge and applying the latest biotech techniques in public health, nutrition, environmental protection/remediation and energy saving. ICGEB provides a scientific and educational environment of the highest standards. Its labs develop state-of-the-art research of importance to bio-industries in Member States. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/ivnews25.htm">Report #25</A>
<P><HR><P>

The opinions and assessments in these reports are solely those of the authors and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR newsletters</A><P>
</BODY>
