<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>S&amp;T Summaries #14</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
Science and Technology Summary #14<BR>
16 October 1996</H3><HR><P>

This is one of a series of reports that summarize the assessments produced by the scientific liaison officers at ONR Europe, by Navy visitors to Europe, Africa, and the Middle East, or by organizers of conferences supported by ONR Europe.  The full reports are available under their by-line on this homepage, or by e-mail to the author.<P>

In this edition, we also point you to some extremely interesting <B>NSF reports</B> on <B>Science in Finland</B>, and the <B>EC Joint Research Center</B>. These may be found in the new section under Newsletters on our homepage, or may be obtained from Dr. Bikales.<P>

Topics:<P>

<OL><B>
<LI>NSF Reports:
<DIR>     a. European Commission - The Joint Research Center </DIR>
<DIR>     b. A view of Science and Technology in Finland; </DIR>
<LI>Conference Reports:
<DIR>a. Progress in Electromagnetics Research Symposium 1996 (PIERS96)</DIR>
<DIR>b. Nonlinear Dynamics & Chaos: Applications in Physics, Biology and Medicine (ICND-96)</DIR>
<LI>Intellectual Property and Business Activity in the Russian Federation
<LI>Ocean, Atmospheric & Space S&T
<DIR>	a. 7th AMS Conference on Mesoscale Processes - The Mesoscale has Grown</DIR>
<DIR>	b. UK Oceanography 96: A Testimony to the Health and Vigor of Ocean Science Research in the UK</DIR>
<LI>	c.  Signal Processing at Heriot-Watt University, Edinburgh, Scotland
<LI>	d. Notes from a visit to Proudman Oceanographic Lab</B>
</OL>

<B>1. NSF Reports; Norbert M. Bikales, Head, NSF/Europe Office (<A HREF="mailto:nbikales@nsf.gov">nbikales@nsf.gov</B></A>)<BR>
<B>a. European Commission - The Joint Research Center.</B><BR>
JRC began as a nuclear research facility at Ispra, Italy.  Starting in the 70s its focus shifted to environmental and solar energy, nuclear safety, and advanced materials.  Over the years JRC expanded to eight institutes at five sites. Its annual budget is now some 300M ECUs.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/nsf81.htm">Report #81</A> provides basic information about JRC and its Institute for Advanced Materials, and describes significant recent changes: As of Apr 96 JRC is an independent Directorate-General (DG) within the EC, and must competitively seek support for 25-30% of its budget from Framework Programs and third parties, including industry; and staffing has been made more fluid through the addition of 3-yr nonrenewable contracts (in addition to 5-yr renewable ones).  These changes reflect the European policy of driving S&T to productivity, innovation, and competitiveness.<BR>
<B>b. A view of Science and Technology in Finland</B><BR>
With a small but well educated population and a modern infrastructure of well equipped labs, Finland is making great strides to establish itself as an international force in advanced technology. It already has leading positions in specialties such as atomic layer epitaxy and mobile telecom equipment. Government policy is to increase investment in research and foster intimate collaboration of government labs and universities with industry. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/nsf86.htm">Report #86</A> gives a general background, and describes the major government players: the Academy, the University of Helsinki, the Technology Development Center (TEKES, the main agency for applied R&D and technological development), and the Technical Research Center (VTT), the largest in the Nordic countries with 9 institutes and 2700 employees.<P>

<B>2. Conference Reports</B><BR>
<B>a. Progress in Electromagnetics Research Symposium 1996 (PIERS96), H. Rott, General Chairman (<A HREF="mailto:piers96@uibk.ac.at">piers96@uibk.ac.at</A>).</B><BR>
Innsbruck, Austria, 8-12 Jul96; 560 attendees from 41 countries.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/rott.htm">Report #3</A> provides titles and brief descriptions of the papers presented by the 11 scientists from Russia and the Ukraine supported by ONR Europe.  These demonstrated excellent theoretical, and in some cases experimental, work in propagation, scattering, polarimetry and interferometry, and remote sensing.<BR>
	<B>b. Nonlinear Dynamics and Chaos: Applications in Physics, Biology, and Medicine (ICND96), P.V.E. McClintock for the Committee (<A HREF="mailto:p.v.e.mcclintock@lancaster.ac.uk">p.v.e.mcclintock@lancaster.ac.uk</A>)</B><BR>
Saratov, Russia, 7-14 Jul 96; 114 attendees from 16 countries.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/mcclinto.htm">Report #4</A> enumerates the 155 papers and posters in a wide range of applications, and highlights key presentations. Proceedings will be published in a special issue of the <I>International Journal of Bifurcation and Chaos</I>.  The standard of presentations was high, and the conference enabled discussion among many scientists and engineers who would not normally have encountered each other.<P>

<B>3. Intellectual Property and Business Activity in the Russian Federation, John Lewis (jlewis@onreur.navy.mil)</B><BR>
The <B>NATO</B> Advanced Research Workshop on Intellectual Property: Influence on Business Activity took place in <B>Moscow</B> from Sept 9-11 96.  This was the third annual workshop aimed at providing to the Russian Federation, Western ideas on how to expeditiously transfer state owned technology to the world market place.  The ten Western speakers and the breakout sessions discussed issues in three areas: firm strategy, finance and capital, and moving federal technology out of the state institutions into the market place.  The prescription in all three categories was the same: pass fair legislation in employee/employer relations concerning intellectual property, get a patent law on the books, straighten out the banks (2/3 of the 3000+ banks are bankrupt), and create a fair tax system so the entrepreneurs of the world can enter and do business.  A comprehensive court system and civil code needs to be put in place so that there is a means for dispute resolution.  MOUs and DEAs are needed, but first the Russians have to know what their national law and policy are, or they can not staff and sign such agreements.<BR>
	Most of the Western speakers had attended the first two workshops and they all spoke of the attitude change in the Russian participants.  There were still a few old school ideologues that advocated state ownership of technology, or at least state compensation for the technological base developed under the old Soviet institutions.  However they were in the minority and mostly derided by their Russian colleagues.  From Vice Minister Yakobashvilli, Ministry of S&T, to the Heads of Agencies, to the new S&T incubators, all appreciated the ideas and workshop, and all seemed determined to make the changes necessary to enter the free market and global market place.  They ask our forbearance and for us to understand the Russian difference, and to appreciate why it was taking a long time.  They do think differently and have a different history and culture.  It is the authors opinion that we made some mistakes in rushing in and buying research at fire sale prices.  What we needed then and need now, is truly collaborative undertakings. <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/jlnews7.htm">Newsletter #7</A>.<P>

<B>4. Ocean, Atmospheric & Space S&T</B><BR>
	<B>a. 7th AMS Conference on Mesoscale Processes - The Mesoscale has Grown; Alan Weinstein (<A HREF="mailto:aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil">aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil</A>)</B><BR>
Reading, UK, 9-13 Sep 96; 300 attendees, mostly from US and UK.  The conference reflected the current expanded definition of mesoscale by devoting almost 1/3 of the time to extratropical cyclones.  The remainder dealt with the more standard mesoscale topics of convection, orographic forcing, the boundary layer and gravity waves. Notable observations include:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>Important interactions between convective and orographic processes on the traditional mesoscale, and such synoptic scale processes and phenomena as baroclinic instability, fronts, cyclones, etc., can send energy either up or down scale. Recognition of this has tied the mesoscale and synoptic communities much closer together.
<LI>Computer technology has brought practical numerical modeling down to scales where classical mesoscale phenomena (e.g. squall lines, sea breezes, mountain winds) are resolvable, thereby unleashing important new observational considerations.
<LI>With growing availability of  "non-conventional" observations (radar, wind profilers, satellite data), data assimilation has taken on greater importance in numerical weather prediction on all scales.  In combination with growing computer power, data assimilation is making previously esoteric methods (e.g. adjoint), commonplace.
<LI>Appreciation for the impact of initial condition errors on numerical forecast skill has generated considerable interest in targeting observations where they can have the most impact on forecast skill, heralding a lively competition for ideas on how to best identify targets.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/awnews4.htm">Newsletter 96-4</A> describes the sessions and analyzes attendance and papers.
</OL>
	<B>b. UK Oceanography 96: A Testimony to the Health and Vigor of Ocean Science Research in the UK, Alan Weinstein et al (<A HREF="mailto:aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil">aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil</A>)</B><BR>
This latest of the Challenger Society for Marine Science's biennial UK conferences was held at Univ. of Wales, Bangor (UWB) 2-6 Sep96.  Topics covered the spectrum from physical, through bgc, to biological oceanography; domains ranged from coastal margins (including estuaries and beaches), through the shelf, to the deep ocean, from the sediments, through the volume, to the surface and atmosphere. This conference, by design, attracts a large number of UK students and postdocs (who speak), plus the national leaders (who listen); the 380+ attendance is 3x that of the first (1984) in this series. Also by design, renowned scientists from other European nations were invited. Other than three from ONR Europe, there were none from US. Notable observations:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>European and UK oceanography continue to have many local field campaigns, resulting in a rich base of new data;  
<LI>Most analysis of this field data to date has been individual case studies, from which overall conclusions have not yet emerged; and
<LI>Many of the local findings have analogies in U.S. work, with little if any mentioned recognition.
</OL>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/awnews5.htm">Newsletter 96-5</A> describes the various sessions and key papers.<BR>
	<B>c.  Signal Processing at Heriot-Watt University, 
Edinburgh, Scotland; John Joseph (<A HREF="mailto:jjoseph@onreur.navy.mil">jjoseph@onreur.navy.mil</A>) Robert Dolan/Ken Lobb (<A HREF="mailto:rdolan@onerur.navy.mil">rdolan@onerur.navy.mil</A>)</B><BR>
A research group under Dr Laurie Linnett of the Dept of Computing and EE has developed a variety of robust signal processing methods using statistical and fractal techniques to extract subtle patterns from complex fields of data, and reduce data storage requirements.  ONR Europe was sufficiently interested in this work that we have made two separate visits to Linnets lab, described in <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/jjnews6.htm">OAS Newsletter 96-6</A> and <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/rdnews2.htm">Coastal Oceanography Report #2</A>.  Linnetts group has demonstrated success in real world problems of texture classification, object detection, and sidescan sonar M&S; and their techniques are of significant interest for a variety of naval and oceanographic applications.<BR>
	<B>d. Notes from a visit to Proudman Oceanographic Lab (POL), Robert Dolan (<A HREF="mailto:rdolan@onerur.navy.mil">rdolan@onreur.navy.mil</A>)</B><BR>
POL, near Liverpool, England, one of the three labs of the UK NERC Centre for Coastal and Marine Sciences (CCMS).  POL specializes in storm surge research (modeling and prediction), large and small scale coastal processes, sediment transport in estuaries, and impact of climate change on coastal environments.  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/rdnews1.htm">Report #1</A> describes the POL funding process, and relates discussions about UK coastal oceanography with four POL scientists, Roger Flather, David Prandle, Peter Hardcastle, and Peter Thorne. <P><HR><P>

The opinions and assessments in these reports are solely those of the authors and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P>


</BODY>
</HTML>
