<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Special Report #1</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H2>ONREUR Special Report<BR>
First FY97 NICOP Awards<BR>
15 August Board</H2>

The Naval International Cooperative Opportunities in Science and Technology Program (NICOP) made its first cost sharing awards at a review Board that met on 15 August 1996.  The NICOP funds available for FY97 and FY98 are approximately $1M and $1.35M respectively. The awards shown below were for a total of $495 FY97, $349FY98, and $150FY 99.  The next deadline for requests will be 15 Jan 97; a future announcement will provide additional details, including focal issues for the next round.<P>

NICOP has three parts: Development of country plans and strategies for international S&T cooperation, improvement of distributed data bases, and cost sharing with Navy S&T sponsors to encourage them to take advantage of international opportunities. ONREur serves as technical manager for the program.<P>

Requests for NICOP cost-sharing are submitted by sponsors (ONR POs, or managers in Labs and Warfare Centers or SYSCOMS via ONR), based on proposals from collaborative teams of US and international investigators. NICOP will fund up to 50% of the US share of overseas costs for proposals selected competitively (based on technical merit, impact on naval requirements, and potential for long term collaboration).  The S&T from such efforts should, over time, improve the opportunities for coplanning and codevelopment.  NICOP also serves to provide continuity to the special emphasis on NIS S&T under its predecessor, SOP.<P>

The projects listed below received awards from the first Board.  The success rate was 50%.  A NICOP award does not guarantee that a project will proceed.  NICOP awarded only 40% of the funds requested for the successful proposals, and it is the responsibility of the individual sponsors to determine whether on not to proceed with funds available.<P>

The requests which received awards are listed below, by nation of the non-US collaborator.  Address questions to <A HREF="mailto:cdorman@onreur.navy.mil">cdorman@onreur.navy.mil</A>.<P>

<B>1.  RUSSIA (6)</B><P>

N6-14  Sonovision<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  N.N.Andreyev Acoustics Institute, N. Dubovsky et al; Naval EOD Tech Division, Bruce Johnson<BR>
 ONR POC:  ONR 332, Wally Smith; ONR 321, Tom Swean;<BR>
 Description:  This project evolved from an ONREur workshop on ultrasonic imaging followed by a visit to the Andreyev Institute in Moscow. The Russians use a "Sokolov tube" which employs a scanned electronic beam (vice contact bonds) to provide the output signal; the US previously failed in attempts to develop this technique. This project improves imaging capability, quantifies system performance, and assesses utility of the technology for "underwater vision", a major need for divers and MCM<P>

N6-18 Modeling of Electron Cyclotron Resonance Plasmas<BR>
 Institutions & PIs: St Petersburg Technical University, Lev Tsendin; NRL DC, Wally Manheimer<BR>
 ONR POC: ONR 331, Chuck Roberson<BR>
 Description: This project supports NRL's ARI on the scientific basis of plasma processing.  The electron cyclotron plasma reactor (ECR) is important for plasma processing, and also a very complex device.  Mannheimer met Tsendin during his sabbatical at MSU.  The collaboration that resulted involves numerical, semi-analytical and theoretical modeling of ECR and other high density discharges.<P>

N6-24 Solar Powered AUVs; Sampling Systems for the 21st Century<BR>
 Institutions & PIs: Institute for Marine Technical Problems, Vladivostok, Mikhail Ageev; Autonomous Underwater Systems, Inc, Richard Blidberg<BR>
 ONR POC:  ONR321OE: Tom Swean<BR>
 Description:  This project contributes to the Multi-University URI on Autonomous Ocean Sampling Network.  Two SBIRs under that MURI are looking at power generation at docking nodes; this project focuses on power generation integral to the vehicle.  The Russian partner has already developed vehicle design parameters for a solar powered AUV.  This program will evaluate its feasibility.  Under this continuing collaboration IMTP will fabricate a prototype testbed in conjunction with AUSI staff, and both parties will work on subsystem improvements and tests.<P>

N6-29 Small Scale Acoustic Tomography in a Bubbly Medium<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  Institute of Applied Physics, Nizhny Novgorod, Alexander Kkil'ko; Shirshov Institute of Oceanology, Moscow, Oleg Goldin; NRL-SSC: Jerry Caruthers<BR>
 ONR POC:  ONR 321 Jeff Simmen;<BR>
 Description: Based on SOP-supported investigations of Russian tomographic approaches by Carurthers and Khil'ko over the past two years, a technique of Goldin's using non-reciprocal tomography to measure ocean currents will be developed and applied.  This will be done in parallel with ONR's project on the influence of bubbles on sonar in shallow water, of which Caruthers is PI.  The NRL Delta Frame will be modified for a range of tomographic techniques, and data collected; Khil'ko will develop inversion techniques and conduct tank experiments on bubble clouds; Godin will analyze local currents based on his new approach<P>

N6-40  Vapor Phase Growth of 3C SiC Crystals<BR>
 Institutions & PIs: Baikov Institute of Metallurgy, Moscow; S. Gorin & L. Ivanova; Univ. Cincinnati, Prof Andrew Steckl<BR>
 ONR POC: ONR 312, Max Yoder;<BR>
 Description: SiC bulk crystals grown by Baikov in the 70's have outstanding structural properties, better than anything available in the US. The proposed 3-year program establishes at the University of Cincinnati a modernized chamber to match the Russian SiC quality, and provides both parties a new chamber design.<P>

N6-44 Turbulent Flame Stabilization & Combustion Control in Subsonic and Supersonic Combusters by a Joint Velocity Scalar PDF Method<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  Semenov Institute of Chemical Physics, Sergei Frolov; Purdue, Steven Frankel; UCSD, Forman Williams<BR>
 Navy POC: ONR 333: Gabriel Roy<BR>
 Description: The PIs will address flame stabilization control and combustion control from the theoretical and computational point of view.  The validated codes can significantly contribute in guiding and optimizing design in missiles like Fast Hawk and Scram Shell.<P>

<B>2.  ARMENIA (3)</B><P>

N6-21 Special Technique for Laser Patterning of Large-Area High-T Superconductor Thin Films<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  Physics Research Institute, Ashtarak, Armnen Kuzanian; NRL 6670, James Horwitz<BR>
 ONR POC:  ONR 312, Deborah Van Vechten<BR>
 Description: This project continues an SOP initiated collaboration on deposition of high-T superconducting films using a new technique called pulsed laser deposition.  Last year the PIs designed and tested a unique deposition system capable of depositing HTS thin films on 4" wafers.  NRL is securing patent rights.  In this project, the PIs will design a laser micromachining system for patterning these wafers, that will be constructed in Armenia, T&E'd in the US, and reside at NRL Code 6670.  This will allow them to customize individual samples and offer a preparation variant currently unavailable at NRL.  The system could also be used to pattern other materials such as ferroelectrics, benefiting many NRL research efforts.<P>

N6-31 Optimization of Parameters of Non-Equilibrium X-Ray/US Detectors<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  Physics Research Institute, Ashtarak, A. Gyulamiryan; NRL 7621, Kent Wood<BR>
 ONR POC:  ONR 312, Deborah Van Vechten<BR>
 Description: This collaboration proposes to optimize parameters for non-equilibrium photon detectors, sensitive to X-rays and UV radiation and designed to serve as space based spectrometers.  There also are many potential terrestrial applications, for which this work will evaluate practicality.  The Armenian team will produce sensors that they will bring to NRL to test; the Armenian team will be augmented by a senior Armenian scientist who will be at NRL for the year.  This is the third year of this collaboration, previously supported by two SOP grants.  However, the phenomena to be exploited are recently discovered.<P>

N6-33 Rare Earth Halide Crystal Growth and Their Optical Characteristics Investigation<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  Physics Research Institute, Ashtarak, E. Vartanian; NRL 5640, Barry Feldman<BR>
 ONR POC:  ONR 312, Ingham Mack<BR>
 Description: NRL is pursuing mid-IR solid state lasers.  An LaC13 laser grown at NRL has operated efficiently at 7.24 microns; however these crystals are hard to grow.  The Armenians have novel techniques (and equipment) which in other materials yield crystals with dislocation densities an order of magnitude lower than conventionally grown materials.  In this project NRL will work with the Armenians to improve growth of improved LaC13.  Armenians will grow the crystals and do initial testing; NRL will evaluate them and feed back recommendations.  There will be face-to-face exchanges.<P>

<B>3.  FRANCE (2)</B><P>

N6-12:  Non-Linear Analysis of Neuronal Cells Behavior<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  Pasteur Institute, H. Korn et al; NRL Center for Biomolecular S&E, Joel Schnur et al<BR>
 ONR POC:   Tom Mckenna<BR>
 Description: This project couples two productive and original groups in a novel bioengineering project, the end objective of which is cell based biosensors for generic early detection of potential hazards. NRL has pioneered control of cell growth and Pasteur the fundamental understanding of neuronal behavior.  This project focuses on nonlinear analysis of synaptic signals and neuronal activity and the influence of chaotic and stochastic patterns of signaling on the input-output functions of neuronal networks.  It is a three year, basic research project.<P>

N6-32 Hierarchical Field Model of Hippocampus for Pattern Recognition<BR>
 Institutions & PIs: Institute de Biologie Theorique, Angers, Gilbert Chauvet; USC, Ted Berger<BR>
 ONR POC: ONR 342, Joel Davis<BR>
 Description: This project analyzes hippocampal activity, models and interprets it in Cellular Neural Network formalism, and validates the approach (including the feasibility of a chip design) for speech recognition.  The two PI's met via Joel Davis, at an ONREur workshop; Berger does biologically based algorithms for speech, and Chauvet is expert in CNN pattern recognition.  The NICOP request was actually initiated by Chauvet, and proposes this (new) collaboration.<P>

<B>4.  IRELAND (2)</B><P>

N6-25 Advanced Permanent Magnets<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  Trinity College, Dublin; NSWC Carderock, James Cullen
 ONR POC: Kristl Hathaway<BR>
 Description: This project takes advantage of Dr Cullen's upcoming Fullbright fellowship to work with Prof Coey on magnetoelasticity, to initiate a collaborative investigation into three novel concepts in permanent magnets.  The PIs propose to formulate analytical models that can provide guidelines in optimizing the materials and structures during later experimental research.  The 3-year project looks for improvements in energy product, high-T performance, and manufacturing cost through energy-coupled two-phase magnets, dipole-coupled two phase magnets, and permanent magnet variable flux sources.<P>

N6-34 Integration of Fabric Reinforced Thermoplastics into GMT Moulding Process<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  University College Gallway, C. O'Bradaigh; University of Limerick, Pat Mallon; University of Delaware, Jack Gillespie; NSWC Roger Crane; NRL Roger Badaliance<BR>
 ONR POC:  332 Jim Kelly<BR>
 Description: The project seeks to integrate high-performance glass-fabric composite materials into the short-fiber GMT molding process, in which Europe has the lead. ONR funds Gillespie at U Delaware, where O'Bradaigh got his PhD and Mallon spent a sabbatical, for similar work.  The project if successful would result in significant cost reduction for structural parts.  There is expected to be  significant commercial application, and industrial involvement will be sought in the third year.<P>

<B>5.  UK (2, one with SWEDEN)</B><P>

N6-42 Flight Tests of C-130 Mounted Counterflow Virtual Impactor<BR>
 Institutions & PIs: British Met Office, Doug Johnson; University of Stockholm, Kevin Noone (formerly URI); CIT, John Seinfeld<BR>
 ONR POC:  321 Bob Bluth<BR>
 Description: The project flight tests a CVI jointly developed by Seinfeld and Noone on the UK Met Office MRF C-130 in preparation for their participation in the international Aerosol Char'n Exp't-2 (ACE-2).  The instrument development and test are jointly supported by the EC, MRF and ONR. This work leads ultimately to an instrument/analytical capability for aerosol measurements from small RPVs.<P>

N6-46 Deployment of Ocean Explorer and Autosub in Scottish Waters for Langmuir Cells and IW Study<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  Southampton Oceanography Center, Steve Thorpe & Gwen Griffiths; FAU, E. An et al<BR>
 ONR POC: ONR 322 Tom Curtin<BR>
 Description: This extends a 4-year collaboration between SOC and FAU on AUV technology.  In addition to continued cooperation on distributed controllers and AUV operations in turbulent waters, it deploys the institutions' two vehicles for Langmuir cell and IW measurements during SOCs major campaign in the very complex shelf break area west of Scotland.  Deliverables are the data, reports, etc. typical of an oceanographic field program.<P>

<B>6.  NETHERLANDS</B><P>

N6-17  Atmospheric Propagation Analysis, Gotland Sweeden Deployment<BR>
 Institutions & PIs:  TNO/FEL, Gerrit de Leeuw; NRAD 754, Rowena Carlson<BR>
 ONR POC:  322, Steve Ackleson<BR>
 Description: This is the 5th propagation experiment in the APA series, in this case at a site at Gotland, as part of a larger multinational air sea exchange study.  The PI collaboration is new though both have worked on similar projects, and de Leeuw is also involved in other aspects of the project.  NCCOSC will make spectroradiometer measurements, and TNO/FEL will measure and analyze aerosol particle size distribution.<P><HR><P><A HREF = "http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A> </BODY></HTML>
