<H3>22 March 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #1<BR>
Romania<P>


Visit to Romania under the USEUCOM Joint Contact Team Program, 03-3/9-96</H3>

<I>Keywords: Romania; Defense R&D; Naval Forces; Diving</I><P>
<PRE><B>
Contents:</B><BR>
1.  Summary
2.  General Information
3.  Romanian MoD Procurement and Logistics Department, and the MoD Institute for Research and
     Development
4.  Romanian Naval Science Research Center
5.  Romanian Navy Diving Center
6.  Romanian Navy Hydrographic Directorate
7.  Romanian Naval Repair Base
8.  Ship Visits: DD111, "Marasesti" and FF264
9.  Points of Contact
10. Feedback
</PRE>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
From 3-9 March 1996, CDR Larry Raithel, USN and Dr. Craig Dorman, respectively CO and TD of ONR Europe, visited the Romanian Military staffs and R&D Institutes in Bucharest and Constanta as a USEUCOM Joint Contact Team Program "Event" (one of about 8/week in Romania).  Trip objectives: Assist Romanians in developing laboratory capabilities (per their request), and evaluate DEA possibilities for USN following Master Information Exchange Agreement (MIEA) signing by USD(A&T) Kaminski in late February (per request of OP-091).<P>

Our event was unusual in that it was the first to deal with R&D.  It also was more senior than most.  Our Romanian hosts demonstrated and described their needs for US Navy assistance.  Now that the MIEA has been signed, they hope to move rapidly from general discussions such as ours and other Military-to-Military visits, to specific, concrete technical support in their priority areas: Design of a new standard frigate; underway refueling and replenishment modifications for their Destroyer; submarine rescue using their 300M capable diving systems; and in general, conversion to US and NATO standards.<P>

<B>2.  General Information</B><BR>
Romania is entering a period of rapid change, nationally and militarily.  Although the revolution that ousted Ceaucescu was in 89 (and they preface most descriptions of organizations and capabilities with "Since 89..."), until the last year or so change has been slow and moderate compared to many other previously Communist nations.  There will be a new budget at the end of March, and this is the first year for major reductions in Defense, due largely to IMF and World Bank pressure. The Ministry of Defense (MoD) expects about a 30% reduction; this reduction has not yet been allocated to the Services.  Local elections occur this spring, Presidential and Parliament in fall.<P>

The Military (especially the Army) is popular due to its role in standing up to (then trying & shooting) Ceaucescu in the 89 revolution.  In response to fiscal pressures and international events the military has decided to restructure and reform, though they are moving slowly and cautiously.  Leadership is, however, converted.  They are enthusiastic about PfP, and seek early NATO membership (though some problems remain, e.g. a border disagreement with the Ukraine over an offshore island).  They have made NATO standardization the top military development priority, and the need for change  now  is a consistent theme; as is lack of money.<P>

One of their major problems is that since the Russians never provided all the military equipment they felt they needed (They were always in their terms the black sheep of the Warsaw Pact, particularly after their refusal to invade Czechoslovakia in 68), they developed quite a complete capability to design/build their own. As a result they now have a huge military industry base with about 160K workers, of which 80K produce purely military equipment, but only about 15K total (9K military) are actively working.  These unproductive workers are a large drain on the national budget. In addition, they developed their own specifications and standards for this equipment, and these must all now be converted if they are to become NATO compatible.<P>  

Thus they have some hard choices to make as they restructure, privatize, and downsize, while simultaneously attempting to adopt western/NATO standards.  The civilian Chief of the MoD (Georghe Tinca) apparently asked Dr. Kaminski for a defense industrial specialist for about 6 months; his reply, we were told, was that we could send in specialist teams for shorter visits.<P>

The MoD has only recently been headed by a civilian.  In addition to the General Staff there are three service branches (Army, Navy, and Air Force/Air Defense), a Civilian-led Policy & International Relations Department, a joint Procurement and Logistics (P&L) Department, under State Secretary and Chief General Florentin Popa (reputedly hard working and extremely capable...as are many of the leaders, if not the nomenklatura), and the military industries.  The P&L Department is responsible for budget, planning, and execution of R&D, acquisition, repair, and logistics; for control of exports/imports; and for coordination (not ownership) of defense industry.  Basic research is under the Ministry of Research and Technology, and the Research Institutes are under the Romanian Academy of Science.  (Apparently science was under Mme Ceaucescu until 89...and thus didnt fare very well).<P>

The Ministry of Research and Technology coordinates the overall national research program (for which there is a plan out to 2000), of which one chapter is defense.  Some of this work is carried out by MoD Institutes - Research Institute of the Armed Forces, Centers for Research on Military Chemistry and Medicine, and the Scientific Research Center of the Romanian Navy (which is subordinated to and receives its requirements from HQ Navy Staff but works iaw P&L Department plans & funding allocations).<P>

The Navy, headquartered in Constanta, has since 89 been organized into the Black Sea Fleet, the Danube Fleet, a separate Submarine and Diving brigade, the Marine Corps (3 Brigades), and Auxiliary forces.  Major fleet units include (see Janes for a more detailed description):<P>

Black Sea Fleet:  DD111 [started in the late 70s, completed in 85 but not fully outfitted with current weapon suite until 92, finished testing 93, and has since participated in PfP and bilateral exercises in Black Sea and Med]; 5 Frigates in two classes [Program started 77; built 4 through 86.  Redesign began in 83 to complete gunnery...first new FF built in 90, in testing 91-93; and the 6th is now in final testing in the shipyard (they made no clear distinction between types of testing - also, time delays were all attributed to fiscal and internal situations, not technical capacity).  Most electronics and armament on the DD and FFs are vintage 60-70s Russian, with Romanian modifications. For the future they want to redesign, modernize, and become NATO compatible.  Development of a new "standard Frigate" and modification of the others is their first priority; the mission of the Frigates is first ASW, then air surveillance, then naval surveillance and counter-surface craft.<BR>
In addition they operate 3 ASW corvettes, 9 missile carriers (6 OSA, 3 Tarantul - with the only gas turbines in the fleet, everything else being diesel powered), 12 fast torpedo boats, 30(?) hydrofoils, each w/2 torpedo launchers, a KILO class submarine, 20 minesweepers, 2 minelayers, and various auxiliaries including 2 rescue tugs (4800HP), used to combat casualties, for support of offshore drilling platforms, for icebreaking in the canal and river, etc.  Over 80% of their ships and systems have been built in Romanian shipyards.  <P>

Danube Fleet:  3 gun & rocket carriers (BRUTAR? - 38.5M, 1.5M draft, beachable, carries a platoon, 80 rockets & many guns, armored [vs 14.5mm ammo] river boat), 25 Aluminum minesweepers, auxiliaries.  (NB: Border location varies along the Danube; agreements with Yugoslavia & Bulgaria provide for common use, with 45 day advance notice of significant military movements.  The Navy doesnt patrol the Delta; the Ministry of the Environment has environmental patrols and Ministry of the Interior has border troops that revert to Naval control in war).<P>

<B>3.  Romanian MoD Procurement and Logistics Department, and the MoD Institute for Research and Development.</B><BR>
Hosts: BG-dr-eng Nicolae Irimie, Chief of the R&D Office, MoD, P&L Dept.; and RADM-dr-eng Ion Plaviciosu, Commander, MoD Institute for R&D.<P>

The MoD Procurement and Logistics (P&L) Department receives requirements from the General Staff, and turns them into "research themes".  These are assigned to the Military R&D Institutes (which were started in 68) or to civilian institutes  to carry out, in parallel with the basic S&T agenda from the Ministry of Research and Technology.  <BR>
National scientific research is now being reorganized, with a combination of state & self-financing.  This causes MoD problems since some institutes (presumably those better able to support themselves on the economy) may not want to work with the military.  MoD will in the future favor its own Institutes because of lack of funds (i.e., theyre already paid for & no money need transfer...this philosophy was reiterated re shipbuilding the next day).  MoD funds (or at least P&L funds) now come from Parliament and the General Staff as a single lump sum, though they are discussing a division of funding into categories such as research, applied development, systems, etc. (details unclear - but there is no line item structure like ours).<BR>
Procurement, modernization and development programs are reviewed and approved by the Sovereign Council for Defense (Council for Endowment).  This Council meets quarterly.  It is chaired by the Chief of the General Staff, and comprises the Deputy State Secretary for P&L, the Service Chiefs, Service Logistics Directors, and R&D Institute representatives [?].  This council apparently makes all the decisions on what to develop and fund (e.g., the Diving Command described their presentation of a swimmer sled to the council as an essential step in obtaining funding). There is a separate commission, chaired by Gen. Popa with membership from the military industrial companies, that coordinates defense production.  As opposed to the other services, Navy spends more on procurement than R&D due to the cost of its systems.  <BR>
"In principle", each program has a manager, with a development team from the R&D Institutes, Military Academy, and appropriate civilian Institutes.  They are apparently in the process of modifying their process - the changes were described as very complex - and would like to better understand the US program management process.  Funds, however, are centrally controlled as opposed to assigned to individual programs, and shifted around in accordance with General Staff and P&L Department priorities.  Significant funding shifts are to be expected during the coming years of reduced funding (in conversations over the next several days, Navy representatives expressed concern over how they would fare relative to the other services, and emphasized the need to have their own institutes and shipyards to ensure Navy needs are met; where have I heard this before?).<P>

MoD utilizes the universities and civilian research institutes for basic science and technology, but has difficulties linking research to production.  In the past, they could simply place groups from the Military Institutes in the Military Industry companies for technical coordination and assistance; this will be more difficult and costly after privatization, so they must develop new methods of coordination.  (Both MoD and Naval R&D institutes claimed close coordination with civilian institutes; however the military prefers to use their own Institutes since they are already paid for).<P>

Radm Plaviciosu (who was spoken of very highly by the Naval Staff in Constanta, and apparently previously directed the Naval Science Research Center) stated that 86% of Romanian military equipment had been produced by their military industries.  The need for such a significant production capability was based on the strained relationships with Russia stemming from their refusal to invade Czechoslovakia in 68; since then, they have had to modify, modernize, and develop and manufacture spare parts for their Russian equipment, as well as to design and develop their own new systems.  However, the philosophy with which they approached this was eastern (example given:  mines to injure or maim vice kill, thus tying up additional forces and increasing the enemys logistic burden); now they must change to a western philosophy, as well as convert all their standards for NATO interoperability.<P>  

The General Staff has agreed that conversion to NATO standards and interoperability of Romanian forces are the top priority, and their approach is to start by cooperating with the US because of its technological leadership.  There are obviously many challenges and major changes associated with this conversion.  Priority areas, discussed with Dr. Kaminski, include sensors, C3I, and territorial surveillance (for which they are procuring a Lockheed-Martin radar), as well as weapons and ammunition.  They are very anxious to obtain STANAGs and other appropriate standards to help in modifying their current Romanian standards.  A major concern (expressed repeatedly, in all meetings) is lack of funding; they have the technical expertise, but can not afford to import anything they can develop or produce themselves.<P>

We commented that production implied sales to sustain capacity, and asked where they believed they were competitive.  Their response was light infantry armament, armored personnel vehicles, trucks, and field cars; however they need to develop new clients.  They are providing some equipment for Egypt and Turkey.  One problem is lack of materials.  They also have good hardware and software capabilities at their informatics institute, and have developed coordination with IBM, Sun, and others.  In addition, they have a large and excellent shipbuilding industry, mostly civilian (we were told the Constanta yard is booked for 2 years, and talked to a Norwegian who had just ordered two 74KT dry cargo carriers). <P>

We visited the R&D Institute, toured the "exhibition" and received a briefing on its organization.  The equipment on display, all produced in Romania, was an extensive array of tanks, trucks (all diesel propulsion; this was true also in Navy; the only gas turbines were in the 3 Soviet Tarantuls. Everything else is Romanian diesel), APVs, and weapons ranging from small arms, mortars and recoilless rifles (122mm) to 152mm artillery, plus communications and surveillance equipment (ground radars, perimeter defense systems, and a 5-station air control van to be integrated with the new Lockheed-Martin radars and their current air control systems), chemical and biological testing and decontamination trucks, and specialized equipment for mountain troops.  Our general impression is that they have an extremely extensive suite of military equipment for a small country to have to develop, maintain, and produce; it was all fairly simple and rugged, and only small portions of the inventory - e.g. the new air control system - appeared to use modern digital electronics.<P>

The MoD R&D Institute has a total staff of about 800.  Technical divisions include Weapon Systems (60 engineers; fire control, armored vehicles, weapons and ammunition), Sensor Systems and Simulation (40 engineers), C3I and Computers (80 engineers; applied software, expert systems and robotics; system architecture and basic software), and Transmission, Information Protection and Radio (60 engineers).  There are also sections for test and certification, logistics and support, patterns and prototypes, quality control, metrology, procurement and documentation, equipment and special vehicles, and administration.  The engineers in general appeared to be system and subsystem designers.  Much of the software (as at the Navy Institute) and virtually all the documentation and manuals were written in Romanian; and in general, although many of the officers under age 40 have some English, very few are fluent.  The Institute is housed in three large office buildings about 5 miles sw of Bucharest.<P>

<B>4.  Romanian Naval Science Research Center</B><BR>
Principal hosts were Capt-dr-eng Constantine Rusu, Director of Logistics, Romanian Navy Headquarters; and Capt-dr-eng Vergil Gradinaru, Commander Naval Science Research Center.<P>

After a general introduction and description of the Navy, we visited the exhibition (no further tour of the Center was offered, and when we asked we were told there was nothing but offices and desks) and then went to the Officers housing building for a briefing on shipbuilding.<P>

The Naval Research Center has a staff of about 2-300, 25% military.  Basically, the Center is responsible for conceptual design, development, and logistics (including spare parts...stressed because one of their problems is building spares for Russian equipment; and for the divers, for the COMEX equipment they purchased in the late 70s) for all naval equipment, from ships to weapons and ammunition.  The exception is diving and submarine equipment, for which there is a separate brigade and development/training organization. <P>

Like MoD, the Navys main overall priority is modernization of their last-generation Soviet equipment, combined with conversion to NATO standards.  HQ staff as well as fleet operators are all committed to NATO compatibility, and they have had many personnel exchanges and participated in several PfP exercises.  The many interactions have created an sense of anticipation of support from the US.  They are now at the point of needing detailed technical assistance, particularly US and NATO specifications and standards, since they can not afford long developments or false starts.  Because they have had to be self-reliant they have a full set of Romanian standards, and these must now all be converted.  Other problems include lack of modern digital equipment, very few computers, and no Internet connections The military is even well behind their civilian institutes and commercial yards, yet the Navy would prefer to use their own institute because of cost.<P>

The Navys exhibition room, like that of the National R&D center, displayed a full range of Romanian-made equipment. Three items were of particular interest to us:<BR>
	<DIR>A new, simple dipping sonar designed for use from small craft and helos.  Characteristics include:  15Khz, 15degree conical beam, 50 msec pulse, mechanical scan (controllable for full or sector scan), can be lowered (2m/s?) to 130m, acoustic svp connected to ray path program (algorithms unexplained, but they know to use ambient vice statistical data and indicated it included bottom conditions), 1.5kw acoustic power, claimed range tested vs their sub to 14 km.  This has been deployed on their Destroyer and the new Frigate.</DIR>
	<DIR>"Trident" minesweeping system:  three remotely controlled craft (32m, 130T ?) with magnetic and acoustic sweeping systems, deployed in advance of a parent vessel.  The modern-looking computer display shows swept path and track of the sweepers, which typically cover 100m per transit and are run in longitudinal s-tracks ahead of a parent minesweeper which carries mechanical sweep and acoustic search gear, or ahead of the vessel to be protected; they remote craft can also be controlled form a shore based van.  Apparently two of these systems have been deployed.</DIR>
	<DIR>"BRUTAR" armored (vs 14.5mm shells) river craft - multiple guns and rockets, 38.5m loa, 1.5m draft, beachable and capable of carrying a platoon.  Mean looking river boat.</DIR>

They presented separate lectures on their "Warship Design Process" and their use of standards.  Ship design at the R&D Institute is still primarily manual; they have no integrated design capability.  They stated that although they had designed and built most of their fleet, they still had a lot to learn and were interested in cooperation.  For example, there is no DC Central, and equipment is not well arranged for damage control.  They have little information on western standards and ship design processes beyond what they can glean from commercial magazines.  They strongly desire assistance and advice. <P>

They can do integrated ship design (using STEERBEAR) at Galatz, location of their naval architecture school and main ship design and test facility ICEPRONAV S.A. (although the DD and FF hulls were tested in Denmark), or in industry.  Of course they prefer to do their design, at least the initial stages, at the Institute to save money and improve control.  They used to do all execution drawings at Galatz or the Institute, but the military yard had trouble adapting their technology to the requirements.  They are trying to work with the yard to reduce this problem, but it still exists.<P>

The military shipyard in Mangalia (which reports to the Industrial Group in MoD, not to the Navy), 2400 workers, constructed the DD, Frigates, river boats and many of their auxiliaries (the DD and FF hulls were constructed in the civilian shipyard because of their size, then moved to the military yard for outfitting).  It also does their repair work, and has a 1600T floating dry dock.  The largest yard (civilian) is in Constanta.  It has built bulk carriers and tankers up to 150KT, and has 2 years of booked work, 80% for foreign customers, including China and South Africa (as noted above, when we were checking our of the hotel we met a Norwegian who had just let a contract for two, 74KT dry cargo carriers; the owner will supply engines and equipment, but uses the Romanian yards for steel, labor, and integration.  He has been dealing with them since 87 and is pleased with their products.).  <P>

Constanta is currently the fourth largest port in Europe, and is expanding to the south, to the mouth of the canal to the Danube, at which point it will be the second largest.  They count on this port and the associated duty free zone for future income. There is also a repair yard in Media, and a well equipped yard in Tulcea on the Danube, specializing in cargo vessels for the river and in fishing vessels (50KT capability).  There are four other smaller construction and repair yards along the Danube.<P>

Given the range of their equipment and the size of the task of converting standards and developing interoperability, they need to make hard choices.  When asked, they stated that their first priority was the Frigates, then the Destroyer (which was initially designed as a cruise ship and has recognized limitations). The frigates primary task is ASW, and they are developing a towed sonar for it (an adapted Russian system, depth 10-100m depending on speed, 10Khz).  Other needs include communications, fire control (now unintegrated and analog), and weapons (e.g., the only anti air armament is 30mm 6-barrel optically controlled guns).  They also several times mentioned the need to modify the DD for NATO standard unrep because of its participation in PfP exercises.  They are looking for detailed specs to minimize the time and cost of the needed conversion.  They stated that they had visited NAVSEA and been shown "the book", but were told that they could not have a copy until the MIEA was signed.  Assistance in converting to western standards is one of their top requirements, and they explicitly solicited detailed technical assistance from the US Navy.<P>

<B>5.  Romanian Navy Diving Center</B><BR>
Primary hosts in addition to Capt. Rusu were Capt. Petru Somfelean, Commander of the Center, and Cdr Paul Chiron (who speaks very good English), himself an experienced diver.<P>

The Diving and Submarine Brigade, which reports directly to Navy Staff, includes the Diving School, Hyperbaric Lab, Underwater Research Lab, Combat Divers Unit (about 60 in number, apparently with a mix of EOD and special ops training), Deep Divers Unit, and the KILO-class submarine.  There have been a number of exchange visits with US forces (the MLT should be able to provide details).  We received briefings on diver training and operations and technical developments, plus papers on submarine rescue and salvage, and toured the hyperbaric facility and the diving ship Grigore Antipa.<P>  

The Center trains all Romanian divers, both military and civilian.  There are three classes of divers (0-40m, 40-60M, >60M), with increasing levels of technical training and annual certification requirements.  In addition to military duties, the divers (and the ship) participated in construction of, and support maintenance of the eight offshore oil rigs and are responsible for their defense. Although their description of the organization was unclear, apparently a highly qualified diver would be expected to participate in a wide range of activities.  CDR Chiron, for example, was for 8 years the head of the shipboard diving unit, but also was a parachutist, pilot, and ship captain  and had specops experience in the Black Sea.<P>

The Hyperbaric lab and deep diving equipment were procured from COMEX around 1978.  The hyperbaric lab (two chambers connected to a wet pot also used for escape training) has a 500M capability; their first saturation experiment to that depth was in 1984, and they do 3-5 sat dives in it per year (training, development, and certification). They also have a number of portable chambers. There is a medical unit which conducts hyperbaric research (there is a small research chamber suitable for mice and ducks) and supports diver safety and health. The principal shipboard equipment includes a 300M capable diving bell, the SM358 (300m, 5 divers, 8 hours...) powered submersible, and two interconnected chambers below decks to service them.  Both the bell and the SM358 showed signs of extensive use, and apparently have been modified over the years to take Romanian manufactured spares and equipment.<P>

Their highest development priority is to modify either the bell or the SM358 for submarine rescue.  To do this they will need advice on Western standards and NATO interoperability requirements.  At least three additional Mil-Mil events are planned around this issue: RO-300 (Fam), a visit to San Diego in late April, and two TCTs (RO-587 and 588) not yet scheduled.  What they really need is technical assistance first to assess the condition of their equipment and practices, second to determine whether either the bell or SM358 could be modified for rescue from the KILO, and third to evaluate in more technical detail the issues of NATO compatibility.<P>

Another development priority is a closed circuit scuba for their combat divers.  They are currently using an older Russian model;  this is another case where procurement (e.g. of Draegers) is viewed as more costly than development.  They expressed further concern regarding a law now at parliament requiring research to be self-financing, and complained that the money they receive for civilian diving services (they have a national monopoly) goes to the national defense budget, not directly back to the center. Additional development projects which they mentioned but we did not see (they wanted us to focus on sub rescue) include diver communications and sonar, and underwater welding and repair technology.  <P>  

<B>6.  Romanian Navy Hydrographic Directorate</B><BR>
This Directorate is responsible for littoral and river hydrographic survey and charting (although charts are printed by MoD), navigational warnings, hydrography and meteorology, navigational buoys and lighthouses, and radio-navigational equipment.  Virtually all the electronics we saw were Soviet manufacture, vintage 60s and 70s, with Romanian modifications.  They have three survey ships and a rescue tug, a mixed civilian and military staff of 140 plus 80 conscripts.  In April and May NAVOCEANO will work with them on a cooperative hydro survey of Constanta Harbor and approaches (Paul Cooper of the NAVOCEANO Cooperative Survey European Office has details, plus more in-depth knowledge of this Directorate).<P>

Romania is a full member of the Hydrographic Commission for the Mediterranean and Black Seas, and an associate member of IHO.  They have cooperative agreements with 15 nations and mentioned good collaboration with the Turkish hydro office. <P> 

We spent some time discussing extensions of the port of Constanta and navigation on the Danube.  Constanta is now the 4th largest port in Europe, and they plan to extend it over the next 4-5 years south to the entrance to the canal to the Danube, with a major duty free zone and a barge on/off loading facility.  It will then be Europes second largest port. They envision this as a major gateway to Europe (navigable Black Sea to North Sea), and a major economic hope for the nation. There are also three navigable channels in the Delta:  The northern Kiria Branch which is Ukrainian and has 70% of the river flow, and two Romanian branches, the central Sulina which has been straightened for navigation and is continuously dredged to 7M (10% flow), and the southern St George Branch.  The delta is advancing in the area of St George, and they survey that area annually.  Since Sept 91 the Sulina branch has been partially blocked by a Ukrainian cargo vessel filled with wire which rolled over and sank broadside to the channel; they completed partial clearing last year (they noted that the Ukrainians started dredging the Kiria branch about the same time their vessel blocked the Sulina).  <P>

We next paid a courtesy call on Eng.-RADM Beches, Deputy Chief of Staff and head of Procurement and Logistics for the Romanian Navy.  The Admiral reiterated their official commitment to western standards and NATO interoperability, and the associated need for technical advice.<P>

<B>7.  Romanian Naval Repair Base</B><BR>
The Repair Base is responsible for intermediate and depot level maintenance and repair.  It reports directly to RADM Beces.  Established in 1982, it moved into new facilities adjacent to the Naval Science Research Center (which provides technical support) in 1993. Total staff is about 350, in 5 Departments: Radiolocation (navigation, sonar, fire control), Radio, Artillery, Engine, and Mechanical.  Each is headed by a senior, experienced Captain, and they claimed that the personnel were all highly skilled and carefully selected.  We saw a mix of military and civilian.  <P>

Most of the repair work is performed directly on board ship.  In addition, they have ship-sets of most significant electronics at the repair center for trouble shooting and repair of subsystems.  The center was busy when we visited, but we were told that many of the workers had come just to see the American visitors.  They were obviously delighted with our presence; although there has been significant contact elsewhere we were the first visitors to the Repair  Department.  One of their principal problems is adapting Romanian products as spares for their largely Soviet electronics.  Prints and manuals were all in Romanian, although most of the analog electronic equipment had its original Russian nameplates. <P>

The Repair Department traditionally was directly funded by headquarters; they are starting to allocate repair funds to individual ships, but stated that this was hard to implement.  Each ship does its own operational level maintenance in accordance with Romanian schedules. The Chief Engineer is responsible for spares and repairs.  Requests go through the Squadron and Brigade to Naval Hq, then to the Repair Department, which can obtain materiel and parts either from depots or industry.  To save money, however, they prefer to design and develop their own parts in the Department.<P>

The Repair Department appeared well organized and tightly managed.  Given the age and condition of their ships they must certainly have their hands full.  The new facilities, while rudimentary, are adequate for their needs and could accommodate more modern repair equipment (we saw lots of multimeters, few oscilloscopes, no computers). We believe the senior members of the Repair Base Staff (Commander and the 5 Department Heads) would benefit from a familiarization tour to a US Naval Ship Repair Facility.<P>

<B>8.  Ship Visits: DD111, "Marasesti" and FF264</B><BR>
Construction of the Destroyer started in 1976; it was initially completed in 1985 (the long delay due to funds and the "internal situation"; as noted above, it apparently started as a cruise ship). The hull was constructed by the civilian yard in Mangalia, and it was then moved to their military yard for outfitting.  After initial testing and training from 85-88 they modernized the armament, adding SS-20 missiles and a 30MM/6 barrel air defense system, and increasing the depth charge range from 2.5 to 6km.  The ship was finished in 1992, commissioned in 93, and participated in exercises in the Med in 94-95.  It is 5500T, has four main 8800HP Romanian diesels and four screws (Dutch variable pitch outboard), and a range of 4000km. Electronics is almost all Soviet, though with numerous Romanian modifications (in some cases required just to make it work). Their major technical concern is modifying it for NATO at-sea refueling; they showed us their preliminary designs for topside equipment and piping/valve changes which were based on their experience and initial discussions with NAVSEA, and requested a technical review and copies of applicable specs and standards. They want to make sure that their design is adequate before they cut metal, since they can not afford false starts.<P>

Like the DD, the Frigate - though their new class and upgraded - is outfitted with very basic, unintegrated armament and older Soviet electronics.  The ship is 1500T displacement, maximum speed 23 knots (18 kts cruise), 3000 km range, crew of 90 (7 officers, 28 warrants or chiefs) and designed only for local operations (poor habitability, no distillation or unrep capability, hard-mounted machinery). CIC was essentially an empty room with a Plexiglas sketch of the Black Sea. Also like the destroyer, with the exception of conscripts the crew doesnt rotate.  <P>

Following the ship visits they summarized for us their priorities for modernization and American assistance.  They are well aware of the limitations of their ships, and of the degree of change necessary to  reach western standards.  They view the Frigates as the core of their Navy, and want to design a new "standard frigate" that would be NATO compatible.  This is their highest modernization/NATO compatibility priority.  They showed us a preliminary concept drawing, and stated that they would send copies of what they had developed. They envision an integrated diesel (Romanian)/gas turbine (imported) propulsion system (CODOG), twin screw, maximum speed 30-32 knots, with active roll stabilization. They need a completely new integrated C3I and fire control system, integrated damage control sensors, bio-chemical protective system, and habitability/crew accommodations for extended voyages. Envisioned armament includes Harpoon and the AK-176 76mm gun for surface-to-surface, Barak and two 30mm AK630M guns for air defense, 6km range depth charges and 53 cm torpedo launchers. ASW would rely on helos for long range detection, towed sonar for mid-range, and the hull mounted sonar for short range attack.<P>

They fully recognize that this would be a stretch for them and stated that they would need US collaboration for definition and design; first to help select weapon systems that they could be assured would be available (including provisions for spares and repair - they were bit bad by the Russians here), and then to understand western and NATO standards.  Their need for help starts with items as simple as no-skid deck paint, and extends through the entire design and integration process.  They now have no integrated or computer-based deign capability in the military (although as noted above they use FORAN and STEERBEAR at ICEPRONAV, the Shipbuilding Research and Design Institute in Galatz). <P>

<B>9.  Points of Contact</B><P>

