<BODY>

<H3>27 March 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #2<BR>
European Center for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF)<P>

ECMWF Status and Plans</H3>

<I>Keywords: Weather; meteorology; supercomputers</I><P>
<PRE><B>
Contents:</B><BR>
1.  Summary
2.  General Information
3.  ECMWF Computer Configuration
4.  Other Recent Initiatives
5.  Comments
6.  Contacts
7.  Feedback
</PRE>

<B>1. Summary</B><BR>
ECMWF is a world leader in its field.  US meteorologists
and climatologists know its programs well, and make extensive
use of its analyses and forecasts.  Of recent interest, after
relying on Cray computers almost since its inception, ECMWF competitively
selected a Fujitsu VPP700 for its next upgrade.  The initial components
of the new machine are on site; by 1998, it will provide about
25x the performance of the current Cray Y-MP C90/16.  ECMWF is
pushing to complete its 1979-1993 (and possibly 1994) reanalysis
before the June switch-over.  In addition, ECMWF received permission
from its Council for a 3-year research program (starting Jan 95)
in seasonal forecasts, with four additional consultancy positions.
<P>

<B>2. General Information</B><BR>
The European Center for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts
(ECMWF) is located outside Reading, England.  Its excellent World
Wide Web homepage, <A HREF="http://www.ecmwf.int">http://www.ecmwf.int</A>, describes its organization and products. The following is a brief introduction,
and the author's impressions from his visit on 26 March.<P>

Discussions about the need for a European meteorological
Center began under COST (European Co-operation in Science and
Technology) in 1967, at about the same time that NCAR was established
in the US.  After considerable discussion, the European nations
decided to focus on operational aspects - medium range forecasts
for distribution to the met services of the 18 member states (ECMWF
also has cooperative agreements with WMO, EUMETSAT, Iceland, Hungary,
and Croatia) - and the associated research and development of
numerical methods.  The stimuli for operational collaboration
were the computational intensity and associated costs of mid-range
(out to 10 day) forecasts, the benefits of pooling the best talent
and then rotating them back to home offices, and analysis that
projected about a 20:1 benefit-cost ratio if the then-quality
of 2 day forecasts could be achieved at 6 days (this level of
improvement in forecastsing has effectively been achieved; cost-benefit
studies have been discussed, but except for a study of the economic
benefit to the UK of hosting ECMWF, are still in the too-hard
box).<P>

The establishing Convention was signed in 1973, and
the first forecasts provided in 79.  ECMWF's ruling Council has
two representatives per member; usually one from the nation's
met office, and one from the responsible ministry (one exception
is the UK; the British Meteorological Office comes under MoD,
and both Council members have been from BMO).  Contributions to
the annual budget (&#163;19M in 95) are determined by GNP (updated
every three years by OECD).  Thus the UK, France, Italy and Germany
are the big members, followed by Spain; Germany's share will increase
considerably when the calculations switch to post-unification
GNP.  The Council normally works well by consensus; but votes
when needed are based on the double-2/3 rule (2/3 of the funding,
plus 2/3 of the members).  The budget provides for the facilities,
computers, a dedicated telecommunications net (64Kbps rates to
each member as part of the basic subscription; wider bandwidth
- used by UK and France - is paid for by the user nation), and
142 staff positions plus a number of consultancies.  ECMWF can
also accept external research contracts (e.g. NSF, JMA and the
EC are contributing to the cost of the reanalysis). <P>

All positions are filled by the member nations, but
visiting scientists from other nations are accepted (e.g., Ron
Gelaro from NRL Monterey spent a TDY period there and Jim Doyle,
also from Monterey, will arrive this summer for 9 months to work
on a coupled wind-wave model).  The organization is simple - the
Research Department (38 staff) under Dr Tony Hollingsworth (Ireland)
with Model and Data Divisions; an Operations Department (76 slots)
under Dr Massimo Capaldo (Italy) with Computer and Meteorological
Divisions; and an Administration Department.  The three Departments
report to the Director, Dr Dave Burridge (UK).  This has basically
been the organization from the start.  ECMWF is small enough that
management is quite informal and the staff all know one another;
thus there is no need to change style to resolve bureaucratic
issues.<P>

We chatted at lunch about the stability and success
of the structure; my host Dr Austin Woods cited &quot;Grooming,
Gossip and the Evolution of Language&quot; by Prof Robert Dunbar
of Liverpool University (to be published Faber on 1 April) which
contends, based on correlation of brain size and group size in
primates, that 150 is about the natural size for a human group.
 At any rate this has worked exceedingly well for ECMWF for some
20 years, and they want not to grow.  At issue of course is tapping
into the best European talent; their ability to draw from the
18 member states is envied in many circles in the US.  And from
my brief exposure, although they described national differences,
the quality and diversity of the staff as well as the rotation
process are rightfully envied.  The multi-national structure combined
with the links to the European Met offices provides them a distinct
competitive advantage.  The US has not as effectively rationalized
its efforts in mid-range (or seasonal) forecasting.  We still
have enough money that we haven't yet been forced to join forces
across organizational boundaries (e.g., NOAA, Navy, NASA), to
the detriment of our national skill.<P>

One concern, although it hasn't impacted yet, is
the potential impact of changing policies on data rights.  Satellite,
radiosonde, etc. data is the lifeblood of any forecasting group,
and restrictions or excessive subscription costs could severely
impact the product.  As indicators of change my hosts cited ECOMET,
an &quot;Economic Interest Grouping&quot; (private) established
to commercialize the products of the European weather services,
and EUMETNET - an umbrella organization of weather services to
foster collaborative projects (and potentially the embryo of a
European Meteorological Organization - there are 25K meteorologists
in Europe service the 400M population compared to some 5-10 K
in the US for its 280M population; some degree of rationalization
and job sharing will eventually occur).  I have heard similar
concerns re data management at NESDIS and Navy in the US; and
the US policy (free access to government data) is certainly at
odds with the trends in the rest of the world.<P>

ECMWF's main product is its daily medium range (10
day) forecast, distributed to the Member State met services. 
They also produce lower-resolution ensemble predictions (currently
33 integrations of the prediction model, going to 50 with the
Fujitsu) that are starting  to be used in innovative ways by some
of the larger met services.  Research associated with these efforts
focuses on exploitation of satellite data for initial conditions,
data assimilation techniques, physics, and numerical methods to
enhance speed, resolution and accuracy.  One initially unappreciated
fallout of the accuracy of ECMWF analyses and predictions is their
ability to precisely and rapidly spot anomalies in data.  This
information is routinely fed back to the collectors, and had resulted
in significantly improved quality, and recalibration of some of
the space based sensors on ERS-1 and 2.<P>

Another extremely valuable product are ECMWF's archive
of data and forecasts.  This archive is widely used throughout
the world, and collaboration with the user meteorologists and
climatologists of course has beneficial feedback to ECMWF's research.
 The 15 year reanalysis (79-93 or 94) using the baseline 1995
operational system (2.5&#176;, T106L31) will be of tremendous
value, and already is being exploited in ECMWF's own seasonal
prediction work.<P>

Of particular interest to Navy is ECMWF's wave predictions,
using the WAM model.  Operational forecasts out to 10 days started
in 1992; resolution is now 1.5&#176;.  They assimilate ERS-1 SAR
data and verify against ERS-2 and buoys.  WAM 1<SUP>st</SUP> guess
(before assimilation) standard deviation vs ERS-1 wave heights
is now about 40cm, compared to a meter or more in the days of
SEASAT.  Although Navy also uses WAM, ECMWF's forecasts are more
accurate across a wider range of sea states, perhaps because ECMWF
uses the wind field for forcing, while Navy uses calculated stresses.
 This is in consonance with the overall ECMWF philosophy of predicting
and assimilating directly observed data rather than values calculated
from the data. <P>

The 'dream' for wave forecasters is a fully coupled
wind-wave model, supported by assimilated SAR, scatterometer,
and buoy data.  Jim Dolye from Monterey arrives shortly after
Easter to work with the ECMWF wave group on its development. 
In addition, ECAWOM and other research projects are expected to
continue to enhance the physics of WAM.<P>

<B>3. ECMWF Computer Configuration</B><BR>
One of the US community's concerns before I left
the States at the end of 95 was NEC's and Fujitsu's bid for the
next ECMWF computer - followed in short order by an expected run
on the European met services (Germany's tender is out, UK is down
to a short list, France will tender soon; NCAR also is will soon
select a new machine) - and the potential impact on Cray, which
has been the traditional main line supercomputer supplier.  Fujitsu
of course won the ECMWF competition; a VPP300 (4 PE Vector Parallel
Processor) is in place for code conversion and experimentation/research,
and the 46 PE VPP700 arrives this summer.  By fall the operational
system will have 5x the performance of the current Cray C90/16,
with further upgrades planned through 1998.  ECMWF has traditionally
leased its main machine, and will continue this practice with
Fujitsu. <P>

Another recent changes in the configuration is a
new IBM RS6000 data handling system for the archives, to supplement
and presumably ultimately replace the IBM ES/9000-720.  Most work
stations are now Silicon Graphics' Indys.  The conventional 64Kbps
dedicated telecommunications links (to most nations - UK and France
pay for extra bandwidth) will likely remain standard for the next
several years.  25% of the computer resources are dedicated to
use by the Member States; most jobs are batch, and only a very
few selected investigators have on-line access. <P>

<B>4.  Other Recent Initiatives</B><BR>
Four staff members are dedicated to the 1979-1993
(hopefully 1994) reanalysis using the 1995 operational system.
 This must of course be completed prior to the switchout of the
Cray, so it has a rather tight time line.  This is an internationally
funded effort, and the resultant consistent data set, generated
with a stable modern assimilation system should be of tremendous
value to researchers worldwide.<P>

There are two aspects to the new Seasonal Forecasting
Project.  The first is to assess atmospheric predictability on
seasonal time scales, given sea surface temperature and soil moisture.
 ENSO impact is now widely appreciated; at issue are the nature
and location of other drivers, and predictability in areas such
as Europe that are less immediately impacted by ENSO.  9-member
ensemble forecasts over 120 day intervals will be made using the
15+ years of information from the reanalysis project.  Initial
results (from the first year of the three year program) do indicate
predictability, at least in cases of strong inter-annual changes
and large SST anomalies.  Other Met offices will conduct similar
studies with the same boundary conditions to test the influence
of different models.
<P>

The second part of this project is the development
and operation of a coupled ocean-atmosphere model.  The German
HOPE is the basis for the ocean model, and French OASIS is used
as the coupling interface.  Most ocean data for assimilation and
spin-up will come from NODC.  Again,.the 79-94 atmospheric reanalysis
will play a major role.  <P>

<B>5. Comments</B><BR>
Like most workers in environmental fields I have
heard about ECMWF and taken advantage of its available products
for many years.  This was my first opportunity to visit, and the
reality more than lived up to my expectations.  Perhaps more impressive
to me even than the well known excellence of the product and the
research, is the stability and quality of the management.  Most
research institutions either have gone through, or shortly will,
major perturbations because of changes in national research policies
and reductions in funding.  While ECMWF has not been immune to
such influences, its international structure and the commitment
of its leadership to spurn growth and stick to producing top quality
research plus a product that is most highly valued by its members,
have minimized disruptions.  ECMWF was well designed at the start,
is well situated in an environment conducive to top quality research,
has been and remains well managed and staffed, and knows where
it's headed.  I can't say that about many institutions I've visited
over the last several years.
<P>

ECMWF's selection of the Fujitsu VPP represents a
significant change for those who care about supercomputers.  ECMWF
was an obvious key target for the Japanese because it is a highly
respected and multinational world leader.  Others will watch its
performance closely and be tempted to follow its lead if successful.
 It will be interesting, to say the least, to watch the outcomes
of tenders at NCAR and the European met services over the coming
months.<P>

ECMWF research promises consistent and continued
progress in medium range forecasting.  Consistent accuracy at
&gt;80% levels at 5 days is in itself astounding at least to me,
and the combination of new machines, new data, new algorithms,
new assimilation techniques and ensemble forecasts should press
the limits of predictability.  After over 20 years, this field
retains every element of its excitement and promise.  If, as I'd
guess likely, the fully coupled wind-wave model becomes available
in a year or so, wave forecasts should be vastly improved and
soon see much wider application, with commensurate feedback into
the research.<P>

ECMWF's new venture into seasonal forecasts is likewise
exciting.  While the initial justification for the seasonal research
was improvements in the medium range forecasting capability (and
vice versa), the potential for effective operational seasonal
forecasts in Europe and Africa has immense ramifications for economics
and quality of life.  ECMWF is obviously in the best position
to exploit its own reanalyses, which will become the world standard.
 Others' use of the reanalyses will only enhance and improve their
own research, at negligible cost.  And ECMWFs entry on the scene
of coupled ocean-atmosphere models promises tough competition
for US researchers.  Their move into this work at the time of
the reanalysis and the acquisition of a significant increase in
computing power was prescient.  It's a safe bet that the &quot;3-year
experiment&quot; is just a warm up.<P>

<B>6. Points of Contact</B><P>
