<BODY>

<H3>27 May 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #3<BR>
Preliminary thoughts on the "Western Europe Science System"</H3>

<I>Keywords: S&T Policy; R&D practices; EC; Transatlantic cooperation</I><P>
<PRE><B>
Contents:</B><BR>
1.  Summary
2.  Introduction
3.  S&T Policies
4.  EC Impact
5.  Scientific and Public Attention to S&T
6.  Practice of S&T
7.  Comments
8.  Feedback
</PRE>
<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
	One of ONR Europe's objectives is to enhance transatlantic S&T collaboration in support of mutual security interests.  Effective collaboration is based on common technical interests and perceived equality of benefit to participants.  Science policies and practices influence the willingness of sponsors, institutions, and individuals to collaborate.  This paper discusses some initial hypotheses about S&T in western Europe, the similarities and differences with the US, and implications for transatlantic cooperation.  In general, the trends favor pan-European coalescence to the detriment of traditional linkages to the US S&T community.  The US needs to take an active role in fostering collaboration if it wishes to maintain or enhance transatlantic security-related S&T cooperation.<P>

<B>2.  Introduction</B><BR>
	Usually we at Edison House report on new S&T ideas in our area of responsibility.  When we sit around and talk, however, the conversation often dwells as much on the practices and problems of research at the institutes we visit as the work itself.  Many of us are struck by the significant differences between how "things work" over here, and how we managed our programs or labs or institutes or individual research projects in the States.  We think the differences are significant, and that we have a lot to gain from learning and talking about them.<BR>
	Thus we have decided to start occasionally writing papers on the Science System in Europe, and the differences between European and US practices.  As time goes on, we hope to extend this discussion to Eastern Europe and other parts of our area; and as we develop S&T cooperative strategies and country plans, we'll try to be more specific and to substantiate the admittedly loose arguments of this paper.  We invite criticisms and thoughts from both sides of the Atlantic - especially if you'll let us promulgate them on our web page.  <P>

<B>3. S&T Policies</B><BR>
	Let's start with S&T policies.  The main difference between European nations and the US is they've got 'em, and we don't.  The Europeans have made hard choices, largely linking S&T tightly to quality of life and economic growth (the UK refers to "wealth generation"), and concentrating on regional and local strengths.  Scientists "know" why they are doing what they're doing and how their work relates to national and international priorities, and describe the utility of their work in their proposals, or they simply don't get funded.  <BR>
Not so, of course, in the US.  Lacking a nationally accepted rationale for S&T, the US community gets buffeted by pragmatic adjustments and an inability to justify projects in terms of why the public should support them (other than "good science" which at the bottom line is a cop out).  We Americans in Europe have great difficulty in explaining this national malaise, and thus in effectively convincing our European colleagues that they should want to deal with us.  Try explaining the current straits of NSF and DDR&E and ONR etc., and our about-faces on industrial support via NIST and ARPA, and our redundant, competitive and wasteful approaches to Federal labs, and our dismal record of "partnership", to a skeptical European Commissioner or to any European national S&T sponsor (like MoD or any of the Research Councils here in the UK).  We're not dealing from a position of strength, and our hard choices - many of which they have made - are still ahead.<BR>
I find a curious inverse between S&T and industry.  There's great concern in Europe about the rationalization of US defense industry and resulting competitiveness.  They're worried here about becoming only subcontractors to the Lockheed-Martin etc behemoths that have slimmed down to competitive supremacy (at least for now...Europe's working on this though with difficulty).  However in S&T and tech transfer, the Europeans are the ones who have rationalized and reengineered, while we have fought change and failed to develop national consensus.<P>

<B>4.  EC Impact</B><BR>
	There are really two closely intertwined levels of European S&T policy, national and international, both through the European Union (whether a nation is in or out, the Union is a powerful influence) and through many other bi- and multi-lateral relationships.  We in the US often tend to underestimate the EU's impact on how science is done.  The newspapers highlight political disagreements, the European Commission's propaganda machine (it's even more prolific than NASA's) accentuates the 'Programmes', and the mechanisms and successes of European cooperation.  The EC is a large, complex, and powerful bureaucracy with a heavy overhead burden. We often tend to confuse the bureaucracy with the reality.  What really has happened in R&D however, is first that the competitive/cooperative dynamic at the European level has inevitably shaped national as well as international S&T policies.  The funding comes from the nations, and they each must figure out how to get back at least their fair share in the areas they care most about, as well as foster European programs that advance their individual interests.  Second, the bureaucratic requirements for transnational collaboration have caused the bench scientists to really come face to face and learn about what each other are doing, and to decide - however reluctantly at the start - that there's a lot to be said for collaboration.<BR>
	I listened the other day to a European scientist griping (somewhat proudly perhaps) that in spite of all the fuss and bother and the low probability of success, the EC programs do really make you fly over and get face-to-face with the folks you signed up to work with and write reports with them; and you really do learn something from the interaction as well as find that working together is fun.  Through such processes the Europeans in many fields have discovered sufficient breadth and depth of interests and capabilities among their continental colleagues that they have little need any longer to seek US training or collaboration.<BR>
	Point?  We shouldn't underestimate the degree to which "Europe" is becoming much more cohesive in S&T via the EC programs and other pan-European pressures.  When its real in the working labs, irrespective of the politics and bureaucracy and what's in the papers, its real.  And oh yes, it sure doesn't include us (US).  Deliberately, and with cause.  And since European S&T is tightly coupled to economic growth, it will contribute directly to competitive dynamics in the marketplace.<P>

<B>5.  Scientific and Public Attention to S&T</B><BR>
	Not only do Europeans take their policies and interactions seriously, they study them and their impact seriously.  Not just by commissions and in ministerial white/green/etc papers, but by graduate students and professors studying how the system works and inquiring in quite ingenious ways about how to make it work better.  In the intellectual analysis of the processes of S&T, and in fields such as IPR, they're doing world class research.  The EC even has an entire Joint Research Center, the Institute for Prospective Technological Studies in Seville, dedicated to "the observation and follow up of technological change, in the broad sense in order to get a better understanding of its links with economy and society."  By comparison, the US hardly considers these legitimate research topics; the demise of OTA is a case in point.<BR>
In a similar sense, there is active public debate in Europe about R&D policies, funding, and priorities.  Research and its impact, national and EC allocations, comparisons of investments and economic growth, and criticism of ministerial decisions are frequent topics in the popular media.  In the US, such discussions are pretty well restricted to journals read only by the affected community, and R&D is a "left-over" in the budget debates.  S&T funding is in difficulty on both sides of the Atlantic; it's the nature and level of concern and discussion that seem to be different. 
The Europe-Europe relationships are closing in with us out not just by political volition, but even more by simple recognition of common interests, strengths, capabilities, and practices, and by intellectual curiosity about the process and the products of S&T.  Europeans want to match long term strength to strength, stability to stability, concern to concern, curiosity to curiosity.  To an increasing degree in some very important areas, that doesn't include us.<P>

<B>6.  Practice of S&T</B><BR>
	Being in London, it would be hard not to comment on "Tea".  I've noticed that many of my European colleagues get together for tea of coffee at their Institutes or universities once or twice a day, and also frequently lunch together.  Departments, divisions, groups or whatever congregate very informally in some common space to have their refreshment and chat.  The work pace includes rubbing time, the work space includes rubbing space.  We in the US occasionally do this, but not as a practice and within a much more proscribed "interaction radius" (and in the government such practice is anathema).  I'd guess our mingle radius is maybe 50 feet, time maybe 1-2 minutes, group size 2-3; theirs is more like 150 meters, 15-30 minutes, 10-30 people.  Quite a different approach, with quite a different scientific society as a result.<BR>
	Formally as well as informally, Europeans seem to put more emphasis on "groups" than we do.  Science-funding agencies interact with Universities differently than we, with regard to what they fund and why.  We still focus on the individual investigator, the PI.  The stress here is on interaction and group participation - among teams, among countries, among industry labs and universities and government labs, between researchers and industrialists or policy makers, etc.  This happens at many levels, but the bottom line -- as revealed by some interesting recent bibliographic studies (Katz and Hicks, University of Suffolk) -- is that (at least in the UK) comparing early 80s to early 90s, a lot more of the peer-reviewed literature has been coming from industry and similar non-traditional sites, a much smaller share is single or double-authored (with a big growth of >4 authors), and there is a striking growth in networking and interdisciplinary work.  The nature of how science is practiced has changed, presumably partly because of the internal dynamics of increased complexity (more of the really interesting questions require a multi-disciplinary, multiple-team campaign) and improved tools for collaboration, and partly because of policy shifts to take advantage of these trends and to foster European and regional strength.  I'm not aware of similar patterns in the states.<P>

<B>7. Comments</B><BR>
My summary so far: Natural proclivities and funding patterns re rationale for, and collaboration and interaction in S&T, are quite different between the US and Europe.  Maintaining traditional levels of transatlantic cooperation will require changes of attitude and approach on the part of the US.  These issues are important for the national security community because they influence our ability to achieve successful defense cooperation in an era of coalition security.  Over the coming months we will test these hypotheses in discussions with European R&D sponsors, and try to provide more specific assessments of policies and trends in individual fields and nations.<P>

<B>8.  Feedback</B><BR>
The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology development in European countries.  In order to better meet your needs, our staff are very much interested in knowing of your specific science and technology interests.  Please let us know what they are.
Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of, who may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail addresses to us and we will add them to the distribution list.<BR>
ONR Europe is on the World Wide Web.  Our home page contains information about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters.  Find us at: http://www.ehis.navy.mil/<P><HR><P>
The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P>

For further general information please contact :<BR>
      Craig Dorman<BR>
      Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
      Tel:           44 171 514 4508<BR>
      Fax:           44 171 514 4924<BR>
      E-mail :      cdorman@onreur.navy.mil<BR>
      International Address:<BR>
            223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
