<HEAD>
<TITLE>CO/TD Newsletter #4</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H3>9 June 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #4<BR>
NATO Advanced Studies Institute (ASI) on Biosocial Bases of Violence: Theory and Research</H3>

<I>Keywords: Violence; psychology; sociology; anti-social behavior</I><P>
<PRE><B>
Contents:</B><BR>
1.  Summary
2.  Description of the ASI
3.  Approaches and Findings
	a.  Violence as a Dependent Variable
	b.  General Biosocial Models
	c.  Laboratory Studies
	d.  Longitudinal Studies
4.  Organizer's Overview
5.  Observer's Comments
6.  Feedback
</PRE>
<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
	The crime rate has risen dramatically in the last half century and violence is an urgent issue for society, though study of its causes is in its infancy.  This ASI brought together over 60 international researchers and students from the biological and psychosocial sciences to contribute their findings in an effort to develop a model of the factors and processes that lead to violence.  Criminal violent behavior is much more prevalent among males than females, and peaks sharply at around age 17.  Thus many of the studies presented at the ASI focused on early biological and social factors.  Correlations with violent aggression were shown with risk factors such as arousal, brain damage, seratonin, parental care and socioeconomic status; in some studies biological factors were more strongly implicated in favored than in deprived environments.  There appear to be at least two classes of offenders, "adolescence limited" and "life-course persistent".  At this point however the field lacks an overall conceptual model; there are few commonly accepted definitions, techniques, and typologies, and virtually no testable theories about cause and effect.  The interactive model proposed at the ASI will further increase the complexity of empirical research in this area.<P>

<B>2.  Description of the ASI</B><BR>
	The NATO Advanced Study Institute (ASI) on Biosocial Bases of Violence was organized by researchers at the University of Southern California and Cambridge University, and directed by Dr. Adrian Raine, Department of Psychology, USC.  The ASI took place in Rhodes, Greece, from 12-20 May 1996.  The format was two morning and one afternoon session per day; each session comprised one major or three shorter papers, plus a discussant and (lively) general discussion.  Per NATO ASI rules, attendance at all sessions was compulsory.  Although the ASI was attended by representatives from many NATO and Partnership for Peace nations, most of the papers were from researchers from the US and the UK.  The ASI did have a good mix of new and experienced scientists.  The papers will be published in book form.<BR>
	The study of violence is inherently multi-disciplinary.  Papers at the ASI came from criminologists, psychologists, psychiatrists, sociologists, cognitive scientists, biochemists and physiologists.  However there was a emphasis on developmental psychology, and on the correlation of various social and biological factors with male anti-social behavior during childhood, adolescence, and early maturity.  There was criticism from both the biological and social sides about gaps in the factors that were considered (e.g., neglect of extrafamilial social factors like peer pressure; no molecular biology; minimal cognitive science).  In addition many of the participants were not familiar with the work or the approaches of others; the field seems to be characterized by many small individualistic groups, with little agreement on models, methods or metrics and even less attempt to integrate process with descriptive studies.  Nonetheless, or perhaps because of these characteristics, the ASI was a significant opportunity for participants with common general concerns to learn and interact, and such of course is the intent of an ASI.  At issue is the ability of the organizers to incorporate the diverse contributions into recommendations for a coherent research agenda which can then be debated within the community as a basis for advancement of the field.<P>

<B>3.  Approaches and Findings</B><BR>
<I>a.  Violence as a Dependent Variable</I><BR>
	There is no generally accepted definition of violence.  The ASI was actually interested in (and papers covered different aspects of) the full continuum of antisocial behavior (ASB), ranging from disruptive actions of children at home and school, to extreme criminal violence such as rape and murder.  It was generally agreed that there are useful ways to broadly subcategorize ASB, e.g. by whether it is directed toward property or people, whether or not the targets are related or otherwise close to the perpetrator, and whether the behavior is impulsive or instrumental.  The relative contribution of genetic and environmental factors varies with the type of ASB.  Many of the papers made such distinctions, one of the more consistent being the degree of impulsiveness and its relationship to various aspects of temperament.<BR>
There also is an emerging and widely accepted hypothesis, credited to Dr. T. Moffitt of the University of Wisconsin, that there is a clear distinction between "adolescence limited" and "life course persistent" offenders.  The general pattern of violent activity by males is a rapid rise during the early teen years, peaking at about age 17 and then decreasing.  Adolescence limited offenders enter into ASB relatively late and desist soon; life-course persistent offenders start displaying ASB very early, and persist.  Such frequent, chronic offenders account for a significant percentage of convictions (and other measures of violence).<BR>
	One consistent difficulty for studies of ASB is the generally poor, often misleading quality of data on violent acts.  Youthful ASB is reported by parents and teachers; because the contexts of home, school and other social circumstances differ, so do these reports.  The alternatives for data on older offenders are self-reports (which no one trusts), and (for criminal violence) court records.  In many countries court records significantly distort reality.  Minors frequently have a dozen or more court appearances (and of course an undetermined number of uncaught offenses) before punishment is imposed (this has a conditioning or learning effect on the perpetrator); plea bargains and legal procedures very often result in convictions for crimes significantly different from the actual violent act (manslaughter or assault for murder, etc); criminal justice practices change over time; courts in many countries do not share records across jurisdictions, etc.  Some of the better data are from Scandinavian countries because of the quality of their records, and thus there are more studies of violence (though not necessarily more violence) in Sweden, Denmark, etc than say in Russia or Italy.<BR>
	Data on ASB can also be influenced by changes across cultures.  For example, similar behavior may or may not be classified as criminal depending on socioeconomic status and profession (generals and politicians were mentioned).  The vast majority of the data at the ASI related to modern western nations (one exception is the Mauritius longitudinal study); though there do not appear to be any major differences across the cultures reported.  While genetic factors are accepted as reasonably universal, the environmental conditions in nations which might be considered of concern to NATO were not discussed.  Perception of the issue, not to mention social factors predisposing to ASB as defined in a culture, may well be significantly different in e.g. Asian or African areas, let alone in societies and groups which promote and extol violence, such as Hammas and the IRA.  <BR>
	Historical trends can also influence findings, particularly if not accounted for in comparative assessments or in lengthy longitudinal studies.  Dr. M. Rutter (Institute of Psychiatry, London)  described the factor of 6 increase in crime rate in the UK between 1950 and 1994 (similar in the US; but in the US the homicide rate is much higher than in almost all other nations, attributed to US gun laws), paralleled by increased conduct problems in more youthful cohorts and a change in the sex ratio from 10 male to 1 female crime, to 5:1.  He also noted that its easier to rule out than to determine reasons for the change, though opportunities and stressors have risen demonstrably and there have been major changes in rearing conditions, living arrangements, and life course [e.g., prolonged transition to adulthood] which are particularly relevant to late adolescence when violence peaks.<P>

<I>b.  General biosocial Models</I><BR>
	Two basic types of models were considered at the ASI.  The first is process models which depict the interaction of different risk and protective factors (independent variables) leading to expression of the dependent variable, violence.  At the start of the ASI, the organizers proposed a model in which biological (genetically determined) and social (environmental) risk factors interact with each other and with biological and social protective factors to influence an individual's propensity for and participation in violence (with feedback); but with the added element of a distinct interactive "biosocial" pathway.  ASI participants were encouraged to debate not just the model but the very existence and nature of "biosocial" factors; and indeed there was a wide range of opinions and lively discussion throughout the workshop.  However at the level of precision with which independent variables were defined and used at the ASI, it was frequently impossible to distinguish clearly which was which (e.g. resting heart rate, which is widely used as a significant indicator of arousal but is influenced both by genetics and by conditioning).<BR>
	In his summary overview at the end of the ASI, David Farrington of Cambridge University, one of the organizers, summarized this type model as follows; even in this simplistic form, much additional debate and analysis will be required before this community has a generally accepted approach within which hypotheses can be evaluated.<P>
<IMG SRC="cd-diag.gif"><P>






 

	The second type model considered at the ASI classifies individuals in terms of personality or temperament.  The objective of such models is to depict a set of factors or traits, which in combination are predictive of propensity toward various behavior patterns.  Inventories or tests are used in classification.  There are many such models, with a similarly large range of factors.  The two models presented at the ASI were the classic 3-factor model of Dr. H. Eysenck (Institute of Psychiatry, London), and a more recent variant developed by Dr. R. Cloninger (Washington University Medical Center, St. Louis, MO).<BR>
	Eysenck's factors are termed psychoticism, extroversion (cortical arousal), and neuroticism (emotional arousal).  The three scales measure individuals' base level of arousal of different types (e.g. extroverts need and seek more stimulation to achieve cortical arousal), their degree of impulsivity, and their response to conditioning of different types.  In general higher scores in the three factors (denoting aggressiveness, insensitivity and impulsive behavior) correlate with a higher probability of ASB, with both general and specific differences with age (e.g., all three peak at ages 16-20, as does criminality; extroversion is more highly correlated with ASB in children, neuroticism in adults).  Generally speaking, traits in Eysenck's personality model relate to propensity as used in Farrington's process model.  <BR>
	Cloninger starts with and extends Eysenck's constructs.  His first set of factors relate to what he terms "temperament".  Temperament stabilizes by about the age of six.  Three of Cloninger's temperament factors are based on the type of stimulus response or conditioning involved (from animal studies).  They are Novelty Seeking (NS; behavioral activation), Harm Avoidance (HA; behavioral inhibition); and Reward Dependence (RD; behavioral maintenance).  These factors are essentially independent phenotypically and genetically, and are substantially (40-60%) heritable.  Measures of these three factors can be plotted, the resultant cube displaying temperament characteristics which then can be correlated to propensity for types of behavior (e.g. high NS and low HA characterizes anti-social adventurousness and is predictive for criminality, alcohol and drug abuse, etc.).  There is also a fourth factor, persistence.<BR>
	Cloninger then notes that the 4 "habit systems" of temperament are based on unconscious response to emotional stimuli; even in extremes, these are moderated in humans by conceptual or symbolic learning.  He thus also measures three factors of "character", which involve the sense of self and propositional learning.  As distinguished from temperament, character changes with age, and it is very strongly influenced by family and other aspects of the social environment.  The three measures are self directedness (relationship to and perception of self), cooperativeness (relationship to society), and self-transcendence (relationship to the world).  Like temperament, measures of character can be plotted on a cube, and they are predictive of maturation, learning, and performance as well as ASB.  Cloninger notes that there are many nonlinear interactions among the 7 dimensions, and the corners of the cubes tend to serve as "attractors". <BR>
	Cloninger's model was (surprisingly) not familiar to the majority of participants in the ASI.  However this report has described it at slightly greater length than other papers both because Cloninger is employing it and the associated tests in work for the USAF (and it would appear to have additional utility in military training), and because it would appear to be a good base for relating and understanding other work in the field, and for starting to formulate and test hypotheses on causative processes underlying many of the otherwise unrelated findings that were presented.<BR>
	First, most case and longitudinal studies (discussed briefly below) use personality factors as a basis for describing or relating the variables of interest.  From discussions with Cloninger, it would appear that the investigators who have employed his model have found it to be consistently useful (and predictive) across a wide range of cultures and behavioral studies (and even the one paper on violent behavior in criminal psychopaths used measures that resembled Cloninger's).  Consistent use of a model such as Cloninger's at least would allow researchers to compare results.  Second, in his talk Cloninger mentioned hormonal correlations with his temperament factors (e.g. dopamine-NS; seratonin-HA and nonepinpherine-RD).  Such hypotheses, if substantiated, may have explanatory value as well as provide guidance for the use of biological assays.  His model combines both genetic and environmental factors in such a way as could be further elucidated and perhaps modeled and studied mathematically in terms of independence and interrelationships (it would appear suitable as the basis for some powerful numerical modeling and advanced statistical analyses, perhaps incorporating chaos theory as Cloninger implied).  Finally it incorporates at least two distinctly different processes of learning (conditioning and symbolic), and thus could incorporate cognitive and information processing theory and associated studies of brain function in a consistently useful way for behavioral studies.  As an observer with minimum experience in the fields employed at the ASI, I may have misinterpreted or been inappropriately impressed, but in my opinion Cloninger's approach could serve as an excellent starting point for the discussions and debates this field will need to engage in if it is to develop a more coherent approach to the problem it has identified.  And if not Cloninger's, then some such internally consistent model will be required for the field to advance.<P>

<I>c.  Laboratory Studies</I><BR>
	These are experimentally oriented studies that focus on groups with common characteristics.  The subjects are usually captive populations which can be induced to participate in lab interventions (e.g. students, prisoners) or groups experiencing similar biological events (pregnancy, puberty, etc).  Many papers at the ASI reported such work, with topics ranging from perinatal influences on early ASB, to hormonal changes in adolescence, to hormonal and psychophysiological functions in wife batterers, to prefrontal glucose metabolism dysfunction in murderers, to the emotional and temperament characteristics of criminal psychopaths.  Such controlled studies form the basis for clinical assessments and interventions, and reveal correlations which can then form the basis for measures and hypotheses employed in longitudinal and other field studies of more diverse populations.<P>

<I>d.  Longitudinal Studies</I><BR>
	Long term field studies of cohorts are a classic tool for both biological and social studies.  A number were discussed at the ASI; two examples are the Dunedin (New Zealand) and the Mauritius Studies.  The former involved 1037 subjects from a lower SES area who were age three in 1975, with follow-up sampling every 2-3 years since.  The latter has followed 1795 children from two mixed Indian/Creole towns, starting at age 3 in 1972.  Such studies obviously require extensive efforts on the part of several generations of scholars and generate massive amounts of data; thus they also produce many theses and papers.  Equally obviously, they are complicated by changes over time in knowledge and available interventions, by historical trends, by later misinterpretation of data inadequately documented by those who collected it, and by simple logistics (e.g. families move and, as noted by one researcher, some of the best subjects for the study of violent behavior tend to get removed from the data pool through early death).<BR>
	The Dunedin and Mauritius studies have followed their cohorts through and past the typical peak of mid-late teen criminality/ASB, and -- as with the historic increase in violence discussed by Rutter --  have demonstrated that it is easier to rule out than to find causes.  As Moffitt stated at the summary session, the field is still in its infancy and practitioners are "too thrilled when we get a finding" to have yet even started to truly understand the findings.  They have however led to Moffitt's contention, mentioned earlier, that the groups of adolescent limited and life-course persistent offenders are distinct, as well as more recent findings such as that seratonin blocks signals of punishment and thus reduces behavioral inhibition.  <BR>
	As a very gross generalization, longitudinal studies show correlations between low arousal (e.g., low resting heart rate) and violence, presumptively through its influence on stimulation seeking and associated hormonal involvement.  Lack of control and disinhibited temperament at an early age (3-5) also correlate with low resting heart rate, and are predictive of violent ASB.  Biological factors like heart rate (measured at an early age, prior to the impact of athletic training) however are closely interrelated with social factors; they are often most significant in conditions of lower environmental risk, e.g. low resting heart rate appears more linked to criminality in individuals with benign backgrounds.<BR>
	Overall the balance between biological and social factors remains unclear.  Certainly adverse family environment (birth complications, maternal neglect, parental abuse or absence, low socioeconomic status) predisposes to ASB, but multiple interrelated variables are almost always involved.  Biological and social factors which lead to predispositions or propensity toward violence -- characteristics of temperament in Cloninger's terms, or factors such as impulsiveness, arousal and emotional detachment -- are strongly mediated by environmental and situational influences.  The bottom line is that in spite of the increasing levels of violence and the need for intervention, longitudinal studies have to date provided little sound scientific foundation for social policy.<P>

<B>4.   Organizer's Overview</B><BR>
	At the conclusion of the ASI, Farrington attempted a summary of the proceedings.  He sketched the model included in paragraph 3.b. above, and stated that the key question remains as to which general model to use.  He then raised eight issues before returning to the central concern of improving progress in the field.  Among his points were the following:<BR>
	<I>Violence:</I> Different theories may be required to understand different types of violence.  The validity of measurement and classification needs to be improved.  Comorbidity with nonviolent offenses, clinical disorders, ASB etc confuses results. <BR> 
	<I>Propensity:</I> Many constructs were implicated as explanatory: e.g., arousal, fearlessness, impulsivity, disinhibition, novelty seeking, self control, etc; these are not all independent, and need to be more precisely defined and related to each other and to their effects.  Cognitive, emotional, attitudinal and social learning need to be incorporated into the model of the processes leading to propensity, and this in turn must be causally linked to situational effects to yield behavior.<BR>
	<I>Biological variables:</I>  Again there is a problem with definitions.  Some of the variables reported as correlated with violent ASB include heart rate, skin conductance, genetics, serotonin, testosterone, frontal lobe disfunction and birth complications; there are disagreements over what, when or how to measure some of these, particularly in community surveys.  Because of measurement difficulties, sample sizes are often much smaller than for social variables.  Some of the data, e.g. influence of sex hormones on ASB, is extremely problematic.  Coincidence in multiple-problem individuals can be confusing.  Are risk and protective factors different, or opposite?<BR>
	<I>Psychosocial variables:</I> Among the main psychological variables discussed were personality, intelligence, self-esteem, and hyperactivity; social factors included socio-economic status, convicted or single parents, school performance, and parental violence.  Similar issues as with biological factors pertain: definition of the constructs and their measurement, separation of risk and protective factors, and coincidence.<BR>
	<I>Causal relationships:</I> There is a lack of well specified testable theories about influences among the "independent" variables, as well as about causal relationships.<BR>
	<I>Interaction effects:</I> Again, theories are needed.  Many examples of interaction were presented, e.g. the increased effect of biological factors in favored vs deprived backgrounds.  Some of these interactions may be protective and have practical implications.<BR>
	<I>Types of Individuals:</I> The postulated difference between adolescence-limited and life course persistent offenders needs to be refined and evaluated.  Models should incorporate personality theories and developmental pathways. <BR> 
	<I>Analytic methods:</I> Most studies employ fairly basic statistical procedures.  Multiple regression techniques are important for testing independence versus additive impact.  Both prospective and retrospective procedures are needed, and more complex modeling will be required to test specific theories as they are developed; to date there have been very few tests of sequential models.<BR>
	<I>How to proceed:</I>  The many different findings, although interesting, all use different constructs.  Each research group has its own approach and interests, and there is little basis for sharing data or building on others' results.  However the problem is larger than the ability of any individual or single group to solve.  The field needs to reach agreement on a general model, to develop some specific theories associated with it, to agree on the definition of its variables and their measurement, and to evolve common or at least compatible experimental designs and analytical methods.  The longitudinal studies are impressive, but the data from them needs to be usable by a variety of groups to independently test theories and to compare results.  <P>

<B>5.  Observer's comments</B><BR>
	I was interested in attending the ASI less because of its focus on violence than because "biosocial" techniques and findings have profound impact on military issues as diverse as selection and training, and information warfare.  Violence certainly is militarily significant, both as a societal phenomenon and as an aspect of warfare (and OOTW), but my curiosity was about whether we now know, or soon will know, enough about human behavior to effectively predict or manipulate it, i.e. to be deliberately helpful or dangerous.  If this ASI was at all representative of the disciplines it gathered together, the answer is pretty conclusively no, except perhaps in very tightly constrained circumstances.  Left unanswered is whether disciplines and countries not represented at this meeting have made any more progress.<BR>
	It's difficult not to make comparisons with a field with which I'm somewhat more familiar, oceanography.  It also has a broad scope and involves many disciplines.  During the last decade or so, many of its most interesting questions have been of a scale that required truly global collaboration to address.  Global climate change and the formation and movement of the ocean floor are examples.  To study such issues, researchers of many different persuasions and institutions, however intellectually (and fiscally) competitive, have been forced to agree on initiatives that combine theoretical development, numerical and analytical modeling, lab experiments and massive international field campaigns focused on a common set of basic questions, and to employ instruments and procedures that permit intercomparison and sharing of data.  <BR>
	The apparent total lack of any such construct in the field addressed by this ASI is striking.  Perhaps the only areas of consistent general agreement were that violence is an urgent social problem and our understanding of it is in its infancy, characterized more by quasi-empirical searches for relationships than by well specified and testable hypotheses soundly based on understanding of cause and effect.  There was no consistency in how to address the problem.<BR>
	The organizers' efforts in running the ASI, and Farrington's observations at its conclusion, indicate that they recognize the need for significantly enhanced collaboration and coherence.  My sense is that the basis for a more unified approach is available, e.g. in some combination and extension of the models proposed by Raine/Farrington and Cloninger.  Powerful mathematical, biological, cognitive, and experimental tools are available.  What seems to be missing is the focus, and the willingness to work together.  At issue is whether any combination of investigators and sponsors (both will be required) have enough concern to devote the needed years of effort, and enough credibility within the community, to change the process by which the problems of violence (and other issues of behavior) are approached.<P>

<B>6.  Feedback</B><BR>
