<H3>6 August 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #5<BR>
ONR Celebrates 50th Anniversary in Europe During TOS 1996 Meeting</H3>

<I>Keywords:   ONR, 50th Birthday, TOS, Amsterdam, Oceanography</I><P>

<B>Contents:</B>
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Symposium Details
<DD>	2 1.  Plenary Session
<DD>	2.2.  Poster Session and Birthday Celebration
<LI>Contacts
</OL>

<B>1. Summary</B><BR>
The <B>Office of Naval Research</B> celebrated the 50th birthday of both ONR Europe and the parent organization during <B>The Oceanography Societys</B> 1996 Meeting in Amsterdam, The Netherlands, 8 - 11 July .  In honor of this anniversary, TOS allocated the evening of 8 July  for a "Symposium on 50 Years of ONR Contributions to International Oceanography".  The Symposium included a plenary session at the main conference site at the Okura Hotel, followed by a poster session and birthday celebration at the Netherlands Maritime Museum.  Attendance was approximately 215 people from 20 countries worldwide.<BR>
The full TOS meeting is summarized in a separate ONR Europe Newsletter.<P>

<B>2. Symposium Details</B><BR>
<B>2 1.  Plenary Session</B><BR>
The plenary session (Fig 1) started at 16:30 on 8 July 1996 in the Heian Zaal Room of the Okura Hotel with welcoming remarks by the Deputy Chief of Naval Research/ONR Technical Director, Dr. <B>Fred Saalfeld</B> (Fig. 2).  Besides welcoming the attendees to this Symposium, Dr. Saalfeld traced the history of ONR, its present mission and the role of  ONR Europe in that mission.  ONR supports science and technology (S&T) in areas of importance to the U.S. Navy.  ONR Europe forges partnerships between U.S. S&T and that going on in Europe.  Dr. Saalfeld emphasized the importance of international partnerships with his discussion of the new <B>Navy International Cooperative Opportunities in Science and Technology Program (NICOP)</B>  that will open a new era of joint U.S. - International cooperation.  Choice of the TOS meeting as the venue for celebrating ONRs 50 birthday highlights the importance of the ocean sciences to the overall missions of ONR in general, and ONR Europe in particular.<P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/50FIG1.GIF"><P>
    
Figure 1.  Plenary Session Overview<P>			

<IMG SRC="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/50FIG2.GIF"><P>
Figure 2.	Dr. Fred Saalfeld welcoming Symposium attendees<P>

Dr. <B>Klaus Hasselmann</B>, Director of the Max-Planck Institute fuer Meteorologie, Hamburg, Germany, followed with a paper entitled "ONR Contributions to International Ocean Science" (Fig 3).  Dr. Hasselmann opened his presentation by noting that the success of ONRs policy of supporting international ocean science can be largely attributed to two essential ingredients: vision and consistency.  He chose two specific examples to make his point; Arctic/Marginal Ice Zone, and Surface Waves.  The paper proceeded to describe the evolution of these areas and highlighted scientific results from both.  The most important result from the latter was the development of the third generation ocean wave model, WAM, which is used today for routine wave forecasts at weather centers worldwide (e.g.. Fleet Numerical Meteorology and Oceanography Center, National Centers for Environmental Prediction, European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasting, and the U.K. Meteorological Office).<P>

Dr. <B>Giancarlo Vettori</B> (Fig 4), Deputy Director of the SACLANT Undersea Research Centre, La Spezia, Italy, next illustrated ONRs contributions to international ocean science and technology with his paper entitled "ONR Contributions to the SACLANT Undersea Research Centre" (Fig 4).   Some of the examples Dr. Vettori chose to highlight included conference support, field experiments, comprehensive reviews, collaborative studies and instrumentation development.  Specific examples included a conference on bottom shear waves, low frequency volume reverberation experiments in the GINSEA to connect fish distributions with reverberation levels, shallow water acoustic measurements review and summary, and collaboration with Columbia University to develop an expendable bottom penetrometer.  These contributions were set into the context of 15 years of SACLANT Centre S&T.<P>

<IMG SRC="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/50FIG3.GIF"><P>        
Figure 3.  Dr. Klaus Hasselmann delivering paper<P>	

<IMG SRC="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/50FIG4.GIF"><P>
Figure 4.  Dr. Giancarlo Vettori delivering paper<P>

Dr. <B>Craig Dorman</B>, Technical Director, ONR Europe, closed the plenary session by thanking the speakers and presenting each of them with a plaque commemorating their contributions to ocean science in general and to the Symposium, in particular.  <P>

<B>2.2.  Poster Session and Birthday Celebration</B><BR>
Following the plenary session, Symposium attendees boarded canal boats (Fig 5) for cruise to the Netherlands Maritime Museum .  At the museum, six invited authors (Fig 6) presented poster papers illustrating work presently funded by ONR.  These covered the spectrum from ocean surface phenomena and processes (<B>Caulliez</B> et. al, FRANCE, <B>Hasselmann</B> et al , GERMANY; <B>Larsen</B> et al, DENMARK; and <B>Serio</B>, ITALY) to the marine atmosphere ( <B>Johnson</B>, UK and <B>Grisogono</B>, SWEDEN).  In addition to discussing the poster papers, Symposium attendees toured the Museum.  Figures 7-12  show some of the attendees enjoying the evening.<P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/50FIG5.GIF"><P>
    
Figure 5.   Symposium attendees on way  to Netherlands Maritime Museum<P>

