<HEAD>
<TITLE>CO/TD Newsletter #6</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H3>27 August 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #6<BR>
Dormans Introductory Visit to Kiev, Ukraine</H3>

<I>Keywords: Ukraine; marine science; S&T management</I>

Contents:
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Introduction
<LI>State Committee on Science, Technique, and Industrial Policy
<LI>Environmental Programs
<DIR>	a.  Ministry of Environmental Protection and Nuclear Safety</DIR>
<DIR>	b.  National Agency of Marine Research and Technology</DIR>
<DIR>	c.  National Marine Program</DIR>
<LI>Comment
<LI>Contacts
<LI>Feedback
</OL>

<B>1.  Summary.</B>  ONRs new NICOP attempts to foster long term collaborative relationships between US and international scientists.  This trip was to introduce the new program to one of the major participants in the previous SOP.  The report details conversations at several Ukrainian state offices.  Dorman concludes that the most mutually profitable interactions will continue to be with individual scientists on specific projects of mutual interest.<P>

<B>2.  Introduction.</B>  Drs. Craig Dorman and Igor Vodyanoy visited Kiev, Ukraine from 24-26 July 1996 to introduce ONRs new Naval International Cooperative Opportunities in Science and Technology Program (NICOP).  The visit was arranged by the Ukrainian Office of International Projects (UOIP), which was established and supported by the EC to coordinate their analyses of the effects of the Chernobyl disaster; although that program is over, the UOIP Secretariat remains operative and assists in the coordination of Ukranian R&D with both NIS and western nations.  In addition to the primary purpose of the visit, presentation of NICOP to the State Committee on Science, Technology, and Industrial Policy, the meetings focused on Ukranian environmental and marine programs (because of Dormans background and Navy interests).  All conversations were conducted through interpreters; the comments below portray Dormans understanding of the major points discussed.<P>

<B>3.  State Committee on Science, Technique and Industrial Policy.</B>  We met with the Deputy Chairman Dr. Victor Svizhenko, and the Chief of the General Department of Critical Technology and Conversion, Dr Anatoly Maximov.  The Committee was formed after independence, in 1991.  Since S&T previously had been governed from Moscow via the Russian Academy and its main Institutes there, the Committees first responsibility was to formulate Ukrainian national S&T policy, and coordinate among the Ukrainian national academies (Ukrainian National Academy of Science and four special disciplinary academies) and the various Ministries and agencies.  At the time of our visit, the President had approved upgrading the committees status to that of a Ministry.  When this occurs the National Agency of Marine Research and Technologies will join it as a Department (but see below; this Agency is fighting absorption); the National Aerospace Agency however will remain separate.<P>

In addition to its policy and coordination responsibilities, the Committee administers funding of S&T.  There are line items in the State budget for the base funding of the Academies and Institutes (of which there are some 1400, about 900 of which are industrial and about 150 military).  In addition, there are two competitive grant programs which make awards to individual investigators irrespective of their organizational affiliation; these supplement the institutional block budgets.  The Directorate of Science administers the applied science program.  It has seven primary areas, confirmed by the Supreme Soviet: Health Protection, Environmental Protection, Agriculture, Materials, Energy, Information Systems, and Communications.  Special national soviets (expert committees) define priorities, and the "Expertise Directorate" forms and coordinates review panels to evaluate the proposals.  There are some 68 individual programs, and about 5000 projects; the average award is enough to support 3 researchers.  The Directorate of Basic Research administers a similar program, divided along standard disciplinary lines.  It supports about 1000 projects per year (NB: EOARD has been attempting to have a list of about 8000 Ukrainian researchers and 5000 proposal titles posted on the web; the site URL will be www.fonon.kiev.ua).<P>

Overall, funding for the academies and Institutes is very low.  The ones we visited and discussed in Kiev all are closed every Friday; and salaries are so low that the researchers all need additional jobs just to survive.  Dr Svizhenko stated that the competitive applied science and basic research programs are much too broad, with too many projects.  They want to focus these efforts (details not provided), and concentrate on areas where the Ukraine was considered world class.  Such areas include materials and welding, remotely controlled coal mining, agriculture, devices for cleaning soil and water, and image processing.  <P>

Other elements of the State Committee include:<BR>
	<DIR>The Legislative Directorate is responsible for developing laws on scientific activity, IPR, etc.</DIR>
	<DIR>The Industrial Policy Directorate is a new organization "trying to find its place", formed from portions of the Ministries of Economics and various different industries, each of which has its own policies.  This Directorate is intended to coordinate industrial policy among the other ministries; exactly how it will function, and how effective it will be, seems unclear.</DIR>
	<DIR>The Directorate of International Relations oversees the governments agreements with some 30 nations and international bodies (individual institutions are also permitted to have bilateral arrangements with counterparts).  President Kuchma recently led an unsuccessful effort to get the FSU nations to agree on a "Single Scientific Space"; in spite of the failure of this proposal the Ukraine still maintains close contacts with the other NIS institutions and academies.</DIR>
	<DIR>The Directorate of Special Works, or General Department of Critical Technology and Conversion, maintains the ties to MoD and assists in the conversion of military industry (especially those aspects associated with weapons of mass destruction).  We were told that the main directions of the program for defense conversion and dual use have been set, and the criteria for selection of critical technologies established.  An advisory commission will soon make the decisions on which parts of the infrastructure to continue to support to meet MoD needs, and which portions to convert. As noted above, there are some 150-200 military-industrial research institutions, although the principal Soviet Military Research Institutions were all in Russia.  In addition there are 32 military academies for education of specialists; many of will these be converted into research centers to establish an indigenous capability to develop military technology.  They have a similar problem with the research fleet; they inherited over 70 ships, few of which they can use.  Some are in commercial service; others are just laid up.</DIR>

We described NICOP and our emphasis on collaborative research.  Dr. Svizhenko indicated that the Institutes were also very interested in undertaking contract research, and that much data and information (e.g. the annual list of proposals) was available and for sale.<P>

<B>4.  Environmental Programs</B><P>

	<B>a. Ministry of Environmental Protection and Nuclear Safety.</B>  We met with Anna Vlasova, Assistant to First Deputy Minister Vasyl Vasylchenko.  The Ministry is about 5 years old, and was merged into its present form in late 1994.  The ministry is responsible for developing and enforcing regulations regarding nuclear safety and ecology, for associated research in five institutions, and for assessments of the state of the environment. We were given a copy of the 1994 State of the Environment report; the 1995 report, and associated reports on the Black Sea (which we saw) and nuclear safety (a copy is available at the US Embassy) were not published due to lack of funds.  The data however could be made available; a "legalized consulting group" could be formed to access it. <BR>
	The Ministry has a staff of about 2000; some 300 in Kiev, and the rest at the research institutions and the 27 regional centers which are responsible for enforcement and regulation and which operate the analytic labs which conduct the annual environmental assessments.  The ministry maintains close relations with the State Committee on S&T through its annual competitions; it supports its own science programs with a fund derived from fines for violation of environmental regulations.  There is also much international support, e.g. for nuclear protection and the Danube and Black Sea programs; but the Ministry finds it hard to assess the impact of these efforts, or even coordinate them effectively, since such support goes directly to the individual institutes.<BR>
	Discussions and the 1994 report make clear that ecology and nuclear safety are major national concerns; the assessments are realistic, and generally pessimistic.  Years of industrial, mining, and agricultural exploitation with virtually no cleanup or concern have resulted in contamination of soils, ground water, rivers, forests, harbors and coasts.  The aftermath of Chernobyl lingers, and there are significant problems with destruction of weapons and silos.  Sevastopol is a major problem due to pollution from naval ships.  There are many such "mini-catastrophes" associated with military and industrial activity.  Pollution is lower today than in former periods, but only because industries are not working because of the economic situation.  A new source of problems is small businesses, which rise and die rapidly and pay little attention to the regulations.  The Ukraine has a sizable and growing set of codes, laws and regulations governing safety and environmental protection, but it a hard uphill battle even to prevent further deterioration.<P>

	<B>b.  National Agency of Marine Research and Technology (NAMRT).</B>  NAMRT was organized in 1993 as a separate state executive, management, and policy agency under the Vice Prime Minister.  As noted above, the State Committee on S&T expects it to become a department under the new Ministry; but the Agency representatives we met (Dr A. Ischenko, First Deputy Director; and Dr I. Skopichenko, Head of the Scientific Organizational Department), expressed their belief that it would instead become a State Committee.<BR>
	Its responsibilities include hydrography (assumed from the Navy; the hydrographers apparently still are naval officers) and the development of a national mapping and charting capability; development of policy recommendations for and coordination of state activity in marine research and use of marine resources, including licensing of research vessels and of resource use in the Black and Azov Seas; official representation in international maritime and marine organizations; coordination of the Antarctic research program including the operation and annual resupply of the Vernadsky Station (competitively acquired from the UK); and development and execution of the "National Program on Research and Use of Resources of the Azov and Black Seas and other regions of the world ocean". <BR>
	Elements of the "National Program" were initially set up by Moscow and spread through various ministries; responsibility for focusing these activities and developing them into a true Program was concentrated in the Agency when it was created in 1993.  The Program - initially involving some 400 "problems" (now about 250) and 40000 participants  was implemented by many different universities, institutes, etc., competitively selected at the start in 1993; if there is more funding, there will be another competition.  It is an applied R&D program, oriented to the development of industrial capability.  It consists of eight "State Programs" (fish farming; non-living resources, i.e. minerals, oil and gas; Fleet and Transport; Recreation; Sea Ecology; Hydrography; the Antarctic Region; and "Poseidon"), and five "Aim-oriented Complex Projects" (Marine Sciences; Strategic Management,; Monitoring; Informatics; and Intellect).  Each of these programs has several major projects (list available); together, and taken at face value, they represent a truly comprehensive effort to develop a modern marine based economy with world wide scope, tightly coordinated by this central agency.  There were major studies leading up to this program, discussing how to make the Ukraine a major seafaring nation; and this is one of five "National Programs" at the Presidential level.  What was not described was funding and progress.  <BR>
Among the various topics we discussed were:<BR>
 The scientific fleet, previously used worldwide by all 
the USSR, had 73 vessels.  Most are now used commercially.  The agency operates one large research vessel (Kiev, used for Antarctic resupply) and several river/coastal vessels; there is one research vessel active in Sevastopol (at MHI, see below) and one in Odessa.  Although these ships may belong to the Academy or institutes, the Agency is the licensing authority.  They also authorize research; the Foreign Ministry turns to the Agency for review of applications for research in Ukrainian waters.
 The fishing fleet has significant economic problems due 
to the doubling of fuel costs.  There is a large Krill fleet, but it sells its catch elsewhere to generate hard currency.  There are 700 km of mollusk farms along the Crimea, but no processing capability and no capital to develop one.  The Black Sea is recovering a bit as industry slows.  However the problem with Black Sea fishing is not depletion of stocks or the environment, but economics.(???)
 The scientific center in Guinea, built in 1973, was 
operated by the Ukraine until 1988.  Guinea then manned it until 1993, when Russia gave it to Guinea as a gift.  It is now in bad shape and Guinea has recently applied for assistance in fixing it and restarting scientific measurements.
 Ukraine is an associate member of the IHO.  They are 
interested in assistance with chart production.  They have the capability to electronically collect hydrographic data (there are 4 hydrographic ships and 28 boats), but not for cartography and chart printing.<P>

	<B>c.  National Marine Program.</B>  We met with Dr. V. Eremeev, Director, Marine Hydrophysics Institute (MHI), Sevastopol, and Dr E. Nikiforovich, Department Head at the Institute of Hydromechanics.  Our host for this meeting was Prof. Peter Shpak, Director of the Institute of Geological Studies. Scince it was Friday, the Institute was otherwise closed; but Prof Shpak very kindly provided a meeting room and hosted lunch in the Chinese restaurant which rents the Institutes ground floor.<BR>
	There are several ongoing international Black Sea programs, sponsored by NATO, the World Bank, GEF, and similar organizations.  Ukrainian marine scientists have participated in these.  At the same time, as noted above, the environmental and ecological conditions continue to deteriorate.  To quote the (translation of the) proposal prepared by Dr Eremeev and his colleagues, "Currently in Ukraine the volume of national production fell by half.  At the same time the national potential or natural resources in our country are being exhausted due to irrational management, basically non-controlled non-regulated exploitation of natural resources, and clear orientation of the market toward exporting of natural resources.  Pollution and degradation of the environment increase significantly, quality of living worsens, vital functions and activities of human life decrease.  All of the above led to significant "ecological" national losses, reaching almost 40% of current gross national product.  This can be estimated at the very least as being no less than $20-30 billion per year...Among the ecologically vulnerable and the most valuable are the southern regions of Ukraine: coastal areas of Black Sea and Azov Sea with concentration of population, ports, industrial and agricultural organizations.  In the recent past this area possessed unique recreation potential and rich natural produce resources."<BR>
	To address these problems, and to derive maximum benefit from the international work in the Black Sea, (again quoting from the proposal translation) "by initiative of employees of a range of leading Institutes of the National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine a proposal of Interstate Programme has been developed.  This programme is aimed on wide ranging and quick solution to most painful ecological problems on the coast of cross-border national reservoirs.  ...In particular, this Programme is dedicated to the following:  R&D and science based implementation within the short time frame of specific practical measures for protection of contact zone "land-sea" from pollution; rehabilitation of natural potential; optimization of land user structure; healthy improvement of the environment populated by people; rehabilitation of natural life-supporting systems."<BR>
	The proposal estimates the cost of the first three years of the program (scientific research and development of methods and technologies) at $14.5M, with additional costs for implementation.  Proposed participants include senior scientists and support staff at the Marine Institute of Hydrodynamics, the Institute of Biology of the Southern Seas in Sevastopol and its Odessa affiliate, the Institute of Hydromechanics, Institute of Geology, Institute of Economics, Ukrainian Center of Sea Ecology, Southern Science and Research Institute of Fishing Industry and Oceanography, Department of Sea Geology and Sediment Ore Formation of the Central Science Museum of Nature Studies, Odessa Institute of Hydrometeorology, and the State Committee for S&T.  Ukranian and English versions of the proposal are available.<P>

<B>5.  Comment.</B>  There was widespread recognition among all those we talked to, of the major problems facing the Ukraine: the environment and economy are both a mess, and the scientific infrastructure is deteriorating.  At issue are the appropriate course of action, and whos in charge.  If the small sampling we observed is any indication, it will be some time before rational progress is made.  The State Committee (Ministry?) of Science, Technology and Industrial Policy has some extremely tough choices to make if it is to rationalize the infrastructure and save the best portions.  Its charter and authorities seem somewhat unclear; the reluctance of the Marine Agency to accept its proposed new status and the tenuous description of the Industrial Policy Directorate suggest that there will be considerable bureaucratic infighting for some time to come.  I believe it unlikely that the necessary draconian decisions can be made and executed under such conditions.<BR>  
	The grandiose nature of NAMRTs "National Program" is reminiscent of Soviet five-year plans.  There was no indication that virtually any of it has been or will be effectively accomplished.  The Academy Institutions, with their own National Marine Program proposal, obviously are charting a different course.  Neither group mentioned, let alone discussed, the other with us, although our agenda was openly available.  In addition, the academicians Proposal in its present form is basically an outline, with little detailed budgetary breakdown or explicit work statements.  <BR>
	We did see evidence of some extremely good science, and of considerable initiative on the part of individuals and organizations.  There does not however appear to be a coherent national policy or rational program in the areas we were exposed to.  This makes it difficult for us to interact with Ukrainian colleagues at other than an individual project level, which may benefit both parties intellectually but does little to improve their national situation or to support the retention of a viable S&T infrastructure.<P>

<B>6.  Contacts.</B><P>

