<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>CO/TD Newsletter #7</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>5 October 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #7<BR>
EU and US Participation in the G7 Project MARIS</H3>

<I>Keywords: marine science; EU; S&T policy; Ireland</I><P>

Contents:
<OL>
<LI>Summary and Appraisal
<LI>EU views of "Information Society"
<LI>MARSOURCE in the EU
<LI>MARTRANS & SAFEMAR in the EU
<LI>MARVEL in the EU
<LI>An Irish Proposal:  MARTOUR, IT for Maritime tourism and leisure
<LI>Canadian, Japanese, and US Positions
<LI>Contacts
<LI>Feedback
</OL>


<B>1.  Summary and Appraisal</B><P>
MARIS - the "Maritime Information Society" - is one of 11 pilot projects adopted by the G7 in June 95, to address the impact of, and adjustments to, the revolution in information technology.  The title comes from the European approach to IT: "Information Society", with an emphasis on people and social/industrial adjustment to technology; the US simply talks about the "Information Superhighway", with the focus on the infrastructure.  The EU and Canada have the lead for MARIS.  This meeting in Dublin (24Sep) was one of several around Europe to further develop the concept, identify opportunities for joint projects, and expose local (in this case Irish) IT and Marine industries to the opportunities.<P>
Following an address by DGIII (Industry) Commissioner M Bangemann on EUs approach to the "Information Society", EC reps gave overviews and chaired workshops on the 4 MARIS subprojects: MARVEL (ship owner, builder, supplier common global network), MARSOURCE (fisheries network for resource preservation and marketing), MARTRANS (port logistics network for real time info on cargo and carriers), and SAFEMAR (ship reporting/tracking and ECDIS).  Canada, Japan and the US also gave their perspectives on this G7 Head of State approved initiative.<P>
The EC has funded and coordinated many dynamic projects under the umbrella of MARIS, focusing on industrial and societal issues.  It is actively soliciting and supporting research and industrial participation in MARIS.  Canada has no single source of MARIS funding, but reported a few related projects, mostly under SAFEMAR.  Japan established a national forum to develop a consensus on what theyre willing to share and how to approach the issue; they suggest a global maritime "intranet" (so one searches using a browser vice requiring standardized formats) keyed to visual presentation of information for "intuitive communication" (e.g., animation to depict weather and wave forecasts and their impact on the consumer at sea).  The US reported that we essentially have done nothing identifiable as MARIS; we agreed to the concept at the Presidential level, but that has not been translated into programmatics or even coordination (although there are of course many relevant efforts underway at a variety of agencies and industries).<P>
The differences between the US and EU (and Japanese) approaches to this G7 initiative are palpable: first, we view the basic IT issue from fundamentally different viewpoints; second, the EC has leaped on this opportunity to advance European maritime potential and tie this initiative in with their Framework etc programmes via bottoms-up participation, and Japan developed a consensus national approach, while the US - for whatever reason - has virtually ignored it.  Equally interesting, no one seemed surprised at the US attitude.  Europeans are looking after their interests and pushing opportunities to improve safety and competitiveness of their industry, especially for SMEs, and if we dont want to (in one of the few areas where, via G7, we have an opportunity to engage closely with the EC), well thats just fine.  American maritime industry can just fend for itself, by itself.<P>

<B>2.  EU views of "Information Society"</B><P>
This well-practiced address was delivered by Martin Bangemann, Commissioner for Industrial Affairs, Information Technologies, and Telecommunications (DGIII).  
The G7 interest in IT and other industrial affairs is global.  However each participant looks for their place in the global society, and Europeans must decide what part of the play must be theirs.  Its important therefore to define the European approach to IT.  In the US, the focus is on the "Information Highway", the infrastructure.  In Europe however it is on the "Information Society", i.e. beyond simply the technology, regulatory framework and infrastructure, to encompass the people who must live with and use the technology.  The EC has thus established an "Information Society Forum" to get all impacted groups involved in the discussion, to avoid splits and the cultural clash of haves and have-nots.<P>
The global growth of IT will have a significant impact on jobs; Ireland is a good example.  The older telecommunications monopolies will initially lose jobs as they are broken through competitiveness, but even they will regrow after restructuring, through the same competitive forces.  This leads now to much concern and fear, and thus it is important to show the utility of the new technologies, both directly and in terms of their "virtual value"; working methods and life styles may change, but this will not reorder the social structure.  As we go through this inevitable transition we must convince the non-believers.  Thus in the EU, and within the Framework of G7, we work to improve user awareness, accelerate development, stimulate new value added services and products in the interest of the consumer, and support R&D that leads to targeted investment.<P>
	There are 4 pillars to the EU strategy within this global effort:  <P>
<OL>
<LI>Improve the business environment (through liberalization).  This means destroy the monopolies (state or not) and therefore allow private investment to flow into the field.  Competition, deregulation, and pilot projects are aspects of this process. 
<LI>Invest in the future.  Here the media plays a vital cultural role, but practicalities also are essential: industries, especially SMEs, must be able to use the technology and this means education and training so that individuals and firms become "consumers of the possibilities" rather than just of entertainment.
<LI>People at the Center. Social questions are at the heart of the Information Society.  There is concern with isolation and invasion of privacy, where it should be just the opposite.  IT can improve access, protect consumer interests, and ensure cultural diversity.  We must also deal with the "computer homeless", those who grew up without the technology and are divorced from the changes. 
<LI>Meeting the Global Challenge.  We must define anti-protectionist global rules.  This is hard for those who are ahead and are challenged.  The US is the prime example, as demonstrated in WTO negotiations; the Americans are all for openness, except until their lead is threatened.  LEOS is a case in point; it must be open access, or there must be 2-3 competing systems.  Europe insists on openness and competition; its restrictions are lower that those of others.  It is also essential to help the developing world participate.
</OL>
For these reasons Europe supported the pilot projects at the Feb95 G7 Brussels conference; and the EU is pleased the G7 agreed. The 11 projects agreed to, and encouraged by the Heads of State at their Summit in Halifax in Jun95 include a Global Inventory (led by the EU and Japan), Global Health Care (EU/France/Germany/Italy), the Global Marketplace for SMEs (since economy of scale no longer rules in the Information Society), and the topic of this workshop, the Maritime Information Society, which from the EU perspective expands upon the preexisting Maritime Industrial Forum and addresses the interface of maritime industrial policy and IT policy.<P>
Like the other pilots, MARIS is user driven, builds on existing systems (e.g., GPS), has an open framework that seeks to integrate all maritime players, and fosters "defacto implemented standards" derived by common usage.  Its overall objective, like the other pilots, is to show the advantage of a global information system through specific applications.  The timetable involves stocktaking in 1995, development of prospects for international cooperation (as at this conference) in 1996, concrete results in 97, and presentation of results at EXPO98 in Lisbon.<P>
	Within the EC there is a manager, reporting to the Commissioner, for each of the subprojects.   There is no identified G7 budget for the project, but the European Parliament has backed Information Society activities.  Therefore the issue in Europe is ideas, not money.<P>
	Ireland is like an India in the EU in terms of its competitiveness in developing software.  It relies on creativity.  A newcomer, it is not stifled by past structures and can make rapid progress in the fresh spirit of competition that characterizes the best in European innovation. <P>

<B>3.  MARSOURCE in the EU</B><P>
	This subproject seeks to link oceanographic, fisheries, and research data bases of the EU, various nations, and several international organizations such as the ICES and FAO to improve transparency in fisheries, help preserve stocks, and improve both sea-catch marketing efficiency and the availability of aquaculture products.  Exemplary data will include resource information (e.g. total allowable catches, fisheries boundaries, member state catches), markets (prices, port accessibility and services), trade (export/import data by product, quantity, value, etc), fleet composition, aquaculture production and problems, and research programs.  One example of a product is an electronic marketing system permitting remote auctions and buying while the ships are still at sea.<P>
The workshop report noted that the Irish fishermen (not dissimilar to many others) were characterized by a poorly organized market structure, low income, no national strategy, and locked-in quotas.  There are two major computerized selling companies in Europe; the technology is not just available but implemented, the issue is the will to use it.  Difficulties include the large amount of "black" fish on the market that never get into the statistics, the short term nature of the catch (vice farming) trade which doesnt let computerized auctions stabilize prices the way futures markets do, the large number of SMEs involved and their independence, and the fact that fishermen at sea wont disclose where they are (or were) lest others flock to their area.  Fishermen themselves need to become involved to a greater extent, perhaps with informal or regional programs in addition to the European approach.<P>

<B>4.  MARTRANS & SAFEMAR in the EU</B><P>
MARTRANS seeks to develop an Electronic Data Interchange (EDI) System to improve efficiency, customer service, and logistics management in multi-modal transport.  The basic concept within the EC is to build up Port Community EDI Systems in local regions, automate the ports not already automated, employ "smart cards" and GPS for information on carriers and their cargo, and then globally interconnect the community systems and their users (using translators or service providers for interfaces between local communities).  Data on port conditions and berthing availability, repair needs to be matched with parts/services availability, and vessels and their cargo would speed throughflow and reduce bottlenecks.  High among the objectives is simplification of the currently complex manifest and customs systems. SAFEMARs objectives are oriented to hazard reduction, but the two major projects - a Vessel Traffic Management Information System and ECDIS - also interface well with MARTRANS.  <P>
	The workshop session, which by far had the largest of the three, featured a set of presentations on cost, logistic and safety benefits, and ongoing implementation projects. One of the largest projects appears to be MARNET which interconnects the Mediterranean ports, specifically focusing on Marseille, Piraeus, Genoa and Valencia, but also includes New York/New Jersey (This was the only mention of participation outside the EU).  An example from the airlines industry described how an Irish Company, Cargo Community Systems Ltd. links carriers and forwarders in the Icarus system and has recently interconnected with TDNI to tie in much of North America.<P>
	The rapporteur concluded from the discussions that the technology is available, and that there is widespread recognition of and agreement on the benefits.  Ports should be the focal points for local community systems, and the approach must be intermodal, with much to be gained for Short Sea Shipping in Europe.  Large companies have made major investments in EDI.  The problem is to interconnect them (they are reluctant because their systems provide competitive advantage) and extend the capabilities to unautomated smaller ports and SMEs.  Other barriers include lack of trading partners with EDI (e.g. SME suppliers, forwarders, carriers), the variety of in-place systems, the great diversity of customs procedures, and dislearning old ways.<P>

<B>5.  MARVEL in the EU</B><P>
MARVEL seeks to create a "virtual enterprise linkage" in support of modern shipbuilding and repair and equipment manufacturing industries, that more and more rely on out-sourcing and work-sharing.  The industrial challenges include increasing international competition and excess capacity, a move to custom tailored ships, the need to optimize the production processes, and the dispersed nature of resources in the global market combined with JIT techniques.  European industry has already formed a consortium (MARVELOUS: Maritime Virtual Enterprise Limited - Open User Syndicate) that gets the competitors around one table to define user needs including design and manufacturing process changes and IT requirements.  This sub-project is of great interest to ONR since it parallels a Navy effort to address the establishment of an international electronic communications network, and ONREur will host a workshop later this month to start to coordinate efforts between Europe and the US (a similar workshop will be held in Japan).  This will be chaired and reported by my colleague Howard Bunch of this office.<P>

<B>6.  An Irish Proposal:  Maritime tourism and leisure</B><P>
	Tourism is a very big business - globally it employs 204 million people, 10.6% of the worlds workforce; it accounts for some $3.4 Trillion annually, about 10.2% of global GNP.  In Europe it accounts for 5.5% of GDP, and in Ireland 7%.  It will probably by the largest single business sector by 2000.  Most tourism is coastal.  In Europe there are some 10 million pleasure boats, 9 million wind surfers; marine mammal watching, sea angling, scuba diving and pleasure cruises, to cite just a few examples, are all multi-billion dollar industries.  Tourism promotes social and economic cohesion; it is labor intensive and dominated by SMEs.  It is based on dynamic use of natural resources, requiring and promoting a high quality environment.  IT can not only provide virtual experiences and promote tourism, but reduce uncertainty in planning (weather, animal sightings, fish locations), improve quality and customer appeal of services (advance bookings, virtual pre-tours, smart cards for entry and departure to marinas) and promote environmental quality through ecotourism and interactive programming.  Ireland, with a large and growing tourist industry, will propose to the Coordinating Committee the addition of MARTOUR as a fifth MARIS subproject.  Ms Yvonne Shields of the Irish Marine Institute (see separate report) made a fascinating and compelling case for this initiative.<P>

<B>7.  Canadian, Japanese, and US Positions</B><P>
	Canada is the co-chair, with the EU, of MARIS.  Richard MacDougal of the Canadian Hydrographic Service/DFO reported that Canada has not established a separate funding stream for the project, but that each separate project is funded on merit and coordination is accomplished through one on one contact. Among the Canadian projects are: <P>
1) The ECDIS (Electronic Chart Display and Information System) demo program, a 4 year $10M effort that started in 1992 to demonstrate viability, test standards, and identify required legislation.  The USCG and NOS were participants.  The project involved 49 vessels and 4 training institutes, logged 14000 sea days on 500 users and produced 360 electronic navigation charts.  Legislation per se does not appear to be a big issue; the biggest concern is updating.  This is now addressed in the new standards, and Canada is testing a commercial service to support dockside updating.<P>
2) INNAV, the Information System for Marine Navigation.  The Canadian Coast Guard is replacing its shore based traffic control system.  It will include dissemination of real time data (e.g. tides and currents) and chart data, and will extend to an international link for the exchange of vessel data.  They are also introducing an automatic vessel ID system, piloted on the St Lawrence to decrease the reliance on shore based control, and with 25 vessels (15 in the Pacific, 10 in the Atlantic) for Fisheries Management.<P>
3) Marine Geomatics: This R&D project will be designed to acquire, process, and manage data to describe the marine environment; it will develop an "information seaway": to extend the information highway to the maritime community.  The objective is to design the system so that the linkages are transparent to the user.<P>
4) A Canadian company is involved in a US project to develop a standard ship safety record, remotely accessible, to assist with inspection.  In addition, the US and Canada have agreed to support differential GPS; discrepancies between GPS and older chart positions will lead to the need for a "chartnet" type approach to collaborative production and dissemination of chart data.<P>
5) In MARTRANS, there is a container tracking project at Montreal; however the major terminal operation is not yet convinced of its value.  And in MARSOURCE, although there are no specific projects yet, Canada sees the major challenge to be stock estimation, and has as a goal the coordination of acoustic and trawl samples, including the development of acoustic techniques for differentiating among species.<P>
	Japan has assigned responsibility for coordination of MARIS overall, and for SAFEMAR, MARVEL and MARSOURCE, to the Ministry of Transport; The Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications is responsible for MARTRANS.  Japan established an "Advanced Maritime Transportation Management Committee" with members from government and industry, suppliers and users, to identify needs and approaches.  Rather than define the project scope narrowly, Japan chose to look across maritime industry to discuss what and how stakeholders would be willing to share.  They envision the goal as a seamless global community that includes ships, operators, and other components of the maritime industrial community.  Concepts include a maritime "intranet" with browser capability that stresses visual presentation of information, and uses tools such as java and aplets to move both data and the programs required to interpret and apply it.  This approach is preferable to standardization because of the multiplicity of systems and users.  They are now considering details such as the information sharing phase and procedures to communicate using visualization techniques to make the date more intuitively useful and to transcend language differences so that the system can be in fact global (e.g., not many Japanese fishermen read French...).<P>
	The US representative received this task only last week; the previous point of contact (who was in MARAD) has moved.  The US has much potential to contribute to MARIS; there are many ongoing projects that relate well to the objectives, and there are US participants in many of the projects described by the EC and Canada.  However the intent to coordinate efforts under the MARIS umbrella has not transitioned to the working level, and the US has as yet no projects identified as MARIS   The representative will attempt to identify offices and individuals for the various subprojects, and coordinate with the EC representatives to tie in better with the ongoing efforts.  An example is MARVEL, via the planned ONREur workshop.<P>

<B>8.  Contacts</B><P>

