<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>CO/TD Newsletter #8</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>5 October 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #8<BR>
S&T In Ireland, Part 1</H3>

<I>Keywords: marine science; materials; S&T policy; Ireland; Trinity College Dublin; University College Galway</I>

Contents:
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Overall Impressions
<LI>Marine Institute
<LI>Trinity College Dublin
<DIR>	a.  Research & Innovation Programs</DIR>
<DIR>	b.  Examples</DIR>
<LI>University College Galway
<LI>Contacts
<LI>Feedback
</OL>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
Universities are the center of Irish S&T.  The nation, and the Universities themselves, are avidly directing research efforts toward innovation and linkages to the booming enterprise sector.  The EU has been a major source for S&T support, and leading researchers have close collaborations throughout the continent as well as with Irish companies.  This newsletter describes the various EC, federal, and local mechanisms employed to successfully couple S&T to innovation in Ireland, and gives examples in materials, optoelectronics, biotechnology, and environmental sciences from visits to Trinity College Dublin and University College Gallway.  <P>

<B>2.  Overall Impressions</B><BR>
	Ireland has a booming economy.  The traditional base, agribusiness, thrives.  Tourism flourishes.  Recent extensions into technologically based sectors are based largely on relatively cheap but well educated labor.  At the 24 Sept MARIS meeting (<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/cdnews7.htm">Newsletter #7</A>) the EC Commissioner for Industry compared Ireland to India in terms of the growth of its cottage IT industry.  R&D at the many excellent Universities is directly oriented to creation of jobs and development of industrial potential.  Ireland also is clearly focused on Brussels; the current Irish Presidency of the EC merely highlights the close linkages (indeed dependency in S&T) that have developed over the few years since Irish entry.  The ties to Irish America remain strong, but the real action - economically and intellectually - is more and more with the continent.<BR>
	Ireland has retained its neutrality, and is not a member of any military or security alliance.  This stance becomes more problematic with its EU membership, given evolving European visions of their collective security responsibilities.  Neutrality and Irelands rich history of participation in UN peacekeeping have however shaped the nature of Irish Defense Forces (IDF), and both recent and ongoing reviews sponsored by the governments Efficiency Audit group (and conducted by Price Waterhouse) suggest the need for change.  The Army, which has 11K of the total IDF 13K personnel, is now looking forward and considering the skills and equipment it may need for participation in coalitions.  Air Force and Navy, about 1K strong each, both have day to day missions and thus are operationally proficient, if in need of upgrading.  The 7-ship Navy in particular is extremely busy given the demands of fisheries protection in Irelands 132K km2 fisheries area, plus the growing concern with drug transshipment.<BR>
	The Universities are going through a period of change.  About 2 years ago, student fees for "3rd level education" was abolished in the interests of equity.  This eliminated about 30% of their income, which they are seeking to make up through other sources and activities, such as research.  They have been greatly helped by EC "structural funds" (via STRIDE, S&T for Regional Innovation and Development) as a new and underdeveloped member of the EU (though this is now over), and are hungrily pursuing industrial, federal, and philanthropic support with, at least at the locations I visited, quite good success.  Some 40% or more of research funds now come from the various EC programmes, so the Brussels orientation is both clear and effective.<BR>
On the day of my visit the new President of the University of Gallway and his academic council were to meet with counterparts from the other national Universities to discuss proposed structural changes that would increase campus autonomy.  This should enhance their ability to independently pursue R&D and educational agendas (but like all such proposals has some faculty opposition).  Another interesting characteristic of the Irish "3rd level" sector is that the Universities do not select their own students; rather it works the other way around.  Students take a single exam at the end of high school, and choose their school and department; those with the highest grades get the first choices.  This obviously puts a heavy premium on reputation for quality, and for the top universities insures excellent input and low dropout rates.  It also means of course that opportunities are rationed by the number of available places, that the student bodies are almost totally Irish, and that faculty (as at Galway) often carry horrendous teaching loads.<BR>
	Since I focused during this trip on specific projects and institutions, I dont yet have a good grasp of Irish S&T policy and the organizations and mechanisms for its management.  Certain aspects of the system however came through clearly:
<UL>
<LI>Ireland has traditionally paid little attention to S&T; it has not been part of the national self image (farming, literature and the arts).  However following the publication of the governments Science, Technology and Innovation Advisory Council (STIAC) report in March 95, and the appointment of Pat Rabbitte as Minister for Commerce, Science, and Technology, S&T has received much more emphasis and had better budgetary success.  In the Ministers words (from his message in the 1996 Yearbook, The Irish Scientist), "Allocation of the Budget funds is being guided by a firm belief in the need to create closer links between the colleges and the enterprise sector...(S&T) are central to economic and social development, to competitiveness and the building of a better life for all.  The purpose must be to achieve sustainable full employment and an improved quality of life for all of our citizens".  This clearly links S&T with innovation and ties it to the industrial economy.
<LI>Much effort is being devoted to "awareness", nationally and internationally. Foras is devoting 250K (1 ~ $1.65 when I visited) to awareness in 96; it is one of the main objectives of the Marine Institute and its sister statutory, semi-state bodies.  The objectives of the awareness campaign are to make S&T part of the national culture, and to sell University-based research to industry in Ireland and overseas, and to the EC.
<LI>Funding while remaining low has increased significantly: 3.3M in 1996 for applied and strategic research (up 700K); plus 1M for what we would call tech transfer and SME encouragement.  Basic research doubled from 94 to 2M in 96; and PhD student grants were doubled (though at ~$4K/yr they remain so low that outside support is essential to avoid starvation).  This is nowhere near enough to sustain the extant research program, hence the pressure for industrial involvement and even more the decision in the Universities to "focus on the Brussels route", where they have had outstanding success.
<LI>The Universities are clearly acknowledged as the centers of Irish S&T and innovation. A variety of structural programmes have been established to help develop and market their research capabilities.  These include seven "Programmes in Advanced Technology" (PATs) which are University centered research institutes managed by Forbairt (the State Agency responsible for science, technology, and the development of the indigenous industrial sector), staffed largely by contract researchers but with heavy participation by the academics, graduate students, and post-docs.  The PATs start with nearly total government funding, and are expected to quickly become almost totally self-supporting.  Their objective is technology development and transfer to industry, and there have been several successful privatized spin-offs. I visited two of the five Centres of "Bioresearch Ireland" -- Pharmaceutical Biotechnology at Trinity College Dublin (TCD) and Diagnostics at University College Galway (UCG) -- as well as the Metals Center of Materials Ireland (TCD) and the CIM Applications Center Advanced Manufacturing Technology Ireland (UCG) and was very impressed with their research, their products, and their ability to attract outside investment.  This industry-University-Government partnership seems to be working extremely well for Ireland. (POCs for the 7 PATs are listed in Paragraph 6, Contacts) 
<LI>In addition to the nationally coordinated programmes, each University has an industrial liaison or innovation department that tailors programmes to their specific needs.  TCDs program, active and innovative, is described below.  And, they advertise.  See Para 6 for university contacts and information on two very useful publications.
<LI>The border with Northern Ireland is transparent for S&T.  On ministerial, academic/research institution and individual researcher levels, there are very close collaborative ties.</UL><BR>
	The bottom line is that Ireland , like much of the rest of Europe, sees academic S&T and innovation as an intrinsic and essential aspect of their national well being.  And as the IDF moves to modernization, it can be anticipated that the Ministry of Defense will take advantage of the excellent structural base being established by the Universities in conjunction with industry and the Ministry of Commerce.<P>

<B>3.  Marine Institute</B><BR>
	The Marine Institute was founded in 1993 to "support and promote the sustainable development of Irelands marine resource, to define the contribution it can make to the Irish economy and to propose and where appropriate implement the necessary programmes and measures to ensure that this development potential is realized".  In practice it promotes awareness of marine issues, provides a channel for marine SMEs and research, and represents Irish interests at international scientific fora (e.g. it cosponsored the MARIS conference with the EU; the Chief Executive is the Irish representative to MAST), recommends policy, and manages selected national programs and organizations including the Fisheries Research Center (70 people, headquarters in  Abbotstown), the Irish Marine Data Center (12 personnel, collocated with the Institutes 8 staff in Dublin), and the 21m research vessel Lough Beltra (with a new 31m multipurpose ship under construction).  It also manages the marine R&D program to promote commercial growth, with 27 active projects and about 1.5-2M/year, and promotes and coordinates Irish competition for EC marine projects.  <BR>
	The Institute is a semi-state, "statutory body". The Chief Executive, Dr. Peter Heffernan (who returned to take the job from a tenured position at the University of Georgia), reports to a Board appointed by the Minister of the Marine; the Minister holds a second portfolio as Minister of Defense, and the Institute has a formal liaison mechanism with the Navy.  It also has signed a "Joint Statement" with NOAA to pursue "Collaboration in the Programmes of Marine Research and Technology Development, Sustainable Development, Coastal Zone Management, and Marine Coastal Protected Areas"; and Dr Heffernan has coordinated with NSF geosciences and international program offices to facilitate a workshop between Irish and US marine scientists. <BR>
	Irelands marine resources are quite large, but underdeveloped.  This is a major contrast to the multi-billion dollar agribusiness that is a more central part of the national heritage.  With 16% of EU waters, Ireland has only 3-4% of the fisheries allocation.  The fishermen are disgruntled but fragmented, with 5 different representative organizations.  95% of the marine companies are small, and lack in-house innovation capability.  Marine territory and  resources have yet to be inventoried; the Institute (with EC support) recently completed a GLORIA reconnaissance of 20% of Irelands offshore area; but there is no national hydrographic service and 90% of Irish waters havent been surveyed since the 1800s.  Marine aquaculture got off to an unregulated start and has not flourished, while having some adverse impacts on wild catch.  The small seaweed industry is just starting to coordinate and develop. Other undeveloped opportunities are in deep water oil, deep water aquaculture, and tourism.  As with S&T in general, the Irish Marine potential is excellent;  but the Institute has its work cut out for it.<BR>
	The small staff of the Irish Marine Data Center has done an excellent job of coordinating national capacity in quite a short time.  A highlight of MARIS was the display of their interactive 3D fly-thru hydrography visualization, based on all available data including the recent GLORIA survey.  As I understand the plans, it will become the basis for an Irish GIS that incorporates other oceanographic data bases.  They also have produced an "Extended EDMED" for Ireland, a metadata directory of over 300 data sets; "CRUISEMAN", a computer application for logging underway data on the national research vessel; and the EROS 2000 database from 8 research cruises in the western Med as part of the European Rivers and Ocean Systems 2000 Project.  Work is underway on compilation of temperature data, extension of the bathymetric and geological data sets, development of the BIOMAR pubs data base with TCD, and a guideline on electronic data publishing.
	Although not part of the Institute, I was briefed on the Hydraulics & Maritime Research Center at the Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering Dept, University College Cork (UCC).  With STRIDE assistance it has upgraded its facilities, and has several well equipped wave basins and tanks.  HMRC with the Coastal Resource Center and Aquaculture Development Center is part of UCCs Coastal Zone Institute.  HMRC projects range from offshore engineering to harbor and coastal protection ad engineering, and associated wave and sediment processes. <P>

<B>4.  Trinity College, University of Dublin (TCD)</B><BR>
	<B>a.  Research and Innovation Programs:</B> TCD is the oldest (founded 1592) and best known of the Irish Universities.  It has 6 faculties and nearly 70 departments. It is the top choice of students; thus of the 11K students (2K postgraduate) from 68 countries, 95% are Irish.  It is also Irelands foremost research institution, with over 830 research accounts and 1995 annual research income over 12M.<BR>
My visit to Trinity was hosted by the new Dean of Research (a 3-year post filled by a faculty member), Prof John Hegarty, and Dr Eoin ONeill and Ms Doris Alexander of the Industrial Services Office.  It featured an introductory description of TCDs approach to research and innovation, and seven presentations by faculty on their Departments and Centers research in materials, computer science, optics, pharmaceuticals, environmental science and zoology.  I have passed the detailed information they provided to my colleagues in the appropriate disciplines, and summarize the major points here.<BR>
	TCD has had an innovation office for over 10 years, and treats innovation as a major source of support for students, faculty and the College.  TCD is owned by the "Fellows" of the College, and thus has somewhat more flexibility than the National Universities; it does however get students and national funding by the same procedures. The Dean of Research (who had seven years experience at Bell Labs, Murray Hill and U. Wisconsin, and directs the TCD Centre of the PAT "Optronics Ireland") recommends policy and chairs the Business and Industry Committee that makes decisions on new projects.  The Innovation Services Office helps with marketing, arranges contracts and major projects, stimulates and supports new ventures.<BR>
 In addition to the PATs (described above and see Para 6 for a listing), TCD promotes on-campus research with technological and marketing services, incubator space, venture capital, and well defined IPR procedures and support via the Innovation Services offices.  Among the successful procedures are the following.
<UL>
<LI>Federal and EC grants. TCD ranks highest in national awards.  It also brings in about 40% of its research funding from the EC (~4M/yr, plus about 4m of structural funds via STRIDE etc); TCD researchers are involved in nearly 200 EU active projects, and head about 50 EU research consortia.
<LI>Campus Companies.  Staff and faculty of TCD can lease space to set up legally separate entities on campus; TCD takes a 15% equity share in these ventures, and plows the profits back into research.  Some very successful ventures have subsequently been sold and have expanded and moved off campus.  An example is Iona Technologies, opened in 1991 as a campus company with 2 employees; in 1994 SUNSOFT acquired a 20% interest and it now employs over 20 professionals in Dublin.
<LI>Industrial Labs on campus.  There now are 5.  The largest is Elan Corporations (drug delivery; first nicotine transdermal patch) commercial research lab with 35 employees.  Another example is Hitachis software lab with 13 Irish graduates (there is a sister lab at Cambridge University); its major discovery, in collaboration with Prof Hegarty, is an "artificial retina".
</UL><BR>
	During lunch Prof Hegarty mentioned that the next steps for research will expand the campus company program outside the walls, and seek to develop links to larger industries.  Other initiatives include collaboration with the University of Belfast in parallel computing, and use of expertise in social sciences to attack social problems.<BR>
	<B>b.  Examples:</B><BR>
	Prof. JMD Coey heads the Physics Departments "Magnetism and Superconductivity Research Group" which includes two postdocs and about 10 graduate students.  Prof Coey and Dr James Cullen of NSWC, who is spending a year at TCD under a Fulbright fellowship, won one of the initial NICOP awards for a three year project to examine new approaches to increasing the energy storage capacity of advanced permanent magnets.  Prof Coey also is Chief Coordinator of the 1985-95 EC program "Concerted European Action on Magnets", a BRITE/EURAM programme to improve cooperation among a hundred industrial labs and research institutions; has recently established the "Oxide Spin Electronics Network" with 8 partners and 1.9M funding for postdocs over the next 4 years; and runs his own small campus company, "Magnetic Solutions" which produces specialty permanent magnets.<BR>
	Dr Mark Costello, a Research and Teaching Fellow, described the TCD program in environmental sciences.  The University offers both a BA and a MSc in Environmental Sciences. The Natural Resources Development Center headed by Prof Adrian Phillips has a staff of 3 research fellows and 6 research assistants.  Its R&D activities focus on Rural Development, Tourism & Environmental Management, and GIS and Database Development.  A major project for the last few years has been a survey of marine life in Ireland as part of EU BioMar.  There is growing interest in ecotoxicology<BR>
	Mr Seamus OHara, Commercial Manager of the National Pharmaceutical Biotechnology Centre (NPBC), described the PAT structure and his centre, one of 5 in Bioresearch Ireland.  Of the total 6.5M operating budget, federal support is stabilized at around 2.2M, with the rest from licensing, industry, and the EC.  NPBC is headed by Prof D.C. Williams (50% of his time) and operates as a "virtual" center; projects are carried out in Departmental labs, with Centre employees acting as technical staff under day-to-day supervision of the academics.  NPBC product areas include vaccines for animals and man, inflammation, neurobiology (antidepressants, neurodegeneration), drug development and molecular biology.  <BR>
	Dr Julian Reynolds, Senior Lecturer in Biology, described the interests of the Zoology Department.  His own research is in freshwater ecology, including turloughs (small seasonal lakes).  The Department is headed by Prof Barry Roberts (vertebrate neurobiology; fish spinal cord injury and repair), has 7 full time and 3 part time academic staff, 25 graduate students, and about 20 undergraduates per year.  The 5 research groups include Freshwater Ecology, Marine Biology, Wildlife Ecology, Parasitology and Neurobiology and Behavior.  Ecological problems of current interest include aquaculture (Irelands small salmonoid industry is poorly regulated and has not only had significant problems but has adversely impacted wild stocks), declining wildlife populations and an growing grey (N American) squirrel population (which displaces the native species).<BR>
	The Chemistry Department has 16 academic and 14 technical staff; for research, they are supplemented by two emeritus fellows and over 50 postdocs and postgraduate students.  Four academics, headed by Prof Jim Greer who holds the Hitachi chair, are involved in computational chemistry.  Prof John Cornish, who gave the Department overview, studies matter transport in solids; more specifically, diffusion of ionic species in polymeric materials and simulation of the defect processes involved, matter transport in corrosion processes in turbine blades, and passive and electrically stimulated transdermal delivery of drug molecules.  Both internally and through its association with Materials Ireland and the Hewlett-Packard and Hitachi labs, the Department is extremely well equipped for most aspects of chemistry. <BR>
	Prof Werner Blau of the Physics Department, like Prof Coey, has a number of avenues through which he pursues research.  The first is his Photonics Materials Group, an "interdisciplinary team (of about 30) to develop new materials and their applications by molecular engineering".  Recent areas of activity, primarily supported by the EU, include blue polymer lasers, ultrafast switching for telecommunications, third-order nonlinear optical materials and effects, and fullerenes and carbon nanotubes. Second is a campus company, HORCOM Ltd that sells materials and devices.  Third is the Polymer Research Unit of the PAT Materials Ireland, which he directs.  Full time professional staff from the centre work with academics throughout the college on industrial projects in polymer research, product development and quality control, with an emphasis on applications for electronic devices. <BR>
	Prof John Byrne is Head of the Dept of Chemistry.  This large and diverse Dept has 34 academics.  It offers specialist (third level engineering) degrees in basic computer engineering and linguistics & natural languages, a multimedia MSc course, and three evening degrees oriented to business.  There are about a hundred research (graduate) students.  Most research funding is from the EU via ESPRIT ands ACTS(~1M/yr), with an emphasis on distributed computing.  There are large groups in knowledge and data engineering, AI and computer vision, computer architectures for fault tolerant systems, and formal methods.  The Machine Vision Centre is run jointly with the Department of Microelectronics and EE as part of the Manufacturing Technology PAT; and Dept personnel are active in four Campus Companies: Ieunet (email and internet access), IONA (distributed programming tools; now off campus, see above), Tolsys (hw/sw products) and Digital Media Technologies (from the Software PAT; commercial multimedia systems).<BR>
	In addition to being Dean of Research and a Prof in the Physics Dept (Physics Dept research is concentrated in optics and  condensed matter physics, with activity in computation physics and radioactivity), John Hegarty heads the TCD research centre of Optronics Ireland.  This centre does basic through applied research in physics and applications of laser diodes, high speed nonlinear and electrooptic properties of semiconductor quantum wells, high speed optical switching, optoelectronic computing, microcavity LED physics and blue light emission from II-VI laser media.  <P>

<B>5.  University College Galway</B><BR>
UCG opened in 1849.  It has faculties of arts, Celtic Studies, commerce, engineering, medicine and science.  UCG has some 800 staff and over 6500 students.  Like TCD, it relies heavily on the EU for research support and has a variety of active innovation and commercial/industrial liaison ventures.  It is however part of the national university system and therefore doesnt have quite the degree of autonomy as TCD.  I visited the new Martin Ryan Marine Science Institute and the Manufacturing Research Center, and heard also about the National Diagnostics Centre (NDC)of Bioresearch Ireland.<BR>
	The NDC is directed by Prof. James Houghton.  Its themes are DNA diagnostics, molecular biology (especially genetics of salmon and shellfish), immunodiagnostrics, aquatic veterinary services, and genetic services (including a complete equine fertility management system).  This is a large and active PAT centre, with about 50 staff that are active in both research and providing services and consultation to industry and farmers.  Their dedicated facility was constructed with the help EU infrastructure funds, and their external (non-federal) funding is about 85% of annual turnover.  They have a US Army contract on recognition of pathogenic microorganisms.<BR>
	Prof. Brendan Keegan is current Director of the Martin Ryan Marine Science Institute (MRI).  MRIs dedicated, modern 2800m2 teaching and research building was funded by a grant from the Martin Ryan University Foundation and matching support from ECs STRIDE.  It enabled UCG to bring together the marine interests of the Departments of Botany, Microbiology, Oceanography (fully housed in MRI and headed by Prof Michael Orren, a chemical oceanographer), Physics and Zoology, which are reinforced by participants from Applied Geophysics, Biochemistry, Geology and Engineering.  Galway has ready access to the shelf and deep ocean, and a wide range of habitats, most still in near-pristine condition.  MRI operates its own research vessel, the recently refurbished trawler 45 r.v. Conamara.  It offers a Marine Science BS with an intake of about 20/year, and has over 50 graduate students and 8 postdocs (in addition to the 9 academics and 16 research assistants) .  There are two field stations, one at Mast Head (see below) for meteorology and the Shellfish Research Lab at Carna (aquaculture support, including restocking lobster, and developing abalone and sea urchin industries).<BR>
	MRI faculty and staff do about 1M of contract research per year.  Topics include marine algae, microbiology, estuarine and marine zoology, and physical and chemical oceanography (trace metals).  A "limited by guarantee" company, Marine Resources International, Ltd. (MRI Ltd), is wholly owned by the University to deal directly with private sector enterprise; and Marine Research (Ireland) Consultants provides a "one-stop-shop" consortium of MRI/UCG personnel together with specialists from 10 private companies for marine and estuarine environmental assessments and similar services.  MRI also helped form and now houses the Irish Seaweed Industry Organization that is helping some 17 SMEs expand their business and improve the quality and consistency or their products.  Other initiatives include a spin-off SME (Sea Sense ltd), calibration and analytical services, and a range of joint projects to stimulate Irish marine industry.<BR>
	Atmospheric research, considered part of MRIs activities, is conducted by three members of the Department of Experimental Physics (Profs Tom OConnor, Egan ORodaighe, and Jerald Jennings who briefed me).  Their principal expertise is in trace gases, aerosols, and cloud physics.  In 1986 their field station at Mace Head became one of the five global sites for the Global Atmospheric Gases Experiment (GAGE).  Mast Head now boasts very well equipped labs and a 20m sampling tower; the site has a 120 clean sector of open access to the Atlantic, making it ideal for background aerosol and trace gas measurements.  <BR>
	The UCG Manufacturing Research Center, much like MRI, is an umbrella organization to coordinate the variety of individual manufacturing research units from several departments: Computer Integrated Manufacturing Research Unit (CIMRU, see below); Thermal Engineering Research Unit, Composite Research Unit (CRU, see below), Digital Signal Processing Research Unit, Aerospace Research Unit (see below), National Centre for Laser Applications, Power Electronics Research Centre, and Sensor Applications Research Unit.  <BR>
	Prof John Eaton directs the 10 member Aerospace Research Unit.  Their work is principally in fluid dynamics, particularly active laminar flow control, prediction of wing tip vortices, flow field mapping at very high resolution, and prediction of acoustic fields for arbitrary shapes and multiple sources.  This units work is all EC funded, and they collaborate with over 120 different EU organizations.<BR>
	Prof Conchur OBraidaigh Directs CRU, which won first-round NICOP support for a project with NSWC, NRL and the University of Delaware to integrate fabric reinforced thermoplastics into the Glass Mat Thermoplastic (GMT) molding process.  In addition to Prof OBraidaigh, CRU has 2 Associate Directors and 125 full time research assistants who are working on MEngScs and PhDs.  Their research is in the areas of polymeric and metal matrix composites, heat transfer, and the design and analysis of offshore structures.<BR>
	CIMRU, directed by Prof Jim Brown (I was briefed by Dr David OSullivan, College Lecturer and Research Manager), has a staff of about 35 and an annual turnover of ~250K.  Its strengths are in logistics and production planning control (production management systems), bench marking and strategic planning, quality assurance, and business process reengineering.  Like the others, it is largely EU supported and has strong collaborations throughout Europe. <P>

<B>6.  Contacts</B><P>

This section is more extensive than in many of these reports, representing the efforts of Irish researchers to make their abilities known nationally and internationally.  Two basic sources include:
The Irish Scientist Yearbook, published by SAMTOM Limited, 17 Pine Lawn, Newtownpark Ave, Blackrock, County Dublin, editor Dr Charles Mollan; (+353-1)-298-6186 fax -7970, email cmol@iol.ie.  PATs, organizations, and individual entrepreneurs "advertise" in this glossy document, and it gives a good overview of the range of Irish S&T interests.<BR>
A Summary Directory of Research and Development Expertise in Science and Technology in Universities in Ireland was prepared by the Industrial Liaison Offices of the seven University Colleges in the Republic of Ireland.  It gives contact names and numbers, a list of specialist centers in the Universities, and an alphabetical list of 2500 areas of expertise where University researchers are willing to wqork with industry, keyed by College.  Its available from any of the Industrial Liaison Offices, listed below, or from the Irish Business Employers Confederation.<P>

