<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>CO/TD Newsletter #9</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>10 November 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #9<BR>
Restructuring UK Public Sector Research Establishments</H3>

<I>Keywords: reinvention; reengineering; research laboratories; RDT&E; DERA; OST</I><P>

<B>Contents:</B><BR>
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Motivation for Visit and Report
<LI>Background: The Policy Setting for Change
<LI>The MOD Experience: Defence Evaluation and Research Agency (DERA)
<DIR>	a.  General Description:  What is it?</DIR>
<DIR>	b.  Establishment and Evolution of DERA: How and Why did it get this way?</DIR>
<DIR>	c.  Managing the Changes</DIR>
<DIR>	d.  Issues</DIR>
<LI>The Civil Sector Experience
<DIR>	a.  Background</DIR>
<DIR>	b.  S&T Policy: Realizing our Potential</DIR>
<DIR>	c.  An example: NERC and two of its PSREs</DIR>
<LI>Observations
<LI>Contacts
<LI>Feedback<P>
Appendix A:  Members of the DoD Delegation visiting UK 7-11 Oct 96<BR>
Appendix B:  Meeting Itinerary<BR>
Appendix C:  Site Rationalisation<BR>
Appendix D:  Privatisation Criteria</OL>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
	<DD>The US Department of Defense has been tasked by both Congress and the President to rationalize the RDT&E infrastructure of its Military Departments.  A well accepted process in responding to such challenges is benchmarking.  The UK, for over 16 years, has been implementing a policy of public devolvement and rationalization.  In the expectation that we have something to learn from their experience, a DoD delegation spent a week visiting with those involved.  The delegation focused on the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency of the Ministry of Defense, but also looked at civil Public Sector Research Establishments because in both countries security relies on the total national intellectual infrastructure.  This report tries to depict what we learned: not just the rationalization process and its results, but the national policy environment that both inspired and enabled the very remarkable changes that have been accomplished.  The report should be worth reading for those involved with the DoD process, if only as background for further assessment of our options.<P>

<B>2. Motivation for Visit and Report</B><BR>
	<DD>The US government has undertaken many initiatives to improve the effectiveness of federal agencies and their political and civil service employees.  While there have been improvements, some practices and organizations have been tough to crack.  A case in point occurred during DoDs 1995 Base Realignment and Closure (BRAC 95) process.  In spite of explicit direction by the Secretary to the Military Departments to take advantage of opportunities for cross-service integration while reducing lab and test and evaluation (T&E) infrastructure in BRAC 95, virtually no cross-servicing resulted.<BR>
	<DD>Subsequently, DoD received both Presidential and Congressional direction to reevaluate opportunities for better utilization of its lab and T&E infrastructure.  DoD responded with a plan entitled <I>Vision 21</I>,  which "will rest on three implementing and integrating pillars: <B>Reduction</B>, <B>Restructuring</B> (intra-service and cross-service) and <B>Revitalization</B> to attain a modern, efficient and effective laboratory and T&E environment with focus on the costs of facilities and infrastructure"<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#1">(1)</A></I> .<BR>
	<DD>As part of its process, the Vision 21 Study Team is conducting case studies of reduction, restructuring and revitalization by other organizations.  The UK Ministry of Defenses (MOD) Defense Evaluation and Research Agency (DERA) has a reputation for having successfully accomplished a major change<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#2">(2)</A></I> , so a contingent of the Study Team (Appendix A) visited the UK during the week of 6 October 1996 to learn in more detail about DERAs experience<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#3">(3)</A></I> . The DoD group also visited the UK Office of Science and Technology (OST) of the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI), and the Southampton Oceanography Center (SOC), to learn about similar change in the civil sector (Itinerary @ Appendix B).<BR>
	<DD>The author helped coordinate the visit, and accompanied the DoD delegation.  This report is based on the weeks discussions. It provides background information about lab/T&E restructuring actions in the UK.  Although it includes some discussion of the differences between US and UK situations, it is solely the responsibility of the Vision 21 Team to determine which if any portions of the UK experience are relevant to their task.<P>

<B>3.  Background: The Policy Setting for Change</B><BR>
	<DD>DERA is a drastically, indeed fundamentally different organization than the establishments it has replaced.  It continues to change.  When asked "whats next", its Chief Executive John Chisholm stated that he had never run an organization that hadnt changed at least yearly.  SOC likewise is a vastly different organization than its major predecessor, IOC Wormley.  It too is planned to evolve.  To understand the nature and degree of such continuous change in UK labs both past and future, its necessary to consider the environment than has not just enabled but inspired it.<BR>
	<DD>The restructuring process described here began with the 1979 change of government, when the Conservatives gained a majority and Lady Margaret Thatcher became Prime Minister.  The process has continued with essentially the same philosophy under Mr. John Major, who replaced Lady Thatcher as PM in 1990.  Summarized oversimplistically, that philosophy is that public sector enterprises work poorly and private sector ones work well; and that "civil servants are sulky and risk averse" (to quote one or our speakers).  Thus, the public sector needs to operate much more like the private sector.  Simplistic as this may be, it has been and remains consistently and thoroughly applied, to all government sectors and activities.  For example in the ongoing "Prior Options" reviews of civil sector research labs the choices are, in clear priority order, 1) for the public sector to stop performing the service altogether and abolish the agency performing it; 2) to the degree the service must be provided, to privatize it; 3) where this is not feasible, to contract out as much of the activity as possible; and then and only then, 4) to improve the efficiency of the inescapable minimum that the government must retain.<BR>
	<DD>Although in retrospect the social and structural changes introduced over the last 16 years of Tory rule have been sweeping, the process took much time, was orchestrated in a series of paced steps, and in some cases suffered failures or setbacks that required reassessment and several tries to get it right.  And as in the US, some sectors have been more successful than others in resisting change, while others have embraced it.<BR>
	<DD>Perhaps the first major Tory impact directly on the Civil Service came in 1982, with the Financial Management Initiative.  FMI had the intent of placing responsibility on individuals, and giving them the means to carry it out.  It introduced two new "systems".  A Top Management System forced managers at all levels to take clear decisions regarding the direction of activities in a department by translating strategic objectives down through line management as personal objectives.  A parallel Budgeting System delegated financial responsibility to specified levels of authority in the hierarchy, giving managers some control over how they spent their allocated funds.  These two systems were accompanied by manpower cuts (20% reduction of civil service between 1979 and 1987), and introduction of controls on running costs in 1985-86.  Manpower controls were lifted in favor of cost controls in 1988.<BR>
	<DD>A scrutiny of progress in 1988 found that changes since 79 had "been important in beginning to shift the focus of attention away from process and toward results...the new systems are demonstrating how far attitudes and institutions have to change if the real benefits of management reforms, in the form of improvement in the way government delivers its services, are to come through...radical change in the freedom to manage is needed urgently if substantially better results are to be achieved."<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#4">(4)</A></I>   In essence, change brought about by FMI was merely procedural, not cultural.  <BR>
	<DD>The report of this scrutiny, <I>Improving Management in Government: The Next Steps</I>, identified 5 main issues: lack of clear and accountable management responsibility and the confidence that goes with it; need for greater precision about expected results of people and organizations; need to focus attention on outputs; the handicap of a uniform system in an organization the size and diversity of the Civil Service; and the need for sustained pressure for improvement.  Three priorities to begin the process of change were established.  These apply equally to all aspects of government:
<UL>
<LI>organize the work of each department to <U>focus on the job to be done</U>: systems and structures must enhance the effective delivery of <B>policies and services</B>; 
<LI>department management must ensure their staff have <U>relevant experience and skills</U> to do the tasks required by effective government; and 
<LI>real and sustained <U>pressure for continuous improvement</U> in the value for money obtained in the delivery of <B>policies and services</B>.
</UL>
	<DD>It is worth considering the findings and recommen-dations of this seminal report in some detail, since they are central to the make-up and operations of DERA (DERA is a "New Steps Agency within Government"<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#5">(5)</A></I> ) and other research labs, and to their core feature of continuous improvement and change.  They also constitute some of the more important findings for the US DoD delegation to consider, for they establish the policy framework and political consensus without which DERAs organizational, philosophical, and operational changes could not have occurred.<BR>
	<DD>The basis for structural change, as stated repeatedly in the Next Steps priorities, is that government departments have two quite separate functions: <B>policy and service</B>: "Departments have two main functions - ministerial support including policy development and evaluation, and managing or influencing the delivery of government service"<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#6">(6)</A></I> . The skills for these two very different tasks, and the nature of the organizations that perform them, likewise should be differentiated and separated.  Traditionally Departments focus on policy, to the detriment of service.  If the functions are properly separated and managed they can both be performed better.  "Clearly, Ministers have to be wholly responsible for policy"(para 23).  However, they neither can nor should have the detailed knowledge about daily operations needed to execute such policy.<BR>
	<DD>Therefore, "We recommend that <B>agencies</B> should be established to carry out the executive functions of government within a policy and resources framework set by a department"(para 19).  Here the term <B>agency</B> means any executive unit that delivers a service for government, whether it is part of public service or outside government<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#7">(7)</A></I> .<BR>
	<DD>There are a couple key aspects of implementation that make this approach work.  The first is, "the choice and definition of suitable agencies is primarily for Ministers and senior management to decide"(para19).  Agencies can be in or out of government, closely tied to or at arms length from the department, large or small; whatever works.  The second is the concept of a <B>framework</B>, which is a formal written understanding, negotiated between the agency and the Department, that spells out in detail how the agency is to operate. An agency's Framework Document "sets out the policy, budget, specific targets and the results to be achieved.  It must also specify how politically sensitive issues are to be dealt with and the extent of the delegated authority of management.  The management of the agency must be held rigorously to account by their department for the results they achieve" (para 20).  Frameworks are updated as part of formal annual reviews, or when changes in agency constitution and missions occur (e.g., DERA operates under the third edition of its Framework: the first was negotiated when it was established as DRA in 1991; the second when it became a "Trading Fund" in 1993; and the third when it was assigned other functions and became DERA in 1995).<BR>
	<DD>The Next Steps first priority is to "focus on the job to be done": "The main strategic control must lie with the Minister and Permanent Secretary.  But once the policy objectives and budgets within the framework are set, the management of the agency should then have as much independence as possible in deciding how those objectives are met...provided management is operating within the strategic direction set by Ministers, it must be left as free as possible to manage within that framework" (para 21).<BR>
	<DD>Because this represented a very new way of doing the governments business, "The Next Steps" dwells at length on shared responsibility for the service function, particularly in terms of accountability to Ministers and Parliament on operational matters.  Some quotes are appropriate: "...when individuals had to answer personally to Parliament, their sense of personal responsibility was strengthened...if the concept of agencies developed in this report is to succeed, some extension of this pattern of accountability is likely to be necessary.   The precise form of accountability for each agency would need to be established as part of drawing up the framework...It is axiomatic that Ministers should remain fully and clearly accountable for policy.  For agencies which are government departments or parts of departments ultimate accountability for operations must also remain with Ministers.  What is needed is the establishment of a convention that heads of executive agencies would have delegated authority from their ministers for operations of the agencies within the framework of policy directives and resource allocations prescribed by ministers (indeed, as described below in more detail, the DERA Chief Executive has a personal letter of authority from his Permanent Undersecretary, that supplements the agency Framework).  Heads of agencies would be accountable to Ministers for the operations of their agencies, but could be called...to give evidence to Select Committees as to the manner in which their delegated authority had been used and their functions discharged within that authority."  <BR>
	<DD>Agency Chief Executives are held fully responsible for the day to day decisions involving the public services they provide.  This is not a new concept either in the UK or the US; the departure from the past is mutual acceptance by Parliament, the Ministers, and agency heads that operations will be conducted in accordance with the framework, and that the managers are fully free to manage as they and only they deem best within its policy and fiscal guidelines.<BR>
	<DD>Once the job is defined and properly organized, the objective must be to provide appropriate skills to do it, within an environment of sustained improvement.  The Next Steps emphasizes that the managerial skills to run agencies and deliver services are not those traditionally rewarded or developed in government; "hitherto relatively few civil servants will have had an opportunity to learn or exhibit these skills" (para 35). Training, secondment, promotion of younger people and skill importation would be needed both to get started correctly, and to built the skills needed in the new culture (this will be clearly apparent in DERA, as discussed below).  And finally, there must be pressure from the top, starting with the Prime Minister and Head of Civil Service, "sustained by understanding and support from Parliament" (para 38), for continuous improvement; but "The Civil Service must own the changes as they evolve"(para 39).<BR>
	<DD>In summary, "The aim should be to establish a quite different way of conducting the business of government.  The central Civil Service should consist of a relatively small core engaged in the function of servicing Ministers and managing departments, who will be the sponsors of particular government policies and services.  Responding to these departments will be a range of agencies employing their own staff, who may or may not have the status of Crown servants, and concentrating on the delivery of their particular service, with clearly defined responsibility between the Secretary of State and the Permanent Secretary on one hand and the Chairman or Chief Executive of the agencies on the other.  Both Departments and their agencies should have a more open and simplified structure"(para 44).<BR>
	<DD>One of the interesting aspects of this policy is that it works, well and widely.  It has led to a great range of innovative solutions to providing services, from literally floating government establishments on the stock market, to abolishing them, selling them (sometimes with a negative price), mingling them with other institutions, and completely reducing, restructuring and revitalizing them.  There has of course been some pain in the change; but the overall result has been dramatically improved quality, responsiveness, and facilities, at much reduced cost.<BR>
	<DD>"The Next Steps" have played out in many different ways in many different sectors.  From driving licenses to prisons, from trains to agriculture, the face of British public service has changed irreversibly.  The DoD contingent examined this process in some detail for two examples: DERA for Defense RDT&E (the closest parallel to the problem they are grappling with in the US), and civil sector research labs, which in both countries form a significant part of the national intellectual infrastructure which must be efficiently harnessed in the interests of national security.<BR>
	<DD>This paper first will discuss the MOD experience, then describe the civil sector process and its impact on some institutions of interest to DRA's Sea Sector.  When looking for useful models for the US situation in these cases it is essential to recall that all the changes, in both military and civil sectors, have been fully consistent with the prevailing political philosophy and have had the strong backing of both Parliament and the Ministers.  Political consensus and policy direction are essential stimulants to the cultural change of large government organizations.<P>

<B>4.  The MOD Experience: Defence Evaluation and Research 
Agency (DERA)</B><P>

	<B>a. General Description: What is it?</B><BR>
	<DD>DERA today "brings together in one agency the core of the Ministry of Defenses non-nuclear scientific and technical assets.  Launched (in its present form) in April 1995, and forming the largest single research organization of its kind in Western Europe, DERA offers a unique range of services, from the highest level of operational studies and analyses, through the various categories of basic and applied research, to consultancy-type advice on the procurement process and the test and evaluation of specific equipment, in both the development phase and during actual operations"<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#8">(8)</A></I> .  DERA "is a Next Steps Agency within government, established ... to operate as a Trading Fund.  It is owned by the Secretary of State for Defense.  It is required to operate in a commercial manner with predetermined performance targets, and is financed by income earned from its customers"<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#9">(9)</A></I> .  Its annual turnover (95/96) is just over 1B (90% from MOD customers), and its staff numbers around 14,400.<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#10">(10)</A></I> <BR>
	<DD>The defining feature of the Agency is that it operates as a <B>Trading Fund</B>.  A Trading Fund obtains all of its income from customers and must meet all of its costs, including salaries, out of income earned.  DERA is like a private company in that it owns its own property (or rents it), pays for all externally provided services (including all costs of any military personnel assigned to it; and it pays Value Added Tax or VAT), charges for all the services it provides (its prices include VAT), and prepares its accounts on an accrual basis.  The Chief Executive has significant (but not total) management freedom to control costs and set corporate strategy; responsibilities and accountability are set out in the Framework Document and in a delegation letter to the Chief Executive from the Permanent Undersecretary.  The Trading Fund (but not its government customers) is free from annuallity; and within the fund, money is simply money, i.e. there are no restrictions into categories.  Performance targets are set by the Minister and include items such as Return on Capital Employed and rates.  The customers control the money and state requirements, DERA costs and proposes activities, the customers prioritize spending, and DERA responds to their choice.  DERA then performs to contract.<BR>
	<DD>DERAs mission ("Aim") is to "provide independent, high quality, efficient and cost-effective S&T services to its customers"<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#11">(11)</A></I> ..  Because its primary product is advice, internal metrics and modes of operation are similar to those of a consulting company.  DERA exists primarily to serve MOD customers, but it is encouraged to seek work on commercial terms with other Government departments, with industry, and with other Governments, and to exploit the wealth-creation potential of the capabilities and facilities required for defense purposes<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#12">(12)</A></I>.<BR>
	<DD>DERA has four operational or product Divisions (POCs are listed in Paragraph 6, Contacts): the Defense Research Agency (DRA, 683M 95/96 Budget, 6793 persons. DRA in turn has seven sectors, described further below), the Defense Test and Evaluation Organization (DTEO, 281M, 3575 staff), Protection and Life Sciences Division (PLSD, 100, 1203 staff), and the Center for Defence Analysis (CDA, 68M, 676 staff).  There is also a Support Services Division (22M, 1802) which is in the process of privatization, a Central staff (17M, 153), and some smaller units (17M, 212).<BR>
	<DD>DERA in its current form really started with the establishment of the Defense Research Agency, DRA, in 1991.  Most of DERAs policies and procedures therefore were developed to manage the S&T remit of DRA.  The other components were added at the start of last fiscal year, 1 April 1995.  They thus have not changed as drastically as have the DRA sectors, but the process will be faster for them since there is now a model and a corporate culture within which they must fit.  Most of the discussion below centers around the DRA experience, since most of the lessons-learned stem from its evolution. <BR>
	<DD>Because the rationale for the DoD visit was to look at aspects of the change process that might provide lessons for Visions 21, it is worth mentioning at this point a few of the basic differences between UK and US systems, and DERA and DoD lab/Center functions, at this point (others will come out during the discussion that follows). <BR>
	<DD>First, Parliament exercises much less direct control over the details of defense spending than does the US Congress.  As opposed to our thousands of line items, funding is allocated to MOD in three basic lumps: salaries, capital, and everything else.  Thus how much gets spent on S&T, training, operations, procurement of specific items, etc, is up to the Ministry.  There are budget battles, of course, but by and large they occur within the Ministry.  The Ministry also is free to reorganize as it sees fit to perform its function, i.e., it can form agencies and change them<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#13">(13)</A></I> .  There is also a considerable degree less "local" pressure exerted by MPs than by US Representatives and Senators; they can ask questions and bring pressure to bear on Ministers, but not to the same extent as in the US.<BR>
	<DD>Second, MOD is truly "Purple" when it comes to requirements and acquisition.  Thus DERAs customer is MOD, not the individual services.  The specific customers for its work packages are in the three main sectors of the MOD: The Deputy Chief of Defense Staff (Systems) (DCDS(S)) under the VCDS; the Chief Scientific Advisor (CSA) under the Permanent Undersecretary; and the various Program Directors under the Chief of Defense Procurement (CDP).  And the Chief Executive is personally responsible directly to the Secretary of State for Defense, who is both owner and customer, for the effective and efficient management of the Agency and for achieving its aim, objectives, and targets.  <BR>
	<DD>Third, DERAs work differs substantially from that performed by DoD Laboratories and Centers.  MOD has no charter for fundamental research; that is managed by the Research Councils, through their institutes and the universities.  Further, virtually all engineering development and in-service engineering is performed by industry and through the services.  Thus DRAs job (and PLSDs in its sphere) is to develop or acquire military technology, advise MOD on its use, and transfer it to the industry that designs and builds the systems.  It essentially does only what would be termed 6.2 and 6.3 in the US.  DoD labs and centers in contrast provide full life-cycle support (6.1 through 6.6 plus ISE) to their Services (albeit differently in each Service).  DTEOs remit is to provide the facilities and services required by the Armed Forces and industry to support development, pre-production, and in-service proving phases.  In this sense it is somewhat parallel to the DoD Major Range and Test Facility Base, but with less interface with DRA than the MRTFB has with DoD labs simply because of DRAs focus on the early aspects of S&T, vice in depth involvement with weapon systems per se.<BR>
	<DD>Finally, of course, DERA as a Trading Fund has a fundamentally different relationship to MOD than the DoD labs to their Military Departments.  DERA is a contractor and must make a profit, albeit a with a trusted partner arrangement with its owner-customer.  And DERA as an Agency has a broader mandate to work for and with other customers, and much more control over its facilities and processes, within the bounds of its Framework Document.  It can work for other customers, indeed for other countries, and retain commercial profits in its venture capital fund.  It can buy or dispose of property, invest and earn interest, reorganize, reskill, and grow or shrink as the market demands.  As noted above, money once inside is simply money; DERA is not annualized, and its financial procedures and accounting systems bear no resemblance to those of its owner.  It is precisely these differences that are of most interest to the current study, but they must be considered with full recognition of the other fundamental differences between national governments, departmental charters, and assigned tasks.<P>

	<B>b.  Establishment and Evolution of DERA: How and why did it get to be this way?</B><BR>
	<DD>The dictates of "The Next Steps" are obviously a considerable deviation from traditional military Chain of Command mentality.  Not surprisingly MOD initially had difficulty understanding the concepts of agencies and frameworks, customer-supplier relationships, etc., and their applicability to Defence.  In considering how to respond to this initiative of the Prime Minister, however, it turned out that there was, in the works of one of our speakers, one "juicy candidate" for drastic reform: research.<BR>
	<DD>Research at the time was the province of the four Defence Research Establishments:  the Royal Aerospace Establishment (RAE, Air Force), Royal Armaments R&D Establishment (RARDE, Army), Admiralty Research Establishment (ARE, Navy), and Royal Signals and Radar Establishment (RSRE).  Over the years their role had devolved from that of arsenals, i.e. research, engineering and production, to research only; but their infrastructure and attitudes had not shifted accordingly.  As DCDS(S) VADM John Dunt put it, there were some who thought the Armed Forces existed to support the DREs.  They were perceived as baronial fiefdoms, financial black holes, that had no sense of responsiveness to the customer.  Their budgets were based on their view of their needs to do what they wanted.  And as Defence funding dropped at the end of the Cold War, they were rapidly becoming unaffordable.<BR>
	<DD>In early 1989, after considerable discussion and study, MOD made the decision to combine the DREs into a Next Steps Agency.  There was pressure from the Prime Minister and others to privatize the agency, but MOD argued successfully that it needed an independent "trusted advisor", and ultimately the government opted for a Trading Fund agency owned by the MOD.  Nigel Hughes, Director of RSRE, was made Chief Executive Designate, and David Tyte was assigned as Technical Director and charged first to determine what went into the new agency, and then to achieve technical rationalization among the establishments. (Tyte states the first was easy, the second impossible under the conditions).<BR>
	<DD>Although the new Agency stood up as DRA on 1 April 1991, it was soon apparent that in fact little had changed, nor was likely to. The DRE Directors were all still very powerful.  Hughes had no real authority and was expected to continue to work through normal MOD procedures, which meant that he got stopped at every turn by vast numbers of people who thought they were in charge of one or another aspect or the operation.  By mid-91 it was apparent that something more radical was necessary, and that the magnitude of change needed could not be brought about by an insider.<BR>
	<DD>The real change process thus began with the selection, through open competition, of an "outsider" from industry to take charge of the new agency, and the negotiation with him of the terms and conditions for his position.  John Chisholm, the new Chief Executive appointed in September 1991, had a history of change management in industry.  As important as his experience, however, were the terms under which he agreed to take the post.  First, he reported directly to the Minister (who selected him), eliminating all layers and naysayers.  Through both the Framework and his personal letter of delegation, he had clear and unquestioned authority to run the Agency as he saw fit; he was not constrained by consensus.  There was a clear understanding that he was to transform the agency and run it as a Trading Fund that would remain in MOD.  And as Chisholm himself notes, the most important condition (but the hardest to negotiate), was that he was allowed to choose his own team.<BR>
	<DD>On Friday 13 September 1991, Chisholm assembled 76 top DRA employees to a closed door meeting, announced his team, and sent the remaining third of them back to MOD.  He made it clear from the start who was in charge, and that change for sure was going to happen (Pick a fight and win it).<BR>
	<DD>The immediate task was to make the new organization financially viable.  Many in MOD expected it to fail, and were clearly willing to live without it.  At best, as a Trading Fund it would have to compete with industry for its work, and the Defence research budget was declining rapidly.  Noncompetitive elements would simply go out of business.  As Chisholm says, to motivate change you need a crisis - real or manufactured.  For DRA, the crisis was that "they took the money away".  <BR>
	<DD>To effectively and quickly turn a proud old civil service organization into a competitive modern company requires change not only of culture, but of almost all business processes.  An accrual based financial system had to be developed, and managers had to be trained how to control true costs, not just cash flow.  MOD had to learn to act like a customer, and to not get what it wouldnt pay for.  A new pay for performance approach was needed to motivate staff to achieve targets.  The "learned helplessness" of the civil service had to be defeated.  There was to be no new money to effect the changes. And, Chisholm concluded after analysis, to make DRA a viable Trading Fund he had to take 90M per year (60%) out of running costs, while still producing quality technical product for the customer.  He planned to take the full reduction out of support infrastructure without hitting scientific capability.<BR>
	<DD>I will discuss some of the processes and the new procedures which appear to be relevant to the US situation in more detail below.  But in outline form, the major moves imposed by Chisholm and his team were as follows:
<UL>
<LI>The old Establishment structure was abolished, both to break down historic loyalties and to permit the new organization to develop along business lines.  DRA was reformed into seven sectors.  Three are environmental (Sea, Air, and Land), retaining the necessary specialties demanded by the different platforms and keeping ties to traditional customers.  Two sectors, Weapon Systems and Command and Information Systems, support the environmental sectors directly, and two others - the Structural Materials Centre and Electronics - provide enabling military technologies.
<LI>Each Sector was tasked to function as a "profit-making" business, with metrics for Key Targets.  All the metrics and Targets were on finance and efficiency.  Forcing the Sectors, and within them Profit Centers, to figure out how to survive motivated cultural change.  Subsequently, ideas on how to improve efficiency bubbled up.  
<LI>Financial managers were hired from industry (civil service accountants simply could not adapt to commercial practices) and an accrual-based commercial accounting system was imposed.  Managers were trained to think in the new terms, and DRA "practiced" trading starting in April 1992, getting a years experience before it officially became a Trading Fund on 1 April 1993.  Because DRA would become the owner of its land at that point, a process called "Business Use Valuation" was established to put a manageable value (i.e. one that wouldnt too adversely affect rates) <I>(John Chisholm comment: not correct; Represent the real cost of investments; a rational provider would not reinvest in the same asset)</I> on assets that, while they existed and were being used, would not meet strict investment appraisal rules were they to come up for replacement.
<LI>Personnel reductions concentrated on support staff.  Essentially no scientists were riffed (of course many opted out) in the drawdown from around 12000 to about 8500 employees.  Of the 90M per year reduction required to make DRA viable as a Trading Fund, 60M came from rationalizing (eliminating and consolidating) support staff (e.g., all the workshops were closed).  The added redundancy costs (some 50M) of "managed exits" were handled centrally, to relieve the sectors from adverse impact on their financial targets.  A "pay for worth" system of set objectives and measured performance was established; managers are judged (and paid) on their performance to targets, and the targets are raised each year.
<LI>MOD agreed to let DRA identify which sites (there were 54 at the start) it wanted to "own" when it started trading, and to keep all property DRA did not want to retain (DRA would pay rent on property to be vacated in less than five years).  David Tyte, who through long experience but especially through his work with Nigel Hughes was very familiar with the entire organization, was appointed Director of Rationalization.  Tyte developed multiple options for each site; the goal was to identify the closures and moves needed to generate the additional 30M per year infrastructure running cost savings required to make the organization viable.  These were ordered in terms of "best buys".  The cost of new construction to facilitate the consolidation (14 sites were vacated and many others changed considerably) was approximately 200M (+VAT).  The Minister  agreed to provide DRA these funds from the 10-year rolling capital improvement budget of the old DREs.  I.e., it effectively cost the customer "nothing" but what he would have paid anyway for capital improvements under the old system; the money just was provided up-front, and DERA was permitted to employ it as it saw fit, rather than following the old bottoms-up plans.  DRA now has 3 Core sites (Malvern, Ft Halstead and Farnborough - the beautiful new facility there opened just days before our visit), 6 "Specific Business Sites", 3 Convenience Sites, and 23 Facility sites.  Site rationalization will be a central issue for Visions 21, so more details as provided by David Tyte are at Appendix C.
<LI>DRA took a loan from the Treasury of 450M to cover its first 6 months of trading (i.e., to cover operations until invoices could be submitted and paid and income could be accrued).  It is required to generate "profit" to pay off the 25-year loan and the 6% interest; the profit comes from the 7% fee on its "contracts", as well as efficiency improvements over target.
</UL>
	<DD>Not everything went smoothly, of course.  Considerable hurt was involved in changing the attitudes of civil servants who had dedicated their lives to the Forces and had, after all, excellent technical reputations.  The initial accounting system proved too fancy and had to be replaced.  Much effort was expended in "process" studies and analyses, not all of it productive.  Communication to the far flung staff proved difficult and imperfect.  And the very tight focus on efficiency and conversion inevitably detracted from "softer" improvements.  But at the bottom line, where it mattered the most, the changes had the intended effect.  DRA not only survived but surpassed its targets, to the considerable surprise of many in MOD.<BR>
	<DD>DRA officially became a Trading Fund as planned on 1 April 1993.  Over the next two years it continued to improve its efficiency, and evolved in its relationships with both customers and industry.  Perhaps the best indicator of its success was the decision to add other organizations to it, in lieu of setting them up as independent agencies.  The former Chemical and Biological Defence Establishment, the Defence Operational Analysis Centre, and the Directorate General of Test and Evaluation were thus joined with DRA to form DERA on 1 April 1995.  They have now completed the transition into trading and have adopted DRA practices and procedures, and the question for the future is how to further rationalize the total organization.<P>

	<B>c.  Managing the Changes</B><BR>
	<DD>As noted earlier, the concept of continuous improvement is the third basic priority of The Next Steps.  DRA, and new DERA, use a Total Quality construct to guide their continuous improvement process, and employ a cyclical management approach of Planning (coupled to communication), Devising Processes (followed by building systems), and Measurement (with resulting rewards).  John Mabberley, Managing Director of DRA and a key mover in the entire restructuring process, uses a viewgraph that says:
<UL>
<LI>learned helplessness in the civil service can be defeated - give managers down through the organization the right freedom and incentives
<LI>being exposed to business failure provides a reason to manage properly; it becomes a habit
<LI>objective is to manage tasks through efficient value-added processes rather than mindless bureaucratic procedures
<LI>support changes in process with proper systems
<LI>measure and measure ... and measure again
</UL>
	<DD>DRA views its changes as taking place in phases. The initial phase (Total Quality 1 or TQ1) was what Chisholm imposed at the onset to make the organization viable in the short term.  The focus was on what had to be put right to survive.  It was characterized by an attitude of crisis, and was totally command driven.  The priority was first to change processes, followed by communications and training. Consensus was immaterial, "softer" issues delayed.  <BR>
	<DD>The first corporate plan had just three priorities: efficiency, customers, and total quality (ISO 9001 certification and pursuit of the European Quality Award).  Metrics were all focused on finance and efficiency.  Key efficiency metrics were (and still are) Utilization (% of direct staff paid hours delivered to customers; 70% for DRA and 59% for DERA as an entity for 95/6), teeth-to-tail (ratio of direct staff doing work for customers to indirect staff), mark-up (proportional increase between salary cost of direct effort and price charged for that effort, now about +1.74), and rates.  These metrics exert strong discipline on management, and have had the effect of rapidly exposing costs and driving them down.  In 2 years, running costs went from over 220M to under 100M, far exceeding the 90M Chisholm calculated was essential for survival.<BR>
	<DD>The cost reductions let the organization exceed its performance against budget, thus its forecast profits and targeted Return on Capital Employed (ROCE; for 95/6, profit was 33M ahead of budget due to higher than expected income coupled with faster reduction in costs, yielding 9.2% ROCE vs a target of 4.7%). DRA proudly displays its statistics in any of the efficiency and finance meetrics, as well the significant improvement in milestone delivery, performance against annual plans, and satisfaction of its customers (from annual surveys conducted since 1991)<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#14">(14)</A></I>.  <BR>
	<DD>The discipline of the metrics - and their tie to senior managers performance contracts - has motivated DRAs sectors, and now the other DERA organizations, to maximize the work for their customers and minimize costs.  The managers we talked to all were keenly aware of their metrics (particularly utilization) and clearly viewed their job as running their sectors as profitable businesses.  And the customers we talked to at MOD - the Chief Scientific Advisor Sir David Davies, DCDS(S) VADM John Dunt, and Director of Corporate Research Mike Markin, all expressed satisfaction with DERA performance and appreciation for the effectiveness of the basic customer-supplier relationship that has developed in such a short period.  They had concerns, but not with the way the business was run internally, with DERA as their key technical performer and advisor, or with DERAs competitiveness.  For DRA at least, "TQ1" has established a firm foundation and a financially viable organization.<BR>
	<DD>DRA is now well into its second change phase, TQ2 (DTEOs programme is termed DTEO 2000, reflecting its later start and the need for additional rationalization).  To be lasting, the changes from the crisis period have to involve the entire staff and be based on a shared vision of the future.  The focus is on effectiveness, on "what we want to be" vice "what we have to do".  Mabberley notes that this phase addresses the "softer" issues with common objectives, behavior and values.  It is based on consensus, not command.  It will be implemented by small teams, not imposed from headquarters.  It addresses a few easily agreed-upon themes, and should result in long term changes.  Like TQ1 however it involves much measurement, and the metrics will continue to include at the top those of finance and efficiency.  <BR>
	<DD>For TQ2, DRA sectors have identified four major themes: Customers, People, Science, and Business.  Each theme has a "sponsor", who is either a Sector Director or a senior manager, and a full time manager.  For each theme there are goals (a total of 14).  Focus groups have identified action items and issues, prioritized the "Best Few", and for each sector established action plans that are incorporated into the annual Business Plans, and lead to new processes and measurements.  Together, the sectors have identified 8 core issues (management in projects; account management; external impact; values and behaviors, roles and competencies, training, careers and status, and developing our knowledge) that get fed back to corporate level working groups.  <BR>
	<DD>TQ efforts are coupled to performance measurement at the corporate level under the DERA Technical and Quality Director, Adrian Meers.  In addition to the metrics and customer survey described earlier, the technical evaluation and improvement process includes sector-level use of the UK Quality Award model (which has a scoring system similar to the Baldridge Award), a 26-factor Technical Assessment at the "team" level that employs self-assessment plus external and internal auditors, and process benchmarking.  A new assessment challenge for DERA is "added value", or technology transfer and exploitation.  On the efficiency side, in addition to the metrics DERA employs "market testing", effectively competing internal units against external service providers when additional privatization or commercialization is feasible.<BR>
	<DD>When discussing change, John Mabberley notes that perhaps the most far reaching reform has been in project management.  The 7 Sectors are organized into 60 Profit Centers.  A matrix approach is used within these Centers.  Each project is led by an individual uniquely responsible for its delivery:  <B>Project Managers</B> obtain the staff they need from Resource Managers (people owners); <B>Resource Managers</B> are responsible for developing the talents and skills of their people, for "selling" them to project managers, and for rating them<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#15">(15)</A></I>.  Resource Managers typically are responsible for about 40 people, and charge about half their time to this role (10% + 1%/person).<BR>
	<DD>Project teams are multi-disciplinary, and Project Managers can draw their team members from any sector or centre;  members are chosen for their skills and contributions, not their role or grade, and they come and go from projects as they are needed.  In addition there are Technical Consultants who provide technical support to projects and staff skill development, and network to develop technical strategies.  Individuals can serve as both Product or Resource Manager and as Technical consultants, but never as both Project and Resource manager simultaneously.  Sectors also have Account Managers to facilitate the interface with customers.  This DERA management procedure seems fully consistent with front line US practices, including those in some of the most innovative DoD labs.<BR>
	<DD>TQ2 is well underway, but still has a long way to go.  The new metrics are just being added, and the "few best actions" are at the front end of implementation.  Already however there is talk of Phase 3 - continuous improvement of quality through benchmarking, working smarter rather than harder.<BR>
	<DD>As noted above, the new arrivals-DTEO, CDA and PLSD-are somewhat behind DRA, but are catching up quickly.  They are subject to the same management philosophy and metrics as DRA, and indeed most of the senior managers (including 3 of the 4 Sector Directors) have come from DRA and thus understand and have experience with the corporate approach.  Of these organizations, DTEO was of most interest to the DoD group because of its T&E responsibilities and make-up.  DTEO started trading in April 95, and rapidly achieved the 20% or so efficiency improvements associated with dismantling of input controls and transition to fiscal and managerial accountability.  Not surprisingly, however, some parts of DTEO - especially some land test sites - are showing signs of non-viability.<BR>
	<DD>Just like DRA at the start, DTEO has an excessive number of sites (40).  Everyone we talked to agreed that some rationalization will be needed, although difficult.  The methodology will be similar to that for DRA, but there are some significant complicating differences.  The sites are scattered all across Scotland, England, and Wales, as opposed to the labs which were largely concentrated in southern England.  DERA essentially owns them all, as opposed to the "walk-away" provisions which applied to many DRA sites; and many are contaminated or of little commercial interest.  Many sites are in remote locations and offer the only, or the best, employment in their areas; thus considerable interest from MPs can be expected.  As opposed to research where there were potentially viable alternate performers in industry and academia (and commercial potential for the Agency), most T&E sites are pretty uniquely military, and also have capabilities which MOD may be reluctant to jeopardize.  There is full recognition that rationalization can not proceed purely on an economic basis, and that DERA must consult carefully and thoroughly with the Minister and MOD customers prior to any closures.<BR>
	<DD>DERA and DTEO managers were naturally very sketchy about their plans for T&E site rationalization.  Some parts of the process have already started however.  One example we saw involved transfer of responsibility and assets from DRA to DTEO.  DRAs Air Fleet Department, after reduction and reorganization, was moved in 1994 to Boscombe Down, headquarters of the DTEO Aircraft T&E Sector.  It now will simply move into that sector and sell its services to DRA.  There is also the possibility of a redefinition of the DTEO sectors, for example to create a separate Range Sector.  DERA managers and customers both expressed great concern that the MOD retain its necessary "capabilities"; but there is a clear expectation that some ranges and other sites will have to be shed, and there is considerable discussion with European allies (especially France and Germany) and to a lesser degree with the US, about opportunities for interdependence and sharing.<BR>
	<DD>Rationalization of the T&E structure is clearly recognized as a difficult problem, with shared customer-supplier responsibilities.  From DERAs perspective, it does not operate here in a completely free market.  The approach will be for DTEO to continue to improve its efficiency and thus drive down overall costs, to examine in detail a variety of options, and to clearly state to MOD the essential costs for the different key capabilities.  MOD will then have to decide what it is willing to pay for, recognizing that there will be a potentially significant impact on how much research it can afford.  <BR>
	<DD>Here it is worth noting again some significant differences between the UK and US situations.  DERA has been forced to rationalize research and T&E separately and serially.  DoD has the opportunity to rationalize them together, in parallel.  Even given the greater distinction between the functions of DRA and DTEO in the UK than between labs and the MRTFB in the US, there undoubtedly would have been advantageous options that would have emerged from consideration of them together.  Some of this may still be possible, particularly if DERA chooses (as it is free to do and already has done to a degree) to reallocate tasks among its units at both the Division and the Sector level - i.e. to reorganize to gain even greater total efficiency in the interest of its customer.  But the range of options might have been considerably greater if the full scope of todays DERA was considered at the onset. The opportunity to consider RDT&E as an entity is a major advantage for the US, particularly when there are opportunities for inter-service interdependence.<BR>
	<DD>One additional major change was in process during our visit: privatization of the Support Services Division (Financial Services, Site Services, Information Services).  This is the portion of DERA that was most severely affected by the downsizing.  Although little was said about the details of the privatization process, DERA management clearly believes it can obtain better support from the marketplace than from an internal organization, and also that Support Services itself should benefit from an opportunity to sell to a larger community.<P>

	<B>d.  Issues </B><BR>
	<DD>During DERAs transition into a thriving Trading Fund Agency, both it and its owner/customer have had to make many basic decisions about their relationships with each other and with other entities. These decisions have changed with time, as both supplier and customer have adjusted to their new roles.  <BR>
	<DD>A primary example is <B>competition</B>.  An the onset, MOD clearly intended to compete much of DRAs work.  "Market testing" competition was in fact tried; but because of DERAs economy of scale and rapid progress in cost reduction, it easily won the initial competitions and thus both potential competitors and customers lost interest.  Now there is a focus on "competitiveness" rather than the process, with internal benchmarking and market testing to maintain a focus on rates and prices.  <BR>
	<DD>The customers we spoke to were all complacent about placing their work directly with DERA, and in fact with having DERA manage "secondary competition" for the out-sourced work (about 700M of its 1B+ turnover is spent in industry - 200M on research, 300M on support services, and 200M on goods and materials).  VADM Dunt noted that he would have to have a significantly larger staff to manage direct competition for the Applied Research Program (about 60% of DERAs research funding), and DERA manages virtually the entire 160M Corporate Research Program.  CRP's Director Mike Markin stated that having set the organization up to support MOD, it should be the repository of UK Defence technology.  Therefore the corporate program is done with and through DERA.  At the same time industry must be healthy, so he "urges" DERA to place about a third of the funds outside.  <BR>
	<DD>The sole-source relationship is not without serious problems.  The major concerns we heard from customers include the quality of research DERA outsources (industry still registers "more than the odd complaint" to quote the CSA), the limited range of approaches to a problem likely to be examined by a monopolistic supplier with in-house capability and thus inevitable technological bias<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#16">(16)</A></I>, and the effectiveness of the technology transfer process in both directions between industry, universities and DERA.  MOD may need a trusted advisor, but by making DERA the filter for all S&T MOD has restricted its open access to the range of options and opinions that may need be considered in modern warfare.  Unless these three concerns are managed properly over time, their effects on both customer-supplier relationships and warfighting could have a serious adverse impact on MOD.  We have similar problems in the US, which must be addressed by Visions 21.<BR>
	<DD>A second aspect of competition is DERAs <B>relationship with industry</B>.  This has even somewhat more problematic to date, and seems not yet to have been fully resolved.  DERA of course is encouraged by its framework to exploit its capabilities for wealth generation<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#17">(17)</A></I> , and to seek outside work that does not conflict with its responsibilities to MOD.  The balance however is delicate, since one of DERAs main tasks is to pass its technology on to the industry that will develop and built systems.  Its tough to both compete and partner, and the balance seems still not quite right.  There is little real head-to-head competition, but many aspects of perceived competition.  Among them is DERAs rate structure, which is heavily influenced by its valuation procedures <I> (John Chisholm comment: <U>not</U> true again; business use valuation indicates our decision not to invest in like facilities)  </I>, its desire to keep mark-up low in behalf of its customers' interests, and its very limited interest in profit (beyond what is is required to make to repay the loan and support new capabilities).  The Framework requires that DERAs programme compare in value for money terms with comparable work in industry.  But DERA is not truly in the open marketplace and must consciously control its rates to not undercut industry, particularly when it does enter the competitive marketplace.<I> (John Chisholm comment: issue is more that DERA scale gives it an economic advantage that is sometimes threatening to industry).  </I><BR>
	<DD>The Structural Materials Centre, for example, is viewed as a threat to industrial labs working in similar areas.  It has actually grown during the rationalization process, although it has just now relocated into its new state of the art facility.  SMC already is Europes largest materials research and technology organization.  The Director John Morton clearly intends to bring academics and industrial researchers into the lab and to develop and deploy world class programs.  He views SMC as a Dual Use Technology Centre, and is very active in EC supported as well as purely UK programs (approximately 25% of SMC income is non-MOD).  It would be hard not to perceive such a dynamic, rapidly growing, and well supported organization with a monololistic relationship with a one of the largest customers as a threat if you were in the same business.<BR>
	<DD>Although it is hard to generalize and we didnt have an opportunity to interact with industry, it appears that at the moment DERA s has established a reasonable if tenuous relationship with industry.  The early views of direct competition both with and against industry are gone, and DERA does see itself more as a trusted consultancy to MOD and thus a key partner and input to the primes in UK Defense industry who do the engineering development and production.  It is undoubtedly more problematic to 2nd and 3rd tier suppliers, and to industrial research labs, than to major primes.  One interesting aspect of the relationship is that DERA does not take patents on the technologies it develops for MOD (it does for items it takes commercial), but rather just passes the invention to industry for incorporation into weapon systems.  If industry chooses to commercially exploit such inventions, more power to them.  <I> (John Chisholm comment: Wrong. DERA retains IPR of own inventions and permits contractors to keep IPR of their inventions under contract to DERA, but reserves free use rights to MOD).  </I>This seems much looser and potentially more problematic than US CRDA and other IPR practices.<BR>
	<DD>Another area that needs further development is the <B>owner/customer-supplier relationship</B>.  The CSA commented that the owner role has not been thoroughly thought out.  DERA has therefore evolved its own policies.  The Framework and Delegation letter, clear as they are, cant and dont cover all issues.  There is much room for interpretation.  Close rapport and mutual trust between the Chief Executive and the Minister are required to maintain the balance defined by the Framework.  There have been examples in other UK Agencies where this has broken down badly, with damaging results to both individuals and institutions.<BR>
	<DD>People move back and forth between MOD and DERA without officially changing their employer, and thus must be both customer and owner.  For example Mike Markin himself is a DERA employee, and a large percentage of his and VADM Dunts staffs are from DERA.  The fox is truly in the hen house, particularly given the (self-reinforcing?) monopolistic relationship.  This arrangement seems clearly in conflict with the basic government policy of separation of executive and supplier jobs. However such issues of individual, vice institutional, conflict of interest seem much less problematic in the UK MOD than they would be in the US.  <BR>
	<DD>At the heart of their system is faith in the integrity of the civil service.  John Mabberley emphasized that integrity was one of the best things the DRE employees brought to DRA.  Part of this stems from a much lower level of inter-service rivalry, most of it is historic and social.  Certainly there are parochial interests, and UK politics is noted for its heated rhetoric and scandals.  But there is a sense of honor and respectability in being a professional Servant of the Crown that is absent in American life.  Consequently there is much less need for detailed regulations and lawyers.  DoD would want, and Congress would certainly insist upon, much more surgical and formal separation of responsibilities than pertains in MOD.<BR>
	<DD>In addition to their greater reliance upon individual integrity, the British are more willing than the Americans to put someone in charge and let him succeed or fail.  We try to build error-free systems, thus stifling initiative.  They are much less risk averse, more willing to set out on a course founded on policy and let the details evolve within a framework (The EU is perhaps the grandest example of this).  We like everything nailed down at the onset.  They are willing to take several runs at a problem, to learn from mistakes and try again.  We construct rules to prevent similar failures.  Such issues of character and style are subtle but pervasive, and must be considered when trying to extract lessons from the UK restructuring process.<BR>
	<DD>Customer-supplier relationships will continue to evolve under the broader DERA. PLSD will likely be similar to DRA.  DTEO and CDA are somewhat more problematic.  As already mentioned, DTEO operates in an even less open market sector than does DRA.  Both customers and suppliers acknowledge shared responsibility (and blame?) for the coming rationalization, and recognize that the processes and rigorous efficiency regime of DRA are appropriate for DTEO.  Thus on balance it was more logical to combine them than to form a separate agency.  The case for rolling up into DERA the variety of analysis organizations that make up CDA was less clear.  CDA plays a central interface role in MOD among policy, operations, and procurement, so among other things it has a significantly different customer base.  The only real benefit is efficiency, and this is unlikely to be dramatic in an analysis house. <I>(John Chisholm comment: Not a well informed comment.  CDA customers are mostly the same as DRAs, and CDA depends on DRA for performance level modeling. It has had more credibility since it has been together in the agency.</I>  N.b., after visiting CDA, the author agrees with this comment).<BR>
	<DD>DERA clearly recognizes that it needs to be more proactive in customer relations.  Customers are one of the four themes in DRA's TQ2, and the objectives are to be/have:
<UL>
<LI>MODs first choice for S&T advice
<LI>a successful supplier in Defence related civil markets
<LI>a commitment to understanding & satisfying customer needs, and
<LI>highly valued products and services.
</UL>
	<DD>The customers we talked to all expressed concern that DERA at the start didnt pay enough attention to the customers approach and psychology.  As in its internal crisis oriented drive for viability, DERA ignored the softer issues in dealing with MOD.  Now that satisfaction with performance is up, relationships can mature.  There will be natural tensions.  Many MOD customers, especially in the applied research side (60% of the business) can be expected to want more control over the nature of the work.  On the other hand, DRA clearly would like broader work packages and interaction restricted to higher levels<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#18">(18)</A></I>.  There are clear US parallels here, with our constant struggle between "requirements" and "solutions" and who is responsible for what (e.g. between OPNAV and the SYSCOMs, OP-91 & ONR, to use a Navy example).  <BR>
	<DD>In DERAs case, there also is a need to balance responsibility in setting and controlling rates, to simultaneously maximize the amount of work produced for available funds, and to protect long term capability which costs money.  The customer could be ignored during the period of crisis and when rates were tumbling dramatically as a result of rationalization and introduction of Trading. Part of consensus development for long term stability must address better realization on both sides of the implications of customer demands and supplier interests.  US experience has shown that its sometimes harder to manage during a period of stability when adjustments are made on the margin, than during crisis where change is wholesale.  DERA has a detailed business model it employs as part of its Corporate Planning Process<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#19">(19)</A></I>  to help address such issues.<BR>
	<DD>On the civil sector side, DERA intends to invest significantly to grow its business infrastructure and develop a sales and marketing staff.  Defense funding will continue to fall, if not as precipitously as during the last few years, and there is some concern that difficulties in rationalizing DTEO could adversely affect MOD funds available for research.  The intent is to provide a buffer, ie to have a business staff large and capable enough to move rapidly into commercial work if necessary to save critical facilities and skills.  It is probable that much of the business marketing effort will focus on other European nations and UK departments.<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#20">(20)</A></I> <BR>
	<DD>Another problematic issue mentioned in most of our discussions is profit.  The formal financial target imposed on DERA by the Trading Fund is an average 6% per year Return on Capital Employed, to pay off its start-up loan (DERA is authorized an indebtedness against "MOD Votes" of 400M).  As noted above, DERA has consistently, almost embarrassingly, exceeded this target.  The Terms of Business Agreement under which MOD and DERA agree on work and price includes a fixed fee.  Thus excess "profit" parallels efficiency improvements above target.  DERA can by agreement with the Minister retain surplus above immediate needs in the business, and earn interest on its accounts. However, excess profit ultimately returns to the Treasury so the question becomes one of proper management and investment for long term stability while maintaining competitive rates.  Sector and Division managers obviously would like to retain control of some of their individual profit, but recognize the need for balance across the entire Agency, particularly during DTEO rationalization.  <BR>
	<DD>In addition to its flexibility with the operating surplus from its government business, DERA "is permitted to invest through its Enterprise Fund the net proceeds from its license and royalty income in projects that will yield benefits, albeit in the longer term, to both the MOD and DERA and that are likely to have dual-use potential"<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#21">(21)</A></I> .  Enterprise Fund revenues from existing patents currently run about 15M/year, mostly from liquid crystal displays.  This money is essentially treated as venture capital, to enable the Agency to move into new business.  It will support the development of the business infrastructure mentioned above.  There are some restrictions on use of these funds; for example, DERA is not allowed to take an equity interest in a private company (this seemed to have been a surprise that they will try to reverse).<BR>
	<DD>Much of what DERA has been able to accomplish is because it has designed and implemented its own <B>personnel system</B>.  Staff remain in the civil service, and many are in (and officially encouraged to join) trade unions.  However, Chisholm has been given adequate authority within the basic regulations and Framework, and in his personal delegation letter from the Permanent Undersecretary<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#22">(22)</A></I>, to be able to make quite major changes and thus motivate behavior.  As with so much of what DERA has been able to do, the policy basis for change goes back to The Next Steps, in this case to its recognition of the handicap of a totally uniform civil service system.  <BR>
	<DD>Many of the personnel changes have been alluded to above: pay for performance (including 20-25% of compensation at risk for senior managers), the Resource Manager-Project Manager system in Profit Centers, short-term employment contracts, centralized management of exit and redundancy costs during the major drawdown, and the willingness to pay the necessary costs of redundancies as the price of financial viability and proper manpower balance<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#23">(23)</A></I>.  And as stressed earlier, the Chief Executives ability at the onset to select his own top team and send those he didnt want back to MOD.  With these changes, the Human Resource function has also changed, to setting policy vice policing.  Authorities have been passed down to the Divisions and sectors, and with them many of the (few) remaining HR staff.  As with financial and managerial matters, the procedure is to motivate desired behavior and provide managers the tools to effect change.<BR>
	<DD>DERAs success in developing and implementing an effective personnel system within the civil service (albeit it has taken time) is a stark contrast to the lack of success DoD labs have had in getting permission to implement many of the most needed changes as part of their reinvention program.  While there are significant differences in the US and UK civil services and in the details of implementation, the basic approach of tailoring the personnel system to the needs of an institution and the nature of its employees and work is worth emulating.<BR>
	<DD>Finally, the transition from DRA to DERA, the plans to devolve the Support Services Sector, concerns with the monopolistic relationship, and the development of DRAs commercial interests keep alive the fundamental issue with which the UK civil sector continues to grapple, as described below: <B>ownership</B>.  The Government (at least the current government) retains the strong belief that services are best provided by the private sector.  An essential element of competition and value for money is impartiality of the customer to the source of the service; this impartiality can not occur when the customer is the owner.  This must be balanced by the need for a trusted partner and in-house capability, and so far that argument has prevailed in MOD.  However DERA itself seems to have decided that it is both appropriate and feasible to privatize a substantial aspect of its operations.  It is reasonable to expect that in future reviews, similar decisions by either DERA or the MOD may extend to other parts of the organization.  The message is clear: plan for continuous change.<P>

<B>5.  The Civil Sector Experience</B><P>

	<B>a.  Background</B><BR>
	<DD>Not surprisingly, the DERA experience - essentially the rationalization of a set of closely related organizations in a single Ministry - has been much more coherent than that in the civil sector.  While by far the largest "Public Sector Research Establishment" (PSRE), DERA is less dispersed and disparate than "everything else".  There have been some notable individual successes in the civil sector. Indeed most of the PSREs have become New Steps Agencies, and many have been privatized or otherwise significantly changed in line with the basic policy of separating policy and service.  The problems, such as they have been, have occurred in trying to identify an overall solution that harnesses the full set of 50+ PSREs in effective support of national S&T policy, which itself has changed.  Some background is necessary before discussing the process.<BR>
	<DD>The total UK annual R&D expenditure is roughly 14B, split 9B industry and 5B government.  There are different ways of categorizing the government expenditures, but basically about 2B is Defense and the rest civil sector.  The civil support comes from three sources: the Education Departments and their Higher Education Funding Councils (separate in England, Scotland, and Wales) sustain basic research at universities at about the 1B level through their general support of research alongside teaching.  The universities themselves essentially decide how to allocate these funds<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#24">(24)</A></I>.  Another 1B is distributed by the six Research Councils (RCs).  Their mission is to promote and support basic, strategic and applied research and related post-graduate training in their disciplinary sectors<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#25">(25)</A></I>.  The RCs accomplish this both directly through their own PSREs (about 20 that are still under review to determine their future status, plus others that have been privatized to a degree like SOC, discussed below.  The PSREs directly receive about 25% of RC funds), and through competitive awards to the PSREs, to private sector establishments of various types (some of which were PSREs), to universities and industry.  Other Departments likewise support S&T at about the 1B level, again to their PSREs (about 30 establishments and 2/3 of the funds, with the same caveats that apply to the RCs) and competitively with other performers.  At issue for this study are the policies and processes whereby the government has already significantly reduced the number of PSREs, the "Prior Options" reviews by which it is looking in detail at 37 PSREs this year, the nature of some of the solutions, and the impact on Defence.<P>

	<B>b.  S&T Policy: Realizing our Potential</B><I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#26">(26)</A></I><BR> 
	<DD>Following the election of 1992, the Prime Minister created, for the first time in 30 years, a Cabinet level Ministry with responsibility for formulating science and technology policy.  The Office of Science and Technology (OST) was established under him , combining elements of the former Department of Education and Science and the Cabinet Office<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#27">(27)</A></I>.  The tasks of the Minister of Public Service and Science, the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster, were to develop a White Paper laying out the Government's policy and strategy for S&T, and to prepare for its execution.<BR>
	<DD>Preparation of the White Paper involved a wide set of consultations.  A major study commissioned in 1992 was "Review of Allocation, Management and Use of Government Expenditure on S&T", led by Sir Peter Levene, the PM's Advisor on Efficiency and Effectiveness, and Prof. W.D.P. Stewart, the Chief Scientific Advisor of OST.  It was essentially a scrutiny of progress since The Next Steps.  It looked at objectives and priority setting, mechanisms for obtaining value for money, customer-contractor relationships, and steps to develop internal markets for government S&T expenditures.  <BR>
	<DD>R&D spending at the time was about 5.2B, down overall 17% since its peak in 85/86; however RC funding during this period had increased by 11%.  Spending was 25% basic research, 34% applied, and 35% experimental development; cut another way, 50% supported government services, especially defense, 25% advancement of the knowledge and science base, and 10-20% technology and industrial development.  The Levene-Stewart report concluded that this allocation was not optimal from the standpoint of the government as a whole, particularly since S&T can make such an important contribution to economic growth.  <BR>
	<DD>The report expressed three areas of concern, and made specific recommendations.  First, there was a need for a statement of government objectives and priorities for S&T (the White Paper), and a means of influencing departmental plans in line with them.  OST's role however should be scrutiny and influence, not direction.  Second, that portion of S&T spending directed toward wealth generation, should have active industrial involvement and often involve shared funding.  Third, Departments should annually publish policies and statistics of their compliance, so that everyone was aware of both intent and progress.<BR>
	<DD>Levene-Stewart reemphasized that the <B>customer-supplier relationship</B> is central to the efficiency and effectiveness of governments S&T expenditures.  Value for money is best when customers act on the basis of clear objectives, with a freedom of choice of suppliers (the situation is not the same for purely curiosity-driven research, but it does apply to all other aspects of S&T).  Departments were doing inadequate competitive tendering, and RCs needed redefined missions fully reflective of government objectives and priorities.  Although there had been progress toward formation of Next Steps Agencies, there were serious impediments to market development because customer-owners were shielding in-house suppliers.  To separate procurement and ownership of S&T, the report recommended consolidation of ownership of all civil PSREs in one (or a few) Civil Research Agency, reconsideration of privatization, implementation of incentives for widening the markets to the private sector, and closer PSRC-industry relationships.  DRA, while remaining separate and staying within MOD, should become more involved with civil markets and realize its commercial potential.<BR>
	<DD>The Government White Paper that resulted from the study and consultation process reflected and in fact expanded upon the findings, philosophy, and overall recommendations of the Levene-Stewart report.  It however did not adopt the specific recommendation for a centralized Civil Research Agency; rather, it reaffirmed the customer contractor principle in applied R&D, and called for a further scrutiny of best structures to respond to the policies and procedures it promulgated.<BR>
	<DD>The White Paper, <B>Realizing our Potential</B>, has had a far reaching impact on S&T in the UK.  Its policies are followed in practice.  Its organizational and procedural rearrangements have changed the way S&T is planned and conducted.  It is well known and widely quoted.  Because the UK S&T policy applies to military as well as civilian research, it is worth exploring some of its most significant aspects before examining its specific impact on PSRE restructuring.<BR>
	<DD>Simply stated, the UK S&T policy is that government funded S&T is to be directed to <B>wealth generation</B> and <B>quality of life</B>.  "...Science needs Government and public funds.  The decision for Government, when it funds science, as it must, is to judge where to place the balance between the freedom of researchers to follow their own instincts and curiosity, and the guidance of large sums of public money towards achieving wider benefits, above all the generation of national prosperity and the improvement of the quality of life."<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#28">(28)</A></I>   "Finding this balance is not a simple task..." but a common theme in the consultations was "the importance of maintaining and improving the UKs scientific and engineering excellence and skills and their application to national wealth creation."<BR>
	<DD>The White paper concluded "we are, as a nation, potentially very strong in science and technology...this strength...will not be properly applied unless efforts are made to break down barriers ...steps should be taken which ... harness that strength in science and engineering to the creation of wealth in the United Kingdom by bringing it into closer and more systematic contact with those responsible for industrial and commercial decisions...The Government will continue to allocate public resources to science and engineering on the scale necessary to finance the policies in this White Paper."<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#29">(29)</A></I> <BR>
	<DD>"The Governments strategy is to improve the nations competitiveness and quality of life by maintaining the excellence of science, engineering and technology in the United Kingdom" by strengthening partnerships between the S&T community and industry, supporting the scientific and engineering base, contributing to international - particularly European - research, promoting understanding, and ensuring the efficiency and effectiveness of Government-funded effort.<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#30">(30)</A></I> <BR>
	The White Paper directed a number of specific organizational and procedural changes:
<UL>
<LI>Direction, balance and content of the government funded S&T programme would be guided by results of a <B>Technology Foresight Programme</B>.  Foresight assessments, jointly conducted by industry and the scientific and engineering communities, would identify those technologies of most importance to the countrys economy, based on trends in research and the strength of the UK research team (science push), and emerging economic developments and the current or potential availability of firms that could appropriate research outcomes to seize market opportunities (demand pull).
<LI>Drawing upon the Technology Foresight assessments, and with contributions from all government departments, OST would annually publish a "Forward Look" that sets strategic objectives over a 5-10 year perspective, and gives a clear and up to date statement of government strategy to industrial and research communities.  It covers gaps and imbalances in the training and research programme; the balance between civil and defence efforts, between the Departmental and RC/HERF programs, and between domestic and international research; a comparison with principal competitors; and the scope for greater collaboration and synergy among the public and private S&T communities.
<LI>The RCs were reorganized (see footnote 25) and their membership streamlined.  The missions were "reformulated to make explicit their commitment to wealth creation and the quality of life".  Each would be headed by a part time Chairman (from industry) and a full time Chief Executive.  Oversight would be exercised by a Director-General of the RCs in OST.
<LI>A new Council for S&T, chaired by the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster, would advise Ministers via the Cabinet Committee on S&T, on the balance and direction of government funded S&T.  It would "bring together customers of publicly funded research, industrialists, academics and business men and women as well as the Chief Scientists (or equivalents) of the Government Departments most directly involved.  It will be an important forum of largely independent members."<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#31">(31)</A></I> 
<LI>Each Department was given an explicit S&T mission statement.  Government negotiating positions on international S&T programmes will be better coordinated, with particular attention to the EU.  Postgraduate training to better meet the needs of employers would focus on the MSc as the normal initial post-graduate degree in science, engineering and technology.
<LI>The <B>customer-contractor principle</B> "will be maintained and strengthened.  The Government believes that many of the services currently provided by Government research establishments could be carried out in the private sector, and that privatization is a realistic prospect for a number of establishments.  There will be a further scrutiny of the best organizational and management structures"<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#32">(32)</A></I> .
</UL>
	<DD>"Government cannot, and will not attempt to, remove from industry its responsibility for investing in innovation and bringing new products to market.  Nonetheless, it is the fundamental theme of this White Paper that a closer partnership and better diffusion of ideas between the science and engineering communities, industry, the financial sector and Government are needed as part of the crucial effort to improve our <B>national competitiveness</B> and <B>quality of life</B>.  We have the talents; now we need fully to realize our potential."<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#33">(33)</A></I> <BR>
	<DD>Realizing our Potential forced a major change in how S&T is funded and conducted in the UK.  Its measures have not all been equally successful (e.g. the Technology Foresights are of uneven quality across sectors), and as can be imagined it caused considerable initial consternation among the academics (although they were vastly relieved at the commitment for continued funding).  However it is now perfectly clear to one and all in the UK why the nation supports S&T, and what approach one has to take to get proposals funded.  As opposed to the US where we have no national consensus or policy on S&T and all decisions are pragmatic, in the UK decisions on funding, organization and management are soundly founded on clear and consistent policy.  One can agree or disagree with the policy itself; but it has been consistently and thoroughly applied, and by and large has been well accepted and effective.  I have stressed it at some length here because in looking for lessons the that US can extract from examination of organizational rationalization in the UK, it is essential to understand that all of the individual changes, in the civil PSREs as well as in MOD and DERA, have been clearly guided by policy and national consensus.<BR>
	<DD>The scrutiny required by the White Paper was conducted by the Governments Efficiency Unit<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#34">(34)</A></I>.  Its report, "Multi-Departmental Scrutiny of Public Sector Research Establishments" was published in June 1994.  The terms of reference were to identify PSREs where early privatization was feasible and desirable, and where not to identify the potential for rationalization; and to consider changes to current ownership and funding arrangements.  The objective was to obtain best value for money.  The scrutiny looked at 50 PSREs from both departments and the RCs.  They were very diverse in size, mission, and business culture, but all were supported by federal money.  <BR>
	<DD>The scrutiny found little scope for immediate privatization, partly because the Ministries had already picked the low hanging fruit.  Two establishments actually privatized during the study.  It did, as expected, find scope for greater play of market forces, and made a number of procedural recommendations to improve coordination and customer-contractor relationships.<BR>
	<DD>On the issue of overall organization structure it noted, like the Levene-Stewart study, that of all the possible coordination and efficiency mechanisms, the most powerful is lumping the PSREs under one Chief Executive.  It recommended two consolidation models for further study: four market sector groups (Marine Resources and Environment; Non-marine Environment; Biotechnology and Biological Sciences; and Food and Agriculture), and two geographical groups (Scotland, and England & Wales).  This, we were told, created a huge controversy; virtually no one liked either suggestion (with the possible exception of Sir Peter Levene, the head of the Efficiency Unit which ran the scrutiny).  This was the first government efficiency scrutiny not implemented.<BR>
	<DD>The lesson learned from the two failed tries was that the PSREs were simply too diverse to tackle by an external review in general terms.  Neither of the scrutinies adequately recognized the differences, among both customers (very different Ministries plus very different RCs) and suppliers.  The RCs and Ministries had themselves to get involved and own the answers if there was to be progress.  The Government response to the scrutiny<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#35">(35)</A></I>  therefore, while reiterating the commitment to best value for money and accepting many of the procedural recommendations, "decided not to proceed with the...specific proposals to group establishments...nor to seek rationalisation through the mechanism of appointing new Directors of Rationalisation".<BR>
	<DD>Instead, the Government elected to "build on the existing prior options process"<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#36">(36)</A></I> .  This is a well established UK process to take a zero-base look at an establishment.  The <B>Prior Options Reviews</B> consider each organization in detail, taking Technology Foresight findings of future roles and requirements into account.  They are conducted by the parent Department or RC but with at least one independent member, and are overseen by a steering committee that represents other public sector interests and customers.  They are publicly announced and comments are solicited from the scientific community, other potential suppliers of the service, etc.  The findings are considered by the Ministers collectively to ensure coordination across Departments.<BR>
	<DD>In order to consider the functions of each establishment in the context of others working in similar fields across the public sectors, the current set of Reviews are being conducted in three tranches, with a common steering committee for related PSREs.  The first tranche, which reported in March 1996, looked at 18 establishments in four sectors (2 Fisheries, 11 Agriculture/Plant Science, 4 Physical Sciences, and 1 Police Science).  The second, which reported in July, looked at 9 establishments in 2 sectors (6 in Animal Science and 3 in Marine and non-marine Environment, although 2 of these 3 have several labs lumped into Centres).  The third, to report in December, will look at 10 in 2 sectors (3 in Food and Nutrition, 7 in Health).<BR>
	<DD>As noted earlier, there is a clear priority order of options to be considered by the Reviews. If possible, abolish the function.  If thats impossible, privatize the establishment. If that isnt feasible, contract out some or all of the work.  Finally, rationalize whats left.  Thus the review proceeds on the basis of "Key Questions:
<UL>
<LI>Is the Function Needed?
<LI>Must the Public Sector be Responsible for Function?
<LI>Must the Public Sector Provide the Function Itself?
<LI>What is the scope for Rationalisation?
<LI>How will the Function be Managed?
</UL>
	<DD>The guideline paper for the Reviews provides specific detailed criteria for privatization, dealing with both appropriateness and feasibility.  This is a very deliberate, intensive process designed to examine all aspects of the service and its provider, and whenever possible to move functions into the private sector.  Because this approach might be instructive for looking at US government labs, some of the suggested questions related to privatization are quoted in Appendix D.  <BR>
	<DD>While it is too early to judge the success of this focused set of Prior Options Reviews, the third try to deal conclusively with the entire set of PSREs, I have seen the results for 13 of the first tranche: three were recommended to become new "Next Steps" Executive Agencies; three will retain their Executive Agency status, but with management or financial accounting changes; one will be examined further for consolidation with related establishments; and six were recommended for further study toward "full independence from the public sector", i.e. privatisation.  If this is any indication of the overall outcome, the Prior Options Reviews will be a success, at least from the perspective of thorough implementation of the government policy.  And of course Prior Option Reviews are conducted every five years, so there will be additional opportunities for institutional change.  Perseverance pays.<P>

	<B>c.  An example: NERC and two of its PSREs</B><BR>
	<DD>To obtain a feel for the impact of Realizing our Potential and rationalization on a civil PSRE and its customer, the DoD delegation visited Southampton Oceanography Center (SOC).  We met there with the Secretary of the Board of the National Environmental Research Council (NERC; Christopher West), the Director (Prof John Shepherd) and staff of SOC and the Vice Chancellor of the University of Southampton (which operates SOC jointly with NERC), the Director (Dr Brian McCartney) of Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory (which as part of NERC's Center for Coastal and Marine Sciences [CCMS] is in the second tranche of the current round of Prior Option Reviews), and the Executive Secretary (Capt Alex Morrice) and members of the Management Group of CAROS, Cooperative Arrangements for Research in Ocean Sciences. CAROS responds to the requirement of the White Paper that RCs form "concordats" with Departments to coordinate their research programmes (here, NERC & MOD).<BR>
	<DD>NERC was established in 1965.  Prior to the White Paper it had three Science Directorates: Marine & Atmosphere, Earth, and Terrestrial & Freshwater.  Each was headed by a powerful scientist that wielded considerable influence over the direction of S&T in his area and developed a strong sense of community in the universities and centers<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#37">(37)</A></I>.  The NERC Directorates in Swindon directly oversaw the operations of some 30 separate sites, coordinated proposal reviews, developed strategies, and pressed initiatives with the government (hence the new 50M facility that SOC now occupies).  This all changed drastically (and the powerful heads of the Directorates returned to their Universities) on 1 April 1994, with the implementation of White Paper reforms.<BR>
	<DD>Today, NERC's Science budget is about 150M; it manages an additional 40M of contract research from various Ministries and the EC.  The three Directorates have been replaced by a single S&T Directorate which reports to the Chief Executive.  The Chief Executive in turn reports to the Chairman of the NERC Council.  The Council has 12 independent members from academia and industry, plus appointees from interested government departments.  It votes on the apportionment of funds among programs and funding mechanisms.  The Chief Executive also oversees the operation of NERC's 8 University Units<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#38">(38)</A></I>  and five PSRE institutes (the British Antarctic Survey, the British Geological Survey, SOC [jointly with the University], the Centre for Coastal and Marine Science [3 labs], and the Centre for Ecology and Hydrology [4 Institutes and some 20+ sites]). The NERC PSREs all operate as Non-Departmental Public Bodies.<BR>
	<DD>NERC's overall strategy document, published per dictate of the White Paper, is entitled "Environmental Directions".  It is based on extensive consultations with its scientific and user communities, and has three major components: Key Challenges identified by the scientists<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#39">(39)</A></I> ; Environmental Foresight Topics distilled by Technology Foresight Implementation Group from the reports of the 15 panels of the programme<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#40">(40)</A></I>; and six principal Environmental and Natural Resource Issues which link them: biodiversity, environmental risks and hazards, global change, natural resources, pollution, and waste.  This document is intended to meet the White Paper's charge to clearly spell out long range directions and communicate them to the public and the communities that perform and use NERCs services.  It also provides programmatic guidance.<BR>
	<DD>Six S&T Boards (Atmospheric, Earth, Earth Observation, Marine, Polar, and Terrestrial & Freshwater), each with both independent (academic and industry) and Council members, report to the Council and advise on new initiatives.  They develop the programmatic and apportionment guidance upon which the Council votes, and which the Directorate of S&T executes.  They are particularly influential because they review bids for new thematic programmes, which they judge for both science quality and relevance, and review the Core Strategic Programme which is executed by the NERC Surveys, Centres, and University Units.  With the Chief Executive, they effectively set the agenda for UK environmental S&T.<BR>
	<DD>Under the Director of S&T, who reports to the Chief Executive, the director of the Technology Interactions Section maintains linkage with users and customers.  The director of Scientific Services manages the infrastructure (ships, special facilities and labs) that is made available without charge to any researcher supported by NERC.  In addition to the Core Strategic (PSRE) and Infrastructure programmes (respectively 24% and 38% of the 1996/7 budget), two competitive programmes or funding modes are executed by the director of the Awards and Training Section.  Non-Thematic research (20%; previously called responsive mode) is curiosity-driven, and only UK universities and academic analogues are eligible.  Proposals are reviewed by six referees, and then ranked by the five disciplinary Research Grants and Training Awards committees<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#41">(41)</A></I>, made up of members of both academic and user communities.  Funding mechanisms include research grants, studentships and fellowships.  Thematic programs (18%; formerly directed mode) last up to five years, and address basic, strategic or applied issues that have been approved by the Boards.  Individual projects within a thematic programme are subjected to peer review and assessed by a Steering Committee.  Anyone can bid for a thematic programme and its projects, although those that rank highest usually have a large number of participants.  Overall, the split of NERC's science expenditure (141.6M in 1994/5) is about 53% Centre/Survey and 47% university.<BR>
	<DD>The main themes of government policy are clearly evident in NERC's make-up and programmes: open consultation and communication, separation between customer and supplier plus competition for services, and extensive industrial involvement.  The scientists booth in the Centres and the Universities are well aware that for their proposals to succeed, they must address the relevance of the work to wealth generation or quality of life.  And since wealth generation is at times a bit of a stretch for many of the interests of the environmental community, NERC itself has to fight just to retain level funding.<BR>
	<DD>SOC was NERC's first venture into rationalization.  The process actually began long before the RC reorganization, responding to an earlier House of Lords Select Committee report that recommended government labs be more closely associated with Universities.  A small team with long term drive and vision, headed by one of the powerful NERC Directors, ultimately convinced the government to provide the funding (nearly 50M, 3/4 via NERC and 1/4 via the Higher Education Funding Council) needed to relocate the previous deep-ocean research labs (which were inland), the national research vessels (which were berthed in Wales), and parts of the University of Southampton to a magnificent new purpose-built facility<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#42">(42)</A></I>  right on the docks at Southampton.  Southampton was selected as the site for the Center both because of its location and because its Oceanography Department had the highest rating in the national Research Assessment Exercise.<BR>
	<DD>SOC is an interesting amalgam.  Within the single new building which houses 450 staff and students are the Research Vessel Services, four NERC divisions (Ocean circulation, Ocean Technology, Ocean Processes, and Seafloor Processes), and two University Departments (Oceanography and Geology).  A third University Department of the Center, Marine Technology, remains on the main campus within the Faculty of Engineering.  At issue is how to integrate all of this into a world class oceanographic center.<BR>
	<DD>SOC provides some interesting contrasts to DERA.  First, it was not driven by the need to cut costs.  Indeed our hosts indicated that it could not be justified on the basis of cost, rather the objective was to improve the national capability to do the science, and SOC was an example of paying full costs to "do it right".<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#43">(43)</A></I>.  Second, perhaps as befits its more academic nature, there is no sense of "crisis", real or created.  Rather than make a force fit between the two very different cultures of NERC and the University, the decision was to move first and then manage integration by "persuading people of the advantages".  <BR>
	<DD>The NERC employees that moved to SOC remain civil servants, and the University employees likewise retain their status.  The balance will change over time, since all new hires will be University employees (thus this is a slow but sure form of privatization).  Likewise all SOC funds (except NERC salaries) and handled by the University.  The Director, who was selected from outside any of the involved organizations, has a full time appointment at the University, and a 5-year appointment as Director.  Some 40 senior NERC staff have adjunct status with the University, and are involved in teaching and mentoring graduate students.  In fact the unspoken expectation seems to be that it is the students that will themselves be the major catalyst for integration.<BR>
	<DD>Obviously, not all the staff are fully pleased with the situation.  There are NERC/University differences in the nature of the work (academic vs core/strategic).  NERC salaries are about 20% above those of the University.  However the University staff can consult and do outside work.  The Director commented that the advantages of integration are clearer for the researchers (e.g. students, magnificent new facilities, waterside location, etc) than for the academics, and that the scientists of both types are more sanguine than the technicians.  Overall there is high chance of success due to the parallel interests of NERC and the University, and to the quality of the staff and facilities.  Ultimately of course, SOC will become fully a University institution as NERC staff are replaced.  At issue is the speed and effectiveness of the integration.  As opposed to the forced conversion of DERA, this will occur at SOC by removing impediments and creating incentives.<BR>
	<DD>Although SOC escaped a Prior Options Review because of its integration with the University, the other NERC Centres (with the exception of the British Antarctic Survey) have just completed them and are awaiting the outcome.  We talked with Dr Brian McCartney of the Proudman Oceanographic Lab, (staff about 100) one of the three that make up the dispersed Centre for Coastal and Marine Studies<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#44">(44)</A></I>.  The Review Group which considered CCMS had 3 members from NERC Council and Boards, and about 10 others from the private sector and other agencies.  There were no local members.  The input comprised statistics of the operation, CCMSs statement of their view, NERCs view (which CCMS has not seen), and solicited comments from colleagues and from users such as MOD, DERA, and the British Meteorology Office.  DERA for example contracts with CCMS for their operational coastal model, and benefits from direct and focused interaction with the researchers and modelers.<BR>
	<DD>Dr McCartney noted that the report, delivered to the Minister 2 October, remains confidential until the decision is made.  He believes the review will conclude that the work is essential to the nation.  He expects one of three options: a trade sale, a non-competitive sale (management buy-out), or enhanced-status quo with the Centre operating at greater arms length and with different funding arrangements.  He noted that reviewing the Centre as a whole rather that by individual lab made it difficult to look an SOC-like University option, because of the labs' geographic dispersion.  He expressed the concern that privatization has the danger of focusing the lab more on survival than science, and that some PSREs which had gone that route had become essentially "beltway bandits".<BR>
	<DD>Both CCMS and SOC do considerable work for MOD, through DERA.  Oceanography is a core concern of Navys, and DERA lost some of its internal expertise during the rationalization.  While it still has oceanographers in its mine, sonar, underwater weapon and hydrodynamic sections, therefore, it needs to rely on the NERC Centres and to a degree on universities for much of its S&T; the "UK OPMOD" work at CCMS is a good example. <BR> 
	<DD>Work had started on a NERC-MOD MOU in Ocean Science and Technology even before the White Paper.  It was recognized that in spite of best intentions, and roughly 50M NERC and 80M MOD in parallel areas, liaison based purely on personal contacts suffered from lack of continuity and security barriers.  This early effort enabled NERC and MOD to formally establish the "concordat" suggested by the White Paper in December 1994.  The resultant CAROS is cochaired by the NERC Executive Director and the MOD Deputy Chief Scientist (Research and Technology).  NERC members of its Management Group have been cleared to the SECRET level to allow free discussion of MOD priorities and plans.  Most activity however is conducted by unclassified working groups, which deal with issues such as ship time, coupled models, and rapid environmental assessment.<BR>
	<DD>The basic procedure by which interests are combined is to expose the Centres' NERC proposals to DERA early in the process.  DERA can then both influence the proposal, and plan its work to complement that of the scientists without security difficulties.  The quid pro quo is MOD advocacy of the project with NERC Council.  Examples include dynamic studies in the Straits of Hormuz, aspects of the coastal LOIS program, and upcoming studies of shelf-break dynamics NW of Scotland.  DERA, especially the DRA Sea Sector, also contracts directly with the Centres for specific research.<BR>
	<DD>The scientists commented that DERA was good to work with and helped to manage the interface.  As a result MOD was clearly a more intelligent customer than the other Departments.  This relationship between the military and civil sectors thus seems to be effective for both parties.  In part the relationship is based on trust that DERA will rely on the civil PSREs rather than attempt to compete with them or duplicate their skills, but the presence of a formal mechanism with an Executive Secretary (paid for by NERC) and senior attention to the cooperation helps maintain the momentum and facilitate long range planning for both parties.  It is particularly important for DERA in helping decide what minimum set of skills and facilities it need retain.<P>

<B>6.  Observations</B><BR>
	<DD>The UK lab rationalization experience has been quite successful from the perspective of those in Government that made it happen.  It also has been quite fast, considering the magnitude of the changes.  Executive offices in Ministries, and service providers in Agencies, PSREs of other types, and in industry, have attitudes and processes that are drastically different from what they were less than five years ago.  Even in academia there is a clear understanding of customer-supplier relationships, and of the rationale for publicly funded S&T be it civilian or military: wealth generation and quality of life.<BR>
	<DD>The restructuring process has proceeded differently both in practice and in style in civil and military sectors (and in other parts of the government's work besides S&T), but in all cases it is underpinned by consistent policy regarding the responsibilities of government and how they should be carried out.  The Visions 21 Team will have to determine which if any of the steps taken in the UK can be transported across the Atlantic.  What this paper has tried to point out is that in addition to the thousands of specific decisions regarding business practices, personnel, policies, financial schemes, site closures, etc., there are some very general principles that must guide successful rationalization.  It the UK these have been:
<UL><B>
<LI>Consistent policy and pressure from the top
<LI>Clear separation and delineation of responsibilities
<LI>Perseverance and willingness to learn and keep trying
<LI>Trust in individuals and organizations
<LI>Participation of the private sector</B>
</UL>
	<DD>At issue is the set of central guiding principles that will enable a similarly successful rationalization in the US.<P>

