 <B>Appendix C: DRA Site Rationalization</B><BR>
	<DD>Like most of the rest of DRAs changes, site rationalization was driven by the need to quickly establish financial viability.  David Tyte who directed the process starts his brief by noting that there were too many sites, too many buildings, the buildings were old and in poor repair, too many workshops and stores and too much stock, too many computer bureaus, too much transport, too many separate support units, and the market was declining.  Even with the best of will, the input-driven system kept things because it didnt know what else to do with them, and added things without any recognition of true costs. DERA had to rationalize on essential sites, and completely restructure the support services.<BR>
	<DD>John Chisholm chose Tyte for the first of these two major tasks.  Tyte had 30 years experience in MOD both in the DREs and in London, and more importantly had been Nigel Hughes TD for the initial phases of establishing the agency.  Thus he had a broad knowledge of the sites.  Tyte in turn was allowed to choose his own team and develop his own process.  The chain of command was kept short: one individual was responsible for the analysis of each site.  He made recommendations to Tyte and Tyte made his to the Chief Executive who made the decisions (subject only to Ministerial approval).  No consensus and certainly no say by the site.<BR>
	<DD>The target for site reduction was based on an assessment of the infrastructure costs that had to be eliminated to achieve competitive pricing at the expected reduced level of income: 90M/year, over 60% of then-current levels.  The reductions had to be taken while retaining the capability to deliver product.  Other objectives included minimizing disruption and moves (the UK housing market is "arthritic"), minimizing the costs and the capital employed (everything had to be done "within the envelope", i.e. without any extra funds), maintaining robustness against future change, contributing to greater flexibility and technology rationalization, and releasing valuable land back to MOD. <BR>
	<DD>The resulting criteria for site selection were efficiency (overhead costs), investment (reprovision, relocation, and redundancy), land release value, and less quantifiable program continuity, technology rationalization, and flexibility.  These had to be considered in terms of the new Sector arrangement, which replaced and shifted functions among the previous DREs (and which itself was in constant flux).  Tyte notes that the most agonizing was Structural Materials since each of the old establishments had materials groups.  The basic strategy was to retain "core" sites that were too expensive to move because of staff numbers or facilities, to retain small sites essential to provide key capabilities<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#45">(45)</A></I>, to fill up the retained large sites, and to release land with a high sales value.<BR>  
	<DD>One of the initial issues to be settled with MOD was what to do with the land DERA vacated.  The choices were for DERA to take ownership of all the property of the DREs and sell off what it vacated, using the funds earned to pay for the rationalization costs; or for DERA to identify what it wanted in the long term and return the vacated property to MOD, paying rent in the interim, and to separately fund redundancies.  Tyte notes that "it was an interesting debate that we got out of very lightly".  At the time there was a big property boom.  MOD has sold some properties to British Aerospace, who in turn made a killing by selling some of it off for housing.  MOD certainly didnt want DERA to get away with the same thing, so it said it would take all the property back.  At which point, the bottom fell out of the housing market, and MOD is stuck with a disposal problem.  Of course DERA is now responsible for all DRA property it has retained, plus that obtained with DTOE; but it is absolved from responsibility for cleanup of pre-existing contamination.<BR>
	<DD>The process Tyte and his team followed was to draw up a list of options for each site (based on personal knowledge), and to look at the cost of each over a 20-25 year time frame.  These of course had to be looked at in combinations, and some compromises were made because of employment and housing considerations in an area.  In addition they managed to put some "hard cases" aside into the T&E organization; those have now come back, but as Tyte notes they now know how to do this job.  Tyte also notes that one reason the DRA job was somewhat easier that DTOEs will be is that most of the sites are in England, in areas where there are other employment opportunities.  The process will be more emotional in isolated areas.  Combined options were arranged in terms of "best buys" based on running cost savings, disposal proceeds and reconstruction costs, to put together a total package that met the initial objectives.  When the decision had been made, they "consulted" with the affected trade unions who had the right to ask hard questions about the economics of the move; DRA obviously had to have a good case.  The unions could either accept DERAs rationale or request assistance of their MPs.  They in turn could attempt to persuade the Minister he had made a poor decision.  MPs also were sent a letter with a copy of the consultative document.  And of course there was considerable personal discussion of Tyte and the Chief Executive with both MOD leadership and MPs.  But basically the decision was that of the Chief Executive with the approval of the Minister.<BR>
	<DD>That left the issue of paying for the costs of the necessary moves and new construction.  The price tag was calculated at about 200M (plus VAT), but the Chief Executive was able to show MOD where to get the money. He also could go around the programmers and naysayers to the Minister to get the ok.  Basically, MOD runs a 10-year rolling budget for capital improvements.  Requests have to go in for improvements 10 years ahead, and once approved it could not be changed.  Chisholm simply arranged to get this money up front to use for the rationalization.<BR>
	<DD>The rest has "simply" been execution, most of which has occurred on schedule and cost. The timetable is instructive:<BR>
Approval for rationalization studies ... Nov 91<BR>
Ministerial & Treasury approval for Programme ... Dec 92<BR>
Project Manager appointed ... May 93<BR>
MOD & Treasury Approvals for Major Construction <BR>
Submitted ... Oct 93<BR>
  Approved ... Dec 93<BR>
Work Contract Placed<BR>
  Minor Sites (DRA delegation<I><A HREF="cdnews9.htm#46">(46)</A></I> ) ... Jun 92-Oct 93<BR>
  Major Sites ... Nov 93-Aug 94<BR>
Moves Completed<BR>
  Minor Sites ... Oct 92-Dec 94<BR>
  Major Sites ... Aug 94-Mar 97<BR>
This speaks to taut management and quality execution.<BR>
	<DD>Tyte did note some weak spots of the process:
<UL>
<LI>Users and senior managers didnt believe it would happen, and were too "busy elsewhere" when needed 
<LI>The organization was changing rapidly, leading to specification changes in the buildings
<LI>DRA was initially dubious about survival and undersized.  Now theyre already over capacity.
<LI>They shouldnt have refurbished any buildings.  Savings are illusory, headaches immense.  Knock em down and rebuild.
</UL><P>

<B> Appendix D: Privatisation Criteria</B><BR>
		<DD>Privatisation criteria can usefully be classified under two headings:<BR>
- those largely associated with <B>appropriateness</B> (whether there are powerful reasons for continued provision by the public sector, irrespective of the saleability of the operations); and<BR>
- those largely associated with <B>feasibility</B> (whether the operation can in practice be packaged for a successful sale).<BR>
	<DD>In most cases there are conflicting objectives, and the appropriate balance between objectives has to be determined.  For example, private sector provision may be deemed to be appropriate but privatisation may be too expensive to be in taxpayers' interests. (For those who like to think in these terms, this issue can be expressed as a question of the <B>relative weights</B> to be attached to privatisation criteria in any particular case.)<BR>
		<DD>In addition, when assessing feasibility, it is rarely the case that a simple "yes or no" answer to a question can be said to make privatisation either feasible or impossible; there is a spectrum of degrees of difficulty which has to be judged according to the perceived acceptability of risk. (Again, for those who think in these terms, the issue here is that of the scoring of an option against a criterion.)<BR>
		<DD>Different judgements against the privatisation criteria can also be made for different methods of privatisation.  Indeed, many of the criteria for assessing whether a body should be privatised are of equal importance for assessing how a body should be privatised.<BR>
		<DD>For the purposes of the present exercise, the focus should probably be on appropriateness criteria, together with any obvious show-stoppers on the feasibility side. A feasibility exercise is needed to complete the evaluation in detail.<P>

<U>Horizon and Scope</U><BR>
		<DD>In making their assessments, Ministers will need to consider not only how the criteria apply at present, but how they are likely to apply in the medium term.<BR>
		<DD>Strictly, privatisation criteria should be applied to the public sector research establishment as a whole and to its constituent parts.  It will be reasonable to ask Departments to consider separately the key activities within each body.<BR>
		<DD>One possible framework for setting out the assessment against privatisation criteria is a matrix.  Using the framework, the criteria are in rows, and a range of status options, (privatisation, contractorisation,   etc) are columns.  The evaluation cells can either be filled in by a descriptive comment or by a summary score.<P>

<U>Appropriateness criteria</U><BR>
		<DD>In considering appropriateness, the presumption is to privatise: in other words, there is a need to turn the question around, so that it represents a judgement as to the appropriateness of keeping the body in the public sector.  It is not just a question of whether the public sector matches the performance of the private sector, nor is the	 issue purely one of saving money.  Activities which can appropriately be carried out in the private sector, should be.  This allows the public sector to concentrate on its key objectives and helps reduce the size of the public sector.<BR>
		<DD>So the question is whether there are any special reasons (for example, national policy concerns or a failure in the operation of existing markets) for keeping the activity in the public sector.<BR>
		<DD>These reasons might arise as answers to the following sorts of questions:<BR>
- Is the service provided fundamental to the operations of the public sector?  If so, the prospects for secure, competitive supplies of the service will have to be considered.<BR>
- Would privatisation impact on the way in which the Secretary of State carries out statutory duties? if so, the case for reviewing those statutory duties and alternative ways of fulfilling them would have to be considered.  The Deregulation and Contracting Out Act 1994 makes possible the use of private sector contractors in delivering a wide range of statutory services.<BR>
- Are there other special policy reasons for keeping the service in the public sector (eg defence implications, security implications, a need for independence from particular suppliers, etc) ? Could these be secured in the private sector?<BR>
- Are there special policy objectives which need to be taken into account (eg perceived issues of public confidence, the effect of disruption on other parts of the public sector, the impact on staff and management, the cost to the taxpayer)?<BR>
- Are the functions concerned already being provided on a competitive basis by other suppliers?  If so, it will be more difficult to make a case for retaining the function in the public sector.<BR>
- Would privatisation of the service produce an actual or effective monopoly or give the privatised body an unfair competitive advantage over other service providers?  If so it will be necessary to consider how the privatised body could be regulated.<BR>
- Does the business provide services which are beneficial to clients, but which they would not, in practice, purchase (either because of a lack of information or because no one client would pay the full cost of providing the service and there is no mechanism for them buying the service jointly)? if so, there may be an argument for the public sector ensuring the service is provided, though not necessarily for delivery by the public sector.<BR>
- Does the service have benefits to the economy which are not reflected in the operations of the market (eg environmental benefits, social benefits)?  If so, the most effective and efficient manner of achieving the desired result would have to be investigated.  There may be a case for either provision or subsidy from the public sector.<BR>
- Would the services if privatised be provided in a <I>less</I> efficient manner (because of a lack of information, the loss of a network, the loss of a natural monopoly, the scale of the investment involved, etc)?  If so, there would be a need to consider whether there are ways of addressing these problems.<P>

<U>Feasibility criteria</U><BR>
		<DD>The feasibility criteria consider both whether the body is in a state where it could, in principle, be sold and whether there would be any interest in buying it, funding its acquisition or contracting to provide its services.<BR>
		<DD>There is a need to consider both the current position and the possibility of changes (whether deliberately instigated as a result of the review or because of external events such as changes in the market) in the coming years.  In the same way, there is a need to consider both whether there might be interest in acquiring the business now and whether there might be interest in the future (possibly after some changes have been made to it).  Timing is therefore a crucial issue.<BR>
		<DD>A number of generic feasibility criteria are listed below.  The questions have been phrased in terms of a trade sale, but, with minor amendment, are in general equally applicable to other forms of privatisation.<BR>
- Does the business make a profit at present?  If not, can a route to financial viability be developed either as a stand-alone entity or as part of a larger organisation?<BR>
- Could performance be improved by removing public sector restrictions eg more flexible employment practices, access to new markets, raising new finance and an injection of private sector management?<BR>
- Is the business in a stable state?<BR>
- Is the business large enough to be self-standing or of interest to potential purchasers?<BR>
- Does the business represent a market opportunity for new owners?<BR>
- If required (either as a result of an assessment against the appropriateness criteria or because of an assessment of the interests of the market) , are the various business units separable?<BR>
- Are the contracts which the business has with its clients of a type which would be appropriate between a private sector provider and its clients?<BR>
- Are the financial and management information systems of the business appropriate to the needs (including audit requirements) of a private sector business?<BR>
- Would the financial and management information systems of the business allow a potential purchaser to review the past performance of the business on a commercial basis?<BR>
- What would be the transitional effects on the business and its customers of a privatisation?<BR>
- What would be the proceeds of privatisation?<BR>
- What would be the costs of the privatisation process; reorganisation; restructuring the balance sheet?<BR>
- How long would privatisation take?<BR>
- Does the business have a secure revenue stream?  Does it rely on one customer or many?<P>

<U>Existing guidance on identifying privatisation candidates</U><BR>
		<DD>The Treasury booklet <B>"Privatisation of Central Government Activities, Guidance for Departments"</B> states that:<BR>
(i) "Activities which may be suitable candidates for privatisation include those already established on a customer/supplier relationship with departmental or agency headquarters; those that do not contribute directly to the Department's or agency's central objectives; and those already performed under contract by the private sector." (paragraph 1.4)<BR>
(ii) "...Ministers may decide that parts of an activity should remain in government control for operational, statutory or market reasons." (paragraph 2.1)<BR>
		<DD>The <B>Next Steps Team</B> issues guidance on the conduct of Prior options reviews of executive agencies.<BR>
		<DD>The <B>Continuity and Change</B> White Paper (paragraph 2.25) lists the key questions as:<BR>
- Does the job need to be done at all?<BR>
- If the activity must be carried out, does the government have to be responsible for it" Since 1979 the government has pursued a consistent policy of transferring organisations which no longer need to be owned by government to the private sector.<BR>
- Where the government needs to remain responsible for an activity, does the government have to carry out the task itself?<BR>
- Where the job must be carried out within government is the organisation properly structured and focused on the job to be done?<P><HR><P>
 

