 <I><A NAME="10">(10)</A></I> DRA started with around 12,500 staff and reduced to 8500 (1800 of these are now in the Support Services Division); the rest came with the additions that make up DERA.  The numbers quoted in this report can be confusing.  They will not match or add up and are not consistent.  The reason is simple: I have tried to repeat what I heard, and people used different accounting systems and different years, and most importantly had different perspectives on how to show numbers.  Measurement is critical to the UK system, but part of the game is what you measure, how you treat the data, and how you display it.  Neither the DoD group through some quite penetrating questions, nor I, have been able to gain a picture that would satisfy an auditor.  Nor was that the intent.  Thus every number is simply a ROM estimate based on the author's interpretation, and the accountants if any in the audience ane cordially invited to sort it out over here for themselves.  After a final review, I have convinced myself that the ROMs are not contradictory and probably display a reasonable first order estimate of reality, at least to within an order of magnitude.<BR>
<I><A NAME="11">(11)</A></I>  Op cit 5, para 2.1, Aim and Functions<BR>
<I><A NAME="12">(12)</A></I>  Generation of wealth and quality of life are the two key reasons for public support of S&T in the UK.  The nations science policy is laid out in the May 1993 White Paper "Realizing our Potential: A Strategy for Science, Engineering and Technology", prepared by the Office of Science and Technology.  This is discussed further in Para 5b; the key point here is that MOD and DERA are expected to coordinate with and support the civil sector.<BR>
<I><A NAME="13">(13)</A></I> "Secondary" legislation is needed to get an "affirmative order" for a specific Trading Fund, but "primary" legislation was not required for any of the changes that created DERA or other New Steps Agencies.<BR>
<I><A NAME="14">(14)</A></I> DERA managers and customers alike raved about the improvements.  The only caveat is that while bragging about productivity they also occasionally spoke of "quality of research".  Everyone waffled when pressed on how this was measured, and essentially stated that it was impossible at this point to judge what all the changes are likely to produce in the long run.  People have been working long and hard because to do otherwise would have had disastrous consequences during the "crisis".  This gets a bit old after a while, and presents a qualitative and quantitative challenge to the current and next TQ phases, when those that have "stuck it out" have every expectation of being able to live normal working lives.<BR>
<I><A NAME="15">(15)</A></I> Ratings are done with input from project managers. The rating scheme assigns up to 20 marks: 10 for current performance, 5 for track record, and 5 for demand for the individuals services<BR>
<I><A NAME="16">(16)</A></I> This concern was expressed most strongly in a later conversation between the author and Chris Fallows, Director of the Navy portion of the Applied Research Program.  The topic under discussion was ASW.  Those familiar with the history of US ASW RDT&E over the last 20 years will recognize the problems that can arise from perceptions of biased approaches to warfighting challenges.<BR>
<I><A NAME="17">(17)</A></I> This derives from the 1993 White Paper on S&T policy, discussed in more detail in Para 5b<BR>
<I><A NAME="18">(18)</A></I> DCDS(S) formulates and sponsors the entire future equipage programme for MOD, and its underpinning research base.  He is responsible for the Applied Research Program (@450M).  Of his staff of about 500, 150 are involved full time in managing research (most of them are seconded from DERA). The ARP is divided into about 50 Packages, each of which is closely monitored by a customer team at MOD.  The Corporate Research Programme under Mike Markin runs @ 160M/year.  It is managed by a staff of 10, with a "light touch" and a trusted partner relationship.  CRP has 11 technical groups, and each has three parts: Targeted Research (20%) where MOD states both what is wanted and when; Underpinning Research (35-40%) where MOD defines what technology needs to provide and DERA interprets how to get there; and Innovative Research, where DERA is simply told to be innovative.  As noted above, DERA places out about 1/3 of the CRP, mostly with industry.  Coupling to basic research, which is supported by the Research Councils, occurs in part through a Joint Grant process to which CRP and the RCs each subscribe 5M.  Additional connection mechanisms, for which ocean science is a good example, are discussed in Para 5c.<BR>
<I><A NAME="19">(19)</A></I>  The Framework requires DERA to each year prepare a five year Corporate Plan (submitted in September for approval by the end of November) and an annual Business plan (mid-February, approved by the start of the fiscal year, 1 April).  The Corporate plan sets out strategic objectives and means of meeting them, including projected organizational changes, rationalizations, and major investments.  The Business Plan includes Key Targets in the areas of financial performance, efficiency improvements, and quality of service. These are negotiated between the Secretary of State and the Chief Executive, announced to Parliament, and form the basis for assessment of DERAs and the Chief Executives performance.  John Mabberly indicated that MOD wanted a 1.5% rate reduction for the coming year, and they were running the busines model to evaluate 8 options to achieve it.<BR>
<I><A NAME="20">(20)</A></I> Work for other nations may be part of bi- or multi-lateral weapon system developments, or direct contracts for military or civil RDT&E.  The EC is unlikely to be a major DERA customer because as a body it supports strictly civil sector research, and is reluctant even to use the term dual use because of the military implications.  Elements of DRA participate - SRC is involved in a dozen EC projects - but "purely" for commercial applications.  The UK has a Cabinet-driven Dual Use Links program between MOD and the Department of Trade and Industry. The proposed mechanism, which provides that each participating ministry fund projects of mutual interest via their own channels but within the umbrella of an overall program, is currently at the EC for review of its IPR and competitive provisions.<BR>
<I><A NAME="21">(21)</A></I>  Op cit 5, para 4.9<BR>
<I><A NAME="22">(22)</A></I>  Paragraph 9.1 states, "Civilian staff in the DERA are MOD civil servants", but DERA operates as a "discrete body" within MOD (ie. different rules). "The Chief Executive will exercise an agreed level of authority on behalf of the Secretary of State...Pay, grading and personnel authorities are vested in the Chief Executive"; and he has permission to request additional authorities if he needs them.  His personal delegation letter addresses his "agreed level" of authority in more detail: "within the standards laid down by the Central Departments for the Civil Service as a whole and within the principles governing the management of the staff throughout the Department", the Chief Executive has authority up to specified (quite senior) grade levels for direct recruitment, complementing, fixed term appointments, within-agency postings, promotion, career development, discipline, pay flexibilities, training, and recruitment/redundancy.  John Chisholm noted that these rules and more importantly the basic civil service standards provide plenty of flexibility for him to accomplish his objectives<BR>
 <I><A NAME="23">(23)</A></I> DRA plans to spend 10M/year for each of the next two years to get its age distribution right.<BR>
<I><A NAME="24">(24)</A></I>  A triannual retrospective review process is used to evaluate the quality of research and teaching, and funding allocations are based on the ratings.  The many interesting aspects of UK university system and this rating process are beyond the scope of this paper.  The key point here is that there is a dual support system for university research, from the Research Councils and the Funding Councils.<BR>
<I><A NAME="25">(25)</A></I>  The 6 RCs are Biotechnology and Biological Sciences, Economic and Social, Engineering and Physical Sciences, Medical, Natural Environment, and Particle Physics and Astronomy.  As distinct from the others, PPARC is devoted almost exclusively to basic science. The major reason to separate it from EPSRC is its reliance on major international facilities (e.g. CERN), and the need to manage international subscriptions to them within the science budget without adversely impacting small science.  In addition to maintaining their PSREs, RCs offer four types of grants: 1)"Responsive-mode", aimed at developing and maintaining underlying capacity in areas of strategic importance. Only universities and academic analogues are eligible. 2) Strategic grants to support specific research aims, open to universities, RE and Ministry PSREs, and non-profits (essentially everyone but industry); 3) LINK grants for pre-competitive collaborative research in specific areas between the public and private sector with 50-50 shared funding; and 4) Contract, for development of technology and software and for information collection, open at market price to all comers.<BR>
<I><A NAME="26">(26)</A></I> "Realizing our Potential: A Strategy for Science, Engineering and Technology", Presented to Parliament by the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster by Command of her Majesty, May 1993<BR>
<I><A NAME="27">(27)</A></I>  After publication of and in consonance with the policy White Paper, OST was transferred to the Department of Trade and Industry.  It has two major sections.  One is responsible under the Director General of Research Councils for the RC function.  The other, directed by Mrs Helen Williams who hosted our visit. Is the Transdepartmental Science and Technology Group.  As its name suggests, it is responsible for coordination among the ministries, and with the RCs and industry.<BR>
