<I><A NAME="36">(36)</A></I>  Ibid.  The Prior Options Process: "It is Government policy to provide only those fundctions which are both necessary and best carried out in the public sector. Prior options reviews involve a rigorous test of whether the function is required at all, and whether there is scope for privatising, contracting out (which could include market testing), merging bodies or transferring work between them.  Research establishments which are executive agencies or non-departmental public bodies are already subject to prior options reviews carried out by their sponsoring Departments"<BR>
<I><A NAME="37">(37)</A></I>  Prof John Woods who headed the Marine and Atmospheric Directorate was particularly influential, in part because of the concern of the Government and the Prime Minister with "Green" issues.  Prof Woods is credited with the government's decision to build SOC.<BR>
<I><A NAME="38">(38)</A></I>  Sea Mammal Research Unit at U St Andrews; Unit of Aquatic Biology, Stirling U; Unit of Comparative Plant Ecology, U Sheffield; Centre for Population Biology, Imperial College; Environmental Systems Science Centre, U Reading; Atmospheric Chemistry Modelling Support Unit, U Cambridge; Joint Centre for Mesoscale Meteorology, U Reading; Centre for Global Atmospheric Modelling, U Reading.<BR>
<I><A NAME="39">(39)</A></I> Characteristics of the atmosphere; Data from satellites; Dynamics of the earth; Evolution, biodiversity and ecological roles; Fluid flow through rocks and soil; Global biogeochemical cycles; Impacts of environmental change and stress; Oceans, atmospheres and ice - linked models; Past environmental change; and Population change and persistence.<BR>
<I><A NAME="40">(40)</A></I> Industry-environment interaction; environmental evaluation; land and soil; urban environments; prediction of extreme atmospheric events; mechanisms of climate change; fluid dynamics in natural resource management; coastal zone modeling and management; structure and properties of the earth's subsurface; use of natural processes and materials; sustainable use of marine resources; ocean circulation; remore data acquisition; social and human health impacts of environmental change; and management of freshwater resources.<BR>
<I><A NAME="41">(41)</A></I> Earth Observation, Earth Sciences, Freshwater Sciences, Marine & Atmospheric Sciences, and Terrestrial Sciences<BR>
<I><A NAME="42">(42)</A></I> SOC is more fully described in Ocean Atmospheric and Space Science and Technology Newsletter #1, 19 July 1996, Lcdr John Joseph; accessible on the Edison House Homepage under ONREUR Newsletters, http://www.ehis.navy.mil/, or from jjoseph@onreur.navy.mil<BR>
<I><A NAME="43">(43)</A></I> NERC and University rates are about +1.4 at full economic costs.  DERA still is around +1.7.  So the issue for the PSRCs is less one of cost than of quality and value.  In addition, there is more attention to "Green" issues in Europe than in the US, and SOC can be viewed as a major government commitment to the environment.<BR>
<I><A NAME="44">(44)</A></I> The other two are Dunstaffnage Marine Lab (50 staff) and Plymouth Marine Lab (150 staff).<BR>
<I><A NAME="45">(45)</A></I>  An example given was St. Thomas Head.  The site is manned by three people.  It has a 40 tide and a flat bottom making it easy to emplace and remove items to be tested underwater.<BR>
<I><A NAME="46">(46)</A></I> The Chief Executive has been delegated the full financial authority delegated to MOD by the Treasury (and can subdelegate); this is up to 30M for capital projects.<P>

