<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>CO/TD Newsletter #10</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>25 October 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #10<BR>
NATO Science Programme</H3>

<I>Keywords: S&T Funding; NATO; Cooperation Partners; Environmental Security</I><P>

Contents:
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Description
<LI>Discussion
<LI>Contacts
<LI>Feedback
</OL>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
This report basically is a reminder about NATO research funding. Much of our DoD audience may have heard about but not thought much about this programme, since it is on the civilian vice military side of the NATO house, with little connection to DRGs/AGARD (except cross-briefings).  The NATO Science Programme has a nearly 40 year distinguished history of broad based support of inter-Alliance collaborative research.  Its major mechanisms are senior teaching seminars (ASIs) and visits between collaborators.   More recently, it has established priority areas (and several additional mechanisms) for research collaboration with Cooperation Partners (CPs; essentially FWP/FSU nations).  All projects are open to application from any Alliance researcher (including those in federal labs - thus this note); the inter-Alliance programs are hotly competitive, but there are ample opportunities for support of high quality projects with CPs, especially in "S&T Policy".  The program soon will receive scrutiny for NATO relevance, and would benefit from new projects of high alliance impact.  US DoD and DoD-affiliated applicants should keep the US Mission to NATO aware of their interests.<P>

<B>2.  Description</B><P>

"In addition to its well known political and military dimensions, NATO has a "Third Dimension" which seeks to encourage interaction between peoples, to consider some of the challenges facing our modern society and to foster development of S&T.  The NATO Science Programme is a major component of the Third Dimension." (NATO Scientific Affairs Division brochure).  This programme is funded at about $30M/year, approximately 1/3 of NATOs non-military expenditures. <P>

The Programmes support of international scientific cooperation among Alliance members  ("Inter-Alliance") covers virtually any aspect of S&T of interest to member nations.  The principal mechanisms for such support are Advanced Study Institutes (ASIs, intensive high-level teaching meetings), and Collaborative Research Grants (for reciprocal visits of one to four weeks for one or two members of a collaborating team).  NATO also offers Science Fellowships (Basic, Advanced, Senior and Senior Guest, depending on the standing of the participant) for study and research in other NATO nations.  See the NATO Science Programme home page at http://www.nato.int/science for further information.  Virtually anyone from an alliance nation can apply for such support, and the program is typically oversubscribed, with success rates typical of NIH and NSF (20-30% max.).<P>

Within this general category of Inter-Alliance support there is a special Science for Stability program targeted at Greece, Portugal, and Turkey.  It is designed to enhance their S&T capacity through demonstration projects co-funded by the Programme and the participants. Examples include a waste management project in Athens, and several Black Sea programmes that have stemmed from a demo project with Turkey to evaluate fisheries resources. <P>

NATO also has identified a set of five Priority Areas for S&T efforts that involve collaboration between Alliance scientists and their colleagues from Cooperation Partners (CP; all former signatories of the Warsaw Treaty, and the derivative states of the FSU) .  In addition to ASIs and Collaborative Research Grants, projects with CP participants in these areas (primarily but not exclusively) can receive support for Advanced Research Workshops (ARWs, planning meetings to critically assess current knowledge, identify research directions, and promote international working relationships), Expert Visits (consultation be high level specialists), and Linkage Grants (reciprocal short visits for four or five members of research teams over periods of a year or two).  CP-nation scientists are also eligible for limited Science Fellowships for study or research in a NATO country.<P>

The 5 Priority Areas for projects with Cooperation Partners were selected for their relevance to the public perception of NATO. They are:  <BR>
1) Environmental Security (cleanup of the cold war military despoilment legacy), <BR>
2) Disarmament Technology (S&T issues arising from NBC and conventional weapon disarmament and nonproliferation treaties and conventions, and reapplication of skills), <BR>
3) High Technology (which had been nurtured by Defense establishments; the issue now is reapplication.  Topics include IT, biotech, and non-nuclear energy), <BR>
4) S&T Policy (especially laws and regulations supporting the research framework, e.g. IPR, marketing, innovation, tech transfer), and <BR>
5) Computer Networking (at grass roots).  <BR>
Applications for support for programs with Cooperation Partners must originate from an Alliance source; and the funds will be granted to, and managed by, that source (this is an acknowledged weakness; it is difficult to properly transfer funds to participants in some of the CP nations, and this places the responsibility in the hands of scientists who are usually not experienced in such matters).  The success rate for proposals to these programs is much higher than for inter-Alliance ones.  Again, proposals can be submitted by anyone, in government or out, given that they have an appropriate Cooperation Partner co-PI.  The Scientific Affairs Division indicated it is particularly interested in increasing the number of quality proposals that provide advice, exchange, and research in the area of S&T policy, IPR, technology transfer, career mobility, and similar topics.<P>

The programme, and its management by the Science Affairs Division (staff of 20 with 6 scientists.  The Assistant Secretary General for many years has been Jean Marie Cadiou; the Deputy is Paul C. Rambaut) is overseen by two subcommittees of the North Atlantic Council.  This can cause some confusion.  The first is straightforward: the NATO Science Committee, comprised of one representative from each of the 16 NATO nations, has primary oversight responsibility.  It meets yearly to review the nature and quality of the efforts, and determine priorities.  The US representative is Bill Brinkman of AT&T labs; he receives his US policy guidance, including input from the US Mission to NATO, the State Departments Bureau of Oceans, Environment, and Scientific Affairs (OES).  <P>

The second oversight group is the Committee on Challenges of the Modern Society (CCMS), established in 1969 to give the alliance a "social dimension".  Its current major thrust is environmental security, and this is one of the Priority Areas for NATO Science Programme funding to cooperation partners; hence the possibility for confusion.  As opposed to Science Programme funded projects which focus on new knowledge, however, CCMS projects are designed to provide advice to, and interactions between, governments.  The main CCMS mechanism is Pilot Projects, for which funding is totally provided by the participating nations.  The Science Affairs Division arranges for the nations to participate and helps coordinate and oversee the projects under the NATO umbrella (it also supports and arranges seminars and conferences and sponsors a Clearing House for Environmental Technical Information on the web at http://echs.ida.org/).  An exemplary pilot project is "Cross-Border Environmental Problems Emanating from Defense-Related Installations and Activities Phase II", which is concerned with radioactive material dumped in the Kara and Barents Seas, and radioactive runoff from the FSU. Principals are Norway, Germany and the US, and there are several associate nations.  Like the Science Committee, CCMS has one representative from each of the 16 NATO nations.  The US representative is Wendy Grieder of EPA; her State Department guidance is staffed by EUR, with heavy input from DoD. <P>

<B>3.  Discussion</B><P>

DoD lab scientists involvement with NATO research has traditionally been through DRG panels or AGARD.  There has also been considerable DoD interest in CCMS projects.  However, DoD scientists are welcome to compete for participation in virtually all aspects of the NATO science Programme.  Members of this staff and our Air Force and Army colleagues at EOARD and ERO have attended several ARIs and ARWs and found them to very informative and of extremely high quality.  We have also helped cosponsor some or augment attendance to them, through our visit and conference support projects.<P>

Like many S&T programs, the magnitude and relevance of NATOs efforts are being questioned by senior management in view of tighter budgets and other pressing priorities. The programme likely will be subjected to scrutiny over the next year or two, with particular attention to the special Priority Areas for Cooperation Partners.  There are three ways in which interested DoD researchers may be able to help: the first is to participate, either as a PI or as a member of a project team.  The second is to help colleagues from CPs identify NATO collaborators and prepare good proposals (i.e. spread the work and help make connections).  The third is for those who have experience with the programme to let the US Mission to NATO know your views, good or bad; and to inform them of particular interests so that these can be passed to the US representative.  To keep them from being inundated, we at ONREur would be happy to act as a collator of comments.<P>

<B>4.  Contacts</B><P>

The best source of information, including instructions on how to apply and downloadable application forms, is the Programmes web site.  It also has an up to date list of upcoming ASIs and ARWs:<BR>
for NATO in general: <A HREF="http://www.nato.int">http://www.nato.int</A><BR>
Science Programme:  <A HREF="http://www.nato.int/science">http://www.nato.int/science</A><BR>
CCMSs Clearing House: <A HREF="http://echs.ida.org/">http://echs.ida.org/</A><P>

The Science Affairs Division also operates an email distribution service called NATOSCI.  It distributes calendar updates, their newsletter, press releases, etc. To subscribe, send the following message: <BR>
SUBSCRIBE NATOSCI <firstname> <lastname> to: <BR>
<A HREF="mailto:listserv@cc1.kuleuven.ac.be">listserv@cc1.kuleuven.ac.be</A><P>

Address:<BR>
NATO Science Affairs Division<BR>
NATO<BR>
B-1110 Brussels, Belgium<BR>
Telephone +32-2-707-4111, fax -4232<P>

CCMS Secretariat at same address and fax, phone -4846 or 4850<P>

US Mission to NATO, NATO, B-1110 Brussels :<BR>
+32-2-726-4580<BR>
Our contact for the Science Programme was:<BR>
Mary Tracy x3145<P>

<B>5.  Feedback</B><P>

The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology development in European countries.  In order to better meet your needs, our staff are very much interested in knowing of your specific science and technology interests.  Please let us know what they are.<BR>
Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of, who may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail addresses to us and we will add them to the distribution list.
ONR Europe is on the World Wide Web.  Our home page contains information about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters.  Find us at: http://www.ehis.navy.mil/<P><HR><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P>

For further general information please contact :<BR>
      Craig Dorman<BR>
      Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
      Tel:           44 171 514 4508<BR>
      Fax:           44 171 514 4924<BR>
      E-mail :      <A HREF="mailto:cdorman@onreur.navy.mil">cdorman@onreur.navy.mil</A><BR>
      International Address:<BR>
