<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>CO/TD Newsletter #11</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>26 December 1996<BR>
Command Activities<BR>
Commanding Officer and Technical Director<P>

Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
CO/TD Newsletter #11<BR>
R&D in Turkey: Overview and Focus on METU and Oceanography</H3>

<I>Keywords: Turkey; S&T Policy; Oceanography; Black Sea</I><P>

<B>Contents:
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Background
<LI>Defense Cooperation & Turkish Military Procurement
<LI>TUBITAK and Turkish S&T
<LI>Middle East Technical University
<LI>METU Institute of Marine Sciences, Erdemli
<LI>Comments and Assessment
<LI>Contacts and Further Information
<LI>Feedback
</OL></B>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
Turkey is a staunch ally, a strong NATO partner, and a "Big Emerging Market" with a rapidly growing but volatile economy.  The Turkish Defense Forces remain a highly respected and powerful force for Turkeys secular western orientation.  The Turkish General Staff recognizes the multiple security threats in the region, and plans continued modernization accompanied by expansion of indigenous defense industries through co-production and technology transfer.  Turkey historically has invested very little in R&D, but both defense and commercial trends indicate a significant upswing in the near future; and the Universities, exemplified by the Middle East Technical University (METU), are ready and eager to respond.  One area where Turkey does have a significant world-class scientific capability is oceanography.  Turkish ocean scientists play a leading role in physical and biogeochemical studies of the Eastern Mediterranean and the Black Sea.  The Black Sea is of interest intrinsically, geopolitically, and as a model for both environmental processes and approaches to the remediation of a badly damaged ecosystem.  This newsletter briefly treats this set of issues: defense cooperation and modernization, the Turkish S&T Research Council, METU and its structure for innovation, and METUs Institute of Marine Sciences and the status and plans for Black Sea studies.<P>


<B>2.  Background.</B><BR>
The main purpose of this trip was to get an update on Black Sea oceanographic programs from Prof. Umit Unluata, Director of the Middle East Technical Universitys (METU) Institute of Marine Sciences (IMS); he is a prime mover of many of them.  I also visited the main METU campus in Ankara, the Turkish Science and Technology Research Council (TUBITAK), and the US Embassy (ODC, Commercial Attach, Ambassador).  This report provides my general impressions based on these discussions and on personal observations (mostly for my own benefit, to capture the key points I derived from the visit - corrections from those more knowledgeable would be appreciated), plus a brief description of Black Sea programs and IMS-METU contributions.<P>

Turkey has for decades been a steadfast ally and NATO partner, "at the crossroads of almost every issue of importance to the United States on the Eurasian continent" <I>(1)</I>.  "Turkey remains the southeastern bulwark of NATO.  It is a focal  point for our interests in the Balkans, the Caucasus, the Middle East, and Central Asia.  Turkey has contributed to peace-keeping efforts in Bosnia, continues to maintain the sanctions against Iraq at great economic cost, and fully supports the Middle East Peace Process. " <I>(2)</I><P>

Turkey also is a land of stark contrasts and major challenges.  Compared to my last visit some 20 years ago, the major cities are much more westernized.  The goods available (and the marketing) in the upscale shops of Ankara equal those of western Europe; in some malls I would have been hard pressed to even identify what country I was in had it not been for the language.  Significant sectors of industry flourish.  Roads are vastly improved.  Even the secondary and tertiary roads in Anatolia were in excellent repair, and the major routes are heavily utilized by international truck traffic.  The south-central part of the country through which we drove was intensively cultivated (except in the high mountains), and the cropland and vineyards were well maintained (except for parts of the southern coast where unfinished tourist hotels have encroached on the farmland).  However the smaller villages were if anything in worse shape, and the non-urban population appeared at least no better off than in the mid 70s. Villages appear to have been stuck in a time warp.  Turkey remains rightly famous for the bargain prices of its time-intensive hand made products, and for the value for dollar of tourism, rugs, silver, onyx and similar goods.  Labor is still extremely cheap, and salaries even for the professionals (especially for academics) low. <P>

The contrasts are starting to show at the national level.  While Turkey remains the only secular democracy in a Muslim country, the Islamic factions are on the rise.  The Islamic Welfare (Rafeh) party received the largest vote in the last national election (>20%, nearly double their showing in 91); and Turkish colleagues commented on the active, and apparently successful, political organizing efforts of fundamentalist groups.  The contrasts in clothing (mens and womens), transport (Mercedez-Benz vs donkeys) and womens roles and positions between city and village are patently obvious.  So are the greatly uneven distribution of wealth, the fact that large parts of the economy operate beyond the effective reach of the government, and the centuries of difference in life styles between segments of the population.  <P>

Turkeys challenges are economic, societal, and military. GNP has grown an average of 4.8% per year since 1981 (the highest in OECD).  The private sector is dynamic and expanding rapidly.  Some sectors, e.g. construction, compete effectively world wide. However the legal infrastructure for open participation in the global market (thus foreign investment) is not fully in place.  Inflation remains very high, and growth is extremely variable (e.g., the financial crisis and -6% GNP change in 94).  Overall the economy is dangerously volatile, due in large part to the continued dominance, and poor performance, of the public sector.  Further structural reform (e.g. continued privatization, revamping of the social security system, and expansion of the tax base to sectors which now operate outside it) is known to be needed, but seems politically impossible to implement.  Turkeys economy also has been adversely affected by its support of the sanctions on Iraq, exacerbating the structural deficiencies (oil started to flow again just as we left).  Turkey this year entered the EU Common Market, and the US views Turkey as one of the 10 "Big Emerging Markets"; but lacking significant government reforms that could accelerate growth and temper volatility, short term uncertainties are likely to outweigh long term potential for years to come, and the contrasts are likely to widen, further abetting the rise of fundamentalism and other symptoms of discontent.<P>

While most other NATO nations are decreasing their defense budgets in the continued wake of the Cold War, Turkey perceives its threats and military commitments to be increasing <I>(3)</I>.  Its relationships with nearly all of its neighbors are troubled (e.g. water rights with Syria, the PKK and Kurdish issues with Iraq and Iran, historic enmity with Greece exacerbated by Greek posturing re 12nm limits in the Aegean, not to mention terrorism and drugs internally).  Turkey highly values its  international ties, especially through NATO and the UN, and participates heavily in peacekeeping and other coalition operations.  <P>

Given its perception of the environment in its part of the world, the defense budget -- at 3.5% of GNP and 12% of the federal budget <I>(4)</I> -- will remain high.  Turkey also has reason to question the dependability of its traditional partners.  Special NATO support (e.g. Science for Stability) is drawing to a close as NATO moves to expand to the newly independent states and PfP; Turkey is unlikely to gain desired entry into the EU; and the US - long a staunch ally - has drastically reduced its support since 93 and failed to follow through on commitments <I>(5)</I> <P>

Societally, in addition to the contrasts already mentioned, Turkey continues to grapple with human rights, gender, and environmental issues.  Interestingly, one of the hot topics during my visit was Turkeys new ban on smoking in public buildings.  This seemed to be cause for much comment (where it was known) but little perceptible change.<P>

<B>3. Defense Cooperation & Turkish Military Procurement</B><BR>
The US Office of Defense Cooperation in Ankara is headed by a two star flag officer (currently Air Force MG Huot), and has a staff of about 40 US.  Although part of the rationale for the offices size and the ODCs rank is historical, the ODC serves as the US point of contact for the Turkish General Staff (TGS; still very powerful and prestigious), and assists with coordination of ongoing operations from and within Turkey <I>(6)</I>.  This summary, however, will focus on the military equipment aspects of cooperation (largely via the Defense Cooperation in Armaments, DCA, Program), and Turkish plans for defense modernization.  It is based on discussions with and papers provided by representatives of the ODC and Embassy; I was unable to visit the Turkish Army Brigadier General who heads the R&D section in the Ministry of National Defense because we did not receive TGS clearance in time.<P>

The DCA program is based on the Defense and Economic Cooperation Agreement of March 80, and its Supplementary Agreement No.2, Defense Industrial Cooperation.  "Since 1946, the US has transferred over $13.6 billion in security assistance to Turkey: $7.6 billion as grants, $6.0 billion as loans.  Assistance since 1962 totals over $11 billion, about evenly split between grants and loans.  Total since 1990: $1.4 billion as grants, $1.7 billion in loans" <I>(7)</I>.  Since 1994, however, all security assistance (@ $1.2B) has been in the form of Foreign Military Financing (FMF) treasury rate loans.  <P>

In parallel with the shift in the financial nature of the assistance from grants to preferential to treasury rate loans, the nature of cooperation has shifted from FMS sales and transfer of excess defense articles, to co-production, technology transfer, R&D cooperation, and multi-national initiatives.  Maj Bill Belknap, USA, of the DCA office stated that the keys to cooperation these days are co-production, technology transfer, and sovereignty, i.e. indigenous versions of all equipment.  As a matter of policy offsets are required, and the Turkish defense procurement establishment actively seeks Turkish industry participation in any overseas procurement.  Turkey wants to become not only its own major defense supplier, but also an arms exporter.<P>

In spite of the current strain on DCA efforts due to the delay in transfer of high profile weapons systems (Frigates, Cobras, Mk 82 bombs, Seahawk helos), there are a significant number of ongoing major Security Assistance/DCA programs (F-16 co-production and maintenance, KC-135 Tanker lease, AMRAAM, Pedestal Mounted Stinger, attack helos, ATACMs, Harpoon and Seasparrow missiles, Knox Class FF maintenance, and Frigate modernization and production).  However the US is by no means Turkeys only partner; e.g., Germany has the prime for the MAKO Frigate construction program (and will likely retain this role for the Frigate 2000 program; although as opposed to MAKO where 4 are being built in each country, all of the new class will be constructed at The Turkish Navys shipyard at Goljuk), and Israel recently won a major contract for F4 upgrades.  More significantly, all current US-Turkey co-production programs end by 1999.  The DCA is thus rightly concerned that US firms win new procurement contracts in order for us to remain engaged with this long term ally.  The two biggest near-term prospects are tank modernization (Army is pushing for M1A2 co-production; the Turkish RFI is expected in early 97 for a program worth about $4-5B) and the next generation Frigate (Frigate 2000; $2.4B for a build of 4-6 ships.  US industry was not sent the RFI for the prime - presumably because of the current transfer impasse - but has received the RFI for major subsystems, and Lockheed-Martin is pushing the SPY-1F for the air defense system, the expected major competition being TNOs AFAR).<P>

There are both security and financial reasons for maintaining an active US role in Turkish defense procurements.  The first - interoperability, stability, etc.-- rests on Turkeys pivotal role and geographic position, in the region and in coalition operations.  The second is the size and content of the TGSs long range modernization plan, which calls for expenditures of some $67B between 1995 and 2004, and projects a total spend of about $150B over the next 25-30 years <I>(8)</I>.   At issue however are the ability of Turkey to accomodate TGSs appetite, the lack of priority accorded Turkey as US and NATO focus on PfP as the centerpiece for engagement and stability, and the Ambassadors understandable concern that the US ODC and defense industry not get out ahead of the USs political willingness to commit to major defense sales in the region.<P>

Turkeys process and organization for defense procurement are interesting.  First, they seem do little direct internal R&D outside of defense industry (there are no MND or TGS labs; and the TUBITAK Defense R&D lab only has about 110 people), but rather rely on partners innovations and then competitively procure the most modern available products, insisting on technology transfer.  They are however astute regarding the status of major defense developments abroad, carefully study the options and competitive possibilities before issuing RFIs, and pursue focused product-development R&D in defense industries.<P>

The TGS and the MND each report directly to the Prime Minister (of the two, the TGS is by far the more powerful).  Tactical and technical requirements are developed by the TGS (or by the office of the CNO for the much smaller Navy; presumably similar for the Air Force. There seems to be little effort to generate Joint requirements) and levied on MND.  Based on these, one of several materiel commands (each service has one for spares and services; the "Foreign Procurement Department" of MND does in-country end-item acquisition; and the Undersecretariat for Defense Industry [SSM] handles overseas procurements and joint ventures - more on them below) conducts the actual procurement, starting with an analysis of the investment required and the appropriate course of action.  <P>

After the resulting "investment project" is approved by the Defense Industry Executive Committee (PM, Chief of the TGS, and MND), project groups from the procurement command (often with heavy TGS participation) undertake the actual acquisition.  For non-indigenous items, SSM conducts procurements in two separate stages: "solicitations are released to perspective international and national contractors who present their articles for testing and demonstration and then present their technical, national industrial cooperation and economic proposals (<I>read offsets, co-production, etc</I>). Once a contractor is selected, then negotiations begin for a firm fixed contract <I>(9)</I>".  This is a nicely efficient fly-before-buy approach, and gives SSM and the TGS an in-depth look at what is available as well as the deals they are likely to get, before they ever commit to a tough cost negotiation.<P>

MNDs SSM (Savunma Sanayii Mustesarligi), according to its brochure, was established in 1985 as a "separate legal entity" with the responsibility for "developing the national defense industry, while meeting the modern defense needs of the Turkish Armed Forces".  Its defense industry projects are financed through the Defense Industry Support Fund, "established independently outside the national budget framework", which is funded from shares of various taxes (income, corporate, fuel), surcharges on tobacco and alcohol, and lotteries.  It thus has both a business development and a procurement role; its brochure includes among its missions: conduct feasibility studies and economic evaluations, negotiate and sign contracts and manage production and quality control, develop new capabilities of the national defense industry and integrate and support current capabilities, promote export-oriented joint ventures and bring in state-of-the art technologies, plan weapon system production in both state and private enterprises, and coordinate offsets and exports.  One of its roles is to provide financial support and credits to Turkish defense industries.<P>

The Turkish defense industries themselves have an interesting mix of public and private ownership.  The public side is represented by the "Turkish Armed Forces Foundation", formed from individual Service Foundations in 1987.  The Foundations President is the Minister of National Defense, and its other Trustees are the Deputy Chief of the TGS, the Undersecretary of MND, and the head of SSM.  It is tax exempt, and can accept "donations", for which it awards documents and medals.  From its income it makes allotments to armed forces projects.  <P>

The Turkish Armed Forces Foundation operates as a holding company, and owns both real property (including a marina and a resort [naval training] facility on the Mediterranean), and shares (from less than 1% to almost 98%) of the major Turkish defense industries.  It also is the sole operator of the biannual IDEF, or Defense Industry and Civil Aviation Fairs.  It has a wide range of partnering and shareholding relationships in 17 main industries (and some 25 others): e.g., 97.9% ownership of Havelsan (electronics depot level maintenance and repair), 95 % of Aspilsan (batteries etc), 15% of Roketsan (a government-private consortium that started with the production of the propulsion system for the European Stinger Co-production Program), 86% of Aselsan (radios, C3, EW) and 45% ownership of Tusash (SSM owns the other 55%) that in turn owns 49% of TAI - the airframe and assembly facility for the F-16 co-production (other partners include Lockheed, Turkey 42%, GE International 7%, and the Turkish Armed Forces Foundation directly 1.9%) - and is a co-owner with the Foundation and GE of TEI, which manufactures aircraft engines and components.  <P>

The bottom line of all of this is that directly, and through SSM and the Foundation, the TGS has pretty complete control over Turkish defense requirements, procurement procedures, and production.  The TGS clearly believes that to meet the increase in threats it is necessary to develop defense industrial capacity; and that "defense industries, inherent to their structure, would need continuous direction, support, and control by the state" <I>(10)</I>.  And if, as they clearly intend, most of the $150B of expected procurement is kept in-country through tech transfer and co-production, and marketing of defense products is a state policy, over the next decade or two Turkey will switch from being a "Big Emerging Market" to a Big Arms Supplier.<P>

Finally, associated with this push to develop industrial capacity and expand foreign sales is a recognition of the need to develop an internal R&D capability, steered and coordinated by the central procurement organization.  Although there is already some R&D within the defense industries, the TGS recognizes that Turkeys intellectual potential and scientific expertise resides in the universities.  It intends to establish closer collaboration between them and the state and industry.  Thus it can be expected that the TGS and MND will support an increase in R&D (currently and historically between 0.3 and 0.5% of GNP).  Direct military funding of university research also is expected (and eagerly awaited by the researchers) for the first time in 1997.<P>

<B>4.  TUBITAK and Turkish S&T</B><BR>
The Turkish Scientific and Technical Research Council, TUBITAK, is Turkeys "exclusive body" for S&T <I>(11)</I>.  The President of TUBITAK reports directly to the Prime Minister; he also chairs the Scientific Advisory Board which is the key S&T decision-making body.  Tubitaks annual budget is on the order of $50M, indicative of the traditional neglect of S&T by the federal government.  TUBITAK however attempts to leverage regional and international programs to supplement the meager national support.  TUBITAK has seven roles:<P>

(1) Its primary function is as a funding agency, like NSF.  It has competitive research grant programs in eight disciplines, each with an Executive Director. <BR>
(2) It owns and operates three Research Institutes: BILTEN at METU (described in more detail below), one in the defense sector (about 110 employees; NFI), and the Marmara Research Center (MRC) near Istanbul.  MRC has a staff of about 800 (half S&T, half support) and a broad scope of work.  TUBITAK has subjected it to two recent external reviews, and hired consultants from TNO to help turn it into a contract research organization.  As a result, contract research has increased from about 5% to 40%, about the level desired. <BR>
(3) TUBITAK is a human resource development organization: It manages a program of scholarships for elite students, starting at the high school level and extending through postgraduate work, to develop the most promising S&T talent.<BR>
(4) It is the national Science Policy Institute, reporting through a Secretariat (President and Vice President of TUBITAK) to the Supreme Council of S&T, chaired by the PM and comprised of all the Ministers.  VP Prof Pak noted that this was both good and bad - it has all the necessary horsepower, but on the other hand S&T is seldom an important enough issue to get their attention.  Although by law it is supposed to convene yearly, it last met early in 1993.  In the interim the Secretariat deals with dynamic policy issues.<BR>
(5) Its is an Informatics Institute: it implemented the national Internet connection (through METU), which has now been privatized (and seems to work well, from the connectivity that I observed - though it doesnt yet serve the villages, etc).  TUBITAK will now focus on enhancing the academic network.<BR>
(6) It is an International institute - responsible for bilateral and international (e.g. with NATO, EC, and the UN) S&T interactions and agreements.<BR>
(7) It supports Industrial R&D; R&D is the only permissible industrial incentive (GATT), so TUBITAK encourages and supports market oriented research.<P>

<B>5.  Middle East Technical University (METU; Orta Dogu Teknik Universitesi)</B><BR>
METU is located on the SW outskirts of Ankara, 7km from city center, on a huge tract of land (thousands of hectares) granted when it was founded in 1956.  It is a state-funded, public University with nearly 20K students (95% Turkish), 680 faculty members, 250 instructors and almost 900 research associates.  METU has 38 Departments in 5 undergraduate Faculties (Engineering, Arts and Sciences, Architecture, Economic and Administrative Sciences and Education) and a "Technical High School", plus Graduate Schools of Natural and Applied Sciences, Social Sciences, and Marine Sciences.<P>

The University has deliberately maintained an international perspective.  Some 10% of the faculty is international, and about the same number of the Turkish faculty is abroad annually as researchers or visiting professors.  About 70% of full-time faculty have studied abroad, and most have their advanced degrees from foreign universities and retain close ties with their international colleagues.<P>

Having celebrated its 40th anniversary this year, METU boasts mostly modern facilities with excellent computer and Internet access throughout.  Classes are all taught in English (students have up to two years to qualify in a preparatory English school). Most students are admitted by a National Competitive Exam (as in Ireland: the top students get first choice of school and Department; METU draws the upper 1%).<P>

My host was Prof. Dr. Cemal Saydam, an oceanographer who recently returned from IMS to set up an environmental remote sensing program in Ankara. In addition to visiting his new satellite down-link lab and discussing his research (currently the impact of Saharan dust on plankton blooms, and a NATO SfS project on snowfall and water volumes in the Euphtretes catchment basin) I met with the METU President and both Vice Presidents, and toured the Computer Center, Mechanical Engineering CAD/CAM and Robotics Center, and the EE Department and TUBITAK BILTEN.  The Computer and CAD/CAM Centers were both modern and well equipped.  METU established, and till recently managed, Turkey's Internet connections; it still serves as the international interface for all Turkish Universities.  The campus has a fiber optic backbone to most academic and administrative units, for communications and access to the 8-node IBM SP2.  There are numerous PC and workstation rooms for teaching and research.  <P>

Similar to the Universities I have visited in western europe, METU is working to greatly expand its research program and develop closer ties with industry in support of national objectives (in its case, even in advance of stated policy).  It already has a number of mechanisms to promote and enhance its research capabilities, and is in the process of establishing the "METU-TECHnolopolis Complex", a combined science and business park, with living quarters, on 210 hectares next to the main campus.  Part of the impetus for this activity is Turkey's entry into the EU common market and the associated need for improved quality to meet the demands of the EU market; Turkey also recognizes that private industry is the key to its competitiveness and in particular to commercial penetration beyond its borders.  GATT restrictions that limit federally funded industrial incentives to R&D also will change historical Turkish patterns of industrial support and should generate additional research funds.<P>

The University obtains government research funding from four primary sources.  The first and most traditional is TUBITAK, through both competitive programs and BILTEN.  Second is the Technology Development Fund, run jointly by private industry and the State Planning Office, with assistance from the World Bank.  It has provided about $40M in support for some 60 projects over the last 3-4 years, with equivalent in-kind support from industry.  Third is the special support directly from the PM's office for issues related to defense, anticipated to begin next year.  This work will be done by university-industry consortia, and is eagerly anticipated.  METU already does some R&D for MND/TGS and is prepared to expand its role.  Fourth is international agencies.  The list of research projects I was provided showed sponsorship from NATO (Science for Stability Program and other parts of the NATO Science Programme, CCMS, and AGAARD), the UN (UNESCO, UNIDO, UDP, FAO, GEF), the EC (EUREKA, and Framework projects via collaboration with scientists from EU nations), foreign nations (Germany, UK, US - NSF, ONR and NASA), and the IAEA.  Private industry - Turkish and international (e.g. Volkswagen, Motorola) - also has started to invest in R&D at the university.  Overall there are about 600 individual research projects, with an annual budget over $25M.<P>

METU has not just recently started active solicitation of research; it has had a contract research organization and program for 30 years.  A number of private and state industries - electronics, rockets, and software - started on campus.  The University brochure lists some 20 Research Centers which report to the Departments, and another seven centers (some R&D, some educational, some support such as testing) that report to the office of the President.  To supplement this, the METU Development Foundation operates seven private companies, in areas as diverse as construction, publishing (the University Press), education (a private high school), food production and distribution, and electronics, computers, and software.  These provide supplementary employment for staff and students.  The computer center director noted that without the opportunity for such work, his staff - whose University salaries are about 1/4 of what they could earn downtown - would quickly disappear; the CAD-CAM center likewise undertakes commercial development.  In addition there are several jointly owned and operated centers and labs on campus including the Air Force-METU Development and Post-Graduate Center, the International Center for Heat and Mass Transfer, the Ministry of Energy and Petroleum Testing lab, and the Chemical Industries Assn Chemical Engineering Rsch Center.<P>

TUBITAK's Information Technologies and Electronics Research Institute (BILTEN, which was started in 1985 and now has about 120 staff) is another campus-based research organization.  Students and faculty are involved in some 15 project groups (in areas such as computer hardware and software, electronics and communications, image processing, power and control systems, GIS, multi-media products, etc. See Para. 8, Contacts, for additional information), which are primarily staffed by 65-70 full time engineers.  New groups, based around the interests of a faculty member who will serve as director of the research unit, are initially funded by TUBITAK, but are expected to attract commercial investment.  The initial goal was to achieve a 50-50 split by 2000, but this was achieved this year.  TUBITAK retains patents on inventions, but the participating industry receives a cost-free license for 5-7 years; and the BILTEN researchers receive 30% of net profits.

Overall then, much as I saw in Ireland, there already are a variety of University and state supported mechanisms by which a university faculty member or research associate can become actively involved in research, and supplement their low state salary while helping national competitiveness.  The Vice President noted that the weak point is that until now, they haven't been able to organize to take on large projects.  They are trying to develop a mechanism so that faculty from different departments can work with industry on major, multidisciplinary projects.  The President stated that his priorities for investment from the University Research Fund are information technologies, microelectronics, materials, and biotechnology.  I saw evidence of this investment in the well-equipped research and teaching labs of Asst Prof Tayfun Akin, who recently received his PhD from the University of Michigan and is actively pursuing MMIC developments with US and Belgian colleagues under both University and NATO SfS support.  Finally, as previously noted, the TECHnolopolis -- offering land and facilities conveniently close to Ankara and with tight ties to the University's intellectual, communications, and recreation resources, should provide a major boost to METU's rapidly growing research agenda.<P>

Given its high quality faculty (with their good international contacts and fluency in English) and student body, its infrastructure, the supportive policy and regulatory environment, the growing strength of Turkish private industry, and the multiple incentives for expanded government investment in R&D (both defense and civil), METU would appear to have the potential to emerge as an extremely strong international research institution within the next decade. <P>

<B>6.  METU Institute of Marine Sciences, Erdemli</B><BR>
METUs IMS (<A HREF="mailto:ims-metu@deniz.ims.metu.edu.tr">ims-metu@deniz.ims.metu.edu.tr</A>) is one of four major Turkish institutions that conduct large scale oceanographic research in contiguous waters <I>(12)</I>. It is located on a dedicated campus about 5km west of Erdemli (45 km west of Mersin), directly on the Turkish Mediterranean coast.  In addition to research facilities and administrative offices, IMS has a small marina (which accommodates its two 16m boats, although its 40m research vessel R/V BELIM is too large to conveniently use it and is homeported further to the west), and housing for faculty and students and a small number of visitors.  These facilities, combined with its library, data processing and computing center, and satellite imaging and processing center, make it an ideal location to serve as the hub of Black Sea and Eastern Mediterranean collaborative oceanography programs.  <P>

IMS was founded in 1975.  Like the rest of METU, it has maintained close ties with the international community, and in particular with US scientists interested in the Mediterranean and Black Seas.  IMS has a faculty of 20, and about the same number of graduate students; it has awarded a total of 64 MS and 18 PhD degrees.  Its primary strengths are physical and chemical oceanography, marine biogeochemistry, and fisheries biology. It also has a small G&G program.  Recent major research activities include circulation dynamics and biogeochemistry of the Levantine Basin, the Sea of Marmara and the Black Sea, dynamical/climatological and forecasting models for these seas, Black Sea ecology and productivity, dynamics and environmental health of the Turkish Straits, and the influence of atmospheric pollutants.  The research program is supported by a combination of TUBITAK, State Planning Organization, and other Turkish Ministry and state industry grants, and funding from UN (IOC, GEF), NATO, IAEA, the US and the British Council for international Black Sea and Eastern Mediterranean projects.  The Director is Prof. Umit Unluata, a physical oceanographer, whom I first met when we were both in graduate school at MIT in the early 1970s.<P>

I had the opportunity to discuss in some depth the current research projects of three of the physical oceanographers.  Sukru Besiktepe, the Assistant Director, is supervising the development of the multinational Black Sea Data Base under the NATO TU-Black Sea Project (see below), and modifying and applying the Harvard Ocean Prediction System models for the Black Sea.  Temel Oguz is continuing his work on the wind and thermohaline driven circulation of the Black Sea, and with US colleagues is developing a physical-biochemical model of plankton productivity and nitrogen cycling in the Black Sea.  Emin *zsoy is working on exchange and mixing processes in the Turkish Straits (some of the field work for this effort was conducted from the SACLANTCTR ship R/V ALLIANCE), and topographic effects on coastal and shelf circulation.  All are excellent scientists who work closely with top US and European researchers.<P>

As noted above, however, my primary interest was in getting an update on the Black Sea Programs, where Turkey has a leading role.  The Black Sea is interesting intrinsically, as a test basin for physical and ecosystem model intercomparisons, and as an example of regional cooperation among very diverse nations facing common environmental challenges.  The Black Seas surface area is about 4.2 x 10<sup>5</sup> km<sup>2</sup>; it has a wide shelf (depth <100) on the western and northwestern margins, and steep slopes with very complex topography along the rest, leading to the flat 2200 m deep abyssal plain of the central basin.  It is almost totally landlocked; the only external exchange is via two-layer flow through the shallow and narrow (and strategically important) Bosporous.  Its overall mass budget and hydrochemical structure depend critically on its hydrologic balance; precipitation and runoff exceed evaporation by about 300 km3, balanced by the net surface outflux through the Bosporous.  The geography and hydrology drive a complex flow, the major features being two sub-basin scale cyclonic gyres, and quasi-permanent anticyclonic eddies along the margins, driven by interactions of the rim current with topography and baroclinic instabilities. Because of its restricted exchange the Black Sea is anoxic in the 87% of its volume below the permanent pycnocline; below 100-200m, the waters are rich in hydrogen sulfide and devoid of life except for bacteria.<P>

Even beyond its unique natural characteristics, the Black Sea is of international concern because of the severity of the anthropogenic degradation of its environment and resources.  Its major freshwater sources are the Danube, Dnester, and Dneper, which drain much of Europe, southern Russia and the Ukraine (and Chernobyl). Huge inputs of heavily mineralized nutrients have caused widespread eutrophication of much of its euphotic zone; heavy metals, pesticides, and hydrocarbons have led to rapid rise of toxicity, especially on the northwestern shelf.  Symptoms of ecological collapse include loss of vast areas of seagrass, nearly total disappearance of benthos over much of the shelf, drastic reductions in plankton diversity, extreme decline of fisheries, and rapid spread of exotics such as the ctenophore Mnemiopsis (introduced in ballast water), which feeds on fish eggs, larvae, and copepods, and has further exacerbated the loss of fish and shellfish stocks.  The Black Sea has been viewed by many as a harbinger of the disasters that could befall other semi-enclosed seas such as the Mediterranean and Baltic, in the absence of drastic remediative measures <I>(13</I>). <P>

My interest in the Black Sea began at WHOI, where following a major 1988 cruise to the area by the R/V Knorr, I was able to provide some funding for the then-Director of WHOIs Coastal Research Center, Dr. David Aubrey, to participate in a 1990 joint coastal wave experiment in Bulgaria.  The participants in that experiment all encouraged Dr Aubrey and WHOI to help establish a joint program in the Black Sea. The series of planning meetings that ensued culminated in the first major oceanographic collaboration among all the Black Sea riparian states, a five ship joint hydrographic cruise entitled HydroBlack 91.  At the end of the cruise, Dr. Aubrey chaired an international workshop attended by some 130 participants and other interested scientists in Varna, Bulgaria.  At that meeting the participants agreed to continue their joint efforts, and established the "Cooperative Marine Science Program for the Black Sea", or CoMSBlack, with a Steering and Executive Committees comprising representatives of each of the riparian nations (Bulgaria, Romania, Turkey, Ukraine, Russia, and Georgia), the U.S., and the IOC (ex-officio).  Dr Aubrey served as its first Chairman.  (See Para 8, Contacts, for a list of key participants in this and other Black Sea programs). <P>

CoMSBlack was and remains a self-initiated, non-governmental organization of participating scientists, designed to bring together the oceanographic specialists from the region (and interested colleagues from the US and Western Europe).  Its terms of reference include coordination, where necessary, of regional scientific programs throughout the Black Sea; conduct of high quality, internationally recognized oceanographic science, communicated through open international channels; and the provision of high quality scientific input to effective and integrated management of the area and remediation of its ecological problems <I>(14)</I>.  The basic program objectives were to provide the underpinning knowledge of the physical and biochemical conditions and processes, and the associated models, that would be needed for wise management decisions; and to develop a cadre of collaborative scientists from around the area who would be willing to work together at sea, share their data, and employ common procedures.<P>

CoMSBlack has, in my opinion, been a great success. During its first five years it coordinated three types of programs: general surveys, process studies, and research into coastal seas circulation dynamics and fluxes. It coordinated at least one major multi-ship cruise per year, produced nearly a hundred publications, and perhaps most importantly developed a team of 60 to 100 scientists from around the region who collaborate well, have inter-calibrated their instruments, use common manuals and procedures, and share their data and models.  It was officially adopted as a programme of the International Oceanographic Commission of UNESCO in 1993.  The participants agreed this year to continue it for a second 5-year phase, under the joint chairmanship of Dr Unluata and Dr. Valery Eremeev, Director of the Marine Hydrophysical Institute, Sevastopol.  In its 2nd phase, it will focus more on shelf and nearshore processes.<P>

CoMSBlack was never actually funded as a major "program" per se.  Rather, participants obtained support for their activities under its aegis from a variety of sources including NSF and ONR, IOC, private foundations, private individuals, and the local national governments.  National governments have provided the vast majority of support for the data collection and analysis, routed through their Institutions.  CoMSBlack has served as the facilitator for these efforts, and because of its non-governmental nature has avoided politics.  It also has served as the catalyst for at least some of the other multi-national programs in the area, and as a result aspects of its objectives are resfected in them.<P>

One of these is the NATO Science for Stability Programme, "Ecosystem modeling as a management tool for the Black Sea: A regional programme of multi-institutional cooperation" (TU - BLACK SEA; funded by a combination of $1.5M NATO-SfS and Turkeys State Planning Organization, with in-kind participation from collaborating institutions <I>(15)</I>), approved in July 1993 and scheduled to conclude in 1997.  Prof Unluata is Project Director.  TU - BLACK SEA is a follow-on to an earlier Turkish SfS fisheries assessment project; it focuses on lower trophic levels and incorporates CoMSBlack's multinational collaborative approach.  To quote the Projects brochure, "the purpose of the TU - BLACK SEA project is to develop and implement ecosystem models as a management tool for improving the health of the Black Sea and also to help build the capacity within the riparian countries for high quality oceanographic measurement and analysis capabilities for carrying out long term monitoring of the Black Sea following the completion of the project."  <P>

TU- BLACK SEA has three major objectives: to establish a common database management system in all Black Sea countries for oceanographic and environmental data (the data base now has over 125 MB of data; several Russian scientists were at Erdemli during my visit, entering historical data from their research); to provide cross training and standard equipment to participating Black Sea countries (e.g., computers, CTDs, rosette samplers, plankton nets, autoanalyzers; and a satellite image processing system installed at METU IMS); and to understand and develop models of ecosystem dynamics of the lower trophic levels of the Black Sea, as affected by physical processes and anthropogenic changes.  Overall this work is progressing well, the key results being the shared data base, the improved national capabilities and common standards, and the models themselves.<P>

In parallel with the increase in scientific activity in the early 90s, the governments of the region reacted to the food, economic, and health impacts of the Black Seas environmental crisis.  In April 1992, the Black Sea governments signed the Bucharest Convention on the Protection of the Black Sea against Pollution, which provided an international framework for management and established common legal tools for controlling marine pollution.  Its three protocols address control of land-based sources of pollution, dumping of waste, and joint action in case of accidents.  To oversee its implementation, the Convention established the Black Sea Commission, headquartered in Instanbul (Istanbul Commission), whose responsibilities include developing criteria for preventing, controlling, and reducing pollution.  <P>

The governments also decided to establish a common environmental policy for the Black Sea.  This was adopted in Odessa in April 1993.  The Odessa Declaration, based largely on the 1992 Rio Summits Agenda for the 21st Century, calls for common environmental quality objectives and coordinated national plans for reduction of inputs of harmful substances, especially nutrients; a ban on radioactive dumping;, implementation of MARPOL special area requirements; development of contingency plans; establishment of national activity centers; an assessment of inputs of harmful materials; and a monitoring system.<P>

In order to help them implement this policy, the Black Sea Nations requested assistance from the Global Environmental Facility (a $2B trust fund managed by the World Bank, UNEP, and UNDP to assist developing countries in protecting the global environment and in transferring environmentally benign technologies).  GEF allocated $9.3M (with collateral funding from the EU, the Netherlands, France, Austria, Canada and Japan) to establish a three year (1993-95) Black Sea Environmental Programme (BSEP) <I>(16)</I>. At the first meeting of its steering committee in Varna in June 1993, the GEF partners, Black Sea Governments and NGO representatives defined a three year workplan oriented toward the development of a strategic action plan.  Three BSEP objectives were defined: increase the capacity of the Black Sea countries to assess and manage the environment; support the development and implementation of new environmental policies and laws; and facilitate the preparation of sound environmental objectives.<P>

Like the scientists, one of the first tasks for the GEF partners was to establish a collaborative infrastructure among both governmental and NGO participants.  The GEF created a Programme Coordinating Unit (PCU) in Istanbul.  A system of Working Parties was established, based upon regional "Activity Centers" hosted by each of the nations and linked to the others through National Focal Points.  The entire network of some 40 institutions has been linked by email.  In addition to helping coordinate the efforts of the Working Parties to develop national and regional thematic reports, the BSEP PCU has focused on capacity building for assessment and management, increasing public awareness, and mobilizing the scientific community through workshops, meetings and training sessions.  BSEP also contributed over $1.5M to re-equipping the pollution monitoring network.  And because Black Sea remediation requires reduction of riverine hazardous material input, GEF has conducted parallel programs for the Danube Basin and the Danube Delta <I>(17)</I>.<P>

Because the BSEP was designed to last only three years, most of the PCUs effort has been directed toward developing a sustainable management capability in the region.  The key product to this end was a Transboundary Diagnostic Analysis (TDA), published by the PCU in June 1996.  The TDA has three levels: a single table listing the seven major perceived problems of environmental degradation, their root causes and action areas <I>(18)</I>; an overview of the specific actions proposed for each identified issue; and detailed information on the "action areas" and related issues.  The TDA in turn served as the basis for a Strategic Action Plan for the Rehabilitation of the Black Sea as called for in the Bucharest Convention.  This Plan was adopted by the Environmental Ministers of the Black Sea nations at their meeting in Istanbul 30-31 October.  The Action Plan specifies Policy Actions in each of the TDAs Action Areas, directs each nation to prepare supporting national Strategic Action Plans, and charges the Istanbul Commission with its implementation.  To do so the Commission will take over and manage the infrastructure developed by BSEP, including maintaining the electronic communication system and GIS and acting as a data clearing house, and will establish Advisory Groups based on the BSEP Working Parties. <P>

In addition to its TDA and other reports, the PCU has published a <I>Black Sea Bibliography 1974-1994</I>, and - with support from the Netherlands, the electronic <I>Black Sea Information System</I>, a set of meta-level directories of organizations, scientists, projects, and environmental data sets.  See paragraph 8 for further information on these and other relevant publications.<P>

Between the oceanographic and the environmental programmes, therefore, the Black Sea has become one of the more intensively studied bodies of water, and the scientific, governmental, and NGO communities of the area have developed effective collaborations.  While effective management hasnt yet taken hold and the "crisis" is by no means over, deterioration has slowed, fisheries have started to recover, the national governments are attuned to the need for continued action, and a workable infrastructure for assessment and action is in place.  As the GEF and the NATO SfS programs draw to a close, at issue is whats next?<P>

Planning for major new international oceanographic programmes is proceeding along two main technical paths.  The first is additional process studies, focused on understanding the nitrate cycle and new production, which must be comprehended by the ecosystem models being developed in TU-BLACK SEA; the second is a transition to "operational oceanography", long term monitoring and forecasting. <P>

Programatically, the following multinational actions (at least) are underway to these ends:<P>  
a.  There was a planning meeting at the December US AGU meeting in San Francisco to discuss a "suboxic zone" study to be conducted as part of, and possibly as an extension to, TU-BLACK SEA.  METU IMS will provide R/V BILIM for a preliminary cruise for this purpose in April 1997. <BR>
b.  As noted above, the IOC adopted CoMSBlack as one of its official programmes in 1993.  ICO also has formed a Black Sea Regional Committee.  At its first session, held at Varna in September of this year, the Committee adopted two Pilot Projects.  Pilot Project 1 is "Black Sea GOOS: a Step toward Observation and Prediction Systems (STOPS)"; project coordinators are Dr. Unluata of METU IMS, and Dr. L.M.Popova of Bulgaria.  Its objectives are to implement basic elements of an operational network using available resources, to restore routine at sea observations using ships from each country, and to develop a science plan for further development.  Pilot Project 2 is "Assessment of the Sediment Flux in the Black Sea: Mechanisms of Formation, Transformation, and Dispersion and Ecological Significance", designed to study recent geologic and pollution history.  The Project coordinator is Dr. K.M.Shimkus (Russian Federation).  Each nation will conduct studies in their own waters; Turkey and the Ukraine will contribute ships for an initial 1997 cruise, and all will share data.  IOC is expected to provide funds for meetings and coordination, and will coordinate approaches to outside donors; but the scientific efforts will be supported primarily by national funds, and possibly the EC.<BR>
c.  Dr Unluata and Mr Gary Vest of the US DoDs Environmental Security office are co-directors for a proposed NATO Committee for the Challenges of Modern Society Pilot Project entitled "Review of Ongoing Black Sea Projects for the Planning of Future Activities".  This proposed 16 month effort would critically review ongoing projects and their expected results, define and plan predictive ecosystem and environmental models with forecasting capabilities that use long term systematic observations, and define and plan such a continuously operational ocean observation system. <BR>
d.  In anticipation of the advent of NATOs Science for Peace Program, the successor to SfS (that focuses on the Partnership for Peace Nations as opposed to NATOs southern tier), and for possible support under IOCs Coastal Seas Program, and Dr Unluata and colleagues will develop a science plan for the Shelf Seas of the Black Sea.<P>

Finally, as part of the transition toward a Black Sea GOOS, several of the IMS scientists expressed interest in the use of acoustics for continuous monitoring in the Black Sea. The Turks have no relevant acoustical experience, however initial conversations with a Russian acoustician indicated that Russia has conducted low frequency acoustic feasibility experiments from the Crimea, and that continuous acoustic monitoring of temperature, wave and wind conditions, and the pycnocline should be possible.  Acoustic monitoring of the Black Sea may be of interest to SACLANTCTR and possibly to the EuroGOOS program as part of a Black Sea GOOS project.<P>

<B>7.  Comments and Assessment</B><BR>
Turkish defense business is characterized by a complex set of intertwining public and private relationships, under the close overall control of the TGS.  Turkish defense industry will grow and diversify over the next decade.  There are sound economic as well as security reasons for the US to want to remain a strong player in Turkish arms developments.  <P>

Similarly, Turkish S&T - abetted by a complex set of interlocking state, commercial and University mechanisms and closely supervised by TUBITAK - can be expected to develop rapidly.  When I asked the Commercial Attach what Turkish technologies I should be interested in, he responded, "nothing jumps out...".  This wont be true in a decade, and again there are compelling reasons to pay close attention to the development of Turkeys S&T potential.<P>

There already is one area where Turkey has, and in fact has had for quite a while, an S&T capability of great interest to ONR: the oceanography of its contiguous waters.  Many of the Turkish ocean scientists have received their degrees or studied in the States, and they collaborate closely with US colleagues; and the US contingent of ocean scientists with long term interests in the region includes some of our best researchers.  Perhaps even more importantly, Turkish scientists continue to play a leadership role in collaborations with their colleagues in the other Black Sea riparian nations.  IMS Erdemli is a natural center of gravity for the 60-100 Black Sea area oceanographers who now work together; this is a regional collaboration that works well and to the benefit of all involved.  <P>

Black Sea oceanography, just like Turkish defense business and R&D, is characterized by a number of interacting arrangements - in this case among countries, between scientific institutions and their researchers, and with international organizations such as the UN, the EU, and NATO.  It has transboundary political, scientific, and ecological dimensions.  International Black Sea oceanographic collaboration is important for the security of the region, in all aspects of the term - environmental, economic, and military.  Only modest external support is required to maintain the momentum that has been built in the 90s; but with the completion of the GEF BSEP, and with the termination of NATOs Science for Stability Programme, other mechanisms must be found if the transition to operational oceanography, essential to continued efforts to understand and manage the ecosystem, is to be effected.  In my opinion it is very much in the interests of the US, the EU, and NATO help the very capable local team continue and expand its effective collaboration. <P>

