<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsletter #4</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<H2>Newsletter #4--High Power Lasers Benefit Naval Welding</H2>
<P>

	
	The document shown below  appeared on the Office of Naval Research Europe "Reading Board" on June 16, 1996.<P><HR><P>
Howard Bunch, Associate Director<BR>
Manufacturing and Ship Production<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
PSC 802, Box 39<BR>
FPO AE 09499-0700<BR>
Tel: +44-171-514-4942<BR>
FAX: +44-171-723-6359<BR>
e-mail: hbunch@onreur.navy.mil<P><HR><P>


High-power lasers benefit naval welding<BR>
Source:  Bristol Opto and Laser Europe in English may 96 pp 17, 19, 21<BR>
Text: [article by John Bell: " High-power lasers weld ship-shape
structures"]  [FBIS transcribed text]<P>

<DD> At the end of May, Europe's shipbuilders and their suppliers will meet to discuss the results of a collaborative research project to exploit the benefits of laser welding in shipyards. They want "dramatic reductions" in the cost of reworking steel components that have been distorted by the heat of conventional welding techniques.   Reworking these parts, which can be tens of metres long, involves thousands of man-hours. Shipbuilders estimate that removing distortions in 6 to 8 mm thick plates and modules accounts for up to 33 percent of the labour costs of a passenger ship or fast naval craft, for example. This figure falls to 25 percent with large tankers and commercial carriers, which contain significant numbers of parts made from steel sheet of up to 20 mm thick.<BR>
  
<DD>The industry's motivation for researching laser welding is the need to compete with far eastern shipyards, especially in Korea and Japan. Laser welding will improve quality, and reduce costs and construction time, plus encourage automation and mechanization.  First, the shipbuilders have to satisfy Europe's classification  societies that laser welds are as good as conventional welds a  meeting safety and performance criteria. The societies - such as  Lloyd's Register, Bureau Veritas, Rina in Italy, Norway's DNV and  Germanischer Lloyd - are employed by ship owners or the insurance  industry. They are closely involved in guiding and evaluating the  3.5million pound programme and are drafting guidelines based on its results.<BR>

  <DD> The meeting in Glasgow will review the programme, which was managed by TWI, Cambridge UK.  The work involved 11 European Research institutions, which in turn represented 41 industrial organizations. Its results are still commercially confidential shipbuilders have cut steel sheet of up to about 20 mm thick with lasers since 1992. None has yet adopted laser welding, although the technique is well established for land vehicles and structures. For example, it is already known that low levels of carbon, sulphur, silicon and phosphorus with a high level of manganese in the steel reduces the chance of laser welds cracking. However, the programme has shown that carbon dioxide lasers in the 8 to 15 KW range are suited to joining heavy steel sheet and components for marine applications.<BR>

  <DD> "We should see the first ship built with the help of laser welding within two years," said Hellmut Wilckens, managing director of FDS, a shipbuilding research group in Hamburg that took part in the programme. "there are more European shipyards than you might guess looking at the process. A good number are at an advanced stage, but there is nothing to stop the Koreans and Japanese doing the same."<BR>

   <DD>Another partner, Odense steel shipyard in Denmark, is likely to be one of the first to benefit from the work. It is investing 5 million pounds in a five-axis gantry for the laser cutting and welding of components of up to 4 x 16 m. The company will take delivery of the gantry, and its 15 kw co2 source built by the German company held, early next year.<BR>

   <DD>Odense's executive vice-president, Torben Anderson, told OLE: "The reason for constructing such a large-scale test plant is to find out what labour costs we can save in reworking distorted components. We can't take the whole thing, but the potential is there to take the lion's share of the costs."<BR>

  <DD> Anderson says that it should be possible to automate the welding of about 265 km or 40 percent of the joints in a 340 m long tanker of 300,000 tonnes dead weight. The widths of these welds depends on the application: t-beams and bulb profiles used to stiffen transverse plates need welds of 10 to 15 mm thick, while butt welds of plates are typically 18 to 25 mm deep.<BR>

  <DD> Odense calculates that laser welding joints could cost 50 percent of conventional techniques. The figures include consumables - such as filler wires and gases, as well as labour costs - but exclude investment outlay. Laser systems are two to three times the price of conventional welding systems, which is why Odense will evaluate both cutting and joining on a single system.<BR>

   <DD>Plasma cutting shapes a steel plate of up to 3 x 16 m to an accuracy of plus or minus 2 to 3 mm over 10 m. Laser cutting is precise to plus or minus 0.5 mm, an accuracy that leads to considerable time and cost savings in a 340 m long ship.<BR>

   <DD>Laser welding delivers 10 percent or less of the energy of conventional methods to the plate surrounding a joint. For example, submerged arc welding (saw) delivers 8 to 12 kj/mm when butt welding 25 mm thick sheet; arc welding involves a heat input of 1 to 2 kj/mm in producing t-beams.<BR>

   <DD>Andersen says that Odense will train about ten technicians and engineers to run its new laser equipment. They will probably start by assembling superstructures and in-board components where the savings are likely to be greatest. Welding hull plates is already fairly highly automated, he says.<BR>

  <DD>Lasers butt weld metal sheets, normally with their ends cut at right angles to the main faces, by melting some of the material to make the joint. Other methods form the weld by melting additional filler wires to fill the joint formed by the bevelled ends of the two sheets. As the wires melt and build up the weld, each one adds to the rotational and linear distortions that appear about the joint.<BR>

   <DD>The programme managed by TWI had to demonstrate to the classification societies that a laser weld can be as good as an arc weld - in terms of its resistance to cracking, porosity, and corrosion, as well as its hardness and ductility, for example- as far as shipbuilding is concerned. Therefore it had to define the limits of the three main factors that control the quality and properties of a laser weld: material composition, welding procedure and weld shape.  The performance of arc welds, for example, depends principally on the procedure. They are generally capable of coping with wide variations in the quality of plate materials.   Most of the material in a laser weld comes from the base metal, even if a filler wire is added to the process. The composition of the steel in addition to joint geometry and beam travel speed also affect its quality and properties.<BR>

   <DD>The co-operative programme defined both the limits of the steel composition and the extremes of the laser processes to produce welds that satisfy the classification societies.
   the partners are not publishing details, for example about acceptable levels of non-ferrous elements in the steel. However, they claim that, within the set limits, the programme produced laser welds that show no cracks when tested by ultrasonics or radiography.<BR>

   <DD>Laser welding of ship components will also meet the standards set in the proposed european standard pr en 1419 for porosity in welds.  The draft allows pores of a maximum diameter of 3 mm or 40 percent  of the weld depth, whichever is the smaller, over no more than 2 percent of the weld's area for an intermediate quality weld suitable for shipbuilding.<BR>

   <DD>Researchers adopted standard hardness tests to assess the relatively narrow laser welds, but they can generally achieve hardness figures below 380 hardness vickers. They also say that the joint strengths are at least equivalent to the strength of the plate. (most of the work was carried out on 240 and 360 n/mm (squared) carbon manganese steels.) They achieve laser welds that show 22 percent elongation before failure, equivalent to the required ductility of arc welds.<BR>

   <DD>Now that the programme has developed an approved welding procedure on specified materials, the next step is to establish courses to train workers. Further research might look at extending the limits of the process or allowing cheaper steels of different grades.<P>

   The Future<P>

   <DD>Work at TWI on the new procedure accelerated the development of a new dual-beam welding technique for thick steels. It is also prompting discussion on the development of CO2 and ND:YAG sources for shipyards.<BR>

   <DD>Shipyards have been attracted to laser processing over the past decade as robust lasers with powers in excess of 10 kw have become available. One problem with these high-power sources is that they generate a large molten pool that tends to be distorted by gravity before it has time to cool and harden.<BR>

  <DD> TWI is currently experimenting with tandem-head welding with 8 kw and 10 kw beams that make a joint in a single pass. The heads of the two sources are arranged to deliver their beams within a short distance of each other. One laser welds the bottom of the weld, while the second completes the joint immediately afterwards.<BR>

   <DD> As shipbuilders turn more and more to laser welding, they will  generate an increasing demand for smaller, more manoeuvrable sources  as well as more powerful ones. "Manufacturers will need to do more  research into the efficiency of their lasers to reduce the size of the source and to improve stability," said Hellmut Wilckens of the FDS research group in Hamburg.  Smaller sources would be able to produce welds with tight radii in restricted spaces. They would also encourage robotics and automation.  For example, the us navy is developing portable 1.8, 2.4 and 3 kw ND:YAG sources for welding, cladding and cutting. <BR>

  <DD>One advantage of these tools is that optical fibres can deliver their beams into restricted spaces. Another is that fibres can multiplex ND:YAG sources to deliver a single powerful beam.<BR>

  <DD>The US Navy is experimenting with nd:yag sources to cut up submarine hulls, weld titanium alloys, build structural stiffeners and buttdoin pipes. Its 3 kw ND:YAG has achieved some success in making underwater welds and clads with filler wire.<BR>

   <DD>However, ND:YAG sources may prove controversial in the shipyards of Europe. "The wavelength of an ND:YAG is a tenth of the wavelength of a CO2 source, and the shorter wavelength is dangerous to the eye," said Wilckens. "but I think we may see pulsed diode lasers in shipbuilding within five years."<P>

<DD>This report may contain copyrighted material.  Copying and dissemination is prohibited without permission of the copyright owners. <P><HR><P><A HREF = "http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR newsletters</A> 
</BODY>

