<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Newsletter #5</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY>
<H2>Newsletter #5 - Report on the 7th International Conference on Marine Engineering Systems, "Safe and Efficent Ships", 13-14 June 1996</H2>
<P><HR><P>
 <DD>REPORT ON THE  7TH INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE
ON MARINE ENGINEERING SYSTEMS, "SAFE AND EFFICIENT SHIPS",
13-14 JUNE, 1996.   Sponsored by The Institute of Marine Engineers,
and hosted by Norwegian University of Science and Technology.
 The Conference was attended by Mr. Zbigniew Karaszewski, Division
Chief, National Maritime Center, U.S. Coast Guard.  The summaries
 of the papers were prepared for distribution by Office of Naval
Research Europe.<P>

 <CENTER>For more information on the conference, and copies of the proceedings, contact:</CENTER><P>

<CENTER>THE INSTITUTE OF MARINE ENGINEERS<BR>
The Memorial Building<BR>
76 Mark Lane<BR>
London EC3R 7JN<BR>
Telephone: +44 (0)171 481 8493   Fax: +44 (0)171 488 1854</CENTER><P>
<P><HR><P>
<CENTER>PAPER ABSTRACTS:</CENTER><P>
"PROPULSION MACHINERY FOR LARGE
SHIPS" by T Henriksson, Msc <I>W&auml;rtsil&auml; Diesel
Oy, Finland</I><P>

<DD> As a response to new challenges in the shipping environment, new propulsion machinery solutions are presented. Propulsion plant availability can increase freight
income and reduce down-time.  Exhaust gas emissions an be reduced without increasing the building costs.  The building costs of tankers can be reduced and the cargo capacity of containerships can be increased with optimal machinery concepts.  The recommended
solution for large containerships and for VLCCs is twin medium-speed  engines and a single cp propeller (alternatively twin-screw).
 For VLCCs, large primary shaft generators and electrical cargo
pumps are recommended.<P>

"SAFE AND EFFICIENT SHIPS- FRIENDLY
TO THE ENVIRONMENT" by #R Kvamsdal, MSc and &#134;Prof Dr
Ing M F&oslash;rde, MSc,<I>*Kv&aelig;rner as and &#134;Norwegian
Institute of Science and Technology, Norway</I><P>

<DD>Safer and more efficient ships, friendly
to the enviornment, can only be a reality after a full and balanced
improvement of all relevant factors.  One should also, in addition
to focusing on the operational phase, give attention to environmental
loads from the building as well as the scrapping processes.  There
should also be a balance between safe arrangments, systems and
components on one side, and human dependent operations, the latter
improved by operator-assisted information (ED) systems.<P>

"RISK ANALYSES FOR <I>SOLITAIRE</I>"  by Ir A M van Wijngaarden, MIMarE, <I>Allseas Engineering bv, The Netherlands</I></FONT><P>

<DD><I>Solitaire</I>  will be the world's
largest pipelay vessel.  The unit is being converted from a bulk
carrier hull and will operate fully on dynamic positioning.  During
design and construction, a systematic review of safety essential
systems is carried out by means of risk analyses for evacuation
routes, ballast system and DP system.  Fire and explosion studies
are carried out for the accommodation, helideck, engine rooms,
gas storage facilities and the gas distribution systems throughout
the pipeline production spaces.  The methodology adopted for the
various risk analyses is described.  Two studies are highlighted
in particular: the hazard and operability (HAZOP) study on fire
and explosion for the gas storage facilities and the mustering
flow simulations for the evacuation analysis.  Conclusions and
experiences from the risk analyses are presented.<P>

"PREDICTING BEARING METAL CONDITION
OF DIESEL ENGINE BY USED OIL ANALYSIS"  by T Hashimoto,
H Aoki and N Baba <I>Nippon Kaiji Kyokai (ClassNK), Japan</I><P>

<DD> The bearing metals of a marine diesel
engine are usually disassembled every four to five years as part
of a special survey.  However, this disassembling and assembling
work requires a significant amount of manpower and time.  Moreover,
it is also dangerous.  The classification society to which the
authors belong has dedicated considerable time and effort to examining
whether used oil analysis can be used as an alternative to carrying
out the aforementioned periodic survey.  This paper reports on
the correlation between results obtained from used oil analysis
vy ferrography and the inspection results obtained during special
surveys from two vessels ove a continuous eight year period. 
As a result, the authors believe that periodic used oil analyses
can be effective as one form of condition monitoring based survey.<P>

"OPTIMISING THE COMPLETE SYSTEM
USING SIMULATION: THE CASE OF PREDICTING ENGINE EMISSIONS DURING
SHIP MANOEUVRING" by Prof N P Kyrtatos, BSc (Hons), PhD,
G Kapetanis, Dipl-Eng, G Korakis, Dipl-Eng and I Koumbarelis,
Dipl-Eng <I>National Technical University of Athens, Greece</I><P> 

<DD>A comprehensive simulation model able
to predict the interaction of a marine propulsion diesel with
the propellor and the ship, was used to predict engine emissions
and other performance characteristics during ship manoeuvres.
 To enable this, a detailed NOx emissions prediction code was
developed and was appended to the main simulation model.  The
predictions of the overall model were validated using instantaneous
emission measurements data from full scale shipboard tests.  The
flexibility of the simulation model is further demonstrated by
predicting the effect of emission reduction techniques applied
on the propulsion engine during ship sailing.<P>

"ISM CODE: IS IT DIFFERENT FROM AN OFFSHORE
SAFETY CASE?" by  *E J Mavromatakis, FIMarE, MASCE, MTEE, &#134;D
Colyvas, MTEE and &#135;E Nicolaou, BEng (Hons)<I>*Ergon Consultants
Ltd, &#134;TARANG Consulting Engineers and Trust Shipping Enterprises
Ltd, Greece</I><P>

<DD>By July 1 1998 any passenger ship,
oil tanker, chemical tanker, gas carrier or bulk carrier greater
than 500 gt will not be allowed to operate if the company which
operates the ship or the ship itself does not comply with the
requirements of the International Safety Management (ISM) code.
 At the heart of the ISM code is the Safety Management System
(SMS).  This paper illustrates how experience gained from the
development of safety cases for offshore installations and the
application of quality assurance (QA) principles have been utilised
by the authors to develop the SMS manual in compliance with the
ISM code requirements.<P>

"SHIP QUALITY INFORMATION SYSTEMS"
 by *Prof R G Bea, MSE, PE, &#134;Dr Ing R Schulte-Strathaus and
*M Dry, MSE, <I>*University of California at Berkeley, USA and
&#134;Germanischer Lloyd, Germany</I><P>

<DD>Information and communications are
key elements in development of a ship safety and quality management
system.  A Ship Quality Information System (SQIS) addresses the
life cycle aspects of a ship including design, construction, maintenance,
and operations.  SQIS provides timely and meaningful information
to help achieve desirable quality in ship operations for shipowners
and operators, shipyards, classification societies, insurance
groups, and regulatory agencies.  A SQIS takes full advantage
of modern computation, communications, and information technologies.
 A SQIS takes full advantage of the principles of re-engineering
to focus on 'processes' instead of 'tasks', elimination of unnecessary
tasks and procedures, and formation of process teams.  Substantial
improvements in ship design, construction, maintenance, and operation
efficiencies are the primary objective of a SQIS.  Safer ships
and higher reliability organisations to design, construct, maintain,
and operate ships are a natural by-product of such a development.
 This paper summarises progress that has been achieved during
the past five years in definition of an approach for development
of a comprehensive SQIS.  The components that have been addressed
include those of ship structure, equipment, operations, and personnel.
 Several prototypes have been developed to illustrate how components
of SQIS could be implemented.  One of these components, a Ship
Structural Integrity Information System (SSIIS) is discussed in
this paper.  Experience of several ship operators indicates that
implementation of these components and organisational changes
can result in dramatic decreases in costs and increases in profitability.
<P>
"INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY IN SHIP
OPERATION: A NORWEGIAN RESEARCH PROGRAMME"  by E Rensvik,
MsC, <I>MARINTEK, Norway</I><P>

 <DD>The international focus on safety
and pollution prevention is becoming sharper, which gives more
stringent demands on the maritime transportation industry.  The
Norwegian initiative for improved competitiveness through development
of new operating concepts and information systems in shipping
companies in close co-operation with equipment suppliers, classification
societies and authorities has been organised in a joint research
programme (1994-97).  Information technology will, through the
projects, be applied to a more efficient performance reporting,
maintenance optimisation, training systems and new classification
concepts.  The results will be installed and demonstrated onboard
two ships in a demonstrator project for a Norwegian company.<P>

"IMPROVED ONBOARD TRAINING USING
COMPUTER-BASED TRAINING MODULES" by *Dr Ing T E Berg, MSc
and &#134;R Skotg&aring;rd<I>*MARINTEK and &#134;Red Band AS,
Norway</I><P>

<DD>This paper summarises part of the
work done in the R&amp;D project, 'Training, Recruitment, Selection'.
 The project is part of the Research Council of Norway's programme,
<I>Information Technology in Ship Operation</I>.  As a part of
the training project, a baseline for an improved training system
has been developed.  The training system's content will be designed
to meet the company's recruitment and training policy.  The system
uses available assessment tools to define the training needs of
each crew member.  Training activities will mainly be given as
part of cyclic training/retraining actions which will be based
on the functional approach given in the 1995 STCW Convention.
 The paper gives a summary of project activities related to development
and introduction of computer-based training (CBT) modules.  The
methodology used by a ship management company and when implementing
the CBT system for onboard training is described.  The final part
of the paper highlights the experience gained from the first operational
period of the CBT system onboard two Suez max tankers.<P>

"FUEL QUALITY RELATED TO UNSEAWORTHINESS" by R F Thomas, CEng, FIMarE, <I>Fuel Oil Bunker Analysis and
Advisory Service (FOBAS), UK</I><P>

<DD>The paper examines various aspects
of fuel quality based on the parameters given in the international
marine fuel standards.  The effects of deviation from these standards
are considered on engine performance, which under certain conditions
can affect the seaworthiness of the vessel.<P>

"THE ROLE OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY
FOR REDUCTION OF MAINTENANCE COST"  by *Prof Dr Ing M
Rasmussen and &#134;H Moen, Msc, <I>*Norwegian University of Science
and Technology and &#134;MARINTEK, Norway</I><P>

<DD>The Reliability Centred Maintenance
concept is an aid to increasing quality in maintenance, ie to
ensure high safety standards and optimise plant availability while
controlling maintenance cost.  The work described in this paper
focuses on the use of this concept and on information technology
in a continuous improvement of the maintenance activities.  Criticality
assessment, reliability and availability analysis are performed
to pinpoint important functions and equipment.  The initial maintenance
policy is based on these analyses, and continuously improved by
data reported from operation.<P>

"TORSIONAL VIBRATION ANALYSIS
AS A TOOL FOR CONDITION MONITORING OF PISTON ENGINES BY ON-LINE
CYLINDER TORQUE ESTIMATION" by*C A J Tromp, &#134;J M Spoelstra
and &#134;Prof J Klein-Woud,<I>*Royal Netherlands Naval College
and &#134;Delft University of Technology, The Netherlands</I><P>

<DD>Torsional vibration contains information
on the operation of all cylinders and thus may have a high potential
for condition monitoring of diesel engines.  Existing methods,
which convert flywheel speed measurements into the shaft torque,
require that the flexibility of the crankshaft can be ignored.
 A new method has been developed for rotor systems with flexible
crankshafts, which converts the vibration at only one arbitrary
chosen measuring point into the cylinder torques.  The amount
of information in torsional vibrations is limited by the structural
dynamics, which act as a filter.  This causes restraints for the
number of cylinders that can be monitored.  It is expected that
in practice the maximum will be about six to eight.<P>

"PMS ON SHIPS: DREAM OR REALITY?"
by G Soncini, <I>SpecTec Srl, Italy</I><P>

<DD> The ISM Code requests the implementation
of planned maintenance onboard vessels.  While the advantages
should be clear to all parties, some of the difficulties related
with installing a PMS, especially a computerised one, are less
known.  Knowledge of the enemy is the first step to his defeat,
so the paper focuses on the main problems and some of the relevant
solutions.  The SpecTec Group has supplied more than 2000 CPMS
onboard ships.<P>

"THE SOCP'S RAM DATABASE/SHIPNET:
A CROSS FUNCTIONAL NETWORK FOR SHIP LIFE CYCLE COST AND SAFETY
DECISION SUPPORT"  by *B Inozu, BS, MSE, PhD, &#134;Z J
Karaszewski, AD, BE and &#135;P G Schaedel, MSE<I>*University
of New Orleans, &#134;United States Coast Guard and Energy Transportation
Corporation, USA</I><P>

<DD> Ship operators are constantly looking
for ways of improving ship safety, reliability and life cycle
cost-effectiveness to face the ever increasing competition of
the global shipping industry.  Vessel operators worldwide are
implementing reliability centered maintenance programs to maintain
and improve vessel reliability with less resources.  In the mean
time, regulatory agencies are embracing risk-based technologies
to improve ship safety with reduced regulatory burden.  In order
to develop reliability characteristics of marine machinery and
to apply risk-based technologies for regulatory reform, a cooperative
structure is desirable, where the failure data is obtained from
many sources operating similar equipment.  This allows statistically
relevant data to be analysed and conclusions drawn on the reliability
of equipment much sooner than would normally be possible.  This
paper describes a cooperative effort at reliability data collection
and sharing being undertaken by the Ship Operations Cooperative
Program (SOCP) to improve total life cycle cost-effectiveness
and safety of ships globally.  Interface between the new Marine
Safety Evaluation Program (MSTEP) of the United States Coast Guard
and SOCP's reliability, availability and maintainability (RAM)
database is also summarised.<P>

"NAUTICUS - A LIFE CYCLE APPROACH
TO SHIP SAFETY" by T Sollie, MSc, M L&oslash;vstad, MSc,
E Rishoff, MSc and S A Brustad, Msc, <I>Det Norske Veritas, Norway</I><P>

<DD>Det Norske Veritas (DNV) has launched
a major development project which is set to provide the company
with its future information system for ship classification.  Being
one of the major classification societies, DNV has its focus on
safety, and Nauticus is set to support safety related decision-making
in a life cycle approach.  It is aimed at improved knowledge transfer
throughout the classification process, using a life cycle ship
product model to ease the recording and retrieval of information.
 The DNV engineers and surveyors shall have at hand an up-to-date
and complete set of information for any DNV classed ship, anywhere
at any time.  The first member of the Nauticus family is the comprehensive
ship modelling and analysis package called Nauticus Hull.  A similar
module on machinery and systems, as well as modules for following
up the ship during construction and operation, are under development.
 This paper gives an introduction to DNV's strategic thinking
behind the Nauticus project, and presents in some detail the first
software module and its implementation in the classification concept.<P>

"SAFETY, AVAILABILITY AND MAINTENANCE
IMPROVEMENTS IN THE SHIPPING COMMUNITY"  by  L Nyh, Msc
<I>SYSTECON AB, Sweden</I><P>

<DD>This paper discusses the objectives,
findings and conclusions of a recently completed prestudy funded
by and with the participation of all the major concerned parties
in the Swedish shipping community.  The prestudy is based on the
assumption that there is a substantial potential in terms of higher
safety, higher availability and lower costs to be gained from
introducing and implementing modern and established concepts for
systems and logistics engineering and for life cycle costing in
the design and operation of ships and ships' systems.  Although
the prestudy has not managed to determine the expected potentials
in quantitative terms, the general conclusion is that by implementing
established methods and techniques for analyses, design and maintenance
of ships and ships' systems, there are potential profits to be
gained for the various actors in the shipping community.  To get
significant improvements, especially regarding safety and life
cycle costs, however, a change of paradigm is probably required
in the shipping community.  The concepts, the methods, techniques
and tools are available and in use, among others, in the aviation
industry and in the power industry.
