<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Newsletter #6</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>WORKSHOP ON ELECTRONIC COMMUNICATIONS
FOR THE SHIPBUILDING INDUSTRY AND ITS VENDOR BASE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>LONDON, OCTOBER 28, 1996<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>I.  INTRODUCTION<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
This report  describes a workshop, held in London, England, on
October 28, 1996, relating to electronic communications within
the maritime industry, with special focus on the shipbuilding
sector and its vendor base.   The workshop was sponsored by Office
of Naval Research Europe.  
<P>
One of the major changes occurring within the shipbuilding industry
 is in the area of electronic communications.  An emplaced  electronic
network is seen as one of the mechanisms  to significantly improve
competitiveness of the shipbuilding enterprise.  It provides the
opportunity to have instantaneous information transfer, which
supports the concepts of shortened production times, of flexible
manufacturing systems and the mass customization of  products.<I>(1)</I>
    In recognition of this benefit, shipyards, and their vendors
around the world are actively involved in developing and emplacing
electronic communication systems.  National efforts are occurring
in the United States, in Europe,  and in the Pacific Rim.  Individual
shipyards are aggressively evaluating the concepts, and some are
actively into the implementation phase.  Some of the vendor associations
are supporting the implementation initiatives of their members.
 And, most of the classification societies are evaluating expanded
electronic communication networks linking them to the shipyards
and to the vendor base.
<P>
The American efforts have revealed issues indicating a need to
examine benefits of international cooperation  on some of the
issues.  First, and foremost, was the question of whether there
is an interest in other regions of the world to have cooperation.
 And, if there is an interest, the question then becomes one of
determining those areas where cooperation would be most beneficial.
 Finally,  there would be the selection of the most effective
method[s] of cooperation. 
<P>
The American investigations have also revealed issues relating
to information security, information formatting, functional relationships,
and organizational and/or institutional barriers.  <P><HR><P>
<I>(1) For an expamded discussion of these, and other, advanced manufacturing concepts refer to <U>Manufacturing Systems: Foundation of World-Class Prectice</U>, National Academy of Engineering, 1992.</I>
<P><HR><P>
Because of the complexity of the issues, the variety of stakeholders,
and the international nature of the questions raised, it was deemed
appropriate to have the workshop, and possibly others, to focus
on issues related to the dynamics of electronic communications
in the shipbuilding industry and its vendor base.   The workshop's
objectives were three-fold:<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I>describe experiences and activities relative to electronic
communications appropriate to shipbuilding and its vendor base;
</I>
<LI><I>share thoughts relative to lessons learned, and problem
areas; and</I>
<LI><I>suggest ideas on how to implement electronic communications
systems that will be internationally responsive.</I>
</OL>

<P>
The list of attendees and the agenda for the meeting are shown
in Appendix A.  <BR>

<P>
As the agenda in  Appendix A indicates,  the workshop was organized
into three sessions.  In the first session there were presentations
by representatives from each of the three major world regions
represented at the meeting:  United States, Europe, and Japan.
  Each presentation was an overview of the major efforts underway
in that region to effect an electronics communication  system,
optimized to the needs of the shipyards and their vendors.  A
summary of each presentation is presented in the next section;
a selection of the overhead slides used by each presenter is contained
in Appendix B.  <BR>

<P>
 The second session was configured into three 6-8 person break-out
groups.  Each of the groups was asked to discuss three general
topics,  and three detail topics if time permitted.  The topics
are shown in  Table 1.   <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><B>TABLE 1.  ISSUES FOR DISCUSSION<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDERCOLOR=#000000 BORDER=1>

<TR><TD BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF WIDTH=461><CENTER><I><B>GENERAL QUESTIONS</B></I></CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF WIDTH=461>
<OL><CENTER>
<B><LI>Does it make sense to be working together? Why?</B></CENTER>
</OL>

</TD></TR>

<TR><TD BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF WIDTH=461><CENTER><B>2.  If so, what are the topics that should be worked on? Why?</B></CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF WIDTH=461><CENTER><B>3.  What is the appropriate structure to use for accomplishing the work? Why?</B></CENTER>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE><P>

<TABLE BORDERCOLOR=#808080 BORDER=1>

