       **ship operators<BR>
   **other</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
The third session was a presentation by the three break-out groups
of their thoughts relative to the topics listed in Table 1.  
Appendix C  lists the persons assigned to each break-out group;
that is followed by a listing of the comments presented by each
group.  
<P>
 
<P>
At the conclusion of the break-out presentations the floor was
opened to general discussion for all of the participants.  The
 workshop was concluded with a wrap-up synopsis by the workshop
moderator.  <BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>II.  INVITED PRESENTATIONS<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<H1>A.  Some United States Initiatives<BR>
</H1>

<H2>1.  The Defense Advanced Research Program Agency [DARPA] &quot;MARITECH&quot;
Program  [presented by Mr. Robert Schaffran,  DARPA]</H2>

<P>
<B> </B>
<P>
MARITECH is a five year program set up by DARPA (Defense Advance
Research Project Agency) of the United States  Department of Defense.
 One of  MARITECH program  aims  is to support research that will
improve the communications and information flow for the shipbuilding
and shipping industry<BR>

<P>
In Phase One, MARITECH supported a series of market analyses during
1994-96 and involved every interested party of the shipping industry.
 Interested parties [which included non-USA organizations] submitted
proposals to MARITECH who reviewed each proposal and selected
those it deemed strongest.  MARITECH's contribution was viewed
as an investment that would assist the U.S. shipbuilding industry
 in providing a quality product.    <BR>

<P>
The following conditions applied:
<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>MARITECH <I>only put up 50% of the project
cost.</I></FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>MARITECH <I>has no data rights on any process/product
developed by the project,  <B>but</B> in the event of any military
movements, MARITECH <B>can</B> gain march in rights.</I></FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>The life of the program is five years; after
that there is no further funding contemplated.</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>MARITECH<I> completed 36 commercial designs
during phase one,  and has 6 ships ready for export.</I></FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>

<P>
 Phase Two of the program was to assist the shipyards in entering
the international market.  The  projects were to encourage and
implement advanced technology development specifically looking
at:<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>the changes in culture to compete with commercial
practices;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>dramatic improvements required to  increase
the market share; and </FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>requirements to self-sustain the shipbuilding
base.</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>
<BR>

<P>
Examples of projects undertaken in this phase  were:<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>Integrated product and process data environment
to revolutionize the ship design and bid process.</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>National shipbuilding information infrastructure
to support ship construction.</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>STEP-Ship product model exchange;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>Digital product catalogues.</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>Commercial ship life-cycle support information
infrastructure.</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2></FONT>
<P>
 In October, 1996, proposals were solicited for the following
thrust areas:<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>Advanced business practices technology [requirements
analysis, supplier relations and material procurement, human resources
management, customer relations and life-cycle support, cost estimating
and financial management systems, and marketing].</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>Enterprise-wide technology [dynamic modeling
and simulation, product-to-process decomposition, production planning
and scheduling, material tracking and control, advanced CAD/CAM/CIM,
ship production processes, and yard layout]. </FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>

<P>
The whole process of the MARITECH program is to assist the industry
to profitably market, design, produce and support ships with greater
value and in less time than anyone else in the world.  <BR>

<H2>2.  Presentation  of  American  Efforts  in  Electronic  Commerce
Infrastructure:  &quot;The Development of Marine Machinery and
Equipment Standards for the U.S. Shipbuilding Industry&quot; [presented
by Dr. Martin Fritts of SAIC.]<BR>
</H2>

<P>
With assistance from MARITECH and US Maritime Administration (MARAD),
The Marine Machinery Association (MMA) is  developing methods
of electronic commerce that will allow manufacturers to present
technical information, prices and availability to the customer
via computer.  The project's purpose is to achieve the following:
<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>revise the standards of marine information,
 and develop the system;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>create electronic vendor catalogs;  and </FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>research and improve electronic communications
for the marine industry.</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>

<P>
The aim is to produce catalogs on a six month time frame, and
to review on a regular basis  the procedure of  recording the
material itself.     This is needed because of the speed in which
technology is improving. <B> </B>The tasks for accomplishing this
are:-<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>assisting in standards generation, revision
and adoption;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>looking at production of prototype electronic
catalogs; and, </FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>electronic commerce.</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2></FONT></I>
<P>
The type of  hard/software used must be easily understood and
operated.  The Internet is ideal as it is both universal and portable.
 The approach is: <BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>the hardware used would be put up by MMA;
and, .  </FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>laptops could be distributed to get things
moving quicker and easier. [CD-ROM is serving as a laptop at the
moment as the Internet is not quite ready. this is still quite
cheap at only 78 cents a CD-ROM which can be distributed overnight.]</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>

<P>
The format is not final and is open to criticism.  There are test
pages set up to look at the way MMA has bought the information
system together; this can be found on: &lt;www.nsf.com/mma&gt;.
<BR>

<P>
Several CD-ROMS have been produced which are currently being developed
for six companies involved in the program.  The companies vary
in size.  Large ones would include Leslie Controls and Carrier
 Transicold Division of Carrier Corporation.   There are also
small companies involved in the project.<BR>

<P>
The CD-ROMs serve as electronic catalogs and are a cheap and easy
way of mailing to engineers and agents.  The data on the catalog
can be updated easily with a simple connection to the vendor's
server.  It is essential to get the electronic in place and get
the infrastructure up and working.  Standards are needed  to make
the electronic data an internationally used package. <BR>

<H2>3.  Concurrent Technologies Corporation (CTC)[presented by
Brian Schweitzer of CTC].<BR>
</H2>

<P>
CTC is a is a manufacturing technology center of excellence that
serves as a national resource center committed to the industrial
base.  The organization has the following federal programs:
<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>National Center for Excellence in Metalworking
Technology(NCEMT)[product and process design, operational performance
analysis, intelligent processing of materials, and systems integration.</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>National Defense Center for Environmental
Excellence (NDCEE)[manufacturing process optimization, environmental
compliance, life cycle design and management, and pollution prevention
and remediation].</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>National Applied Software Engineering Center
(NASEC) [object oriented methods, collaborative/distributed computing,
synthetic environments, and megaprogramming].</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>National Electronic Commerce Resource Center
(NECRC)[ product data modeling, manufacturing process application
protocols, information standards implementation, national deployment
network].</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2></FONT></I>
<P>
NECRC has regional electronic resource centers that support over
350,000 small and medium sized enterprises nationwide who respond
to 98% of all DOD procurements. Its long term mission is to have
a world-class supplier network that links U.S. industry to a national
information infrastructure.   There is a program with a shipbuilding
initiative that has the following activities:  <BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>process analysis with shipbuilding 'network'
to evaluate EC status and needs;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>web-based ISO standards collaboration tool
development with MMA;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>STEP building block development; and</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>demonstration of EC tools [web-based TDI,
STEP, process simulation, legacy data].</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>The long term strategy is to support the
formation of virtual shipyard enterprises.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<H1>B.  European Efforts in Electronic Commerce Infrastructure
<BR>
</H1>

<H2>1.  MARIS Project Overview [presented by Dirk Petrat of the
European Commission].<BR>
</H2>

<P>
The Maritime Information Society (MARIS) is an information society
designed to keep the shipping industry internationally updated.<B>
 </B>The MARIS program was one of eleven projects set up at a
G7 conference in Brussels in 1995.  The idea is to launch these
pilot programs in order to build international links in the marine
industry.<BR>

<P>
MARIS has a framework of programs to help assist in the existence
of the international marine industry including:
<UL>
<LI>MARTRANS which deals with the handling of cargo
<LI>SAFEMAR to make sure regulations are approved to combine and
</UL>

<P>
control these systems (electronic charts/ship reporting/port logistics)
<UL>
<LI>MARSOURCE for the marine resources (fisheries database)
<LI>MARVEL  for the industrial sector (intelligent manufacture)
</UL>

<P>

<P>
 The main objectives of MARIS are to:<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>establish a worldwide maritime information
system;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>promote the operability and connectivity of
existing information systems worldwide;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>demonstrate the possible benefits of maritime
information technology; and,</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>support the worldwide standardization in the
maritime sector.</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>

<H2> 2.  The MARVELOUS[ project presented by Joachim Brodd, of
BALance Consultants].<BR>
</H2>

<P>
 The Maritime Industry's Virtual Enterprise Linkage Open User
Syndicate (MARVELOUS) is an industrial coordination project, and
is part of the MARVEL initiative.   It has been set up to try
to harmonize the generic requirements for the implementation of
information technology.<BR>
 The project began 15 November 1995 and will continue until 14
February 1997.  The budget for this program is 2.4 million ECU.
 MARVELOUS temporarily joins companies together to perform a product.
 Partners of the MARVELOUS project include shipyards, classification
societies and other supporting societies.<BR>
 
<H2> 3.  Electronic Data Interchange for the European MARITIME
Industry (EDIMAR). <BR>
</H2>

<P>
 EDIMAR is a project derived from MARVELOUS to research the electronic
data interchange for the European maritime industry.  EDIMAR applications
link to classification societies which links to the supplier,
shipyards, etc.  The product structure uses standard parts, raw
material and &quot;make-to-order&quot; products.<B>   </B>By using
the EDI system vast amounts of time and money can be saved.  A
survey was performed using a Danish steel mill in which the following
results occurred:<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>Time taken for the preparation of a steel
order (30 pos.) for  ship took:<BR>
  a.  28 minutes (without EDI)<BR>
  b.  8 minutes (with EDI).</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>The adaptation of order responses for steel
took:<BR>
  a.  62 minutes (without EDI)<BR>
  b.  4 minutes (with EDI).</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>
 
<P>
 The steel mill was a very small example but proves that vast
savings can be made in all aspects of the maritime industry by
using electronic data.<BR>

<H2> 4.  Special Interested Groups (SIG)<BR>
</H2>

<P>
             MARVELOUS are already working with many  special
interest groups (SIGs) from European countries, it is hoped that
this can be expanded so SIGs can be located nationally.<BR>

<H2> 5.  The SEASPRITE Project [presented by Fermando Caldeira-Saraiva.]
<BR>
</H2>

<P>
 The Software Architectures for Ship Product Data Integration
&amp; Exchange (SEASPRITE) project, was the first program started
after the MARIS requirements were designed.   The proposal for
SEASPRITE was submitted in September 1995 and was approved in
principle in January 1996.  The technical annex was completed
in April 1995 and the project actually started in July 1996. 
The completion date for this project will be June 1999.  SEASPRITE's
aim is to change the way in which the maritime industry is run
today, concentrating on current systems like :<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>ship plans being the main means of communication
between business partners;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>manual re-entry of data is prevalent;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>tasks being carried out sequentially; and,</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>the control of labor being intensive.</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2></FONT></I>
<P>
 The working methods currently used consist of vast amounts of
paper and storage space, SEASPRITE intend to change this system:
<BR>

<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>using information technology to improve industry
performance;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>creating virtual enterprise solutions with
data sharing between business partners;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>ensuring version control is automated; and</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>encouraging re-use of ship data in all ship
life-cycle phases.</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>

<P>
 This new vision hopes to cut down time, space, wastage and ensure
all information can be gained effectively and efficiently, to
get private and public information stored together.
<P>
A system must be created and carried out in real-life.<BR>

<P>
 It is expected that over a full life-cycle of a plant, 10-30%
of the life-time costs can be saved.  Other industries have found
time-to-market is reduced which increases market penetration.
<BR>

<H1>C.  Electronic Commerce in Shipbuilding and Ship Machinery
Manufacture in Japan [presented by Shigeru Ito of the Japan Ship
Center (JETRO)]<BR>
</H1>

<P>
 The Japanese are behind in relation to the development of electronic
communication for the maritime industry.  Japan is concentrating
on improving the productivity in the field rather than improving
electronic communication facilities.  Japanese builders are in
a difficult situation concerning electronic communication.  There
is no appreciation to the currency and other such cultural issues.
<BR>

<P>
 CIM is a system which started in 1987 and is aimed at improving
productivity.  It is a database which operates in-house and covers
all items from design to construction.
<P>
The system has been found to improve the productivity in the ship
yard.  This project only consisted of major shipbuilders and didn't
affect other marine companies.<BR>

<P>
 In Spring 1995, a report was issued;  &quot;The Future Course
of Ship Building and Ship Building Industry.&quot;  This report
looks at new concepts in shipbuilding, challenges for Japan within
the shipbuilding industries and which measures need to be taken
to achieve these measures.<BR>

<P>
 Appendix B-3 has an expanded description of the Japanese effort.
<P>
 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>III.  BREAKOUT PRESENTATIONS AND OPEN
SESSION<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4> </FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4> The attendees were divided into three discussion
groups [see Appendix C-1 for the listing for the groups].  The
groups were then asked to discuss three general questions, and
, if time permitted, to examine three additional issues.  Table
1, page 4-5, listed the questions/issues.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4> On the question of whether it makes sense for the
various national interest to work together,  all three groups
gave an emphatic &quot;yes&quot; response.   One group summarized
the responses of all: &quot;We must work together due to increasing
globalization in the manufacturing for the marine industry.  The
exchange is inevitable; cooperation will hasten the process, and
will support an enhanced competitive position.&quot;<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4> There was considerable variation in the areas where
cooperation should occur.  Among the ideas that listed were:<BR>
</FONT>
<OL>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>standardization [both in the development and
in the implementation],</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>defining a common vision for what electronic
commerce is to achieve;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>Internet facilitation, and the development
of a common understanding of how to move toward virtual manufacturing
systems; </FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>training program, especially for vendors;</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>test beds for project evaluations; and</FONT></I>
<LI><I><FONT SIZE=2>rationalization of business practices.</FONT></I>
</OL>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>There was agreement by all of the groups
that the cooperation should be directed through the MARIS G-7
organization.  The United States, the European Community, and
Japan are all part of the G-7 structure,  thus a &quot;ready&quot;
vehicle is in place to be utilized.  [The American delegates indicated
during the &quot;open session&quot; they would work to see the
United States more integrated into the MARIS structure, especially
the MARVEL activity.]<BR>

<P>
 One of the groups suggested that the level of concern for protection
of information was a function on the type of information being
discussed: public or private, i.e., proprietary.  Only the proprietary
information should be dealt with, and even then it should be recognized
that it is almost impossible to completely control the security
of the data.    A possible solution would be to develop a repository
of information on security problems and solutions. <BR>

<P>
 In the open discussion  there appeared to be a consensus develop
that the shipbuilding community should be the leader in organizing
an international forum.  The attendees felt that the same force
would not occur with the initiative being led by the vendor community.
<BR>

<P>
 One of the delegates [from Italy] suggested that time is of the
essence in emplacing an effective electronic communications system
that links the shipyards with the vendor base.   At the outside,
it was felt that an effective system must be in place in 2-3 years.
 Delay  beyond that horizon date  would mean loss of any competitive
benefits that would result from early emplacement.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
