<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>High-Temperature Structural Materials Update #1</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>Office of Naval Research-Europe<BR>  Materials Science and
Technology<BR>  High-Temperature Structural Materials Update #1<BR> 
by <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/christod.htm">Julie
Christodoulou</A></H3> 
<P></P>
<H3>September 1995<BR>  Notes from the 4th European Conference on
Advanced Materials and Processes, Padua/Venice, 25 -- 28 September 1995</H3>

<P>Includes:<BR>  Summary<BR>  Intermetallics<BR>  Powder Metallurgy<BR>
  Metal Matrix Composites<BR>  Superalloys<BR>  General Impressions
</P><P><B>Summary</B><BR>  Organized by Associazione Italiana di
Metallurgia on behalf of the 40,000 member Federation of European
Materials Societies, the conference boasted some 300+ oral and poster
presentations of research results from throughout Europe. Five sessions
in addition to the poster session were run simultaneously, and papers
and keynote addresses were organized into eight broad categories
including ceramics and glasses, polymers, composites, structural
metallic materials, surface engineering, materials and processing,
special and functional materials, and environmental effects. My
attention was focused on works presented on intermetallics, powder
metallurgy, aluminum alloys and their composites, metal matrix
composites, innovative steels and superalloys, and small scale
structural alloys. Summaries of presentations and poster displays of
interest that I saw are presented below, as well as general impressions
of the effectiveness of the conference. More detailed information;
including abstracts and copies of papers, and means of contacting
individual participants; will be promptly and cheerfully supplied upon
your request.
</P><P><B>Intermetallics</B><BR>  The keynote lecture; a strong
review of current fundamental understanding of diffusion in Ti-Al, Ni-Al
and Fe-Si and Fe-Ge-Si compounds; was presented by Dr. Helmut Mehrer of
the University of Munster, Germany. Copies are available for those
interested.
</P><P> Interesting work done at the University of Neuchatel in
Switzerland was presented by Drs. David Morris and Maria Morris. Efforts
there are directed toward microstructural characterization of aluminides
and development of structure-property relationships; data for Fe-Al,
Ni-Al and Ti-Al systems were presented. Efforts to associate equilibrium
disorder at domain boundaries in Ni3Al with ductility are interesting,
although controversial. Of particular interest to this participant,
mechanical properties (hardness and yield strength) have been derived
for three microstructural phases in the Ti-Al-Mo system: alpha2, beta2
and gamma. Future efforts will involve assessment of elevated
temperature properties in the Ti-44Al-2Mo alloy as a function of
microstructure.
</P><P> Dr. Johann Mullauer of the GKSS Research Center in Geesthacht,
Germany is investigating a Howmet-cast near-gamma Ti-Al alloy modified
with Cr, Mn, Nb, Si and B additions which show improved specific
stiffness (attributed to boride and silicide precipitates) and
resistance to oxidation (associate with Nb addition) in comparison to a
Ti-48Al-2Cr "pilot" alloy.
</P><P> Dr. Stefan Willems presented work carried out at the Technical
University of Hamburg, Germany which included detailed characterization
of microstructural changes associated with high temperature deformation
of gamma-TiAl. Static and dynamic recrystallization and phase
stabilities have been studied in an attempt to explain the dependence of
strain-rate sensitivity on temperature.
</P><P> More fundamental work to understand deformation in this class
of materials is being conducted at EPFL in Lausanne, Switzerland by Drs.
Joel Bonneville and Jean-Luc Martin. Their work is on the
characterization of superdislocation generation, motion and annihilation
in polycrystalline intermetallics. Results of studies of a gamma-TiAl
alloy (Ti47Al51Mn2) and on Ni3Al variations where significant
proportions of Al is substituted by Hf or Ta were presented at this
meeting.
</P><P><B>Powder Metallurgy</B><BR>  In work presented by Marianne
Leiderman at the Israel Institute of Technology in Haifa, improvements
in the density, hardness and toughness of WC cutting tool materials is
attributed to the use of ultrafine precursor powders (<0.3 micrometers).
It was shown that most of the sintering was carried out in the solid
state, reducing and possibly eliminating the need for matrix cobalt
thereby increasing hardness even further.
</P><P><B>Metal Matrix Composites</B><BR>  Copper MMCs may offer a
reasonable alternative to Cu-Be alloys for high-stiffness,
intermediate-temperature-capable electrical and thermal conduits as
discussed by Dr. Wolfgang Puesche of the University of Dresden. Recent
work there has shown that mechanical and physical properties of Cu-4 wt%
Ti alloys reinforced with 10 vol% TiC approach those of Cu-Be alloys.
The promise of eliminating the need for handling beryllium is very
attractive for reasons of safety and economy.
</P><P> Damage models in particulate reinforced metal-matrix composites
generated collaboratively by Drs. Alan Plumtree of the University of
Waterloo in Ontario and Paul Mummery of the University of Leeds in the
UK were very mature and seem worthy of further assessment.
</P><P><B>Superalloys</B><BR>  The keynote lecture was presented by
Dr. Uwe Glatzel of the Technical University of Berlin where the effects
of relative misfits at the gamma-gamma boundaries of the superalloy
CMSX-4 during high temperature deformation are being studied. They have
found that the magnitude of the internal compressive stresses parallel
to the grain boundaries can be as great as 250MPa. These results were
intelligently related to microstructural development observed during
high temperature deformation.
</P><P> Among the several papers presented on microstructural changes
observed in nickel-based superalloys in response to elevated temperature
stresses, a report given by Muriel Veron on work done with Dr. Yves
Brechet at the Domane Universitaire de Genoble, France was the most
substantive. The effects of plastic and diffusional flow at service
temperatures was incorporated into a simulation program which
demonstrated that the rate of gamma-plate thickening is greater in
response to compressive loading than in response to tensile loading.
These predictions were collaborated by detailed microstructural
observations.
</P><P><B>General Impressions</B><BR>  This was the 4th EuroMat and
the largest to date. These meetings are meant to provide a venue for
researchers from all of Europe to meet and find areas of common
interest. Collaborations among scientists of different nations is
encouraged, and one of the plenary lectures was dedicated to assessment
of the European Commissions priorities for materials research, the
budget allocated for the work, and detailed description of the
Brite-Euram research funding opportunities.
</P><P> The format of the conference with its simultaneous sessions
suggested comparisons with the larger TMS and MRS conferences held in
the United States, and perhaps those more established meetings provided
a model for EuroMat. While several good presentations were made, my
impression is that the conference lacked the "critical mass" of
participants necessary to support strong, focused dialogue. A broad call
for papers was responded to with numerous works of variable quality on
multiple topics, and apparently most were included in the program.
Although papers were clustered into areas of research, the sessions
often lacked unifying themes.
</P><HR><P></P><P>Dear Colleagues,
</P><P> This is Update #1 on high temperature structural materials
efforts in Europe, notes from the 4th Euromat Conference; I hope that
you find it useful. If you have comments or questions, I would very much
appreciate any feedback that you will take the time to give me. Also,
please send this on to colleagues that might benefit and/or send their
e-mail addresses to me.
</P><P> Respectfully,<BR>  Julie A. Christodoulou<BR>  Office of
Naval Research- Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone Rd<BR>  London, NW1
5TH, UK
</P><P> tel. 44 171 514 4943<BR>  fax 44 171 723 6359
</P><P> e-mail: jchristodoulou@onreur.navy.mil
</P><P></P>
<HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to
ONREUR newsletters</A>
</P></BODY></HTML>
