<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>High-Temperature Structural Materials Update #2</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>Office of Naval Research-Europe<BR>  Materials Science and
Technology<BR>  High-Temperature Structural Materials Update #2<BR> 
by <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/christod.htm">Julie
Christodoulou</A></H3> 
<P></P>
<H3>January 1996<BR>  Notes from the Eighth World Conference on
Titanium Birmingham, United Kingdom, 22 -- 26 October 1995</H3> 
<P>Happy New Year, Colleagues!!<HTML>

</P><P> I hope that you each enjoyed a relaxing break over the
holidays. Our server here at ONREUR took several intermittent breaks
into January, and this will mark the third attempt to deliver this
newsletter: Update #2 on High Temperature Structural Metallics efforts
in Europe, Notes from the 8th World Conference on Titanium.
</P><P> A few of you received this report on the second attempt
(initiated two weeks ago). You are excused from reading this document
yet again; please delete this message and accept my best wishes for a
successful and productive New Year.
</P><P> If this is new to you please read on. I hope that the
information is useful to you, will welcome your comments and encourage
you to pass it along to your colleagues who may also find the document
interesting. Please have a great New Year. I look forward to future
communications with you.
</P><P> Respectfully,<BR>  Julie A. Christodoulou<BR>  Office of
Naval Research- Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>  London, NW1
5TH, UK
</P><P> tel. 44 171 514 4943<BR>  fax 44 171 723 6359<BR>  e-mail:
jchristodoulou@onreur.navy.mil
</P><HR><P></P><P>HIGH TEMPERATURE STRUCTURAL METALLICS NEWSLETTER #2<BR>
  NOTES FROM THE EIGHTH WORLD CONFERENCE ON TITANIUM<BR>  Birmingham,
United Kingdom, 22 -- 26 October 1995<BR>  Prepared by Julie
Christodoulou, Office of Naval Research- Europe<BR> 
</P><PRE>
1.  Introduction and general impressions
2.  Plenary lectures
3.  Intermetallics
4.  Process modeling
5.  Conventional titanium alloys
6.  Titanium matrix composites
</PRE>
<P><B>1. Introduction and general impressions</B><BR>  The World
Titanium Conferences have become the meeting ground for researchers in
all of the various fields of Ti development. Nearly 500 works were
scheduled for presentation at the Eighth Conference; topics ranged from
raw materials and primary processing, alloy development including first
principle approaches to alloy constitution and structure predictions,
relationships between microstructure and mechanical properties, modeling
of thermo-mechanical processing, environmental behavior and surfaces,
and applications. Four concurrent oral presentation sessions, in
addition to two extensive poster sessions, were held throughout the
four-day conference. My attention was focused on those sessions that
addressed intermetallics; titanium matrix composites; mechanical
properties and microstructures; and some presentations in sessions on
alloy development, alloy constitution and structure; and environmental
behavior and surfaces. Summaries of selected presentations and poster
displays are presented in the following sections; points of particular
technical interest have been highlighted. More detailed information
about the conference, the work presented, and means of contacting the
researchers' whose observations are discussed here is available upon
request.
</P><P> My general impression of the work presented at the conference
was positive; the caliber of the work was generally very high. As the
meeting progressed some interesting trends developed. Firstly, there
appeared to be distinct differences in research focus between European
and American programs: US presentations tended to be on the more
"advanced" classes of materials (e.g., TMC and intermetallics) whereas
European efforts are directed toward new versions of "conventional
alloys" (e.g., IMI 834 and B-CEZ). Another clear trend was demonstrated
in most of the Chinese presentations where significant language
difficulties were encountered. More casual discussions with these
scientists about their work was impossible because of the communication
failure. An unfortunate consequence of this is that Chinese research
efforts and objectives remain obscure, whether they are intentionally
shielded or not.
</P><P> Perhaps the parcel of information that generated the greatest
impact during the conference was not presented orally nor as a poster,
but rather by word of mouth during coffee breaks and lunches. The merger
of TiMet Corporation and IMI Titanium was announced formally in the
press and circulated quickly among the conference participants.
Potential ramifications of the move provided wonderful topics for casual
speculation; the consensus being that the two companies were joining in
an attempt to increase competitiveness with respect to Russian, Japanese
and Chinese titanium producers who are growing stronger each year.
</P><P> After recent experiments in holding the titanium conferences at
three-year intervals, the organizing committee has decided to return to
the original format and hold the meetings once every four years, and
this decision was received very favorably by the participants. In each
of the sessions that I attended, I found the audience's level of
specialization and expertise to be very high. In general, these
researchers are familiar with current literature, have strong
backgrounds and good memories; only recent observations or fully
developed concepts are of real interest to them. Conversely, since it is
the largest forum for meeting fellow titanium metallurgists there is
sufficient encouragement for everyone to contribute something, even if
it isn't fully developed or if it relies heavily on material that has
been previously reported, in order to justify attendance. Extending the
schedule of the conference to a four-year format may go along way to
balance these opposing needs. The next World Titanium Conference is
being planned for 1999 in St. Petersburg, Russia.
</P><P> Selected Lecture notes:<BR>
<B>2. Plenary lectures</B><BR>  The first morning of the conference
was devoted to introductory presentations that highlighted current
research activities in each of the seven most represented nations: the
United Kingdom, France, Japan, Russia, the United States, Germany and
China. In some cases these were simply introductions to the technical
papers that would be presented during the conference. Other speakers
provided surveys of current research programs and objectives and of the
applications that are driving titanium alloy development.
</P><P> Notably, Dr. Paul Blenkinsop of the Interdisciplinary Research
Center (IRC) at the University of Birmingham discussed current efforts
to optimize existing IMI Titanium alloys for more demanding
applications; the pursuit of superplastic forming and diffusion bonding
technologies at British Aerospace, Rolls-Royce and DRA for potential
weight savings; efforts in forging simulation and welding at Smith
Clayton Forging and Bunting Titanium LTD, respectively; Rolls-Royce's
introduction of discontinuously reinforced, XD intermetallic matrix
composites to the Trent stator vane; and the joint effort in the
development of a "bling," bladed ring assembly, by DRA, Sigma and
Rolls-Royce.
</P><P> Dr. Bernard Champin of CEZUS, France announced SNECMA's
NEAR-TERM APPLICATIONS OF TI-17, 8-CEZ AND TI-6-4-8-2 INTO TURBINE
ENGINES AND DISCUSSED THEIR LONG-TERM GOALS TO INCORPORATE TI3AL AND
TIAL INTO FUTURE GENERATION ENGINES. Current large research and
development activities explore deformation in Ti-Al-V alloys, and
improvements in creep resistance and ductility in gamma-based
intermetallics conducted at ONERA under BRITE EURAM support. Brief
mention of Ti-Co-Cr alloys for potential dental applications was also
made.
</P><P> Dr. Igor Gorynin drew attention to work at the Central Research
Institute of Structural Materials (Russia) to develop Ti-alloys for
marine applications. He illustrated that THE SENSITIVITY OF STRESS
CORROSION CRACKING SUSCEPTIBILITY ON ALLOY COMPOSITION, POINTING OUT
THAT THE CRITICAL ALUMINUM CONTENT APPEARS TO BE BETWEEN 4.0 AND 5.5
ATOM%. Other efforts discussed were directed toward improvements in weld
design and in Ti welding processes.
</P><P> Mr. R. R. Boyer of the Boeing Commercial Airplane Group
presented a lively, applications-oriented view of Ti-alloy development
in the U.S. He pointed TO PRATT & WHITNEY'S POTENTIAL USE OF XD
TITANIUM-ALUMINIDE CAST COMPONENTS AND TO ORTHORHOMBIC-BASED ALLOY
DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITIES AS EXAMPLES OF EFFORTS IN INTERMETALLICS. More
conventional alloys to be incorporated into side-body ribs and bulkhead
(forged by Wymann-Gordon) of the F-22 were noted, and the Ti-10V-2Fe-Al
forgings used in Boeing's 777 landing gear. Also discussed was the
development of Ti/polymer-matrix-composite hybrid laminates for the
MD-11.
</P><P><B>3. Intermetallics</B><BR>  A preponderance of the material
presented on this subject was the result of efforts in the U.S. Dr.
James Chesnutt of GE Aircraft Engines presented the opening lecture: a
general overview of the properties and potential application of
orthorhombic, alpha-2 and gamma titanium aluminides. Current research
and development at GE is focused on Ti-48Al-2Cr-2Nb for potential
incorporation into the GE90 as transition duct beams and low pressure
turbine blades.
</P><P> Dr. James Larsen of Wright Laboratory presented the results OF
A THOUGHTFUL INVESTIGATION OF MICROSTRUCTURAL INFLUENCES ON KEY
MECHANICAL PROPERTIES OF THE NEAR-GAMMA TI-ALUMINIDE K-5
(Ti-46.5Al-3Nb-2Cr-0.2W) quantifying, among other observations, the
enhanced fatigue resistance of the lamellar microstructural condition as
compared with the duplex microstructure of equiaxed grains.
</P><P> Professor I. Polkin of VILS in Moscow presented the interesting
observation that the presence of large, uniformly distributed pores in
as-cast near-gamma titanium aluminides are actually beneficial. They
serve as sites for working and allow dynamic recrystallization to occur
during HIPing whereas fine pores simply heal without affecting the
microstructure.
</P><P> Professor Richard Wagner of the GKSS Research Center in
Geesthacht presented the keynote lecture on the second day of the
conference: a description of German research efforts IN GAMMA
TI-ALUMINIDES WHERE PARTICULAR ATTENTION IS DIRECTED TOWARD PRODUCING
INTERMETALLICS FOR POTENTIAL APPLICATION IN TURBO CHARGER WHEELS FOR
ABB'S LARGE DIESEL ENGINES. A TI-47AL-2CR ALLOY MODIFIED BY THE ADDITION
OF 2000 PPM BORON, GAMMA-TAB, DISPLAYS A HIGHLY REFINED, HOMOGENEOUS
MICROSTRUCTURE AND IS A LIKELY CANDIDATE FOR THIS APPLICATION. Other
efforts include development of powder metallurgy produced billets that
can be forged in a single step, offering potential processing cost
savings over conventionally cast and two-step forged products.
</P><P> Professor Hamish Fraser discussed the results of interesting
work conducted at Ohio State University to understand micro-mechanisms
of fracture and variations in fracture behavior as a function of
temperature.
</P><P> Dr. P.L. Martin of the Rockwell Science Center in California
presented results of recent work to understand the influence of small
amounts of boron and oxygen in near-gamma Ti-aluminides. He reported
that ADDITIONS OF <0.25 ATOM% B TO TI-47AL-2NB-2CR-1MO WERE SUFFICIENT
FOR LACY BORIDE PRECIPITATION AT GRAIN BOUNDARIES. The lacy borides
inhibit grain growth, allow a fully lamellar microstructure to be
achieved in forged components and therefore increase creep resistance,
fracture toughness and room temperature ductility. WHEN OXYGEN CONTENT
IS STRICTLY MINIMIZED IN THIS ALLOY COMPOSITION, THE ORDERED BETA PHASE
WAS FOUND TO BE STABLE AT THE EXPENSE OF THE ALPHA-2 PHASE.
</P><P> Dr. D. Rugg of IMI Titanium, UK reported on work conducted
jointly with DRA and Rolls-Royce. They have demonstrated the feasibility
of extruding near-gamma Ti-aluminide Ti-48Al-2Nb-2Mn and have shown that
extrusions can have as much as 30% higher strength than cast materials.
Although the highest strengths were observed in the as-extruded
condition; extruded, solution heat treated and aged material showed
greater ductility and still maintained yield strengths higher than cast
material.
</P><P> Dr. Gilbert Henaff of CNRS, France presented observations on
the role of environment in fatigue crack propagation in gamma-based
Ti-aluminides. In order to establish the effects of microstructural
state work was done on two alloys: an as-cast Ti-48Al-2Mn-2Nb with a
fully lamellar gamma + alpha-2 microstructure, a cast and HIPed
Ti-48Al-2Cr-2Nb alloy comprised only of fully equiaxed gamma grains. No
significant effect of microstructure or variation between the
composition of the alloys was observed on crack closure behavior,
although a weak interaction between environment (moisture) and closure
effects was noted. Fatigue crack growth rates in gamma-based
Ti-aluminides appears to be highly sensitive to the amplitude of applied
stress.
</P><P> Dr. Brian Worth of the University of Dayton presented the
results of a study of fatigue crack growth behavior in wrought and heat
treated near-gamma Ti-aluminide K-5 in two microstructural conditions:
fully equiaxed and fully lamellar. The alloy in both microstructural
states illustrated improved crack growth resistance at 600C compared
with room temperature. All other variables being equal, fatigue crack
growth rate was found to be lower in the lamellar microstructure and is
considered to be the result of intrinsic toughening mechanisms. As
observed by Dr. Henaff, delta-K has a significant influence on crack
growth rate, and this is attributed to crack closure mechanisms.
</P><P><B>4. Process modeling</B><BR>  Professor Russell W. Evans of
the IRC at Swansea, UK delivered an elegant keynote address; he defined
the key parameters and introduced the approach necessary for developing
models to predict microstructural evolution and recrystallization
phenomena during forging.
</P><P> Dr. S.P. Fox followed Prof. Evan's talk with a description of
current capabilities at IMI Titanium Ltd. where a three-dimensional,
IRC-developed model is used to modify forging practices for greater
microstructural control.
</P><P><B>5. Conventional titanium alloys</B><BR>  Ms. A. Barussaud
of SNECMA discussed efforts to control microstructure in large disks for
the high temperature compressor of the GE90 aeroengine. The
microstructure that offered THE BEST COMPROMISE BETWEEN MAXIMIZED CREEP
RESISTANCE AND LOW-CYCLE-FATIGUE RESISTANCE WAS FOUND TO BE COMPOSED OF
UNCRYSTALLIZED AND COLD-WORKED BETA GRAINS WITH THE ALPHA PHASE PRESENT
IN A WIDMANSTATTEN STRUCTURE. Sub-scale studies correlated slow cooling
from heat treatment temperatures with improved ductility, and
improvements in fracture toughness and creep resistance could be
associated with increased grain boundary angle, theta.
</P><P> Professor G. Lutjering of the Technical University of
Hamburg-Harburg, Germany compared the mechanical properties of Ti-6242
(Ti-6Al-2Sn-4Zr-2Mo-0.08Si) with the Russian alloy BT25Y
(Ti-6Al-2Sn-3.5Zr-3.5Mo-1W-0.2Si). When the two alloys were forged the
BT25Y was found to have a much finer microstructure, and the slower
kinetics were attributed to the tungsten addition. The BT25Y
DEMONSTRATED SUPERIOR YIELD STRENGTH, DUCTILITY AND FRACTURE TOUGHNESS
IN BOTH THE AS-FORGED AND IN THE FORGED+ANNEALED CONDITIONS, AND THIS
TREND IS MAINTAINED AT ELEVATED TEMPERATURE. In the as-forged condition
creep resistance is better for the BT25Y than the Ti-6242, but both
alloys display equivalent creep resistance after annealing.
</P><P> Dr. Mark Hardy of DRA, UK, presented some interesting
observations of a study of fatigue crack growth behavior in near-alpha
titanium alloys, specifically IMI 829 at 600C. He found that fatigue
crack growth rate is time dependent and that loading rate controls
da/dN; these were seen as functions of oxidation and creep effects. The
degree (e.g., number and severity) of secondary cracking was also found
to correlate directly with loading rate. By studying the effects of
symmetric and asymmetric loading schemes it was illustrated that
loading, not relaxation, determines da/dN.
</P><P> Dr. S. Lesterlin of CNRS, France has conducted an extensive
series of experiments to determine the effects of environment on the
fatigue behavior of Ti-6242. For the microstructure composed of 75%
alpha lathes in beta, she found that the material is especially
sensitive to environment over the temperature range of 465 to 600C;
over a magnitude difference in behavior was observed when tests
conducted at 35 Hz and 0.1 Hz were compared. Results of tests done with
various dwell times showed no indication of creep fatigue effects;
however, corrosion fatigue appears to be operative over this temperature
range, and the embrittlement species has been identified as water vapor.
</P><P><B>6. Titanium matrix comopsites</B><BR>  Dr. Malcolm
Ward-Close of DRA, UK, announced that BP SIGMA FIBERS ARE NOW OWNED AND
PRODUCED BY DRA. He then presented the results of technical efforts
directed toward the LONG-TERM GOAL OF PRODUCING TITANIUM MATRIX
COMPOSITE BLINGS (BLADED-RING ASSEMBLIES) AND ACHIEVING A 70% WEIGHT
SAVINGS OVER CONVENTIONAL BLADES AND DISKS. DRA is using physical vapor
deposition to coat the Sigma Fibers with Ti or Ti-alloy. The coated
fibers can then be aligned and consolidated into impressively uniform
arrangements with high packing efficiency. Currently, 1000-meter lengths
of Ti-6-4 alloy-coated fiber can be produced.
</P><P> Dr. D. Upadhyaya of the University of Idaho has developed
email_addressA GADOLINIUM-BASED COATING THAT IS BEING CONSIDERED FOR
USE AS AN INTERFACE MATERIAL IN THE DRA COMPOSITES described above. The
coating is novel because it has a very low modulus and can accommodate
differences in CTE between the matrix and fiber; it also appears to be
chemically stable in the presence of Ti. The gadolinium-based coating is
proposed to be suitable for fiber reinforced composites of conventional
Ti-alloys, Ti3Al and TiAl.
</P><P> Joint work by Dr. K. Takashima of the Kumamoto University,
Japan and Dr. P. Bowen of the University of Birmingham has been
conducted to develop damage assessment techniques for SiC-fiber
reinforced Ti-alloys. Acoustic emission is useful for discriminating
individual fracture events; fiber pullout, fiber fracture and matrix
cracking each have different AE amplitudes. They found that at high
applied stresses acoustic emission is the more sensitive technique; at
lower applied stresses modulus and internal friction measurements are
more effective for measuring individual events.
</P><P></P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return
to ONREUR newsletters</A>
</P></BODY></HTML>
