<HEAD>
<TITLE>High-Temperature Structural Materials Update #3</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>Office of Naval Research-Europe<BR>  Materials Science and
Technology<BR> 
 High-Temperature Structural Materials Update #3<BR> 
by <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/christod.htm">Julie
Christodoulou</A></H3> 
<P></P>
<H3>24 April 1996<BR>
The Development and Potential of Cronidur 30 - An Advanced Nitrogen -Alloyed Stainless Steel</H3> 

This newsletter includes the following sections:<BR>
<PRE>
1.  Summary
2.  Introduction
3.  Materials Performance
4.  Assessment
5.  References & Contacts
</PRE>

<B>Summary</B><BR>
An advanced nitrogen-alloyed steel developed in a joint program between German bearing producer FAG, VSG Specialty Steel, and the University of Bochum for U.S. jet engine manufacturer Pratt & Whitney is reported to have significantly improved performance over currently used bearing steels.  Cronidur 30s unique microstructure of uniformly distributed semi-coherent refractory carbo-nitrides in a nitrogen-rich martensitic matrix enables superior wear resistance, corrosion resistance, rolling contact fatigue resistance, strength and toughness in comparison with conventional bearing steels.  The metallurgists who developed the alloy tell us that in several instances the properties of Cronidur 30 are one- or two-orders of magnitude better than the competitors at similar costs.<P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Cronidur 30 is a promising high-nitrogen containing martensitic stainless steel developed to meet the demands of bearings in the space shuttle main engine by FAG Bearing Co. (German bearing manufacturer), Vereinigte Schmiedewerke GmbH (VSG, German steel producer), Ruhr-Universitat Bochum Institut fur Werkstoffe, and Pratt and Whitney (P&W). These particularly challenging requirements include high hardness (>58 Rc), fracture toughness, wear resistance and corrosion resistance including stress corrosion cracking resistance-- requirements that are common to several naval ship and aircraft applications. The alloys are currently produced and sold by VSG at prices comparative to those for M50 steel.  A licensing agreement is being established that will allow the production by a second source in the United States, Canada and France.<P>

<B>Material Performance</B><BR>
Perhaps the most widely used bearing steels are AMS 6444 (52100) and AMS 6490 (M50).   For more demanding high-speed bearing applications the carburized steel, M50NiL, with its high surface hardness and tough core is another material of choice.  However, these steels do not possess the corrosion resistance required for aerospace applications nor the oxygen compatibility required for Space Shuttle main engine bearings.   In their efforts to meet these demands FAG, VSG and the University of Bochum have developed Cronidur 30, one of a family of nitrogen-alloyed stainless steels boasting superior corrosion resistance.  A subsequent joint FAG/P&W program evaluated the material for use in the Space Shuttle bearing; they met success with the first flight of the high performance reusable Space Shuttle liquid oxygen turbopump bearing on 13 June 1995.  These alloys are also of great interest to those of us who do not fly Space Shuttles, because the reported mechanical properties and corrosion resistance of Cronidur 30 are significantly better than those ascribed to either M50NiL or to AISI 440C.<P>

The chemical composition of Cronidur 30, reported in weight percent, is 
Fe - 15.5 Cr - 1.0 Mo - 0.33 C - 0.33 N. An AMS specification has been released for the alloy: AMS 5859.  The alloy is produced in production pressurized electroslag remelt units in Essen, Germany.  <P>

For comparison the compositions of AISI 440C and M50NiL are <BR>
AISI 440C: Fe - 17 Cr - 0.45 Mo - 1.0 C <BR>
M50NiL: Fe - 4.1 Cr - 4.4 Mo - 1.15 V - 3.40 Ni with the surface carburized to ~0.9 C.<P>

As described by the developers, the microstructure of Cronidur 30 consists of a fine, uniform dispersion of semi-coherent refractory carbo-nitrides, displaying none of the large eutectic carbides and stringers found in AISI 440C after similar treatment.   Thermal processing and resultant characteristics of the stainless steel, as identified by the developers, are as follows.<P>

Through Hardening:  Solution, quench and temper are carried out similarly to the processing of conventional bearing steels.  After solution and quench treatment hardness is approximately 56 Rc.  Subsequent tempering precipitates semi-coherent hard carbo-nitrides throughout the microstructure that strains the martensitic matrix leading to hardnesses of between 58 and 60 Rc.<P>
 
Dual Property (DP) Processing:  DP processing is an induction hardening treatment applied to the bearing surfaces.  It is carried out in three steps: (1) conventional hardening and high temperature tempering to a medium hardness, tough core condition followed by (2) localized gradient induction heat treating to case harden the steel, and (3) finally cold treating the hardened case to lower the retained austenite level and tempering the case to 58 Rc.<P>

After conventional heat treatments to the same hardness and fracture toughness, Cronidur 30 appears to demonstrate superior strength, ductility and toughness over the commonly used corrosion resistant stainless steel AISI 440C.  The room temperature tensile yield and ultimate tensile strength of Cronidur 30 (heat treated to 58 Rc throughout) were found by the developers to be 270 ksi and 315 ksi, respectively; elongation to failure was reported at 4%.  This compares favorably with AISI 440C (heat treated to 58 Rc throughout), for which yield strength is 185 ksi, ultimate tensile strength is 254 and elongation is 0.8%.  Perhaps more significantly, the published impact energy of Cronidur 30 is 120 J/cm2 compared with 19 J/cm2 for AISI 440C.  Cronidurs reported mechanical behavior at elevated and cryogenic temperatures is similarly impressive.<P>

Anodic polarization corrosion testing in both H2SO4 and NaCl aqueous solutions conducted by FAG and P&W show that the passive current density of Cronidur 30 is two orders of magnitude lower than AISI 440C.  At least one-order of magnitude improvements in times to failure during stress corrosion tests at 120 degrees Fahrenheit and 98% humidity have also been reported for Cronidur 30.   The developers of the alloy correlate this behavior with solid solution strengthening influences of nitrogen, chromium and molybdenum and the absence of coarse chromium carbides that can set up localized galvanic cells at the steel surfaces leading to pitting. <P>

Simulated bearing tests have been conducted, including those with and without lubrication and those which incorporated cycles of 4-hour periods in salt spray chambers with 24-hour rolling contact fatigue bearing tests.  Cronidur 30 is reported to have demonstrated fatigue lives 26-times greater than that shown by AISI 440C in the lubricated condition and a 4- to 5-fold improvement in wear resistance in the un-lubricated condition.  Furthermore, the FAG/Pratt and Whitney team informs us that in combined salt spray/rolling contact fatigue AISI 440C failed within 10 hours after the first salt spray while the Cronidur 30 continued to perform well after the ninth cycle when the test was terminated.  <P>


<B>Assesment</B><BR>
FAG and Pratt and Whitney appear to have developed an impressive bearing material with properties superior to many alloys currently in use, and it is clear that numerous advanced systems must face increasingly hostile environments and will require materials that can withstand both corrosion and wear.  Affordable materials that meet these severe demands better than the previous generation are worth investigating.  Further evaluation of  Cronidur 30 for other essential properties, including fatigue performance is therefore recommended.  It is also recommended that the alloy be compared with currently used steels and other alternatives, and be considered for near-term applications in systems where significant bearing loads, wear and corrosion are anticipated. <P>


<B>References & Contacts</B><BR>
If you would like further information regarding these materials, please examine the following references.  <P>

H.A. Chin et al., "Cronidur 30- An Advanced Nitrogen Alloyed Stainless Steel for Advanced Corrosion Resistant Fracture Tough Cryogenic Bearings," NASA Earth to Orbit Propulsion Technology Conference, September 1994, NASA Marshall Space Flight Center, Huntsville, Alabama.<P>

H. Berns and W. Trojahn, "High Nitrogen Cr-Mo Steels for Corrosion Resistant Bearings,"  Proceedings of 1991 ASTM Conference on Bearing Steels.<P>

H. Berns et al., "High Nitrogen Steels (HNS) for Corrosion Resistant Rolling Contact Bearings," Proceedings of the 2nd International Conference on HNS, Oct. 10-12, 1994.<P>

W. Trojahn and H.-W. Zoch, "New Corrosion Resistant Martensitic Steels with High Nitrogen Content for Improved Bearing Performance,"  Proceedings of International Conference on  Rolling Element Bearings, Apr. 1991, Orlando, Florida.<P>

