<HEAD>
<TITLE>High-Temperature Structural Metallics Newsletter #4</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>Office of Naval Research-Europe<BR>  Materials Science and
Technology<BR> 
 High-Temperature Structural Metallics Newsletter #4<BR> 
by <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/christod.htm">Julie
Christodoulou</A></H3> 
<P></P>
<H3>Notes from the NATO- Advanced Research Workshop on Protective Coatings   
and Thin Films:  Synthesis, Characterization and Applications
Portimao, Portugal, 30 May - 5 June 1996</H3> 

<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Introduction and General Impressions
<LI>Plasma-Based Deposition Processes
<LI>Chemical Vapor Deposition Processes
<LI>Coatings for Tribological Critical Applications
<LI>Characterization
<LI>Hard Coatings, Structure/Property Relationships
<LI>Thermal Barrier Coatings and Thermal Spray Coatings
<LI>Optical Coatings
<LI>Ion Beam Assisted Processes
</OL>

<B>Summary</B><BR>
The NATO-ARW on Protective Coatings and Thin Films was successful.   
 Highly qualified participants represented nineteen nations and several   
specific fields of study. Sessions during the one-week program included   
Plasma-Based Deposition Processes, Chemical Vapor Deposition Processes,   
Coatings for Tribological Critical Applications, Characterization, Hard   
Coatings, Structure/Property Relationships, Thermal Barrier Coatings and   
Thermal Spray Coatings, Optical Coatings, and Ion Beam Assisted   
Processes.<P>

The topics of the presentations were diverse ranging from Dr. S. Lucus's   
report on the viable application of soft diamond-like coatings as   
intermediate layers onto steel sheet for the automotive market to Prof.   
V. Valvoda's more academic but equally valuable lecture on   
"Characterization of TiN by X-Ray Diffraction."  Significant   
technological advances were reported by Dr. T. Mantyla who has developed   
a surface modification and sealing technique to be used in conjunction   
with thermal spray coatings for improved wear resistance, and by Dr. K.L.   
Lewis who reported on protective coatings for IR-optics that have   
demonstrated at least a four-fold increase in the life of optical lenses   
on the AV-8B.  Thoughtful reviews were also presented; two of particular   
note were Dr. W.J. Ensinger's discussion of ion implantation and ion beam   
assisted deposition processes for improving corrosion resistance, and Dr.   
C. Donnet's review of solid lubricant development for the demanding   
applications of space-based systems.<P>


<B>Introduction and General Impressions</B><BR>
Organized by Prof. Y. Pauleau of Grenoble the workshop was an opportunity   
for fifty-nine participants representing eighteen European countries plus   
the United States to exchange results of recent technical activities and   
to develop the personal relationships necessary for productive   
collaborations.  These goals were met easily.  During the one-week   
program, a number of very good papers were presented, and the structure   
of the workshop promoted numerous opportunities within the one-week   
program for scientists and engineers to meet in small groups and identify   
common areas of interest.<P>

Other goals of the workshop were more lofty.  Evening sessions were held   
to assess current efforts in specific subjects and to identify future   
research goals.  Topics for these sessions included "Polymer Coatings and   
Thin Films," "Replacement of Electrodeposition Processes and   
Electroplated Coatings," "Coatings for Aerospace Applications," and   
finally, "Future Directions in Research and Development of Protective   
Coatings."  In general, the broad technical issues were defined quite   
clearly during these sessions.  For example, the discussion on coatings   
for aerospace applications was introduced by Dr. Christophe Donnet, who   
presented the tribological requirements and physio-chemio requirements of   
lubricants meant to be used in space-bound systems.   This insightful   
introduction focused the discussion on what could be achieved in the near   
term.  While a variety of viewpoints were proposed some truths were   
agreed upon: there is still a need for better performing, longer lived   
lubricants and coatings, and life prediction is not a mature science and   
should receive more attention.<P>

When the topic becomes more esoteric (e.g., where is future research to   
be directed, why and by whom), the product of the group discussions   
becomes less obvious.  The conversation quickly gravitated toward the   
usual debate about the changing balance between research and development   
efforts.<P>

<B>PLasma-Based Deposition Processes</B><BR>
Dr. S. Lucus of Cockerill Sambre, a Belgian steel producer, reported on   
the practical application of soft diamond-like coatings as intermediate   
layers for paint adhesion and corrosion protection.  In the very real   
world of a steel rolling facility, Dr. Lucus' group has demonstrated a   
continuous cleaning and magnetron sputtering process that is capable of   
meeting the 200 to 400 meter per minute speeds at which sheet products   
are produced.  The resulting coating meets the same porosity and adhesion   
standards as the electrolytically prepared coatings it has been developed   
to replace, eliminating the environmental problems of disposal and   
treatment of electrodeposition waste solutions.<P>

<B>Chemical Vapor Deposition Processes</B><BR> 
Prof. G. Wahl of Technische Universitat Braunschweig, Germany presented   
the keynote talk for the CVD session in which he highlighted the   
development of "reservoir coatings" for protection of turbine blades.  An   
intermediate layer exists between the basic material and the passive   
layer.  In the event of spallation or cracking of the passive layer, this   
intermediate layer must be capable of generating another protective   
layer.  Reservoir coatings contain precipitates of Cr- or Al-rich phases   
within the intermediate layer which serve as reservoirs of the reactive   
metals from which the passive oxide layer can be rebuilt.  His work has   
demonstrated how manipulation of the layer film chemistry enables the   
repassivation kinetics to be controlled.<P>

Dr. O. Conde of the University of Lisbon reported some careful research   
on laser-assisted CVD processed boron carbide thin films.  Her group has   
been able to form stable B4C over a broad composition range and to   
precisely control lattice parameters, and therefore composition, by   
manipulating the partial pressure ratios of carbon carrier to total gas   
pressure.<P>

Dr. P. Rodhammer of Plansee AG in Austria demonstrated the applicability   
of pack cementation for depositing SiCrFe coatings onto Cb 752 screws and   
nuts for the European Space Agency.   Here oxidation resistance,   
resistance to thermal cycling at 800 degrees C and adherence to close   
tolerances within complex interior geometries were critical issues when   
determining the film and process technique to be employed.<P>

<B>Coatings for Tribological Critical Applications</B><BR> 
Dr. E.W. Roberts of ESTL in Warrington, U.K. gave the key note lecture,   
"Solid Lubricant Coatings: Their Performance and Applicability at   
Temperature Extremes," which reviewed the results of modeling and   
extensive testing of several lubricant-substrate systems in various   
environments conducted for the European Space Agency.  In summary, in an   
N2 environment MoS2 has 10-times longer life than WS2 at room   
temperature, and both lubricants degrade with increasing temperature.  In   
both N2 and N2 plus 500ppm O2 environments, silver coatings and the   
NASA-developed PS212 performed best at elevated temperatures (> 800   
degrees C), but these coatings are thicker and cannot be used for   
precision components.  At cryogenic temperatures, MoS2 performed best   
compared with lead and leaded-bronze systems, or PTFE component raceways.<P>

Dr. M.T. Dugger of Sandia National Laboratories continued the discussion   
of solid lubricants for space applications.  He has studied three films   
(MoS2 with columnar grains, Ni/MoS2 multilayer approx. 1-micron thick,   
and SbO2-doped MoS2 approx. 2-microns thick) for low earth orbit (LEO)   
where the environment is primarily atomic oxygen.  MoS2 performed best in   
all exposure conditions, retaining tribological properties even after   
atomic oxygen exposure.<P>

Dr. A. Erdemir reported that he and his colleagues at Argonne National   
Laboratories can produce smooth, nanocrystalline diamond and diamond-like   
coatings (DLCs) when using a fullerene carbon source.  He found that   
diamond coatings produced by conventional CVD methods do not graphitize;   
however, because of their hardness, they do induce wear in mating SiC   
components.  Hydrogenated DLCs will begin to graphitize at temperatures   
above 400 degrees C which limits application temperatures.  However,   
because the hydrogenated DLCs are softer they do not induce wear in   
mating components and therefore maintain a lower system frictional   
coefficient throughout wear testing.<P>

A very animated talk was given by Dr. M. Gardos of Hughes Aircraft Co.   
who presented and supported his theory of reconstruction to describe the   
tribological behavior of polycrystalline diamond films.  Reconstruction   
is the reversible process by which hydrogen atoms are liberated from the   
diamond surface as a function of temperature in vacuum.  With time at   
elevated temperature the carbon bonds, which had been left dangling by   
the liberation of hydrogen, link together and a concomitant increase in   
coefficient of friction is observed.  This leads to the speculation that   
the low frictional properties of diamond at room temperature can be   
attributed to a hydrocarbonate-like friction reducing behavior, liken by   
Dr. Gardos to the effect of motor oil.<P>

Dr. C. Donnet of Ecole Centrale de Lyon discussed "Transfer Film and Tribochemistry: Two Key Factors for the Tribology of Diamond-Like Carbon Coatings."  His work is two-fold.  First he has characterized the effects of ratios of the gaseous components (C4H4 and Ar) during processing on coating properties.  By controlling the ratios of the gases and the bias voltages, Dr. Donnet can produce films that are either soft polymer-like DLCs or hard wear resistant DLCs.  He then compared the wear behavior of these two chemically similar coatings with very different mechanical properties.  While both types of film will show similar environmental sensitivity when tested in ambient air, dry air or ultra-high vacuum, the role of the transfer film is considerable.  Performance was found to be largely determined by the effect of wear particles and debris which are clearly functions of the coating type.<P>

<B>Characterization</B><BR> 
One talk in this session was especially well presented and illustrated just how much data can be retrieved from an x-ray diffraction profile when skillfully analyzed.   Prof. V. Valvoda of the Charles University, Prague, Czech Republic compared the Bragg-Brentano and Seeman-Bohlin methods of x-ray diffraction analysis demonstrating how XRD can be utilized to thoroughly characterize the "picostructure" of a film.  Picostructure information includes lattice parameter, residual stress, microstrain, phase composition, preferred orientation and grain size.  If you share an interest in these analyses, I would recommend contacting Prof. Valvoda (valvoda@karlov.mff.cuni.cz); his understanding is rare and valuable.<P>

<B>Hard Coatings</B><BR> 
Prof. J.E. Sundgren of Linkoping University, Sweden presented the key-note lecture titled "New Hard Coatings through Metastable Thin Films."  Metastable thin films are described here as those with extensive defect structures, layered materials and/or those with metastable crystal structures.  Prof. Sundgren reviewed recent efforts in this area including the effects of ion-induced defects in TiN; the development of multilayer films (e.g., NbN-TiN, Mo-V, and TiN-AlN); and the development of hard elastic C-N films composed of crystalline clusters of a cubic phase in an amorphous matrix.<P>

<B>Thermal Barrier Coatings / Thermal Spray Coatings</B><BR> 
Dr. R.C. Tucker of Praxair Surface Technologies, Indianapolis opened the session with a keynote lecture based on his vast experience with thermal spray coatings entitled "The Use of Thermal Spray Coatings for Protection Against Wear and Corrosion at Ambient and Elevated Temperatures." His overview included descriptions of the High Velocity Oxy-Fuel (HVOF), Detonation Gun and Super D-Gun processes which typically produce coatings with thicknesses of between 50 and 2000 microns.  Higher particle velocities are attained with each new generation of thermal spray processes, and higher particle velocities are correlated with better inter-splat adhesion and consequently increased coating densities, better bonding to the substrate and improved wear resistance.  His work continues.<P>

Dr. T. Mantyla of the University of Technology in Tampere, Finland presented the results of his group's efforts to improve the mechanical properties and corrosion resistance of thermal spray coatings through modification and sealing of the surfaces.  In this work a solution of Al(OH)3 and H3PO4 is applied to an as-sprayed coating, allowed to permeate and then heat treated.  During an extensive comparison of several ceramic oxide coatings achieved by different thermal spray techniques he found that the best wear performance was produced by Detonation Gun Spray (DGS) followed by High Power Plasma Spray (HPPS), High Velocity Oxy-Fuel Spray (HVOF), and finally Atmospheric Plasma Spray (APS).  While Al2O3 with 3 percent TiO2 and Al2O3 with 40 percent Zr2O3 were found to be superior to other coatings tested, the composition of the ceramic oxide coating does not affect the wear behavior as significantly as the process technique.  Further, the wear resistance of each coating is improved by the sealing process.<P>

Dr. M.J. Deakin of Cranfield University, UK presented "The Formation of Intermetallic Diffusion Barriers by High Temperature Reaction Synthesis of Sputter Deposited Multilayers."  In this high temperature technique, the aluminum carrier melts and a step-wise reaction produces the intermetallic coating.   Using this process, Dr. Deakin and his research group have successfully produced 3-micron thick PtAl2 layers on IMI834 and TM754 substrates, demonstrating effective oxidation resistance at temperatures up to 700 degrees C.<P>

Dr. K. Rebstock of Daimler-Benz Aerospace, Germany reported on an oxidation protection system for carbon-fiber reinforced silicon carbide composites intended for use as heat shields on the Hermes.  The 100- to 150-micron thick system is composed of three layers applied by PVD or thermal spray techniques.  The first is a C-SiC bonding layer, the second is a B2O3-SiO2 self-healing functional layer, and the outer-most layer provides erosion protection.  Oxidation resistance has been demonstrated to 1600 degrees C during step-wise testing, and the coating is predicted to withstand operating conditions at 1400 degrees C for at least 100 hours.<P>

Dr. K.L. Lewis of the Royal Signal and Radar Establishment, UK presented "Ultradurable Protective Coatings Using Phosphide Materials."  These coatings have been developed to protect IR-optics from the environment while not compromising the functional properties of the substrate.  Of the phosphides studied, boron phosphide is the most interesting for it displays properties similar to diamond-- high strength, hardness and thermal conductivity.  In a collaborative program with Hugh Blackwell at MCAS Cherry Point, a combination DLC/boron phosphide coating has been found to extend the life of optical lenses installed on AV-8B's from 200 hours to more than 800 hours.<P>

<B>Ion Beam Assisted Processes</B><BR>
This session, on the last afternoon of the workshop, was kicked-off by one of the better delivered lectures of the entire week.  Dr. W.J. Ensinger of the University of Augsburg, Germany presented "Protection Against Aqueous Corrosion by Ion Implantation and Ion Beam Assisted Deposition," a discussion of how ion implantation and ion assisted deposition can be used to generate or manipulate metastable alloys at metal surfaces which behave as predicted by normal electrochemical laws.  Specific techniques highlighted in this talk included the implantation of Pt into stainless steel surfaces where Pt acts as a cathode thus shifting the potential to the anodic polarization region and inducing passivation of the stainless steel.  Pd introduced into Ti-alloys by ion implantation provides cathodic protection.  Ion assisted deposition of TiN-Ti multilayers demonstrate orders of magnitude better corrosion resistance than single layers of either because the process prevents columnar growth and the associated porosity at the grain boundaries.<P>

Julie A. Christodoulou<BR>
Office of Naval Research- Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Rd<BR>
London,  NW1 5TH, UK<BR>
tel. 44 171 514 4943<BR>
fax 44 171 723 6359<BR>
e-mail:  jchristodoulou@onreur.navy.mil<P>

