<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>High-Temperature Structural Metallics Newsletter #5</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>Office of Naval Research-Europe<BR>  Materials Science and
Technology<BR> 
 High-Temperature Structural Metallics Newsletter #5<BR> 
by <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/christod.htm">Julie
Christodoulou</A></H3> 
<P></P>
<H3>Notes from the 7th European Conference on Composite Materials: Realising their Potential (Incorporating Metal Matrix Composites - 5)<BR>
London, United Kingdom, 14 - 16 May 1996</H3> 

<B>Summary</B><BR>
This year the 7th European Conference on Composite Materials included Metal Matrix Composites - 5 and focused on the challenges and successes of bringing composite materials to industry.  The one-day plenary session projected a positive picture -- illustrating how decades of composites research have provided elegant solutions to challenges in civil engineering, transportation, aerospace, marine and biomedical applications -- while emphasizing the contemporary mandate of reducing implementation costs.<P>

Two days of technical sessions followed, and these too were dominated by papers describing unique applications of composites technology and manufacturing approaches.  This summary focuses on the papers presented in the Metal Matrix Composites - 5 sessions, including applications of aluminum alloy-matrix-composites for the automotive and aerospace industries.  Additionally, two new approaches to the production of fiber-reinforced titanium-matrix-composite (TMC) rings  originating at DRL (Institute for Materials Research, Germany) and at Oxford University are described.  Also reported here are the development of alumina-aluminide alloys by a reactive powder metallurgy route as described by Prof. Claussen of the Technical University of Hamburg-Harburg, and some advances in the prevention of fiber-matrix interface reactions in TMCs made by researchers at DRL.<P>

<OL>
<LI>General Impressions and Introduction
<LI>Plenary Session
<LI>Applications
<LI>Manufacturing Technology
<LI>Ceramic Matrix Composites and Intermetallics
<LI>Properties and Testing
</OL>

<B>General Impressions and Introduction</B><BR> 
The theme of this conference on composite materials, "Realising their Potential," encouraged participants to approach their subjects in a way dramatically different from the manner most technical symposia are guided.  Focusing on design and means of increasing the market for advanced materials, and highlighting stellar performances of the right composites in the right applications, the proceedings at times took on the qualities of a pep rally.  Participants were uplifted by illustrations of how decades of research and development have made significant contributions to society and industry.  They were also taken aback by the honest picture of the future of R&D presented there, as cost reduction was emphasized as the primary objective.<P>

Overall, I found this meeting useful for taking stock of the environment in which composites research must be conducted.  However, if this theme is invoked more often than every five years or so, it would simply generate a distraction from the fundamental aim of bringing researchers together so that they can benefit by sharing approaches and observations.  The symposium did provide a good opportunity for some researchers and design engineers to point out hard earned successes and truly innovative ideas and approaches to design limitations.  However, it was not a particularly good forum for discussing detailed research work, and some-well developed, well-presented papers were lost in this event.<P>

Incorporation of Metal Matrix Composites - 5 (MMC-5) into the program of ECCM - 7 was an experiment and is not likely to be repeated.  While the two sciences are linked by a number of common technical goals (e.g., the need for reliable non-destructive evaluation methods and the resolution of interface issues), the two technologies are separated by years of development and market presence.  Hence, the two conferences have different objectives, and the participants have different information needs.  Wisely, MMC-6 will be held independently on the former bi-annual schedule in November or December 1997.<P>

The format of the meeting brought all participants together for a day-long plenary session.  On the second and third days, five sessions were run concurrently; one of these was MMC - 5.  I focused on those papers presented in the MMC - 5 sub-sessions: Applications, Manufacturing Technology, Ceramic Composites and Intermetallics, Microstructure and Characterization, and Properties and Testing.  Those papers that I found particularly interesting are discussed briefly below.<P>

<B>Plenary Session</B><BR>
Focused on innovative applications of composites technology and challenges which face mature technologies, this plenary session had a unique character.  The opening discussions and lectures established an optimistic mood as speakers hold of successful implementation of composites in civil engineering, transportation, aerospace, marine and biomedical applications.  "The Innovation Process" presented by Chris Voss of the London Business School, clearly directed toward the entrepreneur, was a positive -- if unusual -- item on the agenda of a technical conference.<P>

One recurrent theme expressed throughout this first session was that while good science and engineering had brought composites to the point that they accepted by designers and society, future efforts must be directed toward cost reduction if they are to be fully exploited.  Dr. Julia King's (Head of Materials for Rolls-Royce) mantra of "Cost, cost, cost," was echoed throughout the session.<P>

Dr. D. Giachardi, Director, Courtaulds Plc., represented the European Union and presented the first formal lecture of the conference.  The European Union places high value on science that directly benefits society and the environment as well as industry, and his discussion emphasized these points.  He stressed two goals of composites research: (1) reducing total lifecycle costs, including recycling; and (2) developing reliable, high-production, low-cost fabrication technologies.<P>

Dr. W. Bonfield, Director of the Interdisciplinary Research Centre (IRC) in Biomedical Materials presented work on artificial bone and joint replacements.  Work at the IRC has produced a synthetic bone that, like natural bone, is a polymer-matrix-composite reinforced with hydroxyapatite.  Mechanical properties of this composite more closely match those of human bone than the monolithic titanium alloys widely used in biomedical applications.  The compatibility of stiffnesses and strengths means that hydroxyapatite-reinforced composite bone replacements are much less likely to fail by aseptic loosening, the current cause of 90% of all skeletal implant failures.<P>

Dr. J. King of the Rolls-Royce Gas Turbine Materials Centre gave a visually beautiful talk on current aeroengine applications of polymer-, metal- and ceramic-matrix-composites.  While showing numerous slides and describing the choices of composites for each application, she emphasized the driving forces that will bring composites to the industry as major players.  Lower life cycle costs, reduced maintenance costs, cleaner air, quieter engines, and reduced fuel consumption can all be realized now by the implementation of existing composites technologies.  However, if these materials are ever to be fully exploited by the aerospace industry, initial costs must be brought down.  The researchers' goals: reducing unit costs of composite materials and reducing the costs of manufacture.<P>

Jean-Michel Guillemot showed-off the nose of the Eurostar as an example of GEC Alsthom's extensive use of polymer-matrix-composites.  Mechanical components and electrical equipment were presented as examples of successful applications in rail transportation.  The next challenge is improving reliability.  Dr. Guillemot then briefly described a current BRITE-EURAM project to develop self-monitoring composites: Structurally Integrated Systems for the evaluation of Composites (SISCO).  The aim of SISCO is a composite with embedded passive optic sensors that can be monitored via active internal or external piezoelectric actuators.<P>

<B>Applications</B><BR> 
Dr. A.M. Walker of A.E. Goetz, UK, presented "Automotive Applications of MMCs -- Piston Technology," outlining some of the recent advances in squeeze casting.  Typically, aluminum alloys with Si, Cu and/or Ni additions are reinforced with between 0.05 and 0.3 volume fractions of Al2O3, yielding squeeze cast materials that have the temperature capabilities of conventional wrought alloys such as RR58.  This alternative fabrication route offers considerable cost savings over forging and machining operations and will be applied to the manufacture of brake components and engine blocks, in addition to the pistons now being made.  Research and development activity is still required to overcome the challenges of fiber wetting and of matrix nucleation onto reinforcement particles.<P>

A.D. Tarrant of Aerospace Metal Composites Ltd. intelligently discussed "Aerospace Applications of MMCs," illustrating where MMCs are currently implemented and sharing development strategies.  Anisotropy, superior damage tolerance and good fatigue performance of SiC reinforced aluminum alloy composites make them viable replacements for graphite reinforced epoxy composites where high stiffness and low density are key properties: upper wing skins, equipment racks, fuselage-to-wingbox connections, etc.  Future research efforts will be directed toward higher temperature capability (to 350 degrees C), incorporation of Al-Li matrices to improve corrosion resistance and reduce the need for complicated heat treatment, and fabrication technologies for graded structures.<P>

R. Young, of AEA Technology, spoke on the application of Al alloys with high volumes (up to 70%) of SiC or B4C for electronic applications.  The composites are produced by first preparing a SiC slurry that is cast into a preform of approximate density of 70% SiC particles; then the preform is infiltrated with molten Al at low pressures.  Typical property values are 5 - 6 ppm/K for coefficient of thermal expansion; approx. 230 W/m K for thermal conductivity; approx. 3 g/cc for density; and more than 20 MPa sq.rt. meter for fracture toughness.  With these properties and costs nearing one dollar per square inch, these composites may be an attractive alternative to beryllium alloys.<P>

<B>Manufacturing Technology</B><BR> 
Dr. R. Leucht of DRL, Institute for Materials Research, Germany described an interesting development at DRL: a new, lab-scale apparatus for continuously coating SiC-SCS-6 fibers via magnetron sputtering, bundling and canning them in preparation for hot isostatic pressing (HIPing).  In this process, two magnetron sputters are activated as fibers are wound onto a rotating cylindrical holding spool which actually comprises 3 of the 4 sides of the HIP can (inner diameter, top and bottom).  The process generates uniformly packed fibers with homogeneous matrix layers.  The fourth side (outer diameter) of the HIP can is then welded in place, and the assembly is HIP'd.  Because coating, winding and canning of the fiber assembly is carried out inside the apparatus under vacuum, environmental contamination is avoided.  Cross plies with different fiber orientation angles can now be produced, and DRL has demonstrated the feasibility of fabricating a fiber-reinforced titanium ring by this method.  Work is underway to magnetron sputter alloy matrices while maintaining composition control.<P>

"Spray/Wind Manufacturing of Hoop Reinforced Ti-MMC Rings" was presented by Oxford doctoral candidate Z. Fan.  This method may develop into a relatively cost-effective, high-production-rate means of producing cylindrical fiber-reinforced composites.  Best results were achieved with a semi-continuous process.  In this process, CP titanium powders are vacuum plasma sprayed (VPS) onto a heated, rotating mild steel drum to form a matrix layer.  Then a single SiC-SCS-6 fiber layer is wound onto the drum by a computerized unit that controls speed and spacing.  Winding speed is reduced, and matrix VPS and fiber winding are carried out simultaneously.  The operation continues as the layers build into a green composite ring which is then HIPed.  Work continues to identify optimal winding speeds and hot pressing conditions in order to achieve high densities with minimal fiber-matrix interaction.<P>

<B>Ceramic Matrix Composites and Intermetallics</B> <BR>
The keynote lecture was given by Prof. Anthony Kelly of the University of Cambridge and President of the Institute of Materials.  In spite of the many accolades, Prof. Kelly remains very practical and approachable.  His talk was entertaining and bright, focusing on issues that must be considered when identifying ceramics to incorporate into composites.  Written at a level suitable for undergraduates, the printed form of the talk would make a good, brief introduction for students.<P>

Dr. C.P. Beesley, representing Rolls-Royce, discussed "Opportunities and Challenges for CMCs in Gas Turbines."  CMCs promise enhanced performance, elevated operating temperatures and weight savings that are attractive to aeroengine designers.  Yet, behavior is difficult to predict as current fabrication methods offer many opportunities for inconsistencies.  Still, contemporary CMCs have their place in aircraft engines: primarily in static components where temperatures are severe and compressive stresses are active.  Rolls-Royce will soon fly simple components, and materials research continues there in an effort to expand capabilities.<P>

Prof. N. Claussen of Technische Universitat Hamburg-Harburg described the development of fully dense Alumina-Aluminide Alloys (3A) by a powder metallurgy route.  Aluminum, alumina and an oxide of an aluminide former (e.g., TiO2 or Fe2O3) are attrition milled, pressed and heated.  Solid state reactions are seen by XRD to initiate at temperatures below the melting point of Al (around 600 degrees C); at approximately 700 degrees C an exothermic reaction is triggered, yielding an alumina- aluminide alloy compact with sufficient strength to be machined.  The compact is then sintered  Composites of TiAl reinforced with up to 50 volume % Al2O3 have been produced; microstructural features are homogeneous and on the order of 3 to 30 microns.  No mechanical property data was presented.<P>

<B>Properties and Testing</B><BR>
Prof. H.J. Dudek of DRL, Institute for Materials Research, Germany, presented three talks on behalf of his colleagues and himself;  "Fibre Protection for TMC High Temperature Application" is briefly summarized here.  Beautiful TEM micrographs were used to illustrate the effectiveness of various barrier layers proposed to prevent fiber-matrix interactions that occur at temperatures greater than 600 degrees C and to prevent the development of thermal stresses at the fiber-matrix interface.  Working with SiC-SCS-6 fibers in an IMI834 matrix they made some interesting observations.
When C-coated SiC fibers in an IMI834 matrix are annealed at 800 degrees C, two boundary layers form: TiC adjacent to the SiC fiber and a titanium-zirconium-silicide in contact with the matrix.  Together the two layers form an effective barrier to Ti and C diffusion and do not seem to diminish mechanical properties.  The silicide is compositionally similar to S2 particles in the matrix alloy and is very stable.  With longer exposures at 800 degrees C the silicide layer thickens and becomes discontinuous, and TiC permeates the silicide layer.  This activity coincides with depletion of Si, Zr, and Sn in the matrix next to the interface.  Researchers at DRL now plan to deliberately add an interfacial layer of the (Ti, Zr)-silicide in an effort to minimize the effect on the matrix composition while still benefiting from the effective diffusion barrier.<P>

Julie A. Christodoulou<BR>
Office of Naval Research- Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Rd<BR>
London,  NW1 5TH, UK<BR>
tel. 44 171 514 4943<BR>
fax 44 171 723 6359<BR>
e-mail:  jchristodoulou@onreur.navy.mil<P>

Please Note:  The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return
to ONREUR newsletters</A>

