<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>High-Temperature Structural Metallics Newsletter #6</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>Office of Naval Research-Europe<BR>  Materials Science and
Technology<BR> 
 High-Temperature Structural Metallics Newsletter #6<BR> 
by <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/christod.htm">Julie
Christodoulou</A></H3> 
<P></P>
<H3>Notes from the Conference on Processing and Design Issues in High Temperature Materials<BR>
Davos, Switzerland; 19 - 24  May 1996</H3>

<B>Summary</B><BR>
Organized by the Engineering Foundation, the conference dealt with a diverse range of material systems with a primary goal of encouraging wide interdisciplinary interaction.  This aim was achieved.  While there were many opportunities for researchers to compare observations and approaches, few "designers" were present so that the meeting was biased toward materials development and evaluation.  A substantial number of the participants were North American, and significant contribution came from the US materials community with reports covering atomic studies to intermetallics, investment-cast superalloys and steels for steam turbines.  Other countries represented were Japan, UK, Germany and Switzerland.<P>

The majority of talks focused on the difficulties of translating good research to commercial products.  Professor Yamaguchi provided a notable exception to this trend -- and indeed a noteworthy example of commercial application of advanced materials achieved in Japan -- in his description of Nissan's establishment of a mass production plant for TiAl intermetallic exhaust valves.  The TiAl valves yield a 40% reduction in weight and an 8% increase in power.  Literature by Nissan (in the form of brochures) was available in which the virtues of the titanium intermetallics and the production plans were outlined.<P>

Papers were partitioned into nine sessions addressing four major themes: Interfaces, Intermetallics and Composites, Ceramics, and Advanced Metallics.  A few of the more interesting reports from each of these major areas and the keynote lecture are summarized below, and additional information is available upon your request.  (All alloy compositions are given in atomic percent.)<P>

<OL>
<LI>Keynote Lecture
<LI>Interfaces
<LI>Intermetallics and Composite
<LI>Ceramics
<LI>Superalloys and Steels
</OL>

 <B>Keynote Lecture</B><BR>
Prof. A. Evans (Harvard) presented the keynote address, a comparison of design and life prediction criteria for two examples of advanced materials which have received considerable attention: ceramic matrix composites (CMCs) and titanium matrix composites (TMCs).  He showed that in many cases these advanced materials now meet performance requirements but are hindered in their application by relatively high unit costs.  His talk stressed the need for materials scientists to interact with designers and displayed a mature skepticism of the likelihood of many of the "new" materials under consideration finding applications.<P>

<B>Interfaces</B><BR> 
This part of the conference dealt with the role of interfaces across a wide spectrum of materials and ranged from atomic modeling studies on the MoSi2/Mo and MgO/Ag interfaces by John Smith of GM and a paper by M.H. Yoo and C.L. Fu (ORNL) on the role of interfaces in deformation and fracture of intermetallics, to the mechanical behavior of austenitic/ferritic interfaces by S. Suresh of MIT.  The basic science of metal interfaces and polycrystalline plasticity were reviewed by M. S. Daw (Clemson) and H. Mecking (Technical University of Hamburg, Germany).<P>

M. Yoo and CL Fu's work on "Interfaces, Deformation and Fracture" focused on the influences of interfaces on mechanical behavior in two-phase intermetallic systems using the alpha-2/gamma and gamma/gamma interlamellar interfaces in binary titanium aluminides as an example.  Yamaguchi's work on psuedosynthetically twinned (PST) crystals had pointed out the apparent anomaly that the alpha-2/gamma lamellar structure in the soft orientation is actually weaker than single phase microstructures of the weaker constituent, gamma.  Yoo and Fu reconciled this by illustrating that dislocation energy is reduced by a factor of two when the dislocation is allowed to glide at the pseudo-twin interface.  The lowest interfacial fracture energy calculated was along the alpha-2/gamma interface.  They further proposed that strain rate sensitivity observed in these materials is the result of hydrogen segregation to the interfaces and a consequent reduction in interfacial energy.<P>

S. Suresh presented one of better papers of the conference, titled "Geometrical Design of Layered and Graded Materials for Optimum Thermomechanical Performance."  He has developed a model to describe and quantify the evolution of strains and curvatures induced in dissimilar metallic layers as temperature is applied.  The model is supported by results of clever experiments designed to evaluate the effects of soft interlayers.  By explosively bonding austenitic and ferritic stainless steels (with and without BN interlayers), he was able to produce samples with controlled layer thicknesses that would induce compressive stresses at key locations in the component, i.e., at notch sites.  Good correlation between predictions and experiments conducted on layered 3-dimensionally printed zirconia-toughened-alumina components illustrated that the model is valid for multi-layered structures of widely different size scales.  By understanding the curvature, where and when plastic deformation initiates can be predicted; then, predictions of crack arrest behavior can be made and applied to real systems to retard fatigue crack propagation.  For instance, insertion of a thin (50 microns) layer of Ni-5Al between a ferritic steel and its Cr2O3 protective coating (typically 400 microns-thick) significantly increases fatigue life as cracks will repeatedly stop in the softest layer.  Providing that the microstructures are stable with stress and temperature, Prof. Suresh proposes that grading can accommodate, shift and control stresses, can control plasticity in metallic subcomponents, and may be a means of changing thermomechanical fatigue behavior.<P>

<B>Intermetallics and Composites</B><BR> 
TiAl-based alloys were discussed by a number of workers.  In joint presentations, R. Wagner (GKSS, Germany) and M. Nazmy (ABB, Switzerland) discussed two alloy systems: Ti-47Al-4(Nb, Cr, Si, B) "TAB" alloy and ABB's alloy Ti-46-2.1W-0.5Si.  The ABB alloy was said to have performed well in Daimler-Benz tests for valves, but costs still present a problem.  It was reported that MTU was testing cast TAB blades in a RB199 rotor designed to operate at 700 degrees C and 16,000 rpm, and that Plansee had made structural panels from TAB materials.  Wagner reported that carbon additions to TiAl alloys increased strength and creep resistance without adverse effects on ductility.  This effect is explained by Ti3AlC precipitation which is believed to interact with deformation twins in gamma.<P>

M. Yamaguchi reviewed the Japanese efforts in TiAl which is sponsored by AIST-MITI and spans years 1989-1996.  Six corporations, 3 Research Institutes and 2 Universities participated.  A separate program by MESC involved 15 Universities for a total of 67 (!!) research teams.  Interim national goals were 280MPa strength at 1000 degrees C and 2% strain at RT.  These goals appear to have been met by alloy of Ti-47Al-2.3Nb-1.0Ta.  Present goals call for 380 MPa at 1000 degrees C and 3% strain at RT.  Industrial successes were highlighted, including Nissan's plans for a production plant to provide TiAl exhaust valve for use in its sedan automobiles and Nippon Steel's Al2O3 -reinforced alpha-two + gamma alloys.  The Nissan production process appears to be based on elemental powders and be based on a binary Ti-45Al alloy.  Rheocasting of Ti-44Al-10% ZrC composites and directional solidification of lamellar Ti-Al ingots was also reported.  Other goals of the national Japanese effort are centered around isothermal rolling and superplastic forming, and it was reported that progress has been made in all areas although no specific results were given.  A special August 1996 edition of the journal Intermetallics will include extensive papers reporting AIST-MITI progress.<P>

M. Lorretto (Birmingham University, UK) presented data on the microstructural evolution in Ti-47Al-2Mn-2Cr alloys, and L. Christodoulou (Imperial College, UK) discussed the role of the morphology of the alpha/gamma phases on the properties of Ti-(45-48)%Al alloys.  It was shown that an acceptable combination of fracture toughness and ductility can be achieved when the equiaxed proportion of the microstructure is in the range of 30-60%.<P>

A. W. Thompson (Lawrence Berkley Laboratory) reported on hydrogen effects in Ti3Al and TiAl alloys.  In alpha-2 H is absorbed at temperatures of 500-650 degrees C at low pressures and stabilizes the "O" phase; strength is marginally improved while ductility and fracture toughness gradually decrease.  In gamma little H absorption occurs at 1 atm, but large uptake is induced at high pressures and temperatures (800-900 degrees C); two hydrides are formed and considerable strengthening is noted.<P>

In-situ composites through reaction processing were discussed by S. Fishman (ONR HQ).  Benefits of in-situ processing include thermodynamically stable composites that have better performance because of their stability and that are often less expensive to produce than composites generated in other ways.  In-situ processing often relies on inexpensive starting materials and simple techniques.  The science is in kinetic biasing, altering the sequences of phases in a transformation pathway and inducing selective phase formation.  For example, in the production of a Ni-Al2O3 composite, the addition of excess oxygen to the Ni matrix prior to reacting forces the formation of a necessarily stable, spinel interface layer.  MoSi2-SiC composites formed by solid state reaction of MoC and Si forces the growth of platelets and equiaxed particles as a function of dissimilar diffusion rates.<P>

D. Miracle (Wright Labs) introduced his cruciform sample geometry for evaluating interfacial failures and the stresses acting on fibers in TMCs.  With data generated from this series of tests, he proposes that one of three different failure mechanisms can be invoked in response to tensile loading, depending on the strength of the fiber-matrix interface.  When the interface is weak, failure occurs by tangential shear at the interface first.  When the interface has intermediate strength, the interface fails in tension after a crack is initiated by tangential shear; and when the interface is characterized as strong, radial cracking in the fiber generates slip into the matrix.<P>

Efforts on directionally solidified silicides and Cr2Nb-Nb aligned eutectics were presented by B.P. Bewlay (GE Center for Research and Development).  Using a CZ process aligned silicide/Laves phase composites were fabricated with up to 60% volume of Laves phase.  Hf and Ti additions were found to improve toughness and oxidation resistance.<P>

Niobium aluminides were discussed by H. Fraser (University of Ohio).  His work on Nb-15Al-10Ti, Nb-15Al-25Ti and Nb-15Al-40Ti  compositions demonstrates optimum strength and ductility (30% elongation at room temperature) in the alloy with 40% Ti.  The lack of ductility observed in alloys with lower Ti content is attributed to the formation of stress-induced martensite which does not form in the 40% Ti alloy.  Chromium additions improve oxidation behavior.  Electron microscopy work continues in order to understand the ordering scheme and deformation mechanisms in these aluminides containing B2, orthorhombic and A15 phases.<P>

NiAl was discussed by M. Kaufmann (University of Florida), and C.T. Liu of Oak Ridge National Laboratory reviewed progress in Ni3Al.  Fatigue and fracture behavior of intermetallics was reviewed by N. Stoloff (Rensealler Polytechnic Institute), and K.T. Rao (UC Berkeley) reviewed toughening mechanisms in composite systems.  Life prediction of TMC in complex flight profiles was discussed by Ted Nicholas (Wright Labs).<P>

<B>Ceramics</B><BR>
High frequency fatigue behavior in the Nicalon/CAS, Nicalon/Si-C-O-N and Nicalon SiC systems was compared and contrasted in a paper by N. Chawla (University of Michigan) with specific emphasis on differing interface characteristics.  Laminar ceramics with and without fiber layers were discussed by F. Lange (UC Santa Barbara) who pointed out the importance of the interface characteristics, i.e., whether strongly or weakly bonded.  Applications for SiC/SiC as first wall materials for fusion reactors were discussed by R. Jones (Battelle NW).<P>

S. M. Wiederhorn of NIST reviewed the creep behavior of Si3N processed by liquid phase sintering.  Work on nano crystalline ceramics at Hughes Phillips Labs was reported by K. Upadhya.  E. J. Brooks (University of Hull, UK) reported on a technique which employs a soft indentor and is claimed to estimate the critical resolved shear stress in polycrystalline diamond.<P>

A. Eckel (NASA Lewis) discussed damage by oxygen and hydrogen on Si-based CMCs, and W. Hillig of RPI gave an analysis of the role of high concentration of H2O vapor on the oxidation of Si-based ceramics.  Other work also at RPI on the effects of processing and environment on the properties of SiC/SiC composites was presented by P. Lipetzky.  F. Petit (University of Pittsburgh) gave an overview of environmental effects observed in ceramic and intermetallic systems, including the more subtle effects can be controlled by modification of processing techniques.<P>

R. Cocheran of Westinghouse, Bettis Atomic Power Laboratory reported on efforts to develop a pack cementation process for imparting direct conversion coatings onto niobium- and titanium-based aluminides.<P>

S.L. Sass (Cornell) presented work on the Ni-Al-O system which under partial reduction conditions can produce Ni/Al2O3 composites.  Ni can be formed as needles or equiaxed particles depending on the temperature of reaction (1200 and 1350 respectively).  Clean interfaces are consistently formed.  However shrinkage associated with the reaction causes cracking. Addition of 10% ZrO2 addition was found to reduce the tendency for cracking but lead to porosity in the alumina, while TiO2 doping speeds the conversion reaction but reduces fracture toughness by weakening the interfaces.  Work continues to identify a means of tempering the ceramic.<P>

<B>Superalloys and Steels</B> <BR>
Superalloys were discussed from a historical perspective by C. Lund of Lockheed-Martin.  His lecture entitled "Superalloys: the Aging Alloys Have Matured," described how motivation and approaches changed during the forty-year effort to produce the materials the aerospace relies on so heavily now.  Over the years these changes in perception caused leaps in performance every fifteen years or so, but increases in performance have been only incremental recently despite maintained levels of research.  For the next leap in capabilities engineers will need to look to other alloys.<P>

New single crystal alloys without rhenium were described by Cannon-Muskegon scientist G. Erickson.  Notable is the fact that these alloys (one with a higher Cr content of 12.5 - 14.5 for use in sulfur-containing environments) were designed with the industrial turbines in mind, and are approximately half the cost of Re-containing alloys such as CMSX-4.<P>

Steels for steam turbines were discussed by R. B. Scarlin (ABB, Baden) in the context of a European COST program to develop and evaluate improved, weldable, creep resistant 9-12% Cr steels.  Target goals are operation at 600 degrees C and 100 MPa for a lifetime of 100,000 hours.  A 40 ton forged rotor has been made from a 10%Cr, Mo, W, V, Nb, N steel.  Material requirements for advanced power generation turbines were discussed by T.B. Gibbons (ABB-CE, USA).<P>

Julie A. Christodoulou<BR>
Office of Naval Research- Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Rd<BR>
London,  NW1 5TH, UK<BR>
tel. 44 171 514 4943<BR>
fax 44 171 723 6359<BR>
e-mail:  jchristodoulou@onreur.navy.mil<P>

Please Note:  The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return
to ONREUR newsletters</A>

</BODY></HTML>
