<HEAD>
<TITLE>Coastal Oceanography Report No. 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>Coastal Oceanography Report No. 1 <BR>
From ONR Europe<P>

28 August 1996<P>

Robert Dolan<P>


Notes on visit to the Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory Bidston Observatory, Birkenhead</H3>


<B>1.	The Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory</B><P>

	The Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory (POL) is one of the five centers of 
ocean/coastal research in the UK.  The other four are the Department of 
Oceanography, Southampton University, University College of North Wales 
(Bangor), the Defense Research Agency (DRA), and the Plymouth Marine 
Laboratory.  Southampton is the largest program (400), POL next (180), DRA 
(80), with Plymouth and Bangor smaller yet.  There are, of course, several 
other university programs in the UK that carry out ocean and coastal related 
research.  Cambridge and Hull, for example, have coastal studies programs, 
and Imperial College in London has a marine program.  <P>

	POL, located about 10 minutes from Liverpool, has been the subject of two 
excellent ONREUR overview articles prepared by John Dugan in 1993 (ESNIB 
9306) and John Dugan and Tom Kinder that same year (ESNIB 93-02).  Dugan and 
Kinders summary of The Proudman laboratory is still applicable:  this is a 
center of excellence in the marine sciences, especially related to the 
coastal sector.  They specialized in storm surge research (modeling and 
prediction), large- and small-scale coastal processes, sediment transport in 
estuaries, the impacts of climate change on coastal and estuarine 
environments, and modeling all of the above.  In conjunction with these 
programs they have an instrument development staff and facility.  <P>

	The research support for POL is about 50 percent directly from NERC and 50 
percent from competitive contracts.  There is a distinct trend within the UK 
to privatize the government laboratories and The Proudman is included.  The 
staff believe that the complete transition to totally competitive contract 
funding for the support of their programs will take place over the next five 
or so years, amounting to a systematic reduction of the NERC support each 
year (i.e. 50%, 40%, 30%, etc.).  It should be pointed out that the current 
50% NERC support is line-itemized in the NERC budget so The Proudman does not 
have to compete for these funds.  In the future they will.  The 
competitors will include other government labs, universities, and private 
industry.  It goes without saying that the latter two groups are quite 
pleased with this trend, and that the labs will probably devote more time to 
short-term projects with application as opposed to long-term basic research.  
The other implication is that this trend will probably move the UK ocean 
researchers further away from systematic data collection programs.<P>

Tel: 0151 653 8633<BR>
Fax: 0151 563 6269<P>


<B>2.	The Agenda for our Meeting</B><P>

People I talked with:  Roger Flather, David Prandle, Peter Hardcastle, and 
Peter Thorne<P>

	We met as a group and had what might be termed a roundtable exchange.  These 
were the topics:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Wave interactions, wave modeling, and storm surge.
<LI>Coastal sediment transport processes, coastal evolution, coastal 
engineering, monitoring coastal processes.
<LI>Water quality and particulate matter in the waters of the North Sea and 
English Channel.
<LI>Operational models for storm surge prediction and coastal flooding (in collaboration with the UK met office).
<LI>The UK national network of tide and sea level observations.
<LI>Modeling coastal systems and prediction of intermediate-scale coastal processes and morphology.
<LI>Coastal defense research in the UK.
<LI>ONREUR's mission in Europe and the new NICOP program.
</OL>

<B>3.	Roger Flather</B><P>

	Roger Flather heads the team of researchers that I talked with, and he is 
clearly one of POL's top scientists.  His field is waves and modeling, 
currently dealing with the impacts of storm surge and currents on wave 
properties.  He has also been a lead investigator for the past several years 
on a project to develop an operational three dimensional shallow-water tide 
and storm surge forecast model for the NW European shelf area.  The spectral 
model, which has a 12 km horizontal resolution, is being developed to run 
operationally at the UK Meteorological Office for predictions of tides, 
surges, currents, and temperature conditions.  Initial comparisons between 
model and observed surges, tidal currents, and temperatures show good 
correspondence.  POL has excellent documentation on this program.<P>

	Flather has also used this model to investigate trends in storm surges over 
a 40-year period using data from the Norwegian Meteorological Office.  Time 
series analyses of the Norwegian dataset show no significant trends or 
periodicities over the 40 year record, which corresponds with the work I have 
done on middle latitude storms impacting the Atlantic coast of the US.  One 
would expect a detectable signal in the storm data if the climate 
(temperature) was changing significantly.  This raises questions regarding 
the recent excitement in the UK regarding climate change.  If Flather 
cannot detect any significant difference in the frequency, magnitude, or 
tracking of the winter storms that move across the North Sea, its highly 
unlikely that any other weather data will show conflicting trends.  I am 
especially interested in just how these storm data were collected.  
Apparently, a final report summarizing the storm data will be available 6 
months.  I have a follow-up trace on the source of the report and the author.<P>

	Flather has also been active in the development of a 'fully coupled spectral 
wave plus 2D tide-surge model' in order to investigate interactions in 
shallow-water between waves, currents, and water levels.  His work shows that 
the influence of wave-current interactions on both waves and surges is 
substantial and in places highly focused (and predictable).  ONR has a place 
in this project in that the design and results are relevant to the 
international Waves in Shallow Environments (WISE) group's efforts to develop 
a community model for coastal wave propagation and transformation.<P>

<B>4.	David Prandle</B><P>

	David Prandle is one of the top young ocean scientists in the UK.  At POL he 
has been designated a 'special merit scientist' which is a distinct honor and 
gives him considerable flexibility to move from project to project 
independent of the institutional or project structures.  <P>

	Prandle is a coastal oceanographer interested in water quality modeling, 
sediment transport processes, modeling, and verification of models with 
empirical data.  His recent work has focused in two areas:  the North Sea and 
Holderness on the east coast of England.  <P>

	In the North Sea project, Prandle is using principal component (PCA) and 
regression analysis to investigate the spatial and temporal patterns or mode 
of variation (sources and sinks) of suspended particulate matter.  This 
program has been underway for several years and has thus been well documented 
by POL.  Although this is an interesting application of PCA and might 
certainly be worth following up, I found his second project, 'Coastal Area 
Modeling for Engineering in the Long Term' (CAMELOT), closer to my area of 
expertise.<P>

	CAMELOT is also called 'The Holderness Project' at POL.  This field 
experiment has been described as a 'mini-Duck' in that the goal was to 
monitor the processes of sediment transport along the Holderness coastline, 
one of the most rapidly eroding coasts in the UK and the largest source of 
sediment to the North Sea.  The specific goal was to record processes (waves, 
tides, currents, etc.) and beach responses continuously over a winter in 
hopes of capturing in their data one or two significant storms.  The database 
is to be used for verification of their numerical models, not unlike the 
series of 'Duck' projects carried out in North Carolina.  The period of data 
collection extended from October, 1994, to March, 1995, with a follow-up 
between October, 1995, and January, 1996.<P>

	The 'core program' of measurements was carried out by POL and the Hydraulics 
Research laboratory.  This included installation of two lines of three of 
POL's ocean monitoring platforms (PMP's) cross-shore that measured vertical 
profiles of currents and suspended sediment using acoustic Doppler current 
profilers developed by POL together with near-bed turbulence and currents 
with electromagnetic current meters, suspended sediment with optical 
transmissometers, and tide, surge, and surface waves.  In addition to the 
PMP, several other instruments were used at the site, including X-ban radar 
for directional wave spectra, directional wave and meteorological buoys, a 
cross-shore array of bottom mounted pressure sensors, and an H.F. Radar 
back-scattered spectra.  The one component of the program that did not work 
out was the effort to record the fine-scale bathymetery.  At the larger or 
intermediate-scale, POL tested the use of remote sensing and conventional 
surveying to record the beach and cliff retreat processes at the site.  
Finally, the RRS Challenger operated in the area during the experiment 
collecting CTD profiles and before-and-after conditions at the site.  
Although the project was designed to focus on the physical attributes of the 
coast, an add-on experiment was conducted dealing with simulating mixing of 
both biological and chemical tracers in the area.<P>

	In addition to an excellent set of data from a high energy coastal site, 
this experiment confirmed the sturdiness of the PMP's that POL uses in their 
field work.  Their data return for the project was 100% and soon after 
installation of the platforms the site was subject to 80 kt winds and high 
seas.<P>

	One of the problems with a field experiment of this type is that few 
governments can support a continuous monitoring program like that underway at 
the FRF at Duck, NC.  In the CAMELOT project, one of the main goal was to 
record the impact of powerful storms but during a defined period due to 
limitations in the budget.  Unfortunately, with the exception of a few 
moderate storms, nature did not fully cooperate during CAMELOT, but plans are 
afoot to develop a European-wide initiative so that a more comprehensive 
coastal monitoring project can be considered.  This be may the seed for a 
European Sandyduck at some point in the next century.<P>

	The CAMELOT data were collected primarily for calibration of models being 
developed in the UK.  The results are only beginning to appear.  For example, 
the wave data alone provide a large synoptic dataset for the study of wave 
transformation in shallow-water, a subject that the POL scientists are 
focusing on.  However, in the final analysis the UK invested in this project 
for the specific purpose of learning about the processes of coastal erosion, 
and hopefully how to address the issue of rapid beach retreat.  This will be 
the primary product of this project: a model that simulates coastal erosion 
under different environmental states.<P>

<B>5.	Peter Thorne and Peter Hardcastle</B><P>

	Peter Thorne is interested in suspended sediment transport processes in 
shallow-water.  His recent research has focused on the development and 
application of acoustics for measurements in relatively high energy 
environments.  In collaboration with Peter Hardcastle, Thorne has developed 
single frequency (3 MHz) and triple frequency (1, 2.5, and 3 MHz) acoustic 
backscatter device that have been successfully deployed in two estuarine 
sites.  The instruments are mounted on a platform called 'Sediment Transport 
and Boundary Layer Equipment' (STABLE) that has been under development for 
several years and is well documented in several POL documents.  In short, 
this is a tripod-like platform that has attached to it a wide variety of 
instruments that can be positioned to look up, down, to the side, and at 
various locations vertically.  The results Thorne is getting are 
encouraging.  Comparing his acoustical data with direct measurements (pumped 
samples) of suspended sediment, the result are close to unity.<P>

	Thorne has not attempted to use his platform in the surfzone, although this 
is something they would very much like to try.  When I described the range of 
complementary data that would be collected at the Sandyduck97 field program, 
there was interest in the possibility of installing some of his instruments 
at the site.  However, we were both aware that Sandyduck is only 10 months 
from the start-up and that it might be too late to consider complicated add-
on experiments at this late date.<P>

<B>6.	R. Dolan</B><P>

	I provided an overview of the functions of ONREUR, and described the new ONR 
Naval International Cooperative Opportunities Program (NICOP) goals, and our 
possible interest in a coastal oceanography initiative.  In the discussions 
it was evident that the POL staff are not just interested in increased 
collaboration with ONR and US coastal programs, but enthusiastic.  I believe 
this can be traced, to a degree, to changes that are taking place in 
government support for research in the UK specifically, and to Europe in 
general.  The trend is for less support and the question of 'value for money 
invested' that seems to be asked at every front.  Application and competition 
are the key words in seeking support for research.  This leads to concern in 
every institution that support for basic research in the UK for the ocean 
sciences will be reduced and that perhaps a tighter connection with a 
large-scale US program would provide at least some continuity with longer-
termed research efforts.  <P>

	In addition, I did not detect a 'hunger' for the ONR NICOP funding.  It 
appears that POL is adequately supported.  Their best people are fully funded 
and can just about choose what they want to work on.  I believe their 
interest in increased international collaboration can also be traced to 
recent positive experiences with European cooperative programs, such as 
MAST.  To close, it is clear that they are convinced that collaboration with 
the US will result in a 'multiplier' effect in their programs.<P>

	The programs that the POL people would like to pursue with regard to 
increased collaboration, with or without NICOP, are:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Technology -- reciprocal deployments of new instruments.
<LI>Modeling -- inter-comparison of model applications (e.g. WAM-WISE)
<LI>Thematic -- suspended sediment, coastal processes, wave dynamics.
<LI>Organization -- modus operandii such as Community Projects in the UK MAST 
programs in the EEC (experience in initiation).
</OL>
	For the longer term, issues they would be interested in considering for 
parallel research programs include:<P>

<OL>
<LI>The impact of climate change (sea level rise, storm frequency, etc.) on coastal estuarine bathymetery and morphodynamics.
<LI>Development and assessment of technology for monitoring coastal systems.
<LI>Development and assessment of generic models for simulating the coastal zone.
</OL>

	Finally, the POL staff believe a positive start would be reciprocal  lecture 
tours by 3 or 4 people from each side of the Atlantic, which would include 
visiting 4 or 5 laboratories for a week each, and a series of workshops at 
the labs during these visit focusing on research topics of interest to both 
groups.  We did not discuss just how this would be funded, although as a 
college professor it sounds like a great idea.<P>

For further information contact:<P>

Robert Dolan<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
Telephone: 44 171 514-4964<BR>
Fax: 44 171 723-6359<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:rdolan@onreur.navy.mil">rdolan@onreur.navy.mil</A><BR>
International address:  223 Old Marylebone Road, London NW1 5TH, UK<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR newsletters</A>
</BODY>
