<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Coastal Oceanography Report No. 2</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>Coastal Oceanography Report No. 2<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<P>

30 September 1996<P>

Diamonds, Coastal Processes, Signal Processing, and Pattern Analysis of the Sea Bed<P>

Heriot-Watt University<BR>
Edinburgh, Scotland<P>

Robert Dolan and Kenneth Lobb</H3>

<I>Key words: Sea bed texture; sidescan sonar; fractal analysis; signal processing.</I><P>

<B>1.	Introduction.</B><P>

	Heriot Watt University is a moderate-sized institution by US standards, but 
has an excellent reputation throughout the UK as a research-based institution 
focused on technological subjects.  Their strongest programs are in 
engineering and various aspects of computer science. <P>

	The program we wanted to learn more about is in the Department of Computing 
and Electrical Engineering where Professor Laurie Linnett's has a research 
team working in computer vision and signal processing.  We had heard about 
their program in image texture analysis and synthesis using fractal and 
statistical processing techniques work while visiting the Defense Research 
Agency (DRA).  We wanted to explore whether there might be opportunities for 
collaboration applications of their analyses in the inshore and shelf-edge 
research.<P>

<B>2.	The Heriot-Watt Research Program.</B><P>

	The goal of the research underway at Heriot-Watt in signal processing is to 
develop methods for extracting subtle patterns from complex fields of data, 
and to reduce data storage problems by developing models that simplify the 
noise and focus on the signals.  Their models are not deterministic; the 
patterns are described in terms of probabilities.  <P>

	Linnetts group, consisting of about 15 graduate and post-graduate students 
and staff, does not include a single earth or ocean scientist; they are 
electrical engineers who have specialized in signal processing.  However, 
their research in recent years has focused on the texture of the sea bed, 
including several projects supported by DRA, so they have gained considerable 
knowledge about the ocean environment through their work.  In addition, they 
have carried out research under contract with DeBeers to investigate patterns 
of sedimentary on the shelf off the Orange River in SW Africa (more detail 
later), and another project supported by a major US airframe manufacturer to 
see if they could detect "difficult to see" airborne targets.<P>

<B>3.	Fractal Analyses of Images of the Sea Bed.</B><P>

	For the past several years, Laurie Linnett and his team has concentrated on 
development of fractal models for texture analysis and synthesis of sidescan 
sonar data of the sea.  Their work has been sponsored by the mine warfare 
group in DRA, who have interest in development of an automated classification 
of sidescan sonar images, particularly in areas where MCM route surveys are 
needed.  In the beginning, the Heriot-Watt group investigated several 
operated-assisted classification systems, concluding that the fractal model 
would be the most useful and flexible.<P>

	The texture analysis problem, given to them by DRA, involved the automatic 
detection of different textures or changes in texture within in a sonar image 
(like a mine).  Basically, they were trying to segment the image into 
separate areas of texture that the human eye sees as "different".  They used 
fractals to produce realistic images of the natural sonar images but they 
wanted to do more, and in particular they wanted to use a fractal model to 
analyze or interpret the images.  The first step was to develop a series of 
fractal dimensions as image descriptors.  Several techniques were tried but 
they have focused on a rather simple calculation that provides a measure of 
the fractal dimension that is adequate for use in texture segmentation.  As 
Linnett described it, "a feature image is produced for each of these 
directions, and this image is then used as an input to a statistical 
classifier".  The modeling is done in the frequency domain and the spectra is 
then transformed to obtain the textural image in the spatial domain.<P>

	The next step in this process is the classification or "pattern
recognition" of the areas in the original sonar image.  Linnett and his team 
have worked with "operator supervised classification" schemes as well as with 
automated "unsupervised classification" schemes.  However, since quite a bit 
is already known about different types of sea bed configurations, it would be 
foolish to ignore this information.  So they incorporate existing information 
in their analyses and it is only in the boundaries that a kind of 
"unsupervised classification" is incorporated.  The "unsupervised" technique 
is described in a paper that is available from Linnett, but in its simplest 
form the method involves looking for clusters in a transformed space.  The 
computer can then automatically identify these clusters and assign a texture 
or "unknown type" to each cloud.  The final step is the segmentation of the 
original image into separate areas of texture that are "different".  This is 
a rather easy step once the pattern recognition or classification has been 
completed.<P>

	The process of synthesizing sea bed textures is important for two reasons.  
First, the ability to mathematically model a sea bed texture can provide an 
important input for the analysis of a given sonar or perhaps the performance 
of a proposed sonar, and second, an important characteristic of texture is 
that different samples of the same texture appear visually identical despite 
the fact that their corresponding pixel values are different.  This 
characteristic can be exploited in the field of image coding, where it may be 
necessary to compress the data from an image for compact storage or, perhaps 
more importantly, for real-time transmission over a limited-bandwidth link.  
By using these fractal texture techniques, Linnett and his team has 
demonstrated a capability to provide a data compression ratio between an 
original sidescan sonar image and the coded images that was about 100 to 1.<P>

<B>4.	Diamonds and Fractals.</B><P>

	Can signal processing and fractal models of the sea bed help find subaqueous 
diamond placer deposits?  This is what the DeBeers Company wanted to know 
when they offered to support Linnetts team to answer this question.  DeBeers 
provided a set of sidescan sonar images of the sea bed off the coast of SW 
Africa near the Orange River delta.  The geologists who work with DeBeers 
have know for decades that the richest diamond deposits outside of the 
kimberlite pipes are the placer deposits associated with the rivers draining 
the pipe areas.  Mining progressed from the land to the sea bed, but with 
each step into deeper water the cost of dredging and processing increased 
exponentially.  In addition, in the deeper water the surface evidence of 
likely areas to mine became less evident.  Therefore, under the assumption 
that there may be a subtle "signal" within the vast field of sea bed data, 
Linnetts team analyzed the DeBeers sonar data and determined that there 
were, in fact, patterns that could be recognized and mapped.  Using their 
fractal modeling and pattern analysis methods, they located patterns that had 
a higher probability of revealing relic fluvial channels.  What this 
translates into is maps not actually showing diamond deposits, but rather 
places where there is a higher probability of success.  By classifying 95 
percent of the sea bed area as low probability, the return on the costs for 
processing millions of cubic meters of alluvial gravels, in water depths of 
up to 100 meters, can be maximized.  This is exactly what the DeBeers group 
wanted, and the Heriot-Watt team delivered.<P>

<B>5.	Simulation of Sidescan Sonar.</B><P>

	Dr. Judith Bell, one of Linnett's recent graduates, has developed a 
simulation model which permits the pictorial visualization of synthetic 
sidescan sonar images.  The main aspects of her model include: Seabed 
reverberation; acoustic propagation; transmission losses; transducer 
directivity; towfish motion and instabilities.  Any of these effects can be 
considered independently or in combination, to permit the simulation of 
complex scenes.  The simulated sidescan sonar are characterized by the input 
parameters describing the transducer environment.  The model therefore 
provides a valuable tool for the testing and visualization of complex 
processing algorithms and the isolation of the influence of individual 
parameters.  Bells work is also sponsored by DRA, and from what we can 
gather it will form the basis for much of their work on future sonar designs.<P>

	There are several aspects of Bell's work that are interesting, but
perhaps the most important is a further step in the development and use of 
fractal models to represent, both visually and statistically, the seabed 
topography.  This permits the calculation of the interaction of the acoustic 
pulse with complex, yet controlled surfaces.  The fractal models we discussed 
above are used to generate images to represent the seabed topography for 
input to the sonar simulation model.  This technique removes any assumptions 
regarding flat sea beds and the sea floor can be represented as a random 
rough surface.  Dr. Stuart Clarke, another one of Linnetts recent graduates, 
is taking Bell's results and models to investigate ways to analyze existing 
sonar data and, in particular, work on schemes to reprocess the sonar images 
for different depths, azimuths, roll angles, etc., to help provide a good 
registration with other/previous sonar images.<P>

<B>6.	Coastal Applications and Possible Collaboration.</B><P>

	During our initial visit to Heriot-Watt, and subsequent discussions with 
Linnett and has group, we have explored possible applications of their 
pattern analyses in coastal applications.  One could asked, if they can find 
placer deposits on the sea bed, it would seem that this could be extended 
into forms and motions in the inshore zone.  Since they are not geologists or 
oceanographers, and we are not signal processors, these follow-up discussions 
regarding possible collaboration were based to a considerable degree on logic 
and intuition.  However, we are convinced that this is an area worth 
investigating, especially within the groups working on intermediate-scale 
coastal processes.  As our databases become larger, we will need to classify 
and compress.  The Heriot-Watt group seems to be on the way to reaching both 
of these goals.  <P>

	Linnett's team consists of extremely bright young dedicated people, with 
enthusiasm for their work, and eager to expand their applications.  
Collaboration with US coastal scientists would be welcomed, especially with 
DRAs interest in expanding their US connections.<P>

 	The key individuals at Heriot Watt are:<P>

Professor Laurie Linnett<BR>
Dr. Judith Bell<BR>
Dr. Stuart Clarke<BR>
Dr. Bryan Calder<P>

Department of Computing and Electrical Engineering<BR>
Heriot Watt University<BR>
Edinburgh, Scotland<BR>
Tele No:  44-131-451-3357<BR>
FAX:  44-131-451-3327<BR>
e-mail <A HREF="mailto:lml@cee.hw.ac.uk">lml@cee.hw.ac.uk</A><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the authors 
and do not reflect official US Government, US Navy, or ONREUR positions.<P>

For further information contact:<P>

Robert Dolan<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
Telephone: 44 171 514-4964<BR>
Fax: 44 171 723-6359<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:rdolan@onreur.navy.mil">rdolan@onreur.navy.mil</A><BR>
International address:  223 Old Marylebone Road, London NW1 5TH, UK<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR newsletters</A>

