<TITLE>Coastal Oceanography Report No. 3</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>Coastal Oceanography Report No. 3<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<P>

10 October 1996<P>

Robert Dolan<P>

Notes on a visit to the Defense Research Agency<BR>
Winfrith, Dorset</H3>

<I>Key words:  Applied coastal oceanography, mine warfare.</I><P>


<B>1.	The Defense Research Agency (DRA).</B><P>

	The DRA program at Winfrith focuses on military applications in 
oceanography.  It's staffed with about 50 scientists, and has about 30 others 
working under contracts.  They have a satellite remote sensing group, headed 
by John Scott, and an active applied coastal research program, headed by Tony 
Heathershaw.  DRA conducts in-house research, and they support research 
through contracts ranging from basic through to specific problem-solving for 
the military.  <P>

People I talked with:  Graham Jackson, John Scott, and Tony 
Heathershaw<P>

(01305 212762)<P>

<B>2.	DRA Research Program.</B><P>

	Currently, the highest research priorities at DRA are shelf-edge and 
shallow-water processes; what might be termed the mine warfare and amphibious 
planning; and development of capability in rapid environmental assessment.  
DRA has supported the signal processing research underway at Heriot-Watt 
(report No. 2 in this series), and they are also pressing to better 
understand marine aerosols and boundary layer processes in response to the 
threats in chemical warfare.  <P>

<B>3.	Purpose of Visit.</B><P>

	My purpose was to assess DRA's interest in collaboration with ONR-supported 
coastal scientists, to discuss specific areas of interest and opportunities, 
and to learn more about their interest and support in signal processing of 
sidescan sonar data.<P>

<B>4.	Discussion with Graham Jackson.</B><P>

	Graham Jackson, who heads the DRA program at Winfrith, stated in our discuss 
that the position within his program and the operational people in the 
Ministry of Defense (MOD) is that there is a 'total lack of capability in the 
prediction of intertidal zone processes and morphological change at 
sufficient resolution to be of fundamental value to MOD, and that little is 
known regarding aerosols.'  He also stated that from the standpoint of the UK 
military applications, there's little confidence in the linkage between 'what 
we know about coastal processes and our capability to predict for specific 
naval applications.' Graham is convinced that there would be considerable 
support from MOD for increased dedication of resources into that area for 
1998, and perhaps some re-directed resources for 1997.<P>

	DRAs  primary customer, MOD, has high exceptions for rapid advances in 
these two areas.   Jackson's use the term 'customer' reflects the fact that 
DRA is one of the UK laboratories that is undergoing transition into a 'privatized' form of operation.  This means that they compete for contracts 
and support, which will probably lead them away from longer-termed projects 
that ONR would consider 6.1 or 6.2, and toward shorter-termed problem solving 
and application.  This trend in the UK toward 'value received for money 
invested' appears to be the future for the ocean science and technology 
laboratories.  The change from line funding in the NERC budget for the 
oceanography laboratories to full-scale competitive programs will probably 
come sooner than later, and will eventually involved about 15,000 people in 
these labs and facilities.  The field competing for the research projects 
will include the major research laboratories, universities, and private 
consulting firms.<P>

<B>5.	Discussion with John Scott.</B><P>

	John Scott is an oceanographer/modeler who works with satellite remote 
sensing.  He has considerable experience with European satellite data and he 
has good working relationships with several ONR/NRL investigators.  I didnt 
spend much time with Scott simply because the scale of his work is too small 
[coarse] for my focus while with ONREUR; that is, the wave transformation 
zone and inshore processes.  However, he did offer suggestions for contacts 
in the UK and he did express interest in the concept of the NICOP program and 
the opportunity to expand his international connections.<P>

<B>6.	Discussion with Tony Heathershaw.</B><P>

	Tony Heathershaw is a valuable source of information for anyone interested 
in the coastal oceanography and geology in the UK and Europe.  He's a 
physical oceanographer who has made several important contributions in the 
field of shallow-water processes and modeling.  Tony has extensive experience 
in working with most of the better known European coastal scientists, and he 
is familiar with the U.S. coastal research community.  Anyone interested in 
making a UK/European connection in the coastal field should start by 
contacting Tony Heathershaw at DRA.<P>

	Specific projects that Heathershaw and DRA would be interested in 
collaborating on would develop around work already underway, taking advantage 
of the modeling skills and complex coastal environments of the UK, and the 
strong data collection and verification opportunities that the US could 
offer.  He believes, from the standpoint of DRA's priorities, a focus on 
improvement of our ability to model and predict intermediate-scale processes 
would be a welcome element to their program.<P>

	Another area of special interest in their program is sediment concentrations 
in the inshore zone, including the variations in turbidity plumes and 
associated changes in the acoustical properties.  DRA has and continues to 
support research to develop models and instruments, but have had few 
opportunities to carry out calibrations under a range of field conditions.  
The type of data they are interested in is being (or planned) collected at 
the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers Field Research Facility at Duck, North 
Carolina.  Heathershaw is convinced that DRA has instrumentation that would 
be of interest to US investigators that could be adapted to the Duck data 
collection effort.<P>

<B>7.	DRA's Interest in Signal Processing.</B><P>

	DRA has supported research in signal processing and pattern recognition of 
sea bed configuration for the past several years.  This is an extension of 
the UK approach to MCM using the route survey approach.  As most of you no 
doubt know, today's mines are tough, they are difficult to find, they are 
very smart, and they are relatively inexpensive.  Development of methods that 
makes it easier to identify them and predict their behavior in areas of 
common deployment (the surf-zone) is a high priority at DRA.  The remote 
sensing, signal processing, pattern analysis approach underway at Heriot-Watt 
and DRA Bincleaves is an extension of this need.  Douglas Carmichael, who is 
at DRA Bincleaves, is a graduate of Laurie Linnett's program at Heriot-Watt 
(see my report number 2 for more on Heriot-Watt).<P>

<B>7.	Summary.</B><P>

	It appears to me that there are several areas of mutual interest in the DRA 
and ONR/NRL research programs that would be worthwhile to explore.  Clearly, 
any focus on sediment mobilization in the surfzone will be of interest on 
both sides of the Atlantic, and our UK colleagues have dedicated considerable 
time and resources in the development of instruments and models in this 
field.  Their work in signal processing and pattern recognition may also be a 
valuable avenue to pursue; however, I admit only modest knowledge regarding 
this complex subject and recognize that we have, in the US, competitive 
programs underway in this area.  Finally, I was struck by the similarity of 
their specifically expressed needs in what is termed 'rapid environmental 
assessment' and the discussions that I heard at NRL during the course of the 
ONR/NRL coordination meetings last May.  If Graham Jackson and Tony 
Heathershaw did not have British accents, I would have thought I was hearing 
an echo of the discussions at NRL.  <P>


The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the authors 
and do not reflect official US Government, US Navy, or ONREUR positions.<P>

For further information contact:<P>

Robert Dolan<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
Telephone: 44 171 514-4964<BR>
Fax: 44 171 723-6359<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:rdolan@onreur.navy.mil">rdolan@onreur.navy.mil</A><BR>
International address:  223 Old Marylebone Road, London NW1 5TH, UK<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR newsletters</A>

</BODY>
