(44) (0) 1491-825743<BR> 
<A HREF="mailto:rls@hrwallingford.co.uk">rls@hrwallingford.co.uk</A><P>

Workshop Deliberations<P>

The participants initially developed a list of 45 topics related to cooperation and methods of conducting collaborative research (Appendix 1), which were categorized and prioritized. The participants concluded that effective collaboration was best accomplished by having European and US investigators directly working together on  specific projects.  That is, it is better to have a modeller working directly with a field investigator as opposed to making the data and the model "available" on the World-Wide Web.<P>

Following the initial discussions, the workshop participants concluded that the opportunities for successful collaboration could be organized under three general subject areas, which in turn provided structure for further discussions and subgroups.  The participants met, however, several times collectively to discuss the specific recommendations of the three subgroup "teams".<P>

<B>SURFZONE HYDRODYNAMICS:</B>  Team Leader A. Dalrymple with R. Flather and R.  Diegaard<P>

<UL>
<LI>The objective of the hydrodynamics modelling effort is to understand the nearshore wave climate and nearshore circulation system, and to provide the fluid forcing of the sediments in the nearshore zone due to waves and currents.  This area includes wave and current modelling, and can include turbulence.  Generally, deepwater waves are treated with spectral models, while in the nearshore zone other models (parabolic, Boussinesq) are used.
</UL>

<B>Wave Modelling</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Boussinesq models developed in Europe and North America propagate waves from deep-water to the surf-zone with reasonable accuracy.  These time-domain models have an active community of international researchers on both continents that would benefit from collaborative efforts on such topics such as the implementation of wave breaking, wind-generation, wave-current interaction, long-term current generation.
<LI>Rather than working in the time-domain, which is good for short-time scales, numerous frequency-domain models exist that were developed specifically for the shallow-water propagation of wave spectra with wind generation, and those that simply propagate a given spectrum.  The wind-generation spectral modelling, the Dutch (SWAN model) has a strong user-base.   This model propagates the spectrum accounting for varying depths and wind input.  Two and three-dimensional computational fluid dynamics (CFD) modelling has begun to treat such problems as detached run-up and plunging breakers.
<LI>Another important area of research is in stochastic wave modelling.  Unknowns in the input wave and wind conditions, and the uncertainty in the exact bathymetry, lead to errors with deterministic models.  Quantifying these errors would be an important contribution.
<LI>Hydrodynamic forcing produces an oscillatory boundary layer in the vicinity of the bed, which plays a role in the hydrodynamics, but perhaps more importantly, in sediment transport mechanisms.  This boundary layer has been investigated in laboratory experiments (flumes, oscillatory water tunnels), field experiments, and by turbulence models; however, additional field and laboratory verification is needed to explain discrepancies between models and the field.  New investigations should be at scales appropriate to field conditions, and should fill in parts of the parameter space not covered by previous experiments -- and be capable of measuring maximum as well as mean bed shear stresses.  The experiments should cover immobile, rough, as well as mobile beds.  Both total and skin-friction shear stresses are important.  New instrumentation (acoustics, for example) gives hope of acquiring better field data.
<LI>Suspended sediment has an impact on the turbulent boundary layer through stratification effects.  This subject has not been treated satisfactorily to date, and the vertical exchanges of sediment and momentum need further research. 
<LI>In the case of a loose bed, ripple and mega-ripple formation is an important factor for flow resistance and energy dissipation. Although studies of ripples has been carried out by numerical modelling (discrete vortex models and turbulence models), further research in this field is needed.
<LI>The current model discussed below provides the hydrodynamic inputs to sediment transport calculations, there are important feedback mechanisms.  Changes in bottom depth, bed forms, suspended sediment concentrations affect the hydrodynamic calculations.  This information has to be input in the wave model in a simultaneous manner.
</UL>

<B>Current Modelling</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Although running a Boussinesq model over a long time period leads to currents, there is an economy in the use of vertically averaged models to predict nearshore currents.  On-going research in the US  and Europe could benefit from collaborative work on such topics as the influence of 3-D currents, complicated bathymetry, low-frequency motions, friction factor selection, wave-current interaction, and how to use spectral wave information into the hydrodynamic model.
<LI>Cross-shore flows (including undertow) are important for the 2- and 3-dimensional circulation system.  Recently the importance of these flows in influencing the mean nearshore circulation have been elucidated.  As these flows are important for onshore/offshore sediment transport, further research is needed.
<LI>Low frequency motions and instabilities of the nearshore current system are  areas of active interest in both North America and Europe.  How these circulation systems evolve with time to full nonlinear circulation systems is of great interest.  
</UL>
 
<B>Turbulence</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>For both wave and currents in the nearshore zone, turbulence due to the rough bottom and wave breaking is important.  Models have been developed for turbulence (k-epsilon, large eddy simulations) but more work is needed.  The influence of bottom roughness elements, such as ripples, in generating turbulence has received some attention, but the importance of these structures in the hydrodynamics modelling has not been fully explored.  Obliquely descending eddies have been observed to play a role in sediment transport and nearshore mixing by Japanese scientists.
</UL>

<B>Data  Model, Large Lab, and Field Comparisons</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Numerical models require initial and boundary conditions.  In the field, that would dictate a number of gages on the outer boundaries of the model area. There are interesting problems in determining how to start a model with lots of grid points on the offshore row with data from a small number of gages.  How are the remainder of the offshore grid points initialized in a rational way?  In a wave tank, the problem is simplified to two-dimensions and thus more easily modelled. Large wave tanks (such as the Delft Delta Flume and the Hannover Grossen Wellenkanal) are facilities that offer opportunities for modelling in a laboratory at full-scale.  This offers strong possibilities for collaboration.
<LI>Skill criteria needs to be developed to determine how models behave and the degree of disparity between models and data due to random and systematic (bad physics) errors.
</UL>

<B>Data Assimilation</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Running models in 'quasi-real' time permits the use of more than initial and boundary conditions.  Data from within the model data domain can be used to steer the model to a more "correct" solution.  Data assimilation techniques are well-known in meteorology or blue-water oceanography, but have rarely been used in the nearshore field.
</UL>

<B>Testing European Models With US Datasets, Developing Standard Datasets, and Diagnostic Model/Data Tests.</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>There is a need for calibration of existing hydrodynamics models with existing field data. By providing a standard set of data runs, the US field modellers can provide the base for a fruitful collaboration with the European modelling community.  One purpose of this comparison is to determine the differences between models and the data, implying a problem with the physics inherent in the model.
</UL>

<B>Methods for Collaboration</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Collaborative projects between European and U.S. scientists have been developed in the past to facilitate scientific advancement.  The joining of complementary research capabilities can pay important dividends for a research topic.  Based on experiences with the European MAST program and other collaborative efforts, it is evident that some methods foster this process and others do not.  The best approach is to bring together people with a common interest for periods of time greater than a few days or a week. These visits could be in the form of sabbatical visits, or extended visits of investigators between institutions. Also successful are joint research projects that have balance in responsibility.  Methods that do not work so well are periodic meetings of short duration where ideas are discussed but there is little or no follow-up.
</UL>

<B>Recommendations for Collaboration</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>ONR-Europe Fellows:  A proven approach to successful long-term collaborations is the development personal contacts between researchers.  A program that would fund the exchange of recent Ph.D. recipients between research institutions would rapidly develop collaborative relationships and long-term contacts.  This could also be done through  the use of post-docs on a project-by-project basis.  <P>
<LI>Field-modeller Collaborations:  The example in the US of a dichotomy between those who gather field data and those who develop models offers guidance for collaboration between modellers and field investigators.  These relationships result in publications that give credit to both.<P>
<LI>Model Intercomparisons:  There are examples in Europe of model comparisons with numerous laboratories running their models on a standardized data sets (idealized or real).  The result shows discrepancies, but the long-term result is that all the models are improved.  These competitions would be useful in several areas of research--Boussinesq models would be one example for cases where wave breaking is included.  Funding would be needed to develop the standardized datasets and to fund the modelling efforts.
</UL><P>

<B>SMALL-SCALE MORPHOLOGY AND SEDIMENT TRANSPORT:</B> Team Leader E. Thornton with A. Bowen<P>

<B>Process of Sediment Transport</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>The processes of sediment transport and small-scale morphology have time-scales ranging from seconds to hours with space-scales from centimeters to meters. The process of sediment transport and evolution of small-scale morphology are the least understood of the processes in the nearshore environment.  The science/technology objectives are to measure and predict sediment transport and small-scale morphology ranging from vortex (wave) ripples to cross-ripples to mega-ripples until a critical stress is achieved and the bed is flattened under sheet-flow conditions.  <P>
<LI>Small-scale processes integrate to the large-scale morphology; therefore, our understanding of the small-scale processes is essential to our ability to predict large-scales coastal phenomena. Small-scale morphology determines the mode of sediment transport and feeds back to the hydrodynamics though enhanced stress due  to increased bottom roughness.  For example, during Duck94 the bed shear stress coefficient inferred from measured profiles of the longshore current varied by an order of magnitude across the surf-zone as the small-scale morphology varied from wave ripples offshore, to mega-ripples approaching the bar, planar-bed on the top of the bar, mega-ripples again in the trough and planar on the foreshore.  This variation of the bed shear stress coefficient is not presently incorporated in hydrodynamic models and may account for much of the observed discrepancies in model/data comparisons.<P>
<LI>Europeans, funded under the MAST program, have focused on model development and laboratory studies.  Model development is this area includes wave boundary layer and sediment transport models.   Unique European laboratory facilities include several proto-type scale wave flumes and water tunnels.  U.S. coastal scientists have excelled at hydrodynamic and morphologic measurements in the field.  The research carried out by the two communities is complimentary.
</UL>

<B>Goals</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Test European sediment transport models using U.S. field data.
<LI>Evaluate, and further develop, existing sensors for the measurement of sediment transport.
<LI>Develop improved hydrodynamically driven sediment transport and small-scale morphology models and test using lab and field data.
<LI>Perform joint U.S./European field experiments
<LI>Inter-compare new technologies to measure sediment transport and small-scale morphology. 
</UL>

<B>Approach</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>There is a growing suspicion that the present knowledge of  bottom stress related to wave and current forcing, which are essential to our understanding of sediment transport and small-scale morphology, is based on inadequate parameter space.  Most of the data used in this research area is derived from laboratory studies.  There is a consensus for the need for proto-type scale data from both large-scale laboratory facilities (flumes or tunnels) and the field.  A natural collaboration would be to utilize the new instrumentation that has been developed in the U.S. for field experiments, and wave boundary layers in a large-scale flume such as those at Delft Hydraulics or Hanover.  A laboratory experiment allows selecting the input wave conditions and the simplification of a 2-D problem.  The lab also offers the possibility of differentiating between total stress (important to the hydrodynamics) and skin friction (important to the sediment transport), which is not possible in the field.  New instrumentation includes the Bistatic Coherent Doppler Velocimeter (BCDV), acoustic sediment profilers, acoustic bottom profilers, bubble meters, and PIV.  For example, the BCDV measures the profiles 3-components of velocity and sediment mass over the bottom 1 m of the boundary layer at 20 vertical intervals varying between 1 - 5 cm (programmable) sampled at 48 Hz  and resolved at 1 cm.  Using the BCDV wave and Reynolds stresses can be profiled within the wave boundary layer.  The high resolution sonic scanner measures small-scale morphology every 2 cm in an x,y grid over a 3 m square area at mm vertical resolution.  The amount of bubbles in the water column are inferred using void fraction meters that measure the conductivity.  Vertical arrays of void fraction meters can be used to examine the depth of turbulent injection of bubble under breaking waves.   These and other new instrumentation used in a controlled laboratory experiment could greatly increase our understanding of wave boundary layer and sediment process under breaking waves.<P>
<LI>International collaboration would include exchange visits to test sediment transport and hydrodynamics models developed under the MAST programs with field data acquired under the ONR-funded NSTS and DUCK experiments.  A positive example of such a collaboration was between Delft University of Technology and the Naval Postgraduate School in which Reniers applied the Dutch-developed quasi-3-D model to demonstrate that the alongshore pressure gradients due to wave breaking over alongshore inhomogeneous bathymety could explain why a longshore current maximum can occur in the trough of a barred beach.  Field data is essential to test the large-area 3-D hydrodynamic/sediment transport models.<P>
<LI>Opportunities for joint U.S. and European collaborative field experiments  should be explored.  The U.S. scientists have experience, expertise and instrumentation resources, gained from a number of large-scale nearshore field experiments. Collaborations on several field experiments have been successful.  These include field experiments at Skallingen, Denmark, between Brian Greenwood (U. of Toronto) and Troels Agaard (U. of Copenhagen), and participation by Chris Vincent (U. of East Anglia) with Dan Hanes (U. of Florida) in SandyDuck.  Short-term opportunities for collaboration should also be explored, including involving additional Europeans, either as investigators or observers at Sandy Duck, and collaboration of U.S. investigators in future MAST-funded field programs.  Long-term field collaborations should be fostered through workshops and joint planning.<P>
<LI>Ongoing efforts of inter-calibration (standardization) of experimental techniques for the measurement of sediment transport should be continued and fostered.  For example, Alex Hay (Dalhousie) and Arjen Schaafsma (Delft Hydraulics) have been working together on acoustic backscatter theory and techniques applied to the measure of sediment concentration and size.  
<LI></UL> <P>

<B>Suggested Topics for Collaborative to Improve Models for the Prediction of Sediment Transport and Small-Scale Morphology:</B><BR> 
 
<UL>
<LI>Benthic boundary layer dynamics and turbulence, a focus in MAST leading to extensive intercomparisons of European models.
<LI>Parameterisation of complexity. 
<LI>Simple models (Baillard/Bowen), are being evaluated in both Europe and North America. 
<LI>Self -organised models (Werner), offer a new view of simplexity data assimilation, using observed hydrodynamics.
<LI>Diagnostic use of model/ data comparisons.
<LI>Small-scale morphology development.
</UL>

<B>Benefits Of Collaboration</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>The Europeans possess complimentary large-scale laboratory facilities and expertise in sediment transport models; the Americans have developed new instruments and rich databases of field measurements with which to test models.  Combining the expertise of these two communities will accelerate the development of new models, measurement techniques, and data to test the models.
</UL>

<B>LARGE SCALE MORPHODYNAMICS: </B>Team Leader H. de Vriend with R. Soulsby and R. Holman<P>

<B>Science/Technology Objectives:</B><BR>	
<UL>
<LI>To understand and predict- the behavior of open, wave-dominated sandy coasts at various time scales, below and beyond the horizon of the prediction capability of physics-based models.
</UL>
 
<B>Importance Of Topic:</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>The coast is a highly nonlinear system, which means that there may be inherent limits to the predictability of its state. The ability to understand and predict this state is essential to assess its susceptibility to adverse evolution. The large-scale morphology determines, to a considerable degree, the smaller-scale hydrodynamics and morphology, and hence the short-term variability of the system and its vulnerability to extreme events.
</UL>
 
<B>Goals:</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Short-term:<UL>
<LI>To develop techniques to quantify the observed (or modelled) behavior of the coast.
 
<LI>Define measures of skills of models in predicting;

		<DIR>(a) the mean coastal evolution,</DIR>
		<DIR>(b) the natural variation with respect to this mean,</DIR>
		<DIR>(c) the impact of extreme events,</DIR>
<LI>To identify the horizon of predictability of the system's state,
<LI>To identify the horizon of prediction capability of models.</UL>
<LI>Intermediate:<UL>	
<LI>To make sure that long-term data-sets continue to be built up, via the application of existing techniques and the implementation of cheaper new technology; since the coastal system is nonlinear, the availability of consistent, high-density information over long time spans is absolutely essential to its understanding.</UL>
<LI> Long-term:		
<UL>
<LI>To extend the horizon of prediction capability of models,
	<DIR>(a) via improved process descriptions.</DIR>
	<DIR>(b) via data assimilation.</DIR>
<LI>To improve the insight into the capabi-lity of models to reproduce coastal behavior and into their sensitivity to the inclusion of terms/processes (science-oriented angle).
<LI>To identify the "minimum model" to adequately describe the aspects of coastal behavior which are essential to answer specific questions in a particular case (practical-oriented angle).
<LI>To develop a thoroughly underpinned top-down approach, which links input conditions to the coastal behavior to be expected.    
</UL> </UL><P>

<B>Approach: </B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Bottom-up, via integration of detailed physics-based models (white-box approach) and top-down, via empirical models based exclusively on data (black-box approach) and behavior-oriented models based on a combination of data and physical knowledge (grey-box approach).
</UL>

<B>Benefits Of Collaboration: </B><BR><UL>
<LI>To achieve the above goals, it is necessary to bring together the following four elements:<UL>
<LI>Data on the physical processes at work (mainly US-based),
<LI>Process-based models (mainly EU-based).
<LI>Long-term data on coastal behavior (partly US-based, partly EU-based, partly from elsewhere in the world).
<LI>Long-term models (not yet readily available, but being developed in MAST).</UL>
 
<LI>There is clearly significant benefit of US-European collaboration.  Apart from this, interdisciplinary collaboration may be of great use here, especially at the data-oriented end of the spectrum. Comparison with similar nonlinear systems, such as the atmosphere (weather, climate) may be enlightening.</UL>

<B>Opportunities: </B>
<UL>
<LI>Starting from the assumption that, in order to be feasible, NICOP-activities should be linked to on-going projects or existing research networks, there are good opportunities in European via the MAST-program, and SANDY DUCK 1997 provides a good opportunity in the US.
</UL>

<B>Facilities/Technology:</B><UL> 
<LI>To achieve the goals, the following facilities and technology are needed:<UL>
<LI>Access to existing long-term datasets.
<LI>Long-term monitoring programs (including measurements of the external forcing parameters such as waves and tides), and improved enabling technology.
<LI>Adequate access to state-of-the-art physics-based morphodynamic models.
<LI>Techniques to predict the behavior of stochastically forced nonlinear systems.
<LI>Techniques from systems theory (model fitting, data assimilation, diagnostic use of model/data-comparison).
<LI>Facilitation of researchers' exchange, extensive wor-king meetings, etc.</UL></UL>
 
 <B>Examples of Possible NICOP Large-Scale Morphodynamics Projects</B><UL>
<LI>Measures of model skill.<UL>
<LI>Have a workshop on the definition of measures of model skill, in such a way that these measures can be applied to rate a given model's performance in a particular case.
<LI>Realization: get modellers and data gatherers from US, EU (and possibly from other continents) together in a workshop/working session to generate ideas and possibly establish a first version of a set of skill measures.</UL>
<LI>Exchange during field programs. <UL>
<LI>Enable international scientists to participate or attend field campaigns (e.g. SANDY DUCK, Egmond, Teignmouth) and interact with the researchers present there. It may be necessary to explicitly organize a working meetings in order to make this happen.</UL></UL><UL>
<LI>Predictability horizon.<UL>
<LI>Organize a working session, including specialists from other disciplines dealing with nonlinear systems and pattern analysis, for the identification of predictability limits inherent to the coastal system. Links in with ongoing MAST-work and needs ARGUS-data for input.</UL></UL><UL>
<LI> ARGUS-program<UL>
<LI>Increase European participation in the Argus program. Develop teams to investigate top-down and bottom-up modelling.  The objective would be to improve the characterization of the coastal behavior (model-based data reduction) and to test various types of models against the data available (also: blind tests).</UL></UL><UL>
Support data for ARGUS-stations<UL>
<LI>Support of tide and wave data gathering at new ARGUS-stations.
<LI>Support the establishment of ARGUS-stations at new sites where field campaigns will be carried out (e.g. Egmond, Teignmouth).
<LI>Support getting access to existing tide and wave data.</UL></UL>

<B>CONCLUSIONS</B><P>

The workshop participants agreed that the international collaboration on the research questions outlined in this report would improve our predictive capabilities in surf-zone dynamics, and that once collaboration is started, stronger , more lasting relationship would develop.  The participants also recommended establishment of a permanent "Coastal Dynamics Coordinating and Planning Committee", consisting of representatives of the major coastal research groups in Europe and the U.S. <P>

 <B>Appendix 1 - Initial List of  Topics/Concerns/Opportunities</B><P>

