<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Coastal Oceanography Report No. 5</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Coastal Oceanography Report No. 5<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<P>

Summary Of European Union (EU) Marine Science And Technology 
(MAST) Programs Focused On Coastal Research<P>

Past, Present, and Future<P>

<I>Keywords:  Coastal Research; MAST; European Union</I><P>

Professor Huib deVriend<BR>
University of Twente<BR>
Faculty of Technology & Management<BR>
P.O. Box 217<BR>
7500 AE Enschede<BR>
Netherlands<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:h.j.devriend@sms.utwente.nl">h.j.devriend@sms.utwente.nl</A><P>

Dr. Robert Dolan<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London  NW1 5TH<BR>
United Kingdom<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:rdolan@onreur.navy.mil">rdolan@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>

December 20, 1996</H3>

<B>1.  Introduction</B><P>

		This overview concerns recently completed and ongoing projects on coastal dynamics that have been carried out with support in the framework of EU-MAST.  The purpose is to provide information on what MAST actually is, what it has produced so far, and what European research networks have been formed to achieve this.  Facts, figures, names and addresses concerning existing projects were obtained from the project-summaries provided by the European Commission.  <P>

		For each MAST-supported project, a brief description is given in terms which are considered relevant to ONR and the new Naval International Cooperative Opportunities in Science and Technology (NICOP).  Copies of the relevant pages of the aforementioned EC-documents are added in the Annex.  Information on proposed projects has to be more concise and is therefore included in the main text.<P>

	<B>2.  What is MAST?</B><P>

	MAST is the acronym of the Marine Science and Technology programme, one of the research programmes funded by the European Commission.  These programmes are funded in rounds (Framework Programmes);  the first issue of MAST (MAST-I) started as part of the Second Framework Programme.  At the moment, MAST-III is currently underway as a part of the Fourth Framework Programme.<P>

	Apart from support for administrative activities, MAST has always consisted of three research areas; (1) oceanography/marine biology, (2) coastal science/engineering and (3) marine technology (instrumentation, etc.).  Out of these, the coastal section has always been the smallest, with a funding level of approximately 10 million ECU (1.25 US$ = 1 ECU) in MAST-I (total budget 50 million ECU), approximately 15 million ECU in MAST-II (total budget 118 million ECU) and approximately 40 million ECU in MAST-III (total budget 228 million ECU).  Along with the increasing level of funding, the scope of work has been broadened, so that the actual amount of money per working area in this compartment has increased to a lesser extent.  Yet, the amount of money available for coastal research is quite substantial and MAST has definitely boosted the European research activity in this field.<P>

	The basic document in MAST is the Work Plan, which defines the scope of activities without going into detail.  Project proposals within this scope are submitted upon a call for proposals which is issued before the start of each round (only MAST-III is having a second round about one year after its start in 1995).  Proposals are selected by a panel of experts and a board of national representatives.  The most important criteria are multinational collaboration, scientific excellence, practical relevance, exploitability, and European dimension.<P>

	This procedure yields a substantial number of projects, each with a budget of one to a few million ECU.  Each project is carried out by an international consortium of main contractors, and each of them may bring in associated partners, who are supposed to take part in the scientific work, and subcontractors who deliver goods and services.  The principal products are data, models, and instrumentation, mostly described in scientific reports and publications.  Important by-products are a number of quite extensive European research networks, which often survive the end of the project.  Thus MAST has greatly contributed to the integration of the coastal research community in Europe.<P>

	In spite of its success as a programme, it is uncertain whether MAST will be continued as a separate programme under the Fifth Framework Programme.  This is partly due to a concentration of the programmes (most of the working areas will probably come under an environmental programme), and partly to a shift in emphasis of European research.  MAST-III projects will go on until the year 2000 or later.  Therefore, a collaboration with US research networks via NICOP is definitely attractive to European coastal scientists.<P>

<B>3.  Value of US-EU Collaboration</B><P>

	Based on discussions about the NICOP concept with the staff of the MAST-bureau, it is clear that MAST is interested in collaboration with US researchers.  The EU has already demonstrated this interest by allowing the active participation of US researchers through European institutes to some of the MAST-projects, e.g. PACE.  The interest from the part of MAST is driven by needs such as:

<UL>
<LI>cheap and reliable operational tools for event-scale monitoring,
<LI>model validation against a wide range of real-life, data-rich cases,
<LI>broadly agreed measures-of-skill of coastal morphodynamic models,
<LI>identification of predictability horizons in the behaviour of coasts (depending on the aggregation-level),
<LI>further development of data analysis/reduction and data-driven modelling techniques, and
<LI>development of techniques for the prediction of coastal behaviour under uncertainty of model parameters and inputs.
</UL>

Collaboration with US researchers can help to meet these needs, e.g. via <P>

<UL>
<LI>further improvement of the interpretation of data from the ARGUS nearshore monitoring system,
<LI>jointly using some of the larger US datasets (Duck, Florida) for model validation,
<LI>joint definition of measures-of-skill, etc.
</UL>

Moreover, it is of interest to Europe to have its research products applied by a worldwide research community in order to have them challenged at the scientific level, and to increase robustness at the application level.<P>

<B>4.  Relevant MAST-Projects</B><P>

<B>4.1 The coastal compartment of MAST-I.</B><P>

	The coastal part of MAST-I consisted of a section on coastal engineering (hard structures) and one on coastal science (dynamic processes).  The latter involved projects such as:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Coastal Morphodynamics (see Section 4.2),
<LI>Linear Sand Banks, the forerunner of the CSTAB-project (see Section 4.2),
<LI>RESECUSED, the forerunner of the STARFISH-project (see Section 4.2),
<LI>WASP, a modelling project concerning the physical and ecological processes in the Wadden Sea, the barrier island coast along the North Sea coasts of the Netherlands, Germany and Denmark.
</UL>

<B>4.2 Recently finished (or almost-finished) projects under MAST-II (and MAST-III).</B><P>

<B>Coastal Morphodynamics:</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I>	MAST-II<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Coastal morphodynamics in general, but with the emphasis on 
nearshore processes and their interactions at various time scales (process-scale, engineering scale, long-term).<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I>	Theoretical analysis/mathematical modelling/laboratory 
experiments/field work/use of existing field data.<BR>
<I>Network:</I>	An extensive network.  A group of large European hydraulic 
laboratories and institutes; approximately 35 official partners and a number of "affiliated partners" who participated on their own funds; about 130 scientists involved.<BR>
<I>US-connection:</I>  various incidental contacts and exchanges<BR>
<I>Results:</I>	Over 100 peer-reviewed scientific publications, 175 conference 
papers, 25 Ph.D. theses, 100 scientific reports and many datasets; 
overview in final scientific report; book in preparation.<BR>
<I>Remark:</I>	Most of the model software used in the project is owned by private 
		companies and not freely available.<BR>
<I>Further info:</I>	Prof. Marcel Stive, Delft Hydraulics, Delft, NL<BR>
		E-mail <<A HREF="mailto:marcel.stive@wldelft.nl">marcel.stive@wldelft.nl</A>>
		also see attachment<P>

This project, which is considered quite successful, has made an important contribution to Europe's present position in the mathematical modelling of coastal behaviour.  It was the largest project of MAST-II, and the EU refers to it as the "MAST-flagship".  It has created an extensive pan-European network of coastal researchers, centered around the group of nine hydraulic laboratories (G9).  Various part so this network are still intact after the project has ended and operate in various research programmes.<P>

 <B>Evaluation of innovative nourishing techniques (NOURTEC):</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I> 	MAST-II<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Innovative techniques of shore nourishment, based on three full-
scale experiments, in the Netherlands (shoreface nourishment 
Terschelling), Germany (nourishment within a groyne field at Norderney) and Denmark (underwater and beach nourishments at the North Sea coast).<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I>	Towards the effectiveness of new nourishment techniques; using 
		mathematical models (prediction and hindcast) and field 
measurements (process-measurements and monitoring).<BR>
<I>Network:</I>	A conglomerate of institutes from the three participating countries, 
		including a number of large subcontractors (e.g. Delft Hydraulics, 
Danish Hydraulic Institute); participation biased to the Netherlands.<BR>
<I>US-connection:</I>  via Prof. Van de Kreeke, Rosenstiel School, Miami, FL.<BR>
Results:	Reports and publications; interesting findings on how shoreface 
		nourishments work out.<BR>
<I>Further info:</I>	Mr. Rudi Spanhoff, Rijkswaterstaat - RIKZ, The Hague, NL<BR>
		E-mail <<A HREF="mailto:spanhoff@rikz.rws.minvenw.nl">spanhoff@rikz.rws.minvenw.nl</A>>
		also see attachment<P>

<B>Circulation and sediment transport around banks (CSTAB):</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I> 	MAST-II<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Current field, sediment transport and morphological changes around 
the Middelkerke Bank, off the Belgian coast.<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I> 	Field work backed up by process-oriented mathematical 
		modelling/stability analysis of rhythmic features (sand banks, sand 		waves)/technology development (shear plate).<BR>
<I>Network:</I>	A relatively small group of institutes from UK, the Netherlands, 
Germany, Denmark and Portugal, with majority of UK-participants.<BR>
<I>US-connection:</I>  unknown.<BR>
<I>Results:</I>	Publications, reports and an extensive final scientific report; 
interesting result on coexisting rhythmic features 
(bar/sandwaves/megaripples, all with different orientations) and the 
water motion around elongated sand banks.<BR>
<I>Remark:</I>	Adjoining projects: G8-M (modelling) and STARFISH 
(sedimentology)<BR>
<I>Further Info:</I>	Prof. Brian O'Connor, University of Liverpool, UK.<BR>
		E-mail <<A HREF="mailto:cc09@liverpool.ac.uk">cc09@liverpool.ac.uk</A>>
		also see attachment<P>

<B>Sediment transport and bedform mobility in sandy shelf environments (STARFISH):</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I> 	MAST-II<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Sediment transport and morphological changes around Middelkerke Bank, off the Belgian coast.<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I>	Sedimentological field work, backed up by regular morphological 
surveys.<BR>
<I>Network:</I>	A relatively small group of institutes from Belgium, the 
Netherlands, UK and France, with a majority of Belgian 
participants.<BR>
<I>US-connection: </I> unknown.<BR>
<I>Results:</I>	Comprehensive overview of sediment properties, sedimentary 
structure and bed form migration around this bank.<BR>
<I>Remark:</I>	Adjoining project: CSTAB.<BR>
<I>Further Info:</I>	Dr. Jean Lanckneus, University of Gens;<BR>
		also see attachment<P>

<B>4.3 Ongoing Projects Under the First Round of MAST-III.</B><P>

<B>Prediction of Aggregated-scale Coastal Evolution (PACE):</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I>	MAST-III<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Observation, analysis, modelling and prediction of the behaviour of 
sandy coasts at a range of large scales, from seasons to millennia.<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I> 	Analysis of existing data (ARGUS, monitoring programmes, 
historical and geological reconstructions, etc.)/data-driven 
modelling (black-box)/behaviour-oriented modelling (grey-
box)/process-oriented modelling (white-box)/analysis of inherent 
stability and predictability of the morphodynamic system/prediction 
under uncertainty.<BR>
<I>Network:</I>	PACE is the EU-component of a research network on large-scale 
coastal behaviour (LSCB), which also involves researchers from the 
US, Australia and Eastern Europe.<BR>
<I>US-connection:</I> via Oregon State University (Prof. Rob Holman; postdoc-
exchange), Wooward Clyde International (Dr. Alan Niedoroda; 
partner in the project via Barcelona office), Old Dominion University (Dr. Chris Reed; subcontracted by WCI), University of Minnesota (Prof. Gary Parker; subcontracted by WCI), Field Research Facility-Duck (Dr. Bill Birkemeier; data exchange and advice).<BR>
Results:	Reports and publications on analysis and prediction methods for 
large-scale coastal behaviour, including indications of reliability and methods to deal with uncertainty; database with meta-data on the world's most important 	LSCB-datasets.<BR>
<I>Remarks:</I>	Adjoining projects:  SAFE.
		Adjoining proposals:  INDY, SASME.<BR>
<I>Further Info:</I>	Prof. Huib de Vriend, University of Twente, Enschede, NL<BR>
		E-mail <<A HREF="mailto:h.j.devriend@sms.utwente.nl">h.j.devriend@sms.utwente.nl</A>>
		also see "MAST-III Project Synopses-I" p. 4-5 (attached)<P>

<B>Performance of soft beach systems and nourishment measures for European coasts (SAFE):</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I>	MAST-III<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Prediction of the medium-term performance of shore nourishments.<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I> 	Mathematical modelling (beach profile, shoreline), validated with 
laboratory experiments (e.g. the Grosze Wellenkanal in Hannover) and existing field data (e.g. from NOURTEC); special attention for aeolian transport and beach/dune interaction, and for grain sorting effects.<BR>
<I>Network:</I>	A well-balanced group of partners from 8 EU-countries.<BR>
<I>US-connection:</I>  Various bilateral contacts via participating institutes.<BR>
<I>Results:</I>	Reports, publications and possibly auxiliary software on prediction 
methods, to be used in the design of individual nourishments and larger-scale nourishment schemes.<BR>
<I>Remark:</I>	Adjoining projects:  NOURTEC, PACE.
		Adjoining proposals:  SASME.<BR>
<I>Further info:</I>	Dr. Luc Hamm, SOGREAH, Grenoble, FR<BR>
		E-mail <<A HREF="mailto:luc.hamm@pobox.oleane.com">luc.hamm@pobox.oleane.com</A>>
		also see "MAST-III Project Synopses-I" p. 8-9 (attached)<P>

<B>The kinematics and dynamics of wave-current interactions:</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I>	MAST-III<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Analysis and predictive modelling of 2-D and 3-D wave-current 
interactions over a rigid bed, for regular and irregular waves; sediment is not taken into account.<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I> 	Laboratory experiments and field work supported by diagnostic 
mathematical modelling, as well as predictive modelling validated by laboratory and field measurements.<BR>
<I>Network:</I>	A relatively small network of highly specialized top-level 
researchers.<BR>
<I>US-connection:</I>  No formalized contacts.<BR>
<I>Results:</I>	Reports, publications and new data on the various manifestations of 
wave-current interaction.<BR>
Further info:	Dr. Gareth Thomas, University College Cork, IR<BR>
		E-mail <<A HREF="mailto:thomasgp@ucc.ie">thomasgp@ucc.ie</A>>
		also see "MAST-III Project Synopses-I", p. 22-23 (attached)<P>

<B>The morphological development of intertidal mudflats (Intrmud):</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I> 	MAST-III<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Characterization and modelling of intertidal mudflats under a range 
of conditions.<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I> 	Classification/field work/statistical modelling/box-type and process-
oriented modelling/basis of understanding of mudflat response to various inputs.
<I>Network:</I>	Combines a number of ongoing national research networks, such as 
the Dutch BOA-network and involves a number of reputed specialists in mud dynamics and mudflat ecosystems.<BR>
<I>US-connection:</I>  Unknown.<BR>
<I>Results:</I>	Results not only aiming at the scientific community, but also at 
environmental managers dealing with systems which include intertidal mudflats.<BR>
<I>Further info:</I>	Prof. Keith Dyer, University of Plymouth<BR>
		E-mail <<A HREF="mailto:kdyer@plymouth.ac.uk">kdyer@plymouth.ac.uk</A>>
		also see "MAST-III Project Synopses-I", p. 48-49 (attached)<P>

<B>Fluxes across narrow shelves (FANS):</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I> 	MAST-III<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Water, sediment and nutrient fluxes across the narrow shelf around 
the Ebro Delta.<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I> 	Numerical modelling and field work (including satellite and video 
imagery) of interacting nearshore, shelf and slope regions.<BR>
<I>Network:</I>	International network, part of which has work on the Ebro Delta 
since a long time; includes a number of reputed oceanographers and coastal modellers.<BR>
<I>US-connections:</I>  Unknown.<BR>
<I>Results:</I>	Comprehensive picture of forcings and responses of this complex 
interactive system, to be laid down in scientific publications and reports; field data at various levels of aggregation.<BR>
<I>Further info:</I>	Prof. Agustin Sanchez-Arcilla, Univ. Politecnica de Catalunya, 
Barcelona<BR>
		E-mail <<A HREF="mailto:arcilla@esteccpb.upc.es">arcilla@esteccpb.upc.es</A>>
		also see "MAST-III Project Synopses-I", p. 78-79 (attached)<P>

<B>Coastal sediment transport assessment using synthetic aperture radar (CSTAR):</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I> 	MAST-III<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Combination of existing radar techniques for mapping seabottom 
topography and mathematical models, in order to monitor sediment transport and morphology in highly dynamic areas (e.g. tidal inlets).<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I> 	Remote sensing combined with mathematical modelling.
<I>Network:</I>	A medium-scale network of RS-specialists and geoscientists; main 
axis:  Netherlands-Germany.<BR>
<I>US-connection:</I>  Unknown.<BR>
<I>Results:</I>	The project aims at less laborious and more frequently applicable 
morphological monitoring techniques than ship-borne depth-sounding, to be applied in complex, highly dynamic areas.<BR>
Further info:	Dr. Han Wensink, ARGOSS, Marknesse, NL<BR>
		E-mail <<A HREF="mailto:wensink@argoss.nl">wensink@argoss.nl</A>>
		also see "MAST-III Project Synopses-I", p. 74-75 (attached)<P>

<B>Three dimensional sediment transport measurements by acoustics (Tridisma):</B><P>

<I>Framework:</I> 	MAST-III<BR>
<I>Subject:</I>	Instrumentation for sediment transport measurements close to the 
seabed, via simultaneous acoustic measurements of the vertical profiles of sediment concentration, particle size and three velocity-components.<BR>
<I>Orientation:</I> 	Instrument development.<BR>
<I>Network:</I>	A relatively small network, which includes specialists in acoustics, 
as well as specialists in sediment transport.<BR>
<I>US-connection:</I>  Unknown.<BR>
<I>Results:</I>	Instrument tested under laboratory and field conditions.<BR>
Further info:	Dr. Chris Vincent, University of East Anglia, Norwich, UK<BR>
		also see "MAST-III Project Synopses-I", p. 36-47 (attached)<P>

<B>5.  Pathways of collaborations</B><P>

<B>Partners</B><P>

	The part of the MAST Work Programme that corresponds with the ONR-Coastal Dynamics programme is Area B:  "Coastal Science and Engineering".  Most of the aforementioned projects are funded from this part of the EC programme.  Being primarily a funding framework, MAST has an administrative bureau but no in-house researchers.  MAST could, therefore, facilitate collaboration with ONR-NICOP, but the actual connections will depend on the research consortia which are carrying out the projects.  These consortia would be the natural collaboration-partners from the EU-end.  One of the most important consortia in the coastal sciences compartment of MAST is the group of 9 European hydraulic laboratories (G9);  they were behind the G6-M and G8-M projects in MAST-I and MAST-II, and they are behind a considerable number of projects and submissions in MAST-III (PACE, SAFE, INDY, SASME, SEDMOC, COAST3D).  G9 includes Europes most important centres of numerical model development and laboratory work in the coastal research area.<P>


<B>Frameworks</B><P>

Although G9 and other research consortia which are active in MAST are spending significant amounts of their own resources to match MAST-projects (commercial institutes have to cover 50% of the costs of each project, universities can only charge marginal costs made especially for the project), they do not have a joint independent research organization.  Research collaboration exists within the projects, but seldom beyond them.  So the research projects are the natural frameworks of collaboration.  The work definition in the ongoing projects is primarily science-oriented (as opposed to product-oriented), with sufficient flexibility to include an unforeseen collaboration via ONR-NICOP.  If contracts need to be modified, this can be done without too many complications, especially if MAST officially supports the collaboration.  The networks which carry out MAST-projects tend to survive the projects end, but once support ends, the interactions usually reduce to scientific exchange between individuals.  Therefore, collaboration within the framework of ongoing projects is recommended.  As the projects to be funded under the last round of MAST-III are expected to start in 1997, these are also candidates for collaboration.  The decision on which projects will be funded is expected in early 1997.<P>

<B>Scope</B><P>

	Areas of high European research activity in the field of coastal dynamics are in areas of uninterrupted sandy coasts, barrier-island coasts, and estuaries and coastal lagoons.  A range of timescales is covered, from microscale (boundary layers and wave-current interaction, small-scale bedforms), via mesoscale (wave and current patterns, sediment pathways, morphodynamics at the event-scale and the seasonal scale), through to macroscale (decadal/ centennial/millennial scale).  Much of the research is driven by the need for predictions, but, due to the nature of morphodynamic processes, hydrodynamics, sediment transport and micromorphology are equally important research issues.<P>

 <B>Potential links</B><P>

	In the foregoing we have mentioned a number of ongoing and submitted MAST-projects which cover most of this area.  As the principal inputs into this collaboration are numerical and laboratory modelling expertise from the EU-end, and field-oriented knowledge from the USA-end, it would seem logical to link via ONR-NICOP a number of field-work oriented groups in the USA with modelling-oriented MAST-projects, such as PACE for the macroscale (annual and more, depending on the spatial scale of the phenomena), SAFE for the mesoscale (up to decadal), the Wave-Current Interaction project for the micro-scale (hydrodynamics only).  SEDMOC, if funded, would cover micro-scale morphodynamics in general, SASME event-scale morphodynamics of the nearshore, INDY meso- and macroscale morphodynamics of tidal inlet systems.<P>

<B>Multiplier-effect</B><P>

A collaboration between EU-modellers and USA-field workers and modellers would be beneficial to either party, but it would probably not increase the modelling capability in the USA, nor the field work potential in Europe.  The strongest multiplier effect would be achieved if the EU-partners in the collaboration would not only be modellers, and the USA-partners not only field workers.  Exchange of knowledge works best with "senders" and "receivers" at either end.  In other words;  the EU-participation should also involve some joint field work (e.g. via COAST3D and/or the Egmond experiments), and the USA- participation should involve hands-on modelling.
<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR newsletters</A>
