<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 4</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>10 January, 1996<BR>  Command & Control, Surveillance<BR> 
<A HREF="kessler.htm">Otto Kessler</A></H3>  
<H3>Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  C2 and
Surveillance Newsletter No. 4<BR>  Reasoning with Uncertainty in
Robotics</H3>  
<H3>Report on a workshop on Reasoning with Uncertainty in Robotics,
held at the University of Amsterdam.</H3> 
<PRE>
<B>Content:</B>
1. Summary
2. Discussion
3. Assessment
4. Papers
5. Points of Contact
6. Feedback
</PRE>
<P><B>1. Summary:</B> A workshop on Reasoning with Uncertainty in
Robotics was held at the University of Amsterdam under the auspices of
the Department of Mathematics and Computer Science. Researchers from 11
nations were represented in discussions which took place over the course
of three days. The objective was to create interaction among groups
performing research on uncertainty in the fields of artificial
intelligence and robotics. The workshop was successful in highlighting
historical development and current trends in theoretical issues
underlying robotics applications, while current robotics practice seems
to rely heavily on Kalman estimation. Papers outlining theoretical
development, architectures for control, multi-disciplinary estimation
techniques, and information based metrics give indications of progress
and evolving maturity in the field and have significance for military
systems.
</P><P><B>2. Discussion:</B> The workshop was intended to bring
together researchers in the fields of uncertainty in artificial
intelligence and robotics, in order to clarify the relationship between
differing approaches and to identify urgent problems. Problems in
robotics provide a good paradigm for larger scale problems in
information processing and management which occur in military
environments. Further, the small scale and tractable constraints
presented in typical robotics problems provide an excellent focus for
evaluating theoretical issues and their practical implications. Typical
robotics problems deal with localization, navigation, exploration or
sometimes, more generalized actions, in the context of uncertain,
incomplete or inconsistent information.<BR>  Participants at this
workshop could be broadly categorized in two camps: the AI types or
"logicians" - theoretically oriented, seeking robust mathematical
formalisms, relying heavily on symbolic approaches; and the roboticists,
- application oriented, satisfied with narrow formalisms, generally
resulting in numeric solutions. The papers and discussion provided
excellent insight into underlying issues and evolution of thinking and
capabilities in the field.<BR>  The central issue in automated systems
is the problem of dealing with uncertainty. Estimation theory provides a
mathematically consistent method for combining data, for predicting on
the basis of data, and for propagating errors in control systems.
However when source data are incomplete, or ambiguous in terms of
objective statements, additional tools are needed to invoke inferences
or to reason about significance. Probability theory provides a strong
formalism for dealing with uncertainty, but the interpretations are
often subjective, and the combinatorics of the required probabilities,
for full scale problems, can become unmanageable. Early AI workers
developed 'certainty factor models' to apply measures of uncertainty to
qualify facts and rules in expert systems. These approaches, while
sometimes successful, have no theoretical justification, despite
attempts to provide a probabilistic connection. Evidence theory,
embodied principally in Dempster-Shafer Theory, provides a formalism for
representing and combining evidence at different levels of abstraction.
D-S overcomes the combinatorial problem of probability theory, but
recent efforts have focused on the soundness of Dempster's combination
rule, stemming from interpretations of independence in the D-S
framework. The most recent efforts in this field have focused on Bayes
nets, or causal networks, as a means to emulate human reasoning.<BR> 
The evidence of this workshop is that roboticists continue to apply
estimation theory, embodied primarily in Kalman filtering, because it
provides real solutions for combining of sensor data and control of
actuators. Such techniques are deficient when it comes to reasoning
about information in larger contexts, as in problems of route planning
or sensor management. The logicians, meanwhile, continue to seek a
single robust, theoretically sound, formalism for dealing with
uncertainty of all forms. A holy grail perhaps.<BR>  A number of papers
on robot design, indicated the use of a layered hierarchy, with high
level control provided by an estimation approach, generally Kalman, but
utilizing probabilistic (Bayes) or certainty factor models for a
specific solution subset. The best of these provided examples of robots
with ability to navigate through a sequence of corridors, locate and
pass through doors, or to localize an object in a room. One example of a
large scale application was fully automated guidance and control of a
trailer transporting cargo containers through a complex dock area.<BR> 
Two papers were of particular interest in problems of planning and
reasoning under uncertainty. The first, a paper by Glen Shafer,
introducing the concept of a "Probability Tree" as a more robust
structure for capturing causality than Bayes nets. The second, offered
by Leslie Kaelbling described the partially observable Markov decision
process (POMDP) as an approach to choosing optimal actions in partially
observable stochastic domains. The computation is often difficult to
achieve, but has value in problems with discrete domains. An application
of POMDP was discussed in a separate paper showing its utility in map
learning within the design of an office delivery robot at Carnegie
Mellon University.<BR>  A novel approach to capturing and managing
knowledge, with implications for measures of information sufficiency,
was offered by Elfes in the form of a grid based representation of
physical objects. Elfes has developed a formalism for an 'inference
grid', which has multiple properties allowing complex representation of
information about the environment, including entropy measures relating
to mission relevant information. This concept was first outlined in a
paper by Elfes in 1992 and has since been applied with some success in a
number of designs. The question of scalability would be of interest.<BR>
 Three issues were cited in many of the papers and throughout the
discussion. These are core issues underlying collaboration and progress
in all areas of S&amp;T. They are noted here because they were noted
frequently at the workshop, and because they tend to be ignored or
under-supported in emerging technology disciplines.<BR> 
</P><PRE>
1. Modeling 
   - accurate models of sensors and physical environments;
   - understanding of model limitations;
 2. Benchmarks: 
   - measures for comparison;
   - canonical problem sets;
   - shared environments to perform testing.
 3. Semantics:   
   - lack of agreement on terms, ( i.e. "uncertainty" vs. "ignorance", "confidence" vs. "variability");
   - issues of numerical representation 
   - independence of data/information.
</PRE>
<P><B>3. Assessment:</B> Work on robot design appears to be centered
on laboratory or simulation environments, and is applied to narrowly
constrained problems. Typical tasks, while of small scale, provide the
basis for needed theoretical development and insight into larger system
architecture and implementation issues. Progress in this area,
therefore, has significance for military systems. Current efforts to
develop robust formalisms (Voorbraak) and the evolution to hybrid
control architectures (Crowley, Kristensen,) for flexibility and
adaptability, and decomposition of search space to enable evaluation of
appropriate metrics (Elfes, Konolige) are evidence of such progress.
Equivalent military problems to aggregate source data for various types
of decision support (situation assessment, plan development, replanning,
etc.) rely on the same underlying technology, and may benefit from
monitoring of developments in this community particularly in the areas
of theoretical foundations and metrics.
</P><P><B>4. Papers:</B> Presentations included two tutorials: four
invited papers, and 14 selected papers. Many of the papers are currently
available. A complete proceedings will be published, probably by March,
1996.<BR>  Tutorials<BR>  "Mathematical foundations of Navigation and
Perception for an Autonomous Mobile Robot" J. L. Crowley, I. N. P.
Grenoble, France<BR>  "Reasoning with Uncertainty in AI"; F. Voorbraak,
University of Amsterdam, NL
</P><P> Invited<BR>  "Partially Observable Markov Decision Process for
Robotics" L. P. Kaelbling, Brown Univ, US<BR>  "Robot Navigation:
Integrating Perceptual and Environmental Constraints"; A Elfes,
UNDP/CNPq Softex 2000, Brazil<BR>  "The Art of Causal Conjecture"; G.
Shafer, Rutgers Univ, US<BR>  "The problem of Guessing Real World
Probabilities"; J. Paris, Manchester Univ, UK
</P><P> Selected<BR>  "Sensor Planning with Bayesian Decision Theory";
S. Kristensen, Aalborg Univ, Denmark<BR>  "A Refined Method for
Occupancy Grid Interpretation"; K. Konolige, SRI International, US<BR> 
"Knowledge Considerations in Robots"; R. I. Brafman, Yoav Shoham;
Stanford Univ, US<BR>  "A Sensor based Motion Planner for Mobile Robot
Navigation with Uncertainty"; B. Bouilly, T Simeon; LAAS-CNRS, France<BR>
  "Uncertainty Treatment in a Surface Filling Mobile Robot"; E.
Gonzalez, A Suarez, J. Cabo, Y. Rollot, B. Manuel; Univ d'Evry val
d'Essone, France<BR>  "Data Fusion for High Speed Vehicle Navigation";
H. Durrant-Whyte, Univ of Sydney, Aus<BR>  "Neural Network Applications
in Sensor Fusion for an Autonomous Mobile Robot"; J. van Dam, B. Krose,
F. Groen; Univ of Amsterdam, NL<BR>  "Perception Based Self
Localization using Fuzzy Locations"; A. Saffiotti, L. Weslet; Univ Libre
de Bruxelles, Belgium<BR>  "Reasoning About Noisy Sensors (and
Effectors) in the Situational Calculus"; F. Bacchius, J. Halpern, H.
Levesque, Univ of Waterloo, Canada<BR>  "Structuring Uncertain
Knowledge with Hierarchical Bayesian Networks"; T. Frohlinghaus,
Institut fur Informatik, Germany<BR>  "Probabalistic Map Learning:
Necessities and Difficulties"; P. Hebert, S. Betge-Brezetz, R. Chatila,
LAAS-CNRS, France<BR>  "Robot Navigation with Markov Models: A
Framework for Path Planning and Learning with Limited Computational
Resources"; S. Koenig, R. Goodwin, R. Simmons, CMU, US<BR>  "Recursive
Total Least Squares: An Alternative to Discrete Kalman Filters in Robot
Navigation"; D. Boley, E. Steinmetz, K. Sutherland; Univ of Wisconsin,
US<BR>  "Uncertainty Reasoning in Object ecognition by Image
Processing"; R. Hummel, Courant Inst. NYU, US
</P><P><B>5. Points of Contact</B>
</P><P><I>Program Chair:</I><BR>  Frans Groen<BR>  Dept of
Mathematics and Computer Science,<BR>  University of Amsterdam, The
Netherlands<BR>  Tel: 31-20-525-6060<BR>  e-mail: groen@fwi.uva.nl
</P><P><I>Organizers:</I><BR>  Leo Dorst<BR>  Dept of Mathematics
and Computer Science,<BR>  University of Amsterdam, The Netherlands<BR>
 Tel: 31-20-525-6060<BR>  e-mail: leo@fwi.uva.nl<BR>  Michiel van
Lambalgen<BR>  Dept of Mathematics and Computer Science,<BR> 
University of Amsterdam, The Netherlands<BR>  Tel: 31-20-525-6060<BR> 
e-mail: michiell@fwi.uva.nl
</P><P><B>6. Feedback</B><BR>  The Office of Naval Research, Europe
is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology
development in European countries. In order to better meet your needs,
our Scientists and Technologists are very much interested in knowing of
your specific science and technology interests. Please let me know what
they are.<BR>  Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of, who
may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail
addresses to me and I will add them to the distribution list.<BR>  Find
ONR Europe on the World Wide Web. Our home page contains information
about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters:<BR> 
http://www.ehis.navy.mil/homepage.htm
</P><P></P><P> For further general information please contact :<BR> 
Otto Kessler<BR>  Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>  Telephone: 44
171 514 4963<BR>  FAX: 44 171 723 6359<BR>  E-mail :
okessler@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  International Address:<BR>  223 Old
Marylebone Road<BR>  London NW1 5TH<BR>  US Address:<BR>  PSC 802 BOX
39<BR>  FPO AE 09499-0700
