<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>C2 and Surveilllance Newsletter No. 5</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>3 February 1996<BR>  Command & Control, Surveillance<BR> 
<A HREF="kessler.htm">Otto Kessler</A></H3>  
<H3>Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  C2 and
Surveillance Newsletter No. 5<BR>  TNO-FEL, C2 Department</H3>  
<H3>Visit to TNO-FEL Command & Control Department</H3> 
<PRE>
<B>Content:</B>
1. Summary
2. Discussion
3. Programs
4. Assessment
5. Points of Contact
6. Feedback
</PRE>
<P><B>1. Summary</B>
</P><P> Command & Control technology at TNO-FEL is organized into two
groups: tactical C2, dealing with land and air operations, and platform
C2, dealing with maritime operations. The organization has a strong
awareness of underlying trends and issues in C2 development, and appears
to make a strong contribution in areas of applied development. Expertise
is maintained by performing in-house development in selected areas and
programs, with guidance derived from active user relationships. A
limited number of programs were briefed. Two of these, ATCCIS and ISIS
have long term implications for interoperability in that their relation
to GCCS is not clear.
</P><P><B>2. Discussion</B>
</P><P> TNO-FEL is the Netherlands Organization for Applied Scientific
Research (TNO) Physics and Electronics Laboratory (FEL). FEL is one of 3
institutes within TNO, employing approximately 400 people (down about
20% from 1994) and doing approximately 85% of its work for the NL
Ministry of Defence. The other institutes are TNO Prins Maurits
Laboratory (TNO-PML) involved in munitions research and related chemical
and physical processes, and TNO Human Factors Research Institute
(TNO-TM). TNO-FEL is organized in four divisions; Operations Research,
Command & Control and Simulation, Telecommunications and Defense
Electronics, and Observation Systems. The latter contains radar,
electro-optic, acoustic and remote sensing groups. The principal
advertised products are sensor systems, information and
telecommunications systems, trainers and simulators, and policy studies.
This visit focused on command and control activities which are conducted
in two groups - tactical C2, (dry) dealing with land and air operations,
and platform C2, (wet) dealing with maritime operations. TNO-FEL
provided an overview briefing reflecting knowledge and appreciation of
current trends in C2, along with a number of specific program briefings.

</P><P> The overview briefing reflected sensitivity to the range of
drivers affecting modern C2 systems: short planning horizon, the
conflicting problems with upgrading legacy systems and keeping pace with
technology maturation, the need for evolutionary procurement, commercial
leveraging (COTS), and the need for commonality in training,
management/policy development, and operational systems. The development
approach incorporates tenets of evolutionary acquisition, leveraging
COTS wherever possible, encouraging and maintaining user involvement,
and promoting concepts of integrated C2 (i.e. commonality in tools,
environments, databases, etc.). Extensive use is made of testbeds for
simulation and validation. The distinction made between C2 developments
for 'dry' or 'wet' operations is justified on the basis that
organizational structures (Army and AF v. Navy) are quite different, but
is probably a response to customer attitudes. Within the organization
there appears to be active recognition and leveraging of common
technologies.
</P><P><B>3. Programs</B>
</P><P><B>ATCCIS (Allied Tactical Command and Control Information
System)</B><BR>  Under development to provide interconnectivity down to
the database level between C2 systems of different nations. A
demonstration of this capability was conducted at TNO-FEL, November
1995, involving 7 nations (NL, US, UK, GE, DEN, FR, SP). ATCCIS
addresses standardized communications protocols, database structures
(common data transfer), and data models (common language). Extended
discussion on this topic was foreclosed due to limited time. However,
ATCCIS was presented as the basis for NATO's C2 system of the future -
the "A" in the acronym was recently changed from Army to Allied. Some
awareness of GCCS was expressed but the relationship to ATCCIS,
particularly in the area of underlying structures, data models, etc.,
was not clear.<BR>
<B>ISIS (Integrated Staff Information System)</B><BR>  Builds on
ATCCIS, intended to provide a standardized operating environment to
facilitate intelligence information flow and related information to
enhance situation awareness. Deals with network architecture, services,
and selected applications. Will eventually support all organizational
levels, but currently focused at brigade level and upwards.<BR>
<B>DFD (Data Fusion Demonstrator)</B><BR>  This is a multi-phased
program, established under NATO AC/243, Panel 3, with participation of 7
nations (GE, NL, FR, CA, IT, UK, DEN). The purpose is to process
intelligence data to produce a coherent perception of the enemy
situation. Focus is on processing (including correlation and display) of
message based data and environmental information. Emphasis is placed on
knowledge based techniques. The project started in February 1993 and is
approaching the completion of a laboratory evaluation phase this year,
with a prototype to be built and demonstrated by the end of 1997.<BR>
<B>Helicopter Mission Planner</B><BR>  A planning aid which supports
allocation of helicopter resources (three types, limited numbers of
each) to missions of transport, MEDEVAC, C2 and search and rescue. The
planner runs in a PC environment and performs route planning considering
fuel, terrain, and threats, and recommends tasking of required assets,
and load configurations.<BR>
<B>DIS (Distributed interactive simulation)</B><BR>  Demonstration of
a sophisticated capability employing multiple in-house models
distributed throughout the facility, and connected to simulations in
other countries including the US (NAWC, Orlando) and UK (DRA,
Farnborough). Apparently used somewhat routinely within the FEL-TNO, in
various configurations, in support of systems analysis and as a testbed
for different programs. The particular demo was of an engagement of
multiple ships, aircraft, and missiles, to evaluate effectiveness of
ship countermeasures and maneuvers in defeating missile threats.
</P><P><B>4. Assessment</B>
</P><P> Strong awareness of C2 issues and a robust development
capability with expertise in selected areas of emphasis. Selected areas
are driven apparently by a combination of self interest and user
concerns. The role of ATCCIS and related efforts relative to GCCS is an
issue. Is there an intended relationship or is there a looming
interoperability problem?
</P><P><B>5. Points of Contact</B>
</P><P> TNO Physics and Electronics Laboratory<BR>  Oude
Waalsdorperweg 63<BR>  P.O. Box 96864<BR>  2509 JG The Hague<BR>  The
Netherlands<BR>  Peter Schulein<BR>  Tactical Command & Control Group
Leader<BR>  Tel: 31-70-326-4221<BR>  Fax: 31-70-328-0961<BR>  E-mail:
schulein@fel.tno.nl<BR>  Hans Keus<BR>  Platform Command & Control
Group Leader<BR>  Tel: 31-70-326-4221<BR>  Fax: 31-70-328-0961<BR> 
E-mail: keus@fel.tno.nl<BR>  Marcel D. E. van der Lee<BR>  System
development and IT<BR>  Tel: 31-70-326-4221<BR>  Fax: 31-70-328-0961<BR>
  E-mail: vanderlee@fel.tno.nl<BR>  G. A. Willemsen<BR>  Marketing &
Programme<BR>  Tel: 31-70-326-4221<BR>  Fax: 31-70-328-0961
</P><P><B>6. Feedback</B><BR>  The Office of Naval Research, Europe
is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology
development in European countries. In order to better meet your needs,
our Scientists and Technologists are very much interested in knowing of
your specific science and technology interests. Please let me know what
they are.<BR>  Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of, who
may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail
addresses to me and I will add them to the distribution list.<BR>  Find
ONR Europe on the World Wide Web. Our home page contains information
about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters:<BR> 
http://www.ehis.navy.mil/homepage.htm
</P><P></P><P> For further general information please contact :<BR> 
Otto Kessler<BR>  Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>  Telephone: 44
171 514 4963<BR>  FAX: 44 171 723 6359<BR>  E-mail :
okessler@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  International Address:<BR>  223 Old
Marylebone Road<BR>  London NW1 5TH<BR>  US Address:<BR>  PSC 802 BOX
39<BR>  FPO AE 09499-0700
