<HEAD>
<TITLE>C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 6</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>5 February 1996<BR>  Command & Control, Surveillance<BR> 
<A HREF="kessler.htm">Otto Kessler</A></H3>  
<H3>Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  C2 and
Surveillance Newsletter No. 6<BR>  TNO-FEL SAR Testbed</H3>  
<H3>Description of PHARUS: A Polarimetric C-Band Airborne SAR</H3> 
<PRE>
<B>Content:</B>
1. Summary
2. Discussion
3. Assessment
4. Point of Contact
5. Feedback
</PRE>
<P><B>1. Summary</B><BR>  TNO-FEL is currently flying a full
polarimetric C- band SAR (synthetic aperture radar) named PHARUS. As one
of a limited number of SAR systems available for test on an airborne
platform it is worthy of note. The system was designed for remote
sensing applications, is implemented with an active phased array, and
has fully programmable waveform, processing, and recording
characteristics.
</P><P><B>2. Discussion</B><BR>  The Physics and Electronics
Laboratory of TNO (TNO-FEL) is currently flying a full polarimetric C-
band SAR (synthetic aperture radar) named PHARUS (Phased Array Universal
SAR). The design of PHARUS satisfies a variety of remote sensing
purposes including environmental monitoring and military applications.
The system is composed of three subsystems: the base radar mounted in a
pod external to the aircraft, on-board data processing and recording
inside the aircraft, and ground-based SAR processing. The antenna is an
active phased array, configured as part of the pod. It supports a number
of scan modes including swath, spotlight, multi-target tracking, pulse
to pulse beam steering, and active nulling. Single or full linear
polarization modes may be selected. Radar parameters relating to
waveform, processing, and recording characteristics are programmable.
The system is currently flying on a Cessna Citation II.
</P><P> Key specifications are as follows:<BR> 
</P><PRE>
Frequency      5.3 GHz
Peak Power     480 w
Waveform       Linear FM
Bandwidth      100 MHz (max.)
Pulse Length   to 25.6 ms
Resolution     Range:      3.75 m
               Azimuth:   1m.
Polarization   Transmit:  H or V
               Receive:   H and V
Swath width    up to 20 km
Max. range     up to 30 km
Recording BW   100 Mbit/s
</PRE>
<P>In addition to its use for various environmental data collection
programs, it is envisioned that the PHARUS concept provides the basis
for a family of similar airborne SAR's, built on a common basis, and
tailored to individual user needs. PHARUS was designed and built through
the combined efforts of TNO-FEL in The Hague, the National Aerospace
Laboratory (NLR) in Amsterdam, and the Delft University of Technology.
</P><P><B>3. Assessment</B><BR>  PHARUS represents one of a limited
number of SAR systems available on an airborne platform for test
purposes. It is a modern radar design with a number of significant
features. It is fully polarimetric, has programmable waveforms, and is
well instrumented for data recording. The availability of PHARUS on a
Cessna Citation II makes it ideal as a data collection platform.
</P><P><B>4. Point of Contact</B>
</P><P> TNO Physics and Electronics Laboratory<BR>  Oude
Waalsdorperweg 63<BR>  P.O. Box 96864<BR>  2509 JG The Hague<BR>  The
Netherlands<BR>  Peter Hoogeboom<BR>  Remote Sensing Group Leader<BR>
 Tel: 31-70-326-4221<BR>  Fax: 31-70-328-0961<BR>  E-mail:
hoogeboom@fel.tno.nl
</P><P><B>5. Feedback</B><BR>  The Office of Naval Research, Europe
is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology
development in European countries. In order to better meet your needs,
our Scientists and Technologists are very much interested in knowing of
your specific science and technology interests. Please let me know what
they are.<BR>  Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of, who
may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail
addresses to me and I will add them to the distribution list.<BR>  Find
ONR Europe on the World Wide Web. Our home page contains information
about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters:<BR> 
http://www.ehis.navy.mil/homepage.htm
</P><P></P><P> For further general information please contact :<BR> 
Otto Kessler<BR>  Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>  Telephone: 44
171 514 4963<BR>  FAX: 44 171 723 6359<BR>  E-mail :
okessler@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  International Address:<BR>  223 Old
Marylebone Road<BR>  London NW1 5TH<BR>  US Address:<BR>  PSC 802 BOX
39<BR>  FPO AE 09499-0700
</P><P></P><HR><P> <A HREF="onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR
