<HEAD>
<TITLE>C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 7</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>21 February 1996<BR>  
Command & Control, Surveillance<BR> 
<A HREF="kessler.htm">Otto Kessler</A></H3>
  
<H3>Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  
C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 7<BR>  
SHAPE Technical Centre</H3>  
<H3>Report on a visit to SHAPE Technical Centre (STC), The Hague, The Netherlands</H3> 

<I>Keywords:   STC;  The Netherlands; Information Systems; Operations Research; Communications; Command & Control.</I><P>
<PRE>
<B>Content:</B>
1. Summary
2. Discussion
3. Organization and Program Overviews
4. Assessment
5. Points of Contact
6. Feedback
</PRE>

<B>1.   Summary</B><BR>
The SHAPE Technical Centre (STC) has a mission "To provide scientific and   
technical advice and assistance to SHAPE".  It serves primarily as a   
system developer/engineering organization, with close links to the   
requirements organization and to operational users.  STC performs   
technology evaluation through studies and experimentation, and promotes   
technology exploitation through user oriented testbeds and rapid   
prototyping.  In meeting these roles it leverages strong interaction with   
operational users, a multi-national technical workforce, and a proactive   
policy toward evolutionary acquisition.  In the June '96 time frame it is   
expected that STC will merge with NACISA (NATO Communications and   
Information Systems Agency) to form a new NATO C3 Agency.  This change is   
expected to shorten acquisition timelines, and improve the quality of   
fielded products.  This newsletter outlines the organizational structure,   
and highlights selected programs.  Among many technical contributions,   
special note is made of (a) CRONOS - an information exchange network   
built on exercise experience and an Internet paradigm, and now serving as   
a "NATO Wide Web";  (b) RAP - a recognized air picture provided to NATO   
forces on a near real time basis; and (c) ACCS - design work for a future   
NATO air C2 system - this work (similar to work in land C2 systems at   
TNO-FEL) should be examined by US counterparts to avoid problems in   
interoperability downstream.<P>

<B>2.   Discussion</B><BR>
The SHAPE Technical Centre (STC) located at The Hague, The Netherlands,   
has a mission "To provide scientific and technical advice and assistance   
to SHAPE".  It operates effectively as a system engineering organization,   
emphasizing technology exploitation on behalf of operational users in   
support of goals set by Allied Command Europe.  STC employs a scientific   
staff of 113 people with 14 NATO countries represented, 29 are from the   
US.  Lab facilities are quite modern with extensive internal and external   
connectivity, performing simulation, analysis, testbedding, and   
prototyping, in support of either developmental or operational goals.   
 This visit provided a broad overview of the organizational structure,   
visibility into a number of programs, and insight to the nature of   
activity and facilities.<P>

STC is organized into four technical divisions:<BR>
    - Operations Research,<BR>
    - Communications,<BR>
    - Command, Control & Sensors,<BR>
    - Information Systems<BR>
An overview of each division is provided below<P>

Work is performed in nine scientific and technological packages, the   
percentage of the total work program is shown in parentheses:<BR>
    - Support to Defence Planning,  (17%)<BR>
    - Support to Operational Planning,  (9%)<BR>
    - Information Systems,  (13%)<BR>
    - Training and Exercises,  (4%)<BR>
    - Communications,  (21%)<BR>
    - INFOSEC Support,  (3%)<BR>
    - NATO Airborne Early Warning and Control,  (5%)<BR>
    - Electronic Warfare Research Studies,  (4%)<BR>
    - Air Command, Control, Surveillance, Missile Defence Support (21%)<P>

STC work is sponsored primarily by four ACOS' (Assistant Chiefs of Staff)   
at SHAPE, accounting for (88%) of the total budget.  STC has a direct   
connection to the ACOS' as it does with operational units through   
extensive user oriented testbedding, and field prototyping activities.   
 Users are involved in various stages of the development process, through   
lab activity, exercise participation, and phased deployment of technology   
to the field.  STC has positioned itself with a number of features   
well-suited to fulfilling its technology exploitation role.  These are:   
(a) a strong connection with users for sensitivity to emerging   
operational problems, (b) a capable staff with the technical savvy to   
offer appropriate technology solutions, (c) an effective policy for   
applying evolutionary acquisition mechanisms wherever possible, and (d) a   
short sponsor chain so that necessary changes can be effected rapidly.<P>

In the June '96 time frame it is expected that STC will merge with NACISA   
(NATO Communications and Information Systems Agency) to form a new NATO   
C3 Agency.  The effect of this merger will be to bridge the gap which now   
exists between STC as developer and NACISA as acquisition agent.  The   
change is expected to create a closer coupling of plans and prototypes to   
specs and procurements, thus expediting introduction of validated   
products to the field.<P>

<B>3.   Organization and program overviews</B><BR>
Many of the STC programs and products are familiar to performers in the   
US either through direct involvement or usage in NATO contexts.  The   
following brief summaries are intended to outline the resources and   
capabilities offered at STC and to highlight a few selected programs.   
 Additional information is available on request.<P>

<I>3.1  Operations Research Division</I><BR>
       <DIR>[Areas of Interest: Land, Air Maritime Force Requirements;
        Movement and Transportation; Sustainment Requirements;
        Models and Databases; Decision Support; Experimental Gaming.]</DIR>
Performs analyses to support Alliance strategic and operations planning   
in areas of defence planning (threat assessment, readiness estimates,   
coordination of national contribution to defence goals) and support to   
military operations (crisis response planning, lessons learned, decision   
support tools to manage integrated operations).  This latter activity   
includes continued development and dissemination of ADAMS<BR>
   > ADAMS (Allied Deployment and Movement System) -a PC based,
       tool for logistics analysis, movement planning, and execution
       monitoring. ADAMS is employed by SHAPE for planning and
       coordination of multinational deployments.  It includes relevant
       databases, planning tools, decision support, displays and
       communications interfaces.<P>

<I>3.2  Information Systems Division</I><BR>
       <DIR>[Areas of Interest: Information Systems engineering;
        Operations/Logistics Support Systems; Intelligence Systems;
        Command Centers Systems Integration; Computer Assisted
         Exercises.]</DIR>
Provides system engineering and support tools for information systems   
required by SHAPE at the force coordination level and higher.  Heavy   
emphasis is placed on rapid prototyping and user evaluation in functions   
of intelligence, and operations/logistics.  Simulation capability is   
focused on CAE (computer assisted exercises) which provide training in   
simulated battle environments including force maneuvering and threat   
responses.  The intent is to augment (eventually replace) warrior prep   
exercises.<BR>
Developmental efforts include:<BR>
    > CRONOS - an information exchange network put in place as an
       "operating prototype" to support Bosnian operations.  It connects
       organizations such as SHAPE, NATO HQ, AFCENT, AFSOUTH,
       ARRC,SACLANT, SIXATAF, and others.  CRONOS is now
       considered to be operational, and in essence serves as a "NATO
       Wide Web".  It uses Internet (or Internet-like) protocols, is PC   
based,
       uses dedicated routers and 64KB links, and builds on prior   
networks
       employed for exercise support (i.e. SRIXS in Strong Resolve, and
       ECHO a wide area data network).  Maintenance and a help desk are
       provided by STC.  In addition to supporting routine command level
       interaction (monitoring, reporting, etc.), it carries a variety of   

       products, including ADAMS -a logistics planning tool, RAP -
       recognized air picture, and has connections to appropriate   
databases
       and intel systems.<BR>
    > PAIS (Prototype ACE Intelligence System) - upgrades for improved
       crisis monitoring and management.  PAIS provides order of battle,
       situation awareness, and imagery information.<BR>
    > Anchor HQ Concepts - for maintaining staff out of operational areas   

       to reduce associated costs and risks, currently being evaluated   
for
       quality of interaction and support effectiveness.<BR>
    > Information management tools for filtering open source and
       message data, text searches and automated web searching.<P>

<I>3.3  Command, Control & Sensors Division</I>
      <DIR> [Areas of Interest: Air Command & Control; Surveillance; NATO
        AEW&C; Electronic Warfare; Theatre Missile Defence.]</DIR>
Projects focused on planning, execution and monitoring of air power for   
the alliance.  Specific projects include studies, employing modeling and   
simulation, and system upgrades, DT&E focus, for such programs as NATO   
AEW&C (NATO Airborne Early Warning & Control System - E-3A), AADGE (ACE   
Air Defence Ground Environment Improvement Support), and TMD (Theatre   
Missile Defence).  Simulation facilities for testing radar and EW   
responses are extensive and modern.  The EW Tactics Lab in particular,   
offers a unique capability for test of countermeasures under dynamic   
conditions.<BR>
Two efforts worthy of note:<BR>
    > ACCS (Air Command & Control System);
       The future air defence C2 system.  Design activities under the
       direction of NACMA (NATO ACCS Management Agency) primarily in
       areas of simulation and selected prototyping.
              This work has strong interoperability implications as it
                  appears to be conducted independent of ATCCIS
                     (see TNO-FEL newsletter #5) and GCCS.
                NOW IS THE TIME FOR DESIGN COLLABORATION.<BR>
    > Surveillance and Identification Support;
       A "surveillance prototype" which integrates sensor data to form a
       RAP (recognized air picture).  RAP is disseminated to NATO forces
       at regular intervals.  The source data includes message traffic,   
and
       radar observations from ground and air sensors.  The correlation
       algorithm is supplied by Dornier.<P>

<I>3.4  Communications Division</I>
      <DIR> [Areas of Interest: Architectures and Standards; Radio Systems;
        Satellite Communications; Technologies and Techniques.]</DIR>
Performs analysis, concept development and prototyping.
Major projects include:<BR>
    > NATO communications system architecture, covering private NATO
       nets, public nets, and linkage to private national nets (National
       Defense Nets).  Currently addressing modernization using a mix of
       commercial and national defence networks.<BR>
    > ACE radio communications, addressing rapidly deployable line of
       sight and beyond line of sight  radio for voice, data, fax and   
image
       transmission.<BR>
    > UHF/SHF Satellite communications, covering upgrade of aging
       systems and implementation of maritime gateways.<BR>
    > Communications technologies and techniques, including propagation
       models, waveform design, and gateway protection.<P>

<B>4.   Assessment</B><BR>
STC serves primarily as a system developer/engineering organization, with   
close links to SHAPE (Requirements and Sponsors) and to operational users   
(needs and evolutionary paths).  This role will likely be strengthened   
with the upcoming merger of STC and NACISA (NATO Communications and   
Information Systems Agency) to form a single NATO C3 Agency.  The change   
is expected to happen in June '96.<BR>
STC possesses a cadre of technically knowledgeable personnel who stay   
abreast of the state-of-the-art and have demonstrated good ability to   
exploit technology to meet operational needs.  The organization maintains   
strong interaction with users through exercises and fielding of   
prototypes, and supports rapid movement of lab products to operational   
usage by applying concepts of evolutionary acquisition.  Simulation and   
laboratory facilities in support of systems development, test and   
evaluation are excellent.<BR>
Work being conducted at STC in C2 systems architecture and functionality   
(as at TNO-FEL) should be examined by US counterparts to avoid problems   
in interoperability downstream.<P>

<B>5.   Points of contact</B><BR>
