<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 8</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>11 July 1996<BR>  
Command & Control, Surveillance<BR> 
<A HREF="kessler.htm">Otto Kessler</A></H3>
  
<H3>Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  
C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 8<BR>  
Intelligent Methods in Signal Processing and Communications</H3>  
<H3>Report on the Fourth Bayona Workshop on Intelligent Methods in Signal Processing and Communications,  held at Bayona, Vigo, Spain, on 24 - 26 June, 1996</H3>

<I>Keywords:  Signal processing; Communications, Neural networks, Wavelets;  Non-linear systems</I>
<PRE>
<B>Content:</B>

1. Summary
2. Discussion
3. Overview of Sessions and Invited Talks
4. Assessment
5. Points of Contact
6. Feedback
</PRE>
<B>1.   Summary</B><BR>
The Fourth Bayona Workshop On Intelligent Methods In Signal Processing and Communications, held at Bayona-Vigo, Spain, was a gathering of approximately 75 scientists from 16 nations including the US and Canada.  The Workshop had the objective of a cross-fertilization of ideas relevant to intelligent processing and facilities for communication terminals.  The meeting provided a useful sampling of the state of research in signal processing oriented to communications, and exposure to a collaborative program among a few US and Spanish universities which appears to have accelerated the technical maturation of all concerned.  The workshop represented the initial activity of COST #254, "Intelligent Processing and Facilities for Communication Terminals".  COST (European Cooperation in the Field of Scientific and Technical Research) provides a framework for R&D cooperation in Europe.  A description of COST will be provided in another newsletter.<P>

<B>2.   Discussion</B><BR>
<B>2.1   The Environment</B><BR>
The workshop represented the initial activity of COST #254, which addresses "Intelligent Processing and Facilities for Communication Terminals".  COST programs are structured to explore S&T in selected areas where there is strong market potential and demand for new ideas and products.  The strength of the telecommunications arena is beyond question, and it appears that COST has been an effective catalyst in creating networks among researchers in the field across Europe.  Within telecommunications there have been 26 completed COST actions, 25 are currently ongoing, and 5 new ones are being considered.  Among workshop attendees, attitudes about the value of COST in providing focus and support to research activities were quite positive.<BR>
Another complementary activity, which was credited with having a positive influence on programs at universities in Madrid and Vigo was also evident.  It appears that an ad hoc relationship among these institutions and the University of New Mexico has been mutually beneficial in raising the quality of the research program, including overall faculty support, facilities, and student quality.  This relationship is now being institutionalized and expanded under the name ISTEC (Iberoamerican Science and Technology Education Consortium) to include institutions throughout the Americas and Spain.<P>

<B>2.2   The Papers</B><BR>
The workshop offerings were of uniformly high quality, with the papers providing a good mix of theoretical explication and new, often innovative, approaches to current issues.  Papers came from 16 nations with Spain providing the most, but more than half coming from other European countries.  The workshop featured six technical sessions presenting current research, and six invited papers - tutorials/state-of-the-art reviews - to set the theme for each session.  Some fifty papers were offered; persistent themes were modeling and processing of non-linear signals, use of wavelets for analysis and processing, neural nets, chaos in signal and image processing, adaptive techniques including echo equalization, channel modeling, and adaptive arrays.  All of the invited papers were from North America (4 - US, 2 - Canada), the work described is assumed to be known or accessible.  Sessions and invited talks are outlined in the following section.  A proceedings will be published.<P>

<B>3.   Overview of Sessions and Invited Talks<BR>
3.1   Sessions:</B>
<UL>
<LI>"Neural Networks and Non-linear Modeling"- Papers emphasizing the use of chaos theory and neural nets as solutions for problems in speech synthesis / recognition and network management.
<LI>"Image Processing" - Problems in image interpretation and image compression, again emphasizing use of non-linear techniques to deal with issues of segmentation, feature extraction, and shape estimation.
<LI>"Array Processing and Channel Identification" - A broad range of beamforming and channel identification / access issues including a rather elegant adaptive beamforming solution using the spectral line generation properties of CPFSK codes, and a novel use of neural nets to model non-linear network elements for failure mode detection and characterization.
<LI>"Adaptive Systems in Communications" - A number of strong papers dealing with problems in multi-user detection / interference with emphasis on non-linear techniques for data equalization and channel management in environments containing strong interference.
<LI>"Emergent Techniques" - Discussions of genetic algorithms and wavelet based solutions in a variety of applications including speech detection, image compression, signal filtering, and data hashing.
<LI>"Hardware and Software Implementation" - Application papers - including voice control of a telephone set in a reflective environment, VLSI implementation of image and video coding algorithms, and a "toolbox" offering wavelet based processing functions.  This last, named Uvi_Wave is available for Matlab or Khoros 2 environments from <A HREF="http://www.tsc.uvigo.es/tsc.uk.html">http://www.tsc.uvigo.es/tsc.uk.html</A>
</UL><P>

<B>3.2   Invited Papers:</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>"Multidimensional Nonlinear Myopic Maps, Volterra Series, and Uniform Neural Network Approximations";   I. Sandberg, Univ of Texas at Austin
<DD>Identification of dynamic systems using simple non-linear structures, which provide arbitrarily good approximations to approximately-finite-memory maps.
<LI>"Applications of Decision Based Neural Networks to Biometric Identification for Access Control and Security";   S. Kung, Princeton Univ.
<DD>Explores the use of neural networks as the basis for modeling biometric identification systems.  Demonstration of a face recognition system which employs a new probabilistic decision based neural network (DBNN).  The DBNN is computationally efficient and is robust against large variations in features.
<LI>"Adaptive Antenna Arrays in Communications";   L. Griffiths, Univ of Colorado at Boulder
<DD>Tutorial paper on applications of adaptive array processing in communications systems.
<LI>"Advancing Social and Economic Value in the Information Age: The Global Reach of Telecommunication Technology";  N. H. Lee, Nortel; Labs
<DD> An overview of market demand and supplier capabilities in the telecommunications field.
<LI>"Multi-user Demodulation for CDMA Channels";   S. Verdu, Princeton Univ.
<DD>Tutorial paper on the characteristics of multi-access interference in spread spectrum coded communications which may be exploited to achieve jam resistance.
<LI>"Modular Learning Strategy for Signal Detection in a Non-stationary Environment";   S. Haykin, McMaster Univ.
<DD>Application of Time-Frequency methods, using Wigner-Ville Distribution, for improved detection of signals in presence of interference. Superior detection of weak radar targets in sea clutter demonstrated.  Continuing study addresses an integrated receiver for nomadic computing using wireless communications.
</UL>

<B>4.   Assessment</B><BR>
The evidence of this workshop is that European S&T capability in signal processing for communications is quite strong.  The quality of the papers offered in the sessions, and the breadth of nations represented and participating, gives indication of a healthy research environment and of a strong cadre of emerging researchers.  While the largest single source of papers was from Spanish researchers, not surprising given the location, the majority of papers were distributed across thirteen other European nations.  The impact of research level collaboration - apparently spurred by COST - without specific controls and limited guidance appears to have broad benefit.  While there was a general lack of industry presence, much of the work was well framed in the context of real-world problems and market issues.  It is noteworthy that virtually all the invited papers were presented by North Americans - this may be a reflection of where the scientific leadership in this area still resides - for the time being.<BR>
The contribution of COST as an environment for stimulating general progress in S&T capability should be examined in greater detail as it applies to telecommunications and to other areas.  Similarly the benefit and contribution of consortia such as ISTEC should be considered more closely.<P>

<B>5.   Points of Contact</B><P>

