 <HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 9</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>13 July 1996<BR>  
Command & Control, Surveillance<BR> 
<A HREF="kessler.htm">Otto Kessler</A></H3>
  
<H3>Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  
C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 9<BR>  
Cooperative S&T in Europe: COST</H3>  
<H3>Description of COST (European Cooperation in the field of
Scientific and Technical Research) - a framework for scientific and
technical cooperation within the Commission of European Communities.</H3>

<I>Keywords:  S&T Coordination;  Collaborative R&D;  S&T Domains.</I><P>

Content:

<OL>
<LI>Introduction
<LI>COST Cooperation
<DIR> 2.1 Background</DIR>
<DIR>2.2  COST Actions</DIR>
<DIR>2.3  Types and Areas of Collaborative Research</DIR>
<LI>Feedback
</OL>

<B>1.   Introduction</B><BR>
As part of its charter this office is responsible for identifying practices and environments which are conducive to innovation and collaboration in S&T.  COST is a program set up under the Commission of European Communities, General Directorate for Science, Research and Development which appears to have had some degree of success in identifying issues and coordinating national activities.<P>

Cost is primarily a framework for R&D cooperation, which allows for the coordination of nationally funded research on a European level.  COST employs a "bottoms up" approach which addresses a broad range of activities.  A feature of COST is that any group of scientists can propose a new Action on a research activity where they see a need to cooperate.  Only five COST countries need to sign the MoU to put the Action into effect.  COST is funded as part of the European Union (EU) Framework Programme but at a very low level.  (Latest estimate: COST receives approximately 40M ECU out of a 4 year total Programme budget of 13B ECU, about 0.3%!).  (1 ECU ~ $1.25)<P>

The following description of COST is extracted from material provided by the program.  Additional information may be found on the COST homepage at: <A HREF="http://www.cordis.lu/cost/home.html">http://www.cordis.lu/cost/home.html</A><P>

<B>2.  Cost cooperation</B><P>

COST (European Cooperation in the field of Scientific and Technical
Research) is a framework for scientific and technical cooperation, allowing the
coordination of national research on a European level. COST Actions consist
of basic and precompetitive research as well as activities of public
utility.<P>

There are 25 COST member countries : the fifteen European Union (EU) Member States plus<BR>
Iceland, Norway, Switzerland, the Czech republic, Slovakia, Hungary,
Poland, Turkey, Slovenia, Croatia and the European Commission.<P>

<B>2.1  Background</B><BR>
COST Cooperation was set up in 1971 by a ministerial Conference attended by
Ministers for Science and Technology of the 19 original COST countries.
This cooperation was widened to include Iceland, Hungary, Czechoslovakia
and Poland at the second Ministerial Conference held on COST in Vienna in 
November 1991.  This organization, which laid the foundations for scientific
cooperation at the European level, is based upon a flexible set of
arrangements enabling different national organizations, institutes,
universities and industry to join forces and make concerted efforts in a
broad range of scientific and technical areas. From the beginning, the
European institutions (Commission and Council Secretariats) have played a 
particularly important role in the COST framework.<P>

Since 1989, organizations and institutes from non-COST countries and
especially from other Central and Eastern European countries may also
participate in individual COST Actions, if there is a justified mutual
interest.<P>

Four basic principles underlie COST mechanisms :<P>

<OL>
<LI>All COST member countries, as well as the European Commission, can propose COST Actions.
<LI>Participation in these Actions is voluntary and " la carte" (variable geometry), associating only interested countries.
<LI>The research to be coordinated is funded nationally.  The coordination costs are funded both by the participating countries and by the European Commission.
<LI>A COST Action aims to coordinate national research at a European level (concerted action).  The work undertaken by each Action is administered by a Management Committee.
</OL>

In contrast to Community Research Programmes, this form of collaboration
does not require an agreed overall research policy.  It focuses on specific
themes for which there is particular interest in the COST countries.<P>

From an initial 7 Actions in 1971, COST has grown to 123 Actions in
February 1996.<P>

<B>2.2  Cost Actions</B><BR>
A special feature of all COST Actions is the complete freedom of
participation by each country involved, according to national research
priorities. Any COST country can join an Action by signing a "Memorandum of
Understanding" (MoU) which is the legal basis of the Action. This resembles
a "gentleman's agreement" and is an expression of good faith rather than a
formal and legally binding document. The MoU governs the joint aims, the
type of activity to be pursued, the terms of participation and compliance
with sovereignty and if necessary, with intellectual property rights. The
signature of the MoU by at least five COST countries enables the entry
into force of the Action.<P>

The great advantage of this approach lies in a relatively rapid exchange of
information between scientists and technical experts and in the
arrangements made concerning the distribution of tasks for the research
work involved in the Action.<P>

<B>2.3  Types and Areas of Collaborative Research</B><BR>
The COST framework has proved to be suitable for several types of research
work. In most cases it is used to coordinate at European level existing or
proposed research programmes, in such general fields as :<P>

<UL>
<LI>research on topics of international interest such as oceanography, environmental protection, meteorology;
<LI>R & D appealing to a greater or lesser extent to all European countries, both individually and jointly, such as data processing, information technology, advanced materials, agriculture and food technology;
<LI>mutual adaptation of the various standards and specifications among the individual European countries in order to achieve the most widespread cross-frontier uniformity possible, for example in the telecommunications and transport sectors.
</UL>

COST Actions exist in the 17 following domains at present :
<UL>
<LI>Agriculture and Biotechnology
<LI>Archeology
<LI>Chemistry
<LI>Civil Engineering
<LI>Environment
<LI>Fluid Dynamics
<LI>Food Technology
<LI>Forests and Forestry Products
<LI>Informatics
<LI>Materials
<LI>Medical Research
<LI>Meteorology
<LI>Oceanography
<LI>Physics
<LI>Social Sciences
<LI>Telecommunications
<LI>Transport
</UL>

The following are examples of particularly successful COST Actions :

<UL>
<LI>COST Action 70 which led to the setting up of the European Center for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts in Reading (UK);
<LI>COST Actions 50 and 501 which contributed to the development of advanced high-temperature materials for use in gas turbines and energy conversion systems;
<LI>development of electronic traffic aids on major roads (COST Action 30) and of shore-based marine navigational aid systems (COST Action 301);
<LI>the first concerted efforts in the field of environmental protection research (COST Actions 61, 64 and 68, followed-up in COST Actions 611, 641 and 681);
<LI>the development of future telecommunications and tele-informatics facilities for disabled people (COST Action 219).
<LI>COST Action B1 concerning the choice and definition of healthy volunteers and patients together with the role of metabolic and kinetic studies in drug development;
<LI>the study of vesicular-arbuscular mycorrhizae in the circulation of matter in soil and in plant nutrition (COST Action 810)
<LI>COST Action 508 aiming for better knowledge of the various properties and the rheological behaviour of wood as well as the application of new technologies for wood industries.
<LI>COST Action A5 which studies the role of technology in increasing the participation of the elderly in society.
</UL>
In addition, a large number of COST Actions, especially in the fields of
informatics, telecommunications and materials have contributed to the
development of the Community's first major industry oriented programmes
such as ESPRIT, RACE, EURAM and BRITE and also to programmes in the
fields of environment, food technology and social science.<P>

<B>3.   Feedback</B><BR>
The Office of Naval Research, Europe
is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology
development in European countries. In order to better meet your needs,
our Scientists and Technologists are very much interested in knowing of
your specific science and technology interests. Please let me know what
they are.<BR>  
Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of, who
may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail
addresses to me and I will add them to the distribution list.<BR> 

Please note that the opinions and assessments in this report are solely   
those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official ONREUR, Navy,   
or US Government positions.<BR>

ONR Europe is on the World Wide Web.  Our home page contains information   
about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters:
Find us at:    http://www.ehis.navy.mil
</P><P></P><P> For further general information please contact :<BR> 
Otto Kessler<BR>  Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>  Telephone: 44
