<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT13-B25-128</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA074-000483-B027-149</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/oknews10.htm 192.76.237.3 19970124232906 text/html 11929
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: HTTPS/0.8
Allow: GET HEAD POST
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Date: Wednesday, 7-Aug-96 12:49:57 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 27-Aug-96 15:5:42 GMT
Content-length: 11715
</DOCHDR>
<BR>

<I>Keywords: Denmark R&D, polarimetric radar; instrumentation radar; 
                   data fusion;</I>  

<B>Content:</B>
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Organizational Overview
<LI>Programs
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Points of Contact
<LI>Feedback
</OL>

<B>1.   SUMMARY</B><BR>
DDRE (Danish Defence Research Establishment) is the principal government laboratory performing research and development in support of Denmarks Chief of Defence and the Ministry of Defence.  It operates primarily as a consultancy, exercising program development responsibility in only selected cases.  The structure and responsibilities of the lab are outlined, and notable programs and contributions - including world class theoretical work in radar polarimetry, and an instrumentation grade high resolution radar - are described.  The lab is active in NATO and European programs particularly in C2 related programs dealing with aspects of data fusion.  This work is outlined.  <P>

<B>2.   ORGANIZATIONAL OVERVIEW</B><BR>
The DDRE is the principal government laboratory supporting the Chief of Defence and Army, Navy, and Air Force operational and materiel commands.  Located in Copenhagen, Denmark, the DDRE mission is to "satisfy the need of the Danish Defence for knowledge and advice based on technological and scientific competence".  DDRE is a small organization comprising approximately 100 people.  The lab Director is responsible directly to the Denmark Chief of Defence, and accountable for review and oversight purposes to the DDRB (Danish Defence Research Board) which is a 4 person panel made up of Technical University of Denmark professors.  The position of Director, recently vacant, will be filled as of September 1, 1996 by Dr.Scient. Peter Lawaetz, who is a former president of the Technical University of Denmark.  <P>

DDRE functions primarily as a consultant organization.  Only in selected cases does it have development responsibility for programs; in general it acts in an advisory role to the armed forces on issues of procurement, test, operational usage, and training.  The laboratory maintains expertise in technical areas viewed as being important to Danish military concerns.  DDRE participates in relevant NATO DRG (Defence Research Group) activities, including panels and RSGs (Research Study Groups), to stay abreast of technology trends and as one input to guide its determination of where best to apply R&D resources.  <P>

DDREs areas of concern include sensor systems and related countermeasures, technologies for target identification and stealth, command and control systems, computer assisted exercises, software engineering, and operations research.  The organization has three technical components: Sensor Department, Computer Science Department, and an Operations Research Department.  A brief summary of each:
<UL>
<LI>Sensor Department research areas include radar, electro-optics, acoustics, signal processing, and EW countermeasures.  
<LI>Computer Science research areas include command & control systems and architectures, and human computer interaction with emphasis on geographical information systems.  
<LI>Operations Research Department provides modeling and simulation in support of force level assessments and advice to military acquisition components. 
</UL> 

<B>3.  PROGRAMS</B><BR>
MRS (Modular Radar System) <BR>
MRS is a multipurpose experimental radar system designed to perform real time calibrated polarimetric measurements of target cross section and signature.  The radar is fully polarimetric, employs a 20 w. CW waveform, capable of being swept in frequency over the band 2 GHz to 18 GHz, and of measuring a 1 sq. m. target cross section at ranges up to 10 km with better than a 10 dB SNR in a 1 kHz bandwidth.  <P>

MRS was designed and built by the DDRE and a contractor (CRIMP A/S)  as an instrumentation grade radar for measurement of target signatures over a significant portion of the radar spectrum, and at any desired polarization.  Of significance is the calibrated RCS (radar cross section) measurement accuracy of ~0.5 dB, range resolution of 25cm, and the ability to measure target response at frequency pairs which are independently selectable over the operating band.  <P>

The radar achieves high resolution with a phase coded waveform and wide instantaneous bandwidth, thus enabling measurement capability not achievable with synthesized high resolution waveforms.  Complete parameters are available on request. <P> 

The radar has been employed by DDRE in a campaign to reduce the RCS of Danish ships, and to evaluate the effectiveness of deployed chaff.  Such measurements of dynamic phenomena requires high resolution in both range and time.  The system is mounted in a standard shipping container and thus is readily transportable.  <P>

Radar Polarimetry - <BR>
World class theoretical work on analysis of the radar scattering matrix and interpretation of phenomenology measurable using polarimetric techniques is performed at DDRE.  With increasing interest in the application of radar polarimetry to remote sensing for both military and environmental purposes (if indeed there is a difference) this work has large significance.  Among the extant decomposition theories for analyzing polarimetric responses is the so-called Krogager decomposition theory.  Ernst Krogager is a researcher at DDRE.  Krogager has developed a three component decomposition which applies to the coherent case and results in scattering components associated with a sphere, a diplane, and a helix.  Processing of imagery using this technique allows classification on a pixel by pixel basis, in terms of these three components, enabling interesting interpretation of the underlying structure.  <P>

Command & Control - <BR>
C2 developments are applied to each of the services in different ways as the CISs (Command Information Systems) for Army, Navy, and Air Force are not unified.  DDRE efforts in this area emphasize the application of techniques developed elsewhere to Danish environments.  Three levels of activity are addressed: C2 environments, including application of tools and standards; architectures, such as application of open system concepts in the development of DACCIS (Danish Army Command & Control Information System); and selected, specific functional developments such as data fusion.  <P>

The lab has two approaches to the development of data fusion technology.  Fusion of data from multiple diverse or distributed sources is addressed within the Computer Science Department, while fusion of data across commensurate data types or within a platform is addressed within the Sensor Department.  As an example of the former, DDRE is involved in the NATO DFD (Data Fusion Demonstrator) Project, and the EUCLID RTP 6.1 (EUropean Collaboration for the Long term In Defence - Research Technology Package) effort.  Fusion work fitting the latter category is DDREs contribution to NATO AC-243 / Panel 10 / RSG.18: Sensor Fusion for Short Range Air Defence (SHORAD). <P>

DFD  -  is a seven nation project within NATO AC-243 / Panel 3.  The project started in 1993 and is intended to demonstrate the feasibility of automating the process of formulating the enemy ground order of battle.  Its focus is artificial intelligence and knowledge based tools for fusion of all source message traffic.  The demonstrator is implemented in a simulation environment.  The Danish contribution is in a module called CAF - correlation, aggregation, fusion.<P>

EUCLID RTP 6.1  -  EUCLID is a collaborative military research program aimed at developing defence related technologies, under the WEU.  The program is designed to promote trans-national cooperation among companies.  RTP 6.1 involves seven nations and addresses the application of artificial intelligence techniques to C3I systems.  Danish work is focused on a generic workstation for command & control, with emphasis on automated message analysis and decision support for planning. <P>

RSG.18 (SHORAD)  -  is a newly initiated study group with the related objectives of showing that sensors can be used in land and sea battle environments in a more efficient way, to define the benefits, and to describe methods for realizing the benefits for short range air defence.  The Danish representative to RSG.18, Christian Birkemark, is its chairman.  <P>

<B>4.   ASSESSMENT</B><BR>
DDRE is a small organization providing scientific and technological advice and development capability to the Danish Defence structure.  It functions primarily in a consultant role, applying its research and development capability to carefully selected areas.  The organization maintains active involvement with NATO DRG activities, and leverages these for awareness of evolving technical issues and to derive at least part of its guidance for selection of areas of emphasis.  With some notable exceptions, the lab emphasizes the application of techniques developed elsewhere to Danish environments.  A new Director (Dr. Scient. Peter Lawaetz) has recently been appointed, if his background provides any indication, this may signal future support for increased emphasis on research, giving the lab a better balance with what appears to be its current trend toward system engineering.  The efforts of note are contributions to radar polarimetry (world class) and an instrumentation grade, high resolution radar (somewhat unique).  C2 work, particularly in the area of data fusion, is of interest but not ground-breaking.  The NATO DFD and EUCLID RTP 6.1 programs address somewhat similar issues from different perspectives and with different methodologies.  Of the two, the EUCLID effort appears to be the more promising. <P>

<B>5.   POINTS OF CONTACT</B><P>

