<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 11</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>4 August 1996<BR>  
Command & Control, Surveillance<BR> 
<A HREF="kessler.htm">Otto Kessler</A></H3>
  
<H3>Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  
C2 and Surveillance Newsletter No. 11<BR>  
Danish Center for Remote Sensing</H3>  
<H3>A review of the Electromagnetics Institute, of the Technical University of Denmark, with emphasis on remote sensing activities. </H3>  

<I>Keywords: Remote Sensing;   Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR); 
                 Radar Polarimetry;  Radar Interferometry;  Denmark R&D;</I><P>

Content:  
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Electromagnetics Institute 
<DD>         2.1 Optical Communications 
<DD>         2.2 Antennas 
<LI>Remote Sensing 
<DD>         3.1  Danish Center for Remote Sensing 
<DD>         3.1.1  EMISAR 
<DD>         3.1.2  Collection programs 
<LI>Assessment 
<LI>Points of Contact 
<LI>Feedback 
</OL>

<B>1.   SUMMARY </B><BR>
The Electromagnetics Institute of the Technical University of Denmark conducts research and development in three main areas: remote sensing, optical communications, and antennas.  This newsletter provides an overview of research performed at EMI with emphasis on remote sensing activities performed under the Danish Center for Remote Sensing (DCRS) using Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) for earth observation.  The primary instrument for data collection is the EMISAR radar which operates at L- and C-bands, provides 2m best resolution, is fully polarimetric, and has interferometric modes of operation.  EMISAR is flown in a Danish Air Force Gulfstream G-3.  As a data collection resource EMISAR combines a number of advanced capabilities which make it a unique asset for geophysical measurements.  Characterization of topology, vegetation, and man-made objects can be performed in 3-dimensional spatial, velocity, and polarimetric fields.  Programs conducted to date have addressed glaciology, geology, vegetation, and various geophysical parameters. <P>

<B>2.  ELECTROMAGNETICS INSTITUTE (EMI) </B><BR>
The Electromagnetics Institute (EMI) is part of the EE Department of the Technical University of Denmark (TUD).  TUD is located just outside Copenhagen in Lyngby.  The Institute conducts research and development in three main areas: remote sensing, optical communications, and antennas (and EM field theory).  Research at the Institute is sponsored primarily by Danish government funding for civilian technology but EMI also receives support from private sources within Denmark and from other nations.  EMI is an active participant in a number of European research programs and collaborates with other universities and researchers for scientific analysis and experimental support.<P>  

EMI hosts two major national programs:  the Center for Broadband Telecommunications (CBT) is sponsored by the Danish Technical Research Council to perform research in optical communications, and the Danish Center for Remote Sensing (DCRS) is sponsored by the Danish National Research Foundation to address research in radar remote sensing.  In addition EMI hosts the Near field Antenna Test Facility which serves as a calibration facility for the European Space Agency (ESA)..<P>

<B>2.1  Optical Communications </B><BR>
Research activities pertaining to optical communications are organized under the Center for Broadband Telecommunications (CBT) and divided into four main areas: 
<UL>
<LI>Lasers and Optical Amplifiers - including use of fibre optics in microwave links and cellular mobile communication systems, photonic networks and switches, and optical components.  
<LI>Gigabit Electronics - including digital monolithic IC, MMIC and VLSI research.  
<LI>Optical Waveguides and Broadband Switches - including optical waveguide components, and active materials in waveguides.  
<LI>High Speed Systems - including optical front end amplifiers, optical CPFSK experiments, and investigations into non-linear effects in high speed switching.  
</UL>
Additional details or points of contact are available upon request. <P>

<B>2.2  Antennas</B><BR> 
Research on antennas and antenna measurements with emphasis on computational models for describing electromagnetic radiation as well as scattering phenomena.  Theoretical work in the area of near field methods has moved measurement capability beyond conventional frequency domain measurements, to the development of time domain methods which allow transformation of near field measurements to representation of far field radiation patterns for large bandwidths.  Applied work has resulted in design and implementation of airborne and space based antennas, and as noted, EMIs anechoic chamber (dimensions ~17m x 15m x 14m) provides precision calibration for the ESA.  <P>

<B>3.  REMOTE SENSING</B><BR> 
Remote sensing at EMI has a long history of addressing principles for observation of the earth using primarily radar and radiometric techniques.  Research areas include microwave sensors, collection methods, signal interpretation, and presentation techniques.  Since February 1994 research has been organized under the Danish Center for Remote Sensing (DCRS) which is financed by the Danish National Research Foundation, (50M DKK over a five year period; 5.5 DKK ~1 USD) and headed by Dr. Soren Madsen.   <P>

<B>3.1  Danish Center for Remote Sensing (DCRS) </B><BR>
DCRS was established to  "..conduct research relating to instruments for remote sensing and their application to Earth Observation and Earth Science."  Predecessor organizations at TUD have a long history of environmental measurements at various locations throughout the world.  Programs conducted by DCRS to date have addressed glaciology, geology, vegetation, and earth parameters.  The Centers primary instrument for data collection is EMISAR (Electromagnetics Institute SAR). <P>

<B>3.1.1  EMISAR</B><BR>
The EMISAR system is a dual band (L- and C-band) polarimetric SAR with interferometric capabilities which allow generation of 3-dimensional and velocity imagery.  It is capable of repeat track interferometry (RTI) in both bands and cross track interferometry (XTI) in C-band only.  EMISAR is installed an a Danish Air Force Gulfstream G-3 aircraft, it operates at altitudes up to 12 km, and in its high resolution mode has a 12 km swath width and 2m x 2m spatial resolution.  The system has on-board real-time processing and display for a selected mode of data, and high density recording of all data for post flight processing and display.  The aircraft is equipped with GPS and INS navigation systems.  In order to meet stringent data collection requirements, DCRS has designed a novel control system which couples navigation, radar, and aircraft flight management systems to enable the aircraft to fly desired baselines to an accuracy on the order of 10m or less. <P>

The diversity of EMISARs modes make it a powerful instrument for data collection.  Polarimetric data provides robust characterization of topographic features, vegetation, and man-made objects.  While full understanding of scattering responses as a function of different scattering matrix decomposition methods is still being developed, polarization based imagery clearly enables discrimination among different surface features such as changes in vegetation state and recognition of geometric shapes and attitudes. <P> 

RTI allows highly accurate topographic mapping, change detection, and measurement of dynamic phenomena such as movement of glaciers and earthquakes.  The method is based on collection of image pairs from consecutive flight passes and has potential for achieving 10cm height resolution.  XTI enables accurate 3-dimensional measurement of an objects location.  Because image pairs are collected simultaneously, height determination of moving objects is possible.  The method requires that an image pair be collected simultaneously from two antennas displaced in height on the same platform.  The difference in elevation angle between simultaneous observations is used to derive the height dimension in a 3-D SAR image.  <P>

The EMISAR may be unique in providing this combination of measurement capabilities.  While a few other systems (very few) are known to possess some of these advanced features, the flexibility offered by EMISAR for geophysical experiments is believed to be unique.  <P>

<B>3.1.2  Collection Programs</B><BR> 
EMISAR has been employed in a number of flight campaigns to explore the uses of SAR technology  features of the system for improved understanding of geophysical properties.  In many cases these studies are coordinated with other European programs, sharing assets for experiments and data for collaborative analysis and interpretation.  Some of these programs are listed below.  <P>

GLACIER DYNAMICS STUDIES - Storstrommen Glacier, Northeast Greenland; use of SAR RTI to provide spatial measurements of instantaneous ice velocity and micro-topography.  Significant for monitoring changes in glacier size, surface elevations, and velocities, believed to be indicators of global climate change.  <P>

SEA ICE STUDIES - ice monitoring in South Greenland waters to develop an understanding of the microwave signatures of ice surfaces as a function of their physical properties.  Analysis is based on  C-band polarimetry supported by microwave radiometry and video.  <P>

GEOLOGY - a geologic survey of a selected area in Eastern Greenland to determine if polarimetric SAR or interferometric SAR techniques can be applied to study the relation between terrain morphology, geologic structures and the physical properties of mountain complexes.  <P>

SOIL AND PLANT STUDIES - Foulum, Jutand;  research concerning the application of remote sensing techniques to monitor agricultural crops, biomass, hydrology, soil moisture and surface roughness.  <P> 

SAND DUNE DYNAMICS - Rabjerg Mile dune field, Jutland;
research on atmospheric circulation, and effects of friction with the earths surface by estimation of soil removal, dust generation, loss of nutrients and seeds, etc. from detailed topographic information.  Precise topography is derived from repeated measurements of the same area using interferometric SAR techniques.   <P>

<B>4.   ASSESSMENT</B><BR>
DCRS must be rated as a world leader in technology relating to instruments for remote sensing and their application to earth observation.  As noted, EMISAR represents a unique measurement capability.  The diversity of measurements possible from simultaneous modes, and the relative ease with which independent measurements can be made to either verify results, or separate correlated effects, make it a valuable measurement instrument.  DCRS emphasizes applied research, focusing on sensing technology, measurement techniques, and visualization methods, while collaborating extensively with others for scientific analysis and interpretation.  The focus of DCRS research is on civilian applications, but the work it has conducted in remote sensing clearly has implications for military systems, addressing the need to understand details of the environment to be encountered by both friendly and hostile forces, and also for specific requirements such as foliage penetration, and target detection and classification.  .<P>

<B>5.   POINTS OF CONTACT</B><BR>
Prof. Bent Knudsen,   Director EMI<BR>
E-mail: bk@emi.dtu.dk<P>

Dr. Soren Madsen,   Head DCRS<BR>
E-mail: snm@emi.dtu.dk<P>

Common Information:<BR>
      Electromagnetics Institute<BR>
      Technical University of Denmark<BR>
      Building 348 <BR>
      DK-2800 Lyngby<BR>
      Denmark<P>

      Tel:  45 45 88 14 44<BR>
      Fax:  45 45 93 16 34<P>


