<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsletter No. 1</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY><H3>November 27, 1995<BR>  European Remote Sensing<BR>
<A HREF="lewisj.htm">John Lewis</A></H3>    
<P><H3>An Office of Naval Research-European Office-- Space<BR> 
Newsletter No 1<BR>  Space Based Multispectral Imaging System</H3> </P><P>
<B>Contents:</B></P><PRE> 
1.  Summary
2.  Multispectral Imaging System
3.  Personal contact
</PRE>
<P><B> 1. Summary</B><P></P>A spaced based multispectral imaging
system has been developed in Germany by Daimler-Benz Aerospace, now
Dornier GmbH Satellitensysteme. The sensor system is now in its third
generation development called MOMS 03. Forerunners, MOMS 01 and MOMS 02
space qualified on SPAS 01, missions STS-7 and STS 11 and US Space
Shuttle Mission 55, respectively. A version of MOMS 02 is part of the
ongoing MIR Priroda project. MOMS 03 is a tri-partite imaging system
combining a high spatial resolution panchromatic imaging capability with
two channel stereoscopic alongtrack panchromatic imaging and a 4 channel
multispectral imaging unit. Talks are on-going for possible inclusion of
a follow on version of a NRL Clementine class, small satellite, under
the auspices of the Navy Space Science & Technology Council. </P><P><B>2.
MOMS 03 Imaging System</B><P></P>The MOMS 03 characteristics include a
published 5 meter Ground Sampling Distance (GSD) for the high Resolution
Panchromatic Imaging Equipment on a 500 km orbit. Dornier felt that
further improvements might be possible. The stereo alongtrack capability
was 10 meter GSD and the multispectral 4 channel section produced a 15
meter GSD. Under these conditions all three subsystems exhibit a 60 km
swath and a Field of Regard of 645 km. The single panchromatic and the
stereo channels are both 530-760 nm. The 4 spectral channels cover the
bands of 440-505, 530-575, 645-680 and 770-810 nanometers.<BR>  The
following is a summary specification listing of MOMS 03 at a 500 km
orbit: Each parameter is for the HR-Pan, The Stereo and the
Multispectral system in that order. Number of Pixels 12,000 6,000 4,000
Pixel size in micrometers 8x8 8x8 8x8 Effective focal length in
millimeters 800 514 300 Aperture in millimeters 180 100 90 Spectral Band
in nanometers 530-760 530-760 (4)440-810 Percent Relative Nyquist
Frequency 16 17 11 Percent Optics MTF (panchromatic) 61 79 86 Percent
System MTF cross track 37 50 54 Dynamic Range (rho=100%) 2644 5121 3481
S/N Image (rho=35%) 245 347 283 Data rate (12 bit/USES) 100 25 11.7 Data
Rate (8 bit/USES) 67 17 7.5 The equipment weighs in at 77 kg and
requires 91 watts of power from the bus. The download will be compatible
with the LANDSAT ground links.<BR>  MOMS is a commercial development
and the product called EarthMap will eventually be on the market. The
system shows promise for both government and commercial uses once space
qualified. Space qualifying hardware that will be needed for future
naval warfighting requirements is one of the objectives of the Navys
new Space Council under Admiral Peleaz, as Chair. The Council is new,
having stood up in June, but is off to an ambitious start. While no
projects have been approved or funded as yet, one of the considerations
is a Small Satellite of the Clementine class to be a technology
demonstrator platform. Preliminary plans include a series of small
satellites of this variety to be launched on a three year replacement
cycle. It is hoped that the development and launch of this series will
be joint projects under either Memorandum of Understanding or Bilateral
Agreements with our Allies. Talks are on-going with the Germans about
the possibility of space qualifying MOMS 03 on a remote sensing version
of the new Clementines. </P><P><B>3. Personal Contacts</B><P></P>MOMS
03<BR>  Dr. R. Lutz, Head of Earth Observation Optical Instruments<BR>
 Dornier GmbH<BR>  Satellitensysteme<BR>  88039 Friedrichshafen <BR> 
Tel.: (+49 75 45) 8 99 92<BR>  Fax:(+44 75 45) 8 22 06 </P><P>Navy
Space Council <BR>  Captain Patrick OConnell<BR>  Office of Naval
Research<BR>  Space Technology and Liaison Office<BR>  800 North
Quincy Street<BR>  Arlington VA 22217-5660<BR>  USA<BR>  Tel.: +1 703
696-0440<BR>  Fax: +1 703 696-4274 </P><P></P>
<HR><P>The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing
current information on science and technology development in European
Countries. In order to better meet your needs, our Associate Directors
and Scientists are very much interested in knowing what your specific
science and technology interests are. Please provide feedback.<BR>  If
