<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsletter No. 2</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>#001-1996<BR><H3>January 4, 1996<BR>  European Star Navigation<BR>

<A HREF="lewisj.htm">John Lewis</A></H3> 
<P></P>
<H3>An Office of Naval Research Newsletter-European Office -- Space<BR>
 Newsletter No 2<BR>  &Ouml;rsted Stellar Compass </H3> 
<P><B>Contents:</B></P><P></P><PRE>1. Summary
2. Advanced Stellar Compass
3. Acknowledgments
4. Personal contacts
</PRE>
<P><B>1. Summary</B></P><P>A space based stellar compass has been
developed in Denmark at the Technical University of Denmark under the
guidance of John Leif Joergensen. An early version of the stellar
compass is scheduled to fly as part of the &Ouml;rsted project on board
a Danish microsatellite, with mission requirements to determine the
magnetic vector accuracy to at least 3 nT and 20 arcseconds with a
scalar accuracy of at least 1 nT. The advanced stellar compass is
comprised of two separate units, a CCD detector (based on a commercial
Sony interline CCD detector) and data processing unit with a 486
processor. The camera head derives attitude information from star
recognition in its field of view, using a star catalog of 10,000 plus
stars. Prototype testing at the Jet Propulsion laboratory Table mountain
Observatory has been recently completed. This Stellar Compass represents
an advance in the art of star trackers with a low mass, low power
consumption and fully autonomous operation providing a high accuracy
quaternion output and low cost implementation. Talks are on-going for
possible space testing on a follow on version of a Naval Research Lab
Clementine class, small satellite, under the auspices of the Navy
Space Science & Technology Council. </P><P><B>2. &Ouml;rsted Advanced
Stellar Compass</B></P><P>The &Ouml;rsted microsatellite payload
consists of a vector fluxgate magnetometer, an Overhauser scalar
magnetometer, an advanced stellar compass (2), six charged particle
detectors and GPS backup receivers. An eight meter deployable boom
carries the two magnetic-field measuring instruments and the stellar
compass. The boom isolates the instruments from the perturbing magnetic
field generated by the spacecraft. The spacecraft attitude control is by
gravity gradient stabilization, supplemented by active magnetic-torguer
coils. The position is determined by the GPS receivers. The overall mass
of the space craft is 64.4 Kg with a 45 cm width, a 68 cm height and a
depth of 45 cm. It is to be launched on a polar orbit, 450 X 850 km.
</P><P>The stellar compass has been evaluated with real sky images at
JPLs Table Mountain. It was mounted on the front of a 24 inch telescope
with a fairy long interconnection, causing a small degradation in
performance due to noise. The testing was primarily to determine the
noise equivalent angle of the system. The measured relative accuracy was
5.7 arcseconds (3s (sigma)) for each of two axes, 42 arcseconds for roll
angle about the boresight and an NEA of 3.22(3s(sigma)) for each of two
axes. Flight versions of the stellar compass are expected to exhibit
increased accuracy. It is believed that modifications to the optics and
processor would allow cost effective radiation hardening to adapt to
more stressful orbits. For full testing data please contact Allen R.
Eisenman, Jet Propulsion Lab, below. </P><P>The stellar compass shows
promise for both government and commercial use. Space qualifying
hardware that will be needed for future warfighting requirements is one
of the objectives of the Navys Space Science and Technology Council
under Admiral Peleaz, as chair. While no projects have been fully
approved or funded as yet, one of the Councils considerations is a
Small Satellite of the Clementine class to be a remote sensing
technology demonstrator platform. Preliminary plans are for the
Clementine Remote Sensing Spacecraft to be the first of a series,
launched on a three year replacement schedule beginning in 1999. It is
hoped that the development and launch of this series will be a joint
project under agreements with many of our allies. Plans are solidifying
with the Germans about the possibility of flying a multi-spectral
imagining system called MOMS 03. .<I>See</I>, Newsletter Number One on
Space of October 9, 1995. Likewise, talks are progressing towards space
qualifying the subject Stellar Compass on this first launch. </P><P><B>3.
Acknowledgments</B></P><P>"Real Sky Performance of the prototype &Ouml;rsted
Advanced Stellar Compass,"<BR>  Allen R. Eisenman, submitted for
publication, IEEE Aerospace and Electronics magazine. </P><P><B>4.
Personal Contacts</B></P><P>&Ouml;rsted Stellar Compass<BR>  Dr. John
L. J&ouml;rgensen<BR>  Department of Electrophysics, <BR>  Technical
University of Denmark<BR>  2800 Lingby, Denmark<BR>  Tel.: +45 45 25
34 48 </P><P>Table Mountain Testing<BR>  Allen R. Eisenman<BR> 
Member Technical staff<BR>  Celestial Sensors Group<BR>  Jet
Propulsion Laboratory<BR>  4800 Oak Grove Drive <BR>  Pasadena,
California<BR>  Tel.: +1 818 354 4999 </P><P>Navy Space Council<BR> 
Captain Patrick OConnell<BR>  Office of Naval Research<BR>  Space
Technology and Liaison Office<BR>  800 North Quincy Street<BR> 
Arlington VA 22217-5600<BR>  Tel.: +1 703 696 4274 </P><P></P><HR><P>The
Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing current
information on science and technology development in European Countries.
In order to better meet your needs, our Associate Directors and
Scientists are very much interested in knowing what your specific
science and technology interests are. Please provide feedback.<BR>  If
there are others whom you are aware of that have interests in these
newsletters, please pass their e-mail address to me and I will add them
to ONR EUROPE distribution list. </P><P>For more information on this
topic contact:<BR>  Dr. John Lewis<BR>  Office of General Counsel <BR>
 ONR Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone Rd.<BR>  London NW1 5TH<BR> 
England<BR>  Tel.: +44 (0)171 514 4369<BR>  Fax: +44 (0)171 5144924<BR>
    e-mail jlewis@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  US Address: ONREUR, PSC 802 BOX
39, FPO AE 09499 </P><HR><P></P>
