<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsletter No. 3</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY><P>#002-1996<BR>  
</P><H3>February 23, 1996<BR>  European Defense Industrial Policy<BR>
 <A HREF="lewisj.htm">John Lewis</A></H3>  
<H3>An Office of Naval Research Newsletter-European Office -- Space<BR>
 Newsletter No 3<BR>  Defense Industrial Policy, Europe<BR>  Notes
from the Second Annual International Conference on Reshaping Business
Strategies in the European Defence Industry.<BR>  Amsterdam, The
Netherlands, 25 -- 26 January 1996</H3> 
<P>Keywords: <I>European Industry Policy, European Defense Policy,
Euromanagement, Defense Industry Rationalization, Arms</I>
</P><P></P><PRE><B>Content:</B>
1.  Executive Summary
2.  Introduction and General Impressions
3.  The Players
4.  The Speakers
5.  An Asian Aside
6.  Conclusions
</PRE>
<P><B>Executive Summary</B>
</P><P> The Annual Conference on European Defense Industrial Policy was
presented by Euromanagement, a training firm, and Jane's Defence
Magazines. The theme of the conference was in the nature of a wake-up
call for European Governments to guard their Defense Industry Technology
Base from a leaner, meaner American arms export market. Figures were
soft but alarming. The American post cold war share of total world arms
exports has doubled from 25 percent in 1990 to 51 percent in 1995. The
widely shared fear is that the USA will go from the main supplier of
world arms to the only supplier. Since the Cold War, Europe imported 18
b USD in arms, 16 from the United States, which meant Europe bought
eight times more from America than from Europe itself. American
procurement policy was described as subsidized, protectionist,
monopolistic and colbertist. Speakers, all well known defense experts,
articulated a belief in free markets and 'best value for money,' while
advocating policies that would skew the procurement towards national
European champions. The strong American position was seen as the result
of currency, protectionist policy, industrial rationalization and the
Gulf War 'infomercial'. The speakers did not see transatlantic mergers
and acquisitions likely, were unhappy with subcontractor status and
advocated a 'Fortress Europe' defense industry policy. Conclusion:
American defense industry should expect a more difficult European
playing field in the coming decade.
</P><P><B>Introduction and General Impressions</B>
</P><P> The Second Annual International Conference on Reshaping
Business Strategies in the European Defence Industry was held in
Amsterdam on January 25 & 26, 1996. The conference was organized by
Euromanagement, a training firm and Jane's Defence Magazines. The
speakers were well-known global defense experts including government
policy makers, industrialists, journalists and trade union leaders.
Government speakers covered the spectrum from liberal United Kingdom to
nationalistic France. All Governments see the need to both rationalize
their national defense industry and foster cross border European mergers
and acquisitions. All representatives from Europe professed to believe
in the free market and in best value for money in procurement.
</P><P> The constituent Nations were reading from separate scripts,
though, when it came to advocated policy. Even liberal United Kingdom
acknowledged that best value for money did not necessarily mean free and
open competition, as we think of the term in our procurement policy.
France, nationalistic as ever, stood on the left side of the spectrum,
advocating rigid control on import/exports and close government control
over all rationalization, but especially cross border mergers and
acquisitions. Germany, looking both at the rest of Europe and
transatlantic, felt that Europe could consolidate and rationalize along
American lines and welcomed collaboration with enthusiasm. A surprise
player on the world armament stage is Sweden, shedding their pacific
anti-military bias, and speaking of European consolidation and cross
border mergers with both their European brothers and transatlantic
partners. Egon Lindroth, President & CEO of Celsius Industries, used his
own company to underline the Swedish effort at defense industry
rationalization and hinted at two possible cross border mergers not yet
made public. It was obvious to me that Sweden intends to play a bigger
part in European defense now that they are a full member of the EU.
</P><P> The tone of the conference was not hostile towards the
Americans, but we were clearly the target. There was scarcely a speaker
that did not have a slide that highlighted our doubling of world market
share in the last five years. Lockheed/Martin generated a lot of
interest with one slide depicting the possibility of a medium-sized
country going to this single American company for all their defense
needs. Another slide was captioned, 'Lockheed/Loral, Gunning for
European Defense Jobs'. It was acknowledged that we were reaping
benefits from downsizing and consolidation, but the primary emphasis was
on our post cold war defense policy, seen as nationalistic by the
European nations. One futuristic slide showed the European defense
industry, first going to monopolistic national segment champions, then
to subcontractor status with America industry, and finally, out of
existence. One French speaker estimates the United States will command a
75 percent share of the world market in defense technology by 2005.
</P><P> In spite of this 'the sky is falling' ambiance, the attendees
seemed gloomy about obtaining the Pan-European consolidation and
rationalization necessary to compete with the brash, new American
defense industry. Only Germany seemed to think that Europe could
overcome the nationalist tendencies enough to consolidate into a truly
European industry. The German optimism may be attendant to the planned
Daimler-Benz/Areospatiale merger; an enthusiasm not shared by the other
nationalities. In response to a question from the floor as to when was
it too late to take the actions necessary to correct the imbalance,
Francois Heisbourg, Senior-Vice-President, Strategic Development, Matra
Defense Espace, replied, "...last year, ...there are many of us dead
now, we just don't know it yet."
</P><P><B>The Players</B>
</P><P> The United Kingdom has led the way with privatization and
mergers, and consequently, is viewed as the most liberal of the Western
European Nations. The result is a 30 percent loss of defense jobs and
export dollars, but United Kingdom defense experts feel that the United
Kingdom is poised to capitalize on this recent rationalization. BAe
(third) and GEC (ninth) are two of the three European defense companies
in the world's top ten by revenue. The United Kingdom, in contrast to
the Continent, believe themselves ready for both cross-border and
transatlantic alliances.
</P><P> French defense industry is in disarray. Giat (tanks and guns)
and Direction des Constructions Navales (ships), are grossly overmanned,
losing money and not ready for cross border arrangements. Nor is the
nationalistic French Government ready to liberalize enough to
rationalize even within its own borders, let alone cross border. Trade
unions, falling markets, overmanning and a virulent protectionist
attitude do not bode well for building national champions available for
cross border alliances. The French, with a minority voice, support the
Treaty of Rome's article 223 which allows governments to protect defense
firms from EU rules. It is this author's opinion, after hearing the
French rhetoric, that France will be one of the barriers to a
Pan-European defense rationalization. Questions from the floor indicated
Germany and the United Kingdom think this too.
</P><P> Germany has started the rationalization process. R & D is down
thirty percent the last five years, defense jobs down fifty percent and
the exchange rates painful. Germany expects to lead the way toward a
European defense industry. Daimler Benz is looking at an alliance with
French Aerospatiale whereby Germany would own fifty-one percent of the
resultant firm. We will see! The German speakers articulated a free
market policy and underscored the need for creating a unified European
defense industry, but acknowledged a need for transatlantic alliances
during the process. Never-the-less, all German speakers indicated that
reciprocity in defense procurement policy with the Americans was
required to help balance the playing field.
</P><P> Sweden was surprisingly enthusiastic about building a European
defense industry to provide a larger share of Europe's defense needs.
They took a vocal opposition to the Treaty of Rome's article 223 and
hinted at two cross border mergers in the works for Celsius Industries
(Bofors, Klockums, electronics and aerospace). Early rationalizations
have made Sweden more competitive on international markets, both
financially and technically. They are serious about contributing to a
European Defense Industry in the future and should be a much larger
player across the Atlantic during the next decade, as well.
</P><P> The trade unions from United Kingdom, France and elsewhere
naturally were against any rationalization that meant a loss of jobs,
which negates the process. They spoke of supporting the 'best value for
money' concept of procurement but wanted a figure added to all external
bids to compensate for the loss of work to the national industries.
Where were we to get this figure? The trade unions will supply it, of
course!
</P><P><B>An Asian Aside</B>
</P><P> Paul Beaver, a consultant with Jane's, presented an area
analysis of the Asian market. This is the only area in the world where
defense industry markets are growing. From Pakistan to Japan, North
Korea to New Guinea, the region has conflict, tension and turmoil. The
Indian/ Pakistan dispute is the world's only nuclear arms race at the
moment. China's bid to increase its territorial waters has driven
defense markets in Malaysia, Philippines, Singapore and Brunei. (There
were five delegates at this conference from Brunei MOD, out of
approximately 80 attendees???) Indonesia has internal problems with East
Timor, Sumatra and Irian Jaya. Japan remains concerned with an unstable
Russia and North Korea. Western arms spending targeted for these areas
has risen and the trend will continue well into the next century. In
Paul Beaver's words, "Asia is the place to be and be seen in the late
1990's."
</P><P><B>Conclusion</B>
</P><P> This conference was a wake up call for European defense
industries to drop their nationalistic policies and rationalize towards
a competitive position viz. a viz. American industry or prepare
themselves for extinction. All speakers and attendees acknowledged the
need for Europe's national defense industries to cut costs and shed
jobs, to get into a position where national champions can be established
in segments and then industries. The United States was both the target
and the road map to follow out of current difficulties. The speakers
took care not to disparage their transatlantic alliances, but it was
clear that all players intend to reduce the arms purchased from the USA.
Everyone agrees that the American market is protected and an uneven
playing field. While there were at least three different scripts on how
to build a Pan-European defense industry, no one advocated a free
market, as no one thought that Europe could compete in the short term
with the newly lean and mean American defense industry. We heard support
for subsidies, licensing, fudge factors to skew the procurements and
just plain protection, but no Adam Smith, at least not in the short run.
Lockheed Martin was a lightning rod and it is a shame that the one
American Speaker, John Montague, Vice-President Financial Strategies,
Lockheed Martin, flew in at the last minute. He gave his speech in a
vacuum and left without confronting the 'Fortress Europe' mentality
extant at this conference. I would expect the European market to be a
more difficult playing field for American defense industry in the
future.
</P><P><B>The Speakers</B>
</P><P> EMILE BLANC, Head of the Western European Armaments Group<BR> 
DR. JOACHIM GEISEL, Vice-President, Daimler Benz Aerospace<BR>  FRACOIS
HEISBOURG, Senior Vice President, Matra Defense Espace<BR>  EGON
LINDEROTH, President and CEO Celsius Industries<BR>  CHARLES MASEFIELD,
Head of Defence Export Services, UK Ministry of Defence<BR>  JOHN
MONTAGUE, Vice-President Financial Strategies, Lockheed Martin<BR> 
ALEXANDER SCHAUB, Director-General -- DG IV, European Commission<BR> 
JOURNALISTS, Jane's Defence Magazines<BR>  ...and many other well-known
global defense experts
</P><HR><P> The opinions and assessments in this report are solely
those of the author and do not necessarily reflect ONREUR, Navy or U. S.
Government positions.
</P><P> The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing
current information on science and technology development in European
countries. In order to better meet your needs, our Associate Directors
and Scientists are very much interested in knowing what are your
specific science and technology interests. Please let me know what they
are.
</P><P> Furthermore, if there are others, whom you are aware of, that
have interest in these newsletters please pass their e- mail address to
me and I will add them to the distribution list.
