<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsletter No. 4</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY><P>#003-1996<BR>  
</P><H3>June 6, 1996<BR>
  Technology Transfer -- European Union Regulations<BR>
 <A HREF="lewisj.htm">John Lewis</A></H3> 
 
<H3>An Office of Naval Research Newsletter-European Office -- Space<BR>
 Newsletter No 4<BR>  
Technology Transfer -- European Union Regulations<BR>  
Technology Transfer Regulations and Policy, European Union
Notes from the European Study Conference on Technology Transfer<BR>  
Brussels, Belgium, 22-23 May 1996</H3> 
<P>Keywords: <I>European Union Regulations, Technology Transfer, Competition Law,  Euromanagement,  European Mergers and Acquisitions</I><P>
<PRE><B>
Content:</B>
1.  Executive Summary
2.  The new Regulations
3.  R & D Block Exemption
4.  Perceptions
5   Who Cares
</PRE>
<P>
<B>Executive Summary</B><P>

The European Commission has adopted new regulations for Technology Transfer, Mergers and Acquisitions, and cross border Research and Development within the Union.  These new Commission Regulations (EC No 240/96 et seg.), came into effect on 1 April of this year. The new regulations replaced patent licensing and know-how regulations, rolling both into a new technology transfer regulation.<BR>
These regulations apply whenever technology moves into the EU or crosses borders within the Union.  The definition of technology is broad, and the regulations apply to any agreement that involves intellectual property, technical data, trade secrets, licensable manufacturing technology or technical data. The intent of the restrictions is to preclude monopoly and ensure the dissemination of technology widely throughout the Union.
The regulations have certain common features:  they are for defined periods; they contain a defined list of permitted restrictions ("white list")and proscribed restrictions ("black list"); they incorporate an opposition procedure; and they entitle the Commission to withdraw the benefit of granted exemptions under certain circumstances.<BR>
The Commission provided within these regulations provisions for granting block exemptions, in certain areas, for agreements meeting the criteria specified in the relevant exemption.  An agreement either meets the exacting requirements of a block exemption or must be presented to the Commission under a notice provision.  Without a block exemption the notice process is lengthy and requires onerous data to be submitted, and the agreement is likely to be turned down by the commission for the same reasons that it did not fit within a block exemption.  The block exemptions generally do not allow a transferor long term control over their intellectual property,  and permissable controls are fraught with over regulation.  The penalty for failure to obtain Commission approval is invalidity of the agreement and the loss of the National or European Courts as a means to enforce it.<BR>
 A separate provision, article 223 of the Treaty of Rome, exempts defense industry agreements as exclusively within the sovereignty of individual nations and, at this point in time, makes these new regulations a "who cares" for the defense community.  Article 223 is broadly interpreted by Nation States and narrowly by the Commission.  More importantly, the article is under attack as an impediment to European Defense Industry rationalization by many States, e.g., Sweden, U K, and Germany. If  the Defense Community losses 223 as a shield, these regulations will become a concern in the future.<P>

<B>The New Regulations</B><P>

Article 1 sets out a list of obligations that may be included in a licensing agreement and which will not be regarded as restrictive of competition.  The block exemption procedures only apply when there are no more than two parties to the agreement.  With multi-party agreements the notice requirements and full scrutiny by the Commission is required. An agreement that does not fit the rigid requirements of a block exemption and that has not been submitted to the Commission under the Notice Procedures is invalid.  If the agreement involved a patent or patents, the patents would not be enforceable in the National or European courts.  It is important to note that these procedures apply to all Nations doing business within the European Union not just to agreements between Member States.<P>

	The restrictions white listed  in Article 2 are those normal and requisite to a technology transfer agreement and generally do not allow the full exploitation of the  patent or other intellectual property.  The white list has grown from what was contained in the previous regulations but is Milque Toast when it comes to vigorous exploitation of intellectual property rights.  The regulations normally limit protections to less than ten years.  A patent theoretically has up to a 20 year life and trade secrets forever.<P>

	Article 3 is the black list of restrictions that, when incorporated, always cause the agreement to fail.  It includes the familiar prohibition on restrictions on pricing and barriers to parallel imports.  For example, a United States company that markets a product world wide and restricts domestic licensees to U S markets, without allowing exports, may run afoul of the Commission as restrictive of European competition and find their agreement unenforceable on this side of the Atlantic. Other black listed restrictions are automatic term extensions, royalties beyond the life of the patent, tying-in of other licenses, customer division and many more.<P>

	Article 4 contains the opposition procedures that allow challenges.  Your licensee might take a license knowing it to be outside the exemptions and then later challenge the agreement.  Actually, this is a carryover provision from the old rules and has been rarely used.  Article 7 gives the Commission the authority to remove the benefit of a block agreement if they decide that it violates the exemption conditions.  Other articles are definitional and technical.<P>

	Finally, the benefit of a block exemption is denied when market share under the agreement is above 40 percent of the relevant market, which might be the European  Union or the World.  Small companies have to watch out for a small agreement with an industry giant that might exceed the market share test of the combination, resulting in invalidity and unenforceability of the agreement transferring technology.<P>

<B>R & D  Block Exemption</B><P>

	Commission Regulation 418/85 of 19 December 1984 continues to provide for a block exemption for agreements between two parties, where the sole purpose of the agreement is R & D.  Use of this provision requires the agreement to cover an identified R & D project, to give all parties access to and the right to exploit all results.  The agreement must be restricted to intellectual property rights and/or substantial know how.  There are numerous restrictions concerning products and market share of any developed product.  The agreement can cover no more than a 5 year period; renewable once under certain circumstances. There are mandatory requirements for the exchange of information regarding exploitation and granting of non-exclusive licenses regarding improvements of products.  There can be no restrictions regarding production, distribution and marketing other than those contained in the "white list" of the regulations.  It goes on and on.<P>
	
	Delegates at this conference, most of whom are competition or patent attorneys working in this field, indicated they have never seen a real agreement that could use the R&D Block exemption.  The reasons are many, for example, the time constraints mean that the agreement terminates before the intellectual property protection expires and the restrictions on controlling the product of the R&D are simply not adequate for companies to protect their markets.  Mergers and acquisitions can change the market share during the agreement and void the contract protections.  The R&D block exemption is a good idea but still needs a lot of work.<P>

<B>Perceptions</B><P>

	These new regulations suffer from too many cooks.  There are simply too many lawyers, bureaucrats, lawyers, commissioners and lawyers for coherent regulations.  The technical sections stretch on for an interminable length reflecting the many opinions and languages involved.  The operative articles are intertwined with 27 recitals leading up to article 1, and they, too, present binding conditions and proscriptions.  The starting position is that everything is proscribed and that you have to find an exemption for anything one wishes to do.  If you can not make the agreement fit the odd-shaped pigeon hole the agreement fails.  There is no rule of reason such as permeates US anti-trust law and the regulations are stiff and formal.   Worse, there is no history of case law providing a road map for guidance.  It is impossible to cover the multiplicity of business relationships with a list of do's and don'ts that cover the spectrum of agreements or even a single agreement, for that matter.  The seminar, attended mostly by patent attorneys laboring under the incoherence of a legal education superimposed over the exactness of an engineer, soon degenerated into techno-babble when trying to decide what one could or could not do.  Remember, these new regulations come from the same group that gave us the exacting size and curvature of an acceptable banana and a European strawberry!<P>

	The new regulations contain a provision asking those doing business subsequent to implementation, to serve notice to the Commission as to what, and how many, agreements they have entered into in the past that violated the now-superseded, old regulations.  This is like asking a person "when did you stop beating your wife?"  Not surprisingly, the attorneys are advising their clients not to comply with this precatory requirement.<P>

<B>So Who Cares</B><P>

	Not very many, at least, not in the defense community and not yet.  The treaty of Rome contains article 223 that exempts all military and defense activity from Commission regulations.  A couple of caveats are appropriate however, and the first is that article 223 is under attack and several European Union Members advocate eliminating this fence which gives members room to protect their industry under the guise of national sovereignty.  More than one of the speakers at a recent European defense conference cited the provision as an impediment to developing a pan-european defense policy and advocated its rescission.  Europe is concerned with rationalizing defense policy in order to compete with the post cold war competition across the Atlantic.  They see this as one of the beginning steps.  (See, newsletter 002-1996 by this author.)  Without article 223, the defense community would be subject to these regulations.<P>

	Second, while many member states interpret the 223 exemption broadly, the Commission does not.  It is my opinion that 223 will endure but that the Commission will chip away at its breadth.  It is likely that government to government agreements, e.g., MOU's  between DOD and allied MOD's will remain outside the Commission purview, but agreements that embody dual use products might find the Commission ready to sever the agreement and examine the transfer for its commercial impact.  The European court did this very thing a few years ago when they bifurcated an agreement concerning aircraft engines into military and civilian markets, then held the agreement void and unenforceable as an agreement splitting customers between distributors.  Non-defense U S industry takes the Commission seriously now and defense may be forced to in the future.<P>
<HR><P> The opinions and assessments in this report are solely
those of the author and do not necessarily reflect ONREUR, Navy or U. S.
Government positions.
