<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsletter No. 5</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY><P>#004-1996<BR>  
<H3>June 6, 1996<BR>
 Space Technology  Consortium Symposium<BR>
 <A HREF="lewisj.htm">John Lewis</A></H3> 
 
<H3>An Office of Naval Research Newsletter-European Office -- Space<BR>
 Newsletter No 5<BR>  
Space Technology Consortium -- Forging New Alliances for Space Technology
Notes from the Space Technology Consortium Symposium<BR>
Crystal City, Virginia, 14-16 May, 1996</H3> 

Key Words:  <I>Space Technology, National Space Policy, Space Consortium, 
Government and Industry, International Cooperation, Space Consortium</I><P>
<PRE><B>
Content:</B>

1.  Executive Summary
2.  What, Where, When and Why
3.  Kaminski Perspective
4.  The Speakers
5.  Perceptions
</PRE>


<B>Executive Summary</B><P>

The First Annual Space Technology Consortium Symposium convened in Crystal 
City, Virginia on 14 May 1996, with opening remarks by VADM William Ramsey, 
USN RET.  The theme of the symposium was to formulate a national and 
domestic approach to space through smarter make or buy decisions and new 
alliances. It was a Navy organized effort, but all the alphabet soup of 
space was represented;  DOD, Services, NASA, BMDO, DARPA, NRO, NOAA, even 
the White House and Congress, played their part in the activities.  The 
theme was governmental / industry partnerships, teaming, interagency 
cooperation, off-the-shelf acquisition and international collaboration. 
 Budgets drove the participants and will continue to be the driving force in 
space development for the foreseeable future.  What these spacemen want is 
cheaper cost to orbit, more bandwidth and ways to leverage shrinking budgets 
while faced with escalating costs.  There may be a lot of shotgun marriages 
in this group, but everyone is saying their vows and singing from the same 
song book for now.  Space has become too expensive for any single agency, or 
even any single nation, to go it alone.<P>

<B>What, Where, When and Why</B><P>

The Space Technology Symposium, 14-16 May 1996, was organized by the Office 
of Naval Research through private conference support.  Captain Patrick 
O'connell, Secretary of the Navy Space Science and Technology Council and 
Head of the Office of Naval Research Special Programs Department, put 
together a comprehensive conference.  The Speaker roster and attendees 
comprised a 'who's who' listing of national space.  It was a Navy show; 
 consequently there were more Navy stars in the sky than one normally sees 
when looking into space, but it was by no means limited to Navy interests. 
 All the players were represented, including not only Defense and the 
Services, but BMDO, NOAA, NASA, NRO, DARPA, the White House and Congress. 
 The Defense Under Secretary (space) and the National Space Architect, both 
new positions, were participating as speakers and panel moderators.<BR>
     The theme of the conference was Forging New Alliances for Space 
Technology and the program stayed on track.  Smarter make or buy decision 
provided an undercurrent for the conference goals and smarter make or buy 
decisions reduce to national teaming arrangements, government / industry 
partnerships, international collaborative programs and more off-the-shelf 
space hardware.  In a nut shell, those topics dominated the three day 
conference.  Each afternoon provided a panel discussion in the area of 
future technology thrusts, domestic partnerships and international 
cooperation.<BR>
     The Crystal Gateway Marriot was a delightful setting, the conference 
well orchestrated and the program incisively targeted to the theme.  Not 
only the speakers and panelists, but the 240 attendees, kept their minds 
fixed on the conference goals without letting the space techno-bable take 
over, as it often does in high technology conferences.  That will follow, of 
course, with a series of narrowly targeted workshops, invited and staffed 
from the conference attendee list.  The bottom line, and this conference was 
first and foremost concerned with the bottom line, is that conference goals 
were met.<P>

<B>Kaminski Perspective</B><P>

     Donald Stein from OSD International Programs Office spoke on the 
viewpoint of the Under Secretary of Defense ( acquisitions and technology), 
Paul Kaminski.  ---- There is a renaissance in arms cooperation throughout 
the free world.  Defense budgets are down, joint operations and coalition 
agreements up.  We need jointness and teamwork for inter-operability and to 
strengthen relationships, as well as to leverage technology and research 
dollars.  Defense initiatives contributing to the renaissance include 
acquisition reform, switching to ISO standards versus Mil Specs,  reforming 
the International MOU process, supporting more NATO Cooperative R & D, and 
buying off the shelf from our Allies.  An Armaments Cooperation Steering 
Committee has been established, as have International Cooperative 
Opportunity Groups (ICOGs) to guide joint endeavors with our Allies.  The 
ODC network is an essential input into this process and moving the ODCs from 
their position under the CinCs to Kraminski is a possibility.  All 
international cooperation is under Don Stein and he is the policy point, 
while implementation will fall under the military departments.<P>

<B>The Speakers</B><P>

          <I>Lionel Johns, Associate Director of the Executive Office of the
          President of the United States, Office of Science and Technology 
Policy.</I><P>

     The OSTP supports space development, in part, through the "Reinventing 
Government" approach that incorporates reliance between agencies, 
particularly DOD and NASA.  NASA has been restructured, NSA now shares data 
with EPA, and International cooperative projects are growing and critical to 
success.  Space development is too expensive to go it alone; we need 
industry / government teaming, more dual use projects and international 
collaboration. The United States enjoys 85 percent of the satellite and 
space communication systems but only 15 percent of the world's launch 
capabilities.  The OSTP estimates a 60 million USD annual savings from the 
DOD/ NASA reliance and upwards of 1.3 billion USD savings from 
standardization of satellite systems.  We and the world need cheaper access 
to space and we need a space transportation policy.<BR>
     Speaking of which, what about the Presidential Directive on National 
Space Policy?  Well, the process is difficult, differences between the 
Defense and Intelligence communities are extant and we are still digesting 
the changes of the post cold war environment.  Ummm, sounds just like last 
year.<P>

          <I>Robert Davis, Deputy Under Secretary of Defense, (space)</I><P>

     The office is new but Bob Davis is an old spaceman.  His new office is 
now up and operating.  A DOD initiative under DR Anita Jones, DDR&E, has 
done a great job of managing resources and building alliances across the 
Defense Agencies. Defense has several immediate goals in space that include 
enhanced spacecraft power, thermal management, data fusion, spacecraft 
structures and inertial guidance.  Continued collaboration with NASA is a 
must and critical to this nation's space program, especially in areas such 
as propulsion. Mr. Davis felt we were not bold enough in our propulsion 
industry and challenged the industry to march bravely into the future.  He 
felt this is the 'key' to space and one where the U S has only 30 percent of 
the world market.  The world has developed 28 new rocket engines in the last 
20 years and only one was ours.  He wants a Reusable Launch Vehicle (RLV) 
with a single stage to orbit and he wants the national propulsion industry 
to "quit resting on its laurels" and provide it.<P>

          <I>The Services -- Three and Four Star Flags from Army, Navy,
          Air Force, Marine Corps, BMDO</I><P>

     These warfighters want what most everyone else wants in space; cheaper 
access and more bandwidth.  All services consider space systems as not only 
desirable but required to win any major regional conflict.  The collective 
wish list spans the spectrum of space technology but C4I to the individual 
warfighter heads the list.  VADM Paul Reason (4 star select), when ask to 
prioritize the Navy's three main needs in space, replied, "bandwidth, 
bandwidth, bandwidth."  How bad is the problem?  Pretty bad.  The Navy is 
investigating the possibility of spooling fiber optic cables behind our 
ships!   All our warfighters agree that the cost of space is too high, that 
jointness is the key to bringing national costs down and that governments 
must continue R&D funding as industry will not, at least in the military 
arena.  Littoral warfare, shallow water and general ocean surveillance are, 
not surprisingly, high on the Marine Corps - Navy list.  Finally, the space 
development side of the house needs more explicit guidance from the CinCs, 
if the needed future space systems are to be available for acquisition next 
millennium.  Space costs too much, especially space transportation, but the 
good news is that space is the only area of the defense budget that is still 
increasing.<P>

          <I>Gill Klinger, Principal Deputy Under Secretary of Defense (space)</I><P>

     The warfighters care not a wit what happens at Phillips Lab or NRL. 
 Research has to develop the systems and sell them to the warfighters on 
their merits.  While the space budgets, both classified and unclassified, 
are holding their own, R & D is not.  Cryptology is a problem but that is a 
policy issue and must be solved within that purview.  Yes, systems built 
multilaterally cost more, but you get a system you can not afford to build 
yourself for a price you can.  We have a mandate from the highest levels of 
DOD to pursue international cooperation and, while we need a coherent policy 
for space based R & D, we know we need alliance development in the following 
six areas:  Communications, launch capabilities, propulsion Systems, 
environmental monitoring, early warning and Recon/surveillance. 
 International cooperation in space is not a cold war blip; there are 46 
countries engaged in space and 17 with launch capabilities.<P>

          <I>Congressman Bob Walker</I><P>

The Honorable Bob Walker, somewhat subdued from the Special Order days of 
railing at the empty House along with his then minority friends Newt 
Gingrich and Vin Webber, can still capture an audience.  Congress thinks 
that industry is only contributing to the national space programs in the 
communications arena and not doing enough outside.  Those of us inside 
government need to encourage commercial development of space, not fight it. 
 Congress expects results from our developing national space program and 
will not accept monuments again.  We need to balance and coordinate between 
agencies, stop the turf battles, stop punishing success, overcome 
bureaucracy and look at new innovation.  Do we need more symposia?  We know 
what we need; reduced cost to space.  Congressman Walker believes the joint 
space station to be the unique lab in human history.  He envisions an 
industrial park with clusters of commercial 'free flyers,' tethered through 
an umbilical to the lab for power and services, but on an industrial frolic 
of their own.  He also believes small satellites are the way to reduce costs 
in the near future,  then noted that NASA 'Mission to Planet Earth' was 
fighting the concept.  In a spirited outburst reminiscent of the old 'Mad 
Dog' Walker, he scolded the Defense Department for starting the tech demo on 
a Reusable Launch Vehicle, then abandoning it to NASA.  In like spirit, Bob 
quoted a famous Pennsylvanian, Mario Andrettti, "If you are in control, you 
aren't going fast enough!"<P>
     
<B>Perceptions</B><P>

     From a layman's point of view it was one of the better conferences.  It 
was represented by most all of the bright stars within our national space 
program and everyone was in the same room singing from the same song book. 
 Even the services and space surveillance were talking of joint projects, 
teaming and interagency cooperation.  Do not misunderstand me.  These people 
are not suddenly struck with an urge to share their hard fought for turf, 
but are driven by decreasing budgets and the ever increasing cost of space 
systems and transportation.  If there were any peacemakers here, it was the 
comptrollers.  Leveraging budgets, sharing R & D, buying off the shelf, 
collaboration and partnerships are all driven by the preclusive cost of 
space.  These pundits were not the dreamers of yester year but the engineers 
and managers that use space for a purpose.  It may be warfighting, 
environmental, communications or space industry, but it is not man's search 
for knowledge and a new frontier for this group.<BR>
     I can not help lamenting the lack of the Mott's and von Brauns of 30 
years ago.  There were no dreamers of man's expansion into the universe and 
interplanetary exploration at this conference.  When manned space flight was 
mentioned it was with derision for the high risk and costs.  Risk taking was 
to be avoided, which may be why we are left out of the world's space launch 
industry.  The maiden flight of the ESA Ariane 5 last week showed how risky 
heavy launch development is and will remain for some time.  We need cheaper 
cost to orbit but are working to get there by smaller payloads, 
miniaturization, standardization and partnership leverage, not bold 
innovation and new propulsion techniques.  No talk of planets or returning 
to the moon, these are engineers with a narrow purpose in space, and if the 
American people have lost interest in space it is because there is no fire 
in our bellies for knowledge and the conquest of the unknown by humankind. 
  Dollars, bandwidth, surveillance, imaging, technical data and commercial 
profit are all that is left of our glorious national space program.  Dr. 
Eilene Galloway, the Grand old Dame of Space, talked of serving on Senator 
Long's Armed Service Committee when sputnik was launched but only reminisced 
about the old glory.  Congressman Bob Walker was the only speaker that spoke 
from the gut and with vision, but even this may have been more habit, left 
over from his years in the minority, than actual enthusiasm.  We did have a 
futurist, Dr. Ken Cox, from Johnson Space Center, with the enviable topic of 
our third millennium in space.  He skipped the next 50 years!<P>

<P>
<HR><P> The opinions and assessments in this report are solely
those of the author and do not necessarily reflect ONREUR, Navy or U. S.
Government positions.
