<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsletter No. 6</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY><P>#005-1996<BR>  
<H3>July 30, 1996<BR>
 International Acquisition/ Procurement Seminar<BR>
 <A HREF="lewisj.htm">John Lewis</A></H3> 

<H3>An Office of Naval Research Newsletter-European Office -- Space<BR>
 Newsletter No 6<BR>  
8th Annual International Acquisition/Procurement Seminar
Notes from the International Defense Educational Arrangement (IDEA) Seminar<BR>
Royal Military College of Science, Shrivenham, Great Britain, 8 - 12 July 1996</H3>

<I>Key Words:  International Procurement, Acquisition, IDEA, Defense Procurement Education, Intellectual Property Rights</I><P>

Content:

<OL>
<LI>Executive Summary
<LI>What, Where, When and Why
<LI>Keynote
<LI>The Speakers
<LI>Perceptions
</OL>

<B>Executive Summary</B><P>

The 8th Annual International Acquisition/procurement Seminar was held at the Royal Military College of Science, Shrivenham, England, on 8 - 12 July 1996.  These Seminars are Sponsored by the Defense procurement education networks in the four IDEA nations, United States, United Kingdom, Germany and France.  The Keynote Speaker, Sir Robert Walmsley presented the procurement Strategy of the united Kingdom emphasizing the rapid and ongoing privatization and adherence of the UK to a 'Best Value for Money' strategy.  Transatlantic collaboration is considered and considered early, but the negotiations take too long and the money needs to be available sooner if joint projects are to continue.  A comparison was made by speakers from each of the IDEA nations of their respective procurement processes.  Mr. Bruce, Director, Armaments Cooperation, Atlantic - OSD, discussed the new streamlined procurement regulations of the US and emphasized our increasing reliance on international collaboration in filling our Defense procurement needs.  The participants indicated a belief that American policy in procurement was protectionist.  This was countered by Mr. Bruce, pointing out that the dollar amount of our procurement available for international competition was larger than that of any one of our Allies.  The importance of Intellectual Property Rights and the need to settle them in detail were stressed throughout the seminar, with IPR cited as the enemy of  joint projects.  There is a feeling that the US fails to address IPR fairly and adequately in our international negotiations.  The next seminar will be held in Mannheim, Germany, in July of 1997.<P>

<B>What, Where When and Why</B><P>

This conference is the eighth annual seminar sponsored by the International Defense Educational Arrangement (IDEA).  The IDEA group is comprised of directors from the Defense Systems Management College (DSMC), Fort Belvoir, Virginia, Royal Military College of Science (RMCS), Shrivenham, United Kingdom, The Federal Academy of Defence Administration & Technology (BAkWVT), Mannheim, Germany and the Centre d'Enseignement et de Formation d'Arcueil (CEFA), Paris.  Each year the IDEA seminar is hosted by a different national principal with this 1996 seminar at the RMCS, Shrivenham, United Kingdom.  The program was held 8 - 12 July 1996 and attended by over 80 participants from 10 nations plus the US Office of  Defense Cooperation (ODC) officers from Belgium and Italy.<BR>
 The theme of the conference was comparative defense procurement processes and timetables.  Each of the principal nations presented approximately two hours, detailing the cradle to grave procurement process in their respective nations. The presentations gave special attention to the approval and decision makers, the time tables for the different steps, the overall procurement philosophy and stressed the national policy on international collaborative programs and transnational off-the- shelf procurement.  Shrinking defense budgets have forced a change in procurement strategies on both sides of the Atlantic. Industry partnerships, international collaborative programs and off-the-shelf  hardware are now considered earlier in the procurement process of all participating nations.  In a nut shell, international collaboration dominated the first four days of the five day conference.  The final morning centered on comparative defense procurement and acquisition training in the IDEA countries.<BR>
 The Royal Military College of Science in Shrivenham was a delightful setting, the program well orchestrated and our British hosts gracious and attentive.  The Juxtaposition of the several national procurement strategies painted a picture remarkably similar in form and process but strikingly different in nuance.  Attendees gained an insight in the different expectations that collaborative partners bring to the table in a joint enterprise and discussions were frank and vigorous.  The discussion secessions and lectures were interspersed with tours of the RMCS tank and gun museums and a familiarity brief and participation exercise in the Distributive Simulation Laboratory.    Not only the speakers but the 80 plus attendees kept their minds fixed on procurement processes and education.  The consensus was that this seminar was a must for large, international program managers, ODC officers, and acquisition specialists involved with international procurement. As is often the case, the interchange between the various participants and their organizational affiliations in the several countries was as valuable as the formal seminar topics.<P>

<B>Keynote</B><P>

Sir Robert Walmsley KCB, British Chief of Defence Procurement, presented the defense procurement strategy for the United Kingdom in a keynote address.  It was a measured, diplomatic presentation, which mostly reiterated the policy and position long held by our maternal ally.  There were no surprises and privatization continues, 'best value for money' remains the priority and international cooperation, both transatlantic, and across European borders, is considered early and honestly in forming the procurement strategy.  While the defense budget is shrinking and under stress, Sir Walmsley is hopeful that the procurement money will increase in the coming budget cycle.  Collaboration across the Atlantic is considered early, but the agreement negotiations must move more quickly and money must be available in a timely fashion.  Pan-European rationalization is imperative too, and industry must take the initiative, as sovereignty issues and protectionism are still extant. Competitive procurement is the rule.  Off-the-shelf equipment, both at home and abroad, is always considered and even the strategy of choice in these trying budget times. A caveat is appropriate in this regard, however, in that, if a bid is to be successful, the bidder must 'make something' and not be just an integrator.<P>

<B>Speakers</B><BR> 

<B>The Four Principals:</B><P>

The four Principal IDEA Countries gave national presentations that concentrated on the procurement strategies and acquisition processes of their respective Defense Procurement Agencies.  The Juxtaposition of the four systems left the participants of the seminar with a somewhat erroneous impression of similarity.  While the overall process block diagram produced remarkably compatible slides with decision and approval steps and a somewhat synchronized timing, the differences came in the details.   Configuration control shows up for critical parts (although not always by this name)and destruction and disposal are costed from the start, across the board.  Germany and the US consider an international collaborative strategy somewhat earlier in the process than the UK, and the word international did not appear in the French presentation until the 41st slide.  The point where the requirement is frozen varied amongst the participants.  The point where the money was irretrievably committed also varied, with the US always subject to congressional appropriation.  This presents a risk to our allies in collaborating with the US and is considered in the decision making process of whether or not to go international with a joint development project.  A point by point comparison of the IDEA country's defense procurement processes will be the subject of a future newsletter when seminar proceedings are distributed.<P>

<B>US procurement update:</B><P>

Mr. Bruce, Director, Armaments Cooperation, Atlantic, OSD, presented the changes in US procurement regulations and strategy.  The new 5000.1 series acquisition regulations have replaced about two feet of interrelated regulations with a coherent, concise regulation about a half inch thick.  The new regs require that any procurement plan first look at modifying an existing system, then buying off-the-shelf anywhere in the free world, then international collaboration.  Only if these options are not available do we turn to tri-service or single service development. We now think international from the on-set and our current Administration supports and encourages collaboration with our allies to a much larger degree than in our past.  The MOU process which was cumbersome, time consuming and fragmented amongst the services has been standardized by Defense adopting the International Agreement Generator developed by the Navy International Programs Office, with modifications.  The approval process is down from a year or more to 30 days.  The approval points within Defense, Commerce and the services have a 21 day limit and concurrence is assumed if the deadline is not met.  In response to the widespread criticism that our procurement policy is protectionist, Mr. Bruce pointed out that while we have the Buy American Act and a 'within borders' requirement for much of our procurement, any country with whom we have an armament agreement can ask for waivers.  Furthermore, the absolute value of our procurement that is open to international competition is vast and much larger than any other country's requirements allowing US competition.  He asked that we look at what is available and view the glass as half full rather than half empty.  He then pointed out that we have 190 cooperative R & D agreements with 18 countries, 730 DEA's and IEA's with 26 nations, and over 22 armament MOU's and 9 logistic MOUs.  We also have 90 science and technology exchanges with 12 of our allies and 50 co-production programs with 19 countries.  The NATO countries are central within this activity.  We are serious about working with our allies and the trend toward international collaboration will continue. Under Secretary of Defense (acquisitions and technology), Paul Kaminski is hopeful that the decreasing defense procurement budget has bottomed out and that this single area of our defense budget will rise in the next budget cycle.<P>

<B>Intellectual Property:</B><P>

Mr. Bill Cruickshank, Head of Intellectual Property Rights for UK MOD, spoke of the problems associated with Intellectual Property Rights (IPR) in international programs.  He knows.  Bill Cruickshank has had responsibilities for negotiating tech transfers in 15 plus collaborative programs over the last 16 years.  He has worked with some projects, such as the third generation anti-tank program since pre-feasibility in 1981 to the present production phase.  It is a continuity that we lack in the US and his consequent knowledge of international negotiations and associated intellectual property issues is enviable from a US perspective.  He knows more about US requirements and regulations at the negotiating table than the US delegation.  For example, we have no IP attorney assigned to the Navy International Programs Office charged with negotiating all Navy MOU's. There are no IP attorneys within the entire Defense Office of General Counsel and the undersigned is the only IP attorney from any of the Services assigned outside the continental United States.<BR>
 Mr. Cruickshank painted IPR as the enemy of collaborative programs and pointed out that the AMRAAM program collapsed because of IP.  Inadequate program IPR will place the program contractors in a monopoly position.  He finds the US rigid in both our contract and IPR rules, and often sees a US strategy of remaining silent on IPR rights at the MOU stage, thus leaving the program at constant risk.  In his view, you have to have the right people running the program and you have to have the money, but every other concern and deliverable of a collaborative program is intellectual property rights.  They must be thought out carefully and only what you actually need negotiated, otherwise the excess rights often bankrupt the program.<P>

<B>The Industrial View:</B><P>

The most interesting presentation at this seminar was a pragmatic critique of a joint production program between the UK and Italy for EH101 helicopters.  SR  Giacomo Saponaro is the business Director of E.H. Industries, the management company established to coordinate the joint venture between Agusta of Italy and GKN Westland Helicopters of the UK. He contrasted this program (successful so far) and the Concord (unsuccessful) with a conclusion that for a joint venture to succeed, the contractors must have wide latitude and ownership of the IPR, with governments only taking what they need.  The contractors must decide how the work is distributed with contractor competence the pole star.  The work share requirements should be simply a figure and the contractors free to obtain them with their own arrangements. Government oversight in the workshare arena should be only to quality and quantity.  If governments want best value for money they must be ready to compromise and allow the market place flexibility to meet the requirements in a way that also provides the industrial participants a malleable product to service their commercial markets.<P>

<B>Perceptions</B><P>

This was a very productive seminar from the point of the participants.  The value, as so often happens, was more from the interaction of the attendees than from the speaker's rostrum.  A large percentage of the participants are actually involved in international programs. The contacts are valuable and the interchange frank and of practical benefit to those in, or contemplating, collaborative development.  This is an annual event and many of the attendees have consequently established a long term relationship. A criticism of the seminar is that the proceedings are not distributed for months, leaving the attendees without the meat of the program to take home with them.  Many of the speakers did not even furnish biographies.  One either spent all his time trying to take notes and figure out the speaker and where he worked, or listened to the presentation.  The most valuable information was a step by step comparison of the procurement process of the IDEA nations.  These presentations were complex and replete with unfamiliar acronyms, making any meaningful comparison impossible without copies of the slides and presentations.  The next IDEA conference is in Mannheim, Germany.  Entry is without registration fee and those involved with international programs should consider attending.  Equivalent credit is given for the Multinational Program Management Course (Defense Acquisition University course PMT #202) offered buy the Defense Systems Management College, Fort Belvoir, Virginia.<P>

<P>
<HR><P> The opinions and assessments in this report are solely
those of the author and do not necessarily reflect ONREUR, Navy or U. S.
Government positions.
<P> The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing
current information on science and technology development in European
countries. In order to better meet your needs, our Associate Directors
and Scientists are very much interested in knowing what are your
specific science and technology interests. Please let me know what they
are.
<P> Furthermore, if there are others, whom you are aware of, that
have interest in these newsletters please pass their e- mail address to
me and I will add them to the distribution list.
