<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsletter No. 7</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>#007-1996<BR>  
<H3>September 30, 1996<BR>
 Intellectual  Property and Business Activity in the Russian Federation<BR>
 <A HREF="lewisj.htm">John Lewis</A></H3> 

<H3>An Office of Naval Research Newsletter-European Office -- Space<BR>
 Newsletter No 7<BR> 
NATO Workshop on Intellectual Property and Influence on Business Activity 
Moscow, 9 - 11 September.<BR>
Notes and perceptions from the Moscow conference</H3>
 
<I>Key Words:  Moscow, Russian Federation Technology Transfer, Russian Business Policy, Intellectual Property Rights, NATO, Eurasian Patent Office, Rospatent</I><P>

Content:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Executive Summary
<LI>What, Where, When and Why
<LI>Keynote
<LI>The Speakers
<LI>Perceptions
</OL>

<B>Executive Summary</B><P>

The <B>NATO</B> Advanced Research Workshop on Intellectual Property: Influence on business Activity took place in <B>Moscow</B> from September 9-11, 1996.  This was the third annual workshop aimed at providing the Russian Federation Western ideas on how to expeditiously transfer state owned technology to the world market place.  The ten Western speakers and the breakout sessions discussed issues in three areas: firm strategy, finance and capital, and moving federal technology out of the state institutions into the market place.  The prescription in all three categories was the same; pass fair legislation in employee/employer relations concerning intellectual property, get a patent law on the books,  straighten out the banks (two thousand of the three thousand banks are bankrupt) and create a fair tax system so the entrepreneurs of the world can enter and do business.  A comprehensive court system and civil code needs to be put in place so that there is a means for dispute resolution.  Mous and Deas are needed, but first the Russians have to know what their national law and policy are, or they can not staff and sign the agreements.<BR>
	Most of the Western speakers had attended the first two workshops and they all spoke of the attitude change in the Russian participants.  There were still a few old school ideologues that advocated state ownership of technology, or at least state compensation for the technological base developed under the old Soviet institutions.  They were in the minority and mostly derided by their Russian colleagues.  From Vice Minister Yakobashvilli, Ministry of Science and Technology, to the Heads of Agencies, to the new science and technology incubators, all appreciated the ideas and workshop, and  all seemed determined to make the changes necessary to enter the free market and global market place.  They ask our forbearance and for us to understand the Russian difference, and to appreciate why it was taking a long time.  They do think differently and have a different history and culture.  It is my opinion that we made some mistakes in rushing in and buying research at fire sale prices.  What we needed then and need now, is truly collaborative undertakings.  <P>

<B>What, Where, When and Why</B><P>
	
This conference was the third annual  Advanced Research Workshop sponsored by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.  These workshops are sponsored by <B>NATO</B> to contribute to the critical assessment of existing knowledge on new important topics, to identify directions for future research, and to promote close working relations between scientists from different countries and with different professional experience.  This particular workshop was to assist Russia in transferring state owned technology to the market place and developing the infrastructure necessary to sell on the global market.  The workshop was sponsored by Dr. Alain Jubier, Program Director of <B>NATO</B>s Scientific Affairs Division.  The workshop was co-directed by Dr. Willem van Oort of the Netherlands, the managing Director of Lincentec, a technology licensing brokerage consultancy and Mr. Yevgeny Buriak of the  Russian Federation, Vice President of the Russian Association of Patent Specialists. There were ten Western speakers from six <B>NATO</B> nations, Finland, Czech republic and the Republic of Korea. Six formal speakers from Russia  were scheduled but scores of additional Russian participants stepped to the table to speak.  <BR>
A particularly useful part of the workshop was small group breakout sessions where specific topics were vigorously debated.  The subject matter was roughly trifurcated into Business firm strategy, finance and capital, and state support.  I found it interesting that the consensus on how to move forward in all three of these areas reduced to the same prescription.  Russia needs to establish a safe and secure infrastructure in legislation, financial institutes and banking, and the courts.  It was obvious that the economic playing field, that we from the West take for granted, does not yet exist in Russia nor in the thinking of most Russians.  There was still some ideological posturing, mostly from the old guys, but it was clear that the hearts and minds of these participants overwhelmingly were determined to enter into the  global marketplace and compete with the Western nations with their technology.  It will not be easy nor quick, the Russians are truly different in their thinking and grow from a different history and culture.  They need help from the West, and at least this group is ready to accept it.<BR>
	Except for the small group of Western speakers, this was an all Russian conference.  These were not the scientists but the bureaucrats.  The speakers and participants represented the Ministry of Science, Ministry of Nuclear Energy, Minister of Justice, Heads of various state committees and the <B>Eurasian Patent Office</B>.  The participants represented nearly every state agency and committee involved with science and technology including the State Duma.  These are the boys that can and must make it happen if Russia is to take its rightful place in the worlds science and technology marketplace.  The Western speakers, many who attended the first two workshops, were optimistic with the progress and changing attitudes of their Russian colleagues.  <BR>
	The workshop was held in the Headquarters for the Coordination of Military Collaboration of the CIS Countries in <B>Moscow</B>. This was the former <B>Moscow</B> headquarters of the WARSAW PACT, roughly the parallel of our SHAPE Headquarters. It was an august conference chamber replete with the ghosts of old Soviet Communist Party Secretaries and Generals.  This is a military complex located on the main road to <B>Moscow</B> center from the airport.  Security was high and military guards checked your passports coming in the gates, getting into the building, moving from one floor to another and in the hallways.  The building was spacious and glorious in its heyday, but that was before.  Now it was mostly deserted except for our conference and the western speakers that stayed there.  There was a three star in residence as the Commandant and the building was quickly showing the signs of disuse.  My room was a three room suite, replete with china and silver with two large crystal chandeliers and a desk about a mile wide.  There were message ports through the walls, wall safes and message repositories, all with combination locks.  One could almost feel the presence of the old soviet brass that no doubt spent their time thinking about us as we did about them.  But that was the old days.  Now the room is poorly kept, and the toilet paper reminiscent of corrugated aluminum. Light bulbs are missing without enough light to read and it is impossible to make an international call on the phone system.  It was a fitting setting to contemplate the changes needed to propel Russia and her technology into the world market in the 21st century.   <P>

<B>Keynote</B><P>

<I>Mr. Zurab A. Yakobashvilli</I>, Vice Minister of the Russian Federation Ministry of Science and Technology policy gave the keynote opening address.  He was appreciative of the workshop and noted that there were many positive indicators that Russia was moving forward toward a market economy.  He asked those of us from the west to be understanding of the Russian difference and to be sensitive to the difficulties his nation was experiencing throughout the agencies as Russia makes the transition.  He pointed out the progress being made in legislation including Russias new draft patent statute asking us not to be too critical in that it wasnt perfect but the best political compromise they could do at the present time.  Other legislation is in process including a State Secrets Act, employer-employee civil code concerning intellectual property and intellectual property dispute resolution.  He felt as we did, that progress was slow, but moving in the right direction.  Vice Minister Yakobashvilli (its still unofficial, but hes apparently in for a big promotion) was more pro-West in this presentation than his former speeches and writings would indicate.  (still unofficial, but in for a big promotion) He complimented everyone for the efforts leading up to the Gore/Chernomyrdin agreement on intellectual property and pointed out that the chairman and two members of the Chernomyrdin intellectual property committee, staffing the agreement, were participating in the workshop.  It was not just a quick speech and run, as he seemed genuinely interested in the workshop, talked to us during the breaks, and returned to the workshop and participated intermittently over the next three days.       <P>

<B>Speakers</B><P>

One of the main themes of this workshop was that in order to move technology from the state owned institutions into the global marketplace, it is necessary to form and use private firms to raise venture capital and market the technology.  Several of us spoke on this point and I discussed the experiences of our own government, the Stevenson Wilder Technology Transfer Act, the motivating force of this act in providing an incentive to inventors and laboratories to protect and market their inventions, and the important role private technology marketing firms play in this process.  An abstract of some of the other presentations follows. <P>

<I>Vladimir Smirnov</I>, Head of Analysis and Law Department, Ministry of Nuclear Energy, entitled his talk "The allocation of rights for the industrial property objects, developed in the course of works, implemented at the expense of the state budget."  The essence of this unwieldy title was that the West, read United States, were gaining unearned benefits in the Russian Federation by unequal dealings with their research and development community.  He cited 190 research contracts between CIS research institutions under a US DOE program with the title of NIS-IPP, 60 contracts with US DOE  laboratories and other CIS institutions, 450-500 bilateral or multilateral contracts under International Scientific and Technical Collaboration program (ISTC), and a few commercial contracts with companies such as Proctor and Gamble, as exploitative.  Mr. Smirnov cited the Bayh-Dole Act, the Stevenson Wilder Technology Transfer Act, and the US code on collaboration in the field of research and development, as US instruments for forcing these unequal agreements.  Apparently  the head of DOE, Mrs. Hazel OLeary, announced a temporary two year waiver under a government to government agreement (Gore/Chernomyrdin) with enforcing these agreements with respect to the transfer of <B>Intellectual Property Rights</B>,  in order to work out new, and fair terms.  A further change is needed, in Mr. Smirnovs opinion, and that is for DOE to also give up the contract rights to a US license of the technology to practice the inventions for governmental purposes throughout the world, and March-in-Rights.  (This is the contract right to patent technology developed under a contract, if the inventing party fails or refuses to do so.) <BR>
	So what is going on here?  The first question I received from Mr. Smirnov was, "Why does the U S believe that they do not have to pay for background intellectual property in collaborative agreements?".  I fumbled a bit and replied that I am sure that we did not take that position.  He replied that US DOE did.   We were speaking through translators and it took most of the conference to figure out what engendered the bitterness.  Mr. Smirnov believed that the technology developed by the old Soviet State Institutions had great residual value.  When he referred to "background IP" he meant the technical know how and experience of the scientist and engineers, not existing patents, copyrights, etc. that we think of as IP.  We only use the term background referring to technical data, not protected IP.   Furthermore, when he styled the agreements cooperative, he was actually referring to contracts.  He, and others, accused the West (USA) of entering Russia amid the turmoil of social/political change, picking and choosing the plumbs of soviet science, and buying them at fire sale prices.  It was a hard charge to answer for that is what we did.  The DOE agreements were standard Federal Acquisition Regulation contracts (FAR) where we paid certain scientists , usually for a low hourly wage, to conduct R & D.  We took the results of the research as a deliverable under the contract and, in standard FAR terms, owned the rights to subject inventions.  (A subject invention is any invention first conceived or first reduced to practice under a contract.)  We went to the best scientists working in cutting edge research because that is what we needed to augment our own development.  In one of these contracts the scientist designed and built a prototype switch, we claimed rights to the invention in accordance with the contract, and the Ministry of Science stopped performance and refused to relinquish rights to the switch.  Their position is that the knowledge and experience of the researcher acquired before the contract actually resulted in the invention and he only turned it into a device under the contract, not invented it thereunder.  Another contract term that caused heartburn was the FAR provision that allowed a grant of an exclusive license to the contractor for certain subject inventions where we took title, but then kept a US government nonexclusive license to make and use the invention for government purposes throughout the world.  Mr. Smirnovs position was that an exclusive license meant just that, exclusive, and only the licensee could make and use the invention. <BR>
	Although Smirnov represents the old guard and his views are in general disparaged by his colleagues, and he is way off base in western terms, there are some lessons here for us.  These simple contract terms which we all know and love, and have, since we were knee high to a patent attorney, are new and confusing to our Russian colleagues.  We no longer question such terminology since it has been through the courts, accepted, and used for years.  In my opinion, it is a shame that we went after Russian technology with contracts rather than equitable collaborative development agreements, as we have poisoned the well.  We know all that stuffread the contractcaveat emptora deal is a deal, and so forth, but our Russian colleagues do not.  The free market is new and strange to them and it is inevitable that as they learn the street smarts necessary to play this new game, they will both get burned and have a tendency to blame the West for the burning.   We missed a chance to garner their good will and it will take a long time undoing.  Ever wonder why the Gore/Chernomyrdin Agreement on Intellectual Property took so long in coming and then seemed to say nothing?  Mr. Smirnov was the chairman of the Chernomyrdin staff that negotiated the agreement!<P>

<I>Evgeny Buryak</I>, Vice President of Russian Association of Patent Experts, spoke on the Russian Patent office (<B>Rospatent</B>), and the draft patent law that is now before the State Duma.  Mr. Buryak felt that the progress was too slow but that the draft legislation presented a pretty good first effort at a workable patent statute comparable with world wide standards.  The essence of his speech was that there was much pain in getting the consensus necessary to draft legislation that could pass all the agencies necessary to submit legislation and then get it signed into law. The Duma passed legislation for a state secrets law only to have it returned unsigned.  Part of the new patent statute controls how technology impacting national security is protected from publication and one legislative effort is forced to wait on the other.   I will publish a separate newsletter on the draft patent legislation in the near future.<P>

<I>Victor Blinnikov</I>, President of the <B>Eurasian Patent Office</B>, spoke of the historical changes resulting from the USSR <B>Rospatent</B>s termination of functions and authority in the former republics.  The Eurasian Patent Convention arose to fill the vacuum. The idea of establishing a sole patent system was agreed upon by six states in 1991 and the principles for establishment approved by nine states in 1993.  The interstate Bureau for the Protection of Industrial Property was created and was the organizing body for the Eurasian Patent Convention.  This convention was signed into existence officially by 11 states in 1994 and entered into effect in August of 1995.  It is now open to any state that is a member of the UN and bound by the Paris Convention and the Patent Cooperation Treaty (PCT). The convention has set up the Eurasian Patent Organization which includes the <B>Eurasian Patent Office</B> (EAPO) and an Administrative Council.  The EAPO performs all Administrative functions and is now recruiting qualified personnel.  This is a tough job in that personnel requirements include relevant educational backgrounds, practical experience in industrial property, organizational abilities, and fluency in Russian, the official language.<BR>
	Eurasian patent Attorneys must meet two mandatory requirements.  They must have the right to be a representative before the national Patent Office of the member state in accordance with national legislation, and be registered by the EAPO as a patent attorney.  Entry is controlled by a registration procedure which includes a proficiency examination.  There is a grandfather provision that waives the exam for those registered before December 31, 1996.  More than a hundred Attorneys have registered under these grandfather provisions so far.  <BR>
	Filing of an EAPO application saves time and money.  A single filing (in Russian) gives coverage in all member states and costs less than filing in each.  There are procedures for a speedy examination but at considerable extra cost.  An EAPO application proceeds in two phases, the first part is an examination for completeness and formalities, publication and search, with the payment of fees.  Then the examination for patentability and the grant of a patent, again for the payment of fees.  Rule forty provides for a reduction of fees for low income member countries of about 80 percent.  Opposition procedures are available within short timelines. There is a provision for converting an EAPO application to a national application and preserving the original filing date should the EAPO application fail.  In general, the EAPO procedures are pari passu with those of most of the worlds statutes.  In my opinion, like the national patent for the Russian Federation, the fees are too high to be competitive on the world stage, but for a first effort, not bad.  <P>
   
<I>Edouard Bourgeois</I>, Head of International Affairs for ANVAR, the French Agency for technology  and innovation of small to medium sized enterprises(SME) spoke on the French program of subsidizing the transfer of technology to the market place.  His agency takes a demand pull rather than a technology push approach.  The SMEs propose their own projects and the technology is developed under a systemic development plan.  The old paradigm of a lineal process of research to invention to industry has been replaced with an integrated networking that has a product in mind throughout the process.  Product development is complex and technology without a product is worthless to the marketplace.  The SMEs supported by ANVAR receive up to 50 percent total funding with an interest free loan that only has to be repaid if the project is a success.  The Agency stays involved throughout the project, and both influences and monitors the methods of management and human resources.  An ANVAR study encourages SMEs to recruit an academic or Ph.D. with 5 to 8 years experience in higher education to act as the R & D executive and be in charge of the innovative program, at least partially.  ANVAR is the most important actor for the promotion of innovation in French SMEs, but results are hard to measure as ANVAR is supported under the French National Budget and has no result oriented accountability.<P>

<I>Mr. Gijsbert Boot</I>, General manager of a private, joint Czech Western Venture Capital Fund, Regionalni Prdnikatelsky Fond (RFP), discussed the formation of his business and experiences in the Czech Republic.  The RFP was founded in June 1994 by the Foundation for Regional Development, a cooperation between the EU and the Czech government, with the objective of introducing venture capital to stimulate the development of SMEs.  The philosophy is that for SMEs to survive, an entrepreneurial culture and venture capital must exist. RPF provides the former and, first the EU and then investment banks (ING Bank/Baring) the latter. The company is located in a Czech industrial center, not the capital, to keep a hands-on approach.  There is no shortage of proposals with RPF receiving 364 in its first two years of existence.  Only 3 percent (eleven) of the proposals have been funded (5 million ECU or 4 million USD)and one has failed.  The selection criteria is laborious and the due diligence process long and man hour intensive.  A 25 to 50 percent target rate of return is sought and RPF takes an actual stake in the business and a role in the management.    The fledgling company is succeeding.  RPF started as an EU project but is now privatizing and increasing its investment capital from 10 to 50 million ECU.  They are now expanding to other Czech industrial centers.  Sounds good but how do you get out?  Well, we do not yet know, the firm holds investments for 5 to 7 years and the company is either sold to a strategic partner or listing on the Czech stock exchange.  We will see.<P>

	<I>Jan Lettinga</I>, Member of the Executive Board of Delft Instruments, The Netherlands, spoke of conversions from military to civil business.  His theme was again that any technology transfer policy must be product driven.  If supply and demand in a given market are in balance, then there is no demand for an increase in the supply .  The technology in the state and military institutions are just such an increase in supply.  Research and development must be product driven to have value. A successful transfer of military technology must come from market pull which requires thorough knowledge of markets and applications, which a military business does not have.  To convert a military business to a civil business is long and must be done in steps.  You can not take the existing organization and convert it with fiat,  because you bring the old attitudes and prejudices with the transfer.  The only successful way is to absorb the military organization into an existing civil firm by moving only a few of the state employees into the civil organization, with at least a 20 to one workforce ratio, until they are trained. (I think the actual word is reprogrammed)  Once they have learned product driven production, value engineering and the know how associated with a product creation process based on small margins in price/performance ratio, another transfer of personnel can begin.  It is a long and risky business.<P>

<I>Dr. Hans Claes</I> with the Catholic University, Louvain, Belgium, spoke on the University - Industry relationship.  Universities, mostly due to financial concerns, are increasingly induced to collaborate with industry.  The highly competitive technological environment stimulates industry to be interested in the technological and scientific possibilities the universities can offer.  Principal concerns regarding the relationship between the universities and industry, such as the independence of the university, academic values, conflicts of interest and commitment, can all be resolved through university policies.  The Katholieke Universiteit Leuven has set up an organization within the university, Leuven Research and Development, which is responsible for organizing this relationship.  Leuven R & D is an autonomous, service oriented and financially independent organization.  Its Board of Directors is composed of the vice presidents of the university and members of industry users.  The philosophy of Leuven R & D is determined by the choice of high quality research projects, a full disclosure policy and an impartial attitude.  The objectives of this organization include establishing a technology brokerage system, pursuing an active patent policy and the establishment of new companies through a transfer of university technology.  Initial results show results and are encouraging.  <P>

<I>The Russian Participants</I>, about fifty, from a multitude of agencies, ministries and new technology Transfer organizations, spoke mostly on Russian progress in legislation, philosophy and the special nature of Russia.  A common theme was that, as Russians, they are different.  They have a different history and they think differently.  The constantly changing map in that part of the world is driven by 170 separate nations and ethnic groups, gathered by the czars and held together, of late, by the communists.  The people, at first Surfs then Kulaks, are now broke and out of work.  The people lost all they had when the ruble floated to equilibrium, and a large portion of the Russian people, including the military, have not been paid for months.  Surprisingly, at least for this group of workshop attendees, the ideological battles are mostly over.  They like their new freedoms and want to compete on world markets.  Yes, there were still a few of the old school, such as Mr. Smirnov, <I>supra</I>, that thought the infrastructure of the old Soviet regime was just fine and that nothing needed to be done with the courts or civil codes.  He had a minority of support from the participants, and it was obvious that most of the attendees were trying to solve the problems that would open Russia to the West and world markets.  The speakers noted that of the three thousand banks in the Russian Federation, two thousand were bankrupt.  This is a problem that is being swept under the rug, but they are aware.  Not only is it a risk of solvency to bank money, but it creates a record and the tax man cometh. And boy does he come.  New taxes come from every direction, and every agency takes a bite, until there is nothing left.  The small company that arranged the conference for <B>NATO</B> refused to put any money in a bank and dealt with cash.  Dollars of course, and they were hit from every direction until they were forced to approach <B>NATO</B> with a plea for more money to continue.  The Russians know this and talked more about this problem than the Western speakers. Two years ago the funds for the conference came in stashed in a couriers shoe.  <BR>
The Russians appreciated our help, acknowledged their problems and asked our forbearance while they sort out the new country.  They want truly collaborative agreements with the West, not just hourly contracts.  They also realize that we need Data Exchange Agreements and Memoranda of Understanding, but must work out their national policy and legislation before they can be staffed and signed.  The breakout sessions were vigorous, spirited and frank.  There are two competing models of how Russian technology should be held: The Belarus model, which advocates ownership and complete control of the technology by the state, and what they call the American model, which is the state subsidizing the transfer of the technology to private industry and then getting out of the way.  They know the first will not work and they lack funds to do the second.  We were sympathetic and pointed out that the Western countries have the same problem, in that technology languishes in the federal labs.  We suggested, and they agreed, that the creators of the technology must have a stake in the fruits of their labor and that the developing labs and institutions must also.  It is the free market that moves  the technology, turns it into products, and markets it.  The state, theirs or ours, has never been successful in this arena.     <P>


<B>Perceptions</B><BR>

This was a productive conference.  Generally both sides felt that Russia was moving towards the right goal post but that it was very difficult given the social/political turmoil in the Russian Federation.  Perhaps we have tried to move too fast.  The first steps must be to create the infrastructure necessary for the world to conduct business there.  Legislation is needed and a court system established for dispute resolution.  Entrepreneurship is hindered by unjust fees and taxes.  The country still moves on grease and it is driving up the costs, until few of the new small businesses can survive.  But the good news is that most of the socialist/ communist ideologues have faded from view.  The Western participants that attended this conference in the past all report a sea change in philosophy of the bureaucrats towards determination to create a free market.  Yes, just attending this conference is a filter, but its bandwidth is increasing.  We take a lot for granted about markets that they dont yet understand.  It was hard to convince them that for any Russian product to sell on the world stage, it must benchmark against what is available and either provide something new or better or something existing that is cheaper.  This is a problem for Russian goods as they have not had to meet these standards before.  One of the thorns stuck in the foot of the Ministry of Science was that a private deal between Proctor and Gambol and a Russian firm, listed ten million dollars in Intellectual property as assets they were bringing to Russia.  They had no patents or copyrights and the Russians could not grasp the fact that the Trade Name, Proctor and Gamble, had value, as did the company good will.  <P><HR><P>     

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the   
author and do not necessarily reflect ONREUR, Navy or U. S. Government   
positions.<P>
