<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hydrodynamics & Acoustics Newsletter #1</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Newsletter 96-001<BR>                                           
23 April 1996<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/majumdar.htm">Dr Peter Majumdar</A>
<P>

Maritime Research Institute (MARIN), The Netherlands: An Update</H3>

<B>1. Summary</B><P>

On 19 March 1996 I visited the research facilities of MARIN, towards
an update on their current emphasis on research in ship hydrodynamics
and acoustics, their expansion into areas of related research, efforts in
international co-operative reseach, and their rather ambitious plan for a
nearly total replacement of their large test facilities to incorporate more
modern and sophisticated structure, equipment and techniques.  As a
private organization MARIN --until quite recently known as the Netherlands Ship Model Basin (NSMB)-- has traditionally enjoyed financial
support for upgrade as well as operational subsidy from the Ministry of
Transport and Shipping and the Netherlands Government in general.
Their Government has always placed a very high value on basic and
applied ship research and, therefore, the status of a national asset on
MARIN.<P>

In Surabaya, Indonesia, the new Indonesian Hydrodynamic Laboratory
was inaugurated by President Suharto in July 1995.  This laboratory,
which principally comprises a 235 x 11 x 5.5m towing tank and a
variable-depth maneuvering and offshore basin, was designed by MARIN
which also supervised its construction.  Facility calibration and on-site
personnel training are currently being conducted by MARIN.<P>

<B>2. Background</B><P>

To naval architects and those in ship hydrodynamics research, MARIN
has been particularly known for its Depressurized Towing Tank, known
more commonly to the related community as the "Vacu-Tank", a unique
facility since 1970 which enables the standard Froude-number-matched
ship model towing tests at the full-scale cavitation number.  To those in
the field of research and design of marine propellers, MARIN research
has been of historic significance: prior to the advent of computers making
possible the use of lifting-line and lifting-surface theories, the approach
to the design and analysis of propellers, since the 1940s, had been based
on the popularly known Wageningen B-Series Propellers, derived from
extensive research at MARIN (located near the quaint farming town of
Wageningen).<P>

MARIN was founded in 1929 in a joint effort by four Dutch shipowners and
the Government of the Netherlands.  Following the completion of its first
towing tank, research work began in 1932.  Today's facility comprises, in
addition, two cavitation tunnels, a seakeeping basin, a shallow-water basin,
a wave and current basin, a high-speed towing tank, and the depressurized
towing tank (the "Vacu-Tank").<P>

<B>3. Recent Upgrades and Expansion</B><P>

<B>(a)</B>. Following its recent emphasis on support of the industrial services and
nautical research and training MARIN has made substantial investments
in mathematical simulation programs and developed two significant training
simulators: the Vessel Traffic Services Simulator and the Ship Maneuvering
Simulator.<P>

<B>(b)</B>. Recent upgrades in Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) enable a
reliable analysis of mixed-flow phenomena, such as those involving a very
complex interaction of viscous hull-flow with hull-propulsor interactive flow
modification.<P>

<B>(c)</B>. Emphasis on offshore research and an increased interest on the
measurement and prediction of wind resistance of high-speed craft have
led to MARIN's development of their new Windforce Dynamometer which
measures wind forces and torques on a superstructure.  MARIN's recently-
developed techniques for single-point mooring as well as dynamic
positioning (actively controlled) are already in use by the offshore industry.<P>

<B>(d)</B>. A rather new addition to research and service areas is that of Trials and
Monitoring, for full-scale data acquisition and analysis in the disciplines of
hydrodynamics, structures, acoustics, vibration, and ship position-keeping.<P>

<B>(e)</B>. A very new Department of Automation, Intrumentation and Installations
has been created at MARIN, towards the development of software and
hardware in the areas of automatic control, modelling and simulation, and
robotics.  To a large extent this Department today acts in support of the
mainstream MARIN disciplines.<P>

<B>4. Facility Re-Design and Construction</B><P>

About two years ago MARIN presented to the Ministry of Shipping and
Transport a very ambitious plan to re-design and re-construct nearly all
of its facilities at a slightly different location.  This plan included even a
wholly new "Vacu-Tank" with very sophisticated acoustical features built
into it.  MARIN approached the Government requesting its support
as a bank-loan "guarantor".  It appears quite certain that the Ministry's
guarantee will come through very soon.<P>

<B>5. Co-operative Research</B><P>

MARIN formed, in 1969, the Co-operative Research Ships (CRS) Group,
a consortium of ship research sponsors for whom the selected research
would be conducted primarily by MARIN.  The current CRS membership
represents twelve countries, with the total number of sponsor members
being twenty-one.  Exxon and the American Bureau of Shipping have
been the only two sponsor members during the past twenty-seven years.
The CRS research topics are traditionally aimed at solving problems of
common concern among ship designers and ship owners.<P>

<B>6. MARIN Location and Point of Contact (POC)</B><P>

MARIN is located in the Ede/Wageningen area of the lower Dutch midlands.
Ede/Wageningen is about one hour away by train from the Schiphol Airport,
including a change at the Duivendrecht Station.<P>

Dr J Th Ligtelijn, Head of Ship Research Department and my friend and
colleague of twenty-one years, is always a very hospitable host.  Those of
the US Government willing to visit MARIN can contact me for a visit
arrangement.  I can be reached by phone on +44-171-514-4947;
by fax on +44-171-723-6359;  and by e-mail at PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil
Alternatively, one can contact Dr Ligtelijn by phone on +31-317-493 485;
or by e-mail at J.T.Ligtelijn@marin.nl<P>

<B>7. US Govt Disclaimer</B><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author
and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR
positions.<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm"
