<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hydrodynamics & Acoustics Newsletter #2</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Newsletter 96-002<BR>                                           
14 June 1996<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/majumdar.htm">Dr Peter Majumdar</A>
<P>

Marine Technology Directorate (MTD): A UK Consortium for Ship and Offshore Technology Research</H3>


<B>1. Key Words</B><P>

<I>Multi-Sponsor Research; Ship Dynamics; Ship and Offshore Technology;
Ship Acoustics; Composites.</I><P>


<B>2. Summary</B><P>

A research consortium aimed at the advancement of marine and offshore
technology, MTD is regarded in the related UK community as a prime
exemplar of a multi-sponsor research organisation.  Areas of research
are selected based on the requirements of government, the needs of
industry, and the capabilities of academic and applied researchers.
In the recent past the primary thrust of sponsored research by MTD
has been in support of the offshore oil and gas industry, with smaller
but significant support for ships and marine transportation.  Today,
however, the emphasis on ship research is increasing rapidly.  Process
is nearly complete today towards the incorporation of the US Office of
Naval Research (ONR) as the first foreign member of this consortium.<P>


<B>3. MTD Objectives</B><P>

In the broadest terms the objectives of MTD are  (a) to promote ship and
offshore technology advancement with a view to requirements and needs of
government and industry;  (b) to promote collaboration and discussion
among industry, government departments, and Higher Education Institutes;
(c) to support Higher Education Institutes in research in the areas of
strategic importance.<P>

Contribution to community education and training is an important function
of MTD:  it is entrusted with the approval --and introduction-- of courses
towards government Research Studentship for MSc and PhD candidates.  (The
award process for such Studentships is quite the same as that for ONR
postgraduate fellowships in the US.  In addition, however, based on the
needs of government and industry, the MTD can specify a topic of research
for which a studentship is granted.  The uniqueness of this arrangement is
that MTD does not provide the grant itself: it instead acts as the
recommending authority for the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research
Council, which provides the grant.) <P>


<B>4. MTD Structure</B><P>

Responsibility of the formal management of research programs is with
Marinetech South Limited, a Southampton based organisation formed solely
for this function.<P>

In reality, the financial support for the MTD research programs comes
largely from the UK taxpayers, as much of the funding (between 70 and 80
percent) is provided by the UK Government's Engineering and Physical
Sciences Research Council (EPSRC).  The remainder of the required funding
comes from the industry and other UK Government agencies (e.g., Ministry
of Defence --another source of taxpayer support).<P>


<B>5. Research Technology Centers</B><P>

A number of Technology Centers are distributed throughout the UK, on the
basis of technology and research expertise and activities.  A brief
description of these Centers is provided below:<P>

<I>(a) University of Southampton, Department of Ship Sciences.</I><P>

Together with the University's Institute of Sound and Vibration Research,
Departments of Mechanical, Electrical, and Electronics Engineering as well
as Aeronautics and Astronotics, this Technology Center has recently
completed projects on motions and hull-loading characteristics of catamarans
in waves;  shaft- and structure-borne noise induced by inverter-fed motors
on ships;  developments towards the reduction of shipboard piping vibration
and noise;  design studies of power electronic drive systems for thrusters;
and assessment of bahavior and damage tolerance levels of fibre-reinforced
polymer sandwich structures.<P>

<I>(b) University College London, Department of Mechanical Engineering.</I><P>

Research projects at this Center include the problem of variable-amplitude
corrosion fatigue of high strength steel;  studies on subsea umbilicals
suitable for deepwater environments;  nonlinear dynamics;  and advanced
sonar applications for the marine environment.<P>

<I>(c) Cranfield University, Department of Materials.</I><P>

Current activities at this Center include research on the use of high strength
steels in offshore engineering, their weldability, toughness, and corrosion
fatigue behavior;  and applied research on deepwater hyperbaric welding, for
which a new welding facility has recently been commissioned.<P>

<I>(d) University of Manchester School of Engineering.</I><P>

Newest member of the family of Centers, the Manchester School of Engineering
has successfully completed a research program on cost-effective offshore use
of fibre-reinforced composites.  Primarily towards the support of offshore
oil companies, this Center has recently launched a program on the design and
instrumentation for Process Separation Systems.<P>

<I>(e) University of Newcastle-Upon-Tyne, Department of Marine Technology.</I><P>

Together with the Electrical and Electronics Engineering Department and the
Mechanical, Materials and Manufacturing Department, this Center is currently
engaged in research on undersea acoustics;  deepwater umbilicals;  offshore
differential global positioning systems;  and on uncertainties in loads on
offshore structures.<P>

<I>(f) The Heriot-Watt University, Edinburgh, Institute of Offshore Engineering.</I><P>

Current topics of research at this Center include relevant and cost-effective
petrophysical methodologies for improved reservoir characterisation;
technologies for unmanned underwater vehicles (UUVs);  design of wave and
offshore basins from consideration of joint-probability-distribution extreme,
multi-directional wave loads;  sound transmission through offshore and marine
structures;  and effects of motion on topside separation process.<P>

<I>(g) The University of Glasgow, Department of Mechanical Engineering.</I><P>

Principal research emphasis at this Center has been in the areas of ship and
offshore hydrodynamics, structures, and materials:  development of design
and analysis tools for deepwater offshore platforms and high-speed advanced
marine vehicles;  maneuverability of ships in shallow waters;  RO-RO ferry
stability;  heavy-weather oil containment systems;  failure criteria in
high-strength steels for offshore use;  design guidelines for adhesively
bonded steel connections;  erosion and corrosion mechanisms in specialist
steels and alloys;  erosion performance of a range of polymer-glass
composites used for offshore pipes;  and underwater sensor materials.<P>

<I>(h) The University of Strathclyde, Dept of Ship and Marine Technology.</I><P>

Recently-completed projects at this Center include those in the areas of
underwater stereo vision systems;  sonar-based navigation systems for UUVs;
near-surface hydrodynamics of UUVs;  and snatch-loading characteristics of
cables during the launch and recovery of tethered subsea units.<P>


<I>6. Benefits of the MTD Consortium Membership</I><P>

Benefits of the above examples of research are quite obvious to the ships
and offshore community.  Given that about an 80-percent contribution of
the required funding is obtained from the UK taxpayers, by way of EPSRC,
the return of investment of a sponsoring member towards the remaining
twenty percent obviously is extremely high and, therefore, equally
attractive.  Process is nearly at a completion towards the introduction of
the US Office of Naval Research (ONR) as the first foreign member of MTD.<P>

<B>7. Further Details</B><P>

For further details on MTD and, in particular, towards possible participation
of a US Government agency by way of ONR membership, one can contact<P>

Dr Peter Majumdar<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5TH, UK<P>

Telephone: +44-171-514-4947<BR>
Fax:       +44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-Mail:    PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil<P>

Alternatively, for general information one can contact<P>

Dr Jonathan Williams<BR>
Managing Director<BR>
Marinetech South Limited<BR>
Southampton SO14 3ZH, UK<P>

Telephone: +44-1703-59-6140<P><P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm"
>Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A> 
