<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hydrodynamics & Acoustics Newsletter #3</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Newsletter 96-003<BR>                                           
18 June 1996<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/majumdar.htm">Dr Peter Majumdar</A>
<P>

Krylov Shipbuilding Research Institute, St Petersburg, Russia: An Update</H3>


<B>1. Key Words</B><P>

<I>Ship Research in Russia; Propulsor Research; Waterjet Propulsors;
Ship Resistance; Wings-in-Ground Craft.</I><P>


<B>2. Summary</B><P>

Present newsletter provides an update on the home of Russian ship
research, the Krylov Shipbuilding Research Institute (KSRI), based on
my visit of its facilities on 14 and 15 May, 1996.  The most notable
of my observations has been KSRI's rapid adaptation to the context of
world shipping and shipbuilding: Indeed, according to my colleagues
in KSRI's largest department, the Department of Hydrodynamics, about
ninety-five percent of their current research is under the sponsorship
of commercial shipping and offshore companies of western Europe.  The
Department of Acoustics, which commands about the same status for its
excellence, has however remained focussed largely on navy needs.<P>


<B>3. Background</B><P>

The Krylov Shipbuilding and Research Institute, which celebrated its
centenary two years ago, had been established in 1893 as a towing tank
facility for ship resistance and powering research--just as the US Navy's
Carderock Division of Naval Surface Warfare Center began as the Experimental
Model Basin (EMB) about the same time.  Much the same way as Carderock,
KSRI soon became a world leader in fundamental and applied research in
the fields of ship hydrodynamics, acoustics, structures, and related
systems.  During the 1940s this research center was named after Krylov,
a pioneer in mathematical formulation of ship wave resistance mechanisms.<P>

Today, research in ship and propulsor hydrodynamics still dominates the
activity at KSRI.  The facility in this area comprises a deep water towing
tank, a shallow water towing tank, a high-speed towing tank, a seakeeping
and maneuvering basin, a rotating-arm basin, five propulsor cavitation
tunnels, a cavitation basin, an ice model basin, a wind tunnel, and a
number of test units for pressure vessels.<P>


<B>4. Research Emphasis Today</B><P>

Discussions during my visit addressed KSRI's current emphasis, future 
interests, and research collaboration possibilities primarily in two
areas: hydrodynamics and acoustics.  Areas of interest are outlined in
the following.<P>

<B>4.1 Hydrodynamics</B><P>

Much of the current work as well as work planned for the immediate future
are of proprietary nature.  The following provides a description of KSRI's
major in-house efforts.<P>

<I>4.1.1 High Speed Marine Propulsors</I><P>

Propulsors requiring special features for dynamically-supported high speed
marine vehicles have in the recent years received special attention
throughout the world.  The principal challenge in the design of such a
propulsor is in attaining a high efficiency at low speeds.  KSRI's most
notable development in this area has been that of the Ventilated Waterjet
Propulsor.  The design-point efficiency of this propulsor has been shown
to be higher than that of a subcavitating propeller.  However, ventilated
waterjets do have a problem in providing a steady craft acceleration at
intermediate speeds, which can be corrected by means of an active system
modifying blade hydrodynamics instantaneously.  However, this problem can
also be alleviated through design modifications allowing the propulsor to
operate in different hydrodynamic regimes at different speeds.  There does
exist considerable interest among the KSRI scientists and management in a
US-Russian collaborative effort for further research on this concept.<P>

<I>4.1.2 Ship Resistance Reduction by Gas Cavities on Hull Surface</I><P>

This is a KSRI concept towards which considerable effort is expended today
both in theoretical research and in towing-tank measurements for empirical
parameters.  Conceptually, this approach applies and maintains a gas film
separating a large part of the ship bottom from hull boundary layer, thereby
eliminating the associated skin-friction drag.  First introduced more
than a century ago, implementation of this concept has so far not been
possible because of the instability of such a gas film.  Beginning
with a two-dimensional development of theory and its experimental
validation, KSRI has extended this concept to three-dimensional hull
forms and obtained rather promising preliminary model test results.  There
is no particular interest on the part of KSRI at this time to extend this
project into a collaborative effort.<P>

<I>4.1.3 Aerodynamics of Wings-in-Ground craft (WIGs)</I><P>

This project started as a study of near-ground performance of conventional
aircraft, leading to the development of new theories and experiment methods.
Because of the highly nonlinear relationship between ground clearance and
wing lift a measurably high transient gain in lift occurs at very small
heights (under 20 percent wing chord).  Towards craft operation at such
minute clearances  KSRI is currently developing new theories which, if
supported by experimental data, will lead to a wing design of substantial
departure from the conventional.<P>

<B>4.2 Acoustics</B><P>

Applied research in acoustics is quite entirely aimed at navy's requirements.
A description of the general areas of fundamental research is provided below.<P>

<I>4.2.1 Propulsor-Induced Hull Vibration and Acoustics</I><P>

The principal effort in this area appears to be in development of materials
for use as a frequency-tuned compliant stage of thrust bearing to absorb
the propulsor-transmitted fluctuating forces.<P>

<I>4.2.2 Localization of Noise Sources</I><P>

The emphasis is on further development of KSRI's capabilities in this area
thorugh modifications to their directional synthetic aperture antenna
approach, based on simultaneous two-point reception with perpendicular and
parallel bases.<P>


<B>5. Further Details</B><P>

For further details on some of the above projects at KSRI one can contact<P>

Dr P. Peter Majumdar<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5TH, UK<P>

Telephone: +44-171-514-4947<BR>
Fax:       +44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-Mail:    PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil<P>

For general information on KSRI as well as its specific projects one can
contact<P>

Dr Alexandre P. Pylaev<BR>
Deputy Director and Commercial Marketing Manager<BR>
Krylov Shipbuilding Research Institute<BR>
St Petersburg, Russia<P>

Telephone: +7-812-127-96-47<BR>
Fax:       +7-812-127-95-94<P>

Copies of this and other ONR Europe newsletters are obtainable from the
World-Wide Web by reaching<P>

http://www.ehis.navy.mil/<P>


<B>6. US Government Disclaimer</B><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author
and do not necessarily reflect the official US Government, US Navy, or
ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P><A HREF="onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A></BODY></HTML>




    

        
