<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hydrodynamics & Acoustics Newsletter #4</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Newsletter 96-004<BR>                                           
28 July 1996<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/majumdar.htm">Dr Peter Majumdar</A>
<P>

The Eighth International Conference on Laser Techniques in Fluid Mechanics</H3>

<B>1. Key Words</B><P>

<I>Laser-Doppler Anemometry;  Phase-Doppler Anemometry;
Particle Image Velocimetry;  Particle Tracking Velocimetry;
Turbulence Measurement;  Real-time Data Processing. </I> <P>


<B>2. Summary</B><P>

The Eighth International Conference on Laser Techniques in Fluid
Mechanics was held in Lisbon, Portugal, during 8-11 July 1996.
In part, this conference was jointly sponsored by the London-based
Office of Naval Research Europe, US Army Research and
Development Group, and the US Air Force Office of Research.
Hosted by the Department of Mechanical Engineering, University
of Lisbon, this conference is held every two years at the same
venue and it provides the related community with an update on
recent developments in the measurement techniques for unsteady
turbulent fluid flow and related energy transfer.  Non-intrusive means
of measurement such as those discussed in this conference are
essential for many cases of complex fluid-flow: sophisticated but
intrusive means such as hot-wire anemometry can often alter the
basic flow structure.  Based on papers and related discussions of
recent work, the emphasis on advancement of techniques appears
the greatest in Germany and the USA.  Development of equipment
for the measurement of three-dimensional properties together with
data processing software appears to put Denmark, the UK and
the USA in the lead.  As described in the following paragraph, today
there is a particular need in the Navy for sophisticated laboratory
measurement techniques, towards the validation and certification of
numerical simulation tools.  I plan to hold an international workshop
in a few months towards establishing specific needs, related plans,
and international collaboration possibilities in both sponsorship and
execution of the research plans. <P>

<B>3. Background and Naval Perspective</B><P>

This conference was held closely following the 21st ONR Symposium
on Naval Hydrodynamics in Trondheim, Norway, which presented
today's Navy emphasis on numerical simulation and prediction of
ship dynamical and propulsive performance for realistic ship hull
geometry and ocean environments.  In many cases such numerical
"model tests" are aimed at replacing the traditional, expensive
practice of physical model tests.  Detailed and accurate laboratory
measurements are however essential towards sufficient confidence
in these numerical models: for validation of their physics-based
modelling of fluid-flow and associated energy-transfer mechanisms;
and for certification of a physical parameter-based envelope within
which such validation holds.  Because this validation must be
established for each computational step representing a re-distribution
of energy within the fluid, the corresponding laboratory tests must
provide a very accurate, high-resolution description of the kinematic
and dynamic properties of the fluid.  Recent advancements in the
measurement techniques and related data-processing softwares
presented and discussed in this conference are of great significance
to the numerical model validation and certification.<P>

<B>4. Conference Highlights: Advanced Techniques</B><P>

The following provides a brief description of recent advancements in
two areas: Measurement Techniques and Measurement Equipment.<P>

<B>4.1 Measurement Techniques</B><P>

<B>4.1.1  Combined Application of Particle Image Velocimetry (PIV) and
Laser-Doppler Anemometry (LDA):</B> A paper by Volkert, et al, of the
University of Erlangen-Nurnberg, Germany, describes a combined
PIV-LDA technique which is used to measure the properties of a
swirling flow under compression.  Previous measurement approaches
to this problem had been those of scanning LDA measurements,
two-point velocity measurements, the use of filters in the frequency
domain, etc., due to the limitation that the LDA velocity is known
only at one point and any global flow-movement cannot be deduced
from it.  PIV on the other hand is a whole-field technique, but today
it does not provide the sufficient spatial and temporal resolution
necessary for a statistical description of the turbulence field.  The
combined approach presented here, both in the experimental set-up
and in data recognition and processing, are of general nature and
therefore applicable to a range of fluid flow problems.<P>

<B>4.1.2  Application of Particle Tracking Velocimetry (PTV):</B> A paper by
Rothlubbers, et al, of the Technical University Berlin, Germany,
describes a new technique for the analysis of single-frame,
double-exposure PTV images.  As against Digital Particle Image
Velocimetry (DPIV), the PTV technique offers the advantages of
high signal to noise ratio by not requiring a large concentration of
particles; it allows a quantitative measurement of macroscopic
particle behavior with a low-energy laser combined with a camera.
Overall, principally because of its low particle-concentration
requirement, it can be a far less time consuming technique
than DPIV.<P>

<B>4.1.3  Laser-Induced Fluorescence Tomography:</B> A paper by Merkel,
et al, of the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology, Zurich, presents
a novel approach to the 3-D velocity measurement, using an adaptive
least-squares correlation of "grey" level distributions of patches
generated by Laser-Induced Fluorescence (LIF).  Without the
requirement of multiple measurements and subsequent differentiation,
this method allows the determination of the fluid vorticity vector and
rate-of-strain tensor.<P>

<B>4.1.4  Holographic Particle Image Velocimetry (HPIV):</B> A paper by
Katz, et al, of the Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, USA,
presents a hybrid HPIV measurement system developed under the
sponsorship of ONR and the US National Science Foundation (NSF).
In the case of the standard PIV technique a local velocity is obtained
from double-exposure images of the flow field, measuring the particle
displacement.  The HPIV technique, however, is capable of recording
data in a three-dimensional space and therefore providing a 3-D
distribution of velocity.  In their design of the hybrid system the
authors use in-line and off-axis holography for forward- and side-
scattering, respectively, together with a phase conjugate wave which
illuminates the hologram from a direction opposite of the recording
reference beam.  The reconstructed phase-conjugate image allows
the elimination of aberrations introduced by the relay lenses.<P>

<B>4.1.5  Scanning Particle Image Velocimetry (SPIV):</B> A paper by
Brucker of Aerodynamic Institute, RWTH Aachen, Germany,
describes the use of SPIV, an alternative to HPIV for 3-D velocity
measurements.  The paper describes a technique which uses two
color-coded overlapping light sheets and applies a spatial cross-
correlation to the images in the overlapping planes for the
out-of-plane velocity component.<P>

<B>4.1.6  Jet Flames by Laser-Induced Fluorescence (LIF):</B>
A paper by Meier, et al, of Institut fur Physikalische Chemie der
Verbrennung, Stutgart, describes a novel approach to the
characterization of jet diffusion flames in terms of temperature and
chemical composition by spontaneous "Raman Scattering" together
with LIF measurements.  The experiment was aimed principally at
the quantification of a major pollutant in the exhaust: the family of
oxides of nitrogen.<P>

<B>4.2 Measurement Equipment and Softwares</B><P>

The above researchers are no doubt dependent largely on the state
of the art in measurement eqipment and softwares as enabling
technology, developed and provided by organizations dedicated to
this need.  The following three organizations stand out as being in
the lead of such development.<P>

<B>4.2.1 DANTEC Measurement Technology</B><P>

With its corporate headquarters in Skovlunde, Denmark, DANTEC
is an international organization with branch offices in the UK, the
Netherlands, Ireland, France, Germany, Hong Kong, China, and
the USA.  Together with hard- and software capabilities for real-time
data analysis in many cases, DANTEC's flow-measurement systems
include PIV, LDA, hot-wire anemometry, Burst Spectrum analysis,
particle sizing and analysis, as well as laser positioning systems
used by aerospace, automotive and shipbuilding industries.<P>

<B>4.2.2 TSI Incorporated</B><P>

With its corporate headquarters in St Paul, MN, USA, TSI is an
international organization with branch offices in Germany and France.
TSI provides a wide range of LDV systems, up to a Doppler
Frequency of 100 MHz, with single-, dual- and three-component,
single- and dual-axis configurations.  TSI's other capabilities include
a patented method for a real-time estimation of a Doppler burst
signal-to-noise ratio (SNR); and the ability to optimize, on-line, the
the sampling rate for each burst together with SNR-based recognition
of the beginning and end of burst, in order to obtain the center of
burst from which samples were collected.<P>

<B>4.2.3 Oxford Lasers Limited</B><P>

Based in Abingdon, Oxfordshire, UK, with branch offices in the USA
and Germany, Oxford lasers has developed very specialized
capabilities in laser imaging for high-speed photography, flow and
welding visualization, combustion analysis, PIV, etc.  Their principal
innovation is "Laserstrobe", which uses the copper laser of high peak
power and very short pulse (about a 30-nanosecond duration).  This
allows a time-resolved, very-high-resolution imaging system.  The
Laserstrobe recording is on a standard 35-mm film, with a resolution
density of at least 125 lines/mm, at a rate of at least 40,000 frames
per second with an exposure duration of 20-60 nanoseconds.<P>

<B>5. Assessment</B><P>

As observed in sections 4.1 and 4.2 above, there is strong emphasis
in the European fluid mechanics community on the advancement of
measurement techniques and technology.  As with many other areas
of basic research, a greater level of investment is evident in Germany
towards an experiment-based understanding of the physics of
various complex fluid-flow phenomena.  Another noteworthy
observation is that of the close relationship between such scientists
and those engaged in the development of enabling technologies of
equipment for the acquisition, processing and analysis of data.<P>

<B>6. Related Plans for the Future</B><P>

As described in section 3 above, the Navy has a great need today
for laboratory experiment-based validation and certification of the
various numerical simulation models.  I plan to hold an international
workshop in a few months towards establishing their specific needs,
related experimental plans, and possible international collaboration
in both sponsorship and execution of the research plans.<P>

<B>7. Further Details</B><P>

For further details on the above one can contact<P>

Dr P. Peter Majumdar<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5TH,  UK<P>

Telephone: +44-171-514-4947<BR>
Fax:           +44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-Mail:       <A HREF="mailto:PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>

Copies of this and other ONR Europe newsletters are obtainable
from World-Wide Web by reaching<P>

http://www.ehis.navy.mil/<P>

<B>8. US Government Disclaimer</B><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the
author and do not necessarily reflect the official US Government,
US Navy, or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A></BODY></HTML>
