<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hydrodynamics & Acoustics Newsletter #5</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Newsletter 96-005<BR>                                           
11 November 1996<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/majumdar.htm">Dr Peter Majumdar</A>
<P>

University of Southampton, Departments of Ship Science and Electronics</H3>

<B>1. Key Words</B><P>

<I>Education in Ship Sciences; Research in Ship Sciences;
Naval Architecture; Ship Hydrodynamics; Ship Structures;
Control Systems; Fuzzy and Neuro-Fuzzy Logic.</I><P>

<B>2. Summary</B><P>

Hosted by Professor C. Rice, Dean of Engineering, and Professor
W. G. Price, Head of the Department of Ship Science, I visited
on 06 August 1996 the academic and research staff as well as the
laboratories of two Departments of the University of Southampton:
(a) Department of Ship Science; and (b) Department of Electronics.
Professor Price, long regarded as one of world's foremost authorities
on the subject of ship dynamics, joined the Department of Ship
Science eight years ago; and since then he has brought the quality
and diversity of ship related research in this Department to match
today's specialized demands.  The prominent research areas in this
Department are those of ship dynamics, propulsor hydrodynamics
with emphasis on computational fluid dynamics (CFD), and ship
structures with emphasis on light-weight composites.  In the area of
undergraduate education this Department has a unique requisite,
involving all of the real-world features: project definition; preparation of
technical and cost proposals; presentations; obtaining approval and
budget; project planning; hardware purchase; project management
and execution; and, possible budget cut!      My interest in the
Department of Electronics --now called the Department of Electronics
and Computer Science-- was initially related to its research in fuzzy
logic with application to real-time active control systems design.
This Department is however engaged in very high quality research in
a number of areas, including some which combine computer science
with neuroscience.  Until about the mid-1950s, in most universities
the areas of electronics formed a special disciplinary aspect of the
study of electrical engineering.  Established in 1946 as a Department
of its own entity, Southampton's Department of Electronics and
Computer Science is the oldest such department among the UK
universities.<P>

<B>3. Research and Academic Activities</B><P>

Areas of research and academic emphasis in the Department of
Ship Science and the Department of Electronics and Computer
Science are outlined in the following.<P>

<B>3.1 Department of Ship Science</B><P>

Recognition and reputation of the University of Southampton is
world-wide for its excellence in the study and research of ship and
ocean sciences.  The Department of Ship Science is however
separate from the Southampton Oceanography Centre, and its focus
is on basic and applied sciences as they relate to naval architecture
and offshore technology.<P>

<B>3.1.1 Research Areas:</B>  Ship Dynamics, Propulsor Hydrodynamics,
and Structures are the principal areas of research in this Department.
Especially in the prediction of ship motions and sea loads, while the
emphasis throughout the world now is on elaborate numerical models
based on boundary-element and Navier-Stokes approaches often
requiring days of computer time, this Department has in addition
maintained extensive analytical research towards physics-based
problem formulation and understanding of the kinematics as well as
dynamics of ship motions.  Corresponding numerical solution
procedures are then quite straightforward, requiring very modest
computer time while providing sufficient and accurate information on
the rigid-body response of ships and offshore structures to potential
wave loads.  A most recent and very noteworthy of such research
efforts in hydrodynamics is the development of a unified mathematical
model describing the maneuvering of a ship travelling in a seaway.
Through the application of impulse response functions and convolution
integrals to represent fluid actions, this unified model --together with
the traditional formulations of slow-motion derivatives, oscillatory
derivatives, and hydrodynamic coefficients-- describes the dynamical
behavior and maneuvering of a ship travelling in a seaway.
Research in propulsor hydrodynamics emphasizes the mechanisms
of lift modification in a turbulent boundary layer, the shedding of blade
vortices and associated acoustics, tip vortex generation and mixing,
etc., by way of numerical models comprising formulations of
Reynolds-Averaged Navier-Stokes (RANS) equations, Large Eddy
Simulation (LES), and potential vortex theories.  Development of a
generalized "inverse design" formulation is a major research effort for
direct application to the design and optimization of propulsors.
Research in ship and offshore structures appears to have a clear
emphasis on light-weight composites, with researchers working in
close partnership with material scientists.  The principal material type
under investigation is the carbon fiber re-inforced plastic, with a large
variation in its composition, lamination and its directivity, structure
and dimensionality of weave, etc.  The approach of research is largely
empirical, as dictated by its nature, and it has a very direct focus on
the real-world application: structural configurations for offshore and
ship use with particular attention to the unique and complex joints,
as well as the nature of steady, transient, and cyclic loads.  In
addition to problems in common with isotropic metal structures, an
inherent problem in the case of composites is that of simultaneously
meeting the requirements of strength, deflection, and dimensional
limits.  Additionally, the prediction of fatigue failure is difficult today:
For metals of traditional use there exists a sizable volume fatigue
data in the form of "S-N Curves" while for composites that are often
in their developmental stage such data are still being generated.  The
research approach at Southampton is very comprehensive, rigorous,
and thorough; and, as a result, some of these developments are now
being transitioned to actual ship structural applications.<P>

<B>3.1.2 Academic Curriculum:</B>  In general, a UK university appears to
place a much greater emphasis on the undergraduate involvement in
university research than is evident in the US.  In particular, it is true
of the departments of marine technology and ship sciences.  As part
of their graduation requirements the Southampton undergraduates in
Ship Science take part in research projects in their Department, in
addition to their independent work towards the Design Thesis.  A very
unique requirement must additionally be fulfilled by the third-year
undergraduates here: one of a program technical and financial
management.  Students in groups of three or four present to a panel
their technical and cost proposals for projects of their choice.  If a
proposal is accepted based on its technical merit, students then
prepare and present a detailed technical schedule together with a
breakdown of costs.  If it is approved, students are given actual
money for the necessary purchase of hardware and ancillaries.  They
then have exactly three months in which to complete their project,
within cost.  Sometimes they may even be notified of a budget cut,
and asked to tailor their project to a reduced funding level.  Examples
of such projects are an operational wind tunnel, various ship models
for use, a number of complex composite structures for laboratory
tests, and the design and manufacture of an experimental set-up for
material fatigue tests.<P>

<B>3.2 Department of Electronics and Computer Science</B><P>

Established in 1946 as Department of Electronics, this is the first
such Department among UK universities.  My initial interest in this
Department was in connection with its research efforts in fuzzy logic
and related application to active control systems design.  During my
discussions with professors and researchers I came to know of a
large number of areas of research in this Department, some of which
are outlined below.<P>

<B>3.2.1 Research Areas:</B>  The Image, Speech & Intelligence Systems
Research Group (ISIS) carries out fundamental research including
the formulation of "neurofuzzy" algorithms for modelling of command,
control, perception and cognition, and speech processing --much of
it in the context of systems engineering and integration for various
infrastructures related to warfare, public utilities, and transportation
industries.  The goal is that of an Intelligent Autonomous System
which combines the distributed human elements with a complex,
integrated system to perform tasks autonomously in uncertain
and dynamic environments.  The Intelligent Control, Modelling and
Estimation Group (ICME) is active in advanced research developing
an autonomous active-control algorithm for dynamic processes.
This group has developed novel fuzzy-logic algorithms.  An on-board
command and control system has been successfully used on an
unmanned underwater vehicle (UUV).  Planned future work in this
area includes distributed systems of artificial intelligence (AI) for
command and control.  A few other examples of advanced research
are the development of a channel-adaptive speech transceiver; biased
temporal filtering in ultrasound imaging; intelligent parallel image
analysis; and developments in optical fibre technology.<P>

<B>4. Assessment</B><P>

In the Department of Ship Science, while the level of research in
numerical prediction and analysis models in hydrodynamics in
general lacks some of the sophistication and complexity in
formulation, its continued emphasis on the analytical research has
brought significant understanding of the physical phenomena and
therefore the capability for their physics-based modelling.  The
research in the area of ship structures is most comprehensive,
systematic, and thorough.  The undergraduate academic curriculum
of this Department can be regarded as a model, with a very sensible
balance of classroom education, laboratory research, and training in
project formulation, planning, execution, and technical and financial
management.   Research in the Department of Electronics and
Computer Science as it relates to fuzzy- and neuro-fuzzy-logic, and
neural network algorithm for optimal control systems, is of the highest
level of sophistication; and much of it has been implemented and
validated.<P>

<B>5. Further Details</B><P>

For further details one can contact the author:<P>

Dr P. Peter Majumdar<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5TH,  UK<P>

Telephone: +44-171-514-4947<BR>
Fax:          +44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-Mail:       <A HREF="mailto:PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>

For direct information from the University of Southampton
one can contact<P>

(a) Department of Ship Science (Tel: +44-1703-59-5000)<P>

     Hydrodynamics: Dr A. Molland; Dr P. Temarel.<P>

     Structures:         Dr A. Shenoi.<P>

(b) Department of Electronics and Computer Science
     (Tel: +44-1703-59-2493)<P>

     Control Systems Logic: Dr M. Brown.<P>

Copies of this and other ONR Europe newsletters are obtainable
from World-Wide Web by reaching<P>

