<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hydrodynamics & Acoustics Newsletter #5</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>Newsletter 96-006<BR>                                           
12 November 1996<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/majumdar.htm">Dr Peter Majumdar</A>
<P>

The University of Leeds, Computer Model for Simultaneous Engineering</H3>

<B>1. Key Words</B><P>

<I>Process Engineering; Simultaneous Engineering;
Automated Decision Making; Computer-Aided Design.</I><P>

<B>2. Summary</B><P>

I visited the Mechanical Engineering Department of the University of
Leeds on 05 September 1996 for a discussion and demonstration of
its computer model supporting an integrated approach to definition,
manufacture, and in-service upgrades of an engineering product.  In
conformity with the ISO standards for the exchange product model
data, the combined architecture of the computer models comprises
modules for requirements, resources, their interpretation and test
for compatibility; the development of product model of a generic
description for manufacture; and life-cycle configuration control.
Though in most aspects of its structure this integrated model is in
its developmental phase, it nonetheless has a sound, logical basis
for its concept and therefore the promise of a rational methodology
for simultaneous engineering in product definition, manufacture, and
life-cycle management.<P>

<B>3. Background</B><P>

In the UK, both the Ministry of Defence (MOD) and the Engineering
and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC) have over the
recent years maintained a focus on research in the development of
methodology and engineering practices towards streamlining the
steps in Process Engineering and Manufacture as well as in-service
configuration control and logistics support.  The Government and the
private sector are equally active today in their efforts to reduce costs
related to engineering manufacture and maintenance.  The model
currently under development at Leeds, sponsored primarily by the
Government, is an example of such efforts.<P>

<B>4. The Leeds Model: A Brief Description</B><P>

At the top level the Leeds model begins with two Definition and
Descriptions Protocols: the Application Protocol (AP) and the
Resources Protocol (RP).  The Application Protocol first defines the
Application Activity Model comprising the requirements of product,
maintenance, or logistics.  It then translates the information in terms
of the model parameters consistent with ISO standards and, where
applicable, the NATO Stock Numbers (NSN); and the translated
information is then written into the Application Requirements Model.
In parallel, the Resources Protocol provides the Integrated Resources
Model, comprising numerical models and databases for generation
of geometric and topological representation, product structure
configuration, computer-aided design, finite-element analysis for
material and scantlings selection, necessary checks on kinematics,
towards computer-aided manufacture.  The fundamentals of the
model architecture is based on matching the Application
Requirements Model with the Integrated Resources Model in a way
which could enable an automated process that begins with
engineering manufacture or maintenance requirements, selects the
necessary Resources as well as the criteria for an optimal product
decision, and provides the necessary information for computer-aided
manufacture.  This automated decision-based matching process
involves a very logical engineering interpretation of the product
requirements which often are provided in operational parameters.
The current approach, under development, is to further translate the
Requirements Model into Application-Interpreted Definition Model,
and the Integrated Resources Model into Application-Interpreted
Constructs, so that the "Interpreted" models can have a common-
definition-based interface for information transfer and iteration.<P>

<B>5. Assessment</B><P>

Though in most aspects of its structure the Leeds model is currently
under development, it nonetheless defines an integrated architecture
on a very sound logical basis.  The challenge will largely remain in
the various stages of decision-making process which will require a
very sophisticated logic of artificial intelligence (AI).  Relative to
component design decisions towards a set of requirements the goal
of this model is more complex, as it to a large degree attempts to
take into account a system-level synergism towards a product
decision.  However, the University of Leeds is a recognized leader
in the field of Automated Process Engineering and therefore its
progress in continued development of this model is worth studying.<P>

<B>6. Further Details</B><P>

For further details one can contact the author:<P>

Dr P. Peter Majumdar<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5TH,  UK.<P>

Telephone: +44-171-514-4947<BR>
Fax:           +44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-Mail:       <A HREF="mailto:PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>

For direct information from the University of Leeds
one can contact<P>

Dr M. S. Bloor<BR>
Tel: +44-133-341-751.<P>

<B>7. US Government Disclaimer</B><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the
author and do not necessarily reflect the official US Government,
US Navy, or ONREUR positions.
