<HTML><HEAD><TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Newsletter 96-007<BR>                                           
25 November 1996<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/majumdar.htm">Dr Peter Majumdar</A>
<P>

Dantec Measurement Technology</H3>

<B>1. Key Words</B><P>

<I>Fluid Flow Measurement; Laser-Doppler Anemometry;
Particle Image Velocimetry; Fluid Flow Visualization.</I><P>

<B>2. Summary</B><P>

I visited on 12 September 1996 the Bristol, UK, facility of Dantec
Measurement Technology for an update on its recent developments
in complex fluid flow measurement techniques.  Long recognized as
a world leader in measurement technology, Dantec is an international
organization with its corporate headquarters in Skovlunde, Denmark,
and branch offices in the UK, Germany, France, the Netherlands,
Hong Kong, China, and the USA.  In addition to its recent advanced
techniques in Laser-Doppler Anemometry (LDA) with real-time data
processing capabilities, Dantec has maintained a consistent focus
on developments towards the understanding of fluid flow phenomena
which are not easily understood by point-measurement techniques
such as LDA or hot-wire anemometry.  As a result, it has made a
substantial investment in research towards the development of a very
comprehensive method based on Particle Image Velocimetry (PIV),
together with capabilities for on-line, real-time processing of data.
In addition to its efforts towards non-intrusive measurements of
fluid-flow properties, Dantec has also utilized its laser expertise in
the development of precision measurement techniques required in
product manufacture.<P>

<B>3. Background</B><P>

During the past decade, as computational fluid dynamics (CFD)
tools grew in their capabilities to predict complex fluid flows, the
techniques for accurate measurement of such flow fields received
equal emphasis.  Previously-employed measurement techniques
such as hot-wire anemometry, though very sophisticated, would
often alter the basic flow structure.  Non-intrusive approaches were
first started with the use of Laser-Doppler Anemometry (LDA).  But,
because the velocity provided by LDA is known only at one point,
a global flow movement history could not be derived from it.  Next
came the Particle Image Velocimetry (PIV) technique which, though
a whole-field technique, does not often provide a sufficient spatial
and temporal resolution.  Currently, a combined LDA-PIV approach
is being investigated among other techniques such as Holographic
PIV and Particle Tracking Velocimetry (PTV).<P>

<B>4. Dantec's Capabilities</B><P>

Today, Dantec's most recent and most advanced development is that
of "FlowMap", a comprehensive set-up for flow visualization, and data
acquisition and processing based on the PIV technique.  In addition
to especially-designed devices of electro-optics and laser optics for
proper illumination of complex flow fields (e.g., breaking waves, jets,
flows around airfoils, engine flows, etc.) as well as high-resolution
recording devices, this system also includes Dantec's "PIV 2000
Processor", quite possibly the world's only processor designed
uniquely for real-time treatment of the vast PIV data.  One great
advantage of this system is that, by virtue of its efficiency in data
acquisition, processing and management, it enables quick decisions
as to the quality and completeness of information (providing a quick
turn-around for a repeat test with set-up reconfiguration, if necessary.)
Another of Dantec's innovative development is an analysis software
called Light Scattering Analysis (LSA) which provides the mechanism
of how light is scattered by spherical particles in the fluid.  In the LDA
or PIV experiments the detailed knowledge of the scattered light field
is often essential.  The Burst Spectrum Analyzer (BSA), recently
developed by Dantec, is aimed at experimental efficiency: its analog
output provides results on line, enabling real-time optimization of the
experimental set-up.  The Flow Velocity Analyzer (FVA) is another
example of Dantec's software capabilities: a correlation signal
processor for the LDA, the FVA has a large dynamic range for
velocity and, compared to most other processors, is able to identify
and analyze information with lower signal-to-noise ratio (SNR).<P>

<B>5. Assessment</B><P>

With offices and facilities in eight countries, Dantec Measurement
Technology has long been established as one of the leaders in the
development of technology and techniques for measurement of
complex fluid-flow properties.  This organization remains in close
contact with scientists in both experimental and computational
science in order to understand new requirements of information,
towards new developments as well as modification of existing
software for unique test conditions.<P>

<B>6. Further Details</B><P>

For further details on the above one can contact the author:<P>

Dr P. Peter Majumdar<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5TH,  UK<P>

Telephone: +44-171-514-4947<BR>
Fax:           +44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-Mail:        <A HREF="mailto:PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>

<B>7. US Government Disclaimer</B><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the
author and do not necessarily reflect the official US Government,
US Navy, or ONREUR positions.
