<HEAD><TITLE>Newsletter 97-001</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Newsletter 97-001<BR>
18 January 1997<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/majumdar.htm">Dr Peter Majumdar</A>
<P>

MTD-PSTI Merger: CMPT</H3>

<B>1. Key Words</B><P>

<I>Multi-Sponsor Research; Ship and Offshore Technology;
Petroleum Technology; Subsurface Geology; Petrochemistry;
Petrophysics; Offshore Drilling Technology.</I><P>

<B>2. Summary</B><P>

In <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/pmnews2.htm">Newsletter 96-002</A> of last year I reported on the structure, operation
and scope of Marine Technology Directorate (MTD), a UK consortium
for research in ship and offshore technologies, of which ONR had just
become the first non-UK-based member.  Very recently a merger has
occurred between MTD and the Edinburgh-based Petroleum Science
and Technology Institute (PSTI) which has been an organization for
basic and applied research in sciences related to petroleum and its
extraction.  Name for the amalgamated organization has been chosen
as Centre for Marine and Petroleum Technology (CMPT).<P>

<B>3. MTD Background</B><P>

A research consortium aimed at the advancement of marine as well as
offshore technology, MTD has been regarded in the UK as a prime
exemplar of a multi-sponsor research organization.  Areas of research
have been based on the requirements of government, the needs of
industry, and the capabilities of academic and applied researchers.
Responsibility for the formal management of the research programs
has been with Marinetech South Limited, a Southampton-based non-
profit organization formed solely for this function.  In reality, the
financial support for the MTD research programs has come largely
from the UK taxpayers, as much of the funding (between 70 and 80
percent) has been provided by the UK Government's Engineering and
Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC) and only the remainder
has been collectively provided by the consortium members.  Last year
ONR became the first non-UK-based member of this consortium.<P>

<B>4. PSTI Background</B><P>

An Edinburgh-based research organization, PSTI has been engaged in
basic and applied research related to petroleum and its extraction. The
primary areas of emphasis have been subsurface geological prediction
together with reservoir characterization from seismic data; reservoir
modelling; study of materials in deep-water environments; hydrates
and their control; subsea drilling; subsea cleaning; subsea batteries;
subsea communication; and a number of topics in petrochemistry and
petrophysics.<P>

<B>5. Assessment of Future: Newly-Formed CMPT</B><P>

It is currently understood that the charter, structure, management, and
sponsor participation of CMPT will follow those of the former MTD, as
described in section 3 above.  It is naturally speculated that the areas
of research formerly within PSTI will enjoy relative emphasis in funding
as the potential sponsors for such research are oil companies.  The
UK Government's support, by way of EPSRC, for research in the areas
related to ship and offshore structure technology is however expected
to remain as high as it has been for the MTD research.<P>

<B>6. Further Details</B><P>

For further details one can contact the author:<P>

Dr P. Peter Majumdar<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5TH,  UK<P>

Telephone: +44-171-514-4947<BR>
Fax:          +44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-Mail:       <A HREF="mailto:PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil">PMajumdar@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>

Copies of this and other ONR Europe newsletters are obtainable
from World-Wide Web by reaching<P>

http://www.ehis.navy.mil/<P>

<B>7. US Government Disclaimer</B><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the
author and do not necessarily reflect the official US Government, US Navy, or ONREUR positions.
