<HEAD><TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>December 5, 1994<BR>  European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A></H3>
 
<H3>Office of Naval Research-European Office<BR>  Biophysics
Newsletter No. 1 
</H3>
<H3>Russian Foundation for Basic Research</H3>
<P>The field of biophysics covers a vast range of topics. Despite a
lack of definition, biophysics, an amalgamation of the biological and
physical sciences, is recognised as a major scientific activity that has
led to spectacular developments in biology and biotechnology.
</P><P> "European Biophysics" is an electronic newsletter that reports
on items of biophysics (including biotechnology, neurobiophysics,
psychology, psychophysics, chemical detection, bioelectronics,
biomimetic materials, physics of interfaces, personnel training,
underwater bioacoustics, etc.) discovered in Europe, FSU and the Middle
East.
</P><P> My general intent is to send short, 1-3 page newsletters. In
the future I can mail a newsletter series on a specific topic for those
who have interest in that topic.
</P><P> This newsletter is the first report about my trip to Russia in
November of 1994. This first report contains general data about the
trip; newsletters that follow will be technical reports that I divided
(very roughly) by science and technology categories.
</P><P> The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing
current information on science and technology development in European
countries. In order to better meet your needs, our Associate Directors
and Scientists are very much interested in knowing what are your
specific science and technology interests. Please advise.
</P><P> Furthermore, if there are others, that you are aware of, who
have interest in these newsletters please pass their e-mail address to
me and I will add them to the distribution list.
</P><P></P><H3>RUSSIA, Moscow and St. Petersburg, 15 -- 23 November
1994<BR>  Russian Foundation for Basic Research</H3> 
<P><B>Contents</B> 
</P><OL>
<LI>Summary  
</LI>
<LI>Russian Foundation for Basic Research (RFBR)  
</LI>
<LI>Trip experiences  
</LI>
<LI>Next steps  
</LI>
<LI>Concerns  
</LI>
<LI>Institutions visited  
</LI>
<LI>Personal contacts  
</LI> 
</OL><P><B>1. Summary</B>
</P><P> Nineteen Russian private research and development (R&amp;D)companies
and academic research institutions were visited.<BR>  There is a window
of opportunity for the Navy, and US high-tech industries for partnership
and collaboration in various unique and novel R&amp;D projects in
Russia. This window of opportunity should be used expeditiously as
conditions in academic institutions are deteriorating rapidly. Most of
these academic institutions presently have 3 day work-week and do not
have funds to pay utilities and communication bills.
</P><P><B>2. Russian Foundation for Basic Research</B>
</P><P> Visited on November 16, 1994.<BR>  Address: 32a Leninsky pr.,
Moscow, 117334, Russia
</P><P> ONREUR: J. Silva (Director), N. Bottka (electronics), J. Simon
(manufacturing technologies), and I. Vodyanoy (biophysics)<BR>  RFBR:
Fortov (Director), Alfimov (deputy director), Dykhne (head of Physics
section) Other: Ostrovsky, Rachimov
</P><P> The RUSSIAN FOUNDATION FOR BASIC RESEARCH (RFBR) was
established by a Presidential Decree in 1992 as an independent federal
agency for the advancement of science in Russia. They receive and review
research proposals and award individual, pilot and group grants,
instrumentation grants, support of data bases and information systems,
and publication projects.<BR>  Their budget comes from the Federal
Government as a fixed share of the Federal budget for science.
Additional funds are expected to come from foreign sources through
different co-operation and collaboration projects.<BR>  Presently the
RFBR share in 1994 total R&amp;D Russian budget is 5%. RFBR will match
$12 M from SOROS foundation, $2- $5 M from NSF (US), will have matching
funds for German Science Foundation (Fortov' s words). Fortov's office
also works on agreements with Japan and China.<BR>  Thirty panels
(10-16 experts) out of the pool of about 1,000 scientists, reviewing
(for a fee) about 3,000 proposals annually. They allow 20% grantee
institutional overhead.<BR>  RFBR presently supports about 1,200
institutions in the fields of: Mathematics, computer and information
sciences, physics, chemistry, biology, geophysics, atmosphere,
oceanography, humanities and arts. The average grant is $10,000/year.<BR>
    I have a complete list of all projects funded (1994) by RFBR. The
list has the PI's name, project title, and the name of institution. It
is published in Russian, a copy has been mailed to ONR and was made
available to the other services at Edison House.
</P><P><B>3. Trip Experiences</B>
</P><P> Planning for this trip took more than two months. E-mail,
telephone calls to Moscow, St. Petersburg to a more than 20 parties. I
have restored my network of friends and alumna in Russia. Many of them
have become department chairs, institute directors, academicians, full
generals and government officials.<BR>  Our experience indicated that
the number of people in our S&amp;T review party (4) was too large. A
group of this size made planning difficult on the Russian side. I think,
the right number for a party is two. If it is more than two, then
Russians see us as a "delegation" and treat us differently, that is,
they treat us more "officially". That means they start to set up all the
visits from the "centre" to periphery and it takes a lot of time and
puts a lot of unnecessary bureaucratic barriers in the way of visits
arrangement.<BR>  I specifically asked our hosts to treat our party as
a private one. This was very difficult an was possible to accomplish
only with the help of my colleagues' network. During our visit in Moscow
and St. Petersburg there were 10- 15 people working for us behind the
scenes. There was even a person waiting in line at the petrol station to
fuel our cars.<BR>  Dr. Rachimov, a representative of East-West
Technology Partners Inc. (US Virginia) was a big help to Jack Simon and
to all of us. Academician Ostrovsky, who was our primary host, worked 20
hours a day. He travelled with us and helped in both cities, Moscow and
St. Petersburg. His assistance, overall was invaluable to the success of
this mission.
</P><P><B>4. Next Steps</B>
</P><P> There is a tremendous opportunity for the US government
agencies and industry to leverage the enormous scientific and
technological resources in Russian academic and private R&amp;D
institutions. During many years of isolation and secrecy Russian
scientists developed some highly original ideas and technologies that
have not been available. They are available now at all levels, from
conferences to collaboration, to joint projects, and to direct funding
or co-funding.<BR>  The Russian Foundation for Basic Research could be
used as an instrument for proposals screening and review by experts and
also for a fiscal control. RFBR directors expressed their willingness to
screen proposals according to our list of interest, to review them and
to give recommendations. They also proposed to disburse our grants
according to our contractual and legal prescription (collecting reports,
advancing payments, etc.) by using their accountants and contract system
and taking 2-5% of negotiable overhead. Grants can be made to
individuals and they say that PI's institutional overhead can be
specified by the US granting agency.<BR>  The Russian Foundation for
Basic Research proposed to match DOD funding of the projects they
recommended. They also could match funding of workshops and conferences.<BR>
    Proposals from private R&amp;D industry could be developed with the
help of East-West Technology Partners Inc.
</P><P><B>5. Concerns</B>
</P><P> Most Russian scientists are reluctant to submit proposals
directly (personally) to any US agency and specifically to the DOD
agencies. They prefer if a proposal would be submitted through their
institutional directors or would be pre-screened and duplicated for us
by the Russian Foundation for Basic Science. That way all "formalities"
will be satisfied.<BR>  A major concern expressed by many scientists
working in application fields regards their intellectual rights. They
would like to have a grant or a contract that would legally protect
their intellectual rights and are reluctant to submit any technical
proposals or give their samples out without understanding the means of
protections available.
</P><P><B>6. Institutions visited</B>
