<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 3</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY><H3>February 10, 1995<BR>  European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A></H3>
 
<H3>Office of Naval Research-European Office<BR>  Biophysics
Newsletter No. 3</H3> 
<H3>Surface Coatings from Moscow and St. Petersburg</H3><P>If there
are others, that you are aware of, who have interest in these
newsletters please pass their e-mail address to me and I will add them
to the distribution list.
</P><P><B>Contents</B> 
</P><OL>
<LI>Summary  
</LI>
<LI>Pressure sensitive coating  
</LI>
<LI>Electrostatic protection coating  
</LI>
<LI>Anti-biofouling coating  
</LI>
<LI>Carbon-lead electrodes for batteries  
</LI>
<LI>Coating for chemically aggressive environments  
</LI>
<LI>Protection for carbon electrodes  
</LI>
<LI>Next steps  
</LI>
<LI>Personal contacts  
</LI> 
</OL><P><B>1. Summary</B>
</P><P> During many years of isolation, Russian scientists developed
many highly original ideas and technologies. While on my recent visit to
Moscow and St Petersburg in Russia I discovered the few interesting
coatings with potentially significant practical importance. These
provide an opportunity for the Navy, and US high-tech industries for
partnership and collaboration in these unique and novel R&amp;D projects
in Russia.
</P><P><B> 2. Pressure sensitive coating</B>
</P><P> A pressure sensitive surface coating was developed at the
Institute of Physics of the St. Petersburg State University. The coating
is luminescent and its luminescent properties depend on the air pressure
in the range of 0.1-1000 Torr. These luminescence changes can follow the
air pressure change with frequency up to 1kHz. The coating can be
applied to a virtually any material. It could be used for example for
dynamic airflow studies in a wind tunnel.
</P><P><B> 3. Electrostatic protection coating</B>
</P><P> The Plasma Test Inc. has developed and tested a coating that
protects plastic and composite materials against an electrostatic
charge. This coating was utilised on fuselage materials of helicopters
and aeroplanes.<BR>  The coating, when polymerised on the surface,
becomes an integral part of the surface that is uninterrupted
electrically (with conductivity of about 1/2 of aluminium; mesh-like;
flexible) with thickness of about 25 microns and weight of about 40
grams per square meter. <BR>  During the tests it was able to dissipate
from 8 to 10 direct hits of about 300 kV without any damage. The coating
was tested by Sukhoi avionics designers.
</P><P><B> 4. Anti-biofouling coating</B>
</P><P> The Plasma Test Inc. research division has developed and tested
a multilayer non-toxic coating that effectively prevents biofouling in
sea water. The coating is porous, contains heavy metals that form some
salt compounds which fill the pores when exposed to the water. <BR> 
The coating was tested in the Baltic Sea, Indian and Atlantic Oceans.
Tests were conducted using the coating on a hull metal, fiber glass, and
a concrete. Some underwater port structures (in Ethiopia) were coated
and found free from bio-deposits after 7 years of exploitation. A coated
part of the ship's hull was also found practically free from deposits
after six months of navigation in southern hemisphere seas.<BR>  The
coating is claimed to be environmentally safe (salts are leaching very
slowly out of the pores). The coating technology production on
industrial scale and technology of surface treatment are fully developed
and tested. A process of surface treatment is simple, inexpensive, not
time consuming and can be applied to a hull in a dry dock. 
</P><P><B>5. Carbon-lead electrodes for batteries</B>
</P><P> A lead coating process to cover a carbon cloth using plasma
metallization was developed by the Plasma Test Inc. to replace lead
electrode plates in lead-sulphuric acid batteries. This lead covered
carbon electrodes weight 50% less and have 1.4 times increase in life
expectancy compared to the regular solid lead electrodes for batteries.
Batteries made with these compound electrodes have 1.2 times increase in
cold discharge current.
</P><P><B> 6. Coating for chemically aggressive environments</B>
</P><P> The "ANTECH" analytical centre (Moscow) has developed a surface
coating that is highly chemically resistive. The coating can be applied
to a metal and metal alloys surfaces. The coating is named "Tetron" and
is based on organo-soluble polymers with specific modifiers for
adhesion. The coating was tested for a long term use in chemical and
biotechnological reactors, sea water, acids and bases. 
</P><P><B> 7. Protection for carbon electrodes</B>
</P><P> A protective coating for reducing breakdown rates of high
current density arc producing graphite electrodes was developed at the
Plasma Test Inc., and then tested by industry in the full scale
industrial processes. The coating is produced by using a cold plasma
spraying of aluminium compounds (0.4-0.6 mm thickness). The electrode
breakdown rate was reduced by 35% and service time was increased by 50%.
About 150 tons of electrodes were tested.
</P><P><B> 8. Next steps</B>
</P><P> All of these sample coatings can be purchased. For those with
further interest ONR Europe can assist in obtaining additional technical
and proprietary information on the coatings. For those interested,
proposals from private Russian R&amp;D industry could be developed with
the help of East-West Technology Partners Inc. 
</P><P><B> 9. Personal contacts</B>
</P><P> Gonopolsky Adam M., Ph.D., Dr.S.<BR>  Plasma-Test,Inc.<BR> 
General Director<BR>  Moscow, 101000<BR>  Russia
</P><P> Prudnikov Igor. M., Ph.D., Dr.S.<BR>  Deputy Director for
Research<BR>  The Scientific Institute of Physics Research<BR> 
Uljanovskaya str. 1, Petrodvorets, <BR>  St. Petersburg, 198904<BR> 
Russia
</P><P> Rakhovsky Vadim I., Dr.S.<BR>  Director<BR>  Antech<BR> 
Kazarmenny per.,6, bldg.1<BR>  Moscow, 109028<BR>  Russia
</P><P> Rakhimov Alexander Tursunovich, Prof. Dr.S.<BR>  East-West
Techn Partners, Ltd<BR>  Chairman of the Dept Inst for Nucl Physics<BR>
 Moscow State University<BR>  Moscow 117899
</P><P></P><P>For more information on this topic contact:
</P><P> Igor Vodyanoy, Ph.D. <BR>  Associate Director, Biophysics<BR>
 ONR Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>  London, NW1 5TH<BR> 
England<BR>  Tel: 44-171-514-4131<BR>  Fax: 44-171-723-6359<BR> 
E-mail: ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  Military address: ONREUR, PSC
802 Box 39, FPO AE 09499-0700
</P><P></P>
