<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 4</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY><H3>April 6, 1995<BR>  European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A></H3>

<P><H3>Office of Naval Research-European Office <BR>  Biophysics
Newsletter No. 4
</H3></P><P> <H3>Sensory Perception, Learning, Neurophysiology, and
Psychophysics from Moscow and St.Petersburg</H3>
</P><P>The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing
current information on science and technology development in European
countries. In order to better meet your needs, our Associate Directors
and Scientists are very much interested in knowing what are your
specific science and technology interests. Please let me know what they
are.
</P><P> Furthermore, if there are others, who you are aware of, that
have interest in these newsletters please pass their e-mail address to
me and I will add them to the distribution list.
</P><P><B>Contents</B> 
</P><OL>
<LI>Summary  
</LI>
<LI>Emotion detector  
</LI>
<LI>Sound source movement simulation  
</LI>
<LI>Asymmetric brains  
</LI>
<LI>The cocktail party effect (Selective Listening)  
</LI>
<LI>Electric fish technology  
</LI>
<LI>Directional hearing in dolphins  
</LI>
<LI>Next steps  
</LI>
<LI>Personal contacts  
</LI> 
</OL><P><B> 1. Summary</B>
</P><P> This report outlines some projects in the area of sensory
perception, psychophysics and neurophysiology that attracted my
attention by their potential applications in both military and civilian
sectors.
</P><P><B> 2. Emotion Detector</B>
</P><P> Dr. Frolov and co-workers from the Institute Of Higher Neural
Activity & Neurophysiology Of Russian Academy Of Sciences of Russian
Academy of Science(RAS) in Moscow developed an original and
mathematically sophisticated model of human speech analysis. Using 8
parameters of human speech the model is capable of determining the
emotional state of an individual with high fidelity. The model was
developed jointly with the group of mathematicians from the other RAS
institute.<BR>  Multiple speech tests showed that physiological
parameters correlate well with the model's prediction. Tests were
conducted in the laboratory as well as in the field. These field tests
were carried out during simulated and actual jet fighter flights. The
speech analysing system takes just about 30 min. to learn individual
differences.<BR>  Regular telemetry reports physiological parameters,
such as pulse rate and blood pressure, whereas this system can actually
report on the subject's emotion i.e. joy, sorrow, fear, hate or whatever
they are experiencing at the time. The system can be used for personnel
training.
</P><P><B>3. Sound Source Movement Simulation</B>
</P><P> At the Pavlov Institute Of Physiology RAS, St. Petersburg, the
group headed by Dr. Altman has developed a novel and unique auditory
simulation of a sound source's three-dimensional spatial movement and
velocity change. The simulation development was based on psychometric
measurements, an analytical and computer modelling.<BR>  The model was
realised (for two dimensions) as the electronic device that can simulate
the movement of a sound source moving with changing direction and
velocity. This simulation device can be used in computer virtual reality
models and can be integrated into sonar or a radar output for two or
three dimensional orientation enhancement.
</P><P><B>4. Assymetric Brains</B>
</P><P> Dr. Chernigovskaya from the Sechenov Institute Of Evolutionary
Physiology RAS, St. Petersburg, works on mathematical modelling of
cerebral hemispheric functions. It is a multidisciplinary project in the
areas of psychosemantics and neurocognitive research, joint with the
group of knowledge analysts and computer specialists from the St.
Petersburg Technical University. The objective of the project is to
understand and formally define cerebral asymmetry of higher functions by
probing mental and sensory spaces. The ultimate goal understand the
biological basis of artificial intelligence.<BR>  A long-term
preliminary study (of about 15 years) was conducted to define cerebral
mechanisms of individual cognitive styles as a function of cerebral
right-left asymmetry. The studies were conducted using large groups of
children and adults.<BR>  It was established that significant
improvement of instruction process could be reached when instructor's
and students' brain assymetry are matched. The data allow the use of
individual brain asymmetry to substantially improve computer instruction
for computer aided learning processes. The work will greatly contribute
to designing and improving man-computer interface in general.
</P><P><B>5. The Cocktail Party Effect (Selective Listening)</B>
</P><P> At the N.N. Andreev Acoustic Institute RAS, Moscow, Dr.
Dubrovky's laboratory developed a mathematical model of the "listening"
attention mechanism. This mechanism allows conversation in a noisy room
(as a cocktail party effect) and is studied using psychoacoustic
experiments and mathematical modelling.<BR>  The model is tuned to a
number of spatial parameters of an acoustic field. An optimum algorithm
for a sound perception in human (panoramic listening vs. selectivity)
can be realised computationally, provided that the signals pass through
a bank of filters with parameters similar to the critical band filters
of hearing. The mathematical model correlates well with the
psychoacoustic experiments. This mathematical model can be utilised as a
device for a selective multidirectional sound detector.
</P><P><B>6. Electric Fish Technology</B>
</P><P> Environmental Biology group headed by Dr. Baron from the
Severtsov Institute Of Evolutionary Animal Morphology And Ecology, RAS,
Moscow developed a novel technology for underwater short-range
orientation, location and communication based on propagation and
reception principles derived from electric fish.<BR>  The laboratory
has studied electrogeneration, electroreception, electromagnetic field
structure and information processing in so-called "weakly electric
fish". Under a non-wave propagation specification they developed the
full range of technologies for prediction of radiation patterns and
efficiency of electric and magnetic antennas, signal-to-noise ratios,
propagation distance limits, etc.<BR>  A number of experiments were
carried out in water-to- water, water-to-air, and water-to-ground
communication systems. As a result wireless underwater speech
communication for divers, underwater telemetric system, and an
underwater short-range orientation system were designed and successfully
tested: .
</P><P><B>7. Directional Hearing in Dolphins</B>
</P><P> Auditory brainstem response to sound clicks from sources at
different positions were recorded in dolphins by Dr. Supin research
group from the Severtsov Institute Of Evolutionary Animal Morphology And
Ecology, RAS, in Moscow.<BR>  The position of the dolphin's "acoustic
window" was determined by measurements of acoustic delays. The acoustic
window was found to lie close to the auditory meatus and the bulla
rather than on the lower jaw.<BR>  A wave observed in the auditory
brainstem responses was found to be sensitive to the side of sound
presentation. Dependence of the wave threshold on location of the sound
source showed that the interaural intensity difference in dolphins was
more than 20 dB<BR>  Binaural hearing mechanisms were studied in
dolphins. It was shown that the azimuth position of a sound source at
10-15 degrees from the longitudinal axis elicited interaural intensity
disparities up to 20 dB and interaural latency differences as large as
250 microseconds. The latency differences are proposed to be an
effective way of intensity disparity coding.
</P><P><B>8. Next Steps</B>
</P><P> Russian scientists are interested in collaboration at all
levels, from conferences to short visits, to joint projects. ONR Europe
has funds to support European scientists' visits in the US government
and academic laboratories. Proposals can be submitted by individual
scientists upon request.<BR>  The Russian Foundation for Basic Research
(see European Newsletter #1) proposed to match DOD funding of the
projects they recommended. They could also match funding of workshops
and conferences.<BR>  There is a tremendous opportunity for US
government agencies and industry to leverage the enormous scientific
resources in Russian academic institutions. The current window of
opportunity has to be used expeditiously as conditions in academic
institutions deteriorate rapidly.
</P><P><B>9. Personal Contacts</B>
</P><P> Altman Jacob A. M.D., Ph.D., Dr.S.,<BR>  Head, Hearing
Physiology Lab <BR>  I.P.Pavlov Institute of Physiology, <BR>  6
Makarova nab. St Petersburg, 199034, Russia
</P><P> Baron Vladimir D., Ph.D<BR>  International Scientific<BR> 
Environmental Centre<BR>  Russian Academy of Science<BR>  51
Ulianovskaya<BR>  Moscow 109004<BR>  Russia
</P><P> Chernigovskaya Tatiana V., Ph.D., Dr.Sc<BR> . Dept of
Comparative Physiology of Sensory Systems <BR>  I. Sechenov Institute
of Evolutionary Physiology<BR>  and Biochemistry of Russian Academy of
Science <BR>  44 M M. Thorez <BR>  St. Ptersburg 194223 Russia
</P><P> Dubrovsky Nikolay Andreevich, Prof.,<BR>  academician and
Director <BR>  (Pres. Russian Acoust. Soc.) <BR>  N.N. Andreev
Acoustic Institute <BR>  4 Shvernik Street <BR>  117036 Moscow, Russia
</P><P> Frolov Yu. prof, Ph.D., Dr.S.<BR>  Institute of Higher Nervous
<BR>  Activity & Neurophysiology<BR>  Russian Acad of Science <BR> 
5a Butlerova Street <BR>  117865, Moscow Russia
</P><P> Supin Alexander Ya., Prof., Ph.D. Dr.Sc.<BR>  Head, Lab of
Sensory Systems<BR>  Severtsov Institute of Evolutionary <BR> 
Morphology and Ecology of Animals <BR>  Russian Academy of Science <BR>
 33 Leninsky Prosp. <BR>  Moscow 117071 Russia
</P><P></P><P>For more information on this topic contact:
</P><P> Igor Vodyanoy, Ph.D. <BR>  Associate Director, Biophysics<BR>
 ONR Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>  London, NW1 5TH<BR> 
England<BR>  Tel: 44-171-514-4131<BR>  Fax: 44-171-723-6359<BR> 
E-mail: ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  Military address: ONREUR, PSC
802 Box 39, FPO AE 09499-0700
</P><P></P>
