<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 6</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY><H3>April 18, 1995<BR>  European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A></H3>

<P><H3>Office of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR> 
Newsletter No. 6
</H3></P><P> <H3>Review of Sensory Biology & Biosensors Science &
Technology in Russia</H3>
</P><P><H4>Office of Naval Research Europe announces a Workshop-Review
"Sensory Biology And Biosensors"</H4>
</P><P> The workshop will be held in Moscow at the Institute of
Biophysics, and in St. Petersburg, Russia in November of 1995. 
</P><P><I>Objective: Review of the state-of-the-art Russian sensory
biology and biosensors science and technology.</I>
</P><P> Nature has evolved extremely sensitive and versatile sensory
systems for detection of practically any minute change in environment
trace chemicals, electromagnetic fields (and light), and sound. It can
combine extreme sensitivity with amplification and selectivity. 
</P><P> In 1994, the first US-Russian Workshop on Sensory Biology was
held at the University of Maryland at College Park. The workshop was
supported by the Department of Personnel Optimization and Biomolecular
Sciences and Technologies of the Office of Naval Research. It became
clear during the workshop that Russian scientists developed original and
unique approaches to many of the sensory transduction problems. 
</P><P> The Review workshop will allow US science managers to become
familiar with the research progress, to discuss how the work can be
applied for development of man-made sensors, and to review the latest
accomplishments of Russian scientists in applied research in biosensors.
</P><P> The workshop will be hosted by the Biophysics Institute in
Puschino and by the Institute of Evolutionary Physiology & Biochemistry
in St. Petersburg 
</P><P> * * THOSE OF YOU INTERESTED IN BIOSENSORS & SENSORY BIOLOGY: *
* <BR>  * * ONR, ARPA, NSF, NIH, NIST, Air Force, Army, others. * *
<BR>  * * WE INVITE YOU TO PARTICIPATE !!!!!! * *<BR>  * * YOU WILL BE
ABLE TO MAKE SITE VISITS * *<BR>  * * TO THE LABS OF YOUR INTEREST
WHILE AT THE REVIEW * *
</P><P> Preliminary Program: 
</P><P><B>Sensory Biology</B><BR>  
</P><OL>
<LI>Vision <BR>  Byzov - neural networks <BR>  Shevelev - vision
mechanisms<BR>  Ostrovsky - photoreceptors <BR>  Gribakin -
photoreception (insects) <BR>  
</LI>
<LI>Hearing, Mechanoreception  Altman - perception (human, fish)<BR> 
Popov - perception (insects) <BR>  Akoev - mechanoreception<BR>  Supin
- marine mammals<BR>  
</LI>
<LI>Electroreception <BR>   Baron - weak electric fish<BR>  Akoev -
mechanisms   
</LI>
<LI>Sensory Perception, learning  Frolov - speech analysis <BR> 
Dubrovsky - neural networks hearing perception<BR>  Altman -
perception, hearing human<BR>  Chernigovskaya - learning models  
</LI> 
</OL><P><B>Biosensors</B> 
</P><OL>
<LI>Chemical Yevdokimov - DNA based <BR>  Varfolomeev -
electrochemical, receptor-based<BR>  Kurochkin - piesoelectric, optical
fibers<BR>  Yaropopov - enzyme amperometrical<BR>  Gachurin - neural
receptors <BR>  Simonyan - cell based, metabolytes  
</LI>
<LI>Photosensors  Kazanskaya - photochromic Lukashev - photoreceptor
proteins <BR>  Ostrovsky - damage from light  
</LI>
<LI>Nanotechnology Bykov(Zelenograd)- STM <BR>  Kurochkin - STM, AFM  

</LI>
<LI>Electrosensors Baron & all - sensors basedon electric fish  
</LI> 
</OL><P>Workshop is organized by: <BR>  Academician Michael Ostrovsky
(ostrovsky@enh.nist.gov)<BR>  Dr. Yuri Yevdokimov (yevd@imb.msk.su)<BR>
 Dr. Tatiana Chernigovskaya (chern@ief.spb.su) <BR>  Dr. Igor Vodyanoy
(ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil) 
</P><P> Russian Foundation for Basic Science is contributing $3,000.
ONR Europe will fund the workshop running costs, conference facilities
use, and organization. 
</P><P> Excursions - on the "day-off" will be organised on site. The
price of a ticket to the Hermitage (Winter Palace) is now around $8. A
ticket to Mariinsky Ballet (the former Kirov Ballet) is around $40. The
tickets for the excursions to suburban palaces are around $10 The
registration fee for the conference will be around $300.
</P><P></P><P>For more information on this topic contact:
</P><P> Igor Vodyanoy, Ph.D. <BR>  Associate Director, Biophysics<BR>
 ONR Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>  London, NW1 5TH<BR> 
England<BR>  Tel: 44-171-514-4131<BR>  Fax: 44-171-723-6359<BR> 
E-mail: ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  Military address: ONREUR, PSC
802 Box 39, FPO AE 09499-0700
</P><P></P>
