<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 7</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY><H3>May 29, 1995<BR>  European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A></H3>

<P><H3>Office of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR> 
Newsletter No. 7
</H3></P><P> <H3>Scanning Ion-Conductance Microscopy</H3>
</P><P><B>Contents</B> 
</P><OL>
<LI>Summary  
</LI>
<LI>Scanning Ion-Conductance Microscopy of living cells  
</LI>
<LI>Personal contact  
</LI> 
</OL><P><B>1. Summary </B>
</P><P> A novel approach for exploring topographical and functional
characteristics of living cells and to study the electrochemistry of
biocorrosion or spatial electrochemistry of membanes or electrodes using
Scanning Ion Conductance Microscopy has been developed by scientists in
England. This unique instrument has enormous potential for cellular
studies. It expands the capabilities of conventional 'patch- clamp'
technology, and allows real-time imaging and micro- manipulation of
living cells. 
</P><P><B>2. Scanning Ion-Conductance Microscopy</B>
</P><P> It was used for the first time to image ultra-soft samples such
as living animal or human cells in physiological solutions. The high
resolution images captured by this microscope resemble those obtained by
scanning electron microscopy of fixed and shadowed material - the
significant difference being that in this system, the cells remain
viable and active. 
</P><P> This instrument consists of a computer-controlled three-axis
translation stage with measurement and feedback systems. The x and y
axes of the translation stage are driven so as to scan the probe over
the specimen, while recording measurements of some parameter of interest
using the probe. In this system, the probe consists of a micropipette
similar to those used in the patch-clamp technique. The position of the
tip, in relation to the local sample surface, strongly influences the
ion flow through the pipette. This ion current can be used as a feedback
signal, to control the vertical axis of the positioning system, so as to
ensure that the sample and probe do not come into contact with one
another. 
</P><P> The unique capabilities of this microscope allowed studies of
cellular damage and death induced by pore-forming agents, including the
toxins produced by certain pathogenic bacteria (Korchev, Y.E. et al.
(1995) J. Membrane Biol. 143: 143-151). 
</P><P> Further development of this technique will provide technology
which will have far-reaching impact on a wide range of research topics.
At the fundamental level, for example, it will enable studies of the
electro-chemistry of membrane surfaces, by using multi-barrelled
pipettes to scan topography, simultaneously measuring local ion
concentration by employing another of the barrels as an ion-selective
electrode. On higher levels, it will enable exploration of the
topography and specific functions of cell-cell interactions, such as
neural networks or other multicellular systems where cell contacts are
essential for system properties. 
</P><P><B>3. Personal Contact</B>
</P><P> Dr. Yuri E. Korchev <BR>  Department of Cellular and Molecular
Sciences <BR>  St. George's Hospital Medical School <BR>  Cranmer
Terrace <BR>  London, SW17 ORE <BR>  Telephone: 44-181-725-5776 <BR> 
FAX: 44-181-725-2992 <BR>  E-mail: korchev@sghms.ac.uk 
</P><P></P><P>The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to
providing current information on science and technology development in
European countries. In order to better meet your needs, our Associate
Directors and Scientists are very much interested in knowing what your
specific science and technology interests are. Please let me know what
they are.
</P><P> Furthermore, if there are others who you are aware of that have
interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail address to me
and I will add them to the distribution list. 
</P><P> For more information on this topic contact:
</P><P> Igor Vodyanoy, Ph.D. <BR>  Associate Director, Biophysics<BR>
 ONR Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>  London, NW1 5TH<BR> 
England<BR>  Tel: 44-171-514-4131<BR>  Fax: 44-171-723-6359<BR> 
E-mail: ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  Military address: ONREUR, PSC
802 Box 39, FPO AE 09499-0700
</P><P></P>
