<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 9</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY><H3>August 22, 1995<BR>  European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A></H3>

<P><H3>Office of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR> 
Newsletter No. 9</H3>
</P><P> <H3>Underwater Television, Adaptive Mirrors, and UV Biosensor
from Russia</H3>
</P>
<OL>
<LI>Summary  
</LI>
<LI>Underwater television (and seeing through a snow storm)  
</LI>
<LI>Mirror, mirror on the ... piesoelectric.  
</LI>
<LI>UV biosensor  
</LI>
<LI>Next steps  
</LI>
<LI>Personal contacts  
</LI> 
</OL><P><B>1. Summary</B>
</P><P> This report is about some revolutionary and novel vision
devices and optics technology. A biosensor for detectiing UV radiation
based on bacterial proteins is described. These attracted my attention
because of their potential applications in both military and civilian
sectors.
</P><P><B>2. Underwater Television (and seeing through a snow storm)</B>
</P><P> Several unique optical devices were demonstrated in March at
the International Maritime Defence Exhibition and Conference 95 (IMDEX
95) in Greenwich. Developers of these devices from Turn Ltd., a S&T;
company based in Russia, call them Laser Vision Systems (LVS). The
Russian ship-building industry has a special program that will deploy
LVSs on ships and submersible vehicles. Japan is also interested in
installing the underwater television onto their submersibles.<BR>  The
Underwater LSV that was demonstrated at IMDEX 95 extends the television
vision range to 150m (550ft) in the turbid atlantic water! The device
consists of a sensitive (0.002 lx) CCD camera (6 pounds), green laser
(580 nm, 300 W, 12kg), special electronics block, and a monitor. The
camera is synchronised with the laser's pulses. The undisputed advantage
of this method is that vision is not distorted by moving particles or
bubbles. A device similar in principle but for vision in the air (with
red lasers forming a rectangular field of vision) is already in use in
Siberia. A few units were installed on tractors working in oil fields,
where during the winter, snowstorms make it hard to see one's own hand
at arms length. The device is rugged, and can work in extreme
temperatures. The vision distance is extended to 300m (1,100 ft).
</P><P><B>3. Mirror, mirror on the ... piesoelectric</B>
</P><P> The Turn, Ltd. also demonstrated an optoelectronic device
designed to control the radiation wavefront in laser or other optical
systems. The control is accomplished by means of curvature radius change
as the control voltage applied to the piesoelectric understructure. This
"mirror" can be controlled dynamically (resonance frequency is about 3
KHz) and with high precision (there are 18 elements! with sensitivity of
1.5 um/kV). Reflectance (at 10.6 um) is 98.5 for copper and 98.1 for
molybdenum. The light zone is 50mm in diameter. Total shape distortion
is about 316.4 nm. There are numerous applications of this device from
industrial lasers to dynamic abberation correction in photographic
cameras.
</P><P><B>4. UV Biosensor</B>
</P><P> A simple biosensor for ultraviolet light intensity has been
developed at the Institute of Chemical Physics in Moscow, Russia. The
light-sensitive component of this sensor is a photochromic film made of
the light-sensitive protein bacteriorhodopsin and its analogues. This
film is superior to any traditional photochromic materals (organic or
non-organic dyes). The sensitivity of the film can reach 1mW/cm sq. and
it can be cycled through the light-dark periods millions of times
without any decrease of initial optical density. The film is purple and
changes its color (within a few seconds of exposure) depending on the
light spectra and the nature of the bacteriorhodopsin analogue used.<BR>
 The biosensor could be made as a strip of this film embedded into
transparent plastic. The device can detect if radiation is dangerous for
human eyes and skin. If made out of photochromic film with different
sensitivities, it could read light intensity. No power source is needed.
The sensor can also be extremely inexpensive (0.25 mg of protein needed
for the sensor can be produced in Russia for about ten cents)
</P><P><B>5. Next steps</B>
</P><P> Russian scientists are interested in collaboration at all
levels, from conferences to short visits, to joint projects. ONR Europe
has funds to support European scientists' visits in the US government
and academic laboratories. Proposals can be submitted by individual
scientists upon request.
</P><P><B> 6. Personal contacts</B>
</P><P> Turn Ltd<BR>  PO Box 19, Moscow<BR>  Centre 103104, Russia<BR>
  Phone: 095-299-8122<BR>  FAX: 095-292-6511
</P><P> Academician M. Ostrovsky<BR>  Institute of Chemical Physics<BR>
  Russian Academy of Sciences<BR>  4 Kosygin St.,117334 Moscow<BR> 
Russia<BR>  Phone: 095-939-7357<BR>  FAX: 095-938-2156 
</P><P></P><P>The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to
providing current information on science and technology development in
European countries. In order to better meet your needs, our Associate
Directors and Scientists are very much interested in knowing what your
specific science and technology interests are. Please let me know what
they are. 
</P><P> Furthermore, if there are others who you are aware of that have
interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail address to me
and I will add them to the distribution list. 
</P><P> For more information on this topic contact:
</P><P> Igor Vodyanoy, Ph.D. <BR>  Associate Director, Biophysics<BR>
 ONR Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>  London, NW1 5TH<BR> 
England<BR>  Tel: 44-171-514-4131<BR>  Fax: 44-171-723-6359<BR> 
E-mail: ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  Military address: ONREUR, PSC
802 Box 39, FPO AE 09499-0700
</P><P></P>
