<HEAD><TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 11</TITLE>
</HEAD>  
<BODY>
<H3>
September 6, 1995<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/vodyanoy.htm">
Igor Vodyanoy</A><P>

Office of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR>
Newsletter No. 11<P>
Biological antifouling</H3>

<B>Contents:</B>
 <PRE>
Summary
Antifouling in echinoderms
Personal contact
</PRE>

<B>1. Summary</B><P>
     Echinoderms have surfaces remarkably free of fouling
organisms such as bacteria and algae. As part of research
funded by the Marine Technology Directorate (UK) and the
European Commission MAST II program to apply natural
antifouling mechanisms to the development of novel
technologies for the protection of marine sensors, the group
at Dunstaffnage Marine Laboratory (DML) has been studying
the properties of the echinoderm surface.<P>

<B>2. Antifouling in echinoderms</B><P>
     How echinoderms maintain the fouling-free surface is of
wide interest as there is a need to develop effective, non-
polluting, antifouling technologies. Investigations have
been made of the chemical structure of the echinoid surface
coats (cuticle). As little is known concerning surface coats
other than their ultrastructure, the research has
concentrated on the physico-chemical properties of the
echinoderm surface. The surface coats are extremely thin and
closely attached to each other and the underlying epidermis.<BR>
     Scanning electron microscopy was used to look at spines
without any treatment, and after incubation at 50 C with
pronase E. The glycocalyx was intact on untreated spines,
whereas spines treated with pronase E completely lacked
glycocalyx, although surface cells and some cuticle was
still observed.  The results suggest that one hour of
incubation with small amounts of protease is enough to
damage the surface coat of spines. Those damaged spines are
easily susceptible to fouling with bacteria or algae.<BR>
     The chemistry of the surface coats, particularly the
glycocalyx, is similar to mucus secretions released from the
animal. A sensitive method to do in situ labelling has been
developed and this has allowed aspects of the chemical
composition of the surface coats to be investigated.<BR>
     Enzymatic treatment of modified spines indicates that
most of the modified carboxyl groups belong to the protein
and or glycoprotein molecules, situated on the surface of
the sea urchin spines. The general results to dual
radiolabelling experiments provide a half turnover time of
the surface coat of approximately twenty five days. This
would be too long to be an effective method of removing
fouling but it must be remembered that the tumover time
relates to all of the surface coats (and the epidermal
surface). The turnover rate of the fuzzy coat alone may be
radically different.<P>

<B>3. Personal contacts</B><P>
Group at the Dunstaffnage Marine Laboratory<BR>
P.O. Box 3, Oban, Argyll, PA34 4AD, Scotland<BR>
Tel: 01634-56-2244<BR>
Fax: 01631-56-5518<BR>
J D McKenzie<BR>
Scottish Association for Marine Science (SAMS)<BR>
M S Kelly<BR>
SAMS Mobil Research<BR>
Fellows:<BR>
I V Grigolava  SAMS<BR>
F Cerfolli          University of Lecce<BR>
L Newton       Napier University<P>

<P><HR><P>
 
