<HEAD><TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 12</TITLE>
</HEAD>  
<BODY>
<H3>
September 20, 1995<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/vodyanoy.htm">
Igor Vodyanoy</A><P>

Office of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR>
Newsletter No. 12<P>
Underwater Acoustic Imaging System</H3>

<B>Contents:</B>
 <PRE>
Summary
Underwater Acoustic Imaging System
Personal contact
</PRE>


<B>1. Summary</B><P>
     An Underwater Acoustic Image System (referred to as to
the Sonovision Set by the inventors) was developed at the
Andreev's Acoustical Institute in Moscow. The system is
based on the Sokolov Tube - an approach that has had a long
history of research in Russia, but which has received only
modest attention in the US. The system is capable of
resolving down to 0.5 degrees with a field of vision of 40
degrees at a working distance of 20 meters.  The system was
field tested to obtain images of steel pipes, wood beams,
and human divers.<P>

 <B>2. Underwater Acoustic Imaging System</B><P>
     An acoustical image of an object comes into view as
result of object "illumination" by two ultrasonic
transducers. This image is focused by a specially developed
Piezoelectric Element Matrix (PEM) lens.  The PEM lens is
made from a piezoceramic disk with a half-wave thickness at
1.0 MHz frequency. Grooves are cut into the lens surface at
a depth of about 2/3 plate thickness, making about 1000
square elements with sides of 1 mm. Each element is
electrically connected with a glass-metallofiber faceplate
of vacuum cathode-ray tube or Cathode-Ray Converter (CRC).
The combination of the PEM and CRC, named the Acoustic
Electron-Ray Converter (AERC or Sokolov Tube), is the main
component of the imaging system described. The electrical
potential distribution on the back surface of the PEM is
carried to the inner surface of the CRC. An electron beam
scanning this surface converts the electrical image into a
time dependent output signal that can be processed and
displayed as an image. The system has being designed to have
minimal geometric distortions, taking into consideration the
diffraction spot diameter and piezoelements' size.     This
device was first developed by Prof. S. Sokolov (Sokolov,
S.Y.- US Pat.2164125(1937)). In 1955, the  first successful
experiments were carried at the Andreev' Institute.<BR>
     Prof. Kazantsev has described this device at the recent
ONR Workshop on Ultrasonic Imaging Transducers in England.<P>

 <B>3. Personal Contact</B><P>
Dr. Kazantsev Vsevolod F.,<BR>
N.N. Andreev`s<BR>
Acoustical Institute,<BR>
Shvernik str.4,<BR>
117036 Moscow, Russia.

<P><HR><P>
 
