<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 15</TITLE></HEAD>              
                       
<BODY>   <H3>October 13, 1995<BR> European Biophysics
<BR><A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A>  <P></P> Office Of Naval
Research-European Office Biophysics<BR>Newsletter No. 15
<P></P>Radioprotective Peptides from Tortoise</H3>  
<P><B>Contents:</B></P>
<PRE>
1. Summary
2. Research description
3. Point of contact</PRE> 
<P><B>1. SUMMARY</B></P>       <P>Collaborative work in England and
Uzbekistan has demonstrated that  extracts of various tissues of the the
middle Asian tortoise amplifies  radioresistance in mice subjected to a
normally lethal whole body dose of  radiation.</P> 
<P><B>2. RESEARCH DESCRIPTION</B></P>       The middle Asian tortoise
is a remarkable animal.  It exists in a  quiescent state for up to 10
months of the year, surviving on glycogen  stored in the liver during
its active phase.  Of greatest interest, however,  is the fact that it
can survive a whole body dose of ionizing radiation  100-fold greater
than any other known living creature.<BR>      A search for the
explanation of this extreme radioresistance has been  the subject of
joint studies between Peter Quinn, Professor of Biochemistry  at King's
College, London, and Azim Turdiyev at the Institute of  Biochemistry of
the Uzbek Academy of Sciences, Tashkent.<BR>      The most important
discovery to date has been a demonstration that  extracts of various
tissues of the tortoise promote recovery from radiation  damage in mice
subjected to a normally lethal whole body dose of radiation;  in these
experiments, mice were irradiated with gamma radiation.<BR>      One
group of irradiated mice was injected intraperitoneally with an  extract
of tortoise spleen and their survival and haemopoietic functions  over
30 days post-irradiation were compared with a second group given an 
injection of saline.  Only 5% of the control group were alive after 8
days  whereas more than 80% of the treated animals survived compared to
a group of  non-irradiated mice.  The spleen weight of the surviving
animals was the  same as non-irradiated mice after this time but there
was a dramatic  proliferation of spleen colonies.  There was also a
doubling of mitotic  cells in the bone marrow.  Over a 30 day period,
recovery of white cell  populations in surviving mice was significantly
enhanced by administering of  spleen extract.<BR>      The nature of
the experiment determined that the subject mice received  no immediate
radiation damage protection from the spleen extract; this was  confirmed
when the decrease in blood cell populations during the initial  phase
following irradiation was found to be almost identical to mice that  had
not received the extract.  It was the normal appearance of the 
proliferating cells repopulating the blood  and the lack of  evidence of
 anomolous mitosis typical of damaged cells that were encouraging to 
researchers.<BR>      The results have led to the suggestion that
spleen factors present in  the tortoise extract were responsible for the
proliferation of  undifferentiated stem cells that had survived
irradiation and their  differentiation into observable erythroid and
granulocytic cell lines in the  bone marrow on day 8 post-irradiation.<BR>
      Some progress has been made toward identifying those factors
present in  extracts of spleen and other tissues of the tortoise
responsible for  conferring radioresistance to mammals.  These turn out
to be a family of  small, unusual peptides derived from progenitor
molecules present in the  extracts, and are quite different from the
high-molecular-weight Stem Cell  Growth Factors present in regenerating
calf spleen that demonstrate  radioprotective activity.<BR>      The
mechanism of protection also appears to be different from that 
attributed to cytokines - e.g., interlukin-1, TNF or immunostimulants,
all  of which must be present prior to irradiation.  Individual peptides
appear  to play different roles in rescuing the surviving stem cells. 
Some have  been shown to stimulate repair of DNA in human lymphocytes
damaged by  exposure to gamma-radiation; others are more effective as
cell-proliferation  agents.<BR>      Future studies are planned to
characterize and chemically synthesize  each of the bioactive peptides. 
Their effect on animals treated with  chemotherapeutic cancer agents
will also be examined.  Collaboration with  other researchers with
relevant interests and available funding is currently  being sought.<P></P>
  <P><B>3. POINT OF CONTACT:</B></P>  Prof. Peter Quinn<BR>  Division
of Life Sciences<BR>  King's College London<BR>  London W8 7AH<BR>
United Kingdom<BR>  E-mail: udbc600@bay.cc.kcl.ac.uk<P></P><HR><P> 
The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to   providing current
information on science and technology   development in European
countries.  In order to better meet   your needs, our Associate
Directors and Scientists are very   much interested in knowing what your
specific science  and  technology interests are.  Please let me know
what they are.</P> <P>  Furthermore, if there are others who you are
aware of that   have interest in these newsletters, please pass their
e-mail   address to me and I will add them to the distribution list.
</P><P>
For more information on this topic contact:</P><P>Igor Vodyanoy, Ph.D. 
 <BR>  Associate Director, Biophysics<BR> ONR Europe<BR> 223 Old
Marylebone Road<BR> London, NW1 5TH<BR> England<BR> Tel:   
44-171-514-4131<BR> Fax:    44-171-723-6359<BR> E-mail:
ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil<BR> Military address: ONREUR, PSC 802 Box 39,
FPO AE 09499-0700</P><P></P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm"
