<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 16</TITLE>
</HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>
February 13, 1996<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A><P> 

Office Of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR>  
Newsletter No. 16<P>

Science in Armenia</H3>
In November,1995 the visit to Armenia was made jointly by
scientists from the Office of Naval Research Europe and the Air Force
Research and Development European Office. There will be additional
newsletters giving more details on institutions, science and people from
this country. <P><B>Contents:</B>
</P><P></P><PRE>
1. Summary
2. Background
3. The Armenian National Academy of Science
4. Call for help from Armenia
</PRE>
<P><B>1. SUMMARY</B>
</P><P> Some of the Armenian research facilities that we visited were
found to be doing outstanding, world-class work. Institutes and the
universities have done a remarkable job of maintaining their
infrastructure and potential during the worst of times, and are
optimistic that the international scientific community will recognize
the value of what they have to offer. The institutes use the typical
Soviet scientific model of having both testing and engineering
facilities to follow-up on basic scientific results. We feel very
strongly that the timing is optimum for the U.S. academic, government,
and industrial researchers to form a strong, lasting relationship with
Armenian scientists and institutes for the benefit of both of our
countries.
</P><P><B>2. BACKGROUND</B>
</P><P> Armenia has a population of only 3.3 million people, but has a
strong tradition of scientific excellence and was likely the third
largest contributor to research within the USSR, following Russia and
Ukraine. In recent years, however, the resilience and determination of
the country to maintain its scientific infrastructure has been put to
the test. In December 1988, an earthquake devastated the northern
portion of the country killing 55,000 people and swelling the capital,
Yerevan, with refugees. After the breakup of the Soviet Union in 1991,
this land-locked country found itself geographically and politically
isolated. Armenia went to war with its neighbor, Azerbaijan, over
control of Nagorno-Karabakh and region within Azerbaijan populated by
ethnic Armenians. Consequently, Armenia's neighbors, Iran and Turkey,
enforced total land blockades along their borders while Armenia's one
remaining neighbor, Georgia, was deeply embroiled in a civil war. For
the first few years of its newfound independence, virtually any imports
and exports had to be transferred by air. The country's nuclear power
station shut down during the earthquake and a lack of natural fuel
resources led to long periods of power outages, including the cold
winter seasons. In less than three years, the value of currency
decreased by a factor of more than 100,000 while prices of many consumer
goods inflated rapidly to western levels.
</P><P> Today, however, Armenia takes pleasure from relative stability
and a confident outlook towards the future. There is a cease-fire with
Azeibarjan and the land blockades are loosening. The civil war in
Georgia has ended, Armenia's nuclear power station recently re-opened,
and their currency, the dram, has held a constant rate of exchange
against the dollar for more than a year. Economically, however, Armenia
still has a long way to go, but is westernizing quickly and has
attracted more foreign aid from the U.S. per capita than any other
country in the world besides Israel. Although they were the first of the
former Soviet republics to introduce privatization and economic reform,
a typical research scientist for the Academy of Science earns a base
salary of only $8.50 per month -- half that of a scientist in Ukraine,
and ten times less than a scientist in Russia. Scientists are also
frustrated by frequent power outages, and in some cases, loss of power
due to the inability of institutes to pay the bills. A majority of the
institutes and universities are virtually unheated and will be closed
completely during the coldest winter months.
</P><P><B>3. THE ARMENIAN NATIONAL ACADEMY OF SCIENCE</B>
</P><P> The Academy was founded in 1943 as the primary coordinator of
basic research within the Republic. The Academy is composed of 34
institutes, and is divided into departments of Physico-Mathematical and
Technical Sciences, Natural Sciences, and Humanities. Approximately
4,000 researchers work among the various institutes--about 1,500 fewer
than five years ago. Economic conditions have lowered governmental
funding to less than one million dollars annually, causing increasing
emphasis on the need to attract outside funding sources. Last year 428
researchers within the Academy received Soros grants, giving them the
largest number of any FSU country except Russia.
</P><P><B>4. CALL FOR HELP FROM ARMENIA</B>
</P><P> The biggest problem facing Armenian science is information
exchange, according to Academician Fadey T. Sarkissian, the President of
the Academy of Sciences. Power disruptions, a blockade by neighboring
countries, and financial woes make it difficult for the Armenians to
receive or send out scientific information. They require support to
publish and distribute several monographs and books on a wide variety of
scientific subjects. They would like to receive scientific journals,
magazines, and papers. If any of my readers have suggestions or ideas to
help the Armenians, please contact the Office of Naval Research Europe.<P>
</P>  The Armenian Academy of Sciences is situated at  <BR>Marshall
Baghramian Avenue 24  <BR>37019 Yerevan, Republic of Armenia<BR>  Tel
+3742 527031;Fax +374 39 06867<BR>  E-mail: academy@pnas.sci.am
</P><P></P><P> The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to
providing current information on science and technology development in
European countries. In order to better meet your needs, our Associate
Directors and Scientists are very much interested in knowing what your
specific science and technology interests are. Please let me know what
they are.
</P><P>Furthermore, if there are others who you are aware of that have
interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail address to me
and I will add them to the distribution list. </P><P>For more
information on this topic contact:
</P><P>Igor Vodyanoy, Ph.D. <BR>  Associate Director, Biophysics<BR> 
ONR Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>  London, NW1 5TH<BR> 
England<BR>  Tel: 44-171-514-4131<BR>  Fax: 44-171-723-6359<BR> 
E-mail: ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil<BR>  Military address: ONREUR, PSC
802 Box 39, FPO AE 09499-0700
</P><P></P>
<HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to
ONREUR Newsletters</A>
</P></BODY></HTML>

