<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 17</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>
February 21, 1996<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A><P> 

Office Of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR> 
Newsletter No. 17 <P> 

Physics, Lasers and Optics from Armenia </H3> 
<P></P><PRE>
<B>Contents:</B>
1. Summary
2. Institute of Applied Problems in Physics
3. Institute of Radiophysics and Electronics
4. Physical Research Institute
5. Laserayan Tekhinica Armenia
6. Points of contact
</PRE>
<P><B>1. SUMMARY</B><BR>  In November, 1995, scientists from the
Office of Naval Research Europe and the European Office of Aerospace
Research and Development jointly visited some physics and laser research
facilities in Armenia.<BR>  Intriguing work on low frequency acoustic
lasers, X-ray generation enhancement by acoustic waves, novel materials
for lasers, rotation detectors with a resolution of 0.3 arcsec and 22
bits of accuracy, lidars for remote environmental sensing, facilities
capable of growing high- quality doped and undoped crystals and optical
materials, and high-power lasers are just a few examples of science and
technology described in this letter.<BR>  We feel very strongly that
the timing is excellent for the U.S. academic, government, and
industrial researchers to form an effective, stable connection with
Armenian scientists and institutes advantageous to both of our
countries.
</P><P><B>2. INSTITUTE OF APPLIED PROBLEMS IN PHYSICS</B><BR>  The
institute maintains strong relations with their Russian counterparts,
Parma University in Italy, Laue- Langevin Institute in Grenoble, France,
Technical University in Munich, Germany, and is building relationships
with American firms such as HP and GM. The Institute has 14 grants from
the International Science Foundation (Soros Foundation).
</P><P> There are three projects involving acoustic waves that were
described to us which seem to be on the whole with or ahead of research
in the west:
</P><P> a. Modulation of x-rays generated by the dispersion of high-
energy electrons or positrons in crystals by acoustic waves. If the
frequency of the applied acoustic wave is tuned to one of the natural
modes of vibration of the particle traversing the crystal, then the
resulting x-ray radiation can be enhanced to the point where it is up to
two times more intense than is available from x-ray tubes. Armenian
scientists have also been experimenting with the generation of radiation
in the UV to hard x-ray region by skimming high-energy particles over
surface acoustic waves.
</P><P> b. Control of instabilities in gas discharge lasers through the
application of acoustic waves. In particular, a longitudinal acoustic
wave has been used to control the temperature and radial temperature
gradient in a discharge column in a low temperature plasma. This work
has the potential to eliminate the need for the high flow rates that are
currently necessary in high-power discharge lasers.
</P><P> c. Generation of monochromatic and coherent acoustic waves with
frequencies in the area of a few Hertz to tens of Hertz. This can be
used to generate a long standing wave which can be used as a sensitive
seismic detector. For instance, they have created a vertical acoustic
wave in lake Sevan. By monitoring the standing wave they claim to have
enough sensitivity to detect a one kiloton explosion in the US.
</P><P> The institute has developed a lightbulb based on plasma
acoustic modulation which requires only 20-25% of the power needed for
conventional fluorescent bulbs of the same output power and contains no
mercury. Electric heaters have been fabricated from a volcanic rock
(natural Armenian resource) that are 20% more efficient than
conventional electric heaters.
</P><P><B>3. INSTITUTE OF RADIOPHYSICS AND ELECTRONICS</B><BR>  This
institute has been heavily involved with the design and fabrication of
frequency-specific wave detectors and applied research in radiophysics,
electronics, and automatic control. The Institute cooperates with Sogang
University in South Korea, Manchester and Warwick Universities in UK,
and Hengstler company in Germany.
</P><P> Lately, much of their focus is on the development of accurate,
sensitive microwave radiometers for wavelengths in the range of 2mm to
30cm, and the use of masers as receivers up to 200 GHz.
</P><P> Present projects are oriented towards the development of
wavelength specific detectors for particular applications. These
include: a 195 GHz high-Tc superconducting detector for mapping ozone
distribution in the atmosphere, millimeter band detectors for
short-range communications and data transfer, 1-50cm band detectors to
measure water content of the soil, 94 GHz detectors for imaging, and
many other. The soil humidity detector is already operational, and is
claimed to be more sensitive than anything on the market.
</P><P> They also have ideas for developing an amplitude and phase
detector for microwaves with a sensitivity ten times better than any
device presently available.
</P><P> Current research is oriented towards the development of new
materials for these detectors. In particular, they are looking at
different semiconductors, superconducting tunnel junctions, and high-Tc
superconductors. They have made some interesting progress in reducing
the number of free carriers in materials like PbTe by using pulsed laser
evaporation to do epitaxy and in developing high-Tc detectors.
</P><P> Prior to the breakup of the Soviet Union, much of their
research and production capabilities were directed toward military
applications. This includes a series of rotation detectors, the largest
of which have a resolution of 0.3 arcsec and 22 bits of accuracy. A 14
bit accurate detector designed for fighter aircraft is available for
purchase at around $500 per sample.
</P><P> They have also developed a six channel, six centimeter
wavelength radiometer to fly on the MIR Space Station.
</P><P> A theoretical model to predict the radiation emitted by charged
particles in random, inhomogeneous media is currently under development
at the institute.
</P><P><B>4. PHYSICAL RESEARCH INSTITUTE</B><BR>  The research in
this institute is devoted to lasers and laser interactions with matter.
The Institute cooperates with the University of Crete in Greece, Rice
University in Houston, Texas US, number of universities in Israel, Japan
and Germany.
</P><P> There is a project on two-photon resonance up-conversion in
metal vapors. This is a potential method for shifting the incident
wavelength into the UV or farther into the IR. In the area of
solid-state lasers, there is a lot of research in the growth and
characterization of solid-state laser materials, mainly oxides. Over 50
different solid-state laser materials have been grown and studied,
including Er and Ho doped crystals. These materials are characterized
according to their spectroscopy, crystal properties, and lasing
characteristics. This expertise has led to the ability to modify some of
the inherent characteristics of the lasing medium such as the lifetime
of the excited state in Er-doped materials.
</P><P> Two years ago the emphasis shifted to the production and
characterization of scintillator materials.
</P><P> There is also a significant amount of research in nonlinear
optical materials and in particular photorefractive materials. The aim
of the photorefractive work is to understand the role of dopants in the
photorefractive effect. They have been doping LiNiO3 with controlled
amounts of Fe, Cu, Zn, and Hf and then studying the properties of the
resulting material.
</P><P> A novel technique for measuring of ultra short pulses has been
developed using the second harmonic generation in non linear crystals
(in collaboration with Hungerian Institute of Physics).
</P><P><B>5. LASERAYAN TEKHINICA ARMENIA</B><BR>  This was and has
every manifestation of becoming again an influential production and
applied research facility for lasers, laser components and laser
systems.
</P><P> The coating facility contains what was state-of-the-art in 1990
Russian evaporative coating chambers which have been maintained during
the last few years of inactivity. Visual inspection of the coatings
indicates that they are of good quality although serious testing would
have to be carried out in order to ensure that this is the case.
</P><P> The crystal growing facility contains a mixture of homemade and
Russian growing chambers which have also been well maintained. They are
not yet in operation due to the irregularity of the electrical supply.
This has supposedly been addressed and they expect to resume operation
in the spring.
</P><P> The crystal growing facility has the ability to grow a variety
of solid-state laser materials either as rods or slabs. They also have
the facilities to grow fluoride crystals such as YLF. We saw examples of
Er-doped Garnet and YAG rods and slabs. Nonlinear crystals are also
grown, cut and coated in this facility. Examples of nonlinear optical
materials are KTP in sizes up to 10 x 12 x 30mm, BBO in sizes up to 6 x
6 x 10mm and LiNbO3 as well as other standard materials.
</P><P> There is expertise in the design and construction of remote
sensing systems and LIDARs. There was an airborne laser fluorimeter on
display in one of the labs that had flown in helicopter was designed to
detect chlorophyll- A and oil spills.
</P><P> Work had also been done on a LIDAR system for remote sensing in
the wavelength range 500- 4500nm. This facility has also designed a YAG
system for the Russian space effort. It was capable of delivering more
than 1 J per pulse at 20 Hz with a pulse width of 10-12 ns. The
divergence of the beam was 0.8 mrad. The size of the laser, excluding
the power supply, was ~5cm x 15cm x 60cm.
</P><P><B>6. POINTS OF CONTACT:</B>
</P><P> INSTITUTE OF APPLIED PROBLEMS IN PHYSICS<BR>  Director: Prof.,
Dr. A. R. Mkrtchyan<BR>  25 Hratchia Nersisian St.<BR>  375014,
Yerevan<BR>  Republic of Armenia<BR>  Phone: 007-8852-24-14-70<BR> 
FAX: 007-8852-26-28-27
</P><P> INSTITUTE OF RADIOPHYSICS AND ELECTRONICS<BR>  Director: Acad.
Radick M. Martirossian<BR>  378410, Ashtarak-2<BR>  Republic of
Armenia<BR>  Phone: 007-8852-28-78-50
</P><P> PHYSICAL RESEARCH INSTITUTE<BR>  Director: Acad. M.
Ter-Mikhaelian<BR>  378410, Ashtarak-2<BR>  Republic of Armenia<BR> 
Phone: 007-8852-28-81-50<BR>  E-mail: ifi@arminco.com
</P><P> LASERAYAN TEKHINICA ARMENIA<BR>  Director: Prof. V. M.
Arutunyan<BR>  21 Shopron St<BR>  Yerevan, 375090<BR>  Republic of
Armenia<BR>  Phone: 007-8852-65-05-82<BR>  FAX: 007-8852-52-23-18
</P><P> The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing
current information on science and technology development in European
countries. In order to better meet your needs, our Associate Directors
and Scientists are very much interested in knowing what your specific
science and technology interests are. Please let me know what they are.
</P><P>Furthermore, if there are others who you are aware of that have
interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail address to me
and I will add them to the distribution list. </P><P>For more
information on this topic contact: </P><P>Igor Vodyanoy, Ph.D. <BR> 
Associate Director, Biophysics<BR>  ONR Europe<BR>  223 Old Marylebone
Road<BR>  London, NW1 5TH<BR>  England<BR>  Tel: 44-171-514-4131<BR>
 Fax: 44-171-723-6359<BR>  E-mail: ivodyanoy@onreur.navy.mil<BR> 
Military address: ONREUR, PSC 802 Box 39, FPO AE 09499-0700 </P><P></P>
