<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 19</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>
March 14, 1996<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A> <P>
Office Of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR> 
Newsletter No. 19 </H3> 
<P>
<H3>Russian Science in 1995</H3> 
<P></P>
<PRE>
<B>Contents:</B>
1. Summary
2. Science support in Russia in 1995
3. Geographical distribution of funds by the Russian Foundation for Basic Research (RFBR)
4. Age distribution of RFBR grant recipients
5. Interview with Deputy Minister Mr. Yakobashvili
6. Example of a renegotiated international program
</PRE>

<B>1. Summary:</B><P>
 In this newsletter, I have collected some facts about
the direction and financial support of  Russian science in
1995, specifically in the area of biotechnology. There are
also geographical and  age distribution statistics of
Russian Foundation for Basic Research (see European
Biophysics  Newsletters <A HREF="HTTP://WWW.EHIS.NAVY.MIL:80/IVNEWS1.HTM"># 1</A>, <A HREF="HTTP://WWW.EHIS.NAVY.MIL:80/IVNEWS14.HTM"># 14</A>) grant recipients. I have
translated the most interesting parts of the interview with
the Russian Ministry of Science and Technology Policy about
international cooperation. The  ministry is developing new
international policy that will control intellectual rights
transfers, and  centralize and control international
agreements, MOUs and contracts, especially in defense
sensitive science and technology. Recently the ministry
renegotiated a few actual contracts and  agreements.
Examples are DOE contracts and a CRDF call for proposals.<P>

<B>2.Science support in Russia in 1995:</B><P>
 According to 1995 statistics from the Russian
Foundation for Basic Research (RFBR), the science budget in
Russia (officially 4% of the federal budget) was divided as
follows:<P>
<PRE>
   Russian Academy of Sciences                     19.5%
   Russian Academy of Medical Sciences              1.7%
   Russian Academy of Agricultural Sciences         2.6%
   Russian Foundation for Basic Research            6.0%
</PRE>
 About 50% of funds from  the Russian Ministry of
Science and Technology Policy (MRSTP) was spent to support
about 60 "centers of Science & Technology".<P>

In biotechnology, these "centers" are:<BR>
"Vector" - virology<BR>
"Applied Biotechnology"<BR>
"Genetics"<BR>
"Bioorganic Chemistry"<BR>
"Biophysics"<BR>
"Immunology"<BR>
"Biomedical" - space<P>

<B>3. The RFBR geographical distribution of funds in 1995 was:</B><P>
<PRE>
   Central Russia (mostly Moscow and Moscow region) 50.0%
   Siberia (Novosibirsk, Tomsk)                     18.0%
   Urals                                             5.0%
</PRE>

 In 1995, RFBR supported about 37 thousand scientists in
government research institutions and 13 thousand at Russian
universities.<P>

<B>4. Age distribution of RFBR grant recipients:</B><P>

Interesting statistics of grants from RFBR but alarming for
Russian scientists:<P>
<PRE>
Age of applicants:  <30   30-35   35-40   40-50  50-60   >60
Applications %:     2.4    6      10      31.5   30.6   19.5
Grants %:           1.3    4.5    8.9     32.2   32.2   20.9
</PRE>
What obviously follows from these statistics is that there
were very few scientists younger than 35 in Russia who
worked in basic research in 1995.<P>

Federal support by RMSTP of Biosciences:<P>
<PRE>
Program      Million Rubles
1. Novel Methods in Biology            14.480
2. Biological Diversity                 4.000
3. Tools for Physical Chemistry
4. Biology and Biotechnology            5.990
5. Human Genome                         8.000
6. Priority Directions in Genetics      6.528
7. International Projects
</PRE>
Each program consists out of 5 to 7 "coordinated projects"
each containing about 100 individual research grants.
A program, Biosensors and Immunosensors, is a part of the
coordinated project called "Enzyme Engineering" within the
Program of Novel Methods in Biology.<P>

Coordinator is<BR>
Chernukha, Boris A.<BR>
Ministry of Science and Technical Policy of Russia<BR>
11 Tverskaya str., Moscow, Russia.<BR>
Phone: (095) 229-9811<BR>
Fax:  (095) 229-1706<P>

<B>5. Interview with Deputy Minister Mr. Yakobashvili: </B><P>

 An interview with the Russian Science and Technology
Deputy Minister Mr. Z. Yakobashvili has  been published
recently by a weekly paper called "Search" (This is analogue
to the US paper "The  Scientist"). The article is called
"Know Your Price".<P>

 Interview was conducted by Mr. Michael Buben.<P>

This is an abbreviated translation of the paper article:<P>

 Biographical data:<BR>
 Zurab Andreevich Yakobashvili, born in 1946 in the
Georgian capital city Tbilisi. Has lived in  Moscow since
1950. Graduated from Moscow University with master's diploma
in Physics in 1970.  After graduation, sent to Central
Economic - Mathematical Institute of Academy of Sciences,
where he started as a researcher and advanced to become a
deputy director. Mr. Yakobashvili has been a Deputy Minister
since 1992.<BR>
 Some facts on RMSTP of 1995:<BR>
 RMSTP has developed, and is prepared to realize in the
near future, a system of federal registration of
international agreements, contracts and MOUs.
The Russian Patent Office and RMSTP has developed a system
of laws for international intellectual rights control that
has been sent for consideration by the Russian legislature.
RMSTP is looking into a program of loans for patenting.<P>


M.B. - What is the role of your ministry in international
cooperation?<P>

To organize an official "system" of cooperation.
To teach foreign partners how to behave properly in Russia
[how to protect the Russian national
interest].<BR>
To help scientists with an official way of taxation and duty
payments.<P>

M.B. -  How were these questions solved last year?<P>

In 1995 we selected and supported 600 international projects
that were initiated by individual institutes and their
foreign partners (mostly US and Germany)<P>

Major interest is in the area of high energy physics,
biotechnology, novel materials, some new directions in
chemistry and, surprisingly, microelectronics.<P>

An exemplary project -  a new center of biomedicine that is
created under the agreement between our ministry and NASA.
During the negotiations we had to refer to Gore -
Chernomyrdin committee decisions.<P>

Another example is a Sino - Russian Center of High
Technologies. We created a system that will protect
intellectual property and will prevent any leaks of
sensitive information.<P>

We would like to take control over any international
cooperation that involves former defense scientists.<P>

In the US there are about 135 laws that control
international cooperation.<P>

We could not bring to closure an agreement on the free
electron laser project with the US (started on initiative of
academician Scrinsky). Vice president Gore told Saltykov
[Russian minister] that the project is too sensitive for the
US defense interests.<P>

Our (Russian) scientists nevertheless are not at all alarmed
by the Navy or Airforce "partners". They are not alarmed
when a team from CIA or Pentagon comes to conduct a seminar
where the Russian side is represented only by scientists;
and these scientists would explain that they carry out
purely basic (not applied) research. Perhaps their foreign
"partners" in epaulets are getting promotions for making
important contributions in purely basic research [sarcasm].<P>

In 1995, our ministry conducted "in a civilized way" 5
seminars with the Academy of Sciences, the Federal Defense
Ministry and NATO's science committee. We have developed
"rules of the game".<P>

M.B. - You have told us that there are 135 special laws in
the US. What do we have in our country?<P>

We have five laws governing property, and a number of
presidential decrees that control areas of dual
technologies.<P>

M.B. - What are the loopholes in our laws?<P>

We do not have organized control over the relationship
between S&T institutions and the federal government. It is a
slow process [to develop it].<BR>
Some of our institution directors were signing contracts
without any understanding of the legal implications.<P>

An example of the above: Our ministry protested a DOE
contract [with the Kurchatov Institute of Nuclear Physics],
after which DOE issued a document that assigned intellectual
rights to us.<P>

However, we would like to have a share in these intellectual
rights on US territory and to take advantage of the
favorable climate for commercial realization of S&T. We also
will have to share these rights on our territory as well.<P>

Mr. Yakobashvili concluded with the following phrase:
We should cooperate internationally in cases where it is
profitable to all sides. Our scientists have to feel that
they are needed not only abroad, but in our country.<P>

<B>6. Example of a renegoiated international program:</B><P>  

Civilian Research & Development Fund Cooperative Grants
Program<P>

Special Notice for Applicants from Russia and Kazakstan<P>

By agreement with the governments of the Russian Federation
and the Republic of Kazakstan, the CRDF is posting the
following notice, which is an amendment to the procedures it
originally announced on November 6, 1995:<P>

Russian and Kazak scientists and specialists who have
participated in defense-related work and who wish to be
included in a proposal to the CRDF, or those who wish to
submit a proposal for financial support of a project related
to conversion problems, are required to first request the
approval of the Ministry of Science of their respective
country. Only those who receive approval may enter into
discussions with potential American partners for preparation
of a joint grant application. This review will be carried
out in accordance with applicable Russian and Kazak
legislation. Please note that all requests for such
preliminary review must be submitted promptly in order to
allow the proposal to be submitted to the CRDF before its
deadline of March 15, 1996.<P>

In addition, all applicants from Russia and Kazakstan are
required to submit their proposals simultaneously to the
CRDF office in Arlington, Virginia, USA (ten copies, one
with original signature) and to their respective Ministry of
Science (one copy) by March 1, 1996.<P>
