<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 20</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>
April 5, 1996<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A><P>

Office Of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR> 
Newsletter No. 20 <P> 

Neural Calibration</H3> 
<P></P>
<PRE>
<B>Contents:</B>
1. Summary
2. Multi-Sensory Neural Calibration
3. Point of contact
</PRE>

<B>1. Summary</B><BR>
Some virtual reality systems are rather realistic in particular domains of 
activity (e.g. flight or driving simulators). However, they do not include 
any facility for self-motion. Dr. Pelah from Cambridge University has 
recently obtained novel and unique experimental data that will help to 
relate pseudo - to real motion. With these, sensations of locomotion can be 
enhanced, retarded or altered in specific ways, by using these new motion 
after-effects.<P>

<B>2. Multi-Sensory Neural Calibration</B><BR>
The human nervous system continuously monitors and integrates a large number 
of sensory messages (i.e. from motor, vision, etc.). If each message at 
every instance in time was of equal importance, this task would probably be 
intractable, because of the massively large number of possible inputs that 
would need to be processed simultaneously. Fortunately, the statistical 
distributions of sensory message types are highly correlated. For example, 
in human locomotion, proprioceptive inputs that signal motor activity for a 
given degree of effort, such as walking or running, would be correlated with 
corresponding inputs that signal visual flow; that is, the faster one moves 
the faster the world is seen to rush by.  Thus, for a given type of 
activity, associations of a kind are likely to be made between signal these 
combinations of sensory sources.  When the activity changes, so must the 
associations, and it follows that because the time course of re-association 
is finite, after-effects and illusions occurring during such re-calibration 
may be observed.  Dr. Pelah has recently confirmed this by discovering a 
class of visual after-effects following motor-visual association during 
treadmill running and other activities.<P>

To include a facility for self-motion in virtual reality, one must first be 
aware of the perceptual processes taking place, and the inevitable 
technological limitations.  For instance, a virtual reality system for self 
motion will be contained in a limited space and must therefore rely on 
treadmill-type pseudo self-motion actuators to reproduce as much as possible 
the physical sensations of locomotion; the experience of treadmill 
locomotion is very different from real locomotion. The multi-modal 
association mechanisms outlined above can define correlations between pseudo 
and real locomotion. Thus, self-actions and correlated perceptions which, 
once identified, quantified and functionally understood can contribute to 
the design of effective virtual reality systems.<P>

<B>3. Piont of Contact</B><BR>
Dr A. Pelah,<BR>
Physiological Laboratory,<BR>
University of Cambridge,<BR>
Downing Street, Cambridge<BR>
CB2 3EG,  UK<BR>
Tel +44(0)1223-333-876,<BR>
Fax +44(0)1223-333-840<BR>
E-mail ap114@cam.ac.uk<P>
<HR><P>
The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those
of the author and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P>
