<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 23</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>
June 17, 1996<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A><P>

Office Of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR> 
Newsletter No. 23 <P> 

Russian Science in 1995 Control and Financing</H3> 

<PRE><B>
Contents:</B>
1. Summary
2. Distribution of appropriations for basic research from the federal budget 1995
3. 1995 federal budget appropriations for higher education
4. 1995 allocations for procurement and military R&D
5. Federal program to support science and R&D development
6. Membership of the Russian Federation President's Council for S&T Policy
7. Income of scientists in Russia (How do they survive?)
</PRE>

<B>1.Summary</B><BR>
This newsletter is in response to an overwhelming
number of requests for more information on Russian R&D
sparked by the release of the newsletter "Russian
Science". In this letter, I enumerate federal funds
distributed in the areas of basic science, education,
and military R&D (this time I did not forget about the
conversion factor from the Russian ruble to the US
dollar). I think it would be interesting for you to see
how Russians control their R&D policies. They put
forward a comprehensive program aimed at coordinating
different government agencies (and ministries) and at
integrating Russian R&D into the modern international
environment. Also included is a list of prominent
Russian academicians, industrialists, and scholars who
advise the Russian President on S&T policy. At the end
of this newsletter I also added statistics on incomes
of Russian scientists.<P>

<B>2. Distribution of appropriations for basic research from the Federal Budget 1995</B><BR>
In rubles (4500 = $1 approximately)<P>

Russian Academy of Sciences   687,044,500,000<P>

Siberian Branch of the Russian Academy of Sciences   256,900,000,000<P>

Russian Academy of Medical Sciences      65,300,000,000<P>

Siberian Branch of the Russian Academy of Medical Sciences  16,100,500,000<P>

Urals Branch of the Russian Academy of Sciences      72,800,000,000<P>

Far Eastern Branch of the Russian Academy of Sciences      95,700,000,000<P>

Russian Academy of Education    18,700,000,000<P>

Russian Academy of Architecture and Construction Sciences     2,900,000,000<P>

<B>1995 Budget of</B><BR>
Russian Foundation for Basic Research (RFBR)    404,226,300,000<BR>
RFBR Program:<BR>
Competitive Individual Support Fund for Leading Academic and Scientific Schools  100,000,000,000<BR>
RFBR Program:<BR>
Development of Computer Communications Networks and Data Bases for Basic Science and Education     61,530,000,000<P>

<B>3. 1995 Federal Budget Appropriations for Higher Education</B><BR>
In Rubles<P>

Targeted State Support for the Country's Leading Higher Educational Establishments       300,000,000,000<P>

Other Institutions and Spending in the Educational Sphere of which     332,789,100,000<P>

Measures to Carry Out the Summer Health Campaign    153,000,000,000<P>

<B>4. 1995 Allocations for Procurement and Military R&D</B><BR>
In Rubles (trillion - 10^12)<P>

Purchases of arms and military equipment    10.275 trillion<BR>
Of which,<BR>
repayment of debt for 1994   1.333 trillion<BR>
Research and development    4.936 trillion<BR>
Of which,<BR>
repayment of debt for 1994     666.700 billion<P>

<B>5. Federal Program to support science and R&D development</B><P>

A comprehensive program (Decree # 3360 of the Russian
Federation Government) "On State Support for the
Development of Scientific and Technical Developments"
was developed with Russian Academy of Sciences and the
Ministry of Science and Technical Policy. The Decree
was signed by Premier Chernomyrdin in April 1995.
The main points were made on allocation of foreign
funds for purchase of scientific equipment, journals,
patents and certifications; institute tax exemptions for
import and export of scientific materials and
equipment; formulate and implement "measures" to
support development of science and innovative
activities. Below is an itemized plan of this program.<P>

<B><I>1. S&T Policy</I></B><P>

a) Measure: Doctrine for developing Russian science<P>

Participants:<BR>
Russian Academy of Sciences (RAN)<BR>
Ministry ot Science<BR>
Russian Academy of Medical Sciences (RAMN)<BR>
Russian Academy of Agricultural Sciences (RASN)<BR>
State Committee on Higher Education (GOSKOMWZ)<BR>
Ministry of Economics<BR>
Interested ministries and departments<P>

b)Measure: Proposal for priority S&T directions, list of federal-level critical technologies<P>

Participants:<BR>
MinSci, MinEcon<BR>
RAN, RAMN<BR>
RASN, GOSKOMWZ<BR>
State Committee for Industry (GOSKOMI'ROM)<BR>
State Committee for the Defense Industry (GKOOP)<BR>
Interested ministries and departments<P>

c)Measure: Proposal on organizing cooperation between
ministries and departments in utilizing dual-use
technologies<P>

Participants:<BR>
GKOOP, GOSKOMPROM<BR>
MinEcon, MinSci<BR>
RAN, RAMN, RASN<BR>
Ministry of Atomic Energy (MinAtom)<BR>
Russian Space Agency (RKA)<BR>
Ministry of Defense<P>

<B><I>2. Formation of a Legal Base</I></B><P>

a) Measure: Drafts of normative acts regulating the
legal status of RAN and branch academies of sciences<P>

Participants:<BR>
RAN, branch academies of sciences<BR>
State Committee on Property<BR>
MinSci, MinEcon<BR>
Ministry of Finance<BR>
Ministry of Law<P>

b)Measure: Drafts of normative acts regulating the
status and activity of scientific organizations and
defining a system for conferring privileges and
benefits on forms of scientific activity<P>

Participants:<BR>
MinSci, RAN, branch academies of sciences, GOSKOMWZ,
MinFin Ministry of Labor Ministry of Law Interested
ministries and departments<P>

c) Measure: Draft of a normative act regulating
innovative activity in the RF<P>

Participants:<BR>
MinSci, MinEcon<BR>
GOSKOMPROM, GKOOP<BR>
RAN, branch academies of science,<BR>
GOSKOMWZ<BR>
Ministry of Law<P>

<B><I>3. Financing and Economic Stimulation</I></B><P>

a) Measure: Proposal on step-by-step introduction of
return financing of applied developments which were
budget-financed<P>

Participants:<BR>
MinSci, MinFin<BR>
Bank of Russia<HR>
GOSKOMPROM, GKOOP<P>

b) Measure: RF government draft proposal on organizing
the introduction of a federal contract system for
financing S&T projects, using both budget and
nonbudgetary funds<P>

Participants:<BR>
MinSci, MinEcon<BR>
MinFin, GOSKOMI'ROM<BR>
RAN, RAMN, RASN<BR>
