</UL>

<B>7. Income of Scientists in Russia (How do they survive?)</B><BR>
We all heard that Russian scientists do not receive
their salaries for many months in a row. How do they
survive? Russian Ministry of Science and Technology
Policy, Russian Academy of Sciences and Statistical
Center for Popular Opinion surveyed 2510 scientists
from different R&D institutions in Russian Federation.
Here are the results:<P>

<I>Source of income - - Percent </I><P>

Salary from their institution - - 97%<BR>
Additional income from their institution (premiums, additional salary, subsidy for food) - - 47%<BR>
Grants, contracts, additional work at their institution - - 19%<BR>
Grants, contracts, additional work at other Russian institutions - - 10%<BR>
Foreign grants, contracts, international collaborations - - 7%<BR>
Retirement pay, stipends, social security - - 16%<BR>
Participation in private R&D - - 11%<BR>
Tutoring, consulting - - 9%<BR>
Publications in Russia - - 7%<BR>
Publications abroad - - 1.5%<BR>
Business travel abroad - - 5%<BR>
Lectures, seminars abroad - - 1%<BR>
Stocks and bonds - - 4%<BR>
Other - - 5%<P>

Total figure is larger than 100% as the individual answers were not normalized.<P>

58% of the studied group had income earned outside of their institutions. For 35% of these scientists their outside income was higher then their institutional salary.<BR>
(Adapted and translated from the Russian weekly "Poisk" ("Search") - a  paper published by the Russian Academy of Sciences, Ministry of Science and Technical Policy and Committee on Higher Education.)<P>

