<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 24</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY><H3>
July 23, 1996<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A><P>

Office Of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR> 
Newsletter No. 24 <P> 

Science Park of Trieste in Italy</H3> 

Contents:
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>About the Science Park
<LI>Research Areas and Labs of the Science Park
<DD>I.   Materials Analysis And Physics
<DD>II.  Biotechnology
<DD>III. Biomedical Technologies
<DD>IV.  Electronics
<DD>V.   Information Technology
<DD>VI.  Acoustics
</OL>

<B>1. Summary:</B><BR>
The Science Park of Trieste is the first science
and technology park in Italy. It started to operate in
1982. The Park stretches over a territory of 35
hectares, on the plateau surrounding Trieste, and
consists of 41,000 square meters of premises and
facilities. Further 16,000 square meters of premises
are still under construction.<BR>
The presence in Science Park of the International
Center for Genetic Engineering and Biotechnology and of
Elettra Synchrotron Light Laboratory established a tool
of international value for scientific, technological
and economic development in the fields of biotechnology
and of material science.<BR>
 In the Science Park there are about 20
international and national centers, laboratories and
companies run on both governmental and private funds,
employing more than 750 people.<P>

<B>2. About The Science Park</B><BR> 
The Science Park Consortium, which is a
governmental body operating under the aegis of the
Italian Ministry of University and Scientific and
Technological Research, has the task of managing,
promoting and developing the Science Park. Among its
members, there are the Autonomous Region of Friuli
Venezia Giulia, the Province and Municipality of
Trieste, the Universities of Trieste and of Udine, the
National Research Council and the most renowned
scientific institutions of the Friuli Venezia Giulia
Region.<BR>
The Consortium is in charge of the urbanization,
the building of premises and equipped laboratories and
arranges and manages the supply of the logistic and
technological services required by the tenants of the
Park. It looks after the promotion and the image of the
park and fosters relations with other institutions
(such as Public Bodies, Universities, financial
organizations, research centers, industries).
The Consortium supports technical and commercial
development of the centers and companies located in the
Science Park offering administrative, legal and
marketing assistance, and promotes training activities
for junior graduates.<BR>
 The Science Park Consortium may contribute
directly towards projects of applied research and of
technological development of special importance
conducted by the Centers and Companies operating in the
Science Park, through contributions in supporting
expenses, and by means of capital and interest account
financing.<BR>
 Amongst the most effective support measures or
interventions in favor of the Centers in the Park,
there is the fact that the Consortium is willing to
purchase specialized instrumentation and equipment
necessary for the activity of its tenants to whom it is
then rented; this is a neat solution to a not uncommon
problem for those working in R&D - lack of resources
for investments conditioning the overall outcome of the
activity.<BR>
 In accordance with local laws, the Regional
Administration may provide contributions to capital
account up to a 40% of expenses necessary for plant,
expansion or running in the initial development stage
of "research laboratories whose objective is to promote
the industrial development in technologically advanced
sectors with a highly qualified workforce".<BR>
 Included in the Consortium's programs is a
commitment to providing training programs for new
graduates this has led to many young people entering
research and production not only locally: scholarships
are an item in the Consortium's budget and this means
training that is preferably carried out in Centers
working within AREA.<P>

<B>3. Research Areas and Labs of the Science Park</B><BR>  
The main activities of the Science Park are
scientific research, development and transfer of new
technologies and of innovative services in the fields
of information technology and telematics,
biotechnology, electronics and materials science.
Particular attention is paid to the design and testing
of biomedical and industrial equipment and sensors.<P>

<B>I. Materials Analysis and Physics:</B><BR> 
1. -Elettra Synchrotron Light Laboratory -<BR>
Planning, construction and management of a 2 GeV
synchrotron light machine for production of high
brightness X rays, devoted to investigate the structure
of the matter<BR>
2. -National Institute of Physics of the Matter -<BR>
T.A.S.C. Laboratory (Advanced Surface and Catalysis
Technologies), XPS, AUGER and STM surface analysis,
growth of new compound semiconductors for the
realization of microelectronic and optoelectronic
devices<BR>
3. -Laboratory of the National Institute for Nuclear
Physics -<BR>
Research on elementary particles; development of
particles detectors and microelectronic devices<BR>
4. -Institute for the Structure of the Matter -<BR>
Physics and chemistry of surfaces, research on
semiconducting and superconducting materials and on
heterogeneous catalysis<BR>
5. -Institute for Structural Chemistry -<BR>
X-ray crystallography of macromolecules, research on
electronic structure of solids and gases<P>

<B>II. Biotechnology</B><BR>
1. -International Center for Genetic Engineering and
Biotechnology -<BR>
Study of mechanisms for controlling DNA synthesis and
cell growth; research on the Human Papilloma Virus
study of structure of proteins and other
macromolecules; genetic basis of diseases; setting up
of drugs and vaccines; study of the degradation of
lignocellulose<BR>
2. -Gene Technology Laboratory -<BR>
Development of technologies connected with
characterization of human genes<BR>
3. -Polybios -<BR>
Study of polysaccharides from vegetal, algal, and
microbial biomass; high-skilled training<BR>
4. -LBT (Laboratory for Technological Biopolymers) -<BR>
Use of biomass and polymers as renewable resources in
industrial applications<BR>
5. -Tecna -<BR>
Development and design of methods and devices for food
and environmental control. Quality control on analysis
of contamination in food products<P>

<B>III. Biomecial Technologies</B><BR>
1. -Center for Information and Assessment of Biomedical
Equipment -<BR>
Technical and Clinical assessment and costing of
biomedical equipment; production of systems. Study and
training in the field of biomedical and health
technologies; regional observatory for biomedical
technologies<BR>
2. -Research and Study Center for Biomedical and Health
Technologies -<BR>
Study and training in the field of biomedical and
health technologies; regional hub for biomedical
technologies<P>

<B>IV. Electronics:</B><BR>
1. -Center for Advance Research in Space Optics-<BR>
Development and characterization of optical components
and instruments for space and industrial application<BR>
2. -Laboratory 4C (Calculation, Communication, Control
and Cooperation)-<BR>
Design and development of electronic and computer
systems for industrial automation, image processing for
industrial quality control<BR>
3. -Image Processing Laboratory -<BR>
Design and development of image processing systems for
industrial quality control and telemonitoring<BR>
4. -NIRLab (Non ionizing Radiation Laboratory)-<BR>
Development of devices for radio-communication and
sensors for the detection of electromagnetic fields,
mathematical patterns and simulation of electromagnetic
waves propagation<P>

<B>V. Information Technology</B><BR> 
1. -Laboratory for Software Development-<BR>
Development of management software, office automation
and LabTeCo - (Laboratory for Cognitive Technologies)
Artificial intelligence, research on the man-machine
interfaces and development of 'user friendly' machines
interfaces, robotics<BR>
2. -UNIX Scientific Competence Center-<BR>
Research, development, and support of scientific
hardware and software of the UNIX operating system; use
of computers as servers and for scientific calculation<P>

<B>VI. Acoustics</B><BR> 
Center for Applied Acoustics
Design, development, training and certification in the
field of sound, noise and vibration<P>
<HR><P>
For more information on this topic contact:<BR>
Igor Vodyanoy, Ph.D.<BR>
at <BR>
TEL:   +44-171-514-4131<BR>
