<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 25</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>November 4, 1996<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A><P>

Office Of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR> 
Newsletter No. 25 <P> 

International Center for Genetic Engineering and Biotechnology (ICGEB)</H3> 

Contents:

<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>About the ICGEB
<LI>Structure and funding
<DIR>      Who is who</DIR>
<LI>The ICGEB research program
<LI>Research in Trieste
<DIR>          Virology;</DIR>
<DIR>          Cell and Molecular Biology</DIR>
<DIR>          Molecular Pathology</DIR>
<DIR>          Molecular Immunology</DIR>
<DIR>          Microbiology</DIR>
<DIR>          Protein Structure and Function</DIR>
<LI>Training
<LI>Fellowships
<LI>Meetings/courses at ICGEB and at affiliated centers
<LI>Technical support services
<LI>Advisory service
<LI>Co-operation with international agencies and industry
</OL>

<B>1. Summary:</B><BR>
The United Nations Industrial Development Organization
(UNIDO) recognized, at a very early stage the potential
of genetic engineering and biotechnology to alleviate
disease and starvation and to promote the economic
progress of the developing world. It began the
initiative that has led to the foundation of ICGEB.
The research, training schemes and services of ICGEB
represent an innovative and comprehensive approach to
promote biotechnology internationally. The Center aims
at helping developing nations to help themselves and
holds out the prospect for advancing knowledge and
applying the latest biotechnological techniques in
public health, nutrition, environmental
protection/remediation and energy saving.
ICGEB provides a scientific and educational environment
of the highest standards. It brings biotechnology to
developing countries by strengthening their research
capabilities. Its laboratories develop state-of-the-art
research of importance to bio-industries in Member
States.<P>

<B>2. About the ICGEB</B><BR>
In 1981, UNIDO convened a meeting of distinguished
scientists to consider the mechanisms to speed up the
dissemination of these revolutionary technologies. The
result was a proposal to establish an international
center of excellence that, by providing an environment
conducive to research and development, would act as a
vehicle to foster biotechnology in the developing
world. In 1982, this concept was approved by a high
level conference of developed and developing nations in
Belgrade. The first steps to establish the Center were
taken the next year when, at a follow up
Plenipotentiary Meeting in Madrid, the Statutes of the
Center were signed by 26 countries. The establishment
of ICGEB and its subsequent development has been
guided, under the aegis of UNIDO, by a panel of
scientific advisers and by a Preparatory Committee of
representatives of the States having signed the
Statutes. With the entry into force of the Statutes on
3 February 1994, and with the subsequent Agreement
between ICGEB and UNIDO for the transfer of assets at
the end of 1995, the Center has become a fully
autonomous international organization composed of 37
Member States.<P>

Member States of ICGEB<BR>
(1 January, 1996)<BR>
Afghanistan , Algeria, Argentina, Bhutan, Brazil,
Bulgaria, Chile, China, Croatia, Cuba, Ecuador, Egypt,
F.R. Yugoslavia, Hungary, India, Iraq, Italy, Kuwait,
Mauritius, Mexico, Morocco, Nigeria, Pakistan, Panama,
Peru, Romania, Russia, Senegal, Slovenia, Sri Lanka,
Sudan, T.F.Y.R.Macedonia, Tunisia , Turkey, Uruguay,
Venezuela, Viet Nam.<P>

<B>3. Structure and Funding</B><BR>
Located in Trieste, Italy and New Delhi, India the
Center forms an interactive network with Affiliated
Centers in Member States.<P>

The organs of ICGEB are the Secretariat, the Board of
Governors and the Council of Scientific Advisers. The
Secretariat is composed of the Director, the two Heads
of Components and the scientific and administrative
staff operating within the framework of the ICGEB
program. The Board of Governors consists of a
representative of each Member State and constitutes the
directive organ of the Center. The Council of
Scientific Advisers is composed of eminent scientists
and oversees the scientific excellence of ICGEB.
The scientific and administrative management is the
responsibility of the Director and the Heads of the two
component laboratories. The research staff at each
component laboratory consists of senior scientists
directing research groups composed of junior
scientists, support staff and trainee fellows from the
Member States.<P>

The Center presently employs ( 1995 ) over 200 staff
and guests at its premises in Trieste and New Delhi .
The Trieste Component currently occupies 5,700m2 and is
expected to expand to 7,000m2 within 1996. The New
Delhi Component, has moved to the new 1O,OOO m2
premises at the end of 1995. A new guest house is
already available in New Delhi and there are similar
plans for Trieste.<P>

In its second session the Board of Governors endorsed a
program covering the 1996-2000 period and implying an
overall financial requirement of US$72.6 million. Funds
are provided by the Governments of Italy and India, the
AREA Science Park of Trieste - the authority that
administers the science park where the Trieste
Component is located- as well as voluntary
contributions by the participating countries. From
1999, all Member States will participate in the
financing of ICGEB, through a scale of assessment to be
adopted by the Board of Governors.<P>

<B>Who is who:</B><BR>
President of the Board of Governors: Ambassador Adolfo
Raul Taylhardat, Venezuela<BR>
Council of Scientific Advisers:<BR>
L. Luca Cavalli-Sforza, Italy; Nduka Okafor, Nigeria;
Ananda M. Chakrabarty, USA; Govindarajan Padmanaban,
India; Georgii P. Georgiev, Russia; Hector Torres,
Argentina; Xiaocheng Gu, China; Pablo Valenzuela,
Chile; Arthur Kornberg, USA; Ray Wu, USA; Joshua
Lederberg, USA<BR>
Director of ICGEB: Arturo Falaschi, Italy<BR>
Head of Trieste Component: Francisco E. Baralle,
Argentina<BR>
Head of New Delhi Component: Krishna K. Tewari, India<P>

<B>4. The ICGEB Research Program</B><BR>
The program currently consists of three main areas:
<UL>
<LI>Plant Biology, with emphasis on crop improvement;
<LI>Human Health, with emphasis on infectious disease control and vaccine production; and
<LI>Biomass Conversion, with emphasis on lignocellulose degradation.
</UL>
The research groups are led by senior scientists and
are composed of junior scientists, trainee fellows and
technical support personnel.<P>

<B>5. Research in Trieste</B><BR>
Interaction with the local scientific community is well
established and access to a very powerful source of X-
rays from a synchrotron, and to a new neuroscience
Center, both located in the AREA Science Park, is
strengthening the research capability of the Center.<P>

<B>Virology</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Focus: molecular biology of human viruses;
<LI>Targets: human papilloma viruses, hepatitis B and C, HIV and rotaviruses.
</UL>

<B>Cell and Molecular Biology</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Focus: mechanisms of DNA expression and replication in normal and cancerous tissue;
<LI>Targets: identification of human DNA replication origins and of the mechanism of regulation of their function; applications of molecular genetics to medicine, including gene therapy approaches.
</UL>

<B>Molecular Pathology</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Focus: infectious diseases; molecular biology of genetically based diseases; molecular biology of the extra-cellular matrix;
<LI>Targets: hyperlipidemia; hypertension; granulocyte pathology; adducin gene polymorphisms; study of fibronectin and tenascin.
</UL>

<B>Molecular Immunology</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Focus: recombinant monoclonal antibodies; novel vaccines;
<LI>Targets: characterization of antigenic determinants of tumor and virus infected cells.
</UL>

<B>Microbiology</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Focus: biomass conversion;
<LI>Targets: molecular biology/enzymology of lignin degradation; novel host vector systems.
</UL>

<B>Protein Structure and Function</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Focus: biocomputing and protein engineering;
<LI>Targets: structure-function relationships in cytokines and DNA-binding proteins.
</UL>

<B>6. Training</B><BR>
The Center provides training at an international
standard, focusing on specific subjects or techniques,
both in-house and at Affiliated Centers.<P>

<B>7. Fellowships</B><BR>
Long term post-doctoral schemes allow young scientists
from Member States to participate in the ongoing
research of the Center. The duration of the fellowships
varies from twelve to twenty-four months. Post-doctoral
fellows are expected to return to their home institutes
on completion of their training ICGEB trainee
fellowships range between US$ 15000 - 21OOO per annum.
A pre-doctoral fellowship scheme of thirty-six months
duration, leading to doctoral degrees, commenced in
1992 in cooperation with selected universities.
ICGEB has recently implemented a new program of short-
term fellowships (3 months maximum duration).<P>

<B>8. Meetings/Courses at ICGEB and AT Affiliated Centers</B><BR>
Practical and theoretical courses, each of two to four
weeks duration, are held at the Trieste and New Delhi
Components. They are conducted by internationally
recognized scientists. The current five year program
provides for up to 24 weeks of workshops annually at
each of the two Components.<BR>
ICGEB covers the costs of meetings/courses to a ceiling
of US$25000. Two to three week laboratory courses
conducted by Affiliated Center staff and invited
lecturers; up to five such courses take place annually.
Research orientated meetings are generally of two to
five days duration; up to four such meetings per year
are scheduled to take place annually under the five
year work program of the Center.<P>

<B>9. Technical Support Services</B><BR>
ICGEB meets developing countries' computing needs by
providing access to an advanced computer service
laboratory at the Trieste Component. The laboratory
provides remote access to a range of major U.S. and
European public domain data bases, in addition to those
of the Center and its software library.<BR>
Scientists from developing countries, visiting the
Center, have direct access to the full range of state-
of-the-art biocomputational facilities. Remote
accessing of the Center's computer facilities is
operated through existing telematic networks; where
appropriate, accessing by satellite link is envisaged.
ICGEB acts as a repository of information:
<UL>
<LI>by gathering and collating information on research activities in the Member States;
<LI>by hosting information on commercial products developed b) Member State institutes, such as restriction enzymes, diagnostic reagents and vaccines;
<LI>by monitoring matters related to patent laws, the release of genetically engineered microorganisms into the environment anti biosafety procedures/legislation .
</UL>

<B>10. Advisory Services</B><BR>
ICGEB provides technical advice to Member States for the:
<UL>
<LI>formulation of national bioscience policy;
<LI>definition of research goals;
<LI>development of national bioindustries;
<LI>establishment of national biotechnology laboratories.
</UL>
ICGEB seeks to promote the harmonization of biosafety
procedures and regulations in its Member States, in the
framework of the UNIDO, WHO, UNEP, FAO Informal Working
Group on Biosafety. ICGEB has dedicated significant
resources in strengthening institutional capability in
Member States to assess biological safety through
training programmer that are unique in the coverage of
topics and the comprehensives of approach. In addition
UNIDO, in co-operation with ICGEB, has established the
Biosafety Information Network and Advisory Service
(BINAS) which is aimed at serving as a dedicated
resource for assisting Member States in the area of
biosafety. BINAS facilitates regulatory harmonization
by allowing referral to, and cross-correlation of,
existing national regulations and administrative
procedures, thus simplifying identification of
regulatory conflicts. As such BINAS provides a decision
support environment for the formulation and/or
refinement of biotechnology regulations. It strengthens
institutional capability by advisory services, training
in risk assessment methodologies and information
support.<P>

<B>11. Co-operation with International Agencies and Industry</B><BR>
This is promoted to harmonize and speed up projects of
common interest. Apart from UNIDO, ICGEB retains close
contacts with WHO, FAO, UNEP, UNESCO, IAEA, OECD, the
Commission of the European Communities (CEC) and the
European Molecular Biology Laboratory (EMBL); close
collaboration with the International Center of
Theoretical Physics (IAEA/UNESCO) and with the
International Center of Science and High Technology,
located in Trieste under UNIDO auspices, is well
developed.<P>

ICGEB adopts a positive patenting and licensing policy.
Licenses can be made available to enterprises of Member
States. Furthermore, through the establishment of new
guidelines, ICGEB should be in the position of
fostering an innovative approach for industrial
relations at the global level, enhancing the
finalization of joint ventures and other partner
orientated approaches for the commercialization of the
results of research in biotechnology.<P><HR><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely
those of the author and do not necessarily reflect
official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P>

The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to
providing current information on science and technology
development in European countries. In order to better
meet your needs, our Associate Directors and Scientists
are very much interested in knowing what are your
specific science and technology interests. Please let
me know what they are.<P>

Furthermore, if there are others, whom you are aware
of, that have interest in these newsletters please pass
