<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 26</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>December 18, 1996<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A><P>

Office Of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR>
Newsletter No. 26<P>

Tri-Service Workshop Review on Private R&D in FSU</H3>

<I>Key words: workshop, materials, hardening, lasers,
plasma, coatings.</I><P>

Contents:

<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Background
<DD>   2.1 Patent Information</DD>
<LI>Selected technologies
<DD>   3.1  Heat-Insulating Materials</DD>
<DD>   3.2  Hand Held Cutter</DD>
<DD>   3.3  Fire Extinguishing Device</DD>
<DD>   3.4  Underwater Containment Technology</DD>
<DD>   3.5  Electrostatic Protection Coating</DD>
<DD>   3.6  A Single Mode CO2 Laser</DD>
<DD>   3.7  Plasma-Detonation Treatment</DD>
<DD>   3.8  High Frequency Induction Pulse Treatment</DD>
<DD>   3.9  High Speed Streak And Framing Photography</DD>
<DD>   3.10 Low Temperature Plasma Treatment Of Fibers</DD>
<LI>List of presented papers
<LI>Proceedings
<LI>Chapter formation
</OL>

<B>1. Summary</B><BR>
A review of private FSU R&D companies was held at the
resort area near Moscow in September 1996. As the first
meeting of this kind in the FSU, it has attracted
attention of the Russian Department of Commerce, large
Russian R&D institutions, as well as the US industrial
representatives in Moscow. A private design bureau
based at the Bauman Technical University (Moscow)
offered a number of materials and robotics technologies
based on their space vehicle research. About forty
formal papers were given as discussion posters. Most of
the talks were on materials, physics of materials, and
surface physics. There were also papers on laser
physics and laser technologies. In this report you will
find a complete list of reviewed papers and a
description of a few general interest technologies such as
thermal insulating materials, coatings, and lasers. The
unedited proceedings can be made available upon
request. The event was sponsored by all three services
of Edison House.<P>

<B>2. Background</B><BR>
After the breaking of the Soviet Union, centralized R&D
support and leadership have been in decline in the FSU.
Many leading scientists and engineers from academia and
military-industrial complex in FSU have started their
own R&D companies, which sometimes represent the best
of R&D in some areas. These companies invariably stay
underground, as they are afraid of organized crime.
There is also a very little support from the
government. These private companies were often formed
from the former enterprises of the USSR military-
industrial complex, or/and formed by well known
scientists. These companies are market oriented and
often have access to modern equipment that the state
enterprises do not have because of bad planning or lack
of funds.<BR>
"Plasma Test Ltd" in Moscow, a successful hi-tech
corporation working in the area of plasma incineration
and materials coatings, owes much of its prosperity to
Mr. Adam Gonopolsky. Adam is an outstanding
representative of a new class of Russian entrepreneurs
and industrialists and a distinguished scientist and
educator. He took charge of organizing the meeting in
view of his knowledge of private industry in FSU.
The meeting took place in a sanatorium surrounded by
birch and pine woods; all privately owed territory
located about 60 km from Moscow. All modern amenities
were available. There was a swimming pool, sauna and
the were racquetball courts on the grounds.<BR>
Transportation from and to airports and railway station
was arranged for all participants. We also visited the
nearby experimental center of Bauman Technical
University where we saw demonstration of interesting
technologies and visited unique space technology
museum. The Institute was a primary space research and
space engineering education center in USSR. Most of the
cosmonauts were trained there.<P>

<B>2.1  Patent information</B><BR> 
Most of the papers presented are protected by USSR
copyright certificates. However, 19 papers out of 40
did not have copyright. Thirty percent of the papers
have patents that have passed the international
patent standards and whose innovative nature is
indisputable in any country where they are
valid. The remaining seventy percent of patented
projects have Russian Federation patents.<P>

<B>3. Selected technologies</B><P>

<B>3.1 Ecologically safe non-combustible heat-insulating materials based on mineral fibers and non-organic binders</B> are made from mineral superfine fibers (basalt,
kaolin etc.). The materials are chemically inert and
noncombustible; do not liberate toxic substances at
high and low temperatures and offer low thermal
conductivity.<P>
Properties: 
Basalt based
density, 140 kg/m3; thermal conductivity 0.0035 w/mQ;
temperature range -260 +700oC
kaolin based
density, 270 kg/m3; thermal conductivity 0.0045 w/mQ;
temperature range -260 +1300oC
Quartz based
density, 140 kg/m3; thermal conductivity 0.0035 w/mQ;
temperature range -260 +1100oC<P>

Applications: chemical, machine building, electric
power industry (including nuclear), industrial and
civil engineering, cryogenic engineering, ship-
building, aerospace industry, transport, food industry,
etc.<P>

These materials were awarded a diploma and a gold medal
in April 1996 at the Geneva International exhibition of
inventions in Switzerland (salon 24). These materials
were patented in the Russian Federation.<P>

<B>3.2 Hand held cutter</B> (Based on space rocket engine
R&D). Cuts steels, cast iron, concrete, rock, etc. up
to 10 - 15 inches of thickness.<P>

Applications: reclamation, emergency & rescue services,
metallurgy, civil engineering, transport, etc.<P>

Advantages: reliability and simple service due to
simplicity of the design; easy operation, mobility and
flexibility, extremely simple to use. Binary fuel -
kerosene and oxygen, inexpensive.<P>

<B>3.3 Fire extinguishing device</B> (based on space
technology). Using a solid rocket propellant and water,
it extinguishing fires with remarkable speed by filling
the volume under fire with water vapor.<P>

<B>3.4 Underwater containment technology </B> (based on
satellite antennae research)<BR>
Developed for containment of the nuclear submarine
"Komsomolets" that sank in the Norwegian sea on the
depth of 1700m. The whole project from design,
manufacturing and to actual deployment took only three
months. They developed and manufactured: new special
elastic material based on glass fibers and silicone, a
mechanical device that automatically unfolds the
material to envelope part of the submarine hull; self
opening partitions, and elastic bags that were filled
with water inside of the submarine.<P>

<B>3.5 The electrostatic protection coating</B> for aircraft
composite materials allows spray-covering of the
assembled aircraft as well as its separate parts and
can be used during aircraft repairs. The technology was
tested on the KA50 and K62 helicopters and on SU84
airplane. The coating makes a thin conductive layer
that becomes a part of the composite after a special
treatment.<P>

<B>3.6 A single mode CO2 laser</B> was designed using an non-
conventional approach of electrodless AC discharging at
12-15 kHz to generate a highly homogeneous medium in
diffusion-cooled wave-guide tubes with slow pumping. A
beam power of 500w and diameter 7mm, with a divergence
of 1.5mrad has been developed. 5000w laser is under
construction.<P>

<B>3.7 The plasma-detonation treatment</B> is based on the use
of plasma jets powered by the transformation of a
detonation wave into a plasma pulse. Energy density can
reach 10E7 W/cm2. When the pulse interacts with a
surface of metals it forms a region of shock-compressed
plasma with a highly localized temperature of 3000oC.
The device can operate with a frequency of 1-4Hz and a
pulse duration 1-5ms. With evaporation of the central
electrode material a surface layer alloying of 15-18 mm
diameter 100-150 microns depth. Metallographic studies
revealed the presence of a white unetched layer that
coincided with the layer of high hardness.<P>

<B>3.8 High frequency induction pulse treatment</B> -
hardening of asymmetric pieces of metal or metal alloys
without external cooling with speeds of quenching up to
10000oC/sec. About 1mm depth of hardened material was
obtained after 100ms at frequency 66kHz.<P>

<B>3.9 High speed streak and framing photography</B> has been
developed to analyze spatial-temporal characteristics
of IR and UV lasers (CO, CO2, YAG, Er eximer, etc.).
Framing range up to 5000f/s.<P>

<B>3.10 Low temperature plasma treatment of fibers.</B> A glow
discharge in vacuum treatment of organic and non-
organic fibers results in increased adhesive
properties, hydrophilicity (e.g. polyester fabrics
increases capillarity from 40 to 200mm), bonding
strength between fibers. A compact and simple industrial
device was developed.<P>

<B>4. List of presented papers</B><P>

Surface Treatment & Properties Modification.<P>

<I>a. Plasma Treatment.</I><P>

Adam M. Gonopolsky. "Plasma-Test" JSC. Protective Coatings for Aircraft.<BR>
