<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Biophysics Newsletter No. 26</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>January 09, 1997<BR>
European Biophysics<BR>
<A HREF="vodyanoy.htm">Igor Vodyanoy</A><P>

Office Of Naval Research-European Office Biophysics<BR>
Newsletter No. 27<P>

Joint EC-US Workshop on Environmental Biotechnology (1996)</H3>


<I>Key words: workshop, biodegradation, genetics, bioremediation, bacteria, pollution.</I><P>

Contents:
<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Background
<DD>  2.1 EC-US Task Force on Biotechnology
<DD>  2.2 Granada Workshop
<LI>Discussions and Future Directions
<DD>  3.1 The Biochemistry of Anaerobic and Aerobic Biodegradation
<DD>  3.2 The Environment as a Limiting Factor for Biodegradation
<DD>  3.3 Molecular Basis For Recalcitrance Of Pollutants
<DD>  3.4 Biodiversity of Biodegradation
<LI>Future Hands-on Short Course on Bioremediation
<LI>List of Presented Papers
<LI>Current Program of The European Commission on Environmental Biotechnology (1994-1998)
<LI>Points of Contact
</OL>

<B>1. Summary</B><BR>
EC-US Task Force on Biotechnology Research encouraged the
Working Group on Environmental Biotechnology of EU to
support the EC-US workshop on Environmental Biotechnology
that was held in November 1996, Granada, Spain. The
workshop objectives were to examine the biochemical and
genetic bases of biodegradation in different environments
and for the rational design and use of microbes in polluted
sites. Additional objectives were to foster cooperation
between US and EC scientists in the field of environmental
biotechnology, including scientists at an early stage of
their careers, and to provide research managers with
insights, based on case studies, into new directions in
environmental biotechnology.<P>

Nineteen internationally recognized research leaders and 20
advanced students and post-doctoral fellows took part in
oral and poster sessions and extensive discussions that
generated a number of interesting new research venues. In
this letter you will find a short summary of these
discussions, and a list of presented papers. I also
included information on the EU-US Biotechnology Task Force
and on the current program of the European Commission on
Environmental Biotechnology.<P>

The workshop was supported by the Commission of the
European Communities, Brussels, Belgium; Office of Naval
Research, Arlington, VA, US; Office of Naval Research,
Europe, London, UK; and by the US Army European Research
Office, London, UK.<P>

<B>2. Background</B><P>

<B>2.1 EC-US Task Force on Biotechnology Research</B><BR>
The US-EC Task Force on Biotechnology Research was
established on 7 September 1990 by an administrative
arrangement between the European Commission and the United
States Government, with the goal of increasing the mutual
understanding between European Community activities and US
programs related to biotechnology research. The Task Force
was designed to serve as a mechanism for the exchange of
information regarding scientific aspects of biotechnology.
In June 1996, this arrangement between the Commission and
the United States Government was renewed for a period of
five years.<P>

The discussions at the plenary meetings involved subjects
deserving major international attention and collaboration.
Within this framework, a workshop for scientists invited
from Europe and the US was organized in October 1994 in
Brussels on aspects of Environmental Biotechnology. The
workshop focused mainly on Anaerobic Biodegradation, the
Development of Microcosms and Mesocosms for
Biodegradability Testing, and Tailor Made Microbes for
Biodegradation.<P>

Due to the success and interest in the Brussels workshop,
the Task Force encouraged the Working Group on
Environmental Biotechnology to organize two follow-up
activities. One is this workshop, Joint EC-US Workshop
on Environmental Biotechnology which focuses on the
Molecular and Biochemical Bases of Biodegradation
and a Hands-on Short Course on Bioremediation.<P>

<B>2.2 Granada Workshop</B><BR>
The members of the European Steering Committee were Dr. I
Economidis (EC)m Dr. D. Janssen (The Netherlands), Dr. P.
Williams (UK), and Dr. J.L. Ramos (Spain). Members of the
US Steering Committee were Dr. Anna Palmisano (DoD, ONR), 
Dr. Joseph Suflita (U. of Oklahoma) , Dr. Wall (Missouri U) 
and Dr. Young (Rutgers U). The workshop' local and main 
organizer and chair was Dr. Juan L. Ramos, CSIC, Granada.<P>

The major objectives of the workshop were:<BR>
a. to examine the biochemical and genetic bases of
biodegradation in different environments, for the
rational design and use of microbes in polluted sites<BR>
b.  to foster cooperation between US and EC scientists in
the field of environmental biotechnology, including
scientists at an early stage of their careers, and<BR>
c. to provide research managers with insights, based on
case studies, into new directions in environmental
biotechnology. One half-day was dedicated to a
discussion of the state of the art, an assessment of
future directions, and a definition of areas of mutual
EC-US interest.<P>

<B>3. Discussions and Future Directions</B><P>

<B>3.1 The Biochemistry of Anaerobic and Aerobic Biodegradation</B><BR>
Some of these bacterial biodegradative processes take
place as part of co-metabolism with other compounds.
Relevant metabolic processes in anaerobes include
reductive dechlorination and halorespiration, and
degradation of aromatic hydrocarbons (toluenes, xylenes,
ethylbenzene, benzene) and alkanes. Advances in the
biochemistry of biodegradative processes in aerobes include
not only the characterization of key pathways in Gram-
negative bacteria, but also the biochemistry of other less
studied microbes such as Gram-positive bacteria and fungi.
With the aid of recent developments in the area of chemical
engineering, some of these anaerobic and aerobic processes
have been adopted for industrial utilization.<P>

Some aspects of this area of research deserve further
attention, in particular:<BR>
i) Understanding the biochemistry of anaerobic processes as
the molecular basis of the anaerobic degradation;<BR>
ii) Genetics of anaerobes and Gram-positive bacteria, with
emphasis on the development of tools for their engineering
and manipulation.<BR>
iii)Influence of the composition of the medium,
identification of abiotic factors that alter the
control of gene expression for extra- and intracellular
enzymes, etc. The biochemistry, physiology and genetics
related to the utilization of alternative electron
acceptors by anaerobes should also be considered.<P>

<B>3.2 The environment as a limiting factor for biodegradation</B><BR>
On many occasions, limitations to biodegradation are
outside the microorganism, and involve factors such as
limited access of microorganisms to the pollutant because
of physical constraints, such as limitations caused by
reduced mass transfer or reduced desorption of the
pollutant from soil particles and other substrates.<P>

What organisms or microbial activities can be used to
overcome these limitations? How can surfactants,
exoenzymes, carriers, etc help to accelerate pollutant
desorption and mass transfer? Are combined physicochemical
and biological approaches needed in cases for which the
environment is the main limiting factor?<P>

<B>3.3 Molecular basis for recalcitrance of pollutants</B><BR>
Insights have been obtained into the causes of
recalcitrance of many synthetic chemicals, although
unifying concepts are still difficult to define.
Nonetheless, it was clearly shown that certain limitations
can be overcome by expansion of the substrate specificity
of key enzymes, or by coupling the action of several
different enzymes such as oxygenases and ligninases.<P>

Hybrid pathways have been obtained for the metabolism of
certain recalcitrant compounds such as aliphatics and
aromatics with a low level of substitution with nitro
groups or halogen atoms. Hybrid pathways represent a way
to overcome microbiological limitations in bioremediation.<P>

The intrinsic toxicity of some chemicals was shown to
limit the performance of microbes with interesting
biodegradative properties, although an array of microbes
able to thrive in the presence of high concentrations of
toxic pollutants are being found worldwide, representing
new opportunities. The need for microbes to be able to deal
with recalcitrant polychlorinated compounds was found to
be of particular interest. A series of open questions
about the ability of recombinant microbes to survive and
perform under field conditions were raised. Field tests
with wild-type and recombinant microbes have to be
designed to demonstrate biodegradative activity in situ.
Elucidation of the physiological, biochemical and genetic
base of tolerance to organic solvents and other toxic
pollutants will require studies to determine whether these
"new" traits can be transferred to other microbes of
interest for biodegradation. It was suggested that stress
responses that improve activity and survival be studied.<P>

<B>3.4 Biodiversity of biodegradation</B><BR>
In almost any given pollutant, a wide variety of aerobic
and anaerobic microbes, including bacteria and fungi, can
be found. Biodiversity extends not only to microbes but
also to genes and catabolic pathways: at least five
different pathways are now known for toluene metabolism by
aerobic bacteria and fungi and at least one pathway is
known for anaerobic bacteria. Future studies will therefore
involve the design of new pathways via the use of different
genetic modules that will allow the expansion of the
catabolic potential of microbes. This natural process can
be mimicked in the laboratory, which gives new insights in
the molecular mechanisms of bacterial adaptation.<P>

Can such new pathways be designed for recalcitrant
pollutants? Would every synthetic chemical become easily
degradable in the environment? How do natural genetic
processes (transformation, conjugation, transduction)
contribute to the evolution of new pathways? How do
catabolic plasmids evolve and spread? What is the
ecological and environmental significance of these
pathways? How are different catabolic pathways regulated?
Which environmental signals trigger the evolution of
regulatory mechanisms?<P>

<B>4. Future hands-on short course on bioremediation</B><BR>
The Steering Committee has met to plan the "Theoretical and
Practical Course on Environmental Biotechnology", to be
held at Rutgers University in the summer of 1998. To foster
cooperation and collaboration between US and EC scientists,
a Theoretical and Practical Course on Environmental
Biotechnology for advanced students on both sides of the
Atlantic was proposed. The course will be organized by Dr.
Lily Young and Dr. Gerben Zylstra. Members of the Steering
Committees will support the organization of the course and
relevant scientists in the area will be invited to take part
as instructors. The course will be held at facilities
available at Rutgers University in New Brunswick, New
Jersey.<P>

The Course on Bioremediation (Rutgers University,
summer 1998) will be team-taught by faculty from both
the US and EC. Dr. Lily Young of Rutgers University
will be the Course Director. The students will be
drawn equally from the US and the European Community.<P>

Field sites in the northern New Jersey / New York City
area will be exploited to sample a range of
environmental matrices, including soils, groundwater
and estuarine sediments.<P>

In the medium term, exchanges of personnel between US
and European laboratories for training is envisaged as
a way to strengthen links between laboratories. These
links will form the basis of further development in the
area of Environmental Biotechnology.<P>

In the future joint research activities are envisaged
as a way to firmly establish cooperative links.<P>

<B>5. List of presented papers</B><P>

