<B>6. Current program of the European Commission on
ENVIRONMENTAL BIOTECHNOLOGY (1994-1998)</B> 
(from EC announcement)<P>

<B>Prenormative Research: Biotechnology for the Environment</B><P>

Objectives<P>

Biotechnology has an expanded role in the prevention,
detection and remediation of environmental damage. This
topic should take into consideration environmental and
societal needs, emerging biotechnologies and development
of bioindustry. Typical projects should touch upon 
fundamental questions of biology, such as microbial 
molecular biology, microbial physiology and metabolism, 
microbial genetics and ecology, taking into consideration 
problems of bioprocess engineering such as scale-up, 
modelling and control theory, analysis and measurement, 
kinetics, process design and optimization, and 
bioavailability.<BR>
This domain should take into consideration aspects of 
biosafety and its results will contribute to the
ongoing international debate on environmental applications
e.g. OECD (Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development) and the development of standards, CEN (Comite
Europeen de Normalisation.<P>

Research tasks<P>

<UL>
<LI>Elucidation of basic mechanisms of biodegradation and biotransformation. and establishment and maintenance of stable microbial consortia under practical conditions, using the tools of molecular genetics;
<LI>Improvement of existing processes and the development of new ones based on a better understanding of the microbial and transport mechanisms involved, especially related to mixed cultures and mixed substrates;
<LI>Horizontal gene transfer in microbial communities of polluted soils in relation to selection pressure
exerted by pollutants;
<LI>Elucidation of mechanisms of microbial responses to chemical pollution. Possible exploitation for
monitoring pollutants;
<LI>Design and development by utilizing molecular genetic approaches of efficient and safe microorganisms for bioremediation processes in order to detoxify toxic wastes.  In these studies, the aspect of biological containment should be taken into serious consideration
</UL>

Synergies with other specific programs<P>

An emphasis will be given in this part of the program
to develop innovative biotechnological methods for
aspects of bioremediation. Aspects of detecting
polluting substances in the environment will be
approached by the Specific Program in the Field of
Environment and Climate (Biosensors). In addition,
the aspect of pollution prevention will be touched upon
in the Program on Agriculture and Fisheries.<P>

