<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter #1</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>


<H3>July 22, 1996<BR>
European Materials Science and Engineering<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/wilcox.htm">B.A. Wilcox</A> and  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/mecholsk.htm">J.J. Mecholsky, Jr.</A><P>

An Office of Naval Research-European Office<BR>
#96-001: Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter</H3>
Report on:<P>

1. Institute for Advanced Materials (IAM) of the Joint Research Centre (JRC), Petten, Netherlands<P>

2. The National Ceramic Centre of the Netherlands Energy Research Foundation (ECN), Petten, Netherlands<P>


<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Introduction
<LI>Research at the Institute for Advanced Materials of the Joint Research Centre (IAM-JRC) at Petten
<LI>Research at the National Ceramic Centre of the Netherlands Energy Research Foundation (ECN) 
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts
</OL>

<I><P>Key Words:  advanced materials; ceramics; alloys; composites; fuel cells; Institute for Advanced Materials (JRC); National Ceramic Centre (ECN)</I><P>

<B>1. Summary</B><P>

   Two laboratories were visited in Petten, Netherlands:  The Institute for Advanced Materials of the Joint Research Centre (IAM-JRC) and The National Ceramic Centre of the Netherlands Energy Research Foundation, ECN.  Both have excellent materials research programs, state-of-the-art facilities, and first rate scientists.  IAM-JRC focuses on high temperature structural materials--ceramics, alloys, and composites. The National Ceramic Centre (ECN) has excellent processing and testing capabilities and their research is broad, ranging from structural ceramics to solid oxide fuel cells.  Funding for IAM-JRC research is mostly from the European Union, while the Dutch government supports most of the efforts at the National Ceramic Centre.  However both laboratories seek (and obtain) additional funding from European industries.  Industrial support is becoming a more important fraction of both laboratories' research budgets, as government money is decreasing.  The two laboratories are physically adjacent to each other.  They do collaborate on research projects, but often they are competitors for external funding.  US scientists and technologists interested in mechanical property and corrosion testing should visit IAM-JRC to study, and possibly duplicate, their unique testing equipment.  The end use of most of the composite research appears to be shifting from structural applications to energy use and functional material applications.<P>

<B>2. Introduction</B><P>

   This report was prepared jointly by Ben Wilcox and Jack Mecholsky.  Jack will complete his year at ONREUR in August and will return to his faculty position in the Department of Materials Science and Engineering at the University of Florida, Gainesville, FL.  Ben joined ONREUR in May 1996 for a period of three years.  Prior to that he headed the Materials Science Division at the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA), Arlington, VA.  He will report on technical aspects of structural and functional materials research in Europe, Africa, and the Middle East.  He will also report selectively on science policy and funding strategies of different countries and the European Union, particularly as they affect Materials Science and Engineering research.

   Our trip to Petten was arranged by Prof. M.H. van de Voorde who is Head of a Materials Division at IAM-JRC.  He is also a Professor at Delft University of Technology. IAM-JRC and ECN both occupy a research site in Petten, Netherlands, which is about 60 km north of Amsterdam.  They are two separate and independent laboratories; IAM-JRC is funded predominately by the European Union (EU) and ECN is funded mostly by the Dutch Government.  In both cases additional funding is sought and received from industries in the EU countries.  We noted one project where the two laboratories collaborated, an Advanced Coating Centre for the development of new coatings for materials in severe environments, i.e. for wear and corrosion resistance.  However in most cases it appeared that the laboratories were in competition, especially for industrial contract research funding. In both laboratories there is a strong effort to increase industrial support as EU and Dutch government funding decreases, i.e. IAM-JRC is seeking to increase its industrial support from 20% to 30% of its total budget.<P>

<B>3. Research at the Institute for Advanced Materials of the Joint Research Centre (IAM-JRC) at Petten</B><P>

   IAM-JRC, Petten and its sister laboratory at Ispra, Italy were founded in the mid-1960's as part of EURATOM when Europe was investing heavily in nuclear energy R&D.  Both had (and still have) very strong materials research capabilities, including nuclear materials.  In the 1970's nuclear research was de-emphasized and the laboratories broadened their mission, much like some DOE National Laboratories in the U.S.  Nuclear materials testing and evaluation at the Petten High Flux Reactor is still an important function.<P>

   The Institute for Advanced Materials has evolved into a first rate laboratory for the development and characterization of metallic, ceramic, and composite structural materials for advanced high temperature technologies, and they have established an international reputation in materials science.  Much of their success is due to the ten year leadership of the Director, Dr. E.D. Hondros, who retired in 1995, and is now Senior Visiting Professor in the Materials Science Department at Imperial College of Science, Technology, and Medicine, London.  He was succeeded as Director by Dr. Torronen from Finland, an expert on materials and nuclear safety. Much of the research is published in abstract form in "The Materials Challenge", a news bulletin of the Institute for Advanced Materials.  This is a very high quality glossy publication, and is distributed widely. It is also a good marketing document.<P>

   The laboratory staff numbers about 100 plus some post-doctorate and part-time students.  The scientists are multi-national.  We saw excellent state-of-the-art facilities for creep and fatigue testing, ceramic processing, ceramic joining, and high temperature corrosion (including a thermogravimetric Cahn balance capable of testing to 1500C, and a low velocity burner rig).<P>

   Dr. Steen has a vigorous research program on ceramic composites including:  fatigue of 2D woven ceramic matrix composites (CMC's) at high temperatures;  effects of interfacial damage on mechanical properties of long fiber CMC's; and residual stress state and damage mechanisms in CMC's.  The testing equipment for measuring creep, strength, toughness, fatigue, etc., is outstanding.  Much of the equipment was designed at IAM-JRC and either was built on site or contracted for manufacture at their discretion.  For example they developed, with a commercial company, a prototype radiant heating furnace for tensile testing machines which can achieve up to 2000 degrees centigrade in air for isothermal conditions and up to 1750 degrees C in cyclic loading.  They also developed a highly sensitive alignment capability for reliable heating methods for uniaxial testing up to 1600 degrees centigrade.  They perform much of their high temperature testing using local heating and thus cold grips.  Again many of these facilities have been individually designed by the staff.<BR>
 There is a seven-person effort headed by Dr. Bullock on preparation and evaluation of ceramic matrix composites (carbon fibers in a silicon nitride matrix).  They coat the fibers with boron nitride to provide for weak interfaces to enhance toughness, and consolidation is by hot pressing.  Dr. Ceccone has a good effort in joining ceramics (silicon nitride) using diffusion bonding and brazing.  He uses a partial transient liquid phase approach, and includes a nice effort on residual stress modeling and measurement.  Dr. Bresser's metallurgical research centers around: coatings for Ni-base superalloys, including aluminides and MCrAIY coatings, where M is Fe,Ni, or Co; and thermomechanical fatigue of coated and uncoated Ni-base alloy single crystals.<P>

<B>4. Research at the National Ceramic Centre of the Netherlands Energy Research Foundation (ECN) </B><P>

   We were hosted by Dr. L.A. Correia.  She first gave us an overview of ECN, and then focused on their R&D efforts in ceramics.  ECN is the leading center for energy research in the Netherlands.  Their business units work on renewable energy sources (sun, wind and biomass), energy from fossil fuels, the rational use of energy and materials, nuclear energy, radiation technology and policy studies.  ECN's principle mission is to develop innovative technologies and design and to commercialize energy-efficient products for an environmentally safe and sustainable energy supply at an affordable price.  They have a staff of about 750, and carry out national and international R&D for the Dutch Government, Dutch industries, the European Union, foreign governments, and international industries and agencies.  They are similar in many respects to DOE's Pacific Northwest Labs in Hanford, WN.<P>

   The National Ceramic Centre focuses on the development and production of components based on engineering ceramics.  Their charter is broad, ranging from structural ceramics to solid oxide fuel cells.  In 1987 they embarked on a vigorous program (along with the rest of the world) on high temperature ceramic superconductors.  After several years they stopped this research when funding was terminated.  They have excellent ceramic processing, characterization, and testing capabilities.  In the solid oxide fuel cell (SOFC)  research they are pursuing the flat plate concept with metal separator plates (other laboratories throughout the world are investigating tubular and monolithic configurations).  Their research has produced ceramic cells which yielded 0.84 W/cm2.  They have no plans to initiate research on solid freeform fabrication (i.e. selected laser sintering, 3D ink jet printing, etc.), which is rapidly gaining momentum in the U.S., especially for prototyping of ceramic components.<P>

<B>5.  Assessment</B><P>

The testing facilities for tensile, flexural, creep and fatigue testing are unique and first rate.  The fabrication facilities are adequate to produce the materials needed for testing.  Most of the composites efforts at both facilities seems to be shifting from structural applications to functional materials and energy end-uses such as fuel cells, heat exchangers, and solar cells.  US investigators should visit Petten and study their testing facilities for possible duplication in the US.<P>

<B>6. Contacts</B><P>

   For further general information or comments please contact:<P>

   Dr. Ben A. Wilcox or Dr. J.J. (Jack) Mecholsky<BR>
