<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter #2</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>August 20, 1996<BR>
European Materials Science and Engineering<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/wilcox.htm">B.A. Wilcox</A> and  <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/mecholsk.htm">J.J. Mecholsky, Jr.</A><P>

An Office of Naval Research-European Office<BR>
#96-002: Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter</H3>
Report on:<P>

Interdisciplinary Research Centre (IRC) in Materials for High Performance   
Applications  (University of Birmingham and University College Swansea)<P>

<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Interdisciplinary Research Centres (IRC's) in the UK
<LI>Research at the IRC in Materials for High Performance Applications 
(Birmingham & Swansea)
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts
</OL>

<I>Key Words: interdisciplinary research, advanced materials, alloy casting,   
plasma processing, computer aided processing, structural and functional   
ceramics, creep and fatigue testing.</I><P>

<B>1.  Summary</B><P>

The IRC in Materials for High Performance Applications at the University   
of Birmingham and University College Swansea is one of eight IRC's   
established beginning in 1989 by the Engineering and Physical Sciences   
Research Council (EPSRC).  This IRC focusses on metallurgical and   
ceramics processing, with emphasis on a high degree of automation and   
computer control for all the processes.  There are outstanding   
metallurgical processing facilities at Birmingham, including a plasma   
melting furnace, centrifugal spray deposition unit, hot isostatic   
pressing (HIP) unit, casting facilities and forging equipment.  Swansea   
has world class mechanical testing (creep and fatigue) facilities and   
excellent capabilities in computer modeling of processing and component   
design.  The center has about 25 academic staff, 70 research staff, 25   
technicians and 60 graduate students.  The IRC has excellent ties to   
British Industry.  In addition to the $2.6 million annual funding they   
receive from the EPSPC they have obtained an additional $16 million for   
research and facilities over their seven year operation, mostly from   
British Industry.  The quality of research is very high and there has   
been excellent technology transfer to many UK industries.<P>

<B>2.  Interdisciplinary Research Centres (IRC's) in the UK</B><P>

The first of a series of Interdisciplinary Research Centres (IRC's) was   
set up in 1989 by the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council   
(EPSRC), formerly the Science and Engineering Research Council (SERC) as   
a response to the challenge of providing focal points for research of   
international standing in areas where the capital requirements were   
substantial.  The key idea behind the initiative was to persuade   
universities to improve their way of handling interdisciplinary research.   
 A major focus was to enhance University/Industry interactions, and   
provide UK industry with facilities and technical talent to help them   
remain competitive.<P>

Equipment was an important factor behind the concept of the IRC's,   
particularly as a means of catalyzing collaboration among people.  If   
researchers have to share equipment they also end up talking to one   
another about their research.  One of us (BAW) recalls that this is a   
major reason for the success of the NSF Materials Research Laboratories   
(MRL's).  The IRC's are funded at the level of about $24 million a year   
and were designed to last for a period of ten years, with periodic   
reviews to assess performance.  In addition to the quality of research, a   
 major metric of success is how much additional funding is brought in   
from industry.   Historically this has not played such an important   
factor in U.S. University  Materials Research Centers funded by the DOD,   
NSF, or DOE, although interactions with industry and government   
laboratories are strongly encouraged.<P>

There are eight IRC's, and seven of these support research in various   
areas of functional and structural materials, attesting to the importance   
that the EPSPC placed on materials science and engineering research.<BR>   
 These topics were chosen from about 200 suggested research areas.  The   
IRC's are:<P>

(1)  "IRC in Biomedical Materials", Queen Mary and Westfield College,   
London.  Note that QMW was reported on by one of us (JJM) in Materials   
Newsletter #96-10, dated July 31, 1996.<BR>
(2)  "IRC in Materials for High Performance Applications", University of   
Birmingham and University College Swansea (subject of present report).<BR>
(3)  "Optoelectronics Research Centre", Southampton University.<BR>
(4)  "IRC in Polymer Science and Technology", Universities of Bradford,   
Durham and Leeds.<BR>
(5)  "Centre for Process Systems Engineering", Imperial College of   
Science, Technology, and Medicine and University College London.<BR>
(6)  "IRC for Semiconductor Materials", Imperial College of Science,   
Technology and Medicine, London.<BR>
(7)  "IRC in Superconductivity", University of Cambridge.<BR>
(8)  "Research Center in Surface Science", Universities of Liverpool and   
Manchester.<P>

<B>3.  Research at the IRC in Materials for High Performance Applications (Birmingham and Swansea)</B><P>

This IRC was initiated in 1989 and brings together three departments at   
Birmingham University-Metallurgy and Materials, Manufacturing and   
Mechanical Engineering , and Chemical Engineering, together with the   
Department of Materials Engineering at University College Swansea.  The   
Director is Prof. M.H. Loretto, Birmingham, and the Associate Director is   
Prof. R.W. Evans, Swansea. The department head at Swansea ,Prof. B.   
Wilshire, was instrumental in the formation of the IRC and continues to   
contribute to its success. There are about 25 academic staff, 70 research   
staff, 25 technicians and 60 graduate students.  The core funding for   
basic scientific research provided by EPSRC is about $2.6 million per   
year.  Since its inception the additional funding received from industry,   
other government and European programs, is more than $16 million,   
including substantial contributions for major facilities.<P>

The mission of the Birmingham/Swansea IRC is: "....a design-driven   
approach to the development of new materials, novel materials processing   
and manufacturing technologies and the subsequent use of computer-aided   
materials engineering to allow their efficient transfer to industry...."   
 There are six major research thrusts:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Plasma melting, atomization and sprayforming;
<LI>Casting;
<LI>Processing and properties of ceramics;
<LI>Processing of alloys and component production;
<LI>Alloy development and microstructural assessment;
<LI>Mechanical property assessment and life prediction.
</OL>

Thrusts (1)-(5) are mainly at Birmingham, and thrust (6) is at Swansea.   
 The creep and fatigue testing facilities at Swansea are world class.   
 The Swansea group also contributes substantially in computer modeling of   
metal deformation processing and solidification during casting to develop   
software for process and component design.<P>

Selected Facility and Research Highlights:  Extensive metallurgical   
processing facilities at Birmingham, equal to the best in the U.S.,   
include a plasma melting furnace, centrifugal spray deposition unit, hot   
isostatic pressing (HIP) unit, casting facilities, forging equipment, and   
other facilities.<P>

(a)  The plasma melting furnace, manufactured by Retech Inc, Ukiah, Ca,   
uses two 150 kW transferred-arc plasma torches for the cold-hearth   
melting of reactive and high performance materials under inert   
atmosphere.  It is capable of casting ingots in 10cm and 15 cm diameters   
in lengths up to 1.4m with controlled chemistry and good surface finish.<P>

(b)  Centrifugal spray forming of tubular or ring shaped products is   
accomplished by atomizing a molten stream of metal using a rapidly   
rotating water-cooled cup.  The resultant spray impacts onto the inside   
of a computer-controlled reciprocating drum to form the desired shape.   
 This process is carried out in an inert atmosphere or in a vacuum.<P>

(c)   The HIP unit, manufactured by VG Special Systems Ltd, is computer   
controlled, allowing accurate control of process parameters (time,   
temperature, pressure and heating/cooling rates).  The capabilities are:   
max. temp.-2000C, max pres.-200MPa
 max. diameter of work-piece-12cm, max length of work-piece-30cm, max.   
mass of work-piece-35Kg, pressurising atmosphere-argon or nitrogen.  The   
HIP unit has a custom built dilatometer for use in-situ in the vessel   
together with a data acquisition system to record dimensional changes   
that occur during the densification of powders.<P>

(d)  Casting facilities are capable of induction melting up to 25Kg of   
ferrous alloys, resistance melting of up to 250 Kg of light alloys, and   
semi-levitation melting of 5Kg of titanium alloys.  There is real-time   
x-ray equipment for studying mold filling and solidification, e.g. of   
aluminum up to 4.5 cm thick.<P>

(e)  Forging facilities include:  100 ton and 200 ton mechanical presses,   
a 150 ton hydraulic press, and a 500 ton hydraulic press for isothermal   
forging at temperatures up to 1300C in inert atmosphere and for hot-die   
forging with pre-heated dies up to 1050C.<P>

The metallurgical research focuses primarily on nickel, ferrous, aluminum   
and titanium alloys, including extensive work on gamma titanium   
aluminide.  The emphasis is on process development, modeling and control   
to identify the effects of process parameters on microstructural   
development and subsequent component properties.  There is a high degree   
of automation and computer control for all the processes.  IRC was   
successful in developing a predictive model for formation of   
microstructural defects in nickel superalloys during plasma and vacuum   
arc remelting.  In the alloy development area of gamma titanium   
aluminides, addition of boron (via an Al-B compound) provides grain   
refinement and improved mechanical properties.  The IRC is frequently   
called on by UK industry to produce experimental quantities of alloys and   
components for evaluation in specific industrial applications.<P>

The IRC effort on processing of functional and structural  ceramics is   
not as extensive as the metallurgical research, but is very innovative   
and staffed by excellent researchers.  The focus is on understanding and   
controlling the critical parameters in the hydrothermal and emulsion   
synthesis of industrially important ceramics including magnetic,   
piezoelectric, solid oxide fuel cell and ceramic matrix composite   
materials.  In one effort they used colloidal processing of PZT powders   
to fabricate rods with better mechanical and electrical properties than   
materials produced using standard processing techniques.  The improvement   
was correlated with a reduction in micro-defect size.  The ceramics   
research also includes efforts on laser melt growth of complex oxide   
ceramic monofilaments, electrophoretic deposition/infiltration of   
coatings and composite matrices, and processing and modeling of   
particulate paste systems including catalyst monoliths.<P>

Technology Transfer:  The IRC has been tremendously successful in   
transferring technology to British Industry.  Examples are: (a) two   
commercial software packages, MAVIS and DIANA, were developed at Swansea   
for the simulation of heat transfer and solidification in gravity casting   
processes and die casting, respectively.  These PC-based packages are   
used extensively in the UK Foundry industry;  (b) plasma melting   
technology was transferred to IMI for difficult-to-melt titanium based   
alloys, to DRA for gun steels, and to INCO for nickel-based superalloys;   
 ( c) diffusion bonding technology using HIP was transferred to Lucas and   
HIP Infutec Ltd.  Major technology transfer occurs when students trained   
by the IRC are employed by British industry; approximately 35 former   
students now work in UK industries.<P>

<B>4.  Assessment</B><P>
   
There is no question that the IRC has met its objectives in terms of   
developing world class facilities in metallurgical processing   
(Birmingham) and mechanical testing and computer process design   
(Swansea).  The strong computer capabilities at Swansea greatly benefit   
from the Computer Learning Center for Materials, which has over 60   
Pentiums available for undergraduate and graduate laboratories with   
interactive software programs in materials science.  U.S. researchers   
would benefit greatly from visiting all of these laboratories.   
 Interactions with and technology transfer to British industry is   
outstanding.  The quality of education and science and engineering is   
very high.  Fifty PhD's have graduated, and four textbooks and over five   
hundred papers in referred journals have been published.  A major factor   
in the IRC success has been the dynamic leadership of the Director, Prof.   
Mike Loretto.  An internationally renowned electron microscopist, he has   
successfully dedicated his energies over the past seven years to all   
aspects of developing the IRC, ranging from acquisition of space and   
facilities--to hiring of  excellent staff-to fostering outstanding   
interactions with British industry.<P>

<B>5.  Contacts</B><P>

