<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter #3</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>October 22, 1996<BR>
European Materials Science and Engineering<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/wilcox.htm">B.A. Wilcox</A><P>

An Office of Naval Research -European Office<BR>
#96-003: Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter</H3>

Report on:<P>

<B>The Inaugural Hirsch Lecture, " Surprises in Materials Science and Engineering", by Sir Alan Cottrell FRS</B><P>
<OL>
<LI><B>Summary
<LI>Introduction
<LI>The Inaugural Hirsch Lecture, "Surprises in Materials Science" , by Sir Alan Cottrell  FRS
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts</B>
</OL>

<I>Key Words: materials science,  surprises, transmission electron microscopy, fracture of ships, intermetallics, ceramic composites, quasicrystals, fullerines, ceramic superconductors</I><P>

<B>1.  Summary</B><P>

The Inaugural Hirsch Lecture " Surprises in Materials Science" delivered by Sir Alan Cottrell FRS , was presented on October 4,1996 at the University Museum, Oxford. It honored Sir Peter Hirsch, formerly Chair of the Materials Department on the occasion of his 70th birthday. In the future the Hirsch Lecture will be given every other year, alternating with the well known Hume-Rothery Lecture. Sir Alan's lecture was a tour de force both for its clarity and its content of exciting surprises and discoveries in the field of materials science. Included in his "surprises" were: the observation  by Hirsch and his group in the 1950's using transmission electron microscopy that dislocations in Al moved due to stresses generated by beam heating; unexpected catastrophic failure of Liberty ships during World War II because the ductile-to-brittle transition temperature of the ship steel was not sufficiently low to withstand brittle fracture in icy waters; the surprising behavior in Ni3Al where the strength increases with increasing temperature; the observation that brittle solids (glass and ceramics) can be made to fail non-catastrophically by reinforcing with fibers; the discovery of quasicrystals ,or solids which exhibit five-fold crystallographic symmetry; fullerines or , C60, sometimes referred to as "bucky balls"; and most importantly high temperature ceramic superconductors based on the cuprate family.<P>

<B>2. Introduction</B><P>

This newsletter is a report on the Inaugural Hirsch Lecture given on October 4, 1996 at the University Museum, Oxford University.  The Museum, which opened in 1860, is a Victorian Gothic building which houses an extensive natural history collection.  It was a perfect setting for such an important lecture.  The lecture, given by Sir Alan Cottrell, Professor Emeritus at Cambridge University, had the enticing title of  "Surprises in Materials Science".  The lecture was in honor of Sir Peter Hirsch FRS who several years ago retired as Chair of the Materials  Department at Oxford and who just celebrated his 70th birthday.  Professor Brian Cantor, the present Chair of Oxford's Materials  Department, served as Master of Ceremonies.  He noted that the Inaugural Hirsch Lecture is the first in a series which will be given every other year in the future, and will be alternated with the well-known Hume-Rothery lecture which is presented under the sponsorship of Oxford's Materials Department.<P>

Professor Cantor then introduced Prof. Michael Whelan of the Materials Department in Oxford, a long-time collaborator of Peter Hirsch at Cambridge and later at Oxford.  Whelan recounted a number of personal anecdotes and technical achievements of Sir Peter over his long and distinguished career at Cambridge and Oxford.  He reviewed some of Hirsch's early work beginning in 1954 on x-ray microbeams, his enormous contributions in the field of transmission electron microscopy, and numerous other technical and public service achievements during Sir Peter's 26 years as the Isaac Wolfsson Professor at Oxford.<P>

The speaker for the first Inaugural Hirsch lecture, Alan Cottrell, was an exceedingly appropriate choice, since in the 1950's and 1960's both he and Peter Hirsch were at Cambridge University, Cottrell serving as Professor of the Metallurgy Department and Hirsch working as a scientist in the nearby Cavendish Laboratory.  Sir Alan later became Chief Scientific Advisor to H.M. Government, Master of Jesus College, Cambridge, and Vice-Chancellor of Cambridge University.<P>

<B>3.  The Inaugural Hirsch Lecture, "Surprises in Materials Science" , by Sir Alan Cottrell  FRS</B><P>

Sir Alan reviewed many surprises and discoveries in the field of materials science.  He began by discussing Peter Hirsch's early work in electron microscopy where he and his colleagues thinned gold by beating with a hammer until foils were sufficiently thin for transmission by electrons.  This early work was aimed at studying the work hardening behavior of metals.  A surprise came in the early work of Hirsch and his group when they observed in the electron microscope that dislocations moved in aluminum thin foils under the stresses generated by electron beam heating.  This was a major discovery because it did indeed show that dislocations existed in crystals and that they moved under stress, thereby producing plastic deformation.  Hirsch's classic paper showing electron micrographs of dislocations and sub-boundaries in aluminum was published in Phil.Mag. in 1956.<P>

Sir Alan discussed an early surprise in materials science which occurred during World War II when Liberty ships which had been welded broke apart catastrophically by fracturing in two.  It was first thought that there was a design flaw , but it was later shown using notched impact tests that the problem was that the steel exhibited a ductile-to-brittle transition temperature (DBTT) where sustained plastic flow occurred above the DBTT and brittle fracture occurred below the DBTT.  The ship steel DBTT of those days occurred around zero degrees Centigrade.  The original design and tests on the suitability of ship steel were done at room temperature and it was not known that a ship sailing in frigid ice water would undergo this ductile-to-brittle transition and fail catastrophically.  An enormous amount of research was done in the ensuing years and it is known that the DBTT in steel and other metals is complex and is associated with cracking initiated by plastic deformation.  The early solution was to design steels by altering the composition such that the DBTT was sufficiently below the freezing point of water that catastrophic fracture did not occur, even in Artic waters.<P>

A surprising observation was found in research on intermetallic compounds such as nickel aluminides (Ni3Al) which show a very unusual temperature dependence of the yield strength.  Generally, metals become softer and weaker at high temperatures, but in the case of nickel aluminide there first is a strong increase in strength with temperature.  This is very surprising, as well as the observation that there is very little strain rate dependence of the yield strength.  This phenomenon has been studied by a number of workers and is a very complex story.  Research is still continuing in this interesting area.<P>

Another initially surprising development came about as the result of the finding that brittle solids such as ceramics and glasses can be made damage tolerant, i.e., have high toughness and non-catastrophic failure, by introducing fibers and making a composite.  The toughness can be derived from energy absorption by extensive microcracking or from fiber pull-out at weak interfaces between fiber and matrix.  This is presently an exciting area of research and the hope is that brittle solids will become much more useful in engineering structures as a result of compositing.<P>

The 1980's provided three surprises in materials science.  In 1984, Schectman, then at NIST, discovered in rapidly quenched aluminum manganese alloys using electron microscopy diffraction techniques, crystals which had five-fold crystallographic symmetry.  These were named quasicrystals and indeed surprised the world's crystallographers, who thought that such symmetry could not exist.  Subsequent work by Schectman and others using Penrose Tile analogies showed that such structures could be explained.  In 1985, the fullerines were discovered by Kroto (Sussex University) and Smalley and Curl ( Rice University).  These are clusters of 60-carbon atoms which have an unusual structure resembling geodesic domes or soccer balls.  They have been called "bucky balls"-short for buckminster fullerines.  This discovery led to the great surge in present day work in the field of nanostructure materials.  It was recently announced that Kroto, Smalley and Curl will share this year's Nobel  Prize in Chemistry.  In 1986, perhaps the biggest surprise of all occurred when Bednors and Mueller at IBM Zurich discovered high temperature ceramic superconductors based on cuprates.  This surprise discovery was of such magnitude that it sent scientists worldwide pursuing this important area of research.  The field is still very active and applications are being found in thin films for electronic devices and in bulk superconductors for magnets and motors.  It's interesting that the theorists still do not have a universally accepted theory for high-temperature superconductors.  Bednors and Mueller received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their discovery.<P>

Sir Alan concluded with the observation that "our science is rich with surprises".  New discoveries occur with a fairly reasonable frequency.  He predicted that in the future we will see a surprise or scientific discovery in materials science roughly every four years.  He concluded by exhorting the audience to continue their active research and contribute to the future discoveries and surprises in this fertile field.<P>

<B>4.  Assessment</B><P>

This lecture was a tour de force both for its clarity and its content of exciting surprises and discoveries in the field of materials science.  Personally, this was a very memorable event for me.  I conducted post-doctoral metallurgical research at Cambridge University in the early 1960's when Professor Cottrell was Chair of the Metallurgy Department.  He was then making his seminal contributions in dislocation theory and the theory of brittle fracture.  At the same time in the nearby Cavendish Laboratory Dr. Peter Hirsch and his group were conducting their pioneering experimental and theoretical research in transmission electron microscopy which led to such a great increase in our understanding of the nature of defects in crystalline solids.  Cambridge was truly a hot bed of exciting materials science research during that period.<P>

<B>5.  Contacts</B><P>

For further general information or comments please contact:<P>

Dr. Ben A. Wilcox<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5TH<P>

Telephone:  44-171-514-4413<BR>
Fax:  44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-mail:  <A HREF="mailto:bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil">bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>


The Office of Naval Research, Europe, is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology development in European countries.  In order to better meet your needs, our staff are very much interested in knowing of your specific science and technology interests.  Please let us know what they are.  Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of who may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail addresses to us and we will add them to the distribution list.  ONR Europe is on the World Wide Web.  Our home page contains information about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters.  Find us at http://www.ehis.navy.mil<P><HR><P>

The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.

<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A></BODY></HTML>

