<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter #4</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>November 4 , 1996<BR>
European Materials Science and Engineering<BR>
B.  A. Wilcox<P>

An Office of Naval Research-European Office<P>

Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter:  MS&E #96-004<P></H3>

Report on:<P>

<B>Conference on "Ceramic and Metal Matrix Composites-CMMC 96,"<BR>
San Sebastian, Spain, September 9-12, 1996</B><P>

<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Introduction
<LI>Attendance and participation
<LI>Technical sessions
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts
</OL>

<I>Key Words: ceramic matrix composites, metal matrix composites, fibers, interfaces, laminate composites, processing, mechanical properties, applications</I><P>

<B>1.  Summary</B><P>

This conference on ceramic -and metal- matrix composites (CMC's and MMC's), held in San Sebastian, Spain, September 9-12, 1996, was very well attended by representatives from 25 countries.  There were 20 half day sessions for oral presentations and 60 poster session contributions.  Five papers were given on ceramic fibers, and the remaining talks and poster contributions were about equally divided between CMC's and MMC's.  I think that the presentations showed that there has been considerable progress over the last several years in terms of developing the microstructures (especially the interface between the matrix and reinforcement) required to achieve desired performance goals.  The only composite system discussed which appears to be gaining substantial use at present is particulate SiC reinforced Al.  Others, i.e. CMC's and SiC fiber reinforced Ti alloys, show promise in jet engine applications.  However the cost must be reduced-I feel through improved innovative processing-before the composites will see widespread applications.<P>

<B>2.  Introduction</B><P>

CMMC 96,a  conference on ceramic -and metal-matrix composites (CMC's and MMC's) ,was held at The Miramar Palace, San Sebastian, Spain from September 9-12, 1996.  San Sebastian is a seaside resort in northwest Spain located in the heart of Basque country, about 15 miles from the French border.  A major reason for the successful organization and execution was due to the financial and administrative assistance of Centro de Estudios e Investigaciones Technicas de Guipuzcoa (CEIT), which is a non-profit research laboratory associated with the School of Industrial Engineering of the University of Navarra in San Sebastian.  CEIT has about 75 staff plus about 45 students from the University, many of whom perform their M.S. and Ph.D. thesis research at CEIT.  Staff from CEIT conduct research in materials (especially inorganic composites), applied mechanics, micro electronics and  control engineering, and environmental engineering.<P>

The Conference was organized such that there were no separate parallel competing sessions on CMC's and MMC's.  Rather, the program of 20 half-day sessions was structured along generic themes, covering the following topics:<P>

 Processing/Manufacturing (7 sessions)<BR>
 Fibers/Reinforcements: New Developments, Properties (1 session)<BR>
 Interfaces: Synthesis and Characterization (3 sessions)<BR>
 Mechanical Properties: Experimental and Modeling (7 sessions)<BR>
 Thermal and Environmental Stability (1 session)<BR>
 Applications (1 session)<P>

However, there were parallel competing sessions, e.g., processing opposite mechanical properties.  I attended the processing sessions and will report on these.<P>

<B>3.  Attendance and participation</B><P>

The Conference was truly international.  There were about 210 participants from 25 countries, who presented 93 oral papers (including 14 plenary lectures) and 60 poster session contributions.  Five of the oral technical papers dealt with ceramic fibers, and the remaining papers were about equally divided between CMC's and MMC's.  The poster session also was about equally divided between CMC's and MMC's.  There were a large number of delegates and contributions from five countries (Germany, France, Spain, UK, and US).  Participation and contributions were also made by scientists from Australia, Austria, Belgium, Brazil, Canada, Czech Republic, Denmark, India, Ireland, Israel, Italy, Japan, Mexico, Netherlands, Portugal, Russia, Slovenia, Sweden, Switzerland, and Taiwan.<P>

<B>4.  Technical sessions</B><P>

<B>Fibers: </B>A. Bunsell (Ecole des Mines de Paris) gave an excellent historical review of fibers used for reinforcing MMC's and CMC's, beginning with boron and graphite for reinforcing light alloys in the 1960's, development of oxide fibers (especially alumina-based) in the 1970's, and silicon carbide and silicon nitride fibers in the 1980's.  The processing and properties of multifilament fibers in a tow (alumina, silicon carbide, silicon nitride) are entirely different from monofilaments (large diameter silicon carbide made by CVD, single crystal alumina) . The ultimate application depends on the matrix chemistry; the development of suitable fiber coatings; the stress, temperature and environment of the composite; and of course the fiber and composite cost.  The upper temperature limit for using polycrystalline ceramic fibers is about 1300 C because of creep strength limitations.  I believe that single crystal alumina might provide higher temperature capability, but the fibers are too expensive at present.<P>

There continues to be research on development of new fibers.  H. Baldus (Bayer AG) reported results on a new borosilicon carbonitride synthesized from a polymer precursor via melt spinning; G. Chollon (Swiss Federal Laboratories for Materials) discussed the thermal stability of silicon nitride based fibers prepared by a vapor-solid process-the fibers are stable in nitrogen up to 1450 C for 10 hours; P. Doleman (U. Birmingham) discussed the growth of alumina/YAG eutectic fibers by the laser-heated floating zone process.  These will probably have good high temperature creep strength, but I suspect they will be too expensive to gain widespread use.<P>

<B>Interfaces: </B>The interface between a reinforcing fiber or particle and the matrix is of great importance in determining the properties and performance.  Usually a coating is required to provide high temperature diffusion barriers between the reinforcement and the matrix, oxidation protection of the reinforcement, weak interfaces in CMC's for improved toughness, etc.  For CMC's, D. Marshall (Rockwell) and M. Lewis (U. Warwick) showed promising results by coating fibers with rare earth orthophosphates and aligned layer structures (beta-aluminas).  Several papers discussed characterization of interfaces in titanium matrix composites (TMC's) reinforced with SiC monofilaments, especially aimed at understanding the effect of interfaces on the low transverse strength.  A transverse loading test was described by A. Kalton (Cambridge U.) ,and B. Guichet (ONERA) used fiber push out tests on samples with various thicknesses and fiber volume fractions and showed two distinct types of interface decohesion.  W. Clyne (Cambridge U.) discussed SiC monofilament reinforced Ti alloys and speculated that initial debonding may occur as soon as a significant normal tensile stress is set up at the interface, but that subsequent opening of a cavity then depends on the hydrostatic stress in the vicinity of the cavity.<P>

<B>MMC's:</B>  In my view, the most important applications-related presentations centered around the MMC system particulate SiC reinforced Al.  Research on this system has been under way for a number of years and this was reflected by the large number (some 20) contributions dealing with this composite.  A variety of processing technologies have been demonstrated and some of these have been commercialized: pressureless metal infiltration into a ceramic preform; powder metallurgy processing; pressurized metal infiltration of ceramic powder preforms; stir casting followed by closed die forging or extrusion; a combination of spray-forming, extrusion, and thixoforming; and sand and permanent mold casting.  Applications include automotive brake rotors, heat sinks for electronic applications,sporting equipment,and a variety of wear resistant parts.<P>

The half dozen or so papers on SiC monofilament reinforced Ti alloys attracted considerable interest because of the potential application of this composite in jet engines.  S. Sandhu (U. of Surrey) gave an interesting paper on Ti-aluminide composites fabricated by a matrix-coated-fiber (MCF) process using electron beam evaporation followed by hot isostatic pressing.  I think that while SiC fiber reinforced Ti alloys are very promising, the processing must be such that the composites and components are affordable.  This is being addressed in the U.S. by the 3M Corporation.<P>

<B>CMC's:</B>  In terms of applications, CMC's are not as advanced as SiC(p)/Al, but there has been substantial progress in recent years.  P. Spriet of Societe Europeene de Propulsion (SEP) gave an overview of SEP's experience with CMC's in turbo jet engines.  Component demonstrations of SiC(f)/SiC(m) composites were made for flame holders, exhaust cones, and inner flaps which were tested in a Mirage engine.  So far, about 300 flaps have been made.  The Spanish experience in evaluating CMC's for aeroengines was described by I. Gutierre  (INASMET, San Sebastian).  They evaluated SiC(f)/SiC(m) composites for various engine components, but no performance information was presented.  T. Kishi (U. Tokyo) gave an excellent overview on CMC research in Japan (1989-96) and included applications of monolithic ceramics in auto turbines and Si-Ti-C-O fiber-bonded CMC (Tyrannohex) for turbine blisks.  C. Beesley (Rolls Royce) reviewed their experience with CMC's including the possible insertion of a fiber reinforced CMC as a shroud.  He emphasized the necessity of reducing composite and component cost if CMC's are to find widespread use in aircraft gas turbine engines.<P>

<B>Laminate Composites:</B>  Nearly all of the papers dealt with fiber or particulate reinforced composites.  However two papers dealing with laminate composites deserve mention.  In a plenary lecture, A. Kelly (Cambridge U.) pointed out that laminate systems offer the best means of testing ideas aimed at restricting creep at the highest possible temperatures, e.g. CMC's operating at 1500 C.  He also discussed the very high strength of laminates made as strained layer superlattices for semiconductor applications in heterojunctions.  L. Vandeperre (Katholieke U. Leuven) described research on electrophoretic deposition of SiC laminates with carbon interlayers obtained from three types of carbon suspensions.  Depending on the carbon interlayer, various fracture types were observed.  However I think the most important thing that this study showed was that electrophoretic deposition can rapidly produce shaped porous ceramics which could be used for preforms.  The author noted the potential for shaping gradient materials by electrophoretic deposition.  This can be done by switching between suspensions to obtain layers of different composition or changing the solid composition of the suspension.  I think that this technology deserves further investigation.<P>

<B>5.  Assessment</B><P>

CMMC 96 was a well organized, well attended international conference featuring the latest research results of scientists from 25 countries.  There is no question that additional research is required to optimize microstructure and performance of MMC's and CMC's before they are used more widely.  However I think that it is of equal, or even greater, importance to continue to develop processing technologies aimed at reducing composite and component cost.  This appears to have been done in particulate SiC reinforced Al where applications are now being realized.  However, additional processing research will be needed to produce affordable SiC fiber reinforced Ti alloys and CMC's'for a variety of potential high temperature structural applications.<P>

<B>6.  Contacts</B><P>

For additional Newsletters on MMC's and CMC's the reader should consult with ONREUR's Web Site, http://www.ehis.navy.mil and click on <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/jcnews5.htm">High-Temperature Structural Metallics Newsletter No. 5</A> (Julie Christadoulou), and <A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/jmnews11.htm">Materials Newsletter No. 11</A> (Jack J. Mecholsky, Jr.).<P>

For further general information or comments please contact:<P>

Dr. Ben A. Wilcox<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5TH<P>

Telephone:  44-171-514-4413<BR>
Fax:  44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-mail:  <A HREF="mailto:bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil">bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>


The Office of Naval Research, Europe, is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology development in European countries.  In order to better meet your needs, our staff are very much interested in knowing of your specific science and technology interests.  Please let us know what they are.  Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of who may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail addresses to us and we will add them to the distribution list.  ONR Europe is on the World Wide Web.  Our home page contains information about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters.  Find us at http://www.ehis.navy.mil<P><HR><P>

