<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter #5</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>November 26 , 1996<BR>
European Materials Science and Engineering<BR>
B.A. Wilcox<P>

An Office of Naval Research-European Office<P>

Materials Science and Engineering Newsletter:  MS&E #96-005</H3>

Report on:<P>

<B>Structural Materials Centre (SMC), Defence Evaluation and Research Agency (DERA), Farnborough, UK</B><P>

<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Introduction
<LI>Mission and organization of SMC
<LI>Research at SMC
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts
</OL>

<I>Key Words:  structural materials, defense laboratory, dual use, advanced metallics, advanced non-metallics, multi-functional materials</I><P>

<B>1.  Summary</B><P>

The Structural Materials Centre (SMC) of the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency (DERA) was established in 1994 and brought together in Farnborough many staff  working in structural materials from eight Ministry of Defence (MOD) laboratories.  There are some 500 materials scientists and engineers conducting research in three general areas:  Advanced Metallic Alloys and Ceramics, Advanced Non-Metallics, and Multi-Functional Materials.  Their mission includes providing technical advice and research to assist ALL THREE SERVICES.  Approximately 20 percent of their effort is directed toward dual-use research aimed at benefiting both the military and the civilian sector.  They have an extremely capable technical staff and soon will occupy an outstanding new 28,000 square meter well-equipped laboratory.<P>

<B>2.  Introduction</B><P>

On November 5, I visited the Structural Materials Centre (SMC) of the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency (DERA), Farnborough, Hampshire, UK which is a one-half hour train ride (one hour drive) from central London.  I was hosted by Dr. John Morton, director of SMC, who provided an excellent overview of the history and evolution of DERA and SMC, the mission and organization of SMC, and a summary of their current research efforts.  I also spoke with several scientists about their research and toured part of the new 28,000 square meter materials research laboratory which is presently being constructed.<P>

In recent years there has been considerable change in DERA as a result of downsizing by the Ministry of Defence (MOD), very similar to what is occurring in the DOD.  This involves closing, consolidating, and restructuring laboratories, including relocating people and providing the new central research facilities required to support MOD's missions.  The Structural Materials Centre was established in April 1994 by bringing together from various defense laboratories around the UK, some 500 materials scientists and engineers working in structural materials.  They came from laboratories on eight sites, mainly from Farnborough, Fort Halstead and Holten Heath.  In addition to its own staff, the SMC has an extensive network of academic and industrial collaborators.  A major difference between  SMC and  DOD materials laboratories, is that SMC is responsive to the needs of ALL THREE SERVICES, a so-called "purple" laboratory.  I think this is a daunting challenge, but they appear to be making very good progress.<P>

It should be noted that research on semiconductor and optical materials and devices is undertaken in new laboratories at Malvern in Worcestershire.  Here emphasis includes applications such as thermal imaging, gas sensing and ultra high-speed low-power electronics.<P>

<B>3.  Mission and organization of the SMC</B><P>

The major objectives of the SMC are: (a) To be the Ministry of Defence's primary source of impartial and authoritative advice on structural materials research and technology; and (b) To contribute to UK industrial competitiveness and wealth creation via dual-use technology transfer and development.  The research activities are in three general areas: Advanced Metallic Alloys and Ceramics, Advanced Non-Metallics, and Multi-Functional Materials.  The last class includes materials which will have both structural and other functional characteristics, such as structural radar absorbing materials and smart materials.<P>

SMC was the first of four Dual-Use Technology Centers established by DERA, the other three being: Farnborough Supercomputing Centre, Centre for Marine Technology, and Software Engineering Centre.  About 20 percent of SMC's research efforts are Dual Use, i.e., of benefit to both the military and the civilian sector.  These very much resemble activities in DOD's Technology Reinvestment Project (now called  Joint Dual Use Program ).  As part of its thrust in Dual-Use research, SMC is partnering with industry and academia to seek funding of joint research projects from various sources, eg., the European Union, UK Civilian Agencies, etc.  In addition SMC supports, with MOD funds, extramural research at universities and industries in the UK. Their financial plan, which is modeled on industrial practice, has the goal of obtaining research funding from external sources about equal to the extramural support they provide to UK academic and industrial organizations.  It is planned that eventually about one-third of the occupants of the new laboratory will come from SMC partner organizations.  Also, SMC staff will be encouraged to spend time in industry and academia if the joint research efforts will be enhanced.<P>

<B>4.  Research at SMC</B><P>

The new laboratory and research facilities at SMC will be excellent.  In addition to normal laboratory equipment they will have three large bays: one for processing polymer-, metal- and ceramic-matrix composites, another for materials mechanical testing, and a third comprehensive metal processing facility for melting steels, Al and Ti alloys, and rolling, forging, and vapor processing of alloys.<P>

Examples of ongoing research activities are:<P>

<B>Smart Materials/Structures (P.T. Curtis)</B><BR>
Damage detection in polymer composites by embedded optical fibers; shape memory alloys embedded in polymer composites; piezoelectric ceramic, PZT, wafers embedded in polymer composite laminates; hollow carbon fibers which possibly could have materials embedded into the core to perform sensing or actuation functions.<P>

<B>Metal Matrix Composites (C.M. Ward-Close)</B><BR>
SiC monofilament reinforced Ti-6Al-4V produced by foil-fiber-foil bonding, or electron beam deposition of the matrix onto fibers; particulate SiC reinforced Ti-6Al-4V made by mechanical alloying; particulate reinforced Al alloys made by powder atomization/mechanical alloying.<P>

<B>Acoustic Damping Materials (J.R. House)</B><BR>
Viscoelastic polymer composites for noise reduction.<P>

<B>Welding (J.D.G. Sumpter)</B><BR>
Fracture toughness of laser welds in ship steel.<P>

<B>Ceramics (R. Lane; S. Mason )</B><BR>
Piezoelectric ceramic processing-discs, rings, sheets; ceramic -matrix composites<P>

<B>Paints and Coatings ( C. Hitchen )</B><BR>
Environmental issues; performance assessment; new coating development<P>

<B>Blast Protection ( S. Bell)</B><BR>
Armor; large structures; modeling and evaluation<P>

<B>Electromagnetics ( I. Youngs)</B><BR>
Radar absorbing materials; radomes; microwave heating/sintering<P>

<B>Fire Testing (G. Durtnal)</B><BR>
toxicity measurement; test method specifications; assessment of new materials<P>

<B>5.  Assessment</B><P>

The Structural Materials Center at DERA, Farnborough is a very well equipped laboratory with an extremely capable  technical staff.  They are the "corporate" structural materials research laboratory of the MOD, and as such provide the needed technical expertise to assist all three services.  Once their new building and facilities are completed they will have a world class research laboratory.  They appear to have successfully dealt with the difficulties of laboratory downsizing implemented by MOD, and are well on track to being a very effective "purple" MOD laboratory.  I think that their focus of 20 percent of their effort on dual use research is well founded, and will greatly assist in developing collaborations with researchers from industry and academia.<P>

<B>6.  Contacts</B><P>

For additional information concerning the Structural Materials Centre, DERA, Farnborough, the reader should consult:  Advanced Performance Materials, Vol. 3, No. 3-4, July/October, 1996, F.H. Froes, Ed., Kluwer Academic Publishers, Boston. This is a Special Issue devoted to the Structural Materials Centre at the Defense Evaluation and Research Agency.  It contains a Preface by the Director, Dr. John Morton, and ten technical papers contributed by the SMC scientific staff.<P>

For further general information or comments please contact:<P>

Dr. Ben A. Wilcox<BR>
Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
London NW1 5 TH<BR>
Telephone: 44-171-514-4413<BR>
Fax: 44-171-723-6359<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil">bwilcox@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>


The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology development in European countries.  In order to better meet your needs, our staff are very much interested in knowing of your specific science and technology interests.  Please let us know what they are.  Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of who may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail addresses to us and we will add them to the distribution list.  ONR Europe is on the World Wide Web.  Our home page contains information about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters.  Find us at: http://www.ehis.navy.mil<P><HR><P>
The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P>
