<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Oceanography & Meteorology Newsletter #1</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>Meteorology<BR> 
Dr Alan Weinstein</A><P>
  
Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  
Oceanography & Meteorology Newsletter #1<BR>  
British Meteorological Office</H3>

<B>British Meteorological Research Aircraft Available for Hire</B><BR>
The Meteorological Research Flight (MRF), a component of the Research Division of the Ministry of Defense's Meteorological Office, conducts research in stratiform and cirrus cloud physics, volume and particle scattering radiation and atmospheric chemistry.  In addition to their approximately 30 person research staff, MRF's most important asset is their C-130 Hercules aircraft that is fully equipped for long duration (12 hour), large capacity (~18,000kg) flights ranging in altitude from 15 to 10,000m.  The aircraft is available for collaborative research with MRF scientists at no cost or for sponsor supported research at ~L7,5K/hr (~$11,000/hr).  MRF is anxious to establish scientific collaboration with researchers worldwide in their areas of interest.<P>

<B>Aerosols May Partially Mitigate Global Warming</B><BR>
Calculations from the Global Climate Model of the British Meteorological Office's Hadley Center for Climate Prediction and Research show that approximately 1/3 of the global warming due to greenhouse gasses may be mitigated by sulfate aerosols.  This is caused both directly by the increased reflection of solar radiation due to  the presence of the sulfate aerosols, and/or indirectly by reflection from cloud droplets forming around the sulfate aerosols.  Other important results indicate that the annual temperature variability will remain the same no matter the level of global warming. <P> 

<B>British Meteorological Services to Become Customer Reimbursed</B><BR>
Starting in April, funding for the British Meteorological Office (BMO) will come from its customers, ranging from government agencies through private industry.  Presently, ~1/3 of BMO's L80M (~$120M) funding already comes from private interests.  The remaining 2/3 of BNO's funding comes as part of a government appropriation to the Ministry of Defense (MoD).  Starting in April, while BMO staff will remain under the MoD,  their appropriation will be distributed throughout British government agencies, who, in turn, will pay MoD for BMO services.  Approximately half of this funding will be in core budgets over which the individual agencies will have little overall control.  They can either pass this on to MoD for BMO, or return it to the central government for redistribution to other agencies' BMO core.  The other half, however, will be at  the agencys' discretion to be expended on whatever meteorological services they desire, from whomever they desire it.  Initially, it is likely that this second half, called "services" will likely be spent on BMO services.  In time, however, competition for meteorological services may develop.  Time will tell.  <P>


<B>Meteorological Research Flight (MRF)</B><BR>
MRF is an approximately 44 person component of the Research Division of the United Kingdom's Ministry of Defense's (MoD), British Meteorological Office (BMO).  As part of the MoD, BMO is England's govermental-wide weather analysis and forecasting agency, with a full component of numerical models and operational forecasting responsibilities.  The Research Division, under Julian Hunt, is charged with the responsibility of conducting research to improve BMO's forecasts.<P>

As with most modern research establishments, BMO's Research Division requires the use of a full spectrum of tools ranging from in-situ and remote sensing tools and platforms.  One of these is a C-130 Hercules aircraft operated by MRF to support their own cloud physics, radiation, and chemistry research, as well as research performed by satellite, mesoscale meteorology and remote sensing divisions of BMO's Research Division.<P>

Led by Phil Hignet, MRF's three person radiation research studies focus on volume absorption and particle scattering.  The five person cloud physics research group,led by Doug Johnson, studies both stratiform and cirrus clouds (cumulus cloud research is performed by the Research Division's mesoscale meteorology division, lead by Keith Browning).  Research in atmospheric chemistry, led by Ken Dewey,  focuses on tropospheric ozone, stratospheric-tropospheric interaction and OH concentration from HC degradation.<P>

MRF's C-130 Hercules aircraft, based in Boscombe Down, is fully state of the art.  Its crew includes 14 seats for scientific  project participants.  The aircraft has long endurance (11 hours), large capacity (17,600 kg with full fuel load),  and a suite of modern instrumentation including gust probes, aerosol and cloud physics instrumentation, short, long and microwave radiometers, trace gas samplers and a 3 cm radar.  The aircraft is currently used on 36 projects,  including collaboration with US (ASTEX, MAST), French (ETEX, CRAU) and German scientists, covering topics including oil fires in Bahrain, satellite wind and SST comparisons, methane fluxes, .......<P>

The C-130 is available for no charge for research done in collaboration with MRF scientists or for hire otherwise. <P>

Details on the C-130 aircraft and/r MRF research is available from Alan Weinstein at ONREUR <P>


<B>Hadley Center for Climate Prediction and Research</B><BR>
The Hadley Center, an approximately 100 person component off the Research Division of the British Meteorological Office, has responsibility for preparing global forecasts out over the next century for the United Nations' International Policy Formulation (FCCC).  Co-located with BMO's daily operational numerical forecast center, the Hadley Center uses essentially the same model, but includes a fully interaction ocean model as well.  <P>

Key areas of improvement in the model include cloud and aerosol parameterization, radiation, ocean models, ocean and land carbon cycles, and atmospheric chemistry.  Much of the research to develop these improvements is performed by the Hadley Center's sister Meteorological Research Facility and university research supported by the National Environmental Research Center (NERC).<P>

Recent calculations from the Center's Global Climate Model show that approximately 1/3 of the global warming due to greenhouse gasses may be mitigated by sulfate aerosols.  This is caused both directly by the increased reflection of solar radiation due to the presence of the sulfate aerosols, and/or indirectly by reflection from cloud droplets forming around the sulfate aerosols.  Other important results indicate that the annual temperature variability will remain the same no matter what the level of global warming.<P>

Details on the Global Climate Model and the Hadley Center's research is available from Alan Weinstein, ONREUR<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
