<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Oceanography & Meteorology Newsletter #2</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>
28 May 1996<BR>
Earth Sciences<BR> 
Dr Alan Weinstein</A><P>
  
Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  
Oceanography and Meteorology Newsletter #2<BR>  
European Geophysical Society XXI General Assembly</H3>

<I>Key words: Geophysics; boundary layers; air-sea interaction; Baltic</I><P>

<PRE><B>
Contents</B>
1.  Summary
2.  General Assembly
3.  Scientific Sessions
4.  Observations
5.  Feedback
</PRE>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
European Geophysical Society - XXI General Assembly
The 21st General Assembly of the European Geophysical Society was held in The Hague, Netherlands from 6 - 10 May 1996.  Of the over 2500 were in attendance almost 10% were from "Overseas", including about 50 Americans.  The 105 individual sessions covered the full spectrum of solid, fluid and gaseous geophysics.  <BR>
The 25 sessions of the Oceans and Atmospheres Subsection covered a wide spectrum of scales ranging from global through regional (e.g. Baltic Sea Experiment) to local (e.g. boundary layers), over the full spectrum on modern geophysics from solid (earth), liquid (ocean) and gaseous (atmosphere and space). <BR>
General impressions:<BR>
a.  Small, focused  experiments abound;<BR>
b.  Observational S&T is as good as, if not better than in the U. S.;<BR>
c.  Modeling S&T is not as strong, and interactive modeling is practically nonexistent;<BR>
d.  As in the U.S., most European boundary layers research is terrestrial; and<BR>
e.  There is a growing level of pan European cooperation in environmental S&T. <BR>
Notable scientific observations include: <BR>
a.  Under stable stability, boundary layer height may be better scaled by Brunt-Vaisala Frequency (based on stability) than on Coriolis (based on kinematics) and <BR>
b.  Modeling indicates that momentum exchange due to surface waves has considerably less impact on air-sea interaction on regional scales than on local.<BR>
There is much opportunity for cooperation between U.S. and European oceanic  and atmospheric science and technology.<P>

<B>2.  General Assembly</B><BR>
The European Geophysical Society (EGS) celebrated its 25th year at its XII General Assembly in the Netherlands Congresgebouw, The Hague, on 6 - 10 May 1996.  Approximately 2500 solid, fluid and gaseous geophysicists from virtually every European country and approximately 200 from "overseas", including the U.S (~50), attended the Assembly.<P>

History of the EGS can be divided into three phases;<BR>
<UL>
<LI>birth during a meeting of the International Union of Geology and Geophysics (IUGG) in Moscow in 1971 with initial focus on geology;
<LI>expansion in the early 1980s into fluids and gases and publication of its first journal (in partnership with American counterpart, AGU) called "Tectonics"; and 
<LI>maturity in the late 1980s with the establishment of a central office managed by an Executive Secretary. 
</UL> 

Under the executive stewardship of Arne Richter,  the Society has<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Approximately 3000 members in 6 sections (including Ocean and Atmosphere); 
<LI>publishes 11 journals with no page charges (including Annales Geophysicae, Climate Dynamics and Journal of Atmospheric Chemistry of interest to the ocean and atmosphere community);  
<LI>grants awards, medals and honorary membership (including the Fridtjof Nansen and Milutin Milankovic Medal from OA) all aimed "....to promote geo- and space-sciences on a pan-European international level...".  It shares offices and enjoys a close working relationship with its analogous, and much larger, predecessor, the AGU.
</UL>

Assembly.  To those Americans acquainted with annual meetings of US societies, the EGSs General Assembly would had a familiar appearance.  There was a business meeting, award presentations, exhibitors, posters and 106 (most overlapping) individual sessions (including 25 in OA). <BR>
Medals.  Medal presentations of note to the OA community were , the Guttenberg Medal for "...contributions to Solid Earth in general." was awarded to Frank Press, the Nansen Medal for " .....distinguished research in Oceanography."  to Anders Stigebrandt, and the Milankovich Medal for "....outstanding achievements in climatological sciences." to Lennart Bengtsson.<P>

<B>3.  Scientific Sessions</B><BR>
At a meeting this large it is impossible for one person to attend more than a few individual sessions. This reporter spent most of his time at the the Boundary Layers and Turbulence, special Baltic Experiment (BALTEX), and Air-Sea Interaction sessions, and a bit at Oceanography, Predictability and NWP sessions.  From that small sampling, it is clear that European oceanic and atmospheric science is surely comparable to U.S. in quality, if not quantity.  <BR>
<UL>
<LI>Boundary Layers & Turbulence.  In boundary layer research, most of the European investment is in research over land, primarily to improve pollution forecasting.  Most notable was their heavy activity in field observations, in such diverse places as Saheil, Spain, Germany, and Holland. Most of these field efforts appeared rather modest, but first rate.  They use first rate instrumentation, on the ground, on towers and from aircraft, much off it developed locally and sold commercially  by European companies.  All this field activity will contribute to the overall body of knowledge about the boundary layer, that someday someone will coalesce into a major improvement of our understanding of this highly turbulent, very complex region of the atmosphere.  The most interesting new development I heard was a movement away from Coriolis based mixed layer depth scaling toward a scaling based upon Brunt-Vaisala frequency.  The former, after Eckman, is based upon traditional rotation of wind with height in the friction layer.  If this scaling is valid, the mean depth of the atmospheric boundary layer should vary with latitude.  This is not verified, particularly under stable conditions, in the little data that is emerging around the world.  Scaling with inverse Brunt-Vaisala frequency was first introduced in the 1980s by Kitaigorodskii.  Cooperative potential might exist in coastal areas with Navy funding over water and European activity over nearby land.    
<LI>BALTEX.  The Baltic Experiment is a 10 European nation undertaking, under the GEWEX umbrella,  to understand the energy and water budgets of  this semi-enclosed sea and to relate these budgets to large scale atmospheric and oceanic circulation.   Most of this meetings papers concentrated on modeling.  The models were similar, if not a bit behind American counterparts.  Model inter comparisons between various nations' research and/or operational models abounded.  What little verification was shown indicated the models agreed more with each other than with observations.  This is a situation often encountered in American model comparisons as well.  Unfortunately, few model or other studies centered on process understanding.  Although the primary goal of BALTEX is understanding the full ecological picture of the Baltic, no interdisciplinary, interactive studies or even modeling was presented.  
<LI>Air-Sea Interaction.  For session held on the last day, this was surprisingly well attended.  It was worth the wait.  Several papers centered on the role of waves in exchanging gas and momentum between the air and sea.  One interesting result indicated that coupled air-sea exchange appears to have little impact on the regional scale, but greater impact on small scales.  
</UL>

<B>4.  Observations</B><BR>
	Exhibits.  Most of the exhibitors were small instrumentation companies and/or book publishers, of which there are many in Europe.  Other exhibitors, whose activities will be subjects of separate newsletter reports include the  European Commissions Marine Science & Technology (MAST) Program and the Netherlands Organization for Scientific Research (NWO).   <BR>
	Overall.  Overall, the Assembly  indicated that European geophysical science is equal, if not superior, to the U.S. in observational S&T and a bit behind in modeling.  The Hague is an excellent venue, with excellent meeting facilities for daytime work and beautiful outdoors facilities,  the World Court and the Court of Military Justice (two completely different courts) and several museums (including a showing of the Vermeer Exhibit), for after hours enjoyment and informal meetings.<P>

<B>5.  Feedback</B><BR>
The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology development in European countries.   In order to better meet your needs, our staff are very much interested in knowing of your specific science and technology interests.  Please let me know what they are.<BR>
Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of, who may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail addresses to me and I will add them to the distribution list.<BR>
ONR Europe is on the World Wide Web.  Our home page contains information about European activities, conferences, and other newsletters.<BR>
Find us at:  http://www.ehis.navy.mil/<P><HR><P>
The opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P><HR><P>

