<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Ocean, Atmosphere & Space S&T Newsletter No. 96-2</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>August 8, 1996<P>

Europe - Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology<BR>
Alan I. Weinstein<P>

Office of Naval Research - Europe<BR>
Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology Newsletter No.  96-2<P>

Laboratory of Harbor Works, National Technical University of Athens/Department of Civil Engineering: Satisfying Customers Through Solution of Practical Problems
</H3>
<OL><B>
<LI>Summary
<LI>National Technical University of Athens
<LI>Department of Water Resources, Hydraulic and Maritime Engineering of the Civil Engineering School
<LI>Laboratory of Harbor Works.  
<DD>	4.1 Harbor and Beach Evolution
<DD>	4.2 Gas Transport Across the Air-Sea Interface
<DD>	4.3 Wind Wave Relationships
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts</B>
</OL>

<I>Key words:	beach evolution, gas exchange, wind-wave relationships</I><P> 

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
The National Technical University of Athens is Greeces largest engineering school with a full range of curricula from the traditional (CE, ME, EE etc.) through a few specialized areas (Architectural, Mine, Metallurgy) to some of particular interest to the Navy (Naval Architecture, Marine).  Of particular interest for this visit was the <B>Laboratory of Harbor Works</B> in the Civil Engineering School.  Led by Prof.. <I>C. I. Moutzouris</I>, this Laboratory tackles "practical problems" and "satisfies it customers".  They work in three areas, harbor and beach evolution (largest), wind/wave relationships, and gas transport across the air-sea interface.  The harbor and beach evolution programs study the effects of artificial structure (piers, primarily) on beaches and harbor currents and suggest solutions (unfortunately <I>after</I> the structure has been built, not before).  The wind/wave program uses modern telemetry to transmit wind and wave data from throughout the Aegean Sea back to Athens for archiving and analysis.  The gas transport across the air-sea interface program studies dissolved gasses under differing wave conditions in order to understand the effects of structures (e.g. breakwaters) on the ecology of a harbor or beach.  <P>

The faculty and staff at LHW are interested in sharing their technology with U.S. scientists. Dr. Moutzouris was quick to acknowledge the simplicity of many of their projects.  For example, their beaches were sheltered from storms and had no tides to deal with.  However, they often have complicated sand sizes to contend with.  They were interested in working at U.S. sites (e.g. Duck, N.C.) and/or suggesting Greek sites for U. S. programs.<P>

<B>2. National Technical University of Athens</B><BR>
NTUA can trace its ancestry to 1837 as the "Royal School of Arts", later changed to the "School of Industrial Arts" in 1843.  Today it is located over a 100 hectare campus in the Zografou area of Athens.  The teaching staff numbers 560, supported by 900 post-graduate students, 264 laboratory technicians and 242 administrative staff.  Its disciplines include Civil, Mechanical, Electrical, Architectural, Chemical Rural/Surveying, Mining and Marine Engineering, and Naval Architecture, as well as a General Studies.<P>

<B>3. Department of Water Resources, Hydraulic and Maritime Engineering of the Civil Engineering School</B><BR>
The DWRHME faculty includes six Professors, three Associate Professors, seven Assistant Professors, four Lecturers and nine Teaching Assistants (Post-Graduate Students).  This combined faculty teach 27 courses. Their stated areas of competence include Fluid Mechanics (Surface, groundwater and maritime hydraulics), Engineering hydrology (Development and Management of water resources), Hydraulic works (Dams and hydropower plants), Port, Coastal and Offshore Engineering) and Ecology (Sanitary engineering, pollution and protection of aquatic environment).  <P>

Funded research projects over ten years 1982-1991  number 61, worth 2.5M ECU ($3.2M).  This ranks the Department first in the Civil Engineering School and fifth among all NTUA departments. Over the succeeding two years, the department had 24 funded projects totaling 4.5M ECU ($5.8M) ranking it highest in the School and second (1992)  or third (1993) in the University. <P>

Four laboratories function within the Department.<BR> 
	<DD>The <B>Laboratory of Applied Hydraulics</B>  is deployed in a 20X50 M hall that is equipped with a recirculating water supply system with a capacity of 200L/s that covers the needs of flumes, basins and other experimental apparatus.  <BR>
	<DD>The <B>Laboratory of Sanitary Engineering</B> has equipment to carry out conventional as well as specialized analyses for the assessment of the quality of the aquatic environment and of liquid waste.  <BR>
	<DD>The <B>Laboratory of Hydrology and Water Resources</B> affords modern computing facilities with RISC work stations and personal computers connected to the hydrological and meteorological authorities of Greece.  The laboratory also operates an automated telemetric meteorological station in the NTUA campus.  <BR>
	<DD>The <B>Laboratory of Harbor Works</B> houses two wave flumes and a basin 25X27 M with random wave generators, under an enclosure of 5,000sq m.  Instrumentation included measuring equipment for laboratory work, current and wave recorders, data acquisition and processing system for field studies and a series of relevant software packages.<P>

<B>4.  Laboratory of Harbor Works.</B><BR>  
The LHW staff  is composed of four NTUA faculty and 12 soft money people.  The total budget is approximately 120 M Drachma/yr. ($.5M).  Under the direction of Professor C.I. Moutzouris, the LHW has grown over the past ten years by tackling "practical problems" and "satisfying it customers".  <P>

The three main projects of the Laboratory deal with beach and harbor evolution, gas transport across the air-sea interface, and wind wave relationships.  The first of those three is by far the largest.  <P>

<B>4.1 Harbor and Beach Evolution</B><BR>
One example of the beach and harbor evolution program deals with the beach at Aghios Nikolaos, in Crete.  A new harbor for small craft was built to accommodate the growing tourist traffic in small yachts.  This harbor seriously modified the local currents such that the beach that brought the tourists in the first place, became almost completely eroded within one year.  In 1992 the relevant public authority commissioned a study to find out what happened and suggest remedies.  <P>

The team from the Harbor Works set out current meters etc. and ran some models (One called "Mike 21").  From this, they designed a system of two detached breakwaters to correct the problem.. The local authorities built the breakwaters and filled in part of the beach.  Within one winter half of the original beach had returned.  This winter the beach is still growing.  I actually saw the beach when I was in Crete attending the 3rd European Underwater Acoustics Conference described in a separate ONREUR Newsletter.  It was well populated with bathers.  Their customers, the harbor authorities, are very happy.  Original results of this program were reported at <B>HYDRO-PORT 94 in Yokosuka, Japan</B> (Reprint available from ONREUR).  Follow on will be reported at the upcoming  American Society of Civil Engineering (ASCE) International Conference on Coastal Engineering in Orlando, FL in September 1996.<P>


This is but one example of their approach to solving practical problems.  Another they showed related to changes in Pireas Harbor due to installation of a pier.  In this case they not only took in situ observations and ran models, but also replicated the harbor in their laboratory basin.<P>

They are interested in sharing their technology with U.S. scientists.  They were quick to acknowledge that their beaches were sheltered from storms and had no tides to deal with.  However, they often have complicated sand sizes to contend with.  They were interested in working at Duck and/or suggesting Greek sites for Duck follow-ons.<P>

<B>4.2 Gas Transport Across the Air-Sea Interface.</B><BR>
This project, led by Dr. Ekaterini Daniil, is studying oxygenation due to wave breaking.  The application is to understand the ecological effects of wave breaking.  In particular the effects of  a rubble mound breakwater of the S-type were studied using the wave flume in their laboratory.  The water was chemically deoxygenated and dissolved oxygen concentrations were followed over time in characteristic locations.  Experimental results showed that transfer velocity increased with increasing wave height for waves of the same frequency and with increasing frequency for waves of the same height.  This and other similar results were reported in <B>1995 Annales Geophysicae (Vol 13, 1039-1046)</B>.

<B>4.3 Wind Wave Relationships.</B><BR>
This project uses telemetered data from across the Aegean Sea to monitor wave heights under changing weather conditions.  The raw data is stored locally, modestly processed and transmitted to Athens routinely or upon demand.  If weather conditions change, data is take more or less frequently, and transmitted accordingly.<P>

<B>5.  Assessment</B><BR>
The Laboratory of Harbor Works is led by an aggressive director who has identified an area of importance to a community in Greece that is willing to fund his services.  He uses state of the are technology and models to serve real world customers.  He has expressed willingness to cooperate with U.S. programs in his area.  It is worth supporting a visit by him to several U.S. centers doing similar science and technology.  A visit will be arranged in 1997.<P>

<B>6. Contacts</B><BR>
For further general information and copies of the reprints mentioned please contact<BR>
	Dr. Alan Weinstein<BR>
	Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
	223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
	London NW1 5TH<BR>
	Telephone:	44 171 514-4964<BR>
	FAX:		44 171 723-6359<BR>
	E-Mail		aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil<P>

For direct information at the Laboratory please contact<BR>
	Dr. C.I. Moutzouris, Director<BR>
	Laboratory of Harbor Works, Civil Engineering Department, National Technical<BR> University of Athens<BR>
	5, Iroon Polytechniou, 15773 Zografou, Greece<BR>
	Telephone:	30-1-7722367 or 7722376      <BR>
	FAX:		30-1-7722368      <BR>
	E-Mail: 		lhw@central.ntia.gr<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A></BODY></HTML>
