<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Ocean, Atmosphere & Space S&T Newsletter No. 96-3</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>August 9, 1996<P>

Europe - Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology<BR>
Alan I. Weinstein<P>

Office of Naval Research - Europe<BR>
Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology Newsletter No.  96-3<P>

Third European Conference on Underwater Acoustics</H3>

<OL><B>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Venue
<LI>Sessions
<LI>Attendance
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts</B>
</OL>

<I>Key words:  Ocean acoustics, scattering, propagation, modeling, signal processing, communications, tomography, reverberation</I><P>

<B>1. Summary</B><BR>
The 3rd European Conference on Underwater Acoustics was held in <B>Heraklion, Crete, Greece on 24-28 June 1996</B>. 245 Scientists and engineers from 21 countries worldwide attended.. The conference had four simultaneous sessions each day devoted to the following topics: Scattering, Sound Propagation Modeling, Inverse Problems in Underwater Acoustics, Signal and Data Processing, Underwater Communications, Acoustics in Marine Geology and Geophysics, Acoustics in Fisheries, Acoustic Experiments  and Measurements, Tomography, Transducers and Instrumentation, the THETIS II Project (Acoustic Tomography in the Western Mediterranean Sea), Noise, Reverberation, and Bubble Acoustics.<BR>
There were both oral and poster sessions.  <P>

In addition to the regular proceedings, Dr. <B>Walter Munk</B> was granted an honorary doctorate from the University of Crete.  Dr. Munk was recognized for his career long contributions to oceanography, recently focused on acoustic Tomography.<P>

<B>Notable observations from the conference include:</B><BR>
1) The European community in acoustics is active on all fronts from theory through field experimentation.  <BR>
Major participants include <B>France, Russia and the United Kingdom</B>.  Smaller players include Denmark, Germany, Italy (Largely from SACLANTCEN), Norway, Poland, Ukraine, and Belgium.<BR>
2) Russian scientists had much to add to theoretical work, particularly in <B>acoustic tomography</B>.<BR>
3) There is a major EU (MAST) project in the Western Mediterranean, called <B>THETIS</B>, using acoustic tomography on the ocean mesoscale, that bears monitoring in the future.<BR>
4) There is a need for a workshop on the naval applications of ocean acoustics, involving U.S. and European workers.<P>

<B>2. Venue</B><BR>
The Third European Conference on Underwater Acoustics was held at the Institute of Applied and Computational Mathematics (IACM), one of the seven institutes of the Foundation for Research and Technology-HELLAS (FORTH), approximately 10 miles SE of Heraklion, Crete, Greece on 24 - 28 June 1996.  245 Scientists and engineers from 21 countries attended.<P>

FORTH was created in 1987 out of the Research Center of Crete, when the institutes of Patras and Salonica joined the University of Crete for this foundation.  The local hosts for this conference were from the Division of Underwater Acoustics, one of the three Foundation divisions.  Led by Professor J. S. Papadakus, the scientific committee included representation from Denmark, Germany, Italy, France, Spain and Great Britain.  <P>

Each day, there were  four separate, parallel oral sessions that started after a an invited plenary paper.  A total of 154 oral papers were presented.  These were supplemented by 42 poster papers.<P>

<B>3.  Sessions</B><BR>
Oral and poster sessions were devoted to the following topics:  Scattering, Sound Propagation Modeling, Inverse Problems in Underwater Acoustics, Signal and Data Processing, Underwater Communications, Acoustics in Marine Geology and Geophysics, Acoustics in Fisheries, Acoustic Experiments  and Measurements, Tomography, Transducers and Instrumentation, the THETIS II Project (Acoustic Tomography in the Western Mediterranean Sea), Noise, Reverberation, and Bubble Acoustics.<P>

<B>4.  Attendance</B><BR>
The leading countries in Europe in this area, as judged by participation at this meeting, in decreasing order of attendance, are France, United Kingdom, and Italy (Largely from SACLANTCEN).  Other European countries with representation, again in decreasing order of attendance, included Greece (Possibly because they were the host country), Norway, Denmark, Germany, Russia, Poland, Sweden, Netherlands and Belgium.  From North America, the countries represented were USA and Canada.  From Asia, there were attendees from China, Singapore and Japan.<P>

In specific areas, Scattering was led by France, Both Modeling and Inverse Problems by USA and France, Underwater communications by France, Tomography by Russia, Experiments by United Kingdom and France, Transducers by France and United Kingdom, Noise by USA and UK, Bubbles by UK.  Acoustics in Geology and Geophysics and Acoustics in Fisheries had the most number of countries, but were not dominated by any single one. <P>

<B>5.  Assessment</B><BR>
Based upon conversation before, during and after this conference, it is clear that the U.S. acoustics community in the Navy is familiar with most of the European activity, except for that in France.  Judging from this conference, there is much work being done in France.  It is appropriate to explore that further.<P>

Russian scientists are particularly active in acoustic tomography.  They presented several interesting papers on novel techniques for retrieving ocean parameters (currents, density). <P>

The major program in acoustics that is sponsored by the European Unions Marine Science and Technology (MAST) Program is called THETIS.  It started out using tomography for offshore probing.  It has recently moved further offshore for mesoscale features in the western Mediterranean.. Data has been collected and is in analysis presently.  Although little new is coming out of this program, it is a major tomography experiment on the mesoscale and bears monitoring by the Navy S&T community.<P>

This conference dealt largely with research in acoustics.  A few poster papers were on applications.  A longer meeting devoted primarily to applications appears appropriate.<P>

<B>6.  Contacts</B><BR>
For further general information and copies of the reprints please contact<BR>
	Dr. Alan Weinstein<BR>
	Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
	223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
	London NW1 5TH<BR>
	Telephone:	44 171 514-4964<BR>
	FAX:		44 171 723-6359<BR>
	E-Mail		aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil<P>

Conference address for personal copy of proceedings and information on future conference:<BR>
	Secretariat <BR>
	Foundation for Research and Technology - HELLAS (FORTH)<BR>
	Institute of Applied and Computational Mathematics<BR>
	P.O. Box 1527<BR>
	711 10 Heraklion Crete<BR>
	GREECE - HELLAS<BR>
	Telephone:	30 81 391802<BR>
	FAX:		30 81 391801<BR>
	E-Mail:		conference@iacm.forth.gr<P><HR><P><A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil:80/onrnews.htm">Return to ONREUR Newsletters</A></BODY></HTML>


