<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Oceanography & Meteorology Newsletter #4</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><BR>
<H3>
1 October 1996<BR>
Europe - Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology<BR> 
Dr Alan Weinstein</A><P>
  
Office of Naval Research - European Office<BR>  
Oceanography and Meteorology Newsletter 96-4<BR>  
Seventh AMS Conference on Mesoscale Processes - The Mesoscale has grown</H3>

<OL><B>
<LI>Summary
<LI>The American and Royal Meteorological Societies
<LI>Sessions
<LI>Attendance
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts</B>
</OL>

<I>Key words:  Meteorology, Weather fronts, Cyclones, Storms, Convection, Orography, Weather forecasting, Atmospheric boundary layer, Gravity waves.</I><P>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
<B>Seventh Conference on Mesoscale Processes of the American Meteorological Society</B> was held in <B>Reading, UK on September 9 - 13, 1996</B>.  Recognizing the important historic, as well as current, role of  European Meteorologists in general, and UK in particular, the AMS chose Reading as the site for their mesoscale processes meeting. The Royal Meteorological Society served as co-sponsor.  The University of Reading was the venue.<P>

The conference reflected the current expanded definition of mesoscale by devoting the first full day and much of the third (almost 1/3 of the total conference) to the study and forecasting of extratropical cyclones.  The remainder of the conference dealt with the more standard mesoscale topics of convection (both tropical and extra tropical), orographic forcing, the boundary layer and gravity waves..  This expansion into the traditional synoptic scale reflects the increasingly scale interactive nature of weather research and operations these days.  <P>
 
The majority of the approximately 300 attendees came from the United States and the UK.  However there was considerable participation from mainland European countries, as well as other North Americans and Asians.  From the attendance, it is clear that mesoscale meteorology is of world-wide interest these days.  This forum was an excellent opportunity to bring together this varied geographical interest. <P>

Notable among the overall observations were the following:<BR>
(1) There is very important scale interaction between convective and orographic processes on the traditional mesoscale and such synoptic scale processes and phenomena as baroclinic instability, fronts, cyclones, etc., that can send energy either up or down scale. Such scale interaction has tied the previous somewhat separated mesoscale and synoptic communities much closer together.<BR>
(2) Computer technology has brought practical numerical modeling down to scales were classical mesoscale phenomena (e.g. squall lines, sea breezes, mountain winds) are resolvable, thereby unleashing important new observational considerations.<BR>
(3) In view of the growing availability of  "non-conventional" observing tools (radar, wind profilers, satellite data), data assimilation has taken on greater importance in numerical weather prediction on all scales.  In combination with growing computer power, this greater emphasis on data assimilation is making previously esoteric methods (e.g. adjoint), commonplace.    <BR> 
(4) Appreciation for the impact of initial condition errors on numerical forecast skill has generated considerable interest in targeting observations where they can have the most impact on forecast skill, thereby heralding a lively competition for ideas on how to best identify potential areas for such targeting.<P>

<B>2.  The American and Royal Meteorological Societies.</B><BR>
Readers of this newsletter need no introduction to either the <B>American or Royal Meteorological Societies</B>.  The AMS is headquartered in Boston, Ma and has over 11,00 members and a full range of publications and scientific meetings.  The RMS headquarters is in Reading.  Its membership is approximately 3200 and it also supports the full range of meetings and publications, albeit somewhat smaller than the AMS, reflecting its smaller membership.  Many meteorologists hold membership in both societies.  Both societies have long traditions of leadership and communication in their respective countries.  The AMS celebrated its 100th birthday last year and the RMS is scheduled to celebrate its 150th in 1999.  Their joint sponsorship of this conference reflects the growing international nature of current weather research.<P>

<B>3.  Sessions</B><BR>
In order to accommodate the inevitably large number of submissions, particularly in light of the expansion of mesoscale meteorology into traditional synoptic scales, conference organizers had to resort to both parallel sessions and poster papers.  Fortunately, parallel sessions were only required on one of the four conference days.  This was Tuesday, for the Tropical Weather Systems (aka Tropical Convection) and Orographic Processes sessions. <P>

Poster sessions were preceded by a short oral session when poster authors had one minute to summarize their papers to wet the appetite of prospective viewers.   Following these oral summary sessions, specific time was set aside for poster paper viewing that did not compete with oral sessions.  This combination of short reviews and specific viewing time made the poster presentations more important parts of this conference than at others.<P>

<B>3.1 Extratropical Cyclones</B><BR>
The conference started at the large end of the newly defined mesoscale, with one full day devoted to  extratropical cyclones.  It is hard to think of one process, one technique, one relevant geographical domain, or forcing type that was not discussed.  Processes covered the range from inertial, through wave and barotropic, to baroclinic.  Techniques included theoretical studies, modelling (including just about all of the current models on both sides of the ocean), and case studies of individual events.  Domains included sea, land and both, from oceans (Pacific and Atlantic), through seas (e.g. Adriatic, Mediterranean), to lakes (e.g. U/S. Great Lakes), through continents (North America and Europe), to land-sea interface zones (e.g. eastern Pacific cyclones coming ashore onto the U.S. west coast).  Forcing covered the spectrum form orographic, through kinematic to adiabatic.  <P>

In the end, almost all of the processes being explained are presently included in one form or another in todays numerical models.  Modern computing power has made it possible to run these models with ever higher resolution.  Yet, with all the wealth of data, understanding and insight that has been accumulated over the years, numerical forecasts are considered good if, as in the words of one author, "....they have the right shape, and (are) close in space and time".  In this instance "close" in space and time were 10s of miles and hours.  While that is considered a synoptic scale success by most research standards, it is far from the mark in true forecasting satisfaction.  A customer on the ground who was only 10 miles from a forecast rainfall event, or right under one that came a couple of hours early or late, would not be satisfied with this "success"..  Unfortunately, little light was shed in this session on how to assimilate all our growing understanding (or is it just "explanation" ) of individual or theoretical into progress from a research success into an operational one on the scale of fronts and cyclones.  <P>

<B>3.2  Tropical Weather Systems</B><BR>
Held in parallel with Sessions 3.3. below, most of the papers in this session dealt with observations and/or modelling done in conduction with the TOGA-COARE program in the tropical Pacific Ocean.  Understanding of tropical convection was the underlying goal of this major international program.  Hence, most of the papers dealt with observations (radar, wind profilers, satellites) and modelling of mesoscale convective complexes (MCCs), squall lines and other similar convective systems.  It is clear that the international weather research community has only begun to scratch the surface of the TOGA-COARE data.  We will be hearing about this experiment for years to come.<P>

Notwithstanding the dominance of TOGA-COARE papers in this part of the conference, the last session in this series looked at tropical convection in such other areas as coastal Australia, the Gulf of California, around Taiwan and over Thailand.  It was hard to discern any unifying theme or results from these papers other than their concentration on some very local phenomenon that had more individuality than similarity with others in this session.  Much needs to be done in drawing some commonality between varies local processes world-wide. <P>

<B>3.3  Orographic Processes</B><BR>
Held in parallel with Sessions 3.2 above, papers in this session covered the full spectrum of orographic forcing from isolated hills, through low ridges to high mountain ranges.  Papers dealing with coastal topography shared time with those over the more conventional inland mountains.  As might be expected at a conference in Europe, many of the papers described flow over and around the Alps and the Pyrenees.  However, the US Rockies and coastal California as served as the venue for several of the papers.  <P>

In the end, it is clear that topography is just as important a forcing factor as is convection.  The former is dominant in the tropics where moisture is greater and stability less.  Orography becomes more important as moisture declines and stability grows.  Lee waves, of course are the extreme of this progression.<P>

<B>3.4  Forecasting and NWP</B><BR>
As was the case with the conference in general, these sessions covered the spectrum from synoptic through traditional mesoscales.  It is becoming clear that as computer power continues to grow, previously impractical modelling is now becoming realizable.  <P>

On the synoptic scale, this has had two important effects.  In the first case it has allowed considerable attention to systematically identifying cyclone precursors.  In particular, the first session in this series dealt heavily with the method that is most popular in the UK and France, called singular vectors.  The second important impact of growing computer power on synoptic forecasting has been the increasing use of adjoint data assimilation. <P>  

On the traditional mesoscale, the growing availability of computer power has led to the growth of non-hydrostatic models, as ever higher resolution has become possible. Grid spacing of the order of kms is now making it possible to resolve individual thunderstorms, squall lines and mountain valleys in mesoscale models.  Such resolution calls for systematic assimilation from such heretofore non-conventional observation tools initializing numerical models as radar, wind profilers and clouds from satellites.  Adjoint data assimilation, that was originally introduced in conjunction with synoptic weather prediction, is now gaining increasing use in assimilating this high temporal and spatial resolution data in mesoscale models as well.  <P>

<B>3.5  Extratropical Convection</B><BR>
With this session, the conference return the more conventional mesoscale phenomenon such as thunderstorms (with and without hail), squall lines, mesoscale convective systems and tornadoes.  The papers presented here covered the spectrum from theory through observations (both case studies and compilations) to numerical models.  It is clear from these papers that the available of observing tools, from radar to lightning detectors, when combined with sophisticated models, present a powerful arsenal for uncovering the secrets of severe storms that plague humankind on virtually all of the worlds continents.  Those in Europe are rarer and usually less intense than those in the U.S., but when they do occur they can be just as devastating.  Unfortunately, these sessions showed that we have a long way to go before we can reliably predict the occurrence or evolution of these systems.  <P>

<B>3.6  Boundary Layer</B><BR>
The boundary layer is where the atmosphere touches the earth (and/or ocean).  It is in this layer that we live.  More important for physical understanding, it is through this layer that all energy is transferred from the surface to the air.  Papers in this session covered both latent and sensible heat transfer and well as the effects of friction.  Among the more interesting papers in this session were those that dealt with the interaction of fronts and the boundary layer.  Unfortunately (for this reporter) only one paper dealt with air-sea coupling on the mesoscale.  <P>

<B>3.7 Gravity Waves, etc.</B><BR>
By the "etc." in the title of these sessions, you can draw the correct conclusion that they occurred at the end of the conference and included papers that could not logically fit in elsewhere.  While gravity were the waves most commonly discussed, other waves included internal and inertial.  <P>

<B>3.8 Special Programs</B><BR>
Just as TOGA-COARE has served as a focus of attention for tropical convection, two upcoming programs that were discussed at this conference hold similar potential for extratropical cyclogenesis and orographic forcing.  The former is called the Fronts and Atlantic Storm Track Experiment (FASTEX).  Led largely by UK and French scientists, but with a growing U.S. presence, this program will go into the field over the north Atlantic during the winter of 1997.  Its primary focus will be on the prediction of cyclogenesis upstream of Europe.  The organizers of this experiment have assembled an impressive array of aircraft and ships and have interested some of the worlds leading modelling centers. It is surely an experiment with much potential for coalescing much of the extratropical cyclogenesis research presented at this conference.<P>

The second new project that was discussed at this meeting is still in its early planning stages.  Called the Mesoscale Alpine Program (MAP), this project will focus on mountain airflow dynamics and orographic precipitation mechanisms.  Upper level wave breaking, potential vorticity banners and airflow over mountain are presently the main foci of the former. Both dynamics and microphysics are foci of the precipitation component.  <P>

As the name implies, the venue for MAP will be the Alps.  Present plans call for a major field campaign during the fall of 1999.  Over the next couple of years, planning and preparatory modelling will be the main activities.  As might be expected, this program is primarily spearheaded by scientists from central Europe, from France, through Germany, Switzerland, and Austria, to Italy.  To date, U.S. interest has been led by Joachim Kuettner of NCAR and Ron Smith of Yale.   <P>

<B>4.  Attendance</B><BR>
Based upon preregistered attendance, the leading countries interested in mesoscale processes are USA (44% of attendees), UK (23%), France (12%), and Canada (6%). Of course, this was an American Meteorological Society meeting, held in the UK, and all numbers of this kind should be normalized by a countrys total population.  However, there are no real surprises in these statistics.  The US and UK have long been recognized as leaders in this kind of research and France and Canada have shown recent interest.  Perhaps more surprising might be that only 15% or the attendance was from the rest of the world.  That number came from eleven other European nations, four Asian and two South American.  <P>

An analysis of papers in individual session series may be revealing as to where specific national or orgainzational interests lie. In <B>Extratropical Cyclones</B>, half the papers were presented by U.S. authors, (with NOAAs Severe Storms and Environmental Technology Laboratories having half of those), with UK (all from the University of Reading), France (mostly CNRM and CNRS) and Canada (McGill and the University of Toronto) in the 10-15% range and no other country above 5%. <B>Tropical Weather Systems</B> was led by US (60%, led by NCAR and GSFC), France (25%, led by CNRM) and UK(10%, all by U Reading). Europeans led the way in <B>Orographic Processes</B> with 58%, composed principally of France (17%, ), UK(13%), Switzerland (11%), Italy (6%), and Germany (4%), although the US still had 36% (a quarter of those from NCAR).  The US only had 33% (half from NCAR) of the <B>Forecasting & NWP papers</B>, followed by UK (21%, equally divided between U Reading and the UK Meteorological Office) and France (9%).  The most noteworthy aspect of the <B>Extratropical Convection</B> sessions was the leadership by the US (57%, with Colorado State University authors contributing a quarter of that total), with the only other country above 10% being the UK (3/4 of those from the UK Met Office).  The total number of papers in <B>Boundary Layers and Gravity Waves</B> were too small to draw valid conclusions, but both were led by the US and UK as might be expected by their overall leadership in total attendance.  <P>

<B>5.  Assessment</B><BR>
The most notable aspect of this conference was the extension of the traditional mesoscale into such previously considered synoptic scale phenomenon as cyclones and fronts.  Earliest weather research and forecasting centered on these phenomenon and our knowledge and understanding of them is the most mature in all of meteorology. The growth of modern computer power has allowed this understanding to increase considerably, but a "good" forecast on this scale is still off in space by 10s of kilometers and time by hours.  Superb by most standards in the research community,  this "good" forecast is often overshadowed by bad "busts" whose origin is still not clear and whose genesis is the focus of much of the present research in this area.<P>

Modern computer power has allowed resolution of modern mesoscale models to shrink to the kilometer range thereby heralding the rise of non-homogenous models, adjoint data assimilation and realistic predictions of wind events in individual valleys, rainfall events, sea breezes, etc. However, such models require previously unheard of data quality and quantity that will challenge future observation systems and data assimilation techniques.   <P>

Mesoscale meteorology, both from the viewpoint of operational forecasting and research is an international undertaking that is both healthy and vigorous.  Recently completed tropical programs (e.g. TOGA-COARE) and new ones on mid latitude marine cyclogenesis (FASTEX) and mountain phenomena (MAP) should provide the kind of data and modelling studies that will allow the continuation of progress in this exciting weather scale.  <P>

<B>6.  Contacts</B><BR>
For further general information and copies of the Preprint Volume, please contact<BR>
