<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology Newsletter #5</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>October 7, 1996<P>

Europe - Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology<BR>
Alan I. Weinstein<BR>
Craig Dorman<BR>
John Joseph<P>

Office of Naval Research - Europe<BR>
Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology Newsletter No.  96-5<P>

UK OCEANOGRAPHY '96 -<BR>
A testimony to the health and vigour of ocean science research in the UK</H3>

<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Challenger Society for Marine Science  
<LI>Sessions
<LI>Attendance
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts
</OL>

<I>Key words: Oceanography, Physical Oceanography, Biological Oceanography, Ocean Biogeochemistry, Air-Sea Interaction, Ocean Margins, Estuaries, Sediments</I><P>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
UK OCEANOGRAPHY '96, the latest in the Challenger Society for Marine Science's biennial series of ocean science conferences started in 1984, was held at the University of Wales, Bangor (UWB)  on 2 - 6 September 1996.  The topics discussed at this year's conference covered the spectrum from physical, through biogeochemical, to biological oceanography. The domains ranged from coastal margins (including estuaries and beaches), through the shelf and shelf seas, to the deep ocean, from the ocean bottom (primarily sediments), through the volume, to the surface and into the atmosphere above. <P> 

Far outnumbering the normal retinue of established UK ocean science community members , this year's conference, by design, attracted a large number of UK  students and postdocs.   Also by design, the organising committee included participants from other European countries, whose participation was notable.   Other than three from ONR Europe, there were no US participants.<P>
 
As noted by the Challenger Society's president,  UWB's Professor John Simpson, this year's meeting attracted over three times the attendance of the first in this series held in  1984, also hosted by UWB. The 380 person attendance and wide breadth of topics this year, attests the health and vigor of ocean science in the United Kingdom.  <P>

Notable among the overall observations were the following:<BR>
(1) European oceanography in general, and UK oceanography in particular, has had and continues to have, a number of local field campaigns whose success has resulted in the collection of a rich base of new data;  <BR>
(2) Most of the analysis of this field data to date has been primarily as individual case studies, from which overall condenses have not yet emerged; and<BR>
(3)  Much of the local case study findings have analogies in U.S. findings, with little if any mentioned recognition.<P>

<B>2. Challenger Society of Marine Science.</B>  
UK OCEANOGRAPHY '96 is the latest in the biennial series sponsored by the Challenger Society of Marine Science.   Headquartered at the Southampton Oceanography Centre and operating on an annual budget of approximately 18,000 Pounds ($29,000), the Challenger Society is the UK's societal focus for oceanography.  Their primary communication vehicles are their thrice annual Ocean Challenger magazine, their biennial UK OCEANOGRAPHY meeting and other meetings as appropriate.  Started in 1984 at the University of Wales, the UK OCEANOGRAPHY series has been held successively at Southampton, Norwich (University of East Anglia), Plymouth, Liverpool, and Stirling (Scotland).  Growth of ocean science in the UK is reflected in attendance less than 120 in 1994 to over 380 this year.  The 1998 conference will return to Southampton.<P>

In order to focus attention on specific areas of interest, the Society has specialist groups for Air-Sea Interaction, Altimetry, Marine Chemistry, Ocean Modelling. The Society honors one student per year at the Open University and will soon initiate a medal in honor of it's long time Honorary Secretary, Ron Currie, "...to scientist who make outstanding contributions to ocean research.".<P>

After hosting the first biennial UK Oceanography conference, The University of Wales, Bangor returned as host this year  because of a combination of their fine conference facilities and their School of Ocean Sciences, one of the UK's leading oceanography research and teaching centers.   A separate Newsletter describes this School's program in detail.<P>

<B>3.  Sessions</B><BR>
In response to the large number of submitted papers, the conference had both oral and poster sessions. Two simultaneous oral sessions each day were normally initiated by a keynote speaker who set the stage by reviewing past work and suggesting routes for the future.  The only plenary sessions were the opening welcome, the Buckland Lecture by Prof. John S. Gray of the University of Oslo (See 3.12 below) and "A Tribute to the life and work of Dr. John Swallow FRS" by Prof. Henry Charnock, himself a FRS.  The close personal and professional relationship between these two most highly respected members of the UK ocean community was underscored by Prof. Charnock's poignant closing remark that when he has a particularly interesting idea to share with his close personal friend, he is pained by the realization that this friend is no longer there.  <P>

<B>3.1  Ocean Margins</B><BR>
The ocean margin is that critically important zone where the land meets the sea.  As noted by Professor Patrick Holligan in his keynote address,  it is in this zone that human activities have their greatest impact on the sea.  He noted that although great advances have been made in understanding the physical processes in this region of the ocean, considerably less is known about biological and/or sedimentary processes.  By implication, if not direct statement, he suggested that understanding the physical forcing of those two processes holds the key for advancing our overall comprehension of this critically important oceanic region.<P>

Although the ocean margin extends from the immediate coastline out to the shelf break, most of the papers in this session dealt with process on or just off the shelf, leaving inshore processes for other sessions.  As if to illustrate Prof. Holligan's remarks about the relative understanding of physical vs. biological and sedimentary processes, only two papers in this session dealt with the latter. As if to underscore our lack of biological and sedimentary observations on which to even build this understanding, both of these studies were modelling works whose results, although plausible and interesting, lack quantitative verification.  The remaining nine papers in this session concentrated on modelling and observational studies of physical phenomena (currents, tides, internal waves) off such varied locations as East Greenland, Southeast Africa (Agulhas Current), Northwest Africa, New Zealand as well as several sites around the United Kingdom.  Although many interesting site specific observations were presented, there was no apparent unifying underpinning common to all.<P>

<B>3.2 Marine Biogeochemistry</B><BR>
The keynote by Prof R Chester of the University of Liverpool postulated likely directions for biogeochemistry in the coming decade as a challenge to the young audience to think beyond their past training.  Major programs in the 70s and 80s recognized the importance of atmospheric interchange and hydrothermal contributions to BGC; much attention was paid to trace metals, their speciation, roles, and cycles.  Major trends through the early part of next century will include large international interdisciplinary programs, modelling of climate and land/ocean interaction, and continued work on trace metals, all oriented to understanding global cycles and organic marine geochemistry.  The excitement for the researchers will come from the application of sharply focused individual skills in large scale programs designed to answer questions beyond the scope of small teams or institutions.  The 16 short papers, as well as related posters, mostly dealt with analytical techniques and localized studies, but some anticipated the keynote's prognostication by applying data from the major field programs of the last decades to assessments of water mass characteristics and changes, and longer term aspects of BGC cycles.  The session was basically process-oriented, and contained virtually no modelling.<P>

<B>3.3 Paleoceanography</B><BR>
The three papers in this session dealt with sedimentary deposits in areas around the United Kingdom.  There was no keynote speaker for this short session.<P>

<B>3.4 Surface Processes</B><BR>
Discussion of this session will be included in the Air-Sea Interaction session write-up.<P>

<B>3.5 The Deep Ocean</B><BR>
This set of 25 papers dealt primarily with physical oceanography of the oceans beyond the shelf break.  Two papers discussed the freshening of intermediate water in the Faroe-Shetland Channel; four reported on the use of chemical tracers; others discussed results of modelling and observations, both in-situ and remote.  Although there were some interpretive papers, interestingly there were very few on process, and little theory (we did miss one session in order to accommodate a visit to the University's Marine Institute).  Altogether the collection was quite eclectic, indicative both of the traditional wide scope of UK physical oceanography (PO) and of the meeting's emphasis on junior scientists presenting their results.  Harry Bryden's keynote on Variability in the Deep Ocean summarized recent results on basin scale trends in the North Atlantic and discussed several of the current hypotheses (e.g. heaving of T-S surfaces, sloshing of Mediterranean water, variations in ventilation and convection); Bryden made a compelling argument for resurvey in the last 18 months of the measurement phase of WOCE to improve our understanding of the significant basin scale changes.  Although this section was at least as well attended and populated as any of the others, the general impression is of scattered efforts rather than the focused programs, buoyed by EC support, that characterized sections on coasts, margins, and estuaries.  Indeed some concern was voiced during discussion about the UK's ability to maintain its traditional global perspective and strength in PO, given increased emphasis on the economic impact of research, the ever increasing role of Brussels in European science, and the conclusion of the sea going phase of WOCE.  The '98 meeting will likely see significantly fewer papers in this section as the focus shifts to the coastal zone, fisheries, health of the ocean, etc, where industry and research can generate wealth.<P>

<B>3.6 Shelf Seas</B><BR>
Shelf seas are those regions of the world's ocean that are bounded by land on more than one side.  Hence, they are sometimes called "Enclosed" or "Semi-Enclosed" or "Marginal" seas. As stated by the keynote speaker for this session, Prof. John Simpson, these seas have practical importance "   as sources of food, hydrocarbons, ......and (are) sinks for many of the waste products of the surrounding population..."  If properly understood, these seas can be a valuable resource.  If poorly understood their (mis)use can be catastrophic.  <P>

The papers in this session were a mix of physical, biological and sedimentary observations and models studies.  Both vertical and horizontal exchanges processes were described and modelled.  As might be expected at a UK conference, most of the focus was on such locally recognizable seas as the Celtic, Irish and North, although one paper described similar process in the Aegean.  Through a combination of UK and EU funding, a major data base has been collected about the various physical, biological, chemical and sedimentary processes active in these shelf seas.  A synthesis of these observations to elucidate common features of shelf seas was not apparent.<P>

<B>3.7 Estuaries</B><BR>
Estuaries are those regions of the coastal margin where rivers have a major influence.  During his keynote talk, Prof. Dyer gave an excellent overview of existing knowledge about estuaries.  He noted that most of our existing models are highly empirical.  The focus of his message was that estuaries are in change due largely to human activity. River damming is strongly effecting sediment deposits and global warming, although only raising sea level by 1-2%, may effect the tidal prism ( i.e. the difference between high and low tide) by as much as 10%.  Both of these effects bear careful monitoring and study over the next decade.<P>

This session began with two papers that showed how estuary research is evolving from empiricism to physical understanding.  The first showed how estuarine bathymetry responds to tidal amplitude at the mouth and river flow at the head.  The second showed how an empirical relationship of salinity distribution with distance from the estuary mouth could be interpreted in terms of river flow, tidal range and dispersion coefficient.  <P>

<B>3.8 Modelling Ocean Processes</B><BR>
In combination with the Ocean Modelling Special Group Meeting OMSGM), this topic occupied all of the last full day of the meeting. Unfortunately, this session did not include a keynote speaker to set the tone for the papers to follow.  Nevertheless, this session and the OMSGM showed how much insight can be obtained from the correct use of numerical models and the right combination of modelling and observation.  In particular, one paper used an isopycnal model to show how eddies decrease the mean flow.  Other papers dealt with the mechanics of numerical modelling from nesting through data assimilation to model comparison studies.  In the end, it must be remembered that numerical modelling is but one more tool in the box for ocean researchers to use.  It's effectiveness can only be maximized by careful integration with observations, theory and common sense.<P>

<B>3.9 Air-Sea Interaction and Surface Processes</B><BR>
Although separated at the conference, these two sessions have much in common and are treated together in this summary.  In his keynote address, Peter Liss chose to concentrate on gas exchange across the interface.  Much of his time was devoted to dimethylsulfide (DMS), whose evolution can be effected by such unexpected things as viruses and enhanced carbon dioxide uptake by iron.  He illustrated the complexity of this field by describing its four "inters", inter-disciplinary (physics, chemistry, biology), inter-reservoir (air and sea), inter-element (many trace gas compounds abound) and inter-national (a major topic of interest world-wide).<P>  

The remainder of the papers in this and it's companion surface processes session broke into either chemical or physical exchange.  The former covered the range from ozone, through acids to hydrocarbons and trace metals. Many of these exchanges display seasonal and/or diurnal cycles that relate to physical forcing.<P>  

The papers dealing with physical exchange covered both momentum and heat.  The former effects wave spectra through wind, while the latter effects large scale ocean and atmospheric dynamics.  The papers here identified a few important aspects of these exchanges but only scratched the surface of their full impact.<P>

<B>3.10 The Coastal Zone</B><BR>
Virtually all of the papers in the morning session of this section discussed procedures and results from the Holderness Experiment, which is part of the EC LOIS programme (LOIS was oriented to understanding the movement of sediment in estuaries), part of MAST.  Holderness was a major, three-year campaign (major field year 94-95 to study beach and offshore processes and develop models related to sediment movement.  The field experiment is now concluded, and as one of the speakers stated, now is the time to produce "tangible deliverables". From what we heard at the conference, this will not be easy. The afternoon session, after the keynote by Prof de Vriend of Twente University on "Marine Morphodynamic Modelling", had two papers on wave-bottom interaction, and an extremely interesting 3D time dependent model of longshore currents in the surf zone that we will attempt to follow-up on.  De Vriend's keynote was an interesting contrast to the individual presentations, using morphology as an integrating construct within which to apply and assess submodels at the variety of scales needed to understand and predict coastline and bedform behavior.  A major success of the morphodynamics approach, in addition to its contributions to the understanding of process and its effectiveness as a "looking glass" for deficiencies in submodels, is its ability to suggest where and how to (and not to) look for evidence of anthropogenic impact.<P>

<B>3.11 Biological Oceanography</B><HR>
Dr Mike Heath of the SOAEFD Marine Lab, Aberdeen, provided the keynote, focusing on zooplankton studies.  He highlighted the major contributions of Steele and Frost in relating temporal and spatial scales of physics and biology, leading to the concepts of the food web and global productivity studies. Biomass-based models however fail with zooplankton because of the large changes in body size and physiology over the life cycle. Understanding of speciation and life cycles is thus crucial to knowledge of population dynamics and productivity.  This was illustrated with differences between species of Calanus and Alexandrium.  Heath ended with concern for the loss of taxonomic skill and the need for simple molecular approaches as a substitute, given the importance of speciation.  The 8 short papers, as in the other sections, were a mixture of experimental and instrumentation studies.<P>

<B>3.12 The Buckland Lecture.  </B><BR>
Buckland was a natural historian, wildlife enthusiast and prolific writer who left funds to a Foundation that annually supports a professor to deliver three lectures.  This year's Buckland Professor, John S. Gray of the University of Oslo, spoke on "Protecting the Seas: Using Science for Better Environment".  Gray defended science against the claims of the Greens and other critics that science has failed, contending instead that the failure is that of managers and politicians to effectively use science.  The role of science in the decision process is decreasing; we have now even gone beyond the Precautionary Principle which ignores the balance of cost and benefit to where (in the context of the North Sea for example) the 96 Ministerial Conference at Esbjerg totally reversed the burden of proof, requiring demonstration that a substance will not lead to harm before it can be used. Gray demonstrated however, using examples from the North Sea, that scientific analysis has improved monitoring methodologies and impact assessments, and when applied in conjunction with open forum discussions with both Greens and industry has led to effective protective measures during development and operations.  He proposes modified wording top the precautionary principle to explicitly include a scientific basis for decisions, and extended efforts to develop public consensus through open discussions with all groups and new science-based approaches to looking at hard issues. <P>

<B>4.  Attendance</B><BR>
Based upon attendance alone, the leading centers of ocean science research in the UK are Southampton, Bangor, Norwich (University of East Anglia), Liverpool, Birkenhead (Proudman Marine Laboratory) and Plymouth, in that order.  Not coincidentally, with the addition Stirling, Scotland, these have been the locations of the past UK Oceanography conferences.  Attendees from other places such as Reading, Oxford, Cambridge and several places in Scotland were also present. Participation from outside the UK included attendees from Germany, France, Spain, Ireland, Greece, Portugal, Italy, Norway and Russia in Europe; India, Japan, Australia and New Zealand in Asia; and Canada in North America.  U.S. participation was limited to attendance by three members of the ONR Europe office and a couple of co-authors on papers presented by others.<P>

Based upon papers presented at specific sessions, with 20% of it's authors papers as a cutoff point, Southampton focuses most on coastal margins and the deep ocean, Bangor on shelf seas and the coastal zone, Norwich on the deep ocean and air-sea interaction, Liverpool on biological oceanography and air-sea interaction, Proudman on shelf seas, and Plymouth on estuaries.  Viewed another way, with 20% of the presented papers as the cutoff, coastal margins are studied more at Southampton and Bangor than elsewhere, surface/air-sea interaction at Norwich and Liverpool, the deep ocean at Norwich and Southampton, shelf seas at Bangor and Proudman, estuaries at Plymouth, and biological oceanography at Liverpool.  However, virtually all of the centers had at least one paper in every session and virtually every session had papers by all of the centers.  Ten papers were presented by authors from outside the UK, mostly from mainland Europe.  The conference vividly demonstrated the growth of euro-centrism and European Community focus of UK oceanography.<P>

<B>5.  Assessment</B><BR>
Based upon the large number of attendees, many being students and postdocs, and the varied distribution of topics presented, UK OCEANOGRAPHY '96 indicated a healthy and vigorous ocean science research community in the United Kingdom.  Like similar communities elsewhere, UK oceanographers are worried about funding, ships, employment for newcomers, and many other things, but most felt optimistic about the future. <P>

The emergence of the European Union as a major source of funding support has drawn the UK oceanography community closer to their colleagues in Europe.  This support, along with that from within the UK itself has led to many field campaigns whose success has generated a wealth of data about individual areas and processes.  In many case these areas and processes bear striking resemblance to similar ones studied by ocean scientists in the U.S. (and probably elsewhere as well).  Unfortunately little reference was made to this similar work. Since the work of many young UK scientists has its funding roots and data sources from EC programs such as Marine Science and Technology (MAST), it will likely their work will be less known outside EU circles.  We may find the next generation of UK scientists somewhat removed from close associations with US scientists that the current generation has known.<P>

The most important payoff from all of the exciting ocean science activity displayed at this conference will be the synthesis of individual observations into a collective understanding of process world-wide (or at least UK-wide).  Not everything is the same in different areas, but similarities and differences must be identified for real progress to be made.  That identification has yet to be made.<P>

The opinions and assessments in these reports are solely those of the authors and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P>

<B>6.  Contacts</B><BR>
For further general information and copies of the program and abstracts please contact<BR>
	Dr. Alan Weinstein<BR>
	Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
	223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
