<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ocean, Atmosphere, & Space Science & Technology Newsletter #6</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>11 October 1996<BR>
Signal Processing<BR>
LCDR John Joseph, USN<P>

Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
Ocean, Atmosphere and Space S&T - Newsletter #6<P>

Signal Processing Techniques Demonstrated by Heriot-Watt University, Edinburgh, Scotland</H3>

<I>Keywords:  Signal processing; image processing; fractals, remote sensing, sidescan sonar; ocean technology</I><P>

Contents:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>General Information
<LI>Facilities
<LI>Specific Interest Items
<LI>Comments
<LI>Contacts
<LI>Feedback
</OL>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
A research group in the Department of Computer and Electrical Engineering at Heriot-Watt University in Edinburgh is developing a method of signal processing based on statistical and fractal mathematics.  In several applications involving real world data sets containing signals embedded in noisy, textured backgrounds (e.g., sidescan sonar and mammography imagery), they have shown their method can significantly enhance the ability to detect desired signals.  Including a priori information in the processing can further improve results.  They are also investigating methods which can reduce misinterpretation of the output signal caused by instability in sensors.  Incorporating other measurable parameters about the sensor can reduce misleading distortion effects in the output.<P>

The group showed examples of successfully segmenting  imagery containing multiple texture classes (mud, gravel, sand, etc).  They were able to faithfully reproduce texture patterns using a method based on fractals.  Taking advantage of the fact textured backgrounds usually have little or no important information in an image data set, this groups method has great potential for applications where low bandwidth communication (e.g. AUV link to a survey ship) or limited storage is a concern.  Fractal reconstruction of textured backgrounds can reproduce useful realistic (though not identical) imagery at a fraction of the data requirement of pixel-for-pixel reproductions.<P>

Signal processing techniques are often tuned to the specific equipment and environment being investigated.  Investigators in this field may find this a fresh approach in applications where large data sets with textured backgrounds are involved such as remote sensing, ice classification, mine detection, seabed mapping, SAR data sets, etc.  Their demonstrated success using real world applications is a tribute to the robustness of their approach.  It may be worth having a sample data set examined by this group.<P>

<B>2.  General Information</B><BR>
At Heriot-Watt University in Scotland, a research group within the Department of Computing and Electrical Engineering is involved with developing a method of signal processing that applies statistical and fractal techniques.  Dr Laurie Linnett, the groups leader, and Dr Stuart Clarke recently briefed the ONR Europe oceanography staff  on their work, demonstrating some impressive results using real world data.  Their technique has potential applications in a number of areas where weak signals are to be extracted against noisy backgrounds. They not only successfully extracted the signal from real world data, but also demonstrated cases where human senses could not have detected the signal or would be misled by the noise in the data.  To provide us with a better understanding of their work, Dr Linnett arranged for a day long demonstration of the groups work at Heriot-Watt where we were able to spend some time with the team members discussing their specific area.  The group was very gracious and provided us with some very interesting insight on what seems to be a very powerful signal processing technique with extensive applications.   <P>

<B>3.  Facilities</B><BR>
Heriot-Watt University is one of UKs leading researched-based technological universities with a heavy orientation toward natural science and engineering.  Its roots go back some 175 years to the Edinburgh School of Arts, one of the countrys first "mechanics institutes".  First the Watt Institute, then Heriot-Watt College in 1885, it was granted its Royal Charter in 1966.  Previously located in the historic Grassmarket section of "old town" Edinburgh, it completed a 20 year phased move in the early 1990s to a 380 acre park in Riccarton, a few miles west of the city.  There are some 4500 students there, about 15% come from outside the UK.  There are about 900 postgraduate students, 320 academic staff and 450 contract researchers, technicians and other support staff.  The campus includes a 90 acre Research Park started in 1971, the first of its kind in Europe.  Its purpose is to  have R&D-based enterprises located in conditions favorable to long term interaction with the university to foster research based activity and technology transfer.  The park is wholly owned by the university with two phases completed and occupied, and a third phase with all infrastructure in place.<P>

Heroit-Watt has an annual income of $90million, with just less than 50% coming from the Scottish Higher Education Funding Council, about 30% from research grants, contracts and consultancy and the remainder from investment, residential services and other general sources.  The university is reputed for its effective problem solving services for business and industry and has had major opportunities presented by the shift in orientation towards technology research in the UK.<P>

The Department of Computer and Electrical Engineering has about 50 academic staff supported by research staff, postgraduate students and technicians.  The department is involved in a wide variety of research areas including communications systems, networks, sonar systems, ocean systems, image processing, intelligence systems, microwave systems, computer vision and a host of others areas.  During our visit, we spent almost all of our time with Dr Linnetts group in their laboratory, which was a modern and spacious work area in the departments 7000 square meter facility. <P>

<B>4.  Specific Interest Items</B><BR>
Dr Linnetts group demonstrated a number of real world applications in which they have successfully applied statistical and fractal methods to separate signal from noise in very large data sets.  Their methods adapt well to remote sensing  applications such as detecting objects on the sea floor with sidescan sonar, detection of breast microcalcification clusters and masses in digital mammography and edge detection between various textures such as mud, sand and gravel on the sea floor.  In related work, a model is being developed to produce sidescan sonar imagery as output.  This technique provides direct visualization of distortion effects and ambiguity which result in sensor output due to instability of the instrument and lack of incorporating other important measurable parameters such as pitch, roll, ambient temperature, etc.  The distorted output can mislead operators when interpreting an image, an effect analogous to seeing distorted reflections in mirrors at an amusement parks fun house.    <P>

In texture classification and object detection against a highly textured background, it is useful to find a technique which removes subjectivity introduced by manual human interpretation.  The problem is approached by first objectively segmenting the image into areas of various background textures and then locating the object(s) as disturbances against the background.  Fractal dimensions are measured to an adequate degree in multiple directions to use for segmentation without becoming a computational nightmare.  The mathematical basis of this technique can be found in published works coauthored by Dr Linnett and members of his group.  Two techniques can then be used to analyze the data, supervised and unsupervised pattern recognition.  In the supervised method, a priori information about the statistical nature of the texture in incorporated into the segmentation scheme.  This is accomplished by observing "training areas" within the original image where the observer uses representative sections of the image from which the statistics are determined.  This requires some subjective human input in the solution such as determining the number of different textures in the image and picking the representative training areas.  From that, membership in each class is determined on each pixel and the texture boundaries are determined.  In unsupervised  classification, the idea is to automate the entire process so that large volumes of data can be handled and human subjectivity is removed to provide more consistent results.  This is accomplished by applying a "principal components" analysis in which most of the variance which distinguishes the different textures is contained in the first few principal components of the statistics.  The data points fall into unique clusters associated with each texture from which a set of samples from each cluster can be used to construct training areas for each class of texture.  An important characteristic of texture segmentation using the fractal technique is that different samples of the same texture look virtually identical visually, though they would match poorly in a pixel for pixel comparison.  Where a limited bandwidth communications link is involved (e.g. an AUV transmitting data to a survey ship via acoustic link), or compact storage and easy access is desired, the boundaries of the areas and a visual impression of each texture may suffice.  If so, only boundary information, the abnormality (object) information and a set of reconstruction parameters for the textured background are needed to build a realistic (though not identical) image.  This reduces the data package size by as much as a hundredfold compared to a pixel for pixel reproduction.  Though this is not true data compression, it is an effective way of compactly handling the essential data.  The technique works well for busy, highly textured imagery where just a bits of significant information is contained in the background (as opposed to a "head and shoulder" portrait where details throughout the image are important).  The results are quite impressive, particularly in the fact that the technique could be applied to such a wide variety of other areas such as ice classification, satellite imagery, SAR and radar data, to name a few.  In some cases, they had little or no prior hint as to the source the data and we able to extracted signals which even surprised the suppliers of the data.<P>

A fairly new area of their work is their effort in realistically representing motion in data sets.  For example, where sand ripples on the sea floor are fixed, swell or wind waves on the ocean surface involve motion.  Dr Linnetts group is tackling this from a phase shift perspective.  An image, whether it involves a fixed or moving subject, contains phase and magnitude information.  The image can be accurately reconstructed by taking a Fourier transform, then taking the inverse transform.  It appears from their work the most important information that characterizes the image (fixed or moving) is contained in the phase information, however research has been focused on manipulation of magnitude because it is less complex to work with.  Their focus on phase shows promise for signal processing applications such as SAR and radar data sets.    <P>

<B>5.  Comments.</B><BR>
The success Dr Linnetts group has had using real world data sets is a tribute to the robustness of their approach.  Because it is based on the mathematical properties (probability functions, distributions, fractals, etc) of large data sets containing extensive textured areas, the applications are more universal than some other techniques.  Their method can extract signals without knowing the source of the data.  However if a priori knowledge is available, it can often be incorporated to further enhance the results.<P>

Admittedly, the world of fractals and the statistical methods employed are not my area of expertise and I hope I have accurately represented the groups effort in this report.  The results are nonetheless very impressive, showing significant enhancement of imagery which objectively aids interpretation of sensor output, reduces calculation requirements for online use, maximizes the efficiency of weak/slow transmission links and reduces data storage requirements.<P>

The motivation for the work done by Dr Linnetts group is an outgrowth of  the research pattern found throughout the UK today - the goal is to generate wealth (i.e. make a profit or generally improve the quality of life) for the country.  Their association with the Defence Research Agency (DRA) in much of this work is a good example of how the system works.  An agency such as the Ministry of Defence (MoD) has requirements which DRA tries to resolve.  DRA finds a research group such as Dr Linnetts group to tackle the science and technology aspects.  DRA markets the research technique so the commercial/industrial sector can build a system which is sold, in turn, to MoD as well as having a commercial market.  All players gain in this scenario - well, at least thats the theory.<P>

Because the research is driven by a sellable product in mind, there may be other markets for the product, too.  As noted previously, this particular work appears to have potential in a number of remote sensing applications which may also be of Navy interest (i.e. mine detection, ice classification and mapping, SAR, seabed mapping, etc.).  The group is  hard charging and very open to finding new applications for their methods.  Those involved with signal processing may find this a fresh approach to extracting information from large data bases.<P>

<B>6.  Contacts</B><BR>
Heriot-Watt University has a homepage on the Internet at <A HREF="http://www.hw.ac.uk">www.hw.ac.uk</A>.  The Department of Computer and Electrical Engineering also has a homepage at <A HREF="http://www.cee.hw.ac.uk">www.cee.hw.ac.uk</A>.

Information on the group:<P>

Dr Laurie Linnett<BR>
Dept of Computing and Electrical Engineering<BR>
Heriot-Watt University<BR>
Riccarton, Edinburgh  EH14 4AS  UK<P>

Phone:	44-131-451-3357<BR>
Fax:	44-131-451-3327<BR>
	E-mail:	<A HREF="mailto:lml@cee.hw.ac.uk">lml@cee.hw.ac.uk</A><P>

	Other members of the group:<BR>
Dr Stuart Clarke, Dr Judith Bell, Mr Bryan Calder, Mr Yuri Rzhanov <P> 

<B>7.   Feedback</B><BR>
The Office of Naval Research, Europe is dedicated to providing current information on science and technology development in European countries.  In order to better meet your needs, our staff are very much interested in knowing of your specific science and technology interests.  Please let us know what they are.  Furthermore, if there are others you are aware of who may have interest in these newsletters, please pass their e-mail addresses to us and we will add them to the distribution list.<P>

Please note that the opinions and assessments in this report are solely those of the author and do not necessarily reflect official ONR Europe, Navy or US Government positions.<P>

ONR Europe is on the World Wide Web.  Our homepage contains information about European activities, conferences and other newsletters.  Find us at: http://www.ehis.navy.mil.  For further general information please contact:<P>

