<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology Newsletter #7</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>October 20, 1996<P>

Europe - Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/weinstein.htm">Alan I. Weinstein</A><P>

Office of Naval Research - Europe<BR>
Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology Newsletter No.  96-7<P>

Tenth International Research Ship Operators Meeting (ISOM 96) - Lots of Ship Resources Available</H3>

<OL><B>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Activities
<LI>Sessions
<LI>Attendance
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts</B>
</OL>

<I>Key words:  Oceanography, Research Ships, Marine Technology, CTD</I><P>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
 <B>The 10th International Research Ship Operators Meeting (ISOM)</B> was held on <B>2 - 3 October, 1996</B> at the <B>Southampton Oceanography Centre</B>.  As the name implies, this is an annual meeting of the day-to-day operators of oceanographic research ships.  The purpose is to compare notes and share experiences.  There were approximately 25 attendees from 11 countries worldwide in attendance.  The agenda for this years meeting included the regular reports by each ship operator on their activities for the year, followed by discussions on insurance, autosubs, performance indicators, database and planning, Marine Technicians Workshop, ISM code, manning and budgets, vessel and personnel clearences, scientific diving, and deep CTD deployments.  The meeting adjourned with agreement to hold the 1997 meeting around the same time of year, in Spain (probably Barcelona).<P>
 
 Highlights include the following:<BR>
a)  Although the U.S. has the largest number of oceanographic research vessels, many other countries have excellent facilities, and there are a lot of them available.<BR>
b)  There is an increasing use of other countries vessels as part of a "bartering" system,<BR>
c)  All countries share common concerns for budgets, manning and capacity,<P>
 
<B>2.  Activities</B><BR>
<B>Belgium</B> - Belgium has one ship, the "Belgica",  that had a routine operating year with no lost equipment.<BR>
<B>Chile</B> - Chile has four ships, two primarily for general oceanography and two primarily for fisheries.  The main foci of their activities this year were "red and brown tide" research and JGOFS.<BR>
<B>Finland</B> - Finland has one ship, "Armanda" (Flower of the Sea), whose main cruises this year were in conjunction with a Finland-Norway-Sweden survey.  Its major upgrade this year was to improve noise isolation in the laboratories and engine room, at a cost of approximately $1.2M over 3 three years.  Main activities for next year will be a Denmark Strait criuse.<BR>
<B>France</B> - France has six major oceanographic research vessels, operating under a total budget of approximately 150FF (~$30M)/yr.  Their major news of last year was the introduction of their newest vessel, the Nadir.  They are major participants in a three cornered bartering agreement with Germany and England.  <BR>
<B>Germany</B> - Germany has three large oceanographic research ships, and two medium ones.  They are managed by a private contractor.  They made no changes this year.  However, their operation is under review by their federal minsitry of research and they expect to reduce their total inventory by one of the medium size vessels.   "Money is getting scarce" in Germany for all research activities, including ship operation.<BR>
	<B>Japan</B> - Japan has five ships in their inventory.  Three are operated by a private contractor and the other two, that serve as parent ships for their two submersibles and two RPVs, by JAMSTEC.  They are presently refurbishing a previously nuclear ship, that will be the worlds oceanographic research vessel when it is completed in 1996.  This new ship will be called the "Mirai", Japanese for "Future".  <BR>
	<B>Netherlands</B> - The Dutch have one research vessel whose activity is all coastal, in the Nordic Seas /continental shelf.  They lost one mooring in the Biscayne bay, which they never recovered.  <BR>
<B>South Africa</B> - The representitive from South Africa expressed serious concern for the operation of his one vessel ("Afrikaner"), because of decreasing usage.  90% of the cost of the ~$12M ship operation is tied up in salaries.  He is willing to charter his ship simply for the cost of the fuel.  This year his fleet was invcreased by nine smal fishing vessels, for which he has few customers.  Most of the activities of the South African oceanographic fleet is for fisheries research.<BR>
		<B>Spain</B> -  Spain has one oceanographic research vessel that employs thirteen people.  They did 13 cruises last year to such far away places as Antartic, Chile and California. Last year they lost five physical oceanographic moorings due to no response from their (single) acoustic releases.  The discussion that followed concluded that the releases responded to the acoustic signal but jammed before opening.  <BR>
	<B>United Kingdom</B> - The UK has three main ship operators, British Antartic Survey, Scotland Fisheries and NERC.  The BAS has one ship, the "Ross", that is under active deployment from October through May (Antarctic summer).  This deployment accommodated scientists from Japan, U.S. (NASA) as well as Plymouth Marine Laboratory in UK this year.  Their main concern was in replacing the 25 year old ship and with recurring traction winch problems. <BR>  
		Scotland operates two vessels under private contract since 1991.  A new vessels is being procured.  <BR>
		NERC operates 3 oceanographic research vessels, "Discover", "Darwin", and Challenger", out of their Research vessel Support branch of the Southampton Oceanography Centre.  The big news from NERC is the ongoing select panel review of requirements for research vessels over the next ten years, that is expected to be completed in February 1997. <BR>
	<B>United States</B> - The U.S. operates 28 oceanographic research vessels under UNOLS.  These are all at research centers around the country.  The primary news from there was the possibility of adding another vessel, probably a swath design.  Funding for this is under consideration by the U.S. Congress.<P>
 
<B>3.  Other Sessions<BR>
3.1  Insurance</B><BR>
Due the increasing occurrence of bartering ( foreign nationals on host country ships), liability insurance must be seriously considered.  Countries have differing liability laws.  Presently, every operator uses their own carrier, with no group rate possible.  At an earlier ISOM meeting, it had been agreed that large ships should carry $25M liability insurance, and smaller ones $15M.  A candidate group liability plan was circulated among the attendees.  A copy can be obtained from Professor Nixon of the University of Rhode Island, the ISOM leader in this arena.<P>

<B>3.2  Legal Liabilities for Autosubs</B><BR>
This session started with a 5 minute video of Autosub tests.  Autosub is a major NERC undertaking to develop a vessel that will navigate far and wide collecting whatever oceanographic data it has sensors for.  These range from the standard CTD information to more mission specific ones.  
For this meeting, the discussion centered on the legal responsibilities of such vessels.  They are not covered by normal laws relating to dispensing material into the sea, since they move under their own power.  Yet, they are not manned ships.  New ground could be broken in this arena.  After a half hour of discussion, little conclusions were reached other than we had best continue thinking about the problem.<P>

<B>3.3  Performance Indicators</B><BR>
	In these days of shrinking budgets, every organization must defend its performance.  Ship operators are no exception.  This discussion centered on meaningful performance indicators.  For now the standard ones are Days at Sea, Days on Station, Equipment efficiency (including lost equipment), and "Data Quality".  All have their deficiencies, but no better ones were introduced.  <BR>
	An interesting sidelight to this discussion was as description my the MAST representative of how they measure proposer performance.  To nobodys surprise, they count open literature papers.  However, they only credit the first paper in a series that all use the same data.  <BR>
	The NSF representative mentioned that they were abandoning the standard measures and going for one that indicated the ability of the performer to live up to cost and performance estimates in the proposal.  For example, the ability to keep costs within 5% of the estimate, amount of unscheduled down time on equipment.  <P>

<B>3.4  Oceanic Data Base</B><BR>
	There is an extensive data base of all ship operators on the homepage of the University of Delaware.  The address is "<A HREF="http://www.cms.udel.edu">http://www.cms.udel.edu</A>".  Details on each countrys ships statistics and schedule are posted and kept up to date by the individual ship operator.  <P>

<B>3.5  International Marine Technology Workshop</B><BR>
	The 9th ISOM identified a need for such a workshop.  Under the sponsorship of MAST, the first IMTW was held at SOC on 30 September - 2 October 1996.  There were approximately 50 attendees.  Three topics were discussed, Mooring Technology, Standards and Calibrations, and Fishing Technology.  The format called for each session (day) to start with a scientist describing the need and a technologist describing current capability.  Following these introductory presentation were descriptions of specific programs and much open discussion among the attendees.  Plans are underway to held another IMTW in conjunction with the next ISOM in 1997.<P>

<B>3.6  ISM Code</B><BR>
	By 2002, all oceanographic research vessels will have to live under this code.  Presently it is optional.  The only operator at this meeting who was presently certified under it is Capt. Kay of the Scottish Fisheries.  The Scottish Fisheries representative offered Capt. Kays help in getting certified.  The procedure seemed simple, but probably bureaucratic.  <P>

<B>3.7  Deep CTDs</B><BR>
	Deep CTD casts offer a challenge to present winches as they put stress beyond present standards on the cables.  Most operators are willing to extend the standards for those few times when deep CTDs are needed, with few, if any, recorded losses of equipment due to cable failure.  The more serious problem is cable stretching short of actual breaking.  If a cable stretches, its ability to transmit data decreases, thereby jeopardising ship operations during the remainder of the cruise.  <P>

<B>3.8  Next ISOM</B><BR>
	It was agreed that there should be an 11th ISOM.  The representative from Spain offered to be the host.  His offer was accepted, with the tentative dates of 2-3 October 1997 reserved.  <P>

<B>4.  Attendance</B><BR>
	The 10th ISOM was attended by representatives from the following countries:  Belgium, Chile, Finland, France, Germany, Japan, Netherlands, South Africa, Spain, UK (Three organizations including Scotland), and US (NSF and ONREUR)., as well as representatives from The European Community (EC) and OCEANIC (U Delaware).  There were a total of 25 attendees.  Other members of ISOM who were unable to attend this meeting are Australia, Canada, and Korea.  The full description of ISOM, including a list of members with full addresses is available on the WWW under "<A HREF="http://www.cms.udel.edu/ships/isom/">http://www.cms.udel.edu/ships/isom/</A>".  <P>

<B>5.  Assessment</B><BR>
	ISOM is a worthwhile annual meeting that allows oceanographic ship operators to compare notes.  Its duration of 1-2 days is correct.  Most of the attendees are actual ship operators.  The only funding agencies are a representative from EC and NSF.  The latter include ONR interests.  ONR representation is not necessary but would be worthwhile in the future to meet the international participants in the oceanographic research ship operation business.  <P>

<B>6.  Contacts</B><BR>
For further general information and copies of the meeting handouts, please contact<BR>
	Dr. Alan Weinstein<BR>
	Office of Naval Research Europe<BR>
	223 Old Marylebone Road<BR>
	London NW1 5TH<BR>
	Telephone:	44 171 514-4964<BR>
	FAX:		44 171 723-6359<BR>
	E-Mail		<A HREF="mailto:aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil">aweinstein@onreur.navy.mil</A><P>

The ISOM secretary is:<BR>
	Cok van Bergen Henegouw<BR>
	Netherlands Institute for Sea Research (NIOZ)<BR>
	Marine Research Facilities
	
