<HTML><HEAD><TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>November 4, 1996<P>

Europe - Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/weinstein.htm">Alan I. Weinstein</A><P>

Office of Naval Research - Europe<BR>
Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology Newsletter No.  96-8<P>

International Symposium "New Challenges for North Sea Research" - Interaction, Interaction, Interaction</H3>

<OL><B>
<LI>Summary
<LI>Introduction
<LI>Sessions
<LI>Assessment
<LI>Contacts</B>
</OL>

<I>Key words:  North Sea, Baltic Sea, Physical Oceanography, Biological Oceanography, Sediments, Benthic Processes, Coastal Morphodynamics, Ocean Observations, Ocean Modelling.</I><P>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
 An international symposium on "New Challenges for North Sea Research" was held on 21 -23 October 1996 in Hamburg, Germany. Hosted by the Zentrum fur Meeres- und Klimaforschung, Universitat Hamburg, the symposium was both a retrospective look over twenty years of North Sea research since the Fladenground Experiment (FLEX 76), and a prospective view into the future.  Approximately 150 scientists, primarily from countries surrounding the North Sea, were in attendance.  The large attendance, right up to the very last session, for such a focused meeting is  testimony to the importance that northern Europe attaches to the North Sea.  Attendees were rewarded with excellent papers, well organized into cohesive sessions, with adequate time for presentation and discussion.  The retrospective look showed that we understand quite a lot about the boundary forcing (from air, land via river runoff, and surrounding water from the Atlantic Ocean and Baltic Sea) and the resulting circulation and are beginning to gain insight into the resulting biogeochemical structure of this semi-enclosed sea that is so important to northern Europe.  The prospective view called for research on space and time scale (e.g. coastal response to global warming) and disciplinary processes (e.g. bio-physical, air-sea) interaction and a series of specific process studies as opposed to one major experiment.<BR>
 Highlights include the following:<BR>
a)  Industrialized countries surrounding  the North Sea (e.g. UK and Germany) have considerably reduced the nutrient (nitrogen and phosphates) content of their river runoff,  <BR>
b)  Atmospheric particle deposition contributes four times as much nutrient loading than does river input;<BR>
c)  Most of the water entering the North Sea gets circulated around the coasts and exits through the Norwegian Current, leaving only very small (and hard to detect) changes in the large interior bulk;<BR> 
d)  Individual species play critical roles in North Sea ecological dynamics;<BR>
e)  The Skagarrak (Channel connecting Baltic and North seas) and the Norwegian Trench are the final resting places for most of the sediments entering the North Sea; and<BR>
f)  North Sea morphodynamics are 3-dimentsional.<P>
 
<B>2.  Introduction</B><BR>
 Surrounded by Scotland and England to the west, Belgium, Netherlands and Germany to the south, and Denmark and Norway to the east, the North Sea covers an area of approximately 400,000 square kilometers (~160,000 square miles).  This is approximately half the size of the Eastern Mediterranean, 1/3 that of the Gulf of Mexico or the Sea of Okhotsk and about equal to Red and Black Seas. Its average depth of approximately 100 meters ( ~300 ft), is comparable to the three times larger Hudson and the half as large Persian Gulf. Its major inflow is from the North Atlantic, with secondary connections to the Atlantic through the Dover Strait and to the Baltic sea through the Skagerrak.  Strategically located among nations with rich maritime histories and advanced technologies, the North Sea has long been the focus of scientific research.  Its shallow depth and heavy riverine drainage has made its future health the focus of concern for the past two decades that started with the Fladenground Experiment, FLEX 76.<BR>
 Chairman Heinrich Hoeber of Meteorologisches Institut, ZMK, Universitat Hamburg called this symposium to take stock of the present state of understanding of the oceanography of the North Sea (20 years after FLEX 76) and to contemplate the future. The venue was the Kathologiche Akadamie in Hamburg, whose facilities were well suited for the approximately 150 attendees.  These included an excellent spectrum of both junior and senior researchers, virtually all from countries surrounding the North Sea.  The symposium format, again well suited to the task, had each session starting with a keynote speaker (30 minutes), followed by two or three oral presentations (20 minutes each)  and posters near the coffee break area.  The final session (approximately 90 minutes) was devoted to a discussion of where to go next led by the symposium chair and his keynote speakers, with active participation from the audience.<P>
 
<B>3.  Sessions</B><BR>
 <B>3.1 External Forcing</B> - The first day was devoted to external forcing of the North sea by, in turn, the atmosphere, the North Atlantic, the Baltic, and rivers (called "the land").  <BR>
 3.11  Atmospheric forcing is both chemical (wet and dry particle deposition) and dynamic (heat and momentum transfer across the air-sea interface). Particle deposition contributes over four times the nitrate input to the North Sea as does river runoff. (Ed note: This is probably because particles come from everywhere, whereas river runoff comes only from a few specific estuaries.) There is only a small seasonal cycle and, at best, a very small annual trend (with much variance) in this input, making long time records mandatory for valid conclusions about the long term. Observation and models of trace metal and nitrogen input to the Sea are well in hand, but toxic organics remain a mystery.  The impact of these toxics on the health of the Sea is not known.  <BR>
Heat and momentum flux depend heavily on surface drag induced by waves.  This surface stress often varies with the angle between the wind and waves and is usually spatially inhomogeneous.  Long time records depend heavily on stable towers, whose existence in the North Sea is seriously threatened.<BR>
 3.12 The North Atlantic is the single largest input into the North Sea.  Most of the flow, 1.7Sv (approximately 3% of that carried by the Gulf Stream), comes in east of Shetland Island.  Another 0.1Sv, small but critically important, comes in through the Dover Strait.  Tidal forcing confines most of this flow to the coasts off Scotland, England (on the west), Belgium, Netherlands and Germany (to the south), Denmark and Norway (to the east), and out through the Norwegian Current, with a little exchanging with the Baltic Sea, through the Skagerrak.  Possible long term change in this flow due to global warming is quite uncertain.  Although there is not much interannual variability in temperature and salinity flux into the Sea, there is considerable SST change, but no trends.  There is an 8 year periodicity in the flux and SST data.  Combined physical and biological sampling has been going on across the Norwegian Trench since 1983, showing the standard spring bloom of phytoplankton, followed by a rise in zooplankton.
 3.13 Exchange with the Baltic Sea occurs with saline outflow of about 0.8Sv around the north Jutland (Denmark) coast and fresh water inflow through the Skagerrak.  This causes a sharp SST front with many meanders and eddies.  Models show the meanders to be about 50 - 100 Km, last 25 days.  The eddies are 50M deep, typically detach in 6 hours and last for 1-5 days as they travel to the west.  Although the overall statistics seem consistent with the few satellite SST observations taken in the area, the models need far more validation before  taken as fact. The role of the Baltic in North Sea circulation is largely unknown.  Nobody was willing to speculate how the North Atlantic inflow would be changed if the Baltic was cut off from the North Sea.  One hypothesis might be that tidal currents would still drive flow around Shetland Island and the total flow would remain largely unchanged.  The alternate suggests it is the fresh water inflow from the Baltic that drives of the whole North Sea circulation and that without it, the North Atlantic would simply lose connection with the North Sea altogether.  
 3.14 River inflow provides the final input to the North Sea.  Over the past two decades there has been a clear reduction in nutrients and heavy metals from the rivers of the heavily Industrialized nations surrounding the North Sea.  The impact of that on the overall health of the Sea is not as clear as much of the river flow simply hugs the coast and eventually exits out along the Norwegian Current.  The greatest impact of river cleanup may be to improve conditions off your neighbors coast (England to Germany, Germany to Denmark, etc.).  The Huber Estuary is an example of an English outflow.  A key finding here is that up to 70% of the trace metal flux out of the Huber occurs in just two months, highlighting the intermittent nature of such fluxes.  In contrast to the heavy metal focus of the Huber outflow, food web dynamics is the focus of studies of the Elbe River Estuary.  At the end of the food chain, the protozooplanton biomass grew to 40 micrograms/litre. <BR>
<B>3.2 Internal Dynamics</B> - The second day, dealt with internal dynamics.  This included fronts
& eddies, biological oceanography, long tern variability, benthic process, and (in the early morning of the third day), coastal morphology.<BR>
3.21 Stratification, Fronts and mesoscale features.  Although the primary circulation of the
North Sea is tidally driven, with some component due to winds, heating and stirring are critical process controlling the hydrography of the North sea.  The doubling of the tidal currents from neap to spring can result in an eight-fold increase in mixing.  Since much of the internal part of the sea is homogenous, 1-dimensional models are used extensively to account for vertical exchange. In a comparison between TKE and Mellor-Yamada 2.5 closures in 1D formulations, both models were similar in their underestimate of total mixing when compared to observations. Unfortunately, along coastal regions, where much of the North Sea countrys main interests lie advection cannot be ignored and 3-dimentional models must be used.  When comparing 1 and 3-dimentioal formulations of another turbulence closure scheme, advection was found to be of first order importance.  
A 15 month data set between August 1988 and October 1989 showed seasonal variability is the dominant signal in the southern North Sea, with as much as a 6 degree change in SST, but a much smaller change in salinity.  This period was characterized by below average rainfall through most of England and Germany (primary catchment basins for the Southern North Sea) but above average in Scotland.  The resulting salinity showed above average off England (downstream of Scotland) and below average in the German Bight (downstream of England and Germany).  
 3.22 Biological evolution is one of the most compelling reasons for northern European interest in the North Sea. In an excellent keynote paper for this session, Mike Heath traced early understanding of biological-physical interaction to Steeles work in the 1960s. This led to food web models that linked various components of the biologics.  For twenty years, this simple model has been used to describe the spring bloom, but usually with too rapid a rise in total mass.  It is now clear that the model must include more than one zooplankton size to more correctly slow the rise.  This illustrates the need to understand particular species, rather than total biomass.  This was further illustrated by an analysis of a particular species of Callanus who take a whole year for recruitment.  Hence, their bloom is more correctly related to the previous years chlorophyll production than to the current year.  This is in stark contrast to other, very similar appearing but genetically different Callanus species who follow the more familiar spring bloom cycle.  Sorting out different species and, hence different bloom evolution presents a major challenge to fisheries interests in the North Sea.
 The complicated nature of biological evolution was the topic of the remaining papers in this excellent session.  From England, through the German Bight, to coastal Denmark, simple bloom dynamics is not able to explain observed biomass collections.  Strong horizontal gradients shortly offshore complicate the picture even more.  <BR>
 3.22 Interannual and decadal variability papers focused on how sudden major changes in a wide variety of different animal life in the North Sea can occur. The observed doubling of algal biomass in the Wadden Sea between 1976 and 1978 was an example that drew much attention.  However, most other long term records showed similar episodic changes that relate to a complicated mix of bio-physical interaction.<BR>
3.23  Benthic processes are dominated by a sequence of deposition and resuspension that
ultimately results in deposition rates of greater than 1 cm/year off Southern Norway.  This sequence of deposition and resuspension makes it very difficult to sort out local from long distance benthic sources, both organic and inorganic.  One major conclusion of the Benthics Links and Sinks (BELS) project in August and February 1992 was that the Southern Norway deposition zone does not provide an area of high microbial and geochemical turnover because materials deposited there have travelled a long distance.  Hence, they are aged and largely refractory.<BR>
      3.24  Morphological evolution was the last session on internal dynamics.  Here the attention was directed to very local responses.  The keynote address showed examples of how common are beaches with clearly three dimensional structures.  The only way to forecast these structure will be to develop models that combine the best features of existing three dimensional current, wave and tidal models.  <BR>
	The importance of sediment size in understanding and predicting beach evolution was underscored in the papers that followed. For example, in the backbarrier tidal flats of the Wadden Sea, sandy sediments (grain sizes >0.063 mm) are controlled largely by hydrodynamics of current and wave forcing.  Muddy sediments (<0.063), on the other hand, respond to both hydrodynamic and biogenic processes. <BR>
	<B>3.3 The Future</B>- The final day of the symposium centered on new observing  and modelling  techniques and culminated with a lively discussion of where to go in the future.<BR>
3.31  New observational techniques are often the engines for new advances in understanding.<BR>
The FLEX 76 experiment focused on vertical exchanges in the central North Sea.  It used what would now be considered a full array of "standard" observing platforms, including ships (15 in number), aircraft, drifting buoys, etc.  Although the original hypothesis of horizontal homogeneity was proven incorrect, FLEX 76 was a success.  It is now time to contemplate new observing systems. Three interesting ones that were described involved 1) use of seabirds as instrumentation platforms, 2) optical spectrometry, and 3) microstructure profiling.  <BR>
	Seabirds are attractive instrumentation platforms because their natural accumulation zones reflect physical forcing and simple sensors can be mounted on their feet.  In particular, albatrosses were shown to be able to obtain SST patterns that would be hidden from satellite remote sensing because of cloud cover.  It was suggested that penguins could provide some vertical depth.  <BR>
	The shallow depth of much of the interesting parts of the North Sea allows optical remote sensing to be of use in mapping the spatial distribution of sediment types and phytobenthic biomass.  <BR>
Ratios between different windows of a 12 channel spectrometer can differentiate between sediments and phytobenthics. <BR>
	Although advection is a first order process in much of the coastal North Sea, vertical exchange processes are also important there and are the primary agents for change in the interior.  This led to the primary focus of FLEX 76 being on vertical exchange processes.  This, in turn, turned much attention understanding turbulence.  Finally, that attention has led to the development of a (temperature and conductivity) microstructure profiler.  One meter long, with a fall velocity of  0.3 to 10 M/sec, this device is similar to ones in the U.S.  With, however, with one key difference, the ability to operate in a rising mode, thereby getting turbulence data right up to the surface. Cable vibration, the bane of moored turbulence platforms is overcome by use of a buoyant float between the mooring anchor and the instrument to absorb cable vibration.  Operated thusly, the MST can measure dissipation rates down to 10 exp-11 w/kg.<BR>
	3.32  Just as instrumentation has evolved considerably since FLEX 76 so has modelling.  The 1 and 2-dimensional models that reigned supreme in the 1970s are now being replaced by 3-dimentionsional ones with ever increasing process sophistication and resolution. For dynamics, the German Weather Service has been running an operational North Sea prediction model that is forced by wind, waves and tides, since the 1980s.  Closer to shore, a group in Hamburg has been experimenting with a high resolution 3-dimensional coastal model in the Wadden Sea whose verification statistics look encouraging. Overall, physical modelling of the North Sea is quite mature.<BR>
	The more challenging modelling problem involves linking physics with biology.  Here, the range of sophistication is broad.  One extreme  has very complicated ecosystem simulation but with the low resolution of a box model (called ERSEM).  The other extreme has simpler ecosystem dynamics in a fully three dimensional formulation (called ECOHAMI).  Between the two is a 1 dimensional formulation that have very high vertical resolution thereby resolving vertical exchange processes.  In a rare model comparison, it was shown that, although some times one or the other does better (and not always the same one), most of the time there is little to chose between them. It is more a matter of using whichever one better serves the problem you are trying to understand. <P>

<B>4.  Assessment</B><BR>
	Because of its strategic location among technically advanced countries, and its reasonably simple circulation structure, the North Sea is probably one of the worlds most heavily studied, and possibly best understood, semi-enclosed seas.  The final session of this symposium summarized where we stand and where to go next.  Rising out of a discussion that raised many, many issues, two recurring themes developed, interaction and processes.<BR>
	Many of the attendees were comfortable with our broad understanding of North Sea process on any one space or time scale, and with our knowledge of how individual processes evolve. However, the interaction between different time and space scales of similar processes or the interaction between different processes, even on the same scales, was thought to be very poorly understood.  Of all of these, the strongest call was for more study into the bio-physical interactions that abound in the North Sea.<BR>
	Although most attendees were comfortable with our first order process understanding, they were uncomfortable with the depth of that understanding.  It is one thing to describe the overall circulation of the North Sea, but very much another to understand the eddy and/or turbulence evolution.  Similarly, it is one thing to describe the broad evolution from nutrients to zooplankton, but very much another to differentiate between species. The second significant theme of this summary session, then, was to focus future work on deeper understanding of individual process by doing many individual, small, process experiments, rather than one single grand one.   <BR>
	Finally, and possibly of interest to readers outside Northern Europe was the issue of transportability.  Here the feeling was divided.  Some thought the next step in the service to society was to try to apply our understanding of North Sea process to other areas.  Others thought so much still needed to be done in the North Sea itself, that all attention should remain there.  <P>

The opinions and assessments in these reports are solely those of the authors and do not necessarily reflect official US Government, US Navy or ONREUR positions.<P>

