<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Ocean, Atmosphere, & Space Science & Technology Newsletter #9</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>04 November 1996<BR>
Oceanography<BR>
Dr David K van Keuren, NRL Historian<BR>
(Posted by LCDR John E Joseph with permission)<P>

Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
Ocean, Atmosphere and Space S&T - Newsletter #9<P>

Post-Cold War Collaborative Research at NRL: Laboratory Oceanographers Participate in Joint Research With Russians and Norwegians in Norwegian Sea</H3>

Contents:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Summary (compiled by LCDR Joseph)
<LI>Full Report (by Dr van Keuren)
<LI>Contacts
<LI>Feedback
</OL>

<B>1.  Summary (compiled by LCDR Joseph)</B><BR>
A Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) led international scientific team consisting of U.S., Russian, and Norwegian scientists spent a month on a Russian vessel, the Professor Logachev, this last summer carrying out geological and geophysical research in the Greenland-Norwegian Sea. This joint oceanographic expedition was funded by NRL, the National Science Foundation, and the Russian Academy of Sciences, with additional support from the Office of Naval Research and Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory.  Professor Logachev is operated by the Polar Marine Geosurvey Expedition headquartered near St. Petersburg.  The ninety participants included scientists from the VNIIokeangeologia Institute, Institute of Microbiology of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Vernadsky Institute of Geochemistry and Analytical Chemistry, Shirshov Institute of Oceanology, University of Oslo, University of Bergen,  NRL, Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, George Washington University, Maryland Geological Survey and MIT.<P>

One major objective of the cruise was to return to a Norwegian Sea mud volcano site to conduct extensive surveys and analyses as a follow-up to an investigation initiated by scientists on a joint NRL/Norwegian cruise in August, 1995 aboard the Haakon Mosby.  Unique temperature anomalies recorded there by Professor Kathy Crane were a scientific first according to Dr Peter Vogt, the lead American scientist.  The ship moved to the Knipovich Ridge Valley, part of the northernmost extension of the Atlantic Mid-Ocean Ridge, to search for evidence of hydrothermal activity within the rift valley.  Data collection from the region indicates signs of hydrothermal mineralization and recent volcanism in the region.  Further sedimentary coring north and west of Svalbard was done after investigation into deep iceberg plowmarks just north of 80 degrees N was postponed due to the presence of pack ice.<P>

The sharing of research technologies and platforms made the expedition financially feasible for NRL scientists while providing research support for the VNIIokeangeologia and Polar Marine Expedition during a period of severe financial difficulties in the Russian Federation.  It also formed the basis for future research collaboration.<P>

<B>2.  Full Report (by Dr van Keuren)</B><BR>
An NRL-led international scientific team consisting of U.S., Russian, and Norwegian scientists spent a month on a Russian vessel this last summer carrying out geological and geophysical research in the Greenland-Norwegian Sea. Funded by the Naval Research Laboratory, the National Science Foundation, and the Russian Academy of Sciences, with additional support from the Office of Naval Research and Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, the expedition departed Bergen, Norway on 24 July and concluded its work in Longyearbyen, Svalbard, on August 23. Research focused on several sites between 64 degrees N and 80 degrees N along the continental margin and the Knipovich Ridge Valley, a segment of the Mid-Oceanic Ridge where the North American plate is moving away from the Eurasian plate.  <P>   

The international scientific team was housed on the Professor Logachev, a vessel operated by the Polar Marine Geosurvey Expedition headquartered in Lomonosov near St. Petersburg. The Logachev is 104.5 meters in length with a displacement of 5,700 tons and was completed in 1991 after the break-up of the Soviet Union. It houses up to 93 scientists and crew, and contains extensive laboratory space, along with an armada of modern technologies for sampling and analyzing the sea bed, the subbottom, and the water column. The ship is larger and able to carry out a greater diversity of scientific functions than many American oceanographic research vessels.   <P>   

Participants on the cruise included staff members from the VNIIokeangeologia Institute in St. Petersburg, with research groups in gas hydrates, hydrothermal phenomena, and general environmental science; the Institute of Microbiology of the Russian Academy of Sciences in Moscow; the Vernadsky Institute of Geochemistry and Analytical Chemistry, and the Shirshov Institute of Oceanology, both of Moscow. There were two representatives of the University of Oslo, a graduate student and a geophysical engineer. Additional support was provided by the University of Bergen (Professor Eirik Sundvor). Engineering and crew staffing was provided by the Polar Marine Expedition. The head Russian scientist was Dr. Georgiy Cherkashev of the VNIIokeangeologia, and the captain was Alexander Arutyunov, a forty-year veteran of the Soviet Navy. Other Russian participants included Dr. Gennady Ivanov, an expert on the Barents Sea environment; Dr. Gabriel Ginsburg, an authority on gas hydrates; and Boris Malin and Alexander Shagin, Expedition Chief and Vice-Expedition Chief respectively. The Director of the Polar Marine Geosurvey Expedition is Dr. Vladimir Kryukov.   <P>

NRL participants were Dr. Peter Vogt, lead American scientist; Dr. Kathleen Crane, a visiting geophysicist at NRL from Lamont-Doherty Institute of Geophysics and Hunter College; Justin McCune, a computer specialist; and graduate student Jennifer Lee, from NRL and George Washington University. Other Americans included NRL historian Dr. David van Keuren; Jeffrey Halka, with the Maryland Geological Survey; Claude (Pete) Petrone, a retired National Geographic Society photographer; and Stephanie Harrington, a graduate student from MIT. There were ninety cruise participants altogether.<P>

The Norwegian Sea has been a focus of NRL oceanographic attention for a quarter century. The most recent research there was joint NRL/Norwegian work in August of 1995 (Labstracts, June 3, 1996), conducted from the vessel Haakon Mosby, operated by the University of Bergen. In the course of that expedition, NRL and Norwegian scientists discovered and carried out an initial survey of a mud volcano, or warm seep, located at 72 degrees N on the continental slope west of the Barents Sea.<P>     

A major objective of the Logachev cruise was a return to the Haakon Mosby mud volcano to pursue more extensive surveys and scientific analyses than could be accomplished on the Haakon Mosby expedition.  After conducting short investigations at several sites from 64 degrees N to 70 degrees N, the Logachev arrived at the mud volcano site on August 4 and remained there for a week. Transponders were placed on the seafloor to facilitate accurate navigation and instrument positioning. The site was then surveyed by sidescan sonar, video sled (with video and still cameras), and CTD (to take measurements of conductivity, temperature, and depth in the water column). Piston, gravity, and box cores were used to collect sediment samples at various locations within the grid area.<P>

Cores taken at the center of the mud volcano returned sediments rich with hydrogen sulfide gas and methane hydrate crystals. The cores literally bubbled away in front of researchers, as the gas hydrate, an ice-like substance, decomposed to methane gas and water. (Gas hydrates are only stable at the low temperature-high pressure environment of the seafloor). Geologists observed hydrate crystals as large as eight to ten centimeters in diameter, as well as numerous tube worms in the sediment. The video and still films displayed methane hydrates scattered across the sea floor in small fragments and extensive patches. Additionally, CTD measurements gave evidence of a signficant positive temperature anomaly in the water column directly over the volcano center. According to Dr. Peter Vogt, "Nobody has ever, over a so-called cool or warm seep, found a temperature anomaly in the water column" before. This was a scientific first for the Logachev team.              From the site of the mud volcano, the Logachev headed north to the Knipovich Ridge Valley. The Knipovich is the northernmost extension of the Atlantic Mid-Ocean Ridge, running 600 km between 73 degrees 30' N, 8 degrees 0' E, and 77 degrees 40' N, 6 degrees 40' E. It is one of the least known of the oceanic rift valleys and does not even appear on most maps of global plate tectonics. The Knipovich Ridge is characterized by widely spaced clusters of seamounts separated by long stretches of sediment-filled valley floor. This is atypical of mid-ocean ridge topography. The rift valley running along the center of the ridge ranges in depth from 3200 to 3400 meters. Near its northern end is the Molloy Deep, which at 5570 meters is the greatest depth in the North Atlantic-Arctic region.  <P>

The major objective within the Knipovich Ridge area was to search for evidence of hydrothermal activity within the rift valley. The Logachev, using sidescan sonar, profiled part of the rift valley north to south, commencing on the night of August 12. A CTD was attached to the sidescan to search for temperature anomalies in the water column. Early results indicated a temperature anomaly near the north flank of a submarine volcano at 76 degrees 48' N. Coring, dredging, and the video sled were deployed to explore the area around the suspected anomaly site. Although the exact site of the warm vent was not located, CTD readings, along with evidence from dredging and photographic profiles produced signs of hydrothermal mineralization and recent volcanism in this section of the rift valley.    <P>           

A failure of the sidescan sonar in the lower rift valley area limited the ability of the Logachev to complete the bottom profile. However, enough evidence was gathered during this year's visit to warrant a future return in order to continue and expand the investigations. One idea under consideration is to bring the MIR deep submersibles, belonging to the Shirshov Institute of Moscow, to dive on both the mud volcano and the Knipovich Rift Valley sites sometime within the next year. The MIRs are capable of making in-situ sea floor investigations, placing experiment packages, taking measurements, and collecting samples at specific sites. <P>

Departing the rift valley site, Logachev headed toward its northernmost planned site, deep iceberg plowmarks at 80 degrees 10' N. However, the pack ice edge was located just above 80 degrees, so the plowmark site was left for a better ice year. After further sedimentary coring north and west of Svalbard, Professor Logachev disembarked its American and Norwegian contingent at Longyearbyen, in Svalbard (latitude 78 degrees 15' N.), on the 23rd of August. The American Ambassador to Norway, the Honorable Thomas Loftus, and his Military Attache, Captain Robert Paleck, met the Logachev and her crew in Longyearbyen fjord for a ship's tour and reception.<P>

The cruise of the Professor Logachev was more than a joint oceanographic expedition. Scientific expertise and techniques were demonstrated and shared among the American, Russian, and Norwegian participants. Approximately a dozen research seminars were delivered in Russian and English by scientific specialists, and a Russian language course was organized for the benefit of members of the American team. In addition to the regular research staff, the crew included ten graduate students (1 Norwegian, 2 U.S., 7 Russian) pursuing advanced studies in the oceanographic sciences.<P>

In a time of tight financial resources both in Russia and the United States, the Logachev cruise advanced the scientific research front in both countries. The sharing of research technologies and platforms made the expedition financially feasible for NRL scientists, while providing research support for both the VNIIokeangeologia and the Polar Marine Expedition, during a period of severe financial difficulties in the Russian Federation. It has also formed the basis for future research collaborations.<P>

The first follow-up may be next year's spring meetings of the American Geophysical Union in Baltimore, where sessions reporting on the scientific accomplishments of the expedition will be given by American and Russian scientists.<P>

<B>3.  Contacts</B><BR>
Dr David van Keuran is a historian for the Naval Research Laboratory, Washington, DC.  He can be contacted at (202) 767-4263 or e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:dvk@ccf.nrl.navy.mil">dvk@ccf.nrl.navy.mil</A>.<P>

NRLs homepage is found at <A HREF="http://www.cmf.nrl.navy.mil">http://www.cmf.nrl.navy.mil</A>.<P>

<B>4.  Feedback</B><BR>
