<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Ocean, Atmosphere, & Space Science & Technology Newsletter #11</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<H3>16 October 1996<BR>
Polar Meteorology<BR>
LCDR John Joseph, USN<P>

Office of Naval Research, Europe<BR>
Ocean, Atmosphere and Space S&T - Newsletter # 11<P>

Supplementary Comments on the 6th EGS Polar Lows Working Group Meeting at St Petersburg, Russia,  23-26 Sep 96</H3>

<I>Keywords:  Meteorology, polar meteorology, Arctic research, Antarctic research, polar lows, mesoscale cyclones</I><P>

Contents:

<OL>
<LI>Summary
<LI>General Information about EPLWG
<LI>The EPLWG Meeting
<LI>Comments
<LI>Contacts
<LI>Feedback
</OL>

<B>1.  Summary</B><BR>
The EPLWG held is sixth meeting at AARI in St Petersburg, Russia in late September.  The intent of this newsletter is to provide some background and add supplementary editorial comments regarding the workshop as viewed by this author.  A full report of the meeting was prepared by the Chairman of EPLWG and is posted on both the EPLWG homepage and the ONR Europe homepage (addresses below).  The EPLWG consists of an international mix of senior researchers, post-doctorate students and operational meteorologists conducting theoretical and observational studies of polar lows.  This provided an excellent forum to combine western and Russian research in a common area of interest.  The workshop quite successfully accomplished this and hosting  the workshop at AARI boosted Russian participation.  ONR Europes support via its Conference Support Program was instrumental in enabling the workshop to be located in St Petersburg with a full complement of western participants in attendance.  The opportunity to join forces in this cooperative effort was fully embraced by all involved and will undoubtedly enhance understanding of the polar mesocyclone phenomena.<P>

<B>2.  General Information about EPLWG</B><BR>
The EGS Polar Lows Working Group (EPLWG) held its sixth meeting at the State Scientific Center of the Russian Federation Arctic and Antarctic Research Institute (AARI) in St Petersburg, Russia from 23-26 September, 1996. EPLWG falls under the umbrella of  the European Geophysical Society, though they do not receive any financial support from them.  There were some 25 participants from Denmark, Germany, Iceland, Norway, Russia, the United Kingdom and the United States present at this meeting.  Papers from Canadian and French members of the working group who were not able to attend were also presented at the meeting.  The group consists of  a mixture of senior researchers, post-doctorate students and operational meteorologists from a number of institutes and agencies with interest in high latitude operations.  A complete list of attendees is found on the EPLWG homepage.<P>

EPLWG has met each year since its founding in 1989 (except 1995) at Cambridge, Copenhagen, Vienna, Iceland, Paris and St Petersburg, respectively.  One of the intentions of holding this years meeting at AARI was to encourage Russian researchers with interests in this area to participate in the working group.  AARI has much to offer with large databases (particularly in the Arctic) and years of operational activity and experience in the high latitudes.  Their participation is not only beneficial to EPLWG, but serves as a forum to establish new collaborative ties with western researchers.  The cost of  getting to St Petersburg (particularly for post-doctorate students) was sufficiently high that it would have reduced the number of western participants, so outside funding was solicited.  ONR Europe supported the meeting  via its <B>Conference Support Program (CSP)</B>.  This allowed some six additional students to attend the meeting which significantly enhanced its success.  EPLWG has received an invitation from the Norwegian Meteorological Institute to hold its next meeting in Tromsoe, Norway in early summer 1998.<P>

<B>3.  The EPLWG Meeting</B><BR>
The EPLWG workshop was entitled "Theorectical and Observational Studies of Polar Lows".  A full report of the meeting was prepared by Dr Gunther Heinemann, Chairman of EPLWG.  It provides an excellent synopsis of the work being conducted by both western and Russian scientists in this area.  It can be found on the EPLWG homepage at <A HREF="http://www.rhrz.uni-bonn.de/~unf433/eplwg/eplwg.html">www.rhrz.uni-bonn.de/~unf433/eplwg/eplwg.html</A>.  It is also posted on ONR Europes homepage at www.ehis.navy.mil as an Ocean, Atmosphere and Space S&T Newsletter.<P>

<B>4.   Comments</B><BR>
AARI proved to be an excellent site for hosting the EPLWG meeting this year.  <B>CSP funding was instrumental</B> in allowing this to happen.  The primary benefit was that it allowed for much greater Russian participation in the working group than if held elsewhere, enabling numerous AARI scientists (not just workshop participants) to discuss recent similar research work being conducted in the Russian science community.  There were seven Russian presenters at the workshop and numerous other interested AARI staff joining in on various group discussions.  This particularly successful aspect of the meeting has potential for developing  long-term interaction between western and Russian polar researchers.  Had the meeting been held at another site, the extent of Russian input would have been diluted in comparison, if not completely absent from the working group.  The timely interaction that did take place was a mutually recognized "plus" for both sides.   Deputy Scientific Director of AARI, Dr A. Danilov, made it clear in his summary remarks that AARI is enthusiastically embracing the opportunity to participate in EPLWG and welcomed the collaborative nature of the group.<P>

Holding the meeting at AARI also provided the opportunity for the western scientists to tour the facilities and learn a little about the current state of research at AARI.  Tours included a visit to the weather satellite data collection laboratory (which seemed to have some of the most modern equipment in the building) and a visit to the ice tank facilities.  The ice tanks were quite impressive in their size and unique ice making capability by using retractable cooling units.  A brief video provided some insight to the research in ice strength and hull design being conducted there.<P>

Arctic research is one area which continues to hold Russias strong interest and it was evident that difficult financial times are having an impact on the countrys ability  to continue the work in this arena without collaboration.  As mentioned before, AARI has extensive polar region databases and years of field experience to offer in a cooperative effort such as this and their involvement in the EPLWG will significantly enhance understanding of this phenomena.<P>

