<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Newsletter #12</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>January 13, 1997<P>

Europe - Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ehis.navy.mil/weinstein.htm">Alan I. Weinstein</A>  (For Dr. Michael Bruno, Davidson Laboratory,  Stevens Institute of Technology, Hoboken, N.J. USA)<P>

Office of Naval Research - Europe<BR>
Ocean, Atmosphere and Space Science and Technology Newsletter No. 97-12<P>

The Division of Hydraulics and Environmental Engineering/Department of Civil Engineering
The Aristotle University of Thessaloniki</H3>

<OL><B>
<LI>Introduction
<LI>Summary 
<LI>Thessaloniki 
<LI>University of Thessaloniki 
<LI>School of Technology
<LI>Department of Civil Engineering 
<LI>Division of Hydraulics and Environmental Engineering  
<DIR> 7.1 Staff<BR>
 7.2  Facilities<BR>
 7.3  Staff Research Interests</DIR>
<LI>Contact Persons</B>
</OL>

<I>Key Words : Circulation modeling; Water quality modeling; Nearshore processes</I><P>

<B>1. Introduction </B><BR>
 The following report summarizes the capabilities and recent research activities
of the Division of Hydraulics and Environmental Engineering at the Aristotle
University of Thessaloniki, Greece.  The report is based on the Dr. Brunos
experiences during a 4-month Fulbright lecturing/research appointment. He would like to acknowledge the generous assistance of the staff and students of the Division during his stay in Thessaloniki.<P>

<B>2. Summary </B><BR>
 The Division of Hydraulics and Environmental Engineering is an active participant
in European Union and locally-sponsored research efforts covering a wide range
of ocean engineering issues.  The primary areas of interest are Aegean Sea
circulation and water quality dynamics; nearshore processes; fundamental fluid
dynamics; and water resources management.  The Division's focus in addressing
these problems is heavily weighted towards numerical modeling, an area in which
the staff excels.  The Division possesses an impressive suite of numerical
models,  including codes developed by the staff as well as codes originating in
the U.S. and Europe.  The Division is less well equipped in terms of laboratory
and field data collection.  However,  as a result of its participation in
European Union (MAST) joint research ventures and the EU-sponsored
facilities-sharing programs, the Division is becoming more active in the
acquisition and analysis of field and laboratory data.  This has greatly
enhanced the capabilities of the staff, and should contribute to the continued
expansion of the Division's ocean engineering research activities. <P>

<B>3. Thessaloniki </B><BR>
 Located at the head of the Thermaikos Gulf, the northwestern corner of the
Aegean Sea, Thessaloniki is the second largest city in Greece with a population
of approximately 1 million.  <P>

<B>4. University of Thessaloniki </B><BR>
 Founded in 1925, the university is the largest in Greece, with a total undergraduate enrollment of approximately 60,000 students in 35 departments on a campus that covers 137 acres.<P>

<B>5. School of Technology</B><BR>
 Founded in 1955, the school is composed of 7 Departments :
<OL>
<LI>Civil Engineering
<LI>Architecture
<LI>Rural & Surveying Engineering
<LI>Mechanical Engineering
<LI>Electrical Engineering
<LI>Chemical Engineering
<LI>Mathematics, Physical, and Computational Sciences
</OL>

The school has a total undergraduate enrollment of approximately 7,100 students
and 135 post-graduate students.  The staff includes approximately 280 teachers
(lecturers, assistant professors, associate professors, and  professors), all
of whom hold the Ph.D. degree, and approximately 190 technical and
administrative support staff.<P>

<B>6. Department of Civil Engineering </B><BR>
 Founded in 1955, the Department has a total undergraduate enrollment of approximately 2,000 students in 4 divisions:
<OL>
<LI>Structural Engineering
<LI>Hydraulics and Environmental Engineering
<LI>Geotechnical Engineering
<LI>Transport and Organization
</OL>

The undergraduate students pursue a 5-year course of study leading to the Diploma of Civil Engineering.  The curriculum includes 3 years of core courses followed by 2 years of specialized study in any one of the 4 areas listed above.  A
Diploma Thesis is also required.  The graduate ("post-graduate") program is
small by U.S. standards, reflecting both the scarcity of financial support and
the very restricted employment opportunities for Ph.D. degree recipients in Greece.<P>
 
<B>7. Division of Hydraulics and Environmental Engineering</B><BR>  
 The Division conducts teaching and research in many areas of concern to the Navy, including: physical oceanography, fundamental fluid mechanics, circulation and water quality modeling, flow-structure interaction, coastal engineering, hydrology and water resources management<P>

<B> 7.1 Staff</B><BR>
 The Division has a total teaching staff of 18, an administrative/technical
staff of 8, and a total of 25 full-time post-graduate students.  In addition,
the Division is host to several visiting researchers who also hold appointments
at universities elsewhere in Greece.  These visiting researchers are funded on
an entirely "soft-money" basis through government or industry-supported
research projects.  Based on my own experience, they make significant
contributions to the overall research effort within the Division.<P>

<B>7.2  Facilities</B><BR>
 The Division has a reasonably well-equipped laboratory, with several small
recirculating flumes equipped with hot film anemometers, pressure and temperature sensors, etc.  The flumes are primarily used for teaching demonstrations and instructional laboratories, although they are occasionally  employed in Ph.D. thesis research projects.  Such experimental projects are rare, owing to the Division's focus on numerical modeling.  The computer facilities are
first-rate, with workstations and pentium-based personal computers widely
available and network connection to a Vax 9000 mainframe.  Software currently
in use includes "in-house" codes as well as models developed in the U.S. (e.g.,
the Princeton Ocean Model and the Army Corps' shoreline evolution model,
GENESIS) and the European Union.  The Division does not operate a research
vessel of its own, but has access to a 6-meter vessel operated by the Biology
Department.  Field instrumentation includes an ADCP, 2 Aandera current meters,
a thermistor chain, a CTD, an OBS sensor, and a wave recorder.<P>

<B>7.3  Staff Research Interests</B><BR>
 In an overall sense, the marine-oriented staff is heavily concentrated in
computational fluid dynamics and numerical modeling of ocean circulation, coastal dynamics, and water quality dynamics.  This focus has been modified slightly in recent years as a result of the Division's participation in several European Union-sponsored (MAST) research projects involving the acquisition and analysis of oceanographic field data.  The marine research interests of the Division can be summarized as follows.<P>

Numerical modeling of ocean circulation and coastal dynamics<BR>
 Key participants : Professors Yannis Krestenitis and Christoforos  Koutitas;
 Drs. Spiros Christopoulos and Theofanis Karambas<P>

This group has been involved in several MAST projects, including G6M, G8M, MERMAIDS, PROFILE, ECAWOM, and SAFE.  They have employed the Princeton Ocean Model in numerical studies of the full Aegean Sea and the Thermaikos Gulf.  They have also developed their own numerical codes for modeling storm surges, nonlinear wave propagation and breaking, sediment transport and pollutant transport.  Professors Krestenitis and Koutitas have both served on MAST proposal review committees, and Professor Koutitas is a member of the MAST modeling committee.  Drs. Christopoulos and Karambas are particularly active in the modeling of nearshore processes, and are participants in the Waves in Shallow Water Environments (WISE) program. <P>

The group has in the past 5 years expanded its interest and capabilities in field
and laboratory data acquisition and analysis.  Professor Krestenitis and Dr.
Christopoulos form the University of Thessaloniki component of the MAST 
PROFILE ("Processes in Regions of Freshwater Influence") project, which
includes extensive data collection efforts in the Thermaikos Gulf.  The team is
currently comparing numerical predictions of the 3-D Gulf dynamics (using the
Princeton Ocean Model) with an extensive 18-month data set that includes moored observations of the vertical distribution of currents, temperature and
salinity.   Drs. Christopoulos and Karambas are active participants in a
recently-initiated wave data acquisition program in the northern Aegean.  Dr.
Karambas is currently involved in a large wave tank study at the Catalonia
University of Technology (UPC) with the aim of measuring reflection and
transmission coefficients in the vicinity of a submerged breakwater.  His
participation in the project is being supported through the European Union's
program for shared access to laboratory facilities.<P>


Computational Fluid Dynamics<BR>
 Key participants : Professors Petros  Anagnostopoulos,  Christoforos 
 Koutitas, and Jacques Ganoulis<P>

These individuals are active in the numerical modeling of flow-structure interaction, e.g.,  flow around a cylinder and flow-induced vibrations.  Their work is almost entirely numerical, although there has been recent involvement in
combined numerical-experimental efforts aimed at simulating the flow through a
staggered series of cylinders.<P>

Water Quality Modeling<BR>
 Key participants : Professors  Christoforos Koutitas, Yannis Krestenitis and
 Jacques Ganoulis,  Drs. Spiros Christopoulos and Theofanis Karambas<P>

This group has a wide range of interests in the numerical simulation of water
quality dynamics and pollution transport processes.  Extensive use is made of
an "in-house"  version of the EPA's WASP modeling system,  modified to allow
the water quality component to interface with the Princeton Ocean Model. 
Conservative substance transport models have been developed for use in the
Thermaikos Gulf.  Work is also being performed in the nearshore area, with
particular attention to the dispersion characteristics of the surf zone.  The
group conducts limited water quality field data acquisition in the Thermaikos
Gulf.  Professor Ganoulis is also heavily involved in engineering risk analysis
as applied to water pollution problems.<P>

<B>8. Contact Persons</B><BR>
Michael S. Bruno<BR>
