<H3>Newsletter #44<BR>
End of year message<BR>
15-Dec-1994</H3>

Dear reader of ONREUR Newsletter on Electronics:<P>

The year 1994 is steaming to an end and it is time to bid you a cheerful New Year. It is also time to thank you for caring about what we do here at ONREUR.<P>

I am embarking on my third year as a liaison scientist for ONR-London. It is an immensely challenging and rewarding job, one which I fully enjoy. I am looking forward to another productive year reporting on interesting new events in Electronic S&T in Europe. <P>

This is a good time to remind my readers to re-asses my newsletters and to provide me with any constructive criticism to make them better. If you wish to add someone to my distribution list (or want to be deleted from it), please, take the time to inform me as soon as possible.<P>

For those of you who are recent additions to my e-mailing list, below you will find a listing of titles and short table of content of my newsletters on electronics since November 1992. Included is also the titles and table of content on three ESN Information Bulletin articles. Please, reply if you wish to get any of the back issues or reprints of the ESN bulletin.<P>

I am going home (Virginia) for the holidays and will be absent from my desk until 12 January 1995.<P> 

The more I travel in Europe the more I realize how small and wonderful the world is. It is nice to be away, but  ..... it is even nicer to come home.<P>

Have a wonderful Holiday Season and....<BR>
Cheers from London!<P>

Nick Bottka<P>
<HR>
<H3>Newsletter #43<BR>
Visit to Moscow and St. Petersburg<BR>
8-Dec-94</H3>
<B>Content:</B>

<OL>
<LI>Laboratories visited 
<LI>New approach to power vacuum microwave devices
<LI>Using US chips to build faster PC accelerator boards
<LI>New approach to bulk GaN growth
<LI>Miscellaneous
<LI>Contacts
</OL>

<B>Abstract</B><BR>

This article gives an overview of electronic related R&D activities at various institutes in Moscow and St. Petersburg. The author visited these sites on 15-23 November 1994. Topics covered include: vacuum microwave electronics, computer hardware design, diamond doping, SiC and GaN bulk crystal growth, and pattern recognition. Two unique areas of research are identified which merit closer attention: power vacuum microwave devices based on new principles of operation (rooted on transverse grouping of homogeneous electron beam in circularly polarized electromagnetic fields) and growth of high temperature GaN substrates by sandwich sublimation technique.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Newsletter #42 <BR>
Use of STM in studying strain relaxation of lattice-mismatched epitaxial systems<BR>
27-Oct-94</H3>
<B>Content:</B>

<OL>
<LI>Importance of strain in epitaxial growth
<LI>Combining in-situ UHV-STM with MBE growth 
<LI>The evolution of strain relaxation
<LI>Study leads to surprises
<LI>Contacts
</OL>

<B>Abstract</B><BR>

This article summarizes some recent results of a crystal growth study, done at he Johannes Kepler University in Linz, Austria. By using scanning tunneling microscope (STM), the Linz group was able to image misfit dislocation formation in strained epitaxial layers grown within an MBE chamber. By combining the STM with RHEED, in-situ, the Linz scientists were able to study the early stages of strain relaxation mechanism quantitatively and to elucidate the relaxation process in an actual growth experiment.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Newsletter #41<BR>
We hear that .....<BR>
24-Oct-94</H3>
<B>Content:</B>

<OL>
<LI>Foreword by Nick Bottka
<LI>The blue emitting laser diode proposal
<LI>Comments
</OL>

<B>Abstract</B><BR>

This short communication describes a recently funded proposal to fabricate blue emitting laser diodes using II-VI semiconductor materials. The European Community project involves a consortium of laboratories from West and East Europe.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Newsletter #40<BR>
European Workshop on II-VI Semiconductors<BR>
20-Oct-94</H3>
<B>Content:</B>

<OL>
<LI>Introduction
<LI>Good news bad news
<LI>Material problems and failure mechanism
<LI>New hope and challenges
<LI>The Microgun Semiconductor Laser
<LI>Prognosis
<LI>Workshop program
</OL>

<B>Abstract</B><BR>

This report highlights some of the key issue discussed at the II-VI Laser-Workshop held in Wuerzburg, Germany on 18-23 September 1994 and the European Workshop on II-VI Semiconductors held in Linz, Austria on 28-30 September 1994. Focus is on wide-gap II-VI materials and the problems associated with blue emitting laser development. Progress in microgun electron stimulated lasers is also presented.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Newsletter #39<BR>
Using proximal probes to test MMICs<BR>
14-Oct-94</H3>
<B>Content:</B>

<OL>
<LI>Introduction
<LI>Picosecond sampling with Near-Field Scanning Optical Microscope
<LI>Function and failure analysis using Scanning Force Microscope
<LI>Contacts
</OL>

<B>Abstract</B><BR>

This article describes how a research group at the University of Duisburg, Germany is using proximal probes such as scanning force microscope (SFM) and near-field scanning optical microscope (NSOM) to test monolithic microwave and millimeter wave integrated circuits (MMICs) with nanometer spatial resolution and temporal resolution up to 100 GHz.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Newsletter #38<BR>
Report on US-European Workshop on Optical Characterization of Electronic Materials<BR>
12-Oct-94</H3>
<B>Content:</B>

<OL>
<LI>Objective of the workshop
<LI>Issues addressed
<LI>Some highlights
<LI>Organizers
<LI>Scientific program
</OL>

<B>Abstract</B><BR>

The US-European Workshop on Optical Characterization of Electronic Materials was held in Halle, Germany, 5 - 7 October 1994. It was organized by ONREUR, Martin-Luther University of Halle-Wittenberg, and the Technical University of Berlin. Co-sponsors of this workshop included Office of Naval Research European Office, European Office for Aerospace R&D, the Army European Research Office, and the European Community ESPRIT Program. This report summarizes the objectives and some of the highlights of this event. Important new techniques to monitor and control epitaxial growth are discussed; the analysis of electronic materials and circuits using proximal probes is described.<P>
