<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>This report summarizes my activities as a
liaison scientist at ONREUR London from September 1992 to November
1995. The report covers topics in electronics of interest to ONR
and the US defense establishment. The views expressed here reflect
my own biases as a research scientist with experience in electronic
material and devices for the past 30 years.  My observations are
based on numerous personal visits to leading R&amp;D institutions
in Europe and on interaction with scientists, engineers, and S&amp;T
managers throughout Europe. My assessment and recommendations
reflect my strong view that electronic S&amp;T in Europe is healthy,
growing, sometimes very innovative, and of potential benefit to
the DoD community in the US.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000>Key Observations<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000> </FONT></B><I><FONT COLOR=#000000>Germany
<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
Germany is emerging as a leader in numerous electronic-related
technologies. Driven by social, political, and market forces,
German S&amp;T managers are restructuring existing electronic
related programs and are engaged in long-range R&amp;D planning.
 The German S&amp;T blueprint in electronics includes a quest
for higher information and energy density storage devices; smaller,
faster, and more powerful computers; new methods to synthesize,
measure, manipulate, and utilize atomic and molecular structures
(nanotechnology); and new systems for information processing and
communication. Some of the latest innovations include<BR>

<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>1. Design of new tools and process methodologies
for fabricating high-frequency monolithic microwave and millimeter
wave integrated circuits (MMICs).  This development has direct
impact on the mobile communication and the automotive industry.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>2. Novel techniques for measuring high-frequency
electronic components using the latest scientific innovations
pioneered in Europe, e.g., the use of proximal probes such as
the scanning force microscope (SFM) to test MMICs with nanometer
spatial resolution and temporal resolution up to 100 GHz.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>3. Manufacture of inexpensive plastic packaging
for MMICs that are applicable up to 12 GHz operation. These devices
are targeted for commercial and military microwave products, 
e.g., phased array radar (PAR) that use MMIC chips.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>4. Rapid development of application-specific
integrated circuits (ASICs); the integ-ration of electronics with
sensors and miniature mechanical actuators. This fast-paced R&amp;D
is driven by market demands in high-volume, consumer-oriented
chemical, medical, and automobile industries. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>5. Strong support and participation in the
European Commission's Framework Programs targeting information
and communication technologies, e.g., ESPRIT (European Strategic
Program for R&amp;D in Information Technology) and RACE (R&amp;D
in Advanced Communication Technology in Europe). These programs
have serious implications for how Germany and the European Union
will compete within the global information technology market.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>I recommend that we in the DoD<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>1.  look closer at some of these German innovations,
especially the computer-aided design (CAD) of coplanar MMIC chips
and the plastic packaging methodology, to reduce even further
the cost associated with manufacturing our own MMICs for military
systems.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>2. initiate our own R&amp;D program in real-time,
high spatial and temporal resolution testing methodology of MMICs.
 Such dynamic high-frequency testing will be imperative for developing
future communication and millimeter wave DoD system components.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>3. keep a close watch on the &quot;smart&quot;
sensor technology development in Europe.   Although the US still
leads in the manufacturing of such components, the Europeans,
and the Germans in particular, are tooling up for production in
many of their industrial sectors. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>4. keep close ties with the German scientific
community involved in nano-scale R&amp;D.  The Germans have proven
to be leaders in nanoscience; their ministry for S&amp;T is vigorously
funding nanotechnology. They are determined to harvest economic
and social benefits from this scientific discipline in the future.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>5. follow closely the European information
and communication programs. For example,  Germany, in collaboration
with other European Union countries, is vigorously pursuing digital
mobile communication. The Europeans have been leading the world
in digital communication development and are determined to establish
new global standards in it, e.g., the establishment of the new
European Digital Communication System (DCS) standard and pursuing
the development of the Mobile Broadband System (MBS) for digital-based
networking in the 21th Century. These developments are bound to
impact our own information technology strategy.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I> Russia<BR>
</I>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Russia and many of the republics of the Former
Soviet Union (FSU) offer a window of opportunity in selected areas
of electronic-related S&amp;T of strategic importance to the DoD.
Among these are the following.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
1.  Vacuum microwave devices based on concepts less developed
in the West. For example,  vacuum devices that do not use the
conventional &quot;bunching&quot; principle to extract microwave
energy found in traditional klystrons and TWTs. The Russians have
developed novel approaches for extracting microwave energy  based
on transverse grouping of homogeneous electron beam in circularly
polarized electromagnetic fields (in resonant cavities and slow-wave
structures). This approach circumvents the limitation imposed
by bunching and leads to improved device performance, e.g., super
linearity in device characteristics such as frequency and phase.
Specific devices include<BR>
<UL>
<LI>High-power Circularly Polarized TWTs (CPTWT)<BR>
<LI>High-power Cyclotron-Wave Converters (CWC)<BR>
<LI>Low-noise Cyclotron-Wave Parametric Amplifier (CWPA) <BR>
<LI>Cyclotron-Wave Electrostatic Amplifiers (CWESA)<BR>
<LI>Narrowband Controlled CWESA-Filters<BR>
<LI>Cyclotron-Wave Phase Shifters (CWPS)<P></UL>

2.  Multibeam Klystrons (MBKs) for radar applications. Compared
to standard klystron for equivalent power levels, the multibeam
cathode klystron offers:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Higher efficiency (55-70%) and lower operating voltage (25-35 kV)<BR>
<LI>High dynamic range of output power (from tens of kW to tens of MW)<BR>
<LI>Reduced power supply size and weight<BR>
<LI>No arcing and voltage breakdown<BR>
<LI>Gun isolation in air (not oil)<BR>
<LI>No need for X-ray shielding (reduced level of harmful X-ray emission)<BR>
<LI>Easier handling and better reliability<BR>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>3. Russian research and development in the
area of high power gyro-amplifiers at millimeter wave has been
ongoing for many years, and is considered to be more extensive
than anywhere else in the world. The existence of powerful 35
GHz and 94 GHz gyro-klystrons for radar developed in Russia during
the last 15 years became public knowledge only about 2 years ago.
Russian  contributions include the following gyro-klystrons:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>three-cavity, 250 kW peak power, half-power bandwidth of 1.5 % at 35 GHz, gain
of 40 dB and 32% efficiency<BR>
<LI>two-cavity, 750 kW peak power, and 24% efficiency at 35 GHz to be extended
to 1 MW<BR>
<LI>four-cavity, 2.5 kW CW operating at 92 GHz with instantaneous half-power bandwidth
0.3%.  Very compact: 70 kg<BR>
<LI>65 kW peak power, efficiency of 34%, and instantaneous half-power
bandwidth of  0.3% at 93 GHz.<BR></UL>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>4. Advanced S&amp;T of high-temperature semiconductors
such as SiC, GaN, and diamond for application in microwave and
optoelectronics. Previously in the domain  of the defense industry,
 key Russian and Ukrainian laboratories are now opening their
doors to westerners and actively seek cooperation and funding.
 Technologies of interest to the DoD include:<BR>
</FONT>
<P><UL>
<LI>Bulk growth of ultra-pure cubic SiC crystals<BR>
<LI>Growth of large area GaN substrates <BR>
<LI>Doping of diamond films using isotope transmutation.<BR></UL>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>I recommend that the DoD invest in cooperative
R&amp;D programs in the FSU, particularly in<BR>
</FONT>
<P><UL>
<LI>Vacuum
microwave components such as MBKs and gyro-klystrons for radar
systems. We must establish the necessary know-how and infrastructure
within our own country to design and produce such components.
Countries such as China, France, and England have already initiated
such programs.  The DoD is favorably positioned in developing
such programs since it is already playing a major role in vacuum
electronics.<BR>
<LI>Crystal growth of high-temperature semiconductors. Russian experts are
willing to share their knowledge with us and we need to find the
proper funding vehicle to establish closer R&amp;D links with
them.  <BR></UL>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Based on the above recommendations, some programs
have already been initiated by ONR and the DoD (see Sections 2.E.
and 3.C.).<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>TECHNOLOGY ASSESSMENT: EUROPEAN ELECTRONICS
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B>1.  INTRODUCTION<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Electronic science and technology are the
cornerstone of modern warfare. Nearly all Navy hardware rely on
electronic and electro-optic systems to meet required objectives.
The future needs in electronics will be even more demanding in
terms of high-speed, low-power consumption and high-reliability
components. Fundamental to achieving planned device performance
levels is the development of novel materials and the understanding
of their underlying physics. The task at hand is the speedy insertion
of new developments in research into the application community
within the Navy and DoD. Because US leadership in electronics
is currently being challenged by foreign competitors, it is more
important than ever that the US research establishment be kept
abreast of the latest progress in Europe (and Japan). <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>It was therefore one of my main objectives
at ONREUR to assess emerging science and technology (S&amp;T)
in electronics, and to serve as a bridge between leading European
scientists and the Navy's scientific staff concerned with electronics.
The resulting assessment is summarized in this report. It should
be stressed, however, that the viewpoints expressed in this report
reflect my own biases and background in electronics and are not
intended to be all encompassing.  The report focusses on S&amp;T
in only a few European countries that, in my opinion, represent
the regional trends.  For more extensive detail, the reader is
referred to Appendix C, which lists the titles of newsletters
written by this author, copies of which can be obtained from ONREUR
in London.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>2. GERMANY: NEW CHALLENGER IN ELECTRONIC S&amp;T  <BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The Federal Republic of Germany (FRG) has
a well-organized national S&amp;T program, a large part of which
impacts the electronic-based infrastructure. The strength of the
German electronic S&amp;T lies in the strategy of forging ahead
in R&amp;D areas in which it feels it can compete with the US
and Japan - or even lead. Although there are some universities
and research laboratories that pursue &quot;me too-ish&quot; activities,
as a whole, the Germans have proven to be independent thinkers
and innovators.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> A. National Focussed Programs: III/V-Electronics and Photonics
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Much of the success of German innovation can
be attributed to well thought-out, long range planning. Usually
the best and most prestigious scientists of the country participate
in guiding German S&amp;T. Scientists and engineers from the Ministry
of S&amp;T and Education, universities, industry, and scientific
societies such as the Fraunhofer and Max-Planck serve on advisory
committees that set priorities and guidelines for electronic programs.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>A good example of this S&amp;T &quot;forging&quot;
is the National Focussed Programs in III/V-Electronics and Photonics.
Started in 1990, this program concentrates on R&amp;D projects
that have transition potential in the civilian sector. The research
consortium &quot;III/V-Elektronik&quot; will enable the German
semiconductor industry to achieve a competitive edge in micro-
and opto-electronic IC technologies. Accomplishments would also
secure a larger demand for German made GaAs substrates, which
until recently have dominated the world GaAs market.  The main
goals of this III-V program are to<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>1. Develop the technology of high-frequency
integrated circuits for future electronic systems, systems that
will have an impact on transportation safety, monitoring of the
environment, and communication. The Germans anticipate an increased
market demand for<BR>
</FONT>
<P><UL>
<LI>Safer transportation-related systems such as collision sensing radars,
<BR>
<LI>New environmental monitoring systems, such as millimeter wave sensors
and systems for traffic control, and<BR>
<LI>New
communications systems, such as short distance communication using
millimeter wave, and ultra-high data rate transmission in fiber-optic
networks.<BR></UL>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>All of the above applications call for higher
complexity, density, and component integration in the microelectronic
chip.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
2. Focus on III/V semiconductor structures of very small dimension.
Structures in this nanometer-scale or quantum regime reveal interesting
new electronic and optical properties and have lead to new electronic
device concepts. Examples of some of these new structures include
quantum-wells, -wires, and -dots. Applications include very efficient
quantum-well lasers, very fast transistors, and new detectors
for the near and far infrared.<BR>

<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>3. Integrate the abovementioned mesoscopic
structures into functional elements and leap into the domain of
&quot;nanoelectronics,&quot; a realm beyond the limits of present
day electronics. The kernel of this research is the development
of new tools that will allow the realization of multifunctional
circuit elements, e.g., electronics and optoelectronics on the
same chip.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>4. Develop integrated optoelectronic components
(e.g., laser sources, detectors, and optical couplers) and use
them in prototype communication systems. The realization of such
systems hinges on two compound semiconductors: InP for the 1.3
to 1.5 </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">m</FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>m
wavelength application, and GaAs for the shorter 0.9 </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">m</FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>m
wavelength application. The leading coordinators for this two-tier
project are: for InP, the FhG Heinrich-Hertz-Institut for Telecommunication
in Berlin; and for GaAs, the Fraunhofer Institute for Applied
Physics (FhG-IAF) in Freiburg. A total of 15 institutions are
involved in these projects.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Some major successes from this program include:
<UL><LI>The development of new design tools and process methodology for monolithic
microwave and millimeter wave integrated circuits (MMICs), e.g.,
the use of coplanar waveguide technology in the fabrication of
high frequency MMICs (see Report #1 for details). Much of this
pioneering work was done at the FhG-IAF in Freiburg.  This laboratory
also conceived the integration of high-frequency RF and optical
components on a GaAs chip. They have been so successful in this
niche technology that the German Ministry of S&amp;T is entrusting
FhG-IAF to develop the next generation, InP-based, 40 Gbit/sec
opto-electronic ICs under their new Photonic 2 program.<BR>
<LI>The
design, processing, and fabrication of a MMIC amplifier based
on a 0.18 micron gate (pseudomorphic) PM-HEMT (25% In in the InGaAs
channel). The two-stage version has a gain of 10 dB at 60 GHz
with a noise figure of 4 dB. A three-stage unit achieves a 37
dB gain. <BR>
<LI>The
development of an active phase array IC consisting of a 4-bit
analog phase shifter integrated with a digital controller.<BR>
<LI>The
development of a 5-stage distributed amplifier with a gain of
9.3 dB over the 5 GHz to 60 GHz frequency range (with a noise
figure less than 4.3 dB up to 60 GHz); and a narrowband, 3-stage,
low-noise amplifier (LNA) with more than 21 dB gain between 70
and 80 GHz (with a noise figure of 6.4 dB at 76 GHz). These MMIC
amplifiers are the first of its kind using coplanar waveguide
technology; the 21 dB gain from 70 to 80 GHz is believed to be
the highest gain yet reported on any MMIC amplifier above 40 GHz
for both GaAs- and InP- based circuits.<BR>
<LI>Novel
measurement techniques for measuring high-frequency electronic
components, e.g., the use of proximal probes such as the scanning
force microscope (SFM) and near-field scanning optical microscope
(NSOM) to test MMICs with nanometer spatial resolution and temporal
resolution up to 100 GHz [see News #39 for details].<BR></UL>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> B. Industrial R&amp;D Initiatives in III/V Electronics<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>In contrast to the high-risk approach pursued
at FhG-IAF, the R&amp;D modus operandi at industrial laboratories
such as AEG Daimler-Benz and Siemens is much more conservative.
This philosophy derives from their profit-oriented business strategy.
Their semiconductor and GaAs R&amp;D is closely linked to systems
applications, which is the true basis for their profit. Although
no risk takers, the German industrial laboratories are well focussed
in their R&amp;D programs as exemplified by Siemens and illustrated
below.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> C. Case History: Siemens <BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Siemens is ranked as the third largest producer
of electronic components (after Philips and Thomson) in Europe
and the sixth largest electronic supplier in the world. It provides
more GaAs parts than any US company and spends about 8B DM ($5B)
or 10% of its total income on R&amp;D. 300M DM of this is earmarked
for semiconductor R&amp;D. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The company's business strategy for manufacturing
semiconductor products (including GaAs) can be summarized as:
high volume, high performance, small and flexible production lines,
use of Si production resources for GaAs processing as much as
possible, and use of well-developed processing technologies. Siemens
is a very profit-oriented company and, as a result, conservative
about implementing high-risk technologies in unproven markets.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Semiconductor products fall into the following
categories:<BR>
<UL><LI>Dedicated ICs, 39%,<BR>
<LI>Memory, 28%,<BR>
<LI>Small signal, 10%,<BR>
<LI>Optoelectronics, 12%, and <BR>
<LI>Semi-custom devices, 4%.<BR></UL>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The split between silicon MOS devices and
small signal GaAs devices is about 50/50. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Products that are competitive on a global
scale include discretes (MESFETs and HEMTs) and MMICs for consumer
applications (DBS, Mobile Communication, Radar). In 1993, Siemens
fabricated about 6 million GaAs discretes and more than 500,000
MMICs. The major microelectronic products are dedicated ICs, standard
ICs, discrete semiconductors, and opto-electronics. The application
drivers are consumer electronics, telecommunication, industrial
electronics, automotive and transport, data communications, military,
and space. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The following is a short summary of the most
important markets in which Siemens is competing.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT COLOR=#000000> 1. Consumer Electronics <BR>
</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The consumer electronics is the largest volume
market at the moment headed by Direct Broadcasting Satellite (DBS)
application. The key GaAs component is the low-noise converter
(LNC) for DBS reception.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Siemens together with GEC-Marconi produces
DBS MESFET LNCs covering different subbands between 10.95 and
12.5 GHz. The circuit comprises an LNA, an active mixer, a local
oscillator<B> </B>(LO), an intermediate frequency<B> </B>(IF)
amplifier, and an on-chip filter. The Siemens 4 mm square components
have achieved over 30 dB conversion gain and better than 6 dB
noise figure. The associated HEMT LNA MMIC has a gain of 19 dB,
NF of 1.25 dB, and S11/S22 better than 10 dB between 11-12.5 GHz.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT COLOR=#000000> 2. Telecommunications <BR>
</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Mobile communication is the fastest growing
market in Europe headed by cellular or cordless telephones. The
market is expected to increase from 2.6 million units in 1990
to 100M by year 2000. The second generation of mobile communication
services is characterized by the change from analog to digital
transmission techniques. The new system standard is fixed by the
GSM (Group Special Mobile) telephone system. It will be the first
mobile communication standard to be introduced all over Europe.
The first version at 900 MHz is already operational; the second
generation at 1.8 GHz, called PCN or DCS1800 (Personal Communication
Network or Digital European Cordless Telephone) was just introduced
last year.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Siemens has been the leading supplier in Europe
of Si and GaAs components for these mobile communication systems.
The set of GaAs devices for GSM-PCN-DCS include<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_</FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>MESFET
LNA MMICs (NF of 1.5 dB),</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>MESFET
mixer and LNC MMICs (SSB-NF of 5 dB),</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Power
MESFETs (from 0.2 to 1 watt, PAE &gt; 55%), and</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Power
VGAs and HPA MMICs.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>All devices are optimized for 3 V supply and
are assembled in different plastic packages. Siemens is making
money on these GaAs products and sells a 50 cent GaAs part for
cellular communication at 800 MHz. They also manufacture a plastic
package (good to 12 GHz and usable to 180 degrees C) for their
commercial microwave products. Other GaAs items include a 1.8
GHz, 200-700 mW MMIC with PAE &gt; 50% at 3 volts for use in a
GSM system (costs less than $10; about 2 million sold).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT COLOR=#000000> 3. Military and Space <BR>
</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>A major military application is phased array
radar (PAR), which uses active transmit/receive (T/R) modules
in quantities of some hundreds to a few thousand GaAs components.
A typical T/R module consists of a set of GaAs MMICs such as LNA,
VGA, PHS (phase shifter), switches, and medium and high power
amplifiers (MPA, HPA). The special requirements for this module
are low NF for the receiver, high accuracy for the phase/gain
control units, and highest possible PAE for the HPA to reduce
power consumption of the antenna.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Detailed information about device performance
for space and military applications can be found in Report #3.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Siemens is making money on the GaAs foundry
through sales of GaAs parts for the merchant market (mostly commercial).
It uses the most developed and reliable process technology to
cut cost. Commercial cost drivers increase efficiency of resource
utilization and lead to competitiveness. The maxim is to use the
material and technology that proves to be &quot;good enough&quot;
(including packages). Siemens' success with plastic packaging
warrants a closer look at our own DoD programs to reduce MMIC
costs even further.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>This conservative, low-risk approach may be
short sighted. They may have to rely on outside R&amp;D breakthroughs
for their future S&amp;T base. To provide breadth to their research
programs, Siemens is funding research at some of the most prestigious
universities and non-profit laboratories in Germany.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Siemens planners anticipate a booming market
in DBS, mobile communication, wireless LAN, and ASICs in the next
few years and are taking proper steps now to position themselves
as a major provider of GaAs-based components in Europe and the
world.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> D.  The Role of Former East Germany: Personal Observation
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The formal unification of East-West Germany
on October 3, 1990 marked a historic event for the German people
and the world. It brought together two countries that were ideologically
separate for almost four decades and unleashed political and social
changes that are still being felt today.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The unification also heralded major changes
within the East German scientific community. Right from the start,
the government in Bonn set up a Science Advisory Council to evaluate
the different scientific disciplines in East Germany and to implement
a restructuring of its infrastructure in the &quot;western mold.&quot;
This whole evaluation process was finished by the end of 1992.
By the beginning of 1993, the federal government set in motion
sweeping changes within the former East German S&amp;T establishment
(see News #13 &amp; 23 and Report # 2). Some of the key changes
in the former S&amp;T establishment include:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>1. reducing the scientific and technical staff,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>2. laying off the &quot;old guard,&quot;</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>3. abolishing the former Academy of Sciences
structure,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>4. establishing new Max-Planck and Fraunhofer
institutes, </FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>5. appointing new leaders in the newly established
institutions, and</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>6. reinstating research within the new academic
environment.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Over the past 3 years, I was privileged to
visit many of these new institutions and to witness this metamorphosis
first hand. Here are some of my personal observations:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>The
restructuring of the former S&amp;T institutions by West German
scientists was necessary but fair. Today, many senior professors
who were privileged under the old Communist regime continue enjoying
financial security under generous German pension plans. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Although
the initial impact of German unification was severe, the last
five years have heralded a new sense of optimism among the citizens
of East Germany. In contrast to a year or two ago, when the population
seemed to be in a catatonic trance, people today are more confident
and smiling. Service in stores and restaurants is polite and efficient.
There is the feeling of &quot;can do.&quot; Major reconstruction
is taking place: highways, roads, streets are being repaired;
new rail and telephone lines are being installed; old buildings
are repaired and historical sites restored; and new shopping centers
are mushrooming everywhere.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Before
1990, the German Democratic Republic (GDR) was a major contributor
to electronic technology within the Eastern Block. The electronic
R&amp;D centers were located at Berlin, Erfurt, Freiberg, Leipzig,
and Dresden. Most of this R&amp;D was done at the GDR Academy
of Sciences, industrial laboratories, and to a minor extent, at
the universities. Berlin was the hub for processing of microcircuits
and semiconductor lasers, although most computer-related development
and processing took place at &quot;Robotron&quot; in Sommerda
near Erfurt.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Today,
most of these R&amp;D sites have been either taken over by West
German firms, have been completely restructured, or have simply
been shut down. For example, Wacker-Chemitronic, the pioneer of
GaAs and one of the world leading manufacturer of GaAs wafers,
transferred its GaAs production facilities from West Germany to
Freiberger Electronic Materials (Freiberger Elektronikwerkstoffe,
FEW), a new GaAs production complex located in Freiberg/Sachsen.
Most of the electronic R&amp;D that was formerly done at the GDR
Academy of Sciences is now performed at so-called &quot;Blue-List&quot;
research laboratories or at newly established Fraunhofer institutes.
The most notable among them are the Paul-Drude Institute for Solid
State Electronics in Berlin, Institute for Semiconductor Physics
in Frankfurt (Oder), Ferdinand-Braun Institute for High Frequency
Communication Technology and Optoelectronics in Berlin, and the
Fraunhofer Institute for Microelectronic Circuits and Systems
in Dresden (for a complete listing and information, see News #13).
The newly formed Max-Planck Institute of Microstructure Physics
in Halle has new leaders and is playing a key role within the
German electronic R&amp;D community.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Finally,
it is important to add that today, with the new scientific order
in Germany, the research institutions in East Germany represent
an added intellectual force to Germany. They also offer a vital
link to the former Eastern Block states. The former ties with
Russia are still very strong. As East Germany transitions into
a fully integrated democratic Germany, this connectivity will
play an important role in bridging the two worlds. Such bridging
will bring together not only the scientific communities, but will
hopefully spill over into all the other cultural and social ramifications
of life.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>I, personally, have no doubt that a region
which was the nurturing place for giants like Martin Luther, Johann
Wolfgang Goethe, Johann Friedrich Schiller, Johann Sebastian Bach,
and Georg Friedrich Handel will re-emerge from the ashes and will
play again a leading role in shaping the next millennium. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> E. Lessons Learned, Assessment, and Recommendations<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>German R&amp;D institutions have shown to
be innovative and pace-setters in the world of high-technology
electronics. They have demonstrated some of the latest state-of-the-art
design, processing, and testing facilities as good as anywhere.
National processing facilities such as the FhG-IAF are available
for joint projects and are run by crews of highly trained and
talented engineers. The management is efficient and the R&amp;D
well focussed. In the case of MMIC and optoelectronic IC development,
the long-term R&amp;D strategy has proven to be excellent as exemplified
by many &quot;world records&quot; and bodes well for the future
of German GaAs based technology.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Based on numerous visits to key laboratories
involved in RF and MMIC R&amp;D in Germany, it is safe to conclude
that the Germans are on a par with the US when it comes to exploiting
the GaAs-based technology. The MMIC R&amp;D in Germany is much
more commercially oriented than that in the US, where manufacturers
of MMICs are much more inclined to remain in their R&amp;D mode
as long as military applications dominate. This is beginning to
change as new commercial markets are calling for ever increasing
numbers of MMIC components. German manufacturers like Siemens
are convinced that money can be made with GaAs-based products
and are positioning themselves in the lead.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>In the past five years, US DoD has invested
heavily in developing MMICs through programs such as the MIMIC
ARPA/Tri-Service initiative. The major objective of this heavily
subsidized government program was the anticipated improvement
in performance of present and future radar systems. The DoD expects
that, by investing in this MMIC technology, it will drive down
the procurement costs of such systems, provided that the technology
will spill-over into the commercial sector. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Now that DoD is facing cutbacks, it is imperative
that the MIMIC industrial community seek continuity in their programs
in the private sector. In a declining budget scenario, leveraging
by commercial interest becomes paramount. It is hoped that US
manufacturers, now active in the MIMIC program, will pay closer
attention to their competitors in Europe. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>I recommend that the US keep abreast of the
German efforts in MMIC technology and that US government and industrial
laboratories forge a closer link with some of their MMIC programs.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000>3.  THE FORMER SOVIET UNION: A WINDOW OF
OPPORTUNITY<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>In order to assess the S&amp;T activities
in the Former Soviet Union (FSU), it imperative to give the reader
first a short glimpse at the new S&amp;T infrastructure and a
feel for the general R&amp;D climate there.  Since much has been
written about Russia since the dissolution of the FSU, the following
chapter focusses only on S&amp;T opportunities in Russia. The
human dimension and the plight of the R&amp;D community today
is exemplified in the chapter on Ukraine.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> A. Russian Innovation</B>
<P>
  
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Much has been written about the Former Soviet
Union and its S&amp;T infrastructure in the last five years. The
R&amp;D &quot;climate&quot; in Russia is somewhat better than
in the other breakaway republics (see comments on Ukraine in Section
3.B.). My report focusses primarily on research that impacts current
DoD programs and involves potential collaboration between Russia
and the USA.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000> 1. New Approach to Power Vacuum Microwave
Devices<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Much of Russian S&amp;T in electronics during
the Communist era was defense related. Most of our awareness of
their scientific contribution to this important field is just
emerging thanks to the breakup of the Soviet Union<B>.</B>  One
discipline in electronics in which the Russians excelled is vacuum
electronics. This is not surprising since the Russians always
lacked the advanced, market-driven infrastructure of solid state
electronics found in the West and, thus, channeled their R&amp;D
efforts into developing sophisticated vacuum-based electronics,
particularly microwave power devices. In the last few years, much
of this technology has been unveiled for closer scrutiny by Western
scientists.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>A good example of this type of R&amp;D can
be found at the prestigious Moscow State University (MSU). Here,
the Microwave Electronics and Space Power Systems Group has been
developing vacuum microwave electronic devices that do not use
a conventional &quot;bunching&quot; principle to extract microwave
energy, e.g., traditional klystrons and TWTs. Instead, they are
developing new methods of energy exchange where electron-electron
interaction due to close proximity (bunching) is not a problem.
Their approach is totally novel. Microwave energy extraction is
based on transverse grouping of homogeneous electron beam in circularly
polarized electromagnetic fields (in resonant cavities and slow-wave
structures). This approach circumvents the limitation imposed
by bunching and leads to improved device performance, e.g., super
linearity in device characteristics such as frequency and phase.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Using these principles and realistic 3-D computer
simulation, the MSU group have succeeded in designing new types
of microwave devices. Many of these experimental prototypes have
been manufactured and tested at various microwave factories throughout
the FSU. One of their products is a microwave-power-to-dc voltage
converter used in wireless power transmission applications, e.g.,
space power systems. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Table 1 lists these devices and some of their
specifications.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT COLOR=#000000>Table 1</FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">&aelig;</FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>
MSU Microwave Devices<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=1>

<TR><TD WIDTH=295><CENTER>DEVICES</CENTER></TD><TD WIDTH=295><CENTER>SPECIFICATIONS</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=295>High-power Circularly Polarized TWTs (CPTWT)
</TD><TD WIDTH=295><FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Extremely linear phase and frequency characteristics (one to two orders of magnitude better than standard klystrons and TWTs).
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>High efficiency: 35-40% into the load and up to 70-80% with recuperation.
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Wide bandwidth: up to 20-30% of center frequency
<P>
 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=295>High-power Cyclotron-Wave Converters (CWC)</TD>
<TD WIDTH=295><FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>High efficiency: microwave to dc up to 80-90%, from 50 to 100 kW
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Output voltage range: 10 to 100 kV
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=295>Low-noise Cyclotron-Wave Parametric Amplifier (CWPA) and
<P>
 Cyclotron-Wave ElectroStatic Amplifiers (CWESA)<BR>

</TD><TD WIDTH=295><FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Low noise temperature: 30-100 K
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Very high self-protection against microwave overload: up to 500 kW pulse; short restoration time of 1 to 10 ns
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Small size and weight; low voltage supply
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=295>Narrowband Controlled CWESA-Filters</TD><TD WIDTH=295><FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Low noise temperature: 100-200 K
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Wide frequency range: up to 50%; high-speed frequency control
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>High self-protection and short restoration time
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=295>Klystrons with combined longitudinal-transverse interaction<BR>

</TD><TD WIDTH=295><FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Extended bandwidth: up to 8-10% of center frequency
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>High efficiency: 75-80% for various power levels (up to 50 kW) 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=295>Cyclotron-Wave Phase Shifters (CWPS)</TD><TD WIDTH=295><FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Power level: 10-50 kW
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Wide phase control range: 0-360 grad; high-speed phase control
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Low signal losses: 0.5-1.0 dB
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>

<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The MSU group has also developed a number
of software packages for modeling vacuum microwave devices using
a 486 PC. These packages include the following:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>1. TWTs (standard and transverse-type). Features
include:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Turbo Pascal, 3D model
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Coulomb interaction, TE field, accurate
geometry, and high electric field taken  into account
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Screen display of:
<P>
 - efficiency, gain vs distance along the TWT (z-axis),
<P>
 - velocity spread for each z-cut, 
<P>
 - longitudinal velocity spread vs number of modeling beams (total
of 100 beams),
<P>
 - a &quot;bore&quot; view of the beams as a function of time
<BR>

<P>
2. Software for collector and cathode modeling (for optimum efficiency
design)<BR>

<P>
3. Software for modeling standard klystrons featuring:<BR>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Input parameters: Q-factor, dimensions,
etc.
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Analytic and &quot;disc&quot; model
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Output: visualization of bunching
with time along the tube
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Benchmarking against Western klystron
designs<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000> 2. Multibeam Klystron<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The multibeam klystron (MBK) concept was first
proposed by US scientists in the early 1950s but was never developed.
The Soviets took the concept seriously and developed it into a
product that is currently used in many Russian radar systems.
The idea is to distribute and control not one, but multiple electron
beams in the klystron cathode. The low current of each electron
beam leads to low perveance and high efficiency. Since the total
current (NxI) is high, the cathode voltage is considerably lower
than in a conventional klystron. The net gain in design is<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Smaller power and voltage supplies
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>No more arcing and breakdown
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Gun need not be isolated in oil
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>No need for x-ray shielding
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Easier to handle<BR>

<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The gain, power output and the frequency bandwidth
increase nonlinearly with the number of beams.  The overall improvement
is dramatic: higher efficiency (55-70%), lower operating voltage
(25-35 kV) and high dynamic range of output power (from tens of
 kW to tens of MW).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Many institutes and universities were involved
in the development of MBKs during the Soviet era. These included
the Moscow State University, Moscow Power Engineering Institute,
and State Research and Production Corporation &quot;ISTOK&quot;
(an electronic factory outside Moscow).  Although the MBK technology
and know-how is still proprietary, the units can be purchased
from at least two sources in Russia. Recently, Svetlana-Electronpribor
of St. Petersburg has been circulating specifications of various
multibeam klystron amplifiers for sale to the West.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000> 3. Gyro-klystrons<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Russian research and development in the area
of high power gyro-amplifiers at millimeter wave has been ongoing
for many years,  and is considered to be more extensive than anywhere
else in the world. The existence of powerful 35 GHz and 94 GHz
gyro-klystrons for radar developed in Russia during the last 15
years became public knowledge only about 2 years ago. Russian
 contributions include the following:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>the
design of powerful three-cavity gyro-klystrons (developed by the
Institute of Applied Physics (IAP) in Nizhny, Novgorod and the
Moscow-based microwave industry TORY), which are capable of  200
to 250 kW peak power and half-power bandwidth of about 1 to 1.5
% at 35 GHz. This gyro-klystron utilizes a triode magnetron injection
gun for production of electron beam at beam voltage of  50 to
60 kV and beam current up to 15 A. These tubes have been used
in Russian radar as powerful transmitters in a three-stage amplification
chain: solid state amplifier-TWT- gyro-klystron. The gain of the
gyro-klystron is 40 dB and the efficiency is 32%.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>the
development of a 1MW gyro-klystron (fabricated at IAP-TORY) as
a last stage of a four-stage amplification chain. The experimental
two-cavity gyro-klystron achieved peak power of  750 kW with efficiency
of 24% operating at a beam voltage of  74 kV. The input power
for this gyro-klystron was supplied by a 10 kW mechanically tunable
gyrotron.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>the
development of a CW,  2.5 kW four-cavity gyro-klystron operating
at 92 GHz (the result of a joint venture between the Institute
of Applied Physics in Nizhny, Novgorod and the microwave industry
ISTOK at Friasino). This amplifier also utilizes a magnetron injection
gun to produce electron beam at beam voltage of 25 kV and beam
current of 1 A. The instantaneous half-power bandwidth of the
gyro-klystron is 0.3%.  Considering the capabilities offered by
this device, it is quite compact: its maximum length, height,
and weight are 81 cm, 80 cm,  and 70 kg, respectively.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>the
design (also at the Institute of Applied Physics in Nizhny, Novgorod)
of  a gyro-klystron capable of peak power of 65 kW and efficiency
of 34%, and instantaneous half-power bandwidth of  0.3% at 93
GHz. Its beam voltage is 55 kV and beam current is 3 to 5 A.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000> 4. US Chips in Russian PCs<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Another example of Russian ingenuity in electronics
involves using the latest computer chips developed in the US for
improving the graphics capability of PCs. This work is done by
a group of talented young engineers at the Computer Design Group
of the Microelectronic Center at MSU. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>During the Communist regime, this same group
was in charge of developing the Soviet equivalent of our PC. The
result was modest by Western standards, but the knowledge base
was enormous. Today, this group is able to engage in creative,
new hardware projects thanks to the availability of US-made microchips
that are no longer  on the restricted export list.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Using US made programmable microchips and
hardware design tools, they have, for example, built a high-speed
accelerator board called Corvette 860RGB. The Corvette 860RGB
board consists of an 80 MFLOPS 64-bit Intel i80860 chip, 16 MB
of system RAM with extreme access speed, and a high-resolution
true color graphics subsystem with 4 MB of direct-access, dedicated
VRAM video buffer. The unit fits a standard PC and can be used
for image processing, scientific calculations, true color desktop
publishing, computer-aided design (CAD), and 3-D simulation and
animation. The Corvette 860RGB comes with software and graphics
primitives libraries and is compatible with NDP, PGI, STAR860,
and GNU compilers.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>This is a good example of combining Russian
ingenuity with the achievements of Western high technology to
produce new products that may yet compete in a world market. The
abovementioned hardware prototype and its performance is impressive.
The question is whether Russian electronic factories are flexible
enough to mass produce them. One thing is certain, perestroika
has provided the Russian military unprecedented access to advanced
computer design tool technology.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000> 5. High-temperature Electronics<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Electronic devices based on SiC and GaN semiconductors
are finding numerous applications in the automotive, aircraft,
and other commercial and defense sectors.  Both SiC and GaN have
shown potential as light emitting diodes in the blue and blue-green
region of the spectrum while cubic SiC appears to be the best
candidate for high-power, high-temperature electronic applications.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The US and Japan have expended substantial
R&amp;D effort on these materials in the past decade. The USSR
also had an intensive R&amp;D effort in these materials for at
least two decades before its collapse. Much of this work was done
for the military and only recently has the West had a glimpse
as to the extent of these activities. Much of the early information
about FSU SiC research came from Russian scientists who either
emigrated to the US or attended international conferences in the
West.  A more complete picture of the FSU's capabilities in high-temperature
electronic materials emerged in recent visits by DoD scientists
(among them this author) to key Russian and Ukrainian institutions
involved in SiC and GaN research.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Many groups in Russia and Ukraine are working
on SiC and GaN today.  Among them, the Ioffe Physical-Technical
Institute and the Leningrad Electro Technical Institute (LETI)
in St. Petersburg are the most eminent.  Both of these groups
have been working on SiC, GaN, and related compounds for the past
three decades (see author's Newsletter #30 on Electronics). Recent
advances in epitaxial growth of AlN, GaN, InGaN by MBE and CVD,
are challenging these institutes to revisit some of their previous
experimental approaches in growing GaN. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>One of these approaches is to grow thick GaN
by the so-called sublimation sandwich technique. Here, ammonia
is streamed past a GaN powder or polycrystalline substrate in
close proximity to a SiC substrate. GaN grows best on 6H-SiC at
1150 C, although growth on Si is also possible. Growth rates can
be as high as 0.5 mm/hr. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>As early as 1975, Prof. Vodakov and collaborators
at Ioffe showed that this approach can produce 0.5 mm thick free-standing,
high-quality GaN substrates after the SiC substrate is etched
away. This project has been revived, and Vodakov, along with Drs.
Mokhov and Roenkov, are now planning to grow thick GaN on 25 mm
diameter or larger SiC substrates.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The other group at Ioffe doing SiC or GaN
research and headed by Prof. Chelnokov were not forthcoming on
what they are doing. I had a short talk with Dr. Alexander Lebedev
from this group; he is apparently collaborating with the University
of Arizona Optical Sciences Center and Topaz in New Mexico on
SiC related projects. Cree-East is collocated with this group,
but they were not disposed to talk to strangers. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The last group in St. Petersburg involved
with SiC and GaN is LETI (now St. Petersburg State Electrical
Engineering University) headed by Prof. Yuri M. Tairov. Dr. Pitchugin,
who works for Tairov, has built a CVD reactor in which both SiC
and GaN have been grown in the past. The system is currently being
duplicated by Chelnokov's group (with Cree funding). Prof. Tairov
is well known in the West for his pioneering work in SiC. He has
an active group in bulk SiC growth and a first class characterization
laboratory headed by Dr. Pikhtin. I was pleasantly surprised by
the openness, candor, and urbane manner of Prof. Tairov. He is
a scientist and leader in the best tradition. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000> 6. Diamond Doping<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>I met Dr. Raphael Kucherov from ISTOK and
had an interesting discussion about using boron-10 isotope for
n-doping diamond films. This research is done in collaboration
with the Institute of Stable Isotopes in Tbilisi, Georgia and
was first disclosed to the West at the International Diamond conference
held in Lisbon in 1993. The concept involves utilizing 99.6% pure
boron-10 isotope during diamond film growth. The more abundant
boron-11 incorporates readily into diamond during film growth
but gives rise to p-type conduction.  Doping with boron-10 followed
by neutron irradiation leads to Li incorporation and n-type doping.
N-type doping of diamond is extremely difficult because of the
low incorporation and activation when using conventional N or
Li.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>This group also synthesized boron carbide
with the isotope B10. This new material apparently has a thermal
conductivity 2.5 times higher and a sound velocity 20% higher
than normal boron carbide.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> B. The Ukrainian R&amp;D Dilemma</B>
<P>
 
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Despite this highly developed S&amp;T infrastructure,
Ukrainian science is facing severe difficulties due to a general
economic emergency and the slow pace of conversion towards a free
market economy.  The average wage in Ukraine is currently 10 to
15 dollars per month, as compared to 60 to 80 dollars per month
in Russia.  Inflation is approximately 100 percent per month.
As of this writing, Ukraine still does not have a national currency.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Given such a chaotic economic infrastructure,
the Ukrainian scientists and institutions are handicapped doing
research even when funded by US or European agencies.  For example,
the Ukrainian government insists that at least 50% of the foreign
grant for R&amp;D be converted to local &quot;coupons&quot; at
the official government rate, which is about 1/3 the market rate.
If the project needs equipment or supplies, these must be purchased
with hard currency.  To complicate matters, the institutes are
constrained to support their full work force with any contract
money they receive.  It is not possible for institutions to layoff
workers who don't have projects, so their salaries are taken from
active projects.  This is particularly difficult since the scientific
research structure had been created for the USSR as a whole, and
is now much larger than can be supported by the needs of Ukraine
as an independent country.  By the time taxes and overhead are
added, there is very little left for doing the scientific research.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>As a consequence of this economic situation,
institutions such as the Academy of Science are struggling to
find ways to combat what they call the &quot;external and internal
brain drain&quot; - an uncontrolled exodus of scientists leaving
the country for opportunities abroad, and those who leave science
for jobs such as driving taxis, which can pay much more.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The most frustrating aspect of this dilemma
is the abundance of apathy towards changing things. There seems
to be no obvious effort made to convert what used to be defense-related
high technology R&amp;D activities to new commercial ventures
that could benefit the country as a whole. The old system is very
pervasive. Most scientists I talked to were reserved about revealing
who is doing what and where. There is still fear on one hand,
and ignorance on the other, to divulge information about R&amp;D,
a legacy from the old days. Even today, each scientist has only
a narrow view of his/her own research field. Only heads of institutes
(and party members of good standing) were well informed about
the implication of their R&amp;D. In the USSR, over 80% of all
R&amp;D was funded by and done for the Ministry of Defense and
projects were &quot;compartmentalized.&quot; People minded their
own business and did not ask questions about what is going on
next door. Soviets have sacrificed all comforts of life for the
&quot;defense of the motherland.&quot; In return, everyone had
a job, a small flat, a month vacation, and enough food to live
on. Today the R&amp;D funding is reduced to 1/3 and the &quot;good
old days&quot; are just a memory.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> C.  Assessment and Recommendations<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>It is clear that Russia and many of the republics
of the FSU offer a window of opportunity in selected areas of
electronic S&amp;T that may be of strategic importance to the
DoD. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>R&amp;D as exemplified by the MSU's vacuum
microwave activities is representative of Russian technological
advances along &quot;evolutionary branches&quot; different from
those found in the West. Because of economic hardships, there
is a real possibility that such technology &quot;species&quot;
may become extinct before they are fully appreciated (discovered)
by Western scientists. It is therefore recommended that serious
consideration should be given to supporting the R&amp;D activities
at institutions dealing with power microwave development. Small
investment on our part may lead to new information and insight
of FSU vacuum microelectronic technology. The first step in this
direction has already been taken. In the past few months, ONREUR
has facilitated the funding of research at Moscow State University
to further develop the cyclotron wave electrostatic amplifier
concept described above. The program is funded by ONR and its
technical supervision is under the Naval Research Laboratory.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>I further recommend that the DoD invest in
cooperative R&amp;D programs in the FSU, particularly in vacuum
microwave components such as MBKs and gyro-klystrons for radar
systems. It is imperative to establish the necessary know-how
and infrastructure within our own country in designing and producing
such components. Countries such as China, France, and England
have already initiated such programs.  The DoD is favorably positioned
in developing such programs since it is already playing a major
role in vacuum electronics.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The Institute of Stable Isotopes in Tbilisi
is a unique facility that needs closer examination. The facility
has a stockpile of 99.6% purity stable isotopes of boron and other
group III elements. It would be highly useful for the DoD to invite
Dr. Guran Karumidze, principal investigator at Tbilisi, to the
US. The stockpile of isotopes in Tbilisi is a unique resource
for scientific investigation. N-doping of diamond and synthesis
of boron(10) carbide are just a few of the many applications.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000>4.  HUNGARY: S&amp;T LANDSCAPE<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>As in all former Eastern Block nations, the
Hungarian research was modeled along the lines of the Soviet system.
It was based on the idea that basic and applied research was the
responsibility of the Academy institutes and that technical and
industrial research was the responsibility of the R&amp;D units
of the specialized ministries. Universities and industrial laboratories
were not allowed to undertake research activities on their own.
All industrial research laboratories were detached from companies
and were run as independent institutions.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Over the past 40 years this pattern has changed.
Due partly to political and economic changes, universities and
larger firms have gradually established research units. Moreover,
the Academy's institutes have gradually been involved in contract
research activities with industrial applications.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Since the dismantling of the COMECOM in 1989,
Hungary has been engaged in radical economic, political and social
transformation. Although changes have taken place more satisfactorily
than in most central and eastern European countries, they are
proving to be a difficult and painful process. The economic crisis
has not spared science and technology. As a consequence of both
the decline in government support and their dependency on contract
support from industry, Hungarian R&amp;D establishment has been
confronted by serious problems. The deterioration of the economic
climate has led to continued brain-drain within the R&amp;D community.
Many researchers have left their laboratories to seek work abroad
or to work in the private sector in fields marginally related
to their specialization. Throughout the R&amp;D landscape, there
has been a personnel reduction of 25% and a cut by almost half
in R&amp;D funding. Some institutes have closed doors or are operating
with a skeleton staff. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> A. New Blueprint for Hungarian Science &amp; Technology<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Within this climate of change during the past
six years, Hungary has embarked on restructuring its R&amp;D infrastructure.
The new Hungary's R&amp;D blueprint reveals a two-fold structure:
basic research is administered by the Hungarian Academy of Sciences
(HAS) while technology is managed by the National Committee for
Technological Development (OMFB).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>This duality carries over to the R&amp;D funding.
There are two separate funds: one for research, called the National
Fund for Scientific Research (OTKA), and the other for promoting
technology, called the Central Technical Development Fund (KMUFA).
Interestingly, OTKA is financed by KMUFA, but managed by an autonomous
body headed by the Minister without portfolio for Science.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Both entities (science and technology) have
equal status within the echelons of the political system. There
is a Minister without portfolio for science and a Minister without
portfolio for technology. The former chairs the Science Policy
Committee, the highest authority for R&amp;D policy-making in
the country.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The Science Policy Committee coordinates and
proposes the R&amp;D policies to the government. The Committee
is chaired by the president of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences
and is composed of the following additional members: (1) The President
of OMFB, (2) the Minister of Culture and Public Education, and
(3) the Minister of Finance.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>During the Communist regime, the Committee's
task was to implement S&amp;T policy decided upon by the Central
Party Committee. Under the new political climate, the Committee
has the task of coordinating the policy-making process, taking
into account the interests and proposals expressed by the major
institutions concerned.  Whereas before, the Ministries dictated
the S&amp;T policy, now the course is set mostly by HAS, OMFB,
the funding agencies (OTKA and KMUFA), and the commercial sector.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The ministries mentioned previously help to
develop S&amp;T policy in the areas for which they are responsible,
but play a lesser role in the overall charting of the S&amp;T
course. Outside organizations, such as industrialists, educators,
and trade unions, play a lesser advisory role. It is clear that
under the present structure, the future of S&amp;T in Hungary
is in the hands of scientists and government.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>One may question such a &quot;top-down&quot;
approach in setting S&amp;T policy as being incongruous with market
economy and parliamentary democracy currently emerging in Hungary.
However, lacking a democratic tradition in the past, any other
approach would most likely lead to even greater turmoil within
the S&amp;T establishment. There is clearly a need for help in
developing a democratic tradition within the S&amp;T community
in Hungary. Educational institutions must train a new generation
of scientists, engineers, and technocrats who are able to function
and succeed within the new democratic environment. This process
can be speeded by establishing closer ties between the Hungarian
and Western countries'<B> </B>S&amp;T establishments. This can
only be achieved if scientific institutions in the West take a
more active role.  Such steps are beginning to be taken by many
university departments; they are beginning to take a more active
role in research and training a new generation of scientists and
engineers who are comfortable working within a greater European
community.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> B. The Electronic Infrastructure<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>During the Communist era, Hungary had a healthy
electronic infrastructure that was well funded and served the
Warsaw Pact military needs. Si- and GaAs-based discrete device
components were fabricated and traded within that community. 
The center for most of this electronic R&amp;D was the Research
Institute for Technical Physics in Budapest. This institute of
the Hungarian Academy of Sciences was founded in 1956 and reached
its zenith in the 1980s. Unfortunately, the modern Si device fabrication
facility built in 1990, which was supposed to be the cornerstone
for Hungarian electronic infrastructure, was destroyed by fire
shortly after completion.  The Hungarian Academy never found the
resources to rebuild it and many of its technical staff left the
institute to start new careers either in the private sector or
abroad.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> C. Computer and Information Technology<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Aside from fabrication of electronic components,
Hungary was and still is an important player in computer and information-related
know-how. The recent R&amp;D policy changes mentioned above have
had profound impact on this field. According to the Finance Ministry,
Hungary is experiencing a large demand for scientific, business,
trade, and service-related data; there is also great demand for
computer application products. This information technology related
market is still moderate when compared to the West, but it is
one of the fastest growing sectors within the Hungarian economy.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Information technology (IT) is not new to
Hungary. The first telecommunications manufacturing company, the
first research institute, and the first telephone network were
already operating in the early 1890s shortly after the invention
of the telephone by Alexander<B> </B>Graham Bell. The country
has had a rather strong tradition in electronics, computers, and
telecommunication technology, even under the Communist regime.
The IT and computer sector flourished and constituted a significant
fraction of the products exported to the eastern markets, primarily
to the Soviet Union. Items such as computer chips, hard disks,
CD-ROM drives, etc., banned under CoCom regulations, were created
and developed in Hungary (albeit not with the sophistication pursued
in the West).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>With the dissolution of the Soviet Union,
all the former eastern markets collapsed and Hungary was left
only with its technology and knowledge base. To add insult to
injury, the IT and computer sector was further crushed by the
relaxed CoCom restrictions. Western companies were suddenly allowed
to export to Hungary advanced IT systems and components, thus
posing direct competition to Hungarian-made IT products. As a
result, many of the institutionalized (government owned) electronic
and telecommunication enterprises are struggling to survive. Some
have entered into joint venture with western companies, others
were bought up outright. Today, a considerable number of the survivors
pursue &quot;value added&quot; and system integration projects.
The newly established small companies generally do not deal with
development and production; rather, they concentrate more on service-related
activities such as retailing, repair and maintenance, and consulting.
In short, domestic IT and computer firms are compelled to cooperate
with western partners, to cater to the service sector, and to
do business within a much harsher competitive environment.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>To salvage its former IT industry, the Hungarian
government has started to explore new strategies in supporting
this vital technology sector. Unfortunately, within the government,
none of the ministries are responsible for IT policy making. Issues
addressed and decisions made even at the Prime Minister's Office
level still deal with secondary issues such as electronic networking
within the government agencies. All the ministries are mandated
to formulate and update their IT strategy yearly, but an integrated
IT policy is still awaiting presentation to Parliament.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Government agencies assigned with funding
and promoting IT development are looking for mechanisms to leverage
their meager resources. Top priority is given to S&amp;T projects
that involve working partnerships between government and industrial
establishments. Research institutes and universities are directly
involved with some of these programs. A few of the most noteworthy
projects are aimed at rebuilding the information infrastructure
of local governments. The S&amp;T community has already established
its electronic communication under this program. Academies, universities,
and research laboratories were the first to connect to international
networks. Electronic mail, file transfer services, and databases
are available for 6,000 researchers by OSI or TCP/IP protocols.
There are at least four Hungarian Academy of Sciences research
laboratories and about ten university departments dealing with
IT-related R&amp;D. Universities and private institutions teach
courses in the use of electronic communication and computers.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> D. Reaching Towards the West<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Funding agencies are also entrusted with providing
a favorable environment for international collaboration. For a
country with a limited domestic market, it is essential to seek
closer ties with the mainstream international S&amp;T community.
Hungary is currently a member of the European Research Coordinating
Agency (EUREKA), Cooperation on S&amp;T (COST), and the European
Science Foundation (ESF). The Hungarian government is sharing
cost with the EC in developing IT infrastructure within the country
and is participating in the EUREKA COSINE program in linking the
Hungarian computer network with the European research community.
There is also a US-Hungarian S&amp;T Joint Fund, which facilitates
R&amp;D collaboration between the two countries.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The Hungarian research establishment is very
active and competitive in submitting research proposal to the
various EU S&amp;T initiatives. Just in the past six months, out
of the 300 proposals emanating from Central Europe under the European
Union's Fourth Framework Program for Research and Technological
Development initiative, 100 were from Hungary. Out of these, one
third have a good chance of being funded.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Despite all these efforts, the transition
is turning out to be a long and arduous process. There is need
for more funding, for more strategic planning, and for new alliances
with the West. Hungarians must learn to be more self-reliant and
to exercise a new way of thinking about their social, economic,
and intellectual life. This is not easy for people whose lives
were dictated by a central Communist committee for 45 years. The
West, on the other hand, must provide encouragement and financial
stimulation. It is essential that the land that gave the world
John von Neumann, the father of computer sciences, will not be
forgotten. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000>5.  ITALY: SOME S&amp;T HIGHLIGHTS  <BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Italian scientists and engineers have an excellent
reputation within the electronics community. They have contributed
fundamental, as well as, practical knowledge to this field ever
since the term &quot;electronics&quot; was coined. Since the early
1950s and 1960s, Italian scientists have made key contributions
to solid state physics and electronics, e.g., electronic band
structure and optical properties of materials. Top research establishments
throughout the world employ many of Italy's best in this field.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>It is therefore not surprising that we find
in Italy today a continued commitment to electronics R&amp;D excellence
within the university and research community. Solid state physics
and electronic engineering education are among the most prestigious
(and difficult) paths of learning that an Italian student can
follow.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Italian scientists tend to have a thorough
and individualistic approach to scientific research. Their interactions
and collaboration with fellow colleagues, however, tend to be
more international than national in character.  This tendency
may have to do with the way Italian S&amp;T is organized and funded.
The ministry responsible for funding research in Italy (MURST)
tends to give a limited amount of support to everybody, whatever
their research topic (&quot;rainlike funding&quot;). University
professors have complete freedom to choose their research topics
and to use precious resources pursuing their own interests (also
true at national laboratories). This &quot;shotgun approach&quot;
leaves little room for coordination, cooperation, and successful
utilization of the fruits of research on the open market. <BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> A. The National Research Council Institutes<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>A case in point is how electronics R&amp;D
in Italy is managed. MURST splits the R&amp;D funds between the
two major beneficiaries: universities and the National Research
Council (CNR). Careful analysis of the organizational chart reveals
that electronics-related research is spread widely among the numerous
CNR laboratories and university departments. Just within CNR laboratories
engaged in physics and chemistry, there are at least eight institutes
doing electronics-related research, among them the Institute for
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Research
on Electromagnetic Waves (IROE), Florence</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Quantum
Electronics, Florence</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Special
Materials for Electronics and Magnetism (MASPEC), Parma</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Solid-State
Electronics (ESS), Rome</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Structural
Materials (ISM), Rome</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Chemistry
and Technology of Materials and Components for Electronics</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000> (LAMEL), Bologna</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Chemical
Materials (ICMAT), Rome.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>A similar list can be found within the CNR
engineering community.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Although some loose ties exist within the
physics and chemistry groups doing electronics-related R&amp;D,
the connectivity to engineering is very weak. The present system
is, of course, convenient and comfortable for a happy few, but
the R&amp;D establishment is starting to feel the heat from the
harsh environment imposed by international competition. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> B. Industrial Connection<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Within the industrial sector, a few laboratories
are still engaged in electronics or optoelectronics R&amp;D, but
even those few are falling by the wayside. Chief reason for this
decline has, in part, to do with new market realities within the
European Union. For example, the Italian electronics giant Teletra
had for many years a significant effort in III-V semiconductor
R&amp;D. Since the merging of Alcatel and Teletra a few years
ago, however, the bulk of the electronics R&amp;D activities have
been moved to France. Alenia, a Rome-based industrial/government-run
laboratory pursuing Si IC development for defense systems, is
also downsizing. Only the telecommunication industries are in
an expansion mode in Italy. Pirelli, for example, has been so
successful in marketing fiber-optic amplifier components that
it is now developing its own semiconductor laser diodes.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> C. MASPEC - Electronics &amp; Magnetic Materials Institute
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>MASPEC is one of the Italian National Research
Council (CNR) institutes founded in 1970 and dedicated to the
science of electronics materials. It is headed by Prof. Lucio
Zanotti and is divided into sections reflecting activities in
crystal growth, material characterization, magnetic and metallic
materials, semiconductor physics, technology, and structural properties
of materials. About 60% of its research activities are in III-V
compound semiconductors; the rest is in high-temperature superconductors,
ferroelectrics, and magnetic and metallic materials. Of the total
staff of about 50, half are permanent employees of CNR, the rest
are visiting scientists, students, etc. Total MASPEC budget is
about 2.25 B LIRA ($1.4 M). The rough breakdown of income is one
third from CNR, one third from industry, and the final third from
the European Community. The industrial contribution is primarily
for training of students who come from the private sector.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> D. University of Parma - Department of Information Technology
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The Department of Information Technology is
one of the three departments within the faculty of Engineering
at the University of Parma and is the focus for interdisciplinary
and interdepartmental research. It is quartered within a modern
building on the university campus just outside the city. In addition
to educating young engineers, the department is engaged in fundamental
and applied research within the framework of a &quot;center for
interdepartmental research&quot; called the Center for Material
and Information Technology (MTI). This university-CNR consortium
(established in 1992) consists of the Department of Information
Technology, the Department of Physics, and the Institute MASPEC-CNR
mentioned before. The idea was to establish a &quot;center of
excellence&quot; for electronics R&amp;D in Parma and to consolidate
resources now scattered throughout the city. Within this framework,
MASPEC-CNR will move into new laboratory facilities on campus
sometime in 1997.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The Department of Information Technology,
headed by Prof. Fauso Fantini, is engaged in numerous projects
involving device and circuit design, device processing and testing,
and applications in computer science and communication. Within
the realm of semiconductor device technology, Fantini's group
is world renowned for their device reliability research.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The laboratory is equipped with the latest
electronics instruments and computers. For example, a network
of Sun workstations is the workhorse for computer aided design
(CAD) activity that includes IC design and simulation (CADENCE,
HSPICE), 2D drift-diffusion simulation of semiconductor devices,
process simulation, and Monte Carlo simulation of Si devices.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The total number of researchers and professors
at the Department of Information Technology number about 40. Many
of them are graduate students who perform research either at the
university or at MASPEC-CNR, depending on the resources used.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> E. University of Padova - Department of Electronics and Informatics
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The Department of Electronics and Informatics
is collocated with the Electrical Engineering Department of the
University of Padova within the walls of this ancient Roman city.
This department is a busy, high technology research facility staffed
by eager young engineers, many of them still working towards their
doctorates. The department is divided into laboratories bearing
names that reflect the research activities pursued within them.
Some of these activities include:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Automation
and industrial electronics</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Computer
science</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Image
processing</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Microelectronics</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Microprocessors</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Opto
and quantum electronics</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Telecommunication
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The head of the Microelectronics laboratory
is Prof. Zanoni, a well-known and respected member of the international
device reliability community. Professor Zanoni has collaborated
extensively with Prof. Fantini in the device reliability field
over the years.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Details on the R&amp;D activities at MASPEC
and the universities mentioned above can be found in News #51.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>It is important to emphasize that R&amp;D
pursuits as exemplified by the research groups mentioned above
are world class. The research teams persevere, succeed, and prosper
in spite of the system. Their knowledge base is deep, their international
reputation is impeccable, and their contribution to the pool of
electronics knowledge is significant. This quest for excellence
bodes well for the future of Italy and its people.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000>6.  SPAIN: CENTERS OF EXCELLENCE<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>For the last decade, Spain has been pursuing
an aggressive policy of modernization of its industrial infrastructure,
especially the segments depending on information and communication
technology. It is therefore not surprising that a fair number
of Spanish scientific laboratories are dedicated to electronic
and optoelectronic R&amp;D. One of the driving factors in this
high technology pursuit is Spain's membership within the European
Union (EU) and strong coupling to EU information and communication
technology programs such as ESPRIT and RACE. These programs help
in developing the technical know-how of the country and provide
opportunities to train qualified scientists and engineers for
Spain and Europe.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Among the leading laboratories dedicated to
electronic R&amp;D, the following centers have a well-earned,
high reputation within the international scientific community:
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Centro
Nacional de Microelectronica (CNM) or National Center for Microelectronics,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>The
Electronic Engineering Department of the Universidad Politecnica
de Madrid, and</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>Telefonica Investigacion y Desarollo
(Telefonica I+D) or Telefonica R&amp;D<BR>

<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Of course, there are many other universities
throughout Spain doing interesting electronics R&amp;D. The above
three centers, however, do represent the mainstream of electronic
and optoelectronic effort in Spain.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Most Spanish R&amp;D is driven by the commercial
and social needs of the country. Typical impetus for such programs
include: <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>the
need to develop local telephone systems and local area networks
(LANs),</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>special
electronic components for the medical field, e.g., biological
sensors,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>special transducers, e.g., integrated
micromechanical/electronic components such as pressure gauges
and accelerometers for the automotive and biomedical industries,
and
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>hardware and software for the handicapped,
e.g., speech (Spanish) synthesizer and voice recognition, and
bio-electrical stimulators of the cochlea for deaf patients.<BR>

<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Some of the institutes also perform R&amp;D
for the Spanish Defense Ministry. Integration of IR focal plane
array with integrated circuits, for example, is one of the most
ambitious programs. (Note: the Centro de Investigacion y Desarollo
de la Armada (CIDA) or Defense R&amp;D Center in Madrid has a
small but sophisticated laboratory dedicated to the growth and
evaluation of PbSe infrared detectors; the laboratory is also
developing GaAs photo cathodes for night vision applications).
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> A. The National Center for Microelectronics<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Centro Nacional de Microelectronica (CNM)
is part of the Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cientificas
(CSIC) or &quot;scientific research council.&quot; The CNM has
four departments located in the following cities: <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>1. Silicon, in Barcelona, headed by Dr. E.
Lora-Tamayo.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>2. Design (digital, mostly Si-based), in Barcelona,
headed by Dr. J. Aguilo. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>3. Design (analog, mostly Si-based), in Seville,
headed by Dr. J. Huertas, and</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>4. Compound Semiconductors, in Madrid, headed
by Dr. Fernando Briones.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The total staff consists of 104 employees
in Barcelona, 45 in Seville, and 27 in Madrid, respectively. Roughly
30% of the workers in these laboratories have higher degrees in
scientific or engineering fields; the remaining 70% are technicians,
students, and administrators.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Si processing related projects in Barcelona
comprise<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>FET-based
chemical sensors for detecting various ion species (CHEMFETs),</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>pressure
sensors based on piezoresistance,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>accelerometers
based on piezoresistance and capacitance,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>processing
line for 4 inch Si CMOS with 3-5 micron gate length,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>smart
sensors, integration of sensors, and control logic on the same
chip,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>integrated
optics on Si wafer, and</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>SOI
(SIMOX), development of the materials technology. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Design projects based on Si technology include
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>neural
network and fuzzy logic,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>ASICs (Application Specific ICs)
for voice synthesis, MUXs for IR sensor array, and ASIC for coordinate
transformation (used in radar applications), and
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>interconnection of LANs. <BR>

<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Compound semiconductor projects in Madrid
consist of<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>growth
of III-V heterostructures by Atomic Layer Molecular Beam Epitaxy
(ALMBE) at low temperatures,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>GaAs
Schottky FETs for chemical sensors (hydrogen and methane), and
integrated laser-sensor-detector chips for the chemical and automotive
industry,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>integration
of III-V optoelectronic components on processed CMOS Si wafers,
and</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>thin
film deposition of piezoelectric materials such as BaTiO, PZT,
LiNbO2 for integrated optics and nonvolatile memory.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The research approach at CNM-Madrid reflects
the temperament of its charismatic director, Fernando Briones.
This small but highly talented group has tackled some very important
but difficult solid state physics problems. One such &quot;holy
grail&quot; of solid state physics is the design of a buffer layer
that allows growth of epitaxial layers on lattice mismatched substrates,
e.g., GaAs or InP on Si. In this pursuit, Briones has developed
a specially designed P and As effusion cell that operates in a
pulsed mode. This fast-acting valve/cracker can be synchronized
with the layer by layer growth sequence in such a way that it
optimizes the kinetics of growth for each material. Briones and
his team have painstakingly studied the relationship between optimum
growth and valve sequencing (beam flux amplitude and duration)
by using reflection high-energy diffraction (RHEED) and reflectance
difference (RD) spectroscopy to obtain atomically sharp buried
interfaces.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The optimum use of ALMBE allows the growth
and doping of GaAs, AlGaAs, InP, and InGaAs at much lower growth
temperatures than MBE and with a growth rate similar to MBE. The
technique allows growth of different materials at much lower temperatures
than hereto possible.  Some of the achievements of the CNM-Madrid
group include the growth of Be doped InP with ALMBE at low temperatures
with hole mobility and compensation comparable to Be-doped InP
grown by conventional MBE (or gas source MBE) at much higher temperatures.
They have also grown strain-free InP at 350 C on Si with excellent
morphology and optical quality by using strain layer superlattice
(SLS) buffers.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Briones has a patent on the fast-acting group-V
valve/cracker; it is now commercially available from the French
MBE manufacturer Riber. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Most recent work at CNM-Madrid involves the
development of a fast Sb cracker for the growth of Sb-based alloys
such as AlInSb and GaInSb; they are also studying the utility
of SnTe for n-doping at very low growth temperatures.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> B. The Polytechnic University of Madrid<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The Politecnica forms part of the large (more
than 100,000 students!) university complex in the outskirts of
Madrid. The Electrical Engineering Department is part of the Escuela
Tecnica Superior de Ingenieros de Telecomunicacion (ETSI Telecomunicacion)
which, since the early 1930s, has graduated engineers in the field
of telecommunication. Today the department is in the forefront
of high-technology telecommunications and is the training site
for undergraduate and graduate engineers in digital and analog
circuit electronics, integrated circuit technology, and computer-aided
design.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>There are two groups at Politecnica (within
the Engineering Department) that attract the brightest students
in Spain: the Speech Technology Group (Grupo Tecnico de Hablar
(GTH)) headed by Prof. Jose M. Pardo, and the High Speed Electronics
Laboratory (HISEL) headed by Prof. Elias Munoz. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The GTH:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>has
developed the Spanish text-to-speech converter for Speech Plus
Inc. and Digital Equipment Corp.,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>is developing a new diaphanous based
text-to-speech synthesizer,
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>is contributing to the architecture
of the text-to-speech synthesizer in the ESPRIT project &quot;POLYGLOT,&quot;
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>is participating in the speech recognition
ESPRIT project &quot;Linguistic Analysis of the European Languages&quot;,
and
<P>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT>is currently developing a software
for isolated word recognition and continuous speech recognition
under &quot;POLYGLOT.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>This very active group interacts with the
best US and European laboratories in the field of speech synthesis
and recognition. They have a high visibility within Spain because
of their numerous technical contributions to the visually and
hearing impaired, e.g., speech training, speech pathology diagnosis,
speech analysis and display for the training of deaf, etc.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The HISEL group focusses on the following
R&amp;D topics:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Defects
in semiconductors (DX centers). Dr. Munoz and his colleagues have
written numerous papers on the physics of DX centers in III-V
semiconductors and their influence on device performance, e.g.,
HEMTs. This project is now finished.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>MBE
growth on (111) oriented substrates. The objective of this research
is to use the built-in piezoelectric strain along the (111) to
enhance HEMT performance or to produce more efficient low voltage
electro-optic modulators and switches.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Symbol">_ </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000>Designing
more efficient buffer layers for reducing strain and dislocation
in epitaxial layers grown on lattice mismatched substrates. This
is part of an ESPRIT program involving collaboration with CNM-Madrid,
University of Cadiz, and universities in the UK.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Prof. Munoz's projects are well focussed and
in the mainstream of current electronic and electro-optic R&amp;D.
The facilities for MBE growth, processing, and characterization
are as good as found anywhere in the world. Some recent successes
include the modeling, fabrication, and testing of AlGaAs/GaAs
p-i-n electro-optic diodes with a multiple quantum well (MQW)
in its intrinsic region. Such structures were grown both on (100)
and (111) GaAs substrates. Unlike the (100) geometry, which produces
a red-shifted optical absorption with applied bias voltage (due
to the quantum confinement Stark effect), the (111) p-i-n MQW
configurations show strong blue-shifted absorption with much lower
applied voltage. This strong blue shift is attributed to the piezoelectric
strain induced polarization in the (111) geometry and offers potential
in designing more efficient blue-shifting self-electro-effect
devices (BS-SEEDs). The InP/InGaAs analog for longer wavelength
application is currently being developed.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> C. Telefonica R&amp;D<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Telefonica I+D is modeled after Bellcore in
the US. It is a commercial R&amp;D laboratory supporting the telephone
infrastructure of Spain and Europe. This well staffed and equipped
center of excellence in Madrid is dedicated to R&amp;D projects
ranging from software development to optical communication. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The Basic Technology Division headed by Dr.
Lopez Barrio is one of the only divisions within Telefonica involved
with the actual development of electronic components. It consists
of five groups: microelectronics, optoelectronics, reliability
of materials, hardware, and software technology. The optoelectronics
group, staffed by about 12 well trained scientists and engineers,
has the task of developing prototype elements for the telephone
industry. Some of the projects include the development of new
multiplexing techniques for increased transmission capacity in
fiber optic communication, and the growth and processing of InP-based
optoelectronic chips for optical communication.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B> D. Observation<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>It should be stressed that electronic R&amp;D
in Spain is of good quality. The universities and research establishments
produce well trained scientists and engineers, many of whom end
up working either in Europe or the US. In general, the laboratories
mentioned above are well funded, equipped, and staffed. They all
participate extensively in EC-financed projects and are in the
mainstream of European electronic R&amp;D. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Like many other European electronic R&amp;D
laboratories, the Spanish have a weak link to industry. Many elegant
ideas and projects being pursued by bright researchers remain
buried in technical journals without ever seeing market application.
Even the more applied research facilities like Telefonica have
no strong motivation to transfer their in-house developed technology
to the industrial sector.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>National laboratories such as CNM have clear
scientific objectives, but again, no follow-through in the sense
of impacting the Spanish economy. Part of the problem lies with
the lack of a strong &quot;mid-level&quot; electronic industry
and industries within the country that use electronic technology.
Such industries could serve as users of new ideas/concepts coming
out of the Spanish R&amp;D establishments. With the current economic
slump throughout Europe, this &quot;bridging&quot; process between
R&amp;D centers and industry may prove to be even more tenuous
in the coming years.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>On the positive side, Spain is successfully
training a new generation of technocrats who are comfortable with
the latest high-technology tools such as electronics. After all,
they are the ones that will form the core of modern Spain and
will inevitably impact Spanish society and economy in the next
century.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000>7.  CONCLUSION<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The intent of this report was to give a flavor
of the various electronic related S&amp;T activities being pursued
throughout Europe and to concentrate on analysis, comparative
studies, and assessments of diverse electronics and electro-optic
activities taking place there. Special emphasis was placed on
the emerging S&amp;T opportunities in nanoelectronics, solid state
and vacuum microelectronics, microwave integrated circuits, analytical
tools for measuring fast electronic components, novel electronic
materials, and underlying systems such as information technology
and communication. Furthermore, the goal was to get a broad perspective
of the &quot;European S&amp;T scene,&quot; as well as to focus
in-depth on S&amp;T issues in countries, such as Germany and the
Former Soviet Union, which offer a wealth of new ideas and approaches
useful in planning our own DoD's electronics S&amp;T. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000> Geographic focus on Germany and FSU was intentional.
Both of these countries have a strong S&amp;T tradition, have
occupied historic center stage in Europe for the past five years
and offered &quot;targets of opportunity&quot; during my tenure
at ONREUR. The ONREUR office in London has vested interest in
tracking the S&amp;T developments in both of these countries.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>It is undisputed that Germany is a leader
in Europe in forging the blueprint of electronics for the 21st
century. In spite of the social and economic burden of unification,
Germany is and will continue to be a major contributor to European
S&amp;T. It is well organized, creative, and highly respected
within the world's R&amp;D community. It is a  leader in developing
&quot;environmentally conscious&quot; technologies which have
not only positive impact on the environment, but also are creating
new outlets for German high technology products.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Russia and some of the former republics of
USSR, on the other hand, offer a window of opportunity in niche
areas which are of strategic interest to the DoD. There is still
the potential for technology transfer, but we have to be much
more organized in dealing with their S&amp;T community. We also
have to be much more selective and demanding in the S&amp;T programs
we fund. That entails more accurate and more frequent assessment
of their S&amp;T capabilities.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The omission of France and Great Britain in
this report was also intentional. Both France and Great Britain
have close links to DoD through various exchange agreements. There
is a constant US interaction on a technical level with both of
these countries. This fact should, however, not preclude ONREUR
from continued assessment of their contribution to the European
electronic community.  As a matter of fact, we need to pay more
attention to S&amp;T events in France since the French have unique
and elegant ways of solving S&amp;T problems from which we all
can learn. And unlike most Western countries, they are not hampered
by budgetary cuts in R&amp;D.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>The focus on the &quot;S&amp;T scene&quot;
in Hungary, Italy, and Spain was to give balance to the report.
Each one of these countries represent the &quot;emerging&quot;
European nations in the region; they have unique economic and
cultural factors affecting their S&amp;T infrastructure. These
factors needed to be exposed to place them in perspective within
the new European community. After all, the European Commission
is a strong supporter of S&amp;T programs in these emerging nations.
These research programs are vehicles for bringing the communities
together and spawn new technologies that will impact the electronic
market.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>I believe that we need to go out of our way
to promote interactions with our European colleagues in the field
of electronics. There are many talented scientists and engineers
in Europe doing R&amp;D in unique ways. They generate many good
ideas which could be of benefit to our own S&amp;T community.
The major challenge is to identify these &quot;golden nuggets&quot;
and to take timely action. To achieve this, we need to have knowledgeable
people close to the scene. This is not always possible, especially
with the shrinking R&amp;D budget in the US. The recent trend
to staff ONREUR with scientists and technologists from organizations
such as NSF, ARPA, and industry is a step in the right direction.
However, much still needs to be done.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>I recommend that those key areas termed &quot;windows
of opportunity&quot; should be pursued vigorously. I am happy
to report that some of my &quot;alerts&quot; have been taken to
heart and resulted in new S&amp;T initiatives in our own laboratories,
particularly in MMIC and vacuum microwave arena.  The Special
Programs Office at ONR has been very helpful in bringing such
technical transitions to fruition. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>Finally, recruiting competent scienists and
engineers to staff ONREUR is a challenge to the ONR management,
specially during current uncertainties in the DoD. <U>The DoD
electronic S&amp;T community must be represented in Europe.</U>
Recent directive from DoD specifically calls for the Identification
of International Cooperative Opportunities for S&amp;T Programs.
This action alone is sufficient cause to have an electronics expert
in position at ONREUR. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>ONREUR has a long tradition of excellence
in Europe for over five decades. That excellence is bound to continue
and flourish in the next millenium.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR=#000000>8.  ACKNOWLEDGMENTS<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>My assignment in London was highly satisfying,
both from the professional as well as from a personal points of
view thanks to numerous individuals in Europe and the USA. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#000000>First of all I want to thank you, the readers
of my electronic newsletter on electronics, for your support and
feedback. For those of you who took the time to criticize my reports
and assessments, I will remain eternally grateful. I want particularly
to recognize the comradeship and support of present and former
colleagues at ONREUR and the sister organizations at Edison House:
Dr. John Silva, CDR Dale Milton, CDR Larry Raithel, LTCDR David
St Pierre, Dr. Jack Simon, Dr. Elias Ashey, Dr. Otto Kessler,
Dr. Kenneth Lobb,  Dr. Art Diness, Dr. Karl Steinbach, LTCOL Mike
Markow, and LTCOL Don Erbschloe.  Many thanks also to the ONREUR
support staff for handling all the details associated with the
London assignment: Ms. Luci Blethyn, Ms. Joan Scott, Ms. Peggy
Holmes, Mr. Fred Johnson, Mr. Ron Wimberly, Mr. Mike Shear, Mr.
David Lewis, and Mr. Fred Morris. Dr. Craig Dorman, current technical
director of ONREUR, merits special thanks for encouraging me to
bring out this report in a printed form. Last but not least, my
wife Lieselotte, for providing the spiritual support that made
life in London so enjoyable and memorable.<BR>
<BR>
